<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTOM PUTS YANKS ON TOP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During a Yankees batting practice over the weekend,
Joe Torre glanced out at the scoreboard, which had third baseman
Scott Brosius' name and stats in lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that _ 98 runs batted in,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius would finish the season with 98, but after the Yankees'
2-0 victory over the Texas Rangers Tuesday night in the opener of
their American League division series, the 32-year-old third
baseman could take credit for 100 RBI _ one on a punched single
through the right side of the Texas infield that scored Jorge
Posada, and the other moments later on his brilliant base-running,
which allowed Chad Curtis to score before Brosius was tagged out in
a rundown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott's base-running instincts are by far the best on this
team,'' Torre has said. ``He never makes a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, with Curtis on third base and Chuck
Knoblauch up, Brosius broke for second. On a called third strike on
Knoblauch, Ivan Rodriguez, the Ranger catcher, fired toward second
base, where Mark McLemore took the throw in the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than try to get around McLemore, Brosius stopped, then
quickly retreated toward first base. McLemore unwisely chased him
as Curtis hurried across the plate. The run counted because Curtis
scored before Brosius was tagged by first baseman Will Clark.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the batting order _ Curtis hit eighth, Brosius
ninth _ along with David Wells' nine strikeouts in eight shutout
innings, put the Yankees on top, 1-0, in the three-of-five-game
series, which resumes Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to think of another guy at the bottom of the
batting order with as many RBIs as Scott has,'' Torre had said.
``Maybe Paul Sorrento; he had a lot when he was with the Indians in
1995, before he went to Seattle in the off season.''
</P>
<P>
   Although not a day-to-day regular, Sorrento had 79 RBIs that
season as a first baseman and designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, of course, was in the lineup last night primarily for
his glove. Shane Spencer, the September sensation, had hit 10
homers, including three grand slams, but with Wells pitching, Torre
wanted Curtis' more dependable glove in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wells is more of a fly ball pitcher,'' Torre explained.
``Curtis is out there basically for defense.''
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the eighth inning, though, Curtis appeared to
misjudge a McLemore fly ball that sailed over his glove for a
double. But with Wells' ninth strikeout and Derek Jeter's acrobatic
scoop and throw of Rusty Greer's slow grounder, the Yankees
survived the inning, and Curtis exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't pitch,'' Torre had said, ``Texas can score a lot
of runs.''
</P>
<P>
   And last night, the Yankees pitched. Wells was dominant for
eight innings, then Mariano Rivera closed out the Rangers in the
ninth. In recent weeks, Rivera had not been as dependable as usual,
but Torre had pronounced him ready for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fine,'' the Yankee manager said before the game. ``He had
a little problem when he was hit with a line drive in the right
part of his chest and we had to shut him down for four or five
days, but his stuff now is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the middle of the Yankee batting order all but
helpless, the bottom of the order supplied the big hits and the
clever base-running that made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   In that second-inning rally against Todd Stottlemyre, the Texas
starter, Curtis sliced a looping fly ball that just eluded right
fielder Juan Gonzalez's glove not far from the foul line. Then
Brosius slashed a run-producing single, and later danced away from
McLemore as Curtis scored.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the season, Brosius has been a sweet surprise.
Acquired from the Oakland Athletics in the off-season trade for the
left-hander Kenny Rogers and an unspecified amount of George
Steinbrenner's cash, Brosius batted .300 with those 98 RBIs and 19
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, the Yankee front office might have to consider
letting the 32-year-old Brosius, who signed to a one-year contract,
depart as a free agent rather than re-sign him. Some of
Steinbrenner's ``baseball people'' consider the farmhand Mike
Lowell ready to take over at third.
</P>
<P>
   But after last night's theatrics, all the Yankee loyalists in
the crowd of 57,362, the second largest assembly in the 22-year
history of the remodeled Stadium, would insist on re-signing Scott
Brosius.
</P>
</TEXT>
