<HEADLINE>
HACKETT CAN'T PRAISE HIS OWN PASSING GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Whether it's a question of poor blocking or
keeping things simple for the quarterback, there's a reason USC's
passing game has often looked little more than throwing deep to R.
Jay Soward.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a quick ball to throw (when) there's not a lot of pass
protection,'' said USC coach Paul Hackett. ``There's also not a lot
of decision making (for the quarterback) in case the protection
breaks down.''
</P>
<P>
   A limited passing game could be the side effect from being
manhandled by Florida State. USC quarterbacks completed just three
of 19 passes for 23 yards. And the Trojans expect Arizona State's
defense to be just as aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hackett would eventually like to use more plays with
four wide receivers, he's reluctant to do anything with the
offensive line struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last week, I'm not going to be quick to throw all these
(receivers) out here,'' Hackett said. ``Passing is about pass
protection. The passing game is not rolling right now.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Trojans concentrating on Soward or the running backs,
receivers like Billy Miller and Mike Bastianelli are getting fewer
opportunities for receptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't really thrown down the middle of the field at all
this year,'' Bastianelli said. ``That's what I do. He hasn't really
unleashed the offense, yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who caught 56 passes last season, has just nine
receptions. Bastianelli, who caught 33 passes last year, has just
four. Hackett said the sheer number of wide receivers is the reason
Bastianelli's numbers are down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have five wide receivers we feel very confident in,''
Hackett said. ``The return of Larry Parker and the addition of
Windrell Hayes are two huge differences.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Passing genius: Hackett made light of the fact that USC has
passed for 23 yards twice in the past 19 years: last week against
Florida State and in the 1979 Rose Bowl, when he was the Trojans'
offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really a whiz so far,'' he said. ``We're 10th in the
league in passing.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Wilson to redshirt: The offensive line might be in trouble,
but Hackett said true freshman guard Zach Wilson, who was
impressive in training camp, will still redshirt this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tempted (to play him),'' Hackett said. ``I liked what he
did early.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett also officially informed tailback Sultan McCullough that
he will redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to redshirt, really,'' McCullough said. ``I think I
need to gain a little weight.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Practice change: In an effort to increase the tempo and
competition, Hackett had the first-string offense and defense
practice against each other. It's a move welcomed by the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The practices, everyone's gotten into a routine,'' Bastianelli
said. ``At times, it seems to be slower.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Townsend's a Sun Devil: Former USC defensive lineman Tommie
Townsend is a member of Arizona State's football team. Townsend
left USC last year after encountering academic problems with the
NCAA Clearinghouse.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: Tailback Chad Morton did not practice because
he needed to rest his sore back. He is expected to return today.
Center Matt McShane practiced and appears healthy enough to start
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
