<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GONZALEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ HAS BARK BUT NO BITE FOR TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The pitch got away from David Wells and sailed right
into the sight line of Juan Gonzalez, like a deer standing before a
hunter. Gonzalez pulled the trigger, swung with might and fouled
off the 2-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   A wide-eyed Wells wiped his brow. Close call. In one of his few
mistakes of the evening, Wells nearly handed Gonzalez an
opportunity to send the Yankees into a flashback of the 1996
division series, when the Rangers' clean-up hitter huffed and
puffed and blew their staff down.
</P>
<P>
   At least for a night, the ominous Gonzalez turned into a dark
cloud that passed over Yankee Stadium without a drop. The one time
he made contact and produced a ground ball that was fair, it
dribbled three feet in front of him and Wells threw him out. For
the night, Gonzalez was 0 for 4 with a strikeout, ending the night
as a prime example of a threatening lineup coming up dry in the
Yankees' 2-0 victory in Game 1 of their division series against the
Rangers Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any offense at all, it came from the bottom of the
lineup, not from the imposing heart of the order. The Rangers'
second through sixth batters _ Roberto Kelly, Rusty Greer,
Gonzalez, Will Clark and Ivan Rodriguez _ each finished the season
batting over .300. Three of them, Greer, Gonzalez and Clark, had
100-plus RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, with Wells' precision starting to waiver,
Kelly had a prime opportunity to drive in a run for the Rangers
after the leadoff hitter, Mark McLemore, doubled with one out.
Wells battled Kelly and won. On a full count that arrived after
Kelly fouled off three pitches, Wells reached back and delivered a
called strike on the inside corner. Kelly was gone, as was Greer,
who grounded out to Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   The threat was over. With the Rangers unable to cause a ripple
in front of Gonzalez, the Yankees did not have to made a decision
to walk him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they walk Juan, as some teams have done, we can go to a guy
who has only driven in 100-something runs and hit over .300,''
Manager Johnny Oates said before the game, referring to Clark.
``And if they walk him, we've got a guy who has driven in
80-something runs. We have to give Juan some help, because he can't
do it all by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no rescue last night. The Rangers had McLemore aboard
on a walk to start the game, but no one could pick him up as Kelly,
Greer and Gonzalez delivered three consecutive outs. In the fourth
inning, with Greer on first base, Gonzalez and Clark ended the
inning with back-to-back strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can do is try to take advantage of the situation,''
Clark said before the game, knowing if Gonzalez was pitched around,
he would have to deliver. ``If I come up there with runners in
scoring position, I've got to do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   There were chances, but each dissolved, and a shutout was on.
The Rangers were not the run-scoring Rangers everyone had come to
know this season.
</P>
<P>
   And Gonzalez was not himself; not that Wells allowed him to
break free. Instead of pitching around Gonzalez, Wells pitched him
carefully inside. With the exception of one pitch that got away
from him, Wells picked at Gonzalez's weakness: the inside part of
the plate. Generally, Gonzalez likes to extend his arms toward
pitches at the middle and outside part of the plate, about belt
high.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing to connect with for Gonzalez. This was not
1996. During that series against the Yankees, Gonzalez uncoiled for
five home runs and nine RBIs in 16 at-bats, generating the only
offense for a Rangers team that lost in four games.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night was different. There would be a close call, but no
flashback on this night. The gaudy numbers the Rangers put up in
the regular season were nowhere to be found on a blank scoreboard. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
