<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ONEILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMUT FOR O'NEILL: PERFECTION OR RAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jose Cardenal tries not to laugh, and he turns away
if he can't help himself, his body shaking. Cardenal, the Yankees'
first-base coach, not only hears Paul O'Neill's self-indictments
after the All-Star right fielder makes an out, he also all but
feels the heat from O'Neill's explosions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he's saying, `I can't hit anymore, I'll never get
another hit,' and he's batting .320,'' said Cardenal. ``If he goes
0 for 3, that's the first thing he'll say: `I can't play no more.'
The guy just wants a base hit every time he bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Most baseball fans who watched the Yankees defeat the Texas
Rangers, 2-0, in Game 1 of the American League division series last
night know O'Neill for his ability to hit. He averaged .317 this
year, his sixth consecutive season batting over .300, and drove in
116 runs with 40 doubles, 2 triples and 24 home runs. Last night he
was true to form, going 1 for 3 with a first-inning double.
</P>
<P>
   But casual baseball fans _ or fans who hate the Yankees _ have
come to identify O'Neill for his on-field rage, ignited almost
every time he makes an out. If he makes the final out of an inning,
O'Neill might slam his helmet after crossing first base. If O'Neill
makes an out in the middle of an inning, he returns to the dugout
with his head down, sometimes talking aloud. As he nears the bat
rack, the bat boys who sit nearby bend away instinctively, unsure
of how O'Neill's momentary self-loathing might manifest itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens with him is that frustration builds up,'' said
Bernie Williams, the Yankees' center fielder. ``He might fail in
his first at-bat, and then his second at-bat, and then in his third
at-bat, if he doesn't have a hit, he's ready to explode. He's never
satisfied. He could be 4 for 4, and then ground out or strike out
in his fifth at-bat, and he's furious.''
</P>
<P>
   The intensity apparently runs in the family. O'Neill grew up as
the youngest of five brothers, ``in a very competitive
environment,'' he said. ``When you're competing against your own
family, it's a love-hate thing, man. And it's frustrating when you
continually lose. As you get older, you get closer, but it always
seems like you fall short.''
</P>
<P>
   But hating to fall short goes further back than the Ohio
O'Neills. The O'Neill clan is legendary in Ireland. According to
ancient lore, two rival chieftains _ including the O'Neill leader _
agreed that they would row across a body of water and whoever first
touched the Isle of Destiny would possess land rights. As they
neared land, O'Neill realized he was going to lose. He drew his
sword, cut off his left hand and threw it to shore, winning the
race. The bloody hand _ the Red Hand of Ulster _ is part of the
O'Neill coat of arms.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill does not have a sword at his disposal, but he
sometimes throws his helmet or flips his bat or flings his batting
gloves when he makes an out. Any out seems to be one too many.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anyone like him,'' Homer Bush said. ``It can't
be good for your health. But the guys who have been around him say
his rages make him concentrate better and make the needed
adjustments. Every time he comes back, he doesn't just throw things
or hit things _ he knows exactly what he did wrong in that at-bat.
He'll say, `Stay back,' or, `You know he was going to throw you
that pitch, why did you swing at it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Said Williams: ``He just doesn't hide his frustration as well as
everybody else, which I don't think is a bad thing; he'll probably
have less gray hairs than the rest of us, less ulcers.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said: ``I'm not the only guy who does this stuff. I
might be the only one who doesn't make it down to the tunnel where
you can't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Durwood Merrill, an umpire who happens to be working during this
division series, complained about O'Neill's body language at home
plate in a book published earlier this year. But the vast majority
of umpires seem tolerant of O'Neill. Sometimes he twists his head
in disgust on a strike call, and most umpires calmly explain the
location of the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   John Shulock, an American League umpire, interprets O'Neill's
outward demeanor as a reflection of how he is feeling about himself
at a given moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't begrudge us doing our job, he just gets
frustrated,'' Shulock said. ``He feels he should get a hit every
time up. He won't accept mediocrity. If I was a manager of a team
and I had six or seven like him, I'd be completely happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Something O'Neill will probably never be, until the year he bats
1.000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
