<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-FANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS LOOKING TO THE FUTURE: SHOULD THE YANKEES LEAVE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Yankee fans gathered Tuesday night for the team's
fourth straight year in the playoffs, some were already looking
past this season's performance to reflect on the team's future _
and whether that future would take place in the Bronx, in Manhattan
or somewhere across the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Whether moved by tradition or buoyed by the excitement of the
moment, most seemed inclined to think that the club should stay
put. Some cited a new plan by Borough President Fernando Ferrer for
a redesigned ball park as a good way to keep the team in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been coming to Yankee Stadium for 40 years,'' said John
Cott, 63, of the Bronx. ``George is doing the right thing _ he's
keeping quiet. But if he moves out of New York, he's lost four
loyal fans.'' Cott pointed to his family.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the principal owner of the Yankees, has
been agitating for years for a new ball park, and the frequency _
and pitch _ of his demands has increased since the Yankees started
winning again. And this year, with the Yankees winning a lot, talk
of the stadium's future has infected New York City political
debates that on the surface have nothing to do with baseball.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Ferrer offered a plan to modernize Yankee Stadium
that he said would ease traffic jams, add luxury boxes and spruce
up the surrounding neighborhood with new stores and parks. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani declared the plan dead on arrival and continued to
express support for a Manhattan ball park financed by taxpayers.
That plan is opposed by Peter Vallone, the Democratic nominee for
governor and speaker of the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   But Ferrer's plans seemed to appeal to many attending Tuesday
night's game. Before the game, Dan Pagan, 23, was pasting bumper
stickers to his mountain bike reading, ``Keep our team in the
Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good plan,'' Pagan said. ``You can do a lot here. It
would look nice and bring jobs to the Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the stadium, Ed Assile said he felt strongly that the
Yankees should remain but that the neighborhood should be built up.
``I think they should do what they did in Baltimore,'' he said.
``If they rejuvenate the neighborhood, people will come.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend, Bill Meyer, also 50, was circumspect. ``I'd hate to
see them move out, but in the best interest of baseball, they have
to think about security.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men said police officers had told them not to stray too
far. ``They said don't go more than a block from the stadium, so we
stayed inside,'' Assile said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent seasons Steinbrenner has rebuffed plans for a
renovation of Yankee Stadium or even for a new stadium in the
Bronx. He has flirted with New Jersey and shown obvious interest in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In the stands, Charlie Sullivan, 62, was having none if it.
``They can build a new stadium,'' he said, ``as long as put it
right here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
