<SLUG> BC-BBA-WELLS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR WELLS, WHATEVER WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Wells was calm enough Tuesday night that he
paused before facing the second batter of the game to wave to the
rowdy fans chanting his name in the bleacher section. It was
typical Wells. Why be overly concerned about Roberto Kelly at the
plate or Mark McLemore creeping off first base? Just motion toward
right field like always, and then get back to throwing.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever works, right? For Wells, it is about being comfortable
by being himself. If that means wearing a uniform jersey that looks
bulky enough to cover a pool, do it. If that means tweaking Joe
Torre a few days before Game 1 of the division playoff series for a
decision the manager made 12 months ago, do it. If that means
challenging an imposing lineup with a mixture of gutsy pitches deep
into the night, do it. This is Wells. The Yankees know him and
accept him.
</P>
<P>
   When Wells does as much as he did in a 2-0 victory at Yankee
Stadium Tuesday night, the Yankees also love him. Wells throttled
the Rangers over eight sharp innings, delighting the crowd of
57,362 with nine strikeouts and validating Torre's easy decision to
start him. Actually, it was the only decision Torre could have and
should have made. Wells deserved to be on the mound, and he showed
precisely why in limiting Texas to five hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are nervous on both teams out there, so that
can help you out,'' Wells said. ``I don't get nervous. I get
butterflies, but I don't get nervous. I want that opportunity. I
want to pitch in these games.'' That was evident on a mild evening
in the Bronx, especially during the tensest moments.
</P>
<P>
   With the fans chanting, ``Let's go, Boomer,'' in the eighth,
McLemore was on second after Chad Curtis had misjudged a liner to
left field. But Wells battled Kelly for nine pitches before finally
striking him out, then retired Rusty Greer on a trickler to
shortstop on which Derek Jeter made an acrobatic play. Juan
Gonzalez was on deck _ gulp _ but he never got the chance to bring
McLemore home.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning, two singles put runners on first and
second with two outs for designated hitter Mike Simms, and the
sticky situation made the Yankee fans queasy. Torre did not call
the bullpen. This was Wells' game, Wells' batter. Remember, he does
not get nervous.
</P>
<P>
   After jumping ahead of Simms with two quick strikes, Wells let
the count drift to 2-2. Simms fouled off two pitches and then Wells
threw a fastball that barely sailed inside. It was 3-2. Wells was a
pitch away from loading the bases, but he might as well have been
waving to the bleachers again as he pumped an outside fastball by
Simms. Wells used to be accused of quitting. Not this season. Not
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a tougher pitcher now,'' Torre said. ``He demands
more from himself. He's always had that great stuff, but he's never
gone beyond that. If it was a bad day for him, he accepted that.
Now he won't accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans were standing and screaming when Wells reached two strikes
on a Ranger as early as the second inning. Sure, it was the
postseason and there were valid reasons for them to be delirious,
but Wells added to that hysteria in his own brash way. He made
nasty pitches, he collected strikeouts and he gave the type of tidy
effort that made the Yankees look like the team that is expected to
stroll to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Wells, the favored Yankees could exhale Tuesday
night. They did not want to fall behind in the three-of-five-game
series, the sort of series Torre referred to as ``Russian
roulette.'' When you have won 114 games in the regular season, as
the Yankees did, it is imperative to begin a short series
successfully. The Yankees asked Wells to usher them through the
opener and he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has already been a dream season,'' Wells said. ``What
we're trying to do now is an added bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells stifled the dangerous Gonzalez, who did not hit a ball out
of the infield in three at-bats. The burly left-hander did not
allow a Ranger to reach third. He is now 5-0 with a 2.24 ERA in his
postseason career, and this season he is 12-1 at the Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like a decade, not just a year, since Torre kept Wells'
status as a postseason starter in doubt until late September
because he had faltered in six starts in a row. Eventually, Wells
rebounded, but he had not forgotten the perceived slight. Twelve
months, one perfect game and one magical regular season later,
Wells, without solicitation, recalled in a recent interview how he
had floated in uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at last year,'' Wells said. ``He even doubted me
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Wells laughed sarcastically and claimed that Torre forgot
to check his postseason statistics last year. But Torre made the
right call Tuesday night in selecting Wells over David Cone, who
needs the rest, or Andy Pettitte, in whom the Yankees' confidence
is thin. After 135 snazzy pitches, that was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a little more hungry in the postseason than I am
in the regular season because this is what we play for,'' Wells
said. ``When you get here, you got to suck it up. Don't try to
change anything. Stay worthy, you know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
