<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-RANGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS, YANKEES STIFLE RANGERS IN SERIES OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The dream season may be history, but those who made
it happen are intent on burnishing it. Tuesday night the
record-setting Yankees started the postseason the same way they
played during their 114-win regular season: with a big victory.
</P>
<P>
   Maestro David Wells was brilliant against one of the American
League's best offenses, holding the Texas Rangers to five hits over
eight innings. Closer extraordinaire Mariano Rivera mowed down the
heart of the Texas order in the ninth and the Yankees had a 2-0
victory in the opener of this best-of-five Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Wells was overpowering through six innings, then survived on
guile, guts, and fumes in the seventh and eighth. Overall, he
struck out nine, a personal playoff best, in a heroic performance
which featured 135 pitches, 93 of them strikes. It was his highest
pitch count of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Only three Rangers reached second base, and Wells got help when
he needed it, mainly from Derek Jeter with a great play to end the
eighth on a slow roller to shortstop. Meanwhile, the less heralded
bottom of the New York order accounted for both runs in the second
inning, including one on a double steal thanks to a Ranger
breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as good in defeat was Todd Stottlemyre, who settled down
after a shaky start and retired 15 of the final 20 batters he
faced, allowing six hits in eight innings. With his father, Yankees
pitching coach Mel, in the home dugout and his mother in the
stands, Stottlemyre fanned seven and gave the Rangers exactly what
they needed: long, quality innings. But on this night, that was not
good enough. Not against Wells, who prepares for games by listening
to such soothing groups as Van Halen, ACDC, and Metallica. (What,
no Megadeath?) It must work; he's 5-0 in the postseason and has
pitched 15 consecutive scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an all right pitcher, I think,'' Wells said. ``But when it
comes to playoff time, I get focused, mean, and I want my way. And
if I don't get it, I get (upset). I'm a fighter. A gamer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crunch time,'' added Wells. ``I thrive on this kind of
stuff. I want to be the hero and the goat. I want to be the guy who
they blame when I get my butt kicked or the one they pat on the
back.''
</P>
<P>
   He got a lot of pats Tuesday night. It was a festive atmosphere
at the Stadium, and the crowd of 57,362 was the second largest in
the 23 years since the edifice was remodeled. The Yankees brought
out Elston Howard's daughter to sing the national anthem, and
late-season hero Shane Spencer got a rousing ovation when he was
introduced along with the other nonstarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees lost a run in the first when Chuck Knoblauch was
thrown out at the plate (a great relay from Royce Clayton) after a
Paul O'Neill double. But they clicked in the second. Jorge Posada
drew a one-out walk and went to third when Chad Curtis, starting
for his defense, doubled to right, just out of the reach of Juan
Gonzalez. Scott Brosius singled in Posada, and then came the key
double steal.
</P>
<P>
   With the count on Knoblauch 3-2, Yankees manager Joe Torre sent
Brosius. Knoblauch swung and missed, and Texas catcher Pudge
Rodriguez then rifled a throw to second, usually a no-no. Curtis
made a beeline for the plate while Brosius stopped dead in his
tracks. Curtis crossed the plate before the Rangers could tag
Brosius out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't execute very well,'' Texas manager Johnny Oates
said. ``I'm not sure what happened. I don't know if Pudge looked
the runner back. I'm not sure where the breakdown was. I'll have to
look at the video.''
</P>
<P>
   From then on, it was a great pitchers' duel. The meat of the
Texas order _ Rusty Greer, Juan Gonzalez, Will Clark, and Rodriguez
_ were a combined 2 for 16, with putative MVP Gonzalez looking
positively helpless against Wells. Stottlemyre allowed only three
hits after the second, none threatening, while limiting Jeter,
batting champion Bernie Williams, and Tino Martinez to one hit in
eight at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Wells labored through the seventh. In an epic duel, he fanned
Mike Simms to end the inning with runners on first and second. In
the eighth, he yielded a one-out double to Mark McLemore but caught
Roberto Kelly looking (another long battle), and then Jeter bailed
him out, just nipping Greer at first with an across-the-body
bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you win,'' Oates saluted. ``You make those plays
day in and day out on a consistent basis.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Yankees did in the regular season. Why stop now?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
