<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE MARKET MAY BENEFIT FROM FED'S RATE CUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Federal Reserve Board's decision to cut a key
interest rate by a quarter-point will likely further stimulate an
already hot real estate market, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The mortgage banking industry lowered its rates again last week
in anticipation of Tuesday's action by the Fed. The average rate
for a 30-year fixed mortgage is now at 6.64 percent, its lowest
level in 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   This should help keep home sales strong through the fall, which
is when the market typically slows down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there will be much of a drop,'' said Randy
Willox, executive vice president at suburban Calabasas' Countrywide
Home Loans, the nation's biggest mortgage lender. ``September was a
very good month for us purchase-wise, and we think October and
November will be too. The rates are too good to pass up.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Countrywide's 30-year fixed rate was 6.34 percent
with one-eighth of a point and no origination fee.
</P>
<P>
   The rate cut also could encourage homeowners to refinance. The
rule of thumb is that homeowners should consider a refi if they can
save 1 percentage point and plan on staying in their home for at
least five more years.
</P>
<P>
   Realtors also thought the Fed's quarter-point rate reduction
would be good for business. Several said that sales started to
slack off at the beginning of the month but should perk up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to help us have an end-of-the-year sales
volume that's going to be extremely high,'' said Roger Hance,
president of R.R. Gable Real Estate Group in suburban Northridge.
``It's extremely positive for the real estate market.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
