<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE WORKS THROUGH SEASON OF STRUGGLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
UPDATES 
 
By KATHY KUDRAVI 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although Andy Pettitte struggled all year, including
an un-Pettitte like 1-3 September, New York Yankees manager Joe
Torre had no qualms about starting him in today's Game 2 of the
Division Series against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stuff is as good now as it has been this season,'' Torre
said. ``I think the common thread is Andy striving for perfection
all the time and never really being satisfied with what he sees. We
may be satisfied, and we have been satisfied, especially over the
past three or four performances...
</P>
<P>
   ``A perfect game is probably the only way he'll be satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Rangers once this season, Pettitte allowed seven hits
in a 6-4 victory Aug. 14 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte tried working through his problems by focusing on one
part of his pitching in each start. And work with Yankees coaches
helped rebuild Pettitte's confidence to the point that his relief
appearance against Tampa Bay on Sept. 25 was comfortable for the
left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's been one of my problems whenever I've been
struggling the last month or so. I really don't know what the
problem was,'' said Pettitte, who is from Deer Park. ``I've been up
here four years and really haven't struggled until now. But I don't
get down on myself; it's not me.''
</P>
<P>
   One possible explanation for Pettitte's struggles this season
could be that he has been buzzed by several balls hit right back at
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more mental than anything,'' he said. ``Every time the
ball comes, you flinch more, and it can definitely affect you. I
didn't feel like it was, but maybe I was trying to finish in a
better fielding position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
