<SLUG> BC-DELTA-AD-COLUMN-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: CAMPAIGN PROMOTES FUNNY SKIES OF DELTA EXPRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Mo., N.C., N.Y., Tenn.)  (lb) 
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Humor is not a common element in airline advertising. Maybe that
is because so many travelers these days find nothing funny about
flying. Nonetheless, Delta Air Lines is using humor as the central
element in the first television campaign for its low-fare airline,
Delta Express.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which begins Thursday, parodies the classic
marketing technique, seen most often in packaged-goods advertising,
of secretly switching products on unsuspecting consumers and then
showing the results in commercials that use footage from hidden
cameras. The initial television commercial is by Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
in New York, the agency for Delta and Delta Express.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta in the past has not done much with humor,'' said
Paulette Corbin, managing director for Delta Express in Atlanta.
``We took a look at our competition and all of their advertising,
and we pushed the envelope to try to make the ads humorous and
attention-grabbing.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowded field against which Delta Express competes includes
airlines like Southwest, Kiwi and Airtran. Delta Express, which
will celebrate its second anniversary Thursday, flies to
destinations in Florida from cities including Albany, Boston and
Cleveland, serving 22 U.S. cities in all.
</P>
<P>
   The secret product switch is a time-tested tactic that has been
used for selling anything from soft drinks to detergents. Perhaps
the best-known campaign to employ the device was for the Folgers
coffee brand sold by Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. Commercials by what is
now N.W. Ayer &AMP; Partners in New York, part of MacManus Group,
showed the reactions of diners at fancy restaurants when told they
were drinking Folgers instant coffee rather than freshly brewed
ground coffee.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta Express commercial mimics the Folgers campaign in many
ways. The spot begins with an announcer whispering into a
microphone: ``We've secretly replaced this discount airline with
Delta Express to Florida. Let's go aboard, shall we?''
</P>
<P>
   As the announcer boards the plane, passengers ooh and aah over
Delta Express features. ``Wow, reserved seats!'' a man exclaims,
while a boy exudes, ``Whoa, a jet engine!'' The announcer then
asks, ``What if I told you this was really a Delta Express
flight?'' A woman is pleased because, she says, ``We get Delta Sky
miles.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcer concludes, with corny, old-time advertising
enthusiasm: ``That's right! With Delta Express you really can fly
for less and still get that rich, full-bodied experience. But don't
take our word for it.'' A passenger proclaims, ``It's fab-ulous.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial ends with another announcer, a woman, asserting
that ``Delta Express is the difference between an inexpensive seat
and a cheap seat.'' That sentiment also appears at the bottom of
print ads.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is the third initiative for Delta from Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi, part of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC, since the agency was
awarded the Delta account in March 1997. Delta spends an estimated
$100 million a year on advertising; spending for the Delta Express
campaign was estimated at more than $1 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Humor, when used effectively, can be a great way to capture
viewers' attention,'' said Roger Rowe, executive vice president and
executive creative director on the Delta Air Lines account at
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, humor is particularly appropriate because it
captures the pleasant experience we promise on all Delta Express
flights,'' he said. ``Plus, it helps create a brand personality
that differentiates Delta Express from other low-cost airlines.''
(Though of course Southwest has long used humor as a selling tool,
particularly during its flights: pilots are known to tell jokes
over the public address system, and flight attendants engage in
zany banter with passengers, sometimes even dressing in costumes.)
</P>
<P>
   The commercial will run in such markets as Kansas City; Albany
and Buffalo, N.Y.; and Raleigh and Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   In the print ads that are part of the campaign, Delta Express is
compared to an off-price retailer. A label with the words ``Delta
Express'' in place of a clothing brand is shown above this
headline: ``Designer label. Discount price.'' The ad will appear in
newspapers in cities including Buffalo and Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Two radio commercials, which are similar to the television spot,
will run in markets including Cleveland; Nashville, Tenn.; and
Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
