<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-VOICES-HISTORY-NYT     09-30 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VOICES-HISTORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE VOICES STAKE A CLAIM TO HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (About New York)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometimes, Mary Marshall Clark hears voices while
working in her office atop Butler Library at Columbia University.
She doesn't shame them into silence with a shush. They're
reassuring, even if they are in her head.
</P>
<P>
   She has not gone stack-wacky. The voices are also on tapes
stored in hundreds of boxes and among volumes of transcripts, part
of the university's Oral History Research Office Collection, which
celebrates its 50th anniversary next week.
</P>
<P>
   The university calls it the world's largest, with 15,000 hours
of interviews with the famous and obscure that are studied and
treasured by historians, writers, pop culture mavens and broadcast
producers.
</P>
<P>
   They include a history of American artisans, documentation on
how AIDS patients changed the course of medical treatment and a
history of the Black Panthers. The 7,000 interviews are
cross-referenced so you can choose, for example, an interview in
which Lauren Bacall talks about Humphrey Bogart or Adlai Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late at night, in this room there are 7,000 voices talking to
each other,'' said Ms. Clark, the archive's associate director. ``I
can get up and see the 55 places where Thurgood Marshall was
discussed. It's a gigantic conversation happening here all the
time. That's the closest thing to a collective memory.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection was started in 1948 to create an archive that
would be a record of the affairs of ``great men,'' and not of the
current salacious variety of presidential shenanigans. The idea was
to document the decision-making process in the words of the people
who made the decisions. Technology and time had thwarted that kind
of record-keeping, though, since people were talking on phones and
not keeping diaries.
</P>
<P>
   But the Great Men Thinking Deep Thoughts About Big Stuff
approach was challenged during the 1960s, as scholars in the field
extended their microphones and questions to women, members of
racial minorities and regular people who were equally part of
history. Small things, after all, sometimes lead to big changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an idea that some people have no history,'' said
Ronald Grele, the archive's director. ``It's a distortion of their
lives, carrying with it an implication that these people are
history-less. That they are less than historical. People live in
history and do historic things.''
</P>
<P>
   Grele is not a psychoanalyst, although he does interviews on the
development of analysis. But he and his colleagues are seeking the
details of a life story and how it emerges through memories and
contradictions that form even a public figure's persona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in the end of the story,'' Grele said.
``That's when you die, probably. I'm interested in the tension you
face in recreating yourself as something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. CLARK recalled an interview she did with Bella Abzug after
Ms. Abzug had left office, when she asked her when she became a
feminist. ``I was born a feminist,'' Ms. Abzug answered,
characteristically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later, I asked her why she ran for Congress,'' Ms. Clark said.
``Her face changed and became serene. `Well, I was deep sea
diving,' she said. She went through this long explanation that
there was nothing like deep sea diving, where she was totally calm
and serene and allowed to think and be like she was nowhere else.
That's when she decided to run for Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   That introspective moment contrasted sharply with the feminist
pioneer who had been unkindly portrayed in the press as pushy, loud
and unattractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took time to deconstruct the way the media had constructed
her own identity,'' Ms. Clark said. ``We looked at how she saw
herself before all that attention. But that attention was also how
she constructed that public persona and that affected her own
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Grele sees a uniquely American quality surfacing in many of the
interviews. It is a democratic force, of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can change and break boundaries, even though it comes at a
cost,'' he said. ``There is in American culture a very strong
ideology that you will change. That you will become a different
person.''
</P>
<P>
   And you will have a story, even if it's hard to get to, Ms.
Clark said. A few years ago, she helped a local nursery school
start a project on memories of babyhood. One boy insisted he
couldn't recall anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you remember anything?'' Ms. Clark nudged him. ``He
said: `There's one thing. I used to lie down a lot.' Everybody has
a story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
