<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-OBIT-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAYOR HELPED UNITE CITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Bradley, who as the city's longest-serving mayor guided Los
Angeles through a dramatic transformation and some of its most
difficult moments, died Tuesday of a heart attack. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Texas sharecroppers who became a Los Angeles
policeman, Bradley rose to political power in the 1960s as racial
tensions gripped the country. He was elected mayor in 1973 and
served five terms before retiring in 1993, a year after Los Angeles
was swept by racially charged rioting.
</P>
<P>
   During his 20 years in office, Bradley put together an enduring
coalition of business and labor that crossed ethnic lines while
overseeing the dramatic birth of the downtown skyline and the
subway as well as expansion of LAX and the harbor, opening Los
Angeles to international trade.
</P>
<P>
   An imposing 6 feet, 4 inches tall, Bradley became an
internationally recognized figure when Los Angeles hosted the
Olympics in 1984. He was the first African-American elected mayor
of Los Angeles and the first nominated by a major party to run for
governor of California, losing to George Deukmejian in 1982 and
1986.
</P>
<P>
   Tributes to Bradley poured in from around the country Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a builder, bringing a remarkably successful Olympic
Games to Los Angeles, encouraging a thriving downtown and improving
mass transit,'' President Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan, who succeeded Bradley, called it a sad
day for the city but also a reason to celebrate Bradley's
accomplishments during his 50 years of public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Watts Riot in the '60s, Tom Bradley came into office
and united a city that was divided,'' Riordan told the City
Council. ``He has left a great legacy for all Angelenos, from the
Olympics to the skyline to diversity that's united.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley died at 9 a.m. at Kaiser Permanente Hospital in Los
Angeles, after he had apparently suffered a heart attack an hour
earlier, officials said. He had been in the hospital for about a
week undergoing tests.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Bradley suffered a heart attack and a
debilitating stroke after undergoing a triple coronary bypass
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Despite difficulty walking and talking, Bradley began to make
public appearances, and his face would light up when he saw
familiar figures.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said tentative plans called for Bradley to lie in
state Monday at First AME Church, 2270 S. Harvard Blvd., Los
Angeles. Funeral services were tentatively set for Tuesday. Further
details will be released this week.
</P>
<P>
   To most, Bradley came to epitomize the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   Born Dec. 29, 1917, one of seven children of Texan cotton
sharecroppers, Bradley came to Los Angeles with his parents when he
was 7.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, he defied expectations and dealt with
racism and with political enemies with stoic dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Educated at Los Angeles public schools, Bradley won a
scholarship to University of California, Los Angeles, where he
became a track star.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Los Angeles Police Department, patrolling some of
the meanest streets in the city and rising to the rank of
lieutenant _ the highest post then ever attained by an
African-American. He went to law school in his spare time, as his
political ambitions began to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley drew his political support from the community, making
appearances at block meetings and in the churches. In 1963, he was
elected to the City Council where he was the second
African-American to serve on the body and the first to be elected
outright. Councilman Gilbert Lindsay had been appointed the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he offered was to articulate a vision for Los Angeles,''
said Ray Remy, one of several deputy mayors who served Bradley as
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Bradley was a symbol for urban cities across the country.
He was so liked and respected that you couldn't go anywhere in the
country without people coming up to him to meet him.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic consultant Richard Lichtenstein said Bradley was
unique for having healed racial wounds that had crippled Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who bridged communities at a very difficult time
in the city's history, coming after the Watts Riot,'' Lichtenstein
said. ``East meets west, north meets south. The city came together
under Bradley. You look at some of his accomplishments and it's
incredible. This guy had a vision and he delivered on it.''
</P>
<P>
   STORY CONTINUES IN SECOND TAKE &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
