<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEADING-LADIES-REVIEW     09-30 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEADING-LADIES-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MY FAVORITE BROADWAY': ALL STARS, ALL LADIES, ALL GLITTER, ALL
NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All-star benefit concerts are often poorly organized,
long-winded affairs in which the talent is pulled out of a grab bag
and a restless audience longs for a director's blue pencil. That's
why ``My Favorite Broadway: The Leading Ladies,'' a first-class
industrial show (for Continental Airlines) at Carnegie Hall on
Monday evening that also raised $50,000 for two AIDS charities,
came as a happy (and occasionally thrilling) surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The concert, which brought out the cream of younger Broadway
leading ladies, along with such veterans as Elaine Stritch, Dorothy
Loudon and Liza Minnelli (in sad vocal disrepair), kept the remarks
to a minimum and the pace swift. The radiant hostess, Julie
Andrews, told one sparkling anecdote about working with Moss Hart
on ``My Fair Lady,'' and that was it for the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   For the remainder of the evening, the singers, accompanied by a
well-rehearsed theater orchestra led by Paul Gemignani, offered a
fast-moving succession of star turns that ranged from the polished
to the dazzling.
</P>
<P>
   Women on Broadway have tended to fall into two types: brash
personality voices (Ethel Merman, Carol Channing) and semioperatic
ingenues (Ms. Andrews, Barbara Cook), with many shadings in
between. Generalizing about '90s leading ladies in comparison with
their predecessors, you might say that the personalities today
aren't as broad as they used to be, while on the semioperatic end,
the singing has technically improved, as frilly girlish voices have
given way to a fuller, more natural soprano tone.
</P>
<P>
   The one performer on Monday who seemed to embody everything that
is best about contemporary Broadway singing was the remarkable
Audra McDonald, who sang three numbers scattered throughout the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   In a version of Harold Arlen and Yip Harburg's ``Down With
Love,'' she accomplished the seemingly impossible, shading a rich
operatic voice into jazz and back without her singing sounding
affected or self-conscious. Delivering Jerry Herman's ``I've Never
Said I Love You,'' she wasn't afraid to break the rules of vocal
decorum to convey a bursting passion.
</P>
<P>
   Some other high points: Jennifer Holliday, elaborately coiffed
and unrecognizably slimmed down from her ``Dreamgirls'' days,
delivered a polished, sinuously jazzy ``If He Walked into My Life''
that found her working confidently far outside the growling and
grinding pop-gospel style that made her famous. (Later in the show,
her toned down ``And I'm Telling You I'm Not Going'' was less
successful.)
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ziemba, lithe and twinkling, joined a chorus line of 16
Rockettes in ``I Want to Be a Rockette,'' from the still-unproduced
Alan Menken-Tom Eyen musical ``Kicks.'' Rebecca Luker's sweet,
full-toned ``Falling in Love With Love'' was as flawlessly
delivered a traditional-style performance of the Rodgers and Hart
standard as you could hope to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Among the guests who re-enacted their Broadway show stoppers
were Faith Prince (``Adelaide's Lament''), Lea DeLaria (her
iconoclastic, bebop-flavored ``I Can Cook, Too''), Andrea McArdle
(now grown-up and glamorous, singing ``Tomorrow''), Linda Eder (a
Barbra Streisand-like ``Someone Like You''), Ms. Loudon (``Fifty
Percent'') and finally Ms. Stritch (a blistering, harshly funny
``The Ladies Who Lunch'').
</P>
<P>
   Producers and directors of future all-star concerts take note:
This is how it is done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
