<HEADER>
A1311 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-OBIT-2ndTake-     09-30 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-OBIT-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
LOS ANGELES: ``on it.'' As racial tension seized the nation, Los Angeles erupted in 1965
with the Watts Riots. Bradley, like other city officials, stood by
helplessly watching the city burn.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It prompted him four years later to take a major step and
challenge Mayor Sam Yorty in what was to become a bitter, racially
divisive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley lost but he did not lose his mayoral ambition, and he
used the four intervening years to build a coalition of minorities
and liberals that would serve to keep him in office for five terms
_ a record that will not be broken because of term limits.
</P>
<P>
   In winning the 1973 mayoral election, Bradley became a national
figure as the first minority candidate to be elected in a white
majority city in America.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bradley sought to ease the fears of downtown
business leaders and began an aggressive program to modernize and
build up the city where, at the time, the tallest building was City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was first elected, the city was deteriorating,''
Bradley said in the interview. ``It was dying at its heart.
Downtown Los Angeles was dead. Businesses were leaving in droves.
The infrastructure was deteriorating. And I made a commitment to
revitalize the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We not only revitalized downtown, we built a skyline _
something we never had. We established the importance of downtown
Los Angeles to the entire city.''
</P>
<P>
   That work included the creation of the Community Redevelopment
Agency, remodeling of Los Angeles International Airport, and
actively seeking federal funds for a variety of programs, including
the now much-beleaguered subway system.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic consultant Joe Cerrell credited Bradley with turning
Los Angeles into an international city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived here since 1951 and there was a time that
everything _ everything _ was based in San Francisco and the Bay
Area,'' Cerrell said. ``It was Tom Bradley who made Los Angeles as
important as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of his career, Bradley managed a city with a boom
economy. Even with cutbacks forced by the 1978 passage of
Proposition 13, he managed to continue or expand city programs.
</P>
<P>
   His focus on the downtown area would later be used against him
by opponents who said he had neglected needy areas of the city and
allowed unbridled growth at the expense of quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley said he believed his accomplishments helped set the
stage for Los Angeles to capitalize on its location as the gateway
to the Pacific Rim and that many of the city's problems could be
solved with the creation of jobs the development brought.
</P>
<P>
   By 1982, Bradley had a new political ambition _ to be governor
of California. Easily winning the Democratic nomination, Bradley
went on to strongly challenge then-Attorney General Deukmejian. On
Election Day, Bradley actually collected more votes than
Deukmejian. But Deukmejian narrowly won due to an aggressive
Republican effort in getting absentee ballots to supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Bradley would again challenge Deukmejian, but
lost by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   In between those defeats, Bradley oversaw what later he would
call his shining moment _ the 1984 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very special event,'' Bradley said. ``It was
literally a once-in-a-lifetime experience. What happened with the
magic of that event was unreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had policemen more concerned with trading Olympic pins than
stopping crime, because there was no crime. Crime took a holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   What was particularly fulfilling was that he and the city had
defied the experts and were able to stage an Olympic Games that
turned a profit even with the Soviet Union boycotting the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after the Russians pulled out, when people finally
realized the Games were going on, they said, We're going on,''
Bradley said. ``And then we had the torch run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of that torch run captivated people and we had the
spotlight of the whole world focused on Los Angeles for those 16
days.''
</P>
<P>
   There were low points, too.
</P>
<P>
   During his 1989 campaign, Bradley was accused of financial
improprieties by accepting $20,000 in consulting fees from Far East
National Bank while it was seeking and receiving city deposits.
Bradley would later return the money and pay a $20,000 fine for
failing to fully disclose his finances, but he was cleared of any
criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took two years of investigating by the FBI, the police, the
city attorney ... everyone and when it was all over, these
investigative bodies found just as I said _ there was no
impropriety,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the city again erupted into violence following the
acquittal of four police officers in the Rodney King beating in
Lake View Terrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked, saddened by it,'' Bradley said. ``We had a good
strategy to work with the community. We knew people would express
themselves, but we tried to contain it to verbal expressions. We
had people set to walk the neighborhoods to calm people. The rage
was understandable, the violence wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Years after that violence, Bradley said he continued to believe
the riots developed because police failed to respond immediately to
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The failure of the police to deploy their personnel and stifle
the incipient looting and burning that took place in the early
stages permitted it to get out of hand,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   But through all the ups and downs, Bradley remained an
indomitable spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a day when I regret any one thing I've done,'' he
once said. ``This has been the greatest experience, the greatest
satisfaction, anyone could ever know.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
