<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULAR-GUY WELLS MAKES RANGERS HITTERS LOOK ORDINARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Wells may be the only Yankees star who can
actually disappear in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   He peels off his double-X pinstripes, which can barely contain
that bulging body anyway, and suddenly he's the ordinary Joe at the
end of the bar, chin dripping grease from a double-cheeseburger,
ordering a shot and a beer and maybe a round for the house.
</P>
<P>
   Or he's the guy behind the counter, once-white apron stained and
dingy, pulling down a tall, foamy mug of brew, and swiping a wet
rag over the bar with a beefy arm before sending it sliding down to
a thirsty customer.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe he's the dusty truck driver, just rolling in the door
after a long haul, so tired even his tattoos are aching.
</P>
<P>
   There was no disappearing act in Wells' repertoire last night,
though.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee's Round Mound of Frown, author of the most dominating
pitching performance of the 1998 season, pitched the Yankees to a
2-0 victory against the Rangers in Game 1 of the Division Series in
front of a raucous sellout crowd at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The loss makes a victory tonight by Rick Helling and the Rangers
imperative. They cannot afford to limp home to Texas, down 0-2 to
the Yanks in a best-of-five series, if they harbor any hope of
playing beyond the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers insisted that Yankees manager Joe Torre was playing
right into the Rangers' hands by starting Wells last night and Andy
Pettitte tonight in the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat after me: The Rangers KILL left-handers. They eat 'em for
breakfast, hot off the griddle, like fresh flapjacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers led the majors with a .316 average off southpaw
chunkers. Left-handed starters were a pug-ugly 12-23 with a 6.49
earned-run average in 48 regular-season starts against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   What could Torre possibly be thinking, sending a ``left-hander''
out to face the likes of right-handed power hitters Gonzalez,
Rodriguez, Kelly, Zeile and Simms.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this wasn't just any left-hander. This was the Wells
who coughed up a seven-run lead against the Rangers in the first
week in May, then shut them out the next time he saw them.
</P>
<P>
   This was the 250-pound lover of hard rock who last season
threatened to kick Yankees owner George Steinbrenner's butt all the
way down to the Bowery and back.
</P>
<P>
   This was the 35-year-old southpaw who just happened to throw the
first regular-season perfect game in Yankees history back on May 17
on the way to an 18-4 record as the anchor of the Yankees'
spectacular starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Until Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa turned Roger Maris' home-run
record into jelly, that was the most fitting signature moment of
this wild and wacky season, a perfect game from the most imperfect
source.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the Yankees last season, Wells has gone 34-14, and
his stock has soared with Torre.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a battler now,'' Torre said. ``Now, when he's running on
fumes or doesn't have his good stuff, he finds a way to get people
out; he finds a way to stay in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   You saw him last night, an unkempt hulk of a man, the top button
of his jersey undone, his shirttail flapping, his grizzled
double-chin sagging, mesmerizing the Rangers' hitters with soft,
off-speed pitches outside and hard fastballs in on their fists when
they began leaning across the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty he isn't, but he could run for mayor of New York City
today and Rudolph Giuliani, popular as he may be, would be out on
his ear in a Manhattan minute.
</P>
<P>
   Add it up. Gonzalez, Rodriguez, Kelly, Zeile and Simms? A
combined 2-for-18. Two measly singles. Five red faces.
</P>
<P>
   Wells' eight innings were marked by the Rangers' consistently
ineffectual hacks. They didn't get a ball out of the infield until
there were two out in the third. They didn't get their first hit
until Rusty Greer singled off shortstop Derek Jeter's glove in the
fourth. They never pushed a runner past second base and only got
that far twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has been a team that really gives me problems,'' Wells
said after running his shutout string against the Rangers to 19
innings. ``I have to study the (video) tapes hard when I face them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so complete and they have so many great hitters, I
have to keep them off balance. I just go out there, stay focused
and try to make good pitches. If my game is on, not too many teams
are going to score a lot of runs.''
</P>
<P>
   In his eight superb innings, Wells gave up five hits, walked one
and struck out nine. The Rangers actually seemed relieved when
flame-throwing Mariano Rivera came on for the ninth. Three outs
later, it was mercifully over.
</P>
<P>
   The shame of it is that the Rangers wasted Todd Stottlemyre's
scrappy six-hitter. They came here believing that if they could get
good pitching, they could win.
</P>
<P>
   But if they thought that's all it would take to make the Yankees
disappear, they'd best reconsider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 0042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
