<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1320 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     09-30 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT A WASTE! RANGERS BLOW A GREAT CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bats are never forever. Over the course of a baseball
season, they come, they go. Maybe you've heard: Good pitching will
cause wood to rot.
</P>
<P>
   For the '98 Rangers, of course, the bats have beaten the
percentages. This is a team that, over the six-month long haul,
finally rode a load of timber into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, however.
</P>
<P>
   The ride just got real short. It's either hit now or trudge
quietly into winter.
</P>
<P>
   The second-worst thing that happened to the Rangers here last
night was the brilliant shutout pitching by New York's David Wells.
The absolute negative, however, was that no run support wasted a
gutty eight innings from Todd Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   A shock-the-world upset for the Rangers in this playoff series
is dependent upon stellar rotation work. They got it in Game 1, and
still didn't cash, falling, 2-0, to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief five-game series, that simply can't happen. It did,
and now the Rangers are in an early hole that wasn't exactly
unexpected, but ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a critical loss; any loss is critical in a short
series,'' said Rangers hitting instructor Rudy Jaramillo in a
somber postgame clubhouse. ``Then again, we didn't exactly come
into this thing not expecting to see good pitching from the
Yankees. They didn't win 114 games without good pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, we tip our hats to Wells. He was outstanding. But we
also move on and build on what we faced tonight. Our bats tend to
bounce back in a hurry. Good hitters rebound, and we do have good
hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for solving Wells, which is a very strong exception, the
Rangers had a solid postseason debut. Stottlemyre was scrambling,
particularly early, but he made clutch pitches and had clutch
defense behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Kelly, starting in center field, reached high over the
fence in right-center to knock a home run back into play. Tino
Martinez settled for a double and was left stranded.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Stottlemyre should have surrendered only one run, but
catcher Pudge Rodriguez brain-locked on a double steal in the
second inning. His throw to second, without checking Chad Curtis
back to third base, allowed Curtis to trot home with the second run
of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Wells never had to sweat the tying runs being in
scoring position. Actually, Wells never sweated much. The Rangers
had runners at first and second only once in the game, and that
left Mike Simms with a two-out chance in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Simms had a great at-bat against Wells,'' said
Jaramillo. Wells had to use nine pitches on Simms after jumping
ahead 0-2 in the count. At 3-and-2, and with the runners moving,
Simms was suckered by a curveball, and fanned.
</P>
<P>
   The shutout by Wells in Game 1 created an unpleasant flashback
for the Rangers. Two years ago, in an entertaining and tight
playoff series with the Yankees, only Juan Gonzalez provided any
offensive muscle. Juan had a headline series with five homers and
nine RBI in four games.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, however, Gonzalez was a weak 0-for-4, not that a
weak 0-for-4 was anything unusual in the Rangers' batting order.
Juan had three shots at Wells, including a runner at second in the
first inning and a runner on in the fourth, but the ball never left
the infield.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a foul pop to the catcher in the seventh was his
``longest'' blow. Otherwise, Gonzalez struck out and topped a pitch
two feet in front of the plate. Leading off the ninth against
closer Mariano Rivera, he flied out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I want is for Juan to think it's either him or
we sink,'' said manager Johnny Oates. ``Juan can't do this alone,
and he hasn't this season. As great as he is, he's got to have help
from the rest of the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Help never arrived against Wells. So without any other option,
the Rangers now have to fall back on the obvious crutch: They came
in here to win one of the first two games of the series. That is
still possible tonight against another Yankees left-hander, Andy
Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   The fact still remains, however, that Stottlemyre gave the
Rangers exactly what they needed in Game 1. That's why it's a loss
that makes them even a longer shot in this series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
