<SLUG> BC-LIFE-PLANETS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF WASHINGTON OFFERS ASTROBIOLOGY DOCTORAL PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Scientists searching for life on other planets will
soon be able to earn a Ph.D. while they're at it.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Washington plans to launch the first doctoral
program in the country to focus on the emerging field of
astrobiology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that there is a good possibility that life exists
in the solar system outside Earth,'' James Staley, a UW
microbiologist and the lead researcher for the new astrobiology
program, said Tuesday. ``If that life does exist it would be
microbial, not the higher forms.''
</P>
<P>
   To hunt down those microscopic extraterrestrial life forms, if
they exist, will require a marriage of the physical and life
sciences. The new program, which is being paid for with a 5-year,
$2 million grant from the National Science Foundation and a
$500,000 grant from the University, will draw together 11 different
disciplines ranging from astronomy to microbiology.
</P>
<P>
   Students will get their doctorates in one of those disciplines,
but it will include an endorsement noting an emphasis in
astrobiology. Students will take coursework in a variety of the
participating departments, depending on their research interests.
</P>
<P>
   The degree program, which will support about a dozen graduate
students beginning the fall quarter of 1999, will produce its first
full-fledged Ph.D.'s in five to six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most, but not all, researchers in this interdisciplinary field
`believe' that life has probably evolved elsewhere in the universe,
possibly even elsewhere in our own solar system,'' said Richard
Gammon, a professor of chemistry and oceanography at the UW, and
one of the scientists who wrote a financing proposal for the new
degree program.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely places to start looking for new life forms are
Mars, where there is evidence of water, and Europa, the icy moon of
Jupiter, scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the discovery of fossil-like impressions in a Martian
meteorite two years ago, scientists have been captivated with the
notion that there is life out there, said Woody Sullivan, astronomy
professor and adjunct professor of the history of science at the
UW, who is a co-investigator in the astrobiology program.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of life no longer seems far-fetched, he said.
``Nature is often far cleverer than we can be in our imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientific belief in the possibility of microbial life on other
planets has been building since the recent discovery of novel
microorganisms that thrive in extreme environments, such as deep
ocean vents, hot springs, or pools of brine within polar sea ice.
</P>
<P>
   The DNA _ the molecule that carries the hereditary information
of living cells _ of those organisms suggests a very ancient
lineage, which means they may be precursors of advanced life on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have microbial systems on Earth that are good models for
those on Mars or Europa, and those systems are poorly studied,''
Staley said. Understanding those systems better could give
scientists clues for where to discover life on other planets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just scraping around on Mars doesn't tell you much at all,''
said Sullivan. ``Ten to 15 years from now, we'd like to be able to
drill down pretty far under the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA is planning missions within two decades that would give
scientists the opportunity to bring back such samples, Sullivan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Finding life outside of Earth would help human beings understand
our own biology better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more different systems you know about, the better we can
understand our own,'' he said. Being able to learn about the
weather on Mars, for example, has contributed vastly to scientists'
understanding of weather on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true of life too,'' Sullivan said. ``If we could just
find one other example.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the past three years, astronomers have been able to
observe planets going around stars other than our own sun. The
discovery of those new solar systems has also fueled speculation
about life on those new planets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's so on ours,'' he said, ``why not on others?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
