<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GONZALEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES HOLD GONZALEZ IN CHECK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two years ago he was being called ``Senor Octubre''.
Last night he was just another easy out in the Rangers lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez, who drove in 157 runs for the Rangers this year
and terrorized the Yankees pitching staff in the 1996 playoffs, was
rendered ineffective by David Wells and Mariano Rivera in a 2-0
loss last night.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez went 0-for-4 with a strikeout, a far cry from his
7-for-16, five-home run performance in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of expectations from myself,'' Gonzalez said.
``But I'm only one player; there are eight others. I tried the best
I can between the lines. That's all I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's first at-bat was his only one with a runner in
scoring position, and it symbolized his frustrating evening. He
tried to check his swing on a slow curve and tapped the ball out in
front of home plate. Before he realized what had happened, Yankees
catcher Jorge Posada was on the ball and throwing him out at first
base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed hits with men on base,'' Gonzalez said. ``We didn't
get them. But we had no chance against Wells. He's one of the best
left-handers in the game, and he threw a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells took the approach that most pitchers do with Gonzalez:
slow curves and changeups, try to get him to chase something out of
the strike zone. After Rusty Greer reached on a one-out single in
the fourth, Wells struck out Gonzalez. He got him to foul out to
Posada in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make good pitches to all their hitters, especially
Juan,'' Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's fourth at-bat came against Rivera, the Yankees'
closer, leading off the ninth. Gonzalez got the ball out of the
infield, but it was nothing more than a routine fly to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good at the plate,'' Gonzalez said. ``But what can you
say except Wells pitched a great game: good changeup, good curve,
threw strikes. We had no chance. But this game is history. Tomorrow
is another day.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates said: ``Certainly we depend on Juan
a lot, but we have two other guys with 100 RBI, and another one
with 80. Certainly Juan is a big part, but he can't do it all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
