<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS DOMINATES RANGERS IN SERIES OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thirty-three times the Rangers sent a player from
their dugout to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   This recurring procession in Game 1 of their best-of-five,
American League Division Series with the Yankees resembled pigs _
no insult or disrespect intended _ being prepared for slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   That's because left-hander David Wells reduced the Rangers'
powerful lineup to little more than bacon bits during New York's
2-0 victory Tuesday night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Wells surrendered only five hits and one walk through eight
innings before being replaced in favor of right-hander Mariano
Rivera, who retired the side in order _ including a game-ending
strikeout of catcher Ivan Rodriguez _ to complete the Yankees'
dominating pitching performance.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who pitched a six-hit shutout Aug. 21 in the Yankees' 5-0
victory at The Ballpark in Arlington, threw first-pitch strikes to
21 of 30 batters and unveiled a curveball without peer in his duel
with right-hander Todd Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw strikes and probably had the best curveball I've ever
seen from him,'' said first baseman Will Clark, who collected one
of the Rangers' four singles. ``We had a lot of good at-bats, a lot
of 3-2 counts and a lot of hitter's counts, but _ as with
Stottlemyre _ every time he needed to a make a pitch, he threw a
hellacious pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre _ who allowed only 10 base runners during his
121-pitch, complete-game effort _ pitched well enough to win most
nights, but not on this night, with his father, Yankees pitching
coach Mel Stottlemyre, sitting in the opposing dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Not once while on the mound did Stottlemyre glance at his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got the rest of my life to look at him. I didn't even
think about looking at him,'' Stottlemyre said. ``I love him
dearly, but I'll be damned if I was thinking about him. I was
thinking about the Yankees' hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' two-run second inning proved labor intensive for
Stottlemyre, who threw 27 pitches to five batters. The right-hander
threw first-pitch strikes to four of those, but designated hitter
Chili Davis, catcher Jorge Posada and second baseman Chuck
Knoblauch worked their plate appearances for full counts.
</P>
<P>
   Posada drew a one-out walk and advanced to third on an ensuing
double by left fielder Chad Curtis, whose drive to right field
eluded the glove of Juan Gonzalez after a lengthy chase.
</P>
<P>
   Posada scored three pitches later on a single by third baseman
Scott Brosius, the Yankees' No. 9 hitter with the .300 batting
average. Curtis advanced 90 feet and later scored on the series'
first mental blunder.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre retired Knoblauch on strikes, but Brosius ran on the
3-2 pitch. Rodriguez threw to second base, but he erred by not
freezing Curtis with a glance toward third base. Second baseman
Mark McLemore took the throw, and Brosius stayed in the rundown
long enough for Curtis to cross the plate without a throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave the sign for Pudge to look the runner back and throw
through,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``I'm not sure what
happened, but we didn't execute well. Pudge made a good throw. I'm
just not sure if he looked the runner back or not. I'm not sure
where the breakdown was.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells did the rest and came through twice during the latter
innings with seventh- and eighth-inning strikeouts of designated
hitter Mike Simms and center fielder Roberto Kelly, respectively,
with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crunch time,'' Wells said. ``I thrive on this kind of
stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
