<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFFS START AND ALL WE GET IS MR. PEANUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Usually, as in since 1995, the baseball postseason has
presented Seattle with some pretty interesting autumn days.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the good ol' Yankees stop by for a little fifth-game,
winner-take-all, 11-inning engagement. Or that nice team from
Cleveland, the one with Omar and Mike Jackson, shows up for some
American League Championship Series contests.
</P>
<P>
   Once _ it was just last October _ Cal Ripken, Mike Mussina and
Eric Davis came through as the Orioles won two big ones in front of
monstrous Kingdome crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Seattle was starting to get hooked on the special taste of
the baseball postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was not one of those special days in Seattle. The
Yankees got the Rangers. Cleveland got Big Mo Vaughn and the Red
Sox. The Astrodome was all abuzz with the promise of Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle got Johnny Bench and Mr. Peanut.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Famer and the world's most famous goober made a
special appearance at F.X. McRory's. The Pioneer Square restaurant
turns hot spot whenever a big baseball game is going on across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was no such day. Bench and Mr. Peanut were in town
simply to conduct a search for the Most Valuable Peanut Seller in
all of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our postseason,'' said Rick the Peanut Man _ the
Kingdome's most famous vendor who is as dismayed as any Mariner fan
that autumn will be dead silent in Seattle while a 1998 postseason
that all but screams, ``Can You Top This?'' is played out in other
baseball cities.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the fact that the M's were not part of the postseason
accounted for the quiet lunchtime crowd at McRory's.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell no one's into baseball around here right now,''
Bench said, trying to keep things lively as he conducted the upbeat
contest for the Most Valuable Peanut Seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they pay you to do a job, you've got to go out and do your
all,'' said Bench, who joked with contestants, signed autographs
and said he was not jealous that former Big Red Machine teammate
Joe Morgan was calling games for ESPN while Bench was hawking
peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Peanuts, like baseball, is a cause that the Hall of Fame catcher
is passionate about ``because peanuts have always been a part of my
life,'' Bench said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From working in the peanut factories as a kid in Oklahoma, to
all my years spent in ballparks. I've seen some very talented
vendors who, just like ballplayers, work hard at their profession
and have a loyal fan following.''
</P>
<P>
   So Bench was pretty passionate during the lunchtime contest,
which was in full swing just as the Red Sox were wrapping up an
11-3 whipping of Cleveland, and just as Randy Johnson was trying to
keep up with San Diego's Kevin Brown, who turned in an awesome
16-strikeout win over the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   With playoff action kicking off in Houston, Cleveland and New
York, the TV is the only way Seattleites can get a look at the
other lucky teams and the other lucky cities who get to keep this
Mark McGwire/Sammy Sosa home-run-derby season going into late
October.
</P>
<P>
   The TV is the place where Mariner fans can look up and remember
when, in '95, it was Johnson and the M's who pounded the Angels in
that one-game playoff that brought Seattle its first American
League West championship.
</P>
<P>
   And it was that '95 experience that made any good Mariner fan
look at Cubs third baseman Gary Gaetti and think:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah. That seems so familiar. The journeyman infielder
belts a homer to become the unlikely hero of the Cubs' win over San
Francisco, just like Luis Sojo ripped that hit down the line that
drove in all those Mariner runs to beat Mark Langston and those
swooning Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing like the postseason, if you're in it,'' Bench
said Tuesday, after Bench crowned Rick the Peanut Man the MV Peanut
Seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole different smell. Whole different feeling.
Everybody else is in a better mood. The Yankees won 114 games this
season. They could lose in five games to the Rangers and it's over.
That's the thing about the postseason. It's 0-0,'' Bench said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year I was MVP of the World Series, I didn't have a great
season. I was coming off surgery in '76, but when we got to the
playoffs it was a different story. I went about .400 in the
playoffs and .545 in the World Series. You just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the '98 Mariners, as for Seattle, we have reached the end
of the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our postseason,'' Rick the Peanut Man said, clutching
his MV Peanut Seller first-prize check for $500 and a round-trip
ticket to New York where, on Oct. 7, Rick ``The Peanut Man''
Kaminski will compete for the national peanut-seller title against
winners from nine other cities.
</P>
<P>
   How sad is it that the M's and Seattle are left out of the
postseason? How mad are some of the diehard baseball lovers?
</P>
<P>
   ``We wound up paying Heathcliff Slocumb $1 million per save,''
said Rick the Peanut Man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of customers this season saying, `Let the Peanut
Man pitch.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those Mariner fans were on to something. For now, Rick
the Peanut Man is the only one left playing.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 0112EDT &QL; 
