<HEADLINE>
MARINERS PICK UP OPTION TO BRING MARTINEZ BACK FOR 13TH SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The welfare of friends and family have been on his
mind, with Hurricane Georges raging through his native Puerto Rico.
So has impending knee surgery. But Edgar Martinez had one less
worry Tuesday when the Mariners picked up the option year on his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will pay Martinez $3.5 million to return for a 13th
season in Seattle, assuring the two-time American League batting
champion of a chance to play at new Safeco Field, which opens next
July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to be back,'' the 35-year-old designated hitter
said. ``It's a lot of peace of mind to know I'm going to be with
the team. It is the only team I've played with. I'd like to keep it
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   In this age of transient big-leaguers, only four active players
have played longer with the same team _ Baltimore's Cal Ripken Jr.
(18 years), San Diego's Tony Gwynn (17), Anaheim's Chuck Finley
(13) and Cincinnati's Barry Larkin (13).
</P>
<P>
   Despite a slow start this season, Martinez left the club with
little choice but to re-sign him by hitting .322 with 46 doubles,
29 home runs and 102 RBIs. It marked the seventh time in nine full
seasons in the majors that he has finished above .300.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners told Martinez a week ago they would pick up his
option, but, because of club policy, waited until the season ended
to announce it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a pretty easy decision to keep this guy around,''
said Woody Woodward, vice president of baseball operations. ``I can
honestly tell you I figured Edgar would hit .280 to .300. That's
been his history.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, that's going to slow down, but I don't think
we'll see it next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez briefly mulled retirement after the 1997 season, when
there was talk the DH would be eliminated, and again at midseason,
when his name was mentioned in rumored trades involving the New
York Yankees and Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Martinez will have outpatient knee surgery and is
concerned about the recovery time, which could put him up against
the start of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   He also has been on the phone checking in with storm-ravaged
friends and family in Puerto Rico. He owns his family home there,
which he said received minimal damage. An aunt lost everything.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez, who made $3.3 million last season, has job
security, at least for one more year. How much longer he can extend
his career is unclear. He smiled when asked if he could play as
long as Paul Molitor, who recently retired at 42.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends if I'm playing good and the team is doing well
and they want me back,'' Martinez said. ``We'll have to wait and
see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
