<SLUG> BC-BKW-REIGN-STARBIRD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REIGN SEEK MORE OUT OF STARBIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Kate Starbird is talking about last season, trying to
analyze what, in her words, ``did me in.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she reconsiders that choice of words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, not `did me in' _ I look at my stats, and I don't
think they were that terrible,'' said Starbird, who averaged 12.7
points per game for the ABL Reign in her first professional season.
``I learned a lot about passing and other things, getting the ball
in the post. But I wasn't able to do what I do well, and I want to
go back to being able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Starbird can be devastating on a court, something area fans have
known for years. At Lakes High School in Tacoma, she became the
state's all-time scoring leader. She followed that with a standout
career at Stanford, winning the Naismith Award as the nation's top
player as a senior in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But when she returned to the area as an ABL rookie last year,
Starbird didn't dominate. She was third on the Reign in scoring,
but at 6-foot-2, 150 pounds, Starbird was outmuscled and sometimes
an offensive afterthought. She scored 20 or more points five times
in her first 15 games, but not once in her last 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unfortunate that people put some type of unrealistic
expectations on anyone coming right out of college who doesn't
necessarily have a strong professional body at that time,'' said
Reign coach Tammy Holder. ``The physical play and the wear and tear
is something that would take some getting used to and be a
challenge for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It was especially challenging for a two-guard like Starbird,
whose strength was her team's primary weakness. Starbird is best in
the open court, but the Reign had trouble executing their
transition game and struggled to a 15-29 record. After a midseason
coaching change, the Reign concentrated more on high-percentage
shots, giving more opportunities to post players and fewer to
perimeter players.
</P>
<P>
   Starbird, in turn, tried to gear her game away from what she did
best. After a while, she realized that with her size, she simply
can't do what bigger players do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let myself be held, and everyone was telling me you've got
to be physical and push people off, and that's not my game,''
Starbird said. ``What I have to do is be Reggie Miller _ he's not
going to push somebody off, but he's going to get open by being
quicker. So I've got to get back to my strength.''
</P>
<P>
   But while counting on fitting her game into the pro ranks,
Starbird acknowledged she had to get bigger and spent much of the
offseason trying to do so. She spent the summer lifting weights
three times a week and cut down significantly on her distance
running.
</P>
<P>
   The result? She's up to 158 pounds, and after two practices,
Holder has noticed more accuracy and strength on Starbird's passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's gotten a lot stronger,'' said Reign guard Kate Paye, a
teammate of Starbird's for two years at Stanford. ``She was down in
the Bay Area working out, and she spent a lot of time in the weight
room. Physically, she looks bigger to me, and that should help her
strength on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reign welcome that, but they also plan to get the Stanford
Starbird back on the court. Holder and her staff have had time now
to craft their own offense, and the plan is to make Starbird a more
integral part.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about this year, and the potential for this
season, is we are looking to bring a faster-paced tempo into our
game plan,'' Holder said. ``We will be looking to do more things
off the break, and that will accentuate what Kate Starbird can
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
