<SLUG> BC-FBC-COUGARS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 WSU's BIRNBAUM KEEPS STARTING ROLE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Washington State junior quarterback Steve Birnbaum
will retain his starting role and is expected to play the entire
game against UCLA on Saturday, Cougar coach Mike Price said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That means Price won't alternate Birnbaum with sophomore Paul
Mencke as he did last Saturday against California.
</P>
<P>
   Price said he has no plans to continue shuffling the two
quarterbacks and that an evaluation of both players showed Birnbaum
out-performed Mencke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quarterback who gives us the best chance to win needs to
be on the field most of the time, and that's Steve Birnbaum,''
Price said. ``Steve is going to go the whole distance if that's
what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Price believes Birnbaum has performed better in game situations,
though Mencke hasn't had as many chances.
</P>
<P>
   After four games, Birnbaum has completed 59 of 122 passes for
824 yards, with a pass efficiency rating of 110.42. He's thrown
five touchdown passes and five interceptions. In the three games he
has appeared in, Mencke has completed eight of 20 passes for 133
yards, two TDs and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Against Cal, both quarterbacks threw for a touchdown, but each
gave up an interception for a touchdown in WSU's 24-14 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was obvious that both quarterbacks can and need to
play better,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGING HORSES: Although he won't switch starting quarterbacks,
Price did announce a couple of offensive changes. Wide receiver
Jerry Roquemore and running back Kevin Brown, both junior college
transfers from San Francisco City College, will start in place of
injured receiver Nian Taylor (calf muscle, questionable for UCLA)
and fumble-prone running back DeJuan Gilmore.
</P>
<P>
   Against Cal, Roquemore had a 29-yard touchdown catch, while
Brown gained 80 yards on 15 carries without fumbling the ball.
</P>
<P>
   It was Brown's best output since he gained 111 yards in the
season opener against Illinois. Gilmore (239 net yards rushing) has
one more yard than Brown's cumulative total, but he's fumbled four
times this season. Against Cal, one fumble killed a WSU scoring
drive on the first offensive series and another was returned for a
Bear touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Price also said free safety Lamont Thompson would see more
playing time at wide receiver. Thompson had one pass thrown his way
against Cal, but Price plans to use him in the offense on at least
five plays against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA BYE: With UCLA (2-0) getting last weekend off when
Hurricane Georges forced the cancellation of the Bruins' game
against Miami, Price was asked how it might affect Saturday's game
against the Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got them right where we want them,'' he joked.
``They lost a lot of momentum by not playing last week. They are
way too fresh, too healthy, with way too many good football players
to choose from. That will create indecision on the part of the
coaches. Boy, it's a mess, those poor guys.''
</P>
<P>
   On the serious side, Price offered his true assessment: ``They
are really healthy. They have a lot of players back now. They are
all really fresh, they've got their legs and have been practicing
the same stuff for two weeks now without anybody to bang them up.
They are probably licking their chops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
