u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-685&AMP;ADD-1STLD     09-30 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-685&AMP;ADD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIDES STEP BACK FROM AN ALLY'S PLANS FOR `WAR' AGAINST
GINGRICH
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to clarify reference to group that is planning
ad campaign.) 
 (See also CLINTON-CANTON, CLINTON-SALON, CLINTON-JONES,
CLINTON-IMPEACH) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES BENNETT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to reassure congressional Democrats that
President Clinton feels more contrite than belligerent about his
affair, the White House distanced him Tuesday from a declaration of
``war'' on House Speaker Newt Gingrich by James Carville, the
president's longtime political lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry also said a planned
advertising campaign by a group of labor representatives and other
traditionally Democratic supporters to buttress the president would
be better directed at helping Democratic congressional candidates.
But the group, People for the American Way, said it would go
forward with its advertising as soon as next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior adviser to the president also said plans to help raise
several million dollars for a separate pro-Clinton advertising
campaign had been scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   The White House moves were signs of nervousness over the shaky
support for the president among Democrats on Capitol Hill.
Democrats complained about the comments from Carville, in a
television appearance on Sunday, and also worried that the
advertising might siphon money from their cause. Carville, who
managed the president's campaign in 1992, has been an informal
unpaid adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The moves also underscored the trouble the White House is having
as it tries for the right political blend of contrition,
conciliation and attack.
</P>
<P>
   The president's aides and allies argue that in criticizing
Congress, Clinton is helping himself by helping his party in the
November elections. But at times, the president can sound like a
different man than the humble penitent who apologized to a roomful
of clerics three weeks ago. At a $10,000-a-plate fund-raiser here
Monday night, he argued that the furor over his affair with a
former White House intern might help Democrats by motivating
normally apathetic voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adversity is our friend in the sense that at least everyone is
now thinking about the political debate,'' he said. ``I'd do nearly
anything to help the Democrats get elected, but this is a little
bit extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks came a day after Carville announced that ``Corporal
Cue Ball Carville will be rolling into battle against Newt
Gingrich'' on the NBC News program ``Meet the Press.'' Carville
called Gingrich a ``a sanctioned, certified, adjudicated and
confessed liar.'' He spoke after being read critical comments by
the Speaker about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The White House asserted Tuesday that Carville was not speaking
for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made it quite clear that he will not be muzzled by
anybody,'' McCurry said of Carville.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry also said he did not think Carville's attack on Gingrich
was ``particularly helpful, and I think there are others who share
that opinion here.'' But, he added, ``there may be some people who
think it's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for the president's judgment, McCurry said Clinton planned
to stick with ``the very careful, dignified approach that we've
been bringing to the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt called the White House on
Monday to criticize Carville's approach as counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic congressional aide said it might make Democrats
look overly partisan. Democrats in marginal districts want to be
able to assure both Clinton loyalists and people who favor
impeachment that they are intent only on fulfilling constitutional
obligations, the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks as if they're somehow in collusion with a larger
partisan agenda that's being orchestrated by the White House,'' the
aide added.
</P>
<P>
   Carville said he was operating completely on his own, as he
served notice in an interview that he would not back down, citing
criticisms of the president by Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever Newt Gingrich writes a letter of apology for calling
him a misogynist and a criminal, then I'll withdraw my battle
plans,'' he said. ``But until that time I'll proceed,
notwithstanding the judgment of some people in the White House.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton's criticism of Congress for fighting him on issues like
education and health care will help Democrats, said Mark Mellman, a
Democratic pollster who is informally advising the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think he's apologized enough,'' Mellman said. ``There
is a belief that this Republican Congress is more interested in
investigations and in partisan impeachment hearings than they are
in solving people's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   People for the American Way said that despite White House
objections, it would proceed with television advertising attacking
the Republican Congress as obsessed with scandal. Nancy Coleman, a
spokeswoman for the group, said it was still raising money for the
commercials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
