u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SIMMONS-     09-30 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SIMMONS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEHAWKS' SIMMONS BACK IN LINEUP AS A RESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ His knee is wrapped in a black protective
sleeve, weakened by a strange preseason tumble to the AstroTurf.
When he went down, Anthony Simmons was a starting candidate at
middle linebacker who had never been injured. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   Back on his feet after a six-week layoff, the Seahawks' top
draft choice from Clemson finds himself shifted to outside
linebacker, stuck in a reserve role.
</P>
<P>
   Besides partially torn cartilage, what gives?
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, it appears, was headed for a new assignment even before
he went down in a heap, untouched, against the Dallas Cowboys. In
his brief audition in the middle, nearly a dozen plays, he
floundered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't get off to a good start,'' said Jim Johnson,
linebacker coach. ``He didn't look good in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than label him a bust, the Seahawks chose to give Simmons
less responsibility and a chance to flourish once healthy. His
speed was too good to waste. They took away the play calling. They
removed him from the two-sided assault. He was turned inside out.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the fleet-footed first-rounder _ labeled the
fastest linebacker in the draft _ has done well on the outside,
getting a handful of snaps against Washington and a dozen more
against Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons showed his 4.45-second, 40-yard speed against the
Steelers on one particular play, running down a receiver on a
screen pass that had potential as a long gainer.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly, the 6-foot-1, 230-pound defender, who was signed to a
six-year, $7 million contract, seems content in his new position.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's up to the staff, up to the coaches, in how they want to
do things,'' Simmons said. ``I'll play anywhere. They brought me in
to play football. They didn't bring me here to play one position _
I'm a linebacker. Wherever they want to put me, I'm happy to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons backs up outside linebacker starters Darrin Smith and
Chad Brown, his playing time sure to increase now that reserve
James Logan is out for the season after breaking a leg in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Simmons move also was encouraged after fellow rookie DeShone
Myles showed he could stand in there and handle the middle. Oddly
enough, Myles was a four-year college starter playing outside
linebacker, at Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough on him,'' Johnson said of Simmons. ``He goes
out six weeks and he doesn't know where he fits in. I think he's
responded well. I think he's got his confidence back. With the
injury, he wasn't sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons was even more mystified by his injury _ a knee sprain
and partially torn anterior cruciate ligament. In high school and
college, he never had any kind of surgery, splint or stitch. He
never missed a game.
</P>
<P>
   Running the field against the Cowboys in preseason, he planted
and collapsed a good distance from any opponent. He later looked at
film to see what caused the mishap. No answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running and I fell,'' he said. ``I don't know how it
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons sat out the final four exhibition games and the first
two regular-season contests. He went to meetings, lifted weights
and spent time in the training room. Everything except take the
field on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Simmons was the Seahawks' first-rounder, teammates
were eager to see what he could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he can play,'' defensive end Michael Sinclair said.
``The only thing we wondered is when is he going to get a chance?''
</P>
<P>
   Early this week, Seahawk coach Dennis Erickson made a point of
praising Simmons' play against the Steelers. Even with the loss of
Logan, Erickson suggested the club doesn't necessarily need to find
a linebacker replacement, so solid is the group on hand.
</P>
<P>
   As for Simmons, he won't be the man in the middle any more this
season. Next year might be different. Besides, not every linebacker
is cut out to play the position. Smith plays middle and outside,
but is best suited for the former. Brown is far more effective
outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say he stays outside, I don't know,'' Johnson said of
Simmons' middle linebacker aspirations. ``Some guys can do it, some
guys can't.''
</P>
<P>
   HAWK TALK: Two linebackers are scheduled to work out for the
Seahawks Wednesday _ Ray Farmer, who was released by Philadelphia
earlier this month; and Toran James, who was released by San Diego
in August. The club also might bring in another linebacker or two
in its quest to replace James Logan, who broke his left leg in
Sunday's game at Pittsburgh. There is no urgency to sign someone
because the sprained knee that forced rookie DeShone Myles to sit
out the past two games has improved and he is expected to practice
Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
