<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-MCMILLAN-SPI </SLUG>
  
 McMILLAN NOW A SONICS COACH  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Nate McMillan knew a few years ago he would become a
coach. It was almost as if he had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   George Karl practically insisted. Tim Grgurich always encouraged
him. Tuesday, Paul Westphal snared McMillan, the Sonics' newest
assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan, who retired last season after 12 years in the NBA,
joined Dwane Casey and Bob Weiss as assistants to Westphal. Not
only is McMillan eager to return to the sidelines, he feels
prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I've heard the last couple of years is that George
(ex-Sonics coach) wants me,'' McMillan said. ``Any time I was
injured I went to the coaches' meetings, and they had me
demonstrate drills. And there were times when I spoke out in
practice. They've been grooming me.''
</P>
<P>
   McMillan admitted that it is strange that his first coaching job
is not with Karl, who accepted a job with Milwaukee after his Sonic
contract expired.
</P>
<P>
   But McMillan _ known as ``Mr. Sonic'' because he spent his
entire career in Seattle _ is looking forward to building a new era
with Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems like a cool guy,'' McMillan said. ``He's a guy open
to suggestions. He's not a guy who has a certain philosophy in
stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the NBA lockout has precluded the Sonics from filling
out their roster, the team has only six players under contract and
no system in place. McMillan is not sure what his role will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This keeps me close to the game. I want to be in the game and
I'll be as close as you can get,'' said McMillan, who ranks in the
Sonics' top 10 in 10 different categories _ including the all-time
lead in assists and steals _ and played in more playoff games than
anyone else in team history.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan said he always intended to remain in the organization.
He considered a public relations job, but knew coaching was an
option. McMillan was offered the assistant job once Grgurich
informed the Sonics in August that he would not return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
