<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1339 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     09-30 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ON Sunday, after the Astros knew they would be facing the Padres in
the first round of the playoffs, somebody asked Moises Alou what
sort of advice he would provide his Houston teammates regarding
Kevin Brown, a Marlins teammate during Florida's rented
world-championship season of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Alou shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these players have hit against him more than I have,''
he said. ``I don't know what I could tell them, except that he's a
great pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall Tuesday, Moises remained short a constructive
answer. And nobody else, save for perhaps Brad Ausmus, had sorted
out anything on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Alou's imposing presence in a Houston uniform was supposed to
have given the Astros the kind of lineup that wouldn't go down
swinging _ and swinging and swinging _ futilely as the one last
fall did when John Smoltz completed a three-game sweep for Atlanta,
making an 11-strikeout beeline straight through the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   With Moises batting fifth, the Astros could bat Jeff Bagwell
fourth, behind Derek Bell. No longer would Houston be asking a Luis
Gonzalez to impersonate a cleanup man.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, having battle-tested the murderers-row concept with
considerable success throughout the regular season _ they hit .280
and led the National League in runs _ figured to be prepared for
anything or anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Except, apparently, Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   You think Smoltz smoked 'em? Forget it. Kevin's surname
notwithstanding, this was a full-blown blackout, not a mere
brownout. San Diego's Killer P, a B himself, met Houston's Killer
B's head-on and went through their bats like he was wielding a buzz
saw. Those closest to the field must have gagged on the sawdust.
</P>
<P>
   So masterful was Brown that when San Diego manager Bruce Bochy
elected to send in the NL's probable Cy Young Award winner, Trevor
Hoffman, to work the ninth, the Astros wanted to spray each other
with Dom. All Hoffman had done was go 53-for-54 on save
opportunities in 1998, but at least they might catch a passing
glimpse of his pitches as they whizzed by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that a nice feeling or what?'' Jeff Bagwell smirked. ``You
go from Kevin Brown to Trevor Hoffman, and you feel like you have a
chance. Scary deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros would, in fact, nick Hoffman for a run, ``bunching''
two hits with a Ken Caminiti throwing error to avert the shame of a
shutout. Alas, the Padres had already scored twice, and thus Randy
Johnson, the Lesser Unit this day, would lose 2-1 much in the same
fashion as Darryl Kile succumbed to Greg Maddux in last year's
playoff opener against the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, who threw a three-hitter, had set an NL Division Series
record with those 11 whiffs. Brown, brimming with one-upmanship,
set the major-league Division Series record with 16 K's and allowed
but two hits in eight innings, deftly mixing two- and four-seam
fastballs with a looping changeup Bagwell referred to as a
``Frisbee.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Ausmus slapped both of the singles Brown yielded and
twice wound up standing on third base, although you never felt he
had even a snowball's chance of advancing the last 90 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Killer Brad _ and, OK, Killer Billy (Spiers), who
doubled off Hoffman to start the ninth _ Houston's Killer B brigade
experienced only killer blahs.
</P>
<P>
   You may recall how Bagwell, Biggio and Derek Bell were a
collective 2-for-37 vs. the Braves last year. As for Tuesday, with
Alou in the mix allegedly making things so much better? Hmm.
Oh-for-10, with seven strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Three of them by Bell, who will continue his Holy Grail-type
quest for a playoff hit Thursday. At 0-for-17, Derek is the
farthest B-hind the eight ball. His third strikeout, with two down
in the sixth, was particularly ill-timed, since Ausmus and Biggio
were in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Alou, by the way, went 0-for-3 against Brown with two whiffs. We
will, however, remove his honorary Killed B designation in
recognition of his infield single that Caminiti threw away,
permitting Spiers to stagger home with the Astros'
too-little-too-late run.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, for one, contended afterward that comparing the Astros'
latest power outage with last season's is a meaningless endeavor,
that despite the day's considerable evidence to the contrary, it's
more a case of apples and oranges than, say, bagels and doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were in over our heads a little bit against
Atlanta,'' he said. ``Obviously, this team belongs. We just ran
into some great pitching today. But we're a long way from being out
of these playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, two more losses, to be precise. And should Andy Ashby
outpitch Shane Reynolds in Game 2, who's to say Bochy won't bring
back Brown on three days' rest Saturday to shoot for the sweep? He
could still start twice in the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   I decided not to broach the possibility with any of the Astros.
They seemed dazed enough already.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
