<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1342 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      09-30 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Scheduling more favorable to television than baseball dictates an
early day off in the Astros' Division Series against the San Diego
Padres.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astros would be wise to use today's break to search for the
hypnotist who must have made his way to their bat rack. For some
reason, the mere mention of the word playoffs seems to send the
Astros' bats into a deep sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Padres ace Kevin Brown was responsible for Tuesday's trance,
striking out a Division Series-record 16 batters while pitching his
team to a 2-1 victory before 50,080 glassy-eyed onlookers at the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The expressions from the fans didn't come close to matching the
dazed looks on the faces of the Astros, who surrendered the
home-field advantage by dropping Game 1 of the best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's collective bat freeze was eerily similar to that in
the 1997 Division Series, in which the Astros scored only five runs
in a three-game sweep by Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Kevin Brown was throwing was nastier than anything we saw
from the Braves last year,'' said Astros right fielder Derek Bell,
who was 0-for-4 with three strikeouts. ``Fortunately for us, he
can't pitch every game.''
</P>
<P>
   If it were physically possible for Randy Johnson to pitch every
game, the Astros would certainly like their chances, especially in
the Astrodome, where he gave up only two runs in 43 innings this
season. But the Padres caught Johnson on a day when he had less
than his best stuff and matched that total in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson allowed nine hits, struck out nine and kept his team in
the game, but it would have taken a near-perfect effort to beat
Brown, who received high praise from the Big Unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say enough for the performance Kevin Brown had,''
Johnson said. ``He never gave us a chance to get anything going. He
was in command the whole day, and when you start a game like that
and continue it, it really silences the offense on the other team
and sends a message. I pitched a good ballgame, but it wasn't good
enough to win. Kevin Brown pitched a much better game and shut down
a good offensive team in dominating fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros catcher Brad Ausmus had two singles against Brown, and
were it not for Ausmus, the Padres righthander would have taken a
no-hitter into the ninth inning. Instead, Padres manager Bruce
Bochy called on major-league saves leader Trevor Hoffman (53-for-54
in save conversions in the regular season) to protect a 2-0 lead in
the final inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trevor is the best closer in the game,'' Astros third baseman
Bill Spiers said. ``But Brown had our number, and I didn't mind
seeing the pitching change when I led off the ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiers greeted Hoffman with a double to left, and it appeared
the Astros might be setting the stage for another of their
last-inning comebacks. After Bell flied out to right on a pitch he
said he ``just missed,'' Jeff Bagwell struck out, and Moises Alou
reached on a base hit down the third-base line. Padres third
baseman Ken Caminiti, a three-time Gold Glove winner, knocked down
Alou's hit but threw past first baseman Wally Joyner, allowing
Spiers to score from second base. Carl Everett flied out to center
to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it interesting at the end, but we didn't get it done,
and that's all that matters,'' said Bagwell, who was hitless in
four at-bats and struck out twice. ``We didn't mount anything when
Kevin was in there. We only had two hits, and both of them were by
one guy. We know we have to win (Game 2), and I truly believe we
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson matched zeros with Brown through the first five innings,
working out of two-on jams in the second and fifth innings.
Meanwhile, the Astros had just two runners in the first five
innings, but they spent most of their time swinging at balls they
had little or no chance to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have chased some bad pitches,'' Astros second baseman
Craig Biggio said. ``But it's hard to lay off when a guy has stuff
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres used Tony Gwynn's sixth-inning leadoff double to left
as the spark for the first run. Gwynn, who later left the game
because of an Achilles' tendon injury, slapped a slider down the
third-base line just over the leaping Spiers and into left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt like I should have caught that ball,'' Spiers
said. ``I didn't feel like I got off the ground good. It would have
been nice to just knock it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn eventually scored on Jim Leyritz's sacrifice fly to the
warning track in center field. Johnson retired five of the next six
batters he faced, but he surrendered a solo home run to Greg Vaughn
to lead off the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Astros relievers Jay Powell and Doug Henry kept the score close
in the ninth inning and gave the Astros a chance to attempt a rally
against Hoffman, but the effort came up one run short.
</P>
<P>
   ``One game doesn't dictate a series,'' Alou said. ``We know what
kind of team we have. We'll come right back (Thursday) and just
hope (Game 2 starter) Andy Ashby doesn't have the same kind of
stuff Brown had today.''
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   But just in case, it wouldn't hurt to have that hypnotist on
standby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
