<HEADER>
A1343 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     09-30 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
RANDY Johnson threw heat. Kevin Brown left vapor trails.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson fired bullets. Kevin Brown aimed laser beams.
</P>
<P>
   Big Unit. Bigger gun.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was supposed to slam the door on the Padres. But Brown
used bricks and mortar to seal every crack and opening on the
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   After all the hope and all the hype, there were the Astros on
the wrong end of another 2-1 loss in the opener of the National
League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   As Yogi once said, it was dj vu all over again.
</P>
<P>
   As Jeff Bagwell said Tuesday, ``Familiar, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, it was fastballing Darryl Kile who lost an
opening-game duel with Atlanta's Greg Maddux. This time, it was
Johnson who crossed flamethrowers with Brown and got burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want me to answer the question about how dominating a
pitching performance that was,'' Bagwell said. ``Well, I've never
seen Kevin Brown pitch a bad game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it: Last year against Maddux, we put our bats on
the ball. We had our chances to score runs. Today, Kevin Brown just
dominated us. There didn't seem to be anything we could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was everything Johnson was supposed to be _ poised,
confident and unhittable in the Astrodome, striking out 16 and
surrendering only two hits in eight shutout innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros haven't looked this overmatched since Cubs rookie
Kerry Wood struck them out 20 times in May.
</P>
<P>
   Brown didn't just confuse the Astros. He had them confounded,
bewildered, embarrassed, tied in knots like so many pretzels.
</P>
<P>
   Brown pitched a no-hitter last summer and earned a World Series
ring with the Florida Marlins last fall. But he might never have
been better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to say I'll take today because of the situation,''
Brown said. ``The (no-hit) game last year was in the regular season
and didn't have the impact of this game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as if he rode into town and stole the sheriff's horse. He
showed up at Johnson's big playoff dance and did a soft-shoe on the
head of a pin.
</P>
<P>
   Brown set up the Astros with a 93-mph sinker, tied them in knots
with a hot split-finger pitch and then busted them belt-high with a
four-seam fastball that cooked along at 96 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to do with something like that?'' Craig
Biggio said.
</P>
<P>
   The answer for the Killer B's, of course, was the same as last
year's playoffs as Bagwell and Derek Bell each checked in at
0-for-4 and Biggio went 0-for-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things are going to happen,'' Biggio said. ``Last year
was last year, and that's long gone. This was just a dominating
performance by a guy who had all of his best stuff going, so you
tip your cap and go your way.''
</P>
<P>
   Except that after the way Johnson had run up a 10-1 record since
joining the Astros and had not lost a game at the Dome, it was
supposed to be the Padres who were doing the cap-tipping.
</P>
<P>
   This was a different year and a different attitude the Astros
brought into this series, in part because of a more solid every-day
lineup but mostly because of the presence of Johnson in the role of
the terminator.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while Johnson hit the mid- to upper 90s in the first inning,
Brown continued to hit the accelerator through the day. His pitches
stayed hotter than Johnson's and had more bite. Brown was touched
for two singles by Brad Ausmus and gave up just two fly-ball outs.
He struck out the side in the third and eighth innings, fanning
five of the last six batters he faced before giving way to closer
Trevor Hoffman in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game Johnson could have and would have won if the
Astros' bats had produced the kind of offense that led the NL in
scoring this year. Yet it wasn't the game a crowd of 50,080, waving
its strikeout towels, came to see from him.
</P>
<P>
   Brown had the Astros talking to themselves in frustration.
Johnson had the Padres saying it was only a matter of time until
they got to him.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres did it in the sixth with an opposite-field double by
Tony Gwynn, an infield single by Greg Vaughn, a broken-bat flare by
Ken Caminiti and a sacrifice fly to the warning track in center
that Jim Leyritz just missed taking all the way. Vaughn then opened
the eighth by launching a slider into the orange seats in left
field.
</P>
<P>
   With Ausmus on third and one out in the third, Brown struck out
Johnson and Biggio. With Ausmus and Biggio on second and third with
two out in the sixth, he fanned Bell.
</P>
<P>
   One pitcher scuffled, and one sizzled. One guy scattered nine
hits. One guy scrambled brains.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson brought heat. Kevin Brown carried a blowtorch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
