<HEADER>
A1344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-1ST     09-30 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-1ST-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS, CURTIS LED YANKS TO 2-0 WIN OVER TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: SUBS to add quotes, details, refine throughout.)  
(nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yankees Manager Joe Torre jogged to the mound in the
eighth inning Tuesday night and invaded the personal space of David
Wells, going chest to chest. Wells stepped backed uncomfortably,
but Torre moved forward, looking the pitcher directly in the eyes,
and asked, ``How are you feeling?''
</P>
<P>
   This was no time for deception, no time for reckless heroics.
This was Game 1 of the American League division series, the Yankees
leading Texas by two runs and Wells's pitch count nearing 130. How
was he feeling? He was exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   But with corollary lobbying from his catcher, Jorge Posada,
Wells persuaded Torre to let him pitch out of trouble _ and did so.
Mariano Rivera closed out the Rangers in the ninth inning,
preserving the 2-0 shutout over the Rangers. A second-inning double
by Chad Curtis set up both runs.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking the pitching depth the Yankees possess, the Rangers'
best chance in this series would have been to win one or both of
the first two games. Now the Yankees can seize control of the
three-of-five-game series at Yankee Stadium Wednesday night, when
Andy Pettitte faces the Rangers' 20-game winner, Rick Helling, in
Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   True to his history as an exceptional playoff performer, Wells
threw a season-high 135 pitches, allowed just 5 hits and struck out
9 in beating the Rangers' Todd Stottlemyre and lowering his career
ERA in the post-season to 2.22.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was a classic one-on-one,'' said Torre,
referring to the duel between Wells and Stottlemyre. ``David was
running on fumes out there at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Wells, ``I strive for this kind of challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Torre placed Wells at the back end of the Yankees'
playoff rotation, a decision that still bothers Wells. Coming off a
'98 season in which he went 18-4 and pitched a perfect game,
however, Wells got the Game 1 assignment this year, and justified
that decision.
</P>
<P>
   With the top two buttons of his jersey undone and sporting a
hint of a goatee (to Wells, his war paint), the left-hander
challenged the Rangers all game, mixing fastballs, curveballs and
changeups, using all three pitches in pivotal moments. Remarkably,
Wells pitched into ball-strike counts that were favorable to
hitters _ 2-0 or 3-1 _ only three times.
</P>
<P>
   Wells fired first-pitch strikes to 21 of the 30 batters he
faced, reaching 2-0 counts only twice. Conventional wisdom
suggested the Yankees would not pitch to Juan Gonzalez, the
Rangers' massive cleanup hitter. To the contrary: Wells chased
after Gonzalez with inside fastballs and changeups away, and the
slugger went 0 for 3 against him, striking out, fouling out and
chopping a grounder that traveled about two feet from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``No chance for us tonight,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Rangers got two chances, both coming long after
Curtis had spurred the Yankees' offense in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve days ago, Wells gestured angrily on the field when Curtis
and two other Yankees botched a fly ball. Later, Wells sought out
Curtis to apologize. I can't do that, Wells told him, you guys win
games for me.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis batted .216 after the All-Star Game break, .146 in
September, pressing more with each at-bat. In particular, Curtis
was unable to cope with pitches thrown to the outer half of the
strike zone. But Torre started Curtis last night because he wanted
his best defensive left fielder to play behind Wells, who induces
fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   With Posada at first base and one out in the second, Curtis
reached out for a fastball, driving it to the opposite field.
Gonzalez, the Rangers' cement-shoed right fielder, lumbered back
and toward the right-field corner, the ball carrying over his
outstretched glove. Posada stopped at third, Curtis pulled into
second.
</P>
<P>
   After Scott Brosius's ground single scored Posada and sent
Curtis to third base, Chuck Knoblauch battled Stottlemyre to a full
count _ the Ranger pitcher threw 27 pitches in the inning _ and
Torre ordered Brosius to break from first on the pitch. Knoblauch
swung and missed, a strikeout, and catcher Ivan Rodriguez fired a
throw to second in an attempt to intercept Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment Rodriguez released the ball, however, Curtis broke
from third and Brosius stopped about 20 feet from second base.
``It's a set play,'' Curtis said. ``If we're going to make an out
in that situation, we want to make it at home plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas second baseman Mark McLemore caught the ball with no other
choice but to chase Brosius in a rundown, after Curtis had slid
across home plate with the Yankees' second run of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was still 2-0 in the seventh, when Texas put together a
couple of hits. With runners on first and second and two out, Wells
jumped ahead of Mike Simms, no balls and two strikes, the Yankee
Stadium crowd of 57,362 roaring. Simms fouled off a pitch, took two
balls, then fouled off two more pitches with good swings. Wells had
not allowed a three-run homer this year, and this did not seem like
the best of times for the first one.
</P>
<P>
   So Wells zipped a fastball inside, Simms staring at it, the
crowd exploding. Ball 3, said the plate umpire, Jim Joyce, and
Wells turned away disgustedly as fans screamed at Joyce. Posada
signaled for a change-up _ ``He just had a great change-up all
night,'' Posada said later _ and Simms swung and missed. End of
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Wells returned to the mound for the eighth, fatigue setting in,
his arm lagging. McLemore doubled with one out, prompting Torre's
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you feeling?'' Torre asked. O.K., Wells replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``No _ how are you feeling?'' Torre asked, wanting to be
convinced.
</P>
<P>
   Posada then stepped forward and said, ``Joe, he's got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre nodded and ran back to the dugout, from where he saw Wells
strike out Roberto Kelly. Rusty Greer bounced a broken-bat grounder
toward shortstop, Derek Jeter racing in, gloving the ball and
throwing to first for the third out. Wells pumped a fist.
</P>
<P>
   For the Yankees, a team seeking its place in history, one
victory down, 10 to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 0124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
