<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ABORTION-SUIT-NYT &LR;      09-30 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ABORTION-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN SUES HOSPITAL, LAB OVER PRE-ABORTION DIAGNOSIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Texas, Mass.)  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A woman who had an abortion after a test showed that
her female fetus had a serious disease and would not survive
infancy is suing Lenox Hill Hospital and a laboratory over the
diagnosis, saying an autopsy found the fetus was male and perfectly
normal.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed earlier this month in Manhattan federal
court, the woman, Janet Sheikhan, charges that the hospital and
Genetrix, a laboratory in Yonkers, mishandled Mrs. Sheikhan's
amniocentesis _ a test routinely performed on pregnant women over
35 for genetic abnormalities _ possibly switching hers with that of
another pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lenox Hill and the lab defended their diagnosis Tuesday and
said the lab results were not switched.
</P>
<P>
   According to the suit, which was reported Tuesday in the Daily
News, Mrs. Sheikhan, of Franklin Lakes, N.J., learned she was
pregnant in March 1996 and was referred to Lenox Hill for the test
by her obstetrician, who is not a subject of the suit. The test,
which was performed by Drs. Judith Chernevak and Camillo Gugliucci,
showed that she was carrying a 16-week-old female fetus with
Edwards syndrome, a rare birth defect.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sheikhan, then 40, decided based on the report to end the
pregnancy and said that only when she became pregnant again in
January of the following year did she get the chance to read the
pathology report at her doctor's office. It stated that the fetus
was actually a normal boy, reading, in part, ``no external
abnormalities are seen.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Mrs. Sheikhan's lawyer was unable to
explain why her obstetrician, whom Mrs. Sheikhan would not name,
did not tell her of the report's findings after the autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts say such a pathology report would only have been
able to determine the sex of the fetus, not whether there was the
presence of Edwards syndrome. They said that even determining the
sex would be difficult in such an early pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Lenox Hill, upon learning of the suit, sent slides of the test
to a perinatal pathologist, who determined that the fetus, in fact,
was female, and that the original pathologist made an error. The
hospital did not say why it failed to try to resolve the
discrepancy between the amniocentesis and the pathology report
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lenox Hill Hospital is confident that the original
amniocentesis diagnosis of a female fetus with Edwards syndrome was
correct,'' hospital executives said in a prepared statement. ``The
amniotic fluid was not mislabeled, nor were the lab results
switched. It is difficult for pathologists not specializing in
perinatal pathology to accurately identify the sex of a 16-week
fetus with Edwards syndrome because female genitalia may resemble
that of a male.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sheikhan, who is a labor and delivery nurse at St. Luke's
Hospital, would not comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Roderick Cassidy, a partner at the law firm Widowski,
Cassidy &AMP; Steinhart in Manhattan who is representing her, said,
``Since the filing of the lawsuit, they have determined that their
original report was erroneous and their new findings support their
position in the lawsuit. I believe their current position is
unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards syndrome, which affects roughly one in 8,000 births, is
a serious disorder that few afflicted babies survive. A baby with
Edwards is extremely mentally retarded, often with serious heart
and other defects. Most afflicted babies are born dead or die
within the first year of life.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nancy Schneider, a professor of pathology at the University
of Texas Southwestern Medical Center in Dallas, said that while it
was ``virtually impossible'' to see Edwards syndrome in an autopsy,
amnios pick up the disease with ``99 percent'' accuracy. ``The
physical findings are quite subtle,'' she said. She added that it
was very difficult to determine the sex of all babies at 16 weeks,
regardless of whether they have Edwards syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Marcie Campbell, a spokeswoman for Genzyme Corp., a
Massachusetts company that recently acquired Genetrix, said that
the company had concluded from an internal investigation that ``we
believe the original diagnosis is correct; the accuracy rates of
our tests are greater than 99 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Tarlton, a spokeswoman for the New York state Department
of Health, said that Genetrix had a good record and no prior
complaints against it but that the state ``is looking into the
situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
