<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1354 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-HNS &LR;      09-30 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANNY ROBBINS  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Skeptical New Yorkers trying to find the black cloud in
the silver lining that was the Yankees' 114-win season _ after all,
isn't it really the postseason that matters? _ have a reason to
breathe a little easier.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When all else fails, the Yankees have David Wells' left arm and
big heart.
</P>
<P>
   Scattering five hits over eight innings, Wells pushed the
Yankees past the Texas Rangers 2-0 in the opener of the teams'
best-of-five American League Division Series on Tuesday night at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With the crowd of 57,362 standing and at full volume on just
about every two-strike pitch, Wells struck out nine, his playoff
best, and gutted out tense moments in the seventh and eighth
innings before giving way to closer Mariano Rivera, who pitched a
perfect ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Wells walked only one _ the first batter he faced _ and allowed
just one extra-base hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``His curveball is as good as any curveball I've seen,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``It goes right off the table. It's in
the strike zone, out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen that curveball before. The big thing tonight was
his straight changeup.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells' effort was such that the Yankees could survive by
scratching out two runs in the second inning off Todd Stottlemyre,
who pitched with the tenacity he showed in helping the Rangers tie
down the American League West title last week.
</P>
<P>
   After a shaky start, Stottlemyre, whose father, Mel, is the
Yankees' pitching coach, settled down and completed eight innings,
allowing six hits and striking out eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about a courageous outing,'' Yankees manager Joe
Torre said of Stottlemyre's performance. ``And I'm not just saying
that because his father is my pitching coach. That was a classic
one-on-one matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't get a runner to second base against Wells
until the seventh, when Will Clark and Todd Zeile singled.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with his first real sweat _ two out and two on _ Wells
wound up in a protracted battle with Mike Simms, the Rangers'
designated hitter. Simms fell behind 0-2 and got the count to 3-2
before striking out swinging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simms, he's a strong boy,'' Wells said. ``He can hurt you in a
heartbeat. I got to 3-2 with him, gave him a changeup. I hung it
out, and he swung right through it. I felt a sigh of relief,
because that could have been the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the eighth, the Rangers got their only
extra-base hit, Mark McLemore's double over Chad Curtis' head in
left field, and, again, Wells got a dramatic strikeout on a 3-2
pitch _ Roberto Kelly the victim this time. Rusty Greer then hit a
slow roller to shortstop Derek Jeter, who made a great pickup and
throw to get the third out.
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``David, running on fumes in the eighth inning,
managed to get the outs he needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells walked McLemore to open the game and then settled into an
untouchable groove. He retired the next 10 hitters he faced, with
only one hitting the ball out of the infield. He struck out four
during that stretch and got five groundouts.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the fourth, Greer came up with the first Rangers
hit, a sinking line drive to the right of Jeter. Not that the
Yankees had anything to worry about. Wells got a called third
strike past Juan Gonzalez and then fanned Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre hit the Yankees' leadoff batter, Chuck Knoblauch,
and gave up a one-out double to Paul O'Neill. Knoblauch attempted
to score from first on O'Neill's hit, which landed in the
left-field corner, but a perfect relay from shortstop Royce Clayton
got the Yankees second baseman at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius drove in the Yankees' first run when he poked a
single through the right side of the infield with runners on second
and third and one out in the second.
</P>
<P>
   With one away, a 3-2 count on Knoblauch and Brosius on first and
Curtis on third, the Yankees tried a double steal.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch hacked at a third strike, and Brosius dug for second,
drawing a throw from Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez. Curtis was
able to score before Brosius, who made a U-turn, was tagged out by
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it was a gamble,'' Curtis said. ``If he (Rodriguez)
pump-fakes or lobs the ball to the pitcher, I'm out at third.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``We don't do that very often, but first and third
with a 3-2 count was a good spot. I have to compliment Brosius. He
went far enough to make (second baseman) McLemore think he could
tag him, then backed up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
