<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1362 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-30 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ George Steinbrenner, the man who likes to make
headlines, was sitting next to Rupert Murdoch, the man who likes to
make headlines scream across the front page in boldfaced, 72-point
type.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees pitcher David Wells made both of their jobs much, much
easier.
</P>
<P>
   There was much anticipation in the Big Apple before Tuesday
night's American League Division Series, not so much for the
trouble the Rangers might cause but because of a widespread worry
that the remarkable year turned in by Wells might explode in the
Yankees' faces.
</P>
<P>
   These were, after all, the playoffs, where the 114-win season of
the Yankees was rendered meaningless. And this was Wells, the
wildfire one.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Wells might have been perfect in May _ 27 up, 27 down
against the Minnesota Twins _ but he still is Wells, the tattooed,
guitar-strumming, electric personality known to wear his emotions
not just on his sleeve but from head to toe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' Wells said. ``If I don't get my way, I get mad, and
you hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   The man on the brink was in the limelight, pitching at Yankee
Stadium on the brink of October. Some believed there was the
potential for a blowup.
</P>
<P>
   This was Wells amid the demanding, confetti-tossing,
beer-swigging, obscenity-shouting Yanks fans, who considered
Tuesday's opener the first step on the way to a sure World Series
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Runnin' with Van Halen
</P>
<P>
   Emotions were high, and Wells probably was the most emotional
man in the building. But instead of blowing up, he used the energy
of the night to ignite a thrilling pitcher's battle, which, yes,
occasionally can still happen in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be the hero or the goat,'' Wells said. ``I'm
hungry for the big games. I want to get mean, and I want the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He got the ball, and he won a 2-0 match against the Rangers'
Todd Stottlemyre. Suggested headline to the New York tabloids: Rock
On.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, Wells somehow bridged the era of what he once was
_ volatile _ with what he has been in 1998 _ overpowering and in
control. Before Tuesday's game, Wells contacted Eddie Van Halen,
the guitar-gashing rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him a jersey and told him to wear it,'' Wells said.
``Hey, I'm a headbanger. I told him, `Send out some vibes, man.'''
</P>
<P>
   The vibes were electric. And the Yankees took a huge step toward
the title they believe should be theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be beyond great,'' Wells said. ``We want to erase
last year's disappointment and be the greatest ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Last October, after a disappointing first-round elimination at
Cleveland, Steinbrenner, several of his assistants and Yankees
coaches, including Torre, went directly from Cleveland to Tampa,
Fla., where Steinbrenner has a home.
</P>
<P>
   The mission was to come up with a blueprint for a return to
greatness. Steinbrenner ordered the roster trimmed of the me-first
players. One of the names batted about on that trip was Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Wells was a man whose relationship with Torre could only be
called unique, while his relationship with Steinbrenner was at best
tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Torre loved Wells' skills, particularly his grit. But Torre
could not relate to the time-bomb personality and the way Wells
often appeared to be detached from matters at hand, as if he were
preoccupied.
</P>
<P>
   All's well with Wells now
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the blaring hard-rock music Wells demanded to be
played in the Yankees' clubhouse before and after games. It was how
Wells long ago got his nickname _ Boomer. Torre could not
understand someone thumbing his nose at the hallowed Yankees
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Steinbrenner could not relate to Wells, period. The
Boss and The Boomer repeatedly engaged in memorable shouting
matches and clubhouse scenes from the moment Wells became a Bronx
Brute one season ago, signing a three-year, $13 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Steinbrenner and the Yankees traditionally have been
mysteriously drawn to such large figures and large personalities.
Reggie Jackson was one, Darryl Strawberry another. Thus, this
wildfire man, all 6-4 and 230 pounds of him, got a reprieve.
Steinbrenner stayed with Wells, though still occasionally calling
him an underachiever.
</P>
<P>
   Then came last May 6, when Wells could not protect a 9-0 lead
against these same Rangers. Definitely a low point. Wells called
that game ``a nightmare,'' and it prompted Torre and Steinbrenner
to first call Wells into a private meeting, then look for some help
on the trade wire.
</P>
<P>
   But two starts after the Texas debacle, Wells was perfect
against the Twins. And now, some four months later, it was Wells
looming large in a critical game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as good as you'll ever see him,'' Torre said of Wells'
performance Tuesday night. ``That was classic.''
</P>
<P>
   As Torre spoke, somebody turned up the heavy metal rocking the
Yanks' clubhouse. We can only assume it was Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never get used to that noise,'' Torre said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 0204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1366 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-30 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NNEW YORK _ George Steinbrenner, the man who likes to make
headlines, was sitting next to Rupert Murdoch, the man who likes to
make headlines scream across the front page in boldfaced, 72-point
type.
</P>
