</P>
<P>
   The mission was to come up with a blueprint for a return to
greatness. Steinbrenner ordered the roster trimmed of the me-first
players. One of the names batted about on that trip was Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Wells was a man whose relationship with Torre could only be
called unique, while his relationship with Steinbrenner was at best
tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Torre loved Wells' skills, particularly his grit. But Torre
could not relate to the time-bomb personality and the way Wells
often appeared to be detached from matters at hand, as if he were
preoccupied.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the blaring hard-rock music Wells demanded to be
played in the Yankees' clubhouse before and after games. It was how
Wells long ago got his nickname _ Boomer. Torre could not
understand someone thumbing his nose at the hallowed Yankees
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Steinbrenner could not relate to Wells, period. The
Boss and The Boomer repeatedly engaged in memorable shouting
matches and clubhouse scenes from the moment Wells became a Bronx
Brute one season ago, signing a three-year, $13 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Steinbrenner and the Yankees traditionally have been
mysteriously drawn to such large figures and large personalities.
Reggie Jackson was one, Darryl Strawberry another. Thus, this
wildfire man, all 6-4 and 230 pounds of him, got a reprieve.
Steinbrenner stayed with Wells, though still occasionally calling
him an underachiever.
</P>
<P>
   Then came last May 6, when Wells could not protect a 9-0 lead
against these same Rangers. Definitely a low point. Wells called
that game ``a nightmare,'' and it prompted Torre and Steinbrenner
to first call Wells into a private meeting, then look for some help
on the trade wire.
</P>
<P>
   But two starts after the Texas debacle, Wells was perfect
against the Twins. And now, some four months later, it was Wells
looming large in a critical game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as good as you'll ever see him,'' Torre said of Wells'
performance Tuesday night. ``That was classic.''
</P>
<P>
   As Torre spoke, somebody turned up the heavy metal rocking the
Yanks' clubhouse. We can only assume it was Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never get used to that noise,'' Torre said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
