<HEADER>
A1391 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMF-MEETING-SFCHRON &LR;      09-30 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-MEETING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF MEETS WEDNESDAY, SEEKING ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ As the world's finance ministers and central
bankers gather in Washington Wednesday for the annual meeting of
the International Monetary Fund, they face an intensifying global
financial meltdown that is spreading unmistakably to American
shores.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is no small irony that the IMF, created from the rubble of
World War II to prevent another Great Depression, now finds itself
powerless to halt the financial carnage that has ripped through
Asia, toppled Russia, threatens to wreck Brazil and could throttle
the two economic engines where hope for global recovery rests: the
United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have any ideas, for goodness sake, share them,''
President Clinton told the Council of Foreign Relations in New York
two weeks ago. What Clinton described a year ago as ``one small
glitch in the road'' he now calls ``the worst financial crisis in
half a century.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior IMF official conceded last week that the world economy
is ``in a mess.'' Goldman Sachs economists put the chance of a U.S.
recession within the next year at 40 percent. Japan's economy
shrank in the first quarter by 5.3 percent, and a top Japanese
official characterized conditions there as ``extremely severe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer it takes for Japan to recover, the more likely it
becomes that all the major economies will be going into recession
at the same time,'' said economist Andrew Bernard of the Yale
School of Management. ``At that point, it becomes very difficult to
solve.''
</P>
<P>
   While the spectacular $1.2 trillion near-failure of the
Connecticut hedge fund Long Term Capital Management _ and its
controversial rescue _ has caught headlines, a more subtle U.S.
credit squeeze is under way. New stock offerings, the chief money
source for Silicon Valley, have practically halted. Only top-rated
U.S. corporations can find buyers for their bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Attention at the IMF meetings will be riveted on Brazil, the
next teetering domino. Frightened investors are fleeing even
well-managed economies, putting Brazil's currency under severe
strain. IMF managing director Michel &UR;  &LR; Camdessus has pledged that
the the fund ``will not spare any effort'' to provide emergency
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Japan plans to announce this week an aid package to help Asian
nations dig out from under their debts. Britain and France are
floating proposals to revamp world financial institutions. U.S.
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin has called for a ``new global
financial architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair has called for an overhaul of
the global financial system that would allow it to respond to a
world where huge rivers of investor capital can shift abruptly and
capsize entire economies.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the IMF is trying to put out fires country by country,
while attacking the roots of the crisis: lax banking supervision,
inadequate bankruptcy laws, opaque accounting practices and ``crony
capitalism'' where governments direct investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a series of short-run crises they have to cope with,
but in the longer term, they have to think about reforming the
international financial architecture,'' said University of
California at Berkeley economist Barry Eichengreen. ``The two
options we have available to us now _ ever larger bailouts and
doing nothing at all _ are unacceptable. We have to create a third
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve moved Tuesday to bolster the U.S. economy,
announcing a long-awaited interest rate cut. While the
quarter-point cut disappointed many, the Fed signaled that more may
be coming.
</P>
<P>
   Industrialized nations ``need to make sure the financial system
doesn't collapse inward on us,'' said Richard Medley, managing
partner of Medley Global Advisors. ``A Fed rate cut is the first
step in that process.''
</P>
<P>
   Countries hit by the crisis have seen massive huge outflows of
capital as frightened investors fled to safe U.S. Treasury bonds.
Their currencies have collapsed, leaving businesses starved for
capital and foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Lower U.S. interest rates would make U.S. Treasury bonds less
attractive and make it easier for developing nations to buy
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get those dollars to stay in Brazil,'' said Gordon
Richards, an economist at the National Association of
Manufacturers, ``Brazil is more able to keep its economy running,
which in turn keeps all of South America running.''
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. rate cuts only provide breathing room, analysts say.
Longer-run proposals for a ``new financial architecture'' remain
vague and _ despite withering criticism of the IMF _ highly
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no agreement,'' said Joel Prakken, chairman of
Macroeconomic Advisers in St. Louis. ``I don't know of a consensus
anywhere on what sort of institutional arrangements should
supersede what we already have.''
</P>
<P>
   Many compare efforts to remake the IMF now to trying to
construct a new firehouse in the middle of a fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took World War II to bring about Bretton Woods,'' where the
IMF was created, said Medley. ``I don't think we're quite there
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Many panicked developing countries aren't waiting. Watching
their economies crumble, some are reaching for protective remedies
_ this time to control capital flows _ reminiscent of 1930s trade
controls that intensified the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Reigning free-market orthodoxy promoted by the IMF _ open trade
and free-flowing capital _ is now being widely questioned.
</P>
<P>
   While a massive influx of capital fueled a stunning rise in
living standards in once-impoverished nations, it is now clear that
its withdrawal can also make nations poor again. Highly integrated
world capital markets ruthlessly punish bad economic policies, but
investor panics also punish nations with sound ones.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few months ago, capital controls, which restrict the
movement of money over national borders, were widely discredited,
on a par with nationalized banks and telephone companies as quaint
remnants of primitive closed economies.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are seen by many, including some leading Western
economists, as a wooden stake to halt the Dracula-like speculative
attacks on developing country markets. Malaysia has banned all
trading of its currency; Russia has indefinitely suspended all
trading in rubles. Even France has proposed temporary currency
controls for some markets.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Treasury Secretary Larry Summers, acknowledging the human
devastation in Asia, warned that ``it would be an even greater
catastrophe if countries were to absorb the wrong lessons from
these crises'' by ``withdrawing from the global system.''
</P>
<P>
   As Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan noted last
year, the clock cannot be turned back to a simpler time, before
high-speed telecommunications forever altered the world financial
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technological progress is not reversible,'' Greenspan said.
``We must learn to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether world financial leaders can learn quickly enough remains
an open question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
