<HEADER>
A1393 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MADCOW-DETECTION-SFCH     09-30 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADCOW-DETECTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK WAY TO DETECT `MAD COW' DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; Researchers at the University of California at
San Francisco say they have developed a highly sensitive technique
for rapidly detecting the infectious proteins known as prions that
cause ``mad cow disease'' in cattle and a variety of rare but
deadly nerve disorders in humans.
</P>
<P>
   And because the technique is scientifically both straightforward
and simple, the researchers say, it may well be applicable for
spotting many other human neurological diseases, even before
symptoms arise.
</P>
<P>
   Prions (PREE-ons) are curious microscopic protein particles that
exist in all mammals, including humans. When their normal molecular
structure mysteriously folds into new shapes, they become
infectious and cause diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery of the prion proteins and their role in disease won
the Nobel Prize only a year ago for Dr. Stanley B. Prusiner of
UCSF.
</P>
<P>
   In this week's journal Nature Medicine, a team of Prusiner's
colleagues at UCSF, headed by Dr. Jiri Safar and Dr. Fred E. Cohen,
describe how they developed the testing technique and how it could
be put into widespread use when it is perfected.
</P>
<P>
   A series of trials using hamsters infected with eight different
strains of the prions that cause disease showed that the technique
could accurately detect extremely low levels of the proteins within
eight hours, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, assays for the infectious agents have involved
injecting suspected tissue samples into the brains of laboratory
animals and then waiting for many months to see if the test animals
developed disease.
</P>
<P>
   The new test is based on an antibody to the normal prion that is
labeled to become fluorescent and light up when it encounters a
folded region of the dangerous form of the prion.
</P>
<P>
   Turning their laboratory method into a widely available test is
now merely a problem of development and engineering, Safir and
Cohen said, and it could readily be automated to detect the
dangerous prion forms for other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Practical applications, the researchers said, could include
automated testing of beef products when new outbreaks of mad cow
disease are suspected; routine testing of donated human blood or
blood products, and testing of donated human brain tissues that are
used in certain types of brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The prion diseases, whether human or animal, have major signs in
common: The brains of the victims become filled with spongy holes,
and the lesions result in staggered gait and dementia.
</P>
<P>
   One of those human prion disorders is Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease,
which in most cases seems to arise sporadically but occasionally is
known to be inherited, or even more rarely, can become infectious.
</P>
<P>
   Dementia is also a common phenomenon in other brain disorders
like Alzheimer's and Huntington's diseases, and recent research
indicates that although prions are not involved in those disorders,
they, too, may be caused by other proteins that become folded into
abnormal disease-producing shapes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Cohen said in an interview, the test that Safar and
he have developed might also be adapted for the early diagnosis of
those and other disorders known collectively as conformational
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Many unsolved mysteries concerning these diseases remain for
brain researchers to solve, Cohen said, and one of the most
difficult questions is what causes the three-dimensional structure
of the normal proteins to fold over into new disease-causing
shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers all over the world are tackling that puzzle, he
said, and ultimately a Nobel Prize may well await the scientist who
solves it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
