<HEADER>
A1612 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-DOMINICAN-$AD     09-30 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-DOMINICAN-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: GEORGES' IMPACT ON DOMINICANS TEACHES HUMANITY AND HOPE
 &HT;    With photo mug of Lipman available in the National folder on the
Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, Oct. 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   POLO, Dominican Republic _ As I trudged up a dusty street in
this impoverished town of ramshackle wooden houses -- where 30
people died, nearly one-fifth of Hurricane Georges' victims in this
small country -- I thought about my 9-year-old daughter, Margaret.
</P>
<P>
   For most of her life I have tried to impress upon her how
incredibly lucky she was to have been born an American. It's not
that I want her to feel superior, it's that I want her to realize
that when things seem difficult in her life -- if a meal is an hour
later than usual and she claims she's starving -- her minor
inconveniences pale against the sufferings of many in this world.
</P>
<P>
   In Polo, I gathered first-hand knowledge of that suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Following me up the hill were a score of children, many who
hadn't eaten a regular meal since Hurricane Georges paid its
howling late-night visit four days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In a small wooden house I sat with a woman who had lost a sister
and four members of her sister's family. The woman's 4-year-old
niece was still missing and presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   The only furniture in the house was a table and a few chairs.
The floor was a concrete slab. Unpainted walls were bare save for
two brightly colored prints -- one of a landscape, another a
religious icon. Overhead, a light bulb dangled from two wires.
</P>
<P>
   As I and another reporter spoke with the woman, more than two
dozen people clustered into the tiny room, smaller than the
smallest bedroom in my house. A young girl, no more than 5 or 6,
peeked shyly at me from around an older girl's legs.
</P>
<P>
   There was deep sorrow in this room, and fear for the future.
There was no food, no clothing, nothing to sleep on. The nearest
water must be fetched in plastic jugs from a pipe that sticks out
of a hill about a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   To exist, they eat bananas and toronjas, a green-skinned fruit
about the size of a coconut, but with a similar look, feel and
taste to a not-quite-ripe orange.
</P>
<P>
   What concerned them most, however, was the loss of the local
coffee crop. Without it, their meager income appears doomed.
</P>
<P>
   What does the future hold for them, I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no future for this place,'' a woman said.
</P>
<P>
   A few yards outside the woman's house I stood at the edge of a
fresh ravine some 20 feet deep and about 100 yards wide. On the
other side of the ravine, what was left of a wooden house perched
precariously on the edge. Six houses once stood between me and the
shattered house -- the rushing floodwaters spawned by Georges swept
them away.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy for me to tell my daughter about the poverty,
the heartache, the misery I witnessed. But that would be only part
of what I experienced in Polo, a community so small it is not on
many maps of this nation -- which shares the island of Hispaniola
with Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   What I saw in Polo taught me something about humanity and hope.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone shared the sentiments of the woman in the house.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of Polo, small stores were open for business even
though they did not have electricity. The merchants apologized that
their drinks were warm.
</P>
<P>
   At the remains of a shattered wooden house nearly covered by
uprooted trees, I paused to watch three men hammering on its
twisted tin roof. What were they doing with the roof, I wondered?
</P>
<P>
   Taking it apart to re-use it to cover another house that had
lost its roof, I was told. Nearby, a man washed off a mattress.
Further on a woman was cooking beans over an outdoor fire.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of a street, boys wearing baseball gloves played
stickball with a rubber ball.
</P>
<P>
   There are some in this town who want to escape. They want the
government to move them some place else, an unrealistic hope born
of fear. But there are many more who plan to stay and rebuild their
lives. Fernando Feliz is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Feliz, 25, sought shelter with his wife and two children when
the hurricane swept through. They emerged to discover that his and
several other houses had disappeared, replaced by a gully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do whatever I have to,'' he said of his plan to rebuild
his life.
</P>
<P>
   I'll probably continue telling my daughter that the world is
full of hardships, and I've seen some of them. But I'll also
remember, when things look bleak in my life, the lesson Polo taught
me about the resilience of the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Lipman, Washington correspondent for The Palm Beach Post,
recently covered the aftermath of Hurricane Georges in the
Dominican Republic for the Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
