<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1641 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-REGIONS-$ADV03     09-30 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-REGIONS-$ADV03-1STLD-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: subs 5th, 6th grafs to update with Primakov moves; in 21st
graf, deletes word 'has . . . '
 &HT;    MOSCOW LOSING ITS GRIP ON THE REGIONS
 &HT;    EDs: For the purposes of a locator map, the city of Saratov is
on the Volga River about 450 miles south of Moscow; it is the
capital of a region of the same name.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Oct. 3 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOV, Russia _ The political and financial disorder of Moscow
seems faraway and irrelevant in this city on the mighty Volga
River, in the heart of Russia's southern farming and industrial
district.
</P>
<P>
   When the current economic crisis seized the country two months
ago, the regional governor of Saratov overlooked concerns of
national unity and put his 2.7 million people first.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Dmitri Ayatskov instituted emergency measures that
encouraged growers to keep their produce at home. Farmers were
allowed to sell to local consumers free of middlemen mark-ups and
other trade tariffs. The steps kept prices low and prevented
shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Ayatskov, 47, identified by President Boris Yeltsin himself as a
rising young star who may be president someday, warned that if the
national government cannot fix Russia's problems ``undoubtedly the
governors will unite their efforts to solve the problems
themselves,'' he told the Cox News Service in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   The central authority of Moscow has been undermined by the
economic turmoil in Russia, prompting governors across the
country's 89 regions to usurp the role of the federal government --
and in some cases to defy it in mutinous fashion. Some regions have
threatened to withhold tax revenues from Moscow, print their own
currencies and commandeer
</P>
<P>
   industries.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Prime Minister Yvegeny Primakov summoned the
powerful regional governors to a meeting in Moscow and urged them
not to splinter the country. ``We must put an end to feudal
attitudes,'' Primakov told them, ``or we shall lose Russia as a
single state.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Russia break apart, as the Soviet Union did seven years
ago? The prospect seems unlikely, according to many political
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is a rhetorical question increasingly pondered in Moscow.
The power shift has forced Primakov's still-fledgling government to
give regional governors -- who comprise the upper house of
parliament -- a more formal role in national policymaking.
</P>
<P>
   Rumblings from the regions began even before the shock of
mid-August and have been plentiful amid the uncertainty and
hardships since the ruble and banking system collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Russian consumers have been faced with massive price increases
and food shortages. The unstable ruble has plunged to half its
value since the crisis broke in mid-August. What's more, recent
government forecasts now show that inflation could reach 300
percent or more by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Lebed, the retired army general and governor of the
huge Krasnoyarsk region in Siberia, sent an open letter to Moscow
in late July demanding that servicemen at an intercontinental
ballistic missile base in his district be paid their back wages.
Lebed said he was ``seriously thinking'' of establishing
jurisdiction over the base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in Krasnoyarsk are not rich yet,'' he wrote, ``but in
exchange for the status of a nuclear territory we could feed the
formation and become a headache for the world community along with
India and Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Lebed's younger brother, who is governor of the adjoining region
of Khakassia, was among at least six regional leaders who
threatened to withhold tax payments to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Samara Governor Konstantin Titov is building his region's own
gold reserve by bartering with the gold-producing Siberian region
of Sakha (formerly known as Yakutia), which in return gets food
shipments.
</P>
<P>
   But most of Russia's regions are poor, not rich. The number of
``donor'' regions -- those that contribute more to the federal
coffers than they get back -- fell from 20 in 1994 to eight this
year.
</P>
<P>
   In the depressed Murmansk region of the far north, officials,
without consulting with Moscow, declared a state of emergency
earlier this month and appealed directly for international
humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Already there have been pledges of food aid due to be sent this
month from Norway, Finland and Sweden designated for orphanages and
pensioners. The area has relied on food aid, which have been
falling steadily, since the collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, said vice-governor Igor Chernyshenko, is that
Murmansk is in the far north with a short growing season. ``Besides
potatoes, there is little that can grow here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worry is that Moscow continues its politics as usual while
the financial situation grows worse,'' added a Western diplomat in
Moscow. ``Were that to happen, I think we will see regions,
particularly the strong regions, attempting to assert their de
facto independence and the poor regions following them, not
Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, Saratov has been a region of relative
prosperity thanks to Ayatskov's tireless pursuit of foreign
investment to revitalize decrepit Soviet-era factories.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Case, the Wisconsin-based manufacture of farm
machinery, began negotiations in April with the regional government
in Saratov on a $140 million joint venture and, in the first step,
delivered 100 combines in June. But further progress on using a
factory
</P>
<P>
   in Saratov to assemble combines are on hold amid the economic
turmoil in Russia. ``We'd like to move forward as soon as we can.
The fit is right, but the economics are not,'' said Case spokesman
William Masterson.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Saratov is an attractive place for Western firms to do
business. But the economic crisis has for now forced Case to put
its plans on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Ayatskov complains that the current crisis has cost his region
$800 million in foreign investment that now will not come. Yet
Ayatskov claims no desire for independence or more economic
autonomy, only for a strong and unified Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Like any good politician, he seems to be reading his
constituency well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of animosity. There is even more despair,''
said Lilya Chudaeva, editor of a local Saratov newspaper, Pokrovski
Vesti. ``And a lot of it is aimed at Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
