<HEADER>
A1697 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STERBAK-ART-2TAKES-$A     09-30 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STERBAK-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ABSURDIST WHO SAVORS THE POETRY OF TECHNOLOGY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Ann Wilson Lloyd is an independent critic and curator who last
wrote in these pages about Myron Stout and Provincetown in the
1950s.  
 By ANN WILSON LLOYD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The conceptual sculpture of the Canadian-based artist
Jana Sterbak has inspired reams of humorless, abstruse theoretical
writing that leaves none of her layered metaphors unturned. Yet Ms.
Sterbak's work _ seductive, intensely physical and edged with dark
absurdity _ delivers a mind-body frisson unknowable by intellect
alone.
</P>
<P>
   In art circles in the United States, she is perhaps best known
for what could be called a piece of wearable art. ``Vanitas: Flesh
Dress for an Albino Anorexic,'' from 1987, is an actual shift of
raw, sewn-together flank steak, which, when fresh, was modeled (but
not by the artist) and then left to hang, rank and wizening, in a
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   A wider view of Ms. Sterbak's nuanced provocations will be
furnished in a mid-career survey of her work at the Museum of
Contemporary Art in Chicago, from Saturday through Feb. 21. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Flesh Dress,'' which will not be in the Chicago show, was
featured in several exhibitions about clothing and fashion or
mortality in the body-conscious climate of the late 80s and early
90s.
</P>
<P>
   It was discussed in numerous art journal articles about those
trendy subjects, thus fixing Ms. Sterbak within the camp of
feminist or body art. In truth, her oeuvre is more subtle and much
less categorical, ultimately stemming from the human condition as
seen through the eyes of a cultural nomad.
</P>
<P>
   Now living part time in Montreal and Barcelona, Spain, Ms.
Sterbak, 43, left her native Prague as a young teen-ager, but not
before absorbing an Eastern European mix of existentialist-informed
irony and a poetic touch with materials.
</P>
<P>
   The extremes of political ideologies she experienced at an
impressionable age, from that of dour, Communist-block
Czechoslovakia to that of cheerfully capitalist Canada, taught her
to buy into none of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her distrust of dogma fits perfectly into these
post-ideological times,'' says Amada Cruz, the former acting chief
curator at the Museum of Contemporary Art, who organized the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has this weird combination of skepticism, which is also
very timely, and yet an incredible faith in humanity,'' Ms. Cruz
says. ``Although her work does have a very strong point of view and
does deal with issues that could be thought of as specifically
feminist, she also deals with things universal in terms of just
being a human _ desire, longing, the contradiction between one's
will and the limits to what one can physically do.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sterbak agrees that her work comes more from life's currents
than current events, and that body- and AIDS-related art was a
trend many artists were shoehorned into by critics and curators.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways this interest in the body is misguided,'' she
says. ``What people should have been looking at, not only in my
case but in that of other artists, is how the representation of the
human has changed over time. We are so far away from historical
perspective, into a kind of theoretical language, that historical
context is not discussed.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Ms. Sterbak, the critical condition for humanity today is
that of the individual besieged by technology compared with, say,
the Greek model of the body filled with optimism, or the
Renaissance mix of religion and rationality.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work has to do with the limits of the individual, limits
that are defined as they always have been, and always will be, by
our mortality,'' she says. ``We have always tended to minimize this
mortality, and are now encouraged to do so by technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's medical advances that keep mortality at bay, or the
personal limitlessness proffered by cyber communications systems,
Ms. Sterbak says that technology also needs to be rescued from such
strictly utilitarian roles. ``For it to be mostly functional is
sad. Technology is in need of imbuing with a little poetry,'' she
says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Literature and technology were both important to her early on.
``Corona Laurea,'' 1983-84, was an electrified stove-coil headpiece
based on the Medea myth. Since the late 1970s Ms. Sterbak's
polymath methods have included traditional and mechanical
sculpture, performance, video, photography and borrowed ready-made
objects injected into multimedia installations.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than art theory, she reads fiction and poetry and cites
an international range of favorites including Milan Kundera, Max
Frisch, Paul Bowles, Heinrich Boll, Octavio Paz and Emily
Dickinson, often including passages of their writing in her
exhibition catalogs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I find the language of fiction more subtle than what usually
gets written about artists,'' she says. ``In fiction and poetry the
meaning is communicated on many levels, and there is also craft, or
style _ both form and content, as in my work. Form facilitates the
ease with which a work of art can be approached.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Sterbak's early work seemed more personal, invoking
highly charged, clashing sensations, since ``Flesh Dress'' her art
seems to be increasingly extroverted, even lighthearted. Technology
is given a playful break with ``Baldacchino,'' a 1997-98
interactive work that will have its debut in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   This head-high, metallic, mesh-veiled canopy on wheels moves
independently about the gallery, making seemingly random choices of
viewers to hover over and follow about. The hidden mechanisms have
to do with reflective properties; more than that the artist prefers
not to say.
</P>
<P>
   Another piece she is developing for a show at the Fabric
Workshop in Philadelphia involves a tent made from space-age fabric
that blocks all electromagnetic waves, literally sheltering
inhabitants from the pervasiveness of technology. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sterbak continues to be fascinated with electricity, a
perfect metaphor for danger and seduction. Many of her works
combine materials that conduct heat, light, electromagnetism or
mild electrical shock.
</P>
<P>
   A new incarnation of the Medea piece is ``Hot Crown,'' a metal
crown that becomes incandescent as viewers approach. Lower-tech
themes explore implied physical burdens and metaphors of wearisome
tasks. A group of late performance pieces involving husks or a
cocoonlike apparatus suggests metamorphoses a la her Czech
compatriot Franz Kafka.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absorption,'' 1995, is an art-historical conceit involving the
artist's desire to become a moth and consume all of Joseph Beuys'
felt suits, making the implicit point that men's clothing art is
regarded as humanist while dress-related art is seen as feminist.
It was inspired by an actual moth-infested Beuys suit she
discovered in storage at the Tate Gallery in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Condition,'' a 1995 video performance piece, required a man to
walk in circles dragging a large wheeled contraption resembling an
insect exoskeleton. Portability is also a subtext, perhaps because
of her peripatetic life style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Combat Cricket Compartment,'' 1993-97, contains live crickets
in a small carved horn case, allowing the carrier to transport
cricket songs of love and war. In all her work, the compelling
object seduces, while the implication or action surprises, shocks
or amuses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Material presence is the way to know,'' she says. ``It's
important for my objects to have a definite physical presence, that
they are physical in the way that we are, and that presence is our
first access.'' Her materials, though as quotidian as flank steak
and crickets, disabuse us of assumptions that we mistake for
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   A quote by Emily Dickinson included in the catalog of her
forthcoming show offers a parallel in such everyday enlightenment:
``To live is so startling, it leaves little room for other
occupations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1699 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV     09-30 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AH, FOR THE DAYS WHEN NEW MUSIC STIRRED THE BLOOD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (af)  
 David Schiff is a composer on the faculty of Reed College in
Portland, Ore.  
 By DAVID SCHIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have a bad case of the post-avant-garde blues. Whenever I hear
people praise a new piece of music for being ``accessible,'' and
for nothing else, I long for the days when new music could strike
terror in the soul instead of just aiming to please.
</P>
<P>
   Since most of the American music business has been dancing on
the grave of difficult music for the last decade, I often find
myself playing the role of the Ancient Mariner, spoiling the
festivities with obsessive memories of an episode everyone else has
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   The avant-garde may no longer represent the music of the future,
but now that it has been out of fashion for a generation, it is a
good time to reconsider how it fits into the musical past.
</P>
<P>
   I should declare my own prejudices: my adolescent encounters
with the European avant-garde were among the most formative
experiences of my musical life. In 1959, when I was 14, the cover
of a record on display in a music store on Main Street in New
Rochelle, N.Y., caught my eye.
</P>
<P>
   The album contained performances of Karlheinz Stockhausen's
``Zeitmasse'' and Pierre Boulez's ``Marteau Sans Maitre,''
conducted by Robert Craft.
</P>
<P>
   The titles and the names of the composers, who were then in
their early 30's, were unknown to me, but the cover reprinted a
page from the Stockhausen score, and it was like no music I had
ever seen. Five staffs of music were notated in four different
tempos, with independently changing meters. Within the different
tempos each instrument was playing triplets, quintuplets or
septuplets.
</P>
<P>
   Dotted lines indicated approximate places where the lines
coincided. Because I was young, the mad-scientist aspect of the
score made it all the more irresistible, and I bought the record on
the spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Stockhausen piece, with its sporadic blips, gurgles and
gushes of sound, proved as odd to the ear as it had to the eye, but
the life-changing revelation was the Boulez on the flip side.
Whereas Stockhausen's music was weird, Boulez's was sexy.
</P>
<P>
   Its scoring for alto voice, alto flute, viola, guitar,
vibraphone, marimba and percussion had the suggestive coolness of
Chet Baker, but the music wasn't jazz; it was wildly atonal and
arhythmic, a spray of unpredictable accents and fleeting colors.
Call me a nerd, but ``Le Marteau Sans Maitre'' knocked my teen-age
socks off more seismically than ``Hound Dog'' ever did.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 60s I lived in England, where Karlheinz Stockhausen
was the leader of the avant-garde pack, a position he never
attained in New York. Many English composers felt they were in a
hopeless state of catch-up with the Meister. Several had studied
with him, even lived in his house. They owned all of his scores and
could recite a litany of his innovations, from total organization
to total improvisation in the space of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   I heard ``Gruppen,'' Stockhausen's 1957 extravaganza for three
orchestras and three conductors, at Royal Festival Hall. (It has
never been performed in New York.) The hall was packed with
swinging Londoners who cheered as wildly for the composer as they
would for Pete Townshend or Jimi Hendrix.
</P>
<P>
   But my most vivid Stockhausen memory is of a recital of piano
pieces by Aloys Kontarsky, at the German Consulate in London.
Running late, I tripped on the sidewalk, ripping my trouser legs
and some skin as well. I will forever associate the relentless
pounding clusters of ``Piano Piece X'' with the sting of blood
running down my leg; that was the way new music was meant to feel.
</P>
<P>
   Youthful enthusiasm is a historical accident, a random
convergence of affinities. I don't know why my hormones bonded me
to Pierre Boulez rather than Buddy Holly, but I was unconsciously
seeking a kind of musical rebellion not available in most concert
music of the 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Craft, the skinny young man in a T-shirt who conducted
``Le Marteau,'' certainly looked more like a rebel with a cause
than Richard Rodgers or Aaron Copland did at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In the Eisenhower years, American music was dominated by
composers like Gian Carlo Menotti and Samuel Barber, whose idiom
went back to the 1930s. Even ``West Side Story,'' which critics
today describe as groundbreaking, echoed two Depression-era works,
Copland's ``Salon Mexico'' and Marc Blitzstein's `'Cradle Will
Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   It was music, I felt, by and for my parents' generation. To my
ears only the wild and crazy new European music had the subversive
scariness of Abstract Expressionist painting or beat poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Today, unfortunately, much of the music is forgotten. Neither
``Zeitmasse'' nor ``Gruppen'' is available on CD in the United
States. Deutsche Grammophon has never reissued its vast catalogue
of Stockhausen recordings, and the fine series of new-music
recordings Earle Brown produced for the Time label has never
resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
   While Stockhausen and Boulez remain canonical figures in Europe,
especially in Britain, performances of their music are rare on this
side of the Atlantic. Many critics and composers in their 30s,
blinded by their hatred of American ``academic'' music of the 1960s
and 70s, barely know this repertory.
</P>
<P>
   The music and ideas that emanated from Princeton and became
dogma in university departments for 20 years pursued certain
aspects of the European style, like electronic music and total
Serialism, in a sober, scholarly way. The academic scene was devoid
of vanguardist zeal if not entirely free of silliness and
posturing. It was a minor aftershock of what had been going on in
Europe since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Postwar Western Europe sought to create a music free of ties to
the Nazi era and distinct from Soviet Socialist Realism and its
American counterpart, the populism of Copland and Roy Harris.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany and Italy, government-sponsored radio stations and
festivals discovered an untainted and audacious new generation,
many trained by Olivier Messiaen. By the early 50s Boulez,
Stockhausen, Luigi Nono, Luciano Berio and Bruno Maderna had become
the most pampered young revolutionaries of all time, free to pursue
their impractical dreams in the well-subsidized hothouse atmosphere
of new-music festivals in Cologne and Darmstadt, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Although their music was termed post-Webernian, these composers
broke free of the inhibitions, refinements and Viennese trappings
of the Schoenberg school. Quickly assimilating the severely
organized pointillism of Webern's music, they were ready for more
radical speculation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Their music soon mixed science fiction with Dada; mathematical
manipulations of rhythm and pitch were pushed beyond the limits of
the ``playable.'' New instrumental techniques and notational
devices seemed to appear with every festival, leading to a
``breakthrough'' mentality that often turned into a parody of
itself but also produced innovations still being explored.
</P>
<P>
   The new technology of the tape recorder, which seems absurdly
low-tech today, made possible a tantalizingly dehumanized musical
expression, which Stockhausen vindicated with his tape masterpiece
``Gesang der Junglinge'' in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-60s, Stockhausen was eliminating notation altogether
and creating works for improvising musicians who had memorized most
of his previous works. When his improvised, intuitive work
``Stimmung,'' for eight singers who sustained a mystical chord for
an hour, appeared in 1967, the composer Roger Smalley compared it
to the opening of ``Das Rheingold,'' but Stockhausen's intentions,
to say nothing of his ego, seemed to dwarf Wagner's. Even the
Beatles paid attention.
</P>
<P>
   Today there is little awareness of new European music in this
country. (Quick, name a French, German or Italian composer under
60.) But Americans were deeply engaged in the European scene of the
50s, learning from it and influencing it.
</P>
<P>
   John Cage, in particular, had a traumatic impact on both Boulez
and Stockhausen. Although Boulez thought in the early 50s that he
was pursuing experimental aims similar to Cage's, he gradually came
to realize that Cage had less interest in sounds than in ideas.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Le Marteau'' Boulez reaffirmed his own preference for the
minute shaping of rhythms and colors, a choice that prefigured his
later work as a conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Stockhausen, by contrast, seized Cage's conceptualism and ran
with it. He played the fox to Cage's hedgehog. Where Cage left the
choice of notes to chance, Stockhausen increasingly assigned this
lesser task to assistants and acolytes.
</P>
<P>
   But Cage was not the only American on the scene. Edgard Varese,
Stefan Wolpe and Earle Brown toured the festival circuit. Elliott
Carter's style changed sharply after he heard ``Le Marteau.'' His
Double Concerto of 1961 linked the stereophonic experiments of
Stockhausen's ``Gruppen'' and Boulez's ``Doubles'' to techniques of
American ultramodernists like Charles Ives, Henry Cowell and Conlon
Nancarrow.
</P>
<P>
   And the old master himself, Igor Stravinsky, gave his blessing
to ``Le Marteau'' and ``Gruppen,'' and even imitated Stockhausen's
notational idiosyncracies in his latest scores.
</P>
<P>
   Since there are no new recordings of these works, I went back to
my well-worn LPs to see how the music holds up. Any successful
style, whether Neo-Classicism or Minimalism, eventually falls
victim to its own cliches, and I feared that these works would
sound as stale as their imitators.
</P>
<P>
   Instead I felt again the old exhilaration. Not only does ``Le
Marteau'' still sizzle, but I can still sing the tunes. I listened
to two recordings, Craft's, and Boulez's CBS version from the 70s,
which I now prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Craft brought out the Stravinskian aspects of the score, making
it sound at times like ``L'Histoire du Soldat,'' with taut rhythms
and dry articulation. Boulez's recording reveals the work's French
roots, especially its connections to Debussy's Sonata for Flute,
Viola and Harp and to the Orientalist side of Messaien. The rhythms
are more flexible than in Craft's reading; the sonorities,
particularly the percussion, more sensuous.
</P>
<P>
   But revisiting this work in either performance reconfirms
Stravinsky's judgment that it was a masterpiece. It gives enormous
pleasure in its intricate details, in the way it varies and
elaborates its materials and in its dramatic form.
</P>
<P>
   Stockhausen's music remains more difficult to assess, because it
refuses to fit into any previous esthetic or expressive category.
But the young Stockhausen was full of beans, and the inventiveness
of ``Zeitmasse'' and ``Gruppen,'' their fearless discovery of
complex rhythms and colors, compensates for their apparent
rootlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The extravagant virtuosity of ``Zeitmasse,'' a woodwind quintet
with English horn replacing the traditional French horn, still
sounds marvelously fresh, and the piece has a succinctness rare in
Stockhausen's music. Rehearing ``Gruppen'' on an old Deutsche
Grammophon LP is a more mixed experience, though it may be unfair
to judge such a technically difficult work on the basis of a rough
performance in a bizarrely unbalanced recording.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously intended as a visionary work, ``Gruppen'' sends off
conflicting signals. Although Stravinsky wrote that its ``groups,''
or short phrases, were ``admirably composed,'' they often seem
haphazard in shape, color and sometimes even style.
</P>
<P>
   Bits of Webern and Schoenberg float by, but there are also
gestures that sound like Stan Kenton's ``experimental'' phase. And
then there are those strange passages for electric guitar and
baritone sax, which suggest that Stockhausen was listening to
rhythm-and-blues, but not closely enough.
</P>
<P>
   By definition avant-garde works have a short shelf life.
Whatever is merely new soon becomes merely old. Vanguard art
flourishes after events of political turmoil that make it seem as
if the past no longer existed, like the two world wars or the
Russian revolution.
</P>
<P>
   As the history of Italian Futurism shows, historical
developments can make artistic manifestoes seem naive if not evil.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as their novelty fades, the works remain, and in the case
of the postwar European avant-garde, their youthful vehemence and
bravado was supported by musical talent and technique of a high
order. In an era of retro-this and neo-that, these works remind us
of a time when music looked toward its future with a sense of
infinite possibilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
