r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTIN-FILMFEST01-COX     09-30 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-FILMFEST01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin Film Festival debates screen writing credits
 &HT;    EMBARGOED FOR 10/1
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSPIN, Texas _ Austin screenwriter Lawrence Wright recently was
sitting in a Dallas movie theater with his family when the trailer
for the film of his first produced script, ``The Siege,'' flickered
across the screen. After a scene in which star Denzel Washington
delivers a stirring speech, Wright's nephew turned to him and
asked, ``Did you write that, Uncle Larry?'&AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Wright recalls this with a tinge of disappointment because, no,
he didn't write that. Not exactly. Well, he did, but he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the snarled conundrum of the modern movie screenplay.
Wright wrote the speech, but at least three other writers rewrote
it and most of the rest of the script as well. This makes things
rather ticklish when it comes to claiming writing credit.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on his nephew's question, Wright says, ``How do you
answer that? I told him I sort of wrote it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the fifth annual Heart of Film Screenwriters Conference and
Competition gets under way, now is a good time to ask: What does a
screenwriting credit mean on a movie anymore?
</P>
<P>
   From the famous, if perhaps apocryphal, case of a 60-person
committee writing ``The Flintstones'' to ``Armageddon'' requiring
eight writers, it can be difficult to truly know who wrote what.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to measure,'' agrees Wright. ``The Writers
Guild (of America) makes an honest effort to apportion credit in a
way that's just. But it's almost impossible to do it fairly because
it's hard to quantify who wrote which parts. There are so many
variables.''
</P>
<P>
   The Guild maintains firm jurisdiction over these variables. For
instance, for a writer to earn a screen credit, he or she has to
have written 50 percent of the final version of an original
screenplay. Only a 33 percent contribution is required to get
credit for a screenplay made from other source material, such as a
novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``These percentages gbviously cannot be determined by counting
lines or even the number of pages to which a writer contributed,''
states the Guild's Screen Credit Manual. If a second writer is to
get credit, ``his/her contribution must consist of dramatic
construction, original and different sequences, original
characterization and dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the clincher: ``There have been instances in which every
line has been changed and still the (Guild) can find no significant
change in the screenplay as a whole.'' Which means someone can
rewrite every line and still get no credit.
</P>
<P>
   These notorious rules often don't sit well with Hollywood
wordsmiths. ``It doesn't make sense that someone can put a
considerable amount of time to rewsite a screenplay and not get
credit, while the caterer gets a credit,'' says Wright.
</P>
<P>
   But it happens all the time, leading to arbitration between
Guild and scribe on a regular basis. The Guild manual notes that
more than 150 times a year it is asked to resolve credit
controversies. Here are just a few notable arbitration cases:
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Steven Soderbergh (''Out of Sight'') quit the
Guild in disgust over its decision not to give him sole credit for
his 1994 film ``The Underneath,'' which he filmed in Austin and was
based on the 1948 film noir ``Criss Cross.'' Soderbergh told us he
completely rewrote the original's script but was still denied full
credit. So$he used a pseudonym.
</P>
<P>
   John Sayles wrote the entire last draft of ``Apollo 13'' yet got
no screen credit. A miffed Sayles told The Independent of London,
``The habit of Hollywood is to have serial writers, to use them a
bit like toilet paper. ... Your claim to a screen credit isn't
based on whether you make it better, but on the percentage of the
script you can prove you've changed. So if you make it 40 percent
worse, you're going to get credit, but if you make it 10 percent
better, you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   When an arbitration panel denied writer David Mamet a
first-position writing credit for ``Wag the Dog,'' director Barry
Levinson threatened to quit the Guild. Hilary Jenkin had adapted
her screenplay for the film from a novel, and Levinson claims Mamet
rearranged sequences, rewrote dialogue and added characters,
including key ones played by Dustin Hoffman and Woody Harrelson.
Mamet skirmished with the Guild again over credit for ``Ronin,''
the Robert De Niro film that opened last week. Director John
Frankenheimer told the Los Angeles Times that Mamet completely
rewrote J.D. Zeik's original script. ``We didn't shoot a line of
Zeik's script,'' he said. Mamet, he added, chose to use the
pseudonym Richard Weisz instead of taking second billing as a form
of protest.
</P>
<P>
   The names of three writers appeared in the credits for ``The
Mask of Zorro,'' but not that of David Ward, who director Martin
Campbell insists rewrote almost every line of dialogue. By not
getting his name on the film, Ward told the Los Angeles Times he
lost out on $150,000 in extra pay.
</P>
<P>
   Guild arbitration is rarely simple* Wright, who went through
screen credit arbitration for ``The Siege,'' which is scheduled to
open Nov. 6, ended up with first-position credit as well as the
line ``Based on a story by Lawrence Wright.'' That means he created
the story and characters and also owns the rights to them. It
doesn't mean he's completely comfortable with the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange for me to read the shooting script and see my
characters say things I didn't write,'' says Wright, who is now
working on a script by Pat Conroy about a newspaper editor and is
the fifth writer on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Being rewritten ``is not a terrible thing,'' says Wright. ``If
you're an honest craftsman, sometimes it's better. You can learn
from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most writers who have been rewritten generally are not ecstatic
with the results. Dale Launer _ who wrote the screenplays for ``My
Cousin Vinny'' and ``Dirty Rotten Scoundrels,'' and will appear on
a panel about Guild issues at 3 p.m. today at the Driskill Hotel as
part of the Austin conference _ had his script for ``Blind Date''
rewritten.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's probably my worst film,'' he says from Los Angeles.
``I tried to get my name taken off it, but I couldn't. Because I
was guaranteed $125,000 or more for writing a script, the studio
can decide if you can use a pseudonymous name.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' he says with a laugh, ``my pseudonym of Vidal
Grosswanker was rejected.''
</P>
<P>
   Launer's theory about multiple screen credits is simple. ``Odds
are if you see a single credit on a movie, that person was the only
writer,'' he says. ``When you start seeing a lot of writers, it's
usually not that good of a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Often so many uncredited writers maneuver behind the scenes that
the audience may never know just how much brain power was exerted
to realize the final product. (Fortunately, the audience rarely
cares as long as the movie is good.)
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Daniel Petrie Jr. _ who is president of Writers
Guild of America/West and will appear with Launer on today's Guild
issues panel _ was nominated for best screenplay for ``Beverly
Hills Cop,'' even though it was a rewrite job for him. There were
three scripts before his that took a more dramatic tone and told
different stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio wanted something very different, starting from a
new outline,'' says Petrie from his L.A. office. ``My contribution
was to think about it in more comedic terms. I changed the entire
thing, from structure to characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrie did share ``Story by'' credit with the original writer,
and they sat together at the Oscar ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, a New Yorker magazine staffer known largely for his
magazine journalism and books, was on the other end of the
screenwriting journey for his ``Siege'' script, which imagines
internment of U.S. citizens in the wake of a terrorist attack.
After he gave director Edward Zwick a first draft, Zwick asked for
a rewrite. Unsatisfied with it, Zwick took the script and worked on
it with Menno Meyjes. Finally, hot screenwriter Paul Attanasio
(''Quiz Show'') did what's called a ``production rewrite'' on the
script. His script doctoring will go uncredited. (But not
unrewarded: Script doctors earn up to $200,000 a week for their
handiwork.)
</P>
<P>
   The extremely massaged final script is altered but recognizable,
says Wright. ``The structure is very similar and the characters are
the same,'' he says. ``The dialogue is mostly changed, and they
changed the terrorists' weapon from nuclear to conventional. I'm
amazed there's as much of my story left up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Though disappointed that he had to be rewritten, Wright is not
surprised. ``It's something every writer in this business
expects,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Garcia is the film critic for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
