<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tuer to focus on speed, discipline, hard work and fun
 &HT;    By Ian Tennant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Speed. Discipline. Hard work and fun. Those are the
attributes Al Tuer wants to use this season as the new head coach
of the Austin Ice Bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a demanding person and a demanding coach,'' the
soft-spoken Tuer said at a news conference recently at the Radisson
Hotel downtown. ``I like to have my fun, but I also enjoy winning
and I enjoy working. I think the only way to have fun is to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuer, 35, known as a hard-nosed defenseman during 10 years of
professional hockey, spent nearly 2,500 minutes in the penalty
boxes of various leagues and another 208 minutes in 57 National
Hockey League games, and he has a few scars to prove it. At around
six feet, the trim, blond Tuer (pronounced ``tour'') looks fit
enough to pull on a Bats jersey if need be.
</P>
<P>
   He considers himself a coach who runs a disciplined team that
has ``an unmatched work ethic.'' Tuer was coach and general manager
of the Moose Jaw Warriors for the past five seasons and took the
Western Hockey League team to the playoffs three times.
</P>
<P>
   Tuer was a former teammate of Ice Bats General Manager Blaine
Stoughton and Vice President Paul Lawless. Stoughton tried to hire
Tuer in July, and although he was impressed with Austin and the Ice
Bats, Tuer returned to Saskatchewan for what looked like a
promising junior hockey season. But the board that operates the
community-owned amateur Warriors wouldn't let Tuer make some
personnel moves, Tuer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things fell apart for one thing or another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuer was on the phone to Stoughton in mid-August asking if the
contract was still on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of shocked,'' Stoughton said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Factors that influenced Tuer's decision to move south from the
Canadian prairie city were the chances to focus only on coaching,
move up to the professional level and join a solid organization.
Since arriving last week, one of Tuer's first jobs has been finding
a home for his wife and three children, preferably one with a pool
to help beat the Austin heat. Tuer played in at least 11 U.S.
cities and appeared excited about moving to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   One piece of local turf the coach will have to get used to is
the aptly named Bat Cave, the Travis County Exposition Center. When
asked about the Ice Bats' quest to build a new home near downtown
Austin, Tuer said, ``It's a beautiful city, so it should have a
beautiful arena.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuer's presence behind the bench looks like a good fit for the
Ice Bats. Tuer and Stoughton have discussed players for a couple of
years, and the new coach has a roster stocked mostly with young
western Canadian players.
</P>
<P>
   Tuer acknowledged that his fingerprints are on the Bats. ``I
think we will be young and hungry this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The coach expects the third line of forwards, traditionally the
checking line, to push the first and second lines to work hard. The
Bats must have roster depth to win the Western Professional Hockey
League's President's Cup, but also ``a group of kids that want to
get there.'' Tuer looks for the Ice Bats to be a high-scoring,
aggressive team that also plays tough defense.
</P>
<P>
   Ice Bats management has cleaned house this summer, and so far
only three players are returning from last season _ Andy Ross, Ryan
Anderson and Mike Jackson. Former Bats player Jim Burton started
last season as coach but was fired Feb. 10, the day before a team
photo was taken, and replaced by Lawless. Burton is now coaching
the expansion Tupelo (Miss.) T-Rex, and Lawless returned to the
front office.
</P>
<P>
   Training camp starts Saturday at Chaparral Ice Center. The first
of four exhibition games is Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
