<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: A book works magic on long car ride
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What looked like an interminable drive to Cleveland _ as
interminable as only four hours with kids in a motor vehicle can be
_ turned out to be a joy, thanks to one magic trick: a book.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the drive we read From the Mixed-Up Files of Mrs.
Basil E. Frankweiler, the 1967 classic about a brother and sister
who run away from home and hide out at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art, making amazing discoveries (about themselves and Michelangelo)
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Yep _ books are the perfect prescription for the tedium of a
road trip, or just about anything else that ails you. Just ask
folks at the Children's Health Clinic at Children's Medical Center,
where books are quite literally what the doctor orders.
</P>
<P>
   With the ``Reach Out and Read'' program, introduced last year,
clinic doctors fill out a prescription, which comes with a free
book, for every child from six months to five years who comes in
for a checkup. During the program's first year, about 2,000 books
have been distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinic doctors hand out a neat white card with the
official-looking text: PRESCRIPTION FOR READING: WHAT TO DO: Share
a book with your child. TIMES: Every night at bedtime for 10
minutes every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This takes advantage of the relationship that already exists
between parent and pediatrician,'' said Dr. Maria Nanagas, director
of the Children's Health Clinic, who introduced the national
program to Dayton. ``The pediatrician is one of the few people who
has day-to-day contact with the parent from day one. We're in a
good position to offer advice to parents to read to their children.
It is taken more seriously, coming from the doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reach Out and Read program started at Boston City Hospital
in 1987, based on the theory that failure in school can lead to
other problems such as teen pregnancy and substance abuse. It
became so successful that the American Academy of Pediatrics helped
to launch a national program.
</P>
<P>
   Kids benefit from lap time with Mom and Dad as well as from
having their own library _ a luxury some of Nanagas' patients can't
afford. ``If it's a choice between bread and books, you'll go to
the grocery,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring last year from Wright-Patterson Air Force Museum,
Irina Voise, 68, of Riverside had one clear goal for her free time:
She wanted to read to children. (Now, that's my kind of woman.) She
became part of a corps of volunteer readers in the clinic's waiting
room.
</P>
<P>
   Voise loves working with the gifted children: ``I smile to
myself when I think of these children whose diction and mastery of
the English language is so impeccable, who deal with complicated
concepts at an early age with such ease and flair that I switch to
reading to these children from books written for much older
children.''
</P>
<P>
   But then again, maybe working with the average child is even
better: ``I can tell, from visit to visit, when these children
begin to enjoy being read to more and more. The hard-won successes
can be a lot sweeter than the easy ones.''
</P>
<P>
   No, no, after thinking about it, Voise knows what's the best
part of all: ``It is that moment when the parent comes to get the
child in order to go home and the child begins to cry because he or
she wants to be read to some more.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you suppose she hires out for road trips?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
