<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I'm taking leave to take a chance
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service-Palm Beach Post
<TEXT>
<P>
   I returned his message on a Thursday morning. It was about 10
o'clock when I borrowed somebody's office, privacy seemed in order,
and dialed up this perfect stranger with the polished voice and the
212 area code.
</P>
<P>
   There I was, holed up in foreign work space, feeling a little _
OK, a lot _ like I did back in 1970 when I was trying out for
eighth-grade cheerleader. Shaking hands. Stomach in knots.
Imagination running full force.
</P>
<P>
   What did a famous literary agent from New York want with me?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, all right already. Maybe I should start at the beginning.
The day I got the phone call from the man who left his name but not
his number.
</P>
<P>
   There I was trudging into the office. It was April and we were
getting ready to pay our income taxes and it was hot outside and I
felt fat and I'd just quit smoking so I was a little nutty.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, another day, another dollar, I was thinking when I
checked my voice mail and some guy named Sterling Lord had left a
message.
</P>
<P>
   I figured he was calling to promote a book or something, so I
instructed my smart phone to save the message for seven days. Then
I proceeded to sit there and brood about the lack of nicotine and
money in my life. When I was done moping about that, I called and
got the local times for Weight Watchers meetings. I think I might
have done some work in between, but I'm only saying that because my
editor will read this.
</P>
<P>
   But the man's message, his smart tone, his lovely style, his
stated profession (I am a literary agent from New York City) kept
my imagination going. And days later, when I mentioned the call to
two people I work with, the woman next to me nearly lost her
eyeballs.
</P>
<P>
   She had heard of him.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out lots of other people had also heard of Sterling Lord,
a prominent New York literary agent who years ago discovered a
young talent named Jack Kerouac. Yes. Sterling Lord is the man who
sold Kerouac's famous On TheRoad. And he was calling me.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, after I called my mother and my sister and my brother
and my best friend since kindergarten, after I hyperventilated
myself into what felt like a four-beer stupor, I got the nerve to
call 212 information, get his number and return his phone call.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out he often spends weekends in Palm Beach and was calling
to say that maybe, just maybe, he could help me get a book
contract, a little something he did in very short order after I
provided him with a few breathless ideas.
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. Good things can happen to chubby,
unsuspecting non-smokers who sit around and mope on company time.
Good things can just reach out from the 212 area code and damn near
grab you.
</P>
<P>
   So, I am taking a leave from my columnist job at The Palm Beach
Post, but just for three months. I will miss you, the calls, the
craziness, the regular purging of my soul with the honest thoughts
that have become both my professional tools and my personal
medicine. It's just that someone, somewhere, is paying me to
collect my thoughts on family and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Someone, somewhere, thinks I can write a book. Some guy named
Sterling Lord.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
