<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Holy war _ on contraception?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There they go again _ reminding Americans why, even with chagrin
over dumb things done in office, they don't regret having elected
Bill Clinton president.
</P>
<P>
   There they go reminding Americans, particularly women, of the
ballot alternative they had on one of the most fundamental issues
of all: family planning.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is policy makers who couldn't care less about
holistic family planning.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: A group of Republicans led by Rep. Christopher
Smith of New Jersey and Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma is attempting
to revoke a policy approved by the House and Senate that would
allow federal workers' health insurance to cover prescription
contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   The wisdom of covering contraception seems a slam dunk. It's
basic health care, basic common sense for an employer _ in this
case, you and me _ who wants to keep employees on the job.
</P>
<P>
   But, no. The Smith-Nickles group asserts that some of the birth
control methods are abortifacients _ meaning they would destroy
fertilized eggs.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would cover birth control pills, diaphragms,
intrauterine devices, Norplant and Depo-Provera.
</P>
<P>
   None of these are designed to be abortifacients. All are
designed to prevent conception. Yes: contraception.
</P>
<P>
   Lord, lord. What the tunnel-vision set does to make the world of
public policy a more difficult place. Health insurance for public
employees is only one example. Here's another.
</P>
<P>
   Since abortion foes can't ban it here or anywhere, you'd think
they would commit themselves to preventing unwanted pregnancies.
But it's just the opposite. They target the agencies around the
world that do the most to prevent unwanted pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the House passed a foreign appropriations bill
containing an amendment by Rep. Roger Wicker, R-Miss., forbidding
U.S. family planning funds to organizations that ``engage in . .
.efforts to alter laws or government policies of any foreign
country concerning the circumstances under which abortion is
permitted, regulated or prohibited.''
</P>
<P>
   This takes up a notch in absurdity a Reagan administration
wrinkle that barred family planning funds to international
organizations that did abortion, even if the funds did not go to
the abortion services. (It's long been against the law for U.S. tax
dollars to fund abortion. That was never the issue.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton revoked that policy. Republicans have been trying to
revive it since. Now, in the Wicker amendment, they're talking not
just about forbidding U.S.-funded overseas agencies from doing
abortions but also from expressing views about abortion policies.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton promising a veto to this absurd rule, crucial
foreign appropriations, including reauthorized funds for the
International Monetary Fund, hang in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Republican anti-abortion budget riders have become to lawmaking
in Washington what burrs are to socks. The authors are trying to
make a point _ but what point? Generally these riders in some way
end up impeding birth control, which impedes unwanted pregancy,
which is why women have abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast this policy of destructive obstruction with Clinton's
common-sense policy aim to make abortion ``legal, safe and rare.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a motto that best fits the public mood and best deals with
reality. All Americans would prefer to see fewer abortions. But the
majority would not ban abortion. The majority would promote more
responsible choices.
</P>
<P>
   Puzzled by anti-abortion crusaders who work to undermine those
choices? Look. There they go again.
</P>
<P>
   Joh n Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
