<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-MEMORABILIA01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The ball's in his court
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark McGwire's historic season ended Sunday in St. Louis. The
chase for his 70th home run started Monday in Fort Lauderdale on
the second floor of a Las Olas Boulevard bank building.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the Law Office of David Kraythen, which specializes
in medical malpractice cases, suddenly became the negotiating
backdrop for perhaps the most prized piece of memorabilia in sports
history.
</P>
<P>
   The McGwire-Kraythen connection is this: Philip Ozersky, the
26-year-old Missouri man who snagged McGwire's record-setting
homer, is a cousin of Kraythen's wife.
</P>
<P>
   So when a dive for a baseball landed Ozersky in a high-pressured
game of faxes, sports agents and seven-figure offers, the frazzled
research scientist called his cousin Francine in Florida for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they start talking about million-dollar offers and
drawing up insurance for the ball and if I need insurance for
myself, it's time to get somebody who knows about the law, somebody
you can trust,'' Ozersky said Tuesday in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was grateful to have someone I know I can trust.''
</P>
<P>
   David Kraythen, a lawyer for 26 years, said he isn't charging
Ozersky a nickel. ``It's been mind-boggling to this kid. He has
been inundated. He had problems sleeping (Sunday) night. He turned
to his family for help. Hopefully we'll be able to make his life a
little easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Making life easier for Ozersky this week has meant a much busier
and exciting week for Kraythen's office, just down the boulevard
from the offices of Florida Marlins owner H. Wayne Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   While Kraythen sorts out offers for the ball of up to $1 million
from professional memorabilia dealers, associate lawyer Mike
Freedlund spent part of Tuesday fielding calls from The Tonight
Show with Jay Leno, Today (Ozersky is tentatively scheduled to
appear Friday), and Late Show With David Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   And the ball? It's in a safe-deposit box in a St. Louis bank.
It's next move may be across the street from where it was hit _
near Busch Stadium at the St. Louis Sports Hall of Fame, which
hopes to open a temporary display of the ball in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky, a season-ticket holder for the St. Louis Rams football
team, decided at the last minute to attend McGwire's final game for
a chance to see history.
</P>
<P>
   History came screaming right at him in the seventh inning.
Ozersky, who was with friends in a party suite behind the
left-field wall at Busch Stadium, said he picked up the flight of
the ball ``just over the third baseman's head.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball kept getting bigger. ``People were screaming, `It's
coming here! It's coming here!' I was moving toward it, but you
didn't want to get in its way. It hit a couple of (other fans')
hands, and they're still black and blue today.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ball hit a wall and bounced under some bleachers,
Ozersky said he threw his body flat on the ground to get a better
look. ``And it was right there. I picked it up and said, `Oh, my,
God. . . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky said he was not injured in the pileup. In newspaper
photographs the next day, he is shown holding the ball with what
appears to be a black-and-blue mark under his left eye. ``That's a
birthmark,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals tried to pressure him into giving the ball to
McGwire, but Ozersky said he wasn't sure what he wanted to do and
wanted time to think. He tried to sleep Sunday night, with the ball
in a basket next to his pillow. ``I got maybe an hour's sleep. At
5:30, the phone started ringing.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ozersky nor Kraythen will say how many offers have been
made. But St. Louis attorney Alan S. Cohen said he represents three
collectors who have combined to offer Ozersky $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the deadline on that offer is 4:50 p.m. EDT Thursday.
deadline was 72 hours after the end of SUnday's game which ended at
3:50 Central time/ deadline was extended a day because Wednesday is
Yom Kippur Ozersky said he won't be rushed into making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't a had a second to put some good thought into
it,'' he said. ``Before the game, people were saying, `If I catch
ball. . . .' I was like, `Right!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ozersky laughed that he should have had a clue, when the game's
ceremonial first pitch was thrown by actor Cuba Gooding Jr., who is
known for his famous ``SHow me the money!'' line in the movie
``Jerry Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the best piece of advice he's gotten so far was from
Krayeth who told him: ``It can have a positive change in your life
and it can have a negative change. Notoriety and `Fifteen Minutes
of Fame can do different things to differnt people. He needs to be
cognizant of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
