<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 01-COX &HT;    Jailer hasn't missed a day in 16 years
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If you think Cal Ripken is an iron man who
exemplifies the work ethic, check out Sgt. Curtis Ladewig of the
Travis County sheriff's office.
</P>
<P>
   Now here's a real role model who deserves a spot in the Blue
Collar Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken's major-league record of playing in 2,632 consecutive
baseball games came to an end a week ago Sunday, when he took
himself out of the lineup. Ripken's streak began on May 30, 1982.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 28, 1982, Ladewig began working for the sheriff's
office. And, according to Deborah Rich, the sheriff's personnel
coordinator, he hasn't taken a sick day yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that's right, not even a sick hour,'' said Ladewig, 62,
a modest, soft-spoken guy who works the graveyard shift as a
supervisor at the Travis County Correctional Complex in Del Valle.
</P>
<P>
   Ladewig attributes his string to good genes and not wanting to
leave his fellow employees holding the bag while he's home with the
sniffles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an accident of genetics, I suppose,'' Ladewig said
of his longstanding good health. ``I had the foresight to choose my
parents wisely.'' A trim fellow, Ladewig also says he doesn't order
Big Macs.
</P>
<P>
   But Ladewig also attributes his streak to want-to and accepting
responsibility. Mothers, have your kids read this part of the
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder, `Man, if I could only get off today to do this or
that,' '' Ladewig said. ``But if you're not there, somebody has to
be. Somebody has to take up the slack and take your position. And
then you're altering somebody else's day.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Deputy Dan Richards has been in law enforcement since
1969. He says he's never been around a string like Ladewig's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have met me a lot of cops, and I have logged a few sick days
myself,'' Richards said. ``And being a supervisor, I'm familiar
with the concept, `Oh, Sarge, I can't come in today. I feel so
bad.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of feeling bad, Ladewig admits there were days when he
felt like taking himself out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not some kind of Superman,'' he said. ``I've had colds.''
He also admits to having been late for work a few times.
</P>
<P>
   So he missed the National Anthem now and again. Big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken's and Ladewig's careers are remarkably similar, with
Ladewig beginning his streak just a few months after Ripken started
his.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's kinda close,'' Ladewig said. ``Course, he kinda
voluntarily broke his string.''
</P>
<P>
   But when you compare their schedules, Ladewig's ongoing
accomplishment beats Ripken's record like a set of bongos. The
regular baseball season runs from late March or early April into
September and includes 162 games. But since they continually throw
people in jail out in Del Valle, Ladewig's season lasts all year.
</P>
<P>
   And if you want to talk night games, Ladewig's current shift
starts at 10 p.m. and doesn't end until 8 the next morning. That's
worse than playing a night game in Anaheim, then catching the
red-eye for Kansas City. At least you can try to sleep on the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working all night, you never get used to it,'' said Ladewig,
who began his career with the sheriff's office as a jailer at the
old county jail downtown, on top of the Travis County Courthouse.
``You're completely out of sync with everybody else. You're eatin'
supper when they're eatin' breakfast. But that's the nature of the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Ladewig going to take himself out of the game any time
soon? Sure doesn't sound like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think probably now that I've gone this far into the season,
I'll try to play it out as long as providence keeps me healthy,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes a humor column on Mondays, Wednesdays and
Fridays. He can be reached at jkelsostatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
