<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1742 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-BIZ-COLUMN01-CO     09-30 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-BIZ-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unplanned growth can swamp small companies
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN -- Snagging a contract with a big company such as Dell
Computer Corp. or IBM presents two issues to a small business
owner.
</P>
<P>
   First, the small business owner must get in the door to make the
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the owner must be ready for the sudden increase in
business with enough employees and money to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it the other way around ?
</P>
<P>
   ``If an extraordinary large volume of new business comes in that
requires people and capital and it isn't planned,'' says Austin
business consultant Ron Walters, co-owner of R.D. Walters
Consulting &AMP; Associates, ``it can be disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Saper, co-founder of Saper Media Group, used a combination
of contacts, luck and tenacity to nab some of his first big
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Saper Media got its foot in the door at Dell six months ago when
it partnered with T3, one of Dell's primary vendors, to develop
Dell's small business Web site. Saper had become friends with T3's
owners while he was working for AT&AMP;T. Saper Media has since won
contracts to build the Dell University Web site and is now
completing a Web site for its Brazil customers.
</P>
<P>
   Building a client roster that includes such companies as Dell
and Tivoli Systems helps Saper Media when it is trying to get the
attention of new customers, says Jeri Saper, co-founder of the
company. ``I think it legitimizes us,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That helps us get appointments,'' adds Paul Saper, ``but it
doesn't necessarily help us close the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Good old-fashioned luck can also play a part in winning
important clients. Geofox Ltd., a British company that makes
hand-held computers, came across Saper Media's Web site a year ago.
Geofox happened to have an executive flying into Austin and
arranged to meet. A few days later they signed a contract. The
Geofox contract has led to a major relationship with Tivoli
Systems, now one of Saper's biggest clients.
</P>
<P>
   Guts played a part in how Saper Media won the attention of
Samsung Austin Semiconductor three years ago. Paul Saper says he
was at a local copying store when he happened to see a Samsung
executive's business card lying on the counter. He quickly jotted
down the name and phone number and placed a call when he got back
to the office.
</P>
<P>
   He reached a key executive with Samsung and a member of the team
choosing a vendor. ``He said, 'Your timing is perfect. Can you send
over a proposal today?' '' Saper says that within two weeks he had
the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Walters, the Austin business consultant, says small companies
eager to grow quickly must make sure they have sufficient resources
lined up before going for the big contracts.
</P>
<P>
   He says getting a large influx of business when a small company
isn't ready can create untold problems. If the employees, financing
and other resources aren't in place when the contract comes in, it
will undermine its reputation for doing quality work, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sometimes difficult for the small entrepreneur that is
working very diligently to grow their business to accept,'' Walters
says. ``Too much growth, too quickly can be as devastating as not
enough business.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan Triplett, co-founder of the Entrepreneurs' Association, says
small companies must also be ready to adapt their operations to
mesh with how the corporation wants to do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things about working with a large company is when
they say 'jump' you say, 'how high,' '' Triplett says.
</P>
<P>
   Kelsey August, who owns 5-year-old Lone Star Direct, says she
had lined up several hundred thousand dollars in credit at Frost
Bank and Compass Bank in anticipation of landing a major contract.
She says she followed Walters' advice to line up financing, even
though it still wasn't clear to her why she needed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, ``Why do I have this huge line of credit ? I don't
even have the business,' '' she recalls. But when National Heritage
Insurance Co. suddenly placed a $70,000 contract with Lone Star
Direct, which is a direct mail and marketing company, it took every
bit of the credit she'd arranged.
</P>
<P>
   August says lines of credit are important for her company's
cash-flow when a contract with a large company comes in. She says
up to half of the contract can be the cost of postage. While small
customers can quickly write a check to advance her company money
for the postage necessary to process the orders, it can take much
longer to get these payments from large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is done on purchase orders. It may take 60 to 90
days to get paid because of the red tape,'' she says. ``I really
have to groom my clients and tell them why I need postage prepaid a
month from now.''
</P>
<P>
   She says Lone Star Direct's willingness to front postage costs
has helped it win contracts, as well as its flexibility in handling
sudden orders.
</P>
<P>
   She says an employee at Harte-Hanks Direct Marketing called Lone
Star Direct when the company couldn't find the quick help it needed
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked for a miracle. She needed a job processed within 24
hours,'' August says. ``It was a three- to four-day regular turn. I
jumped to it and hired temporary workers and got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   August says Lone Star's relationship with IBM Corp. started
after she had approached nearly two dozen IBM executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the company's current vendor defaulted, they had
something on file on me,'' she recalled. ``They said, 'OK, you're
on.' '' Paul Saper, with Saper Media, has found that while it's
nice to win contracts with large customers, it is also important
that a company keep a good balance of smaller customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any small business, you have to be careful not to put too
many eggs in one basket,'' he says. He says Saper Media's largest
client represents less than 20 percent of its total revenues. ``It
means you have more interactions with more companies, but it
ensures no one company is driving your revenue base.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Tyson writes Wednesdays on small-business issues. Send
information to her at P.O. Box 670, Austin, 78767 or by e-mail at
ktysonstatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Look for experts' answers to frequently asked questions
regarding raising money for small businesses at Austin360.com/biz/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
