<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EATON-PLANTCLOSING01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eaton to close plant in Austin
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Eaton Corp., reacting to the prolonged
semiconductor slump, will close its 239-employee Austin
semiconductor equipment plant and transfer its operations to
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it will lay off 200 workers in Austin starting
Dec. 1. It will phase out production at the Austin plant, located
on Spectrum Drive near RM 620, by March 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   At least 40 workers will be asked to move to Beverly, Mass.,
where the company's semiconductor equipment business is based.
Another 30 Eaton employees will remain in Austin to support and
service Eaton equipment installed in local chip manufacturing
plants.
</P>
<P>
   The move is part of the restructuring of Eaton's semiconductor
equipment business that will include eliminating 275 jobs outside
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The parent company, Eaton Corp. of Cleveland, will take a $42
million charge against earnings in the current quarter to pay for
the restructuring. The company expects to take additional charges
of about $4 million in each of the following two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton, like other chip-equipment makers, is feeling the impact
of lower semiconductor sales around the world. Chip makers have
postponed new factories and expansions, which hurts demand for
equipment makers such as Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see any light at the end of the tunnel,'' said
Maureen Hart, an Easton spokeswoman. ``We don't see the market
coming back until the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to lose $80 million this year in its
semiconductor equipment business with revenue down 50 percent, Hart
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin plant makes ion implantation equipment, which is used
to bombard silicon wafers with precise amounts of chemical
impurities -- called dopants _ to change their electrical
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   The $15 million plant was completed in 1996 to accommodate the
company's business expansion in Austin, where Eaton has had
manufacturing operations for nearly two decades. Employment peaked
around 400 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton becomes the latest Austin casualty in the long-running
slump, which began late last year. Other semiconductor and related
companies cutting jobs include Applied Materials Inc., many of
Applied's suppliers, and Motorola Inc., which has offered a sizable
voluntary severance plan. Motorola is signaling to workers that it
will eliminate jobs if enough employees leave the company
voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton officials said they examined other alternatives before
deciding to close. ``In the final analysis, we took the action that
we felt would best preserve our business for the future and be in
the best interests of our entire work force,'' said Mary Puma, vice
president and general manager of the Implant Systems Division.
</P>
<P>
   All Austin full-time workers will receive severance pay,
extended medical benefits and outplacement services.
</P>
<P>
   After it cuts 475 jobs, Eaton Semiconductor expects to have
1,050 workers worldwide. The company is the second largest maker of
ion implantation devices. It also makes other semiconductor
manufacturing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said companies like Eaton are making cutbacks now
because forecasts indicate that an upturn is at least a year away.
</P>
<P>
   Pathfinder Research of San Jose, Calif., said its latest
forecast calls for the chip industry revenues to shrink by 12
percent this year to $120 billion. The research firm says the
industry may grow modestly in 1999 if the world economy doesn't
weaken further.
</P>
<P>
   The parent company is a $7.6 billion maker of equipment for the
automobile, industrial, construction, commercial and semiconductor
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
