</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARILYN-FRENCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 01-COX &HT;    ``I was only dying'': Feminist author chronicles campaign to
beat cancer
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marilyn French was supposed to be dead five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She heard the doctors diagnose her in 1992 with terminal
esophageal cancer, and give her a year to live.
</P>
<P>
   But the 68-year-old feisty feminist, probably best known for her
1977 novel, The Women's Room, is still alive, although neither she
nor her doctors can say why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if you really talk to doctors who are honest,
they will admit they don't know anything about it. They have no
idea who will die and who will live, especially with cancer and
heart attacks,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The cure for the spreading cancer was terrifying. French, who
has a home on Singer Island, struggled through horrendous radiation
and chemotherapy that broke her back (repeated radiation exposure
can damage the spine), weakened her heart and affected her brain.
</P>
<P>
   She survived a two-week coma.
</P>
<P>
   Having been through such an overwhelming, life-altering
experience, she performed almost a cleansing ritual: She documented
her journey in her newest book, A Season in Hell, a Memoir ($23,
Knopf.)
</P>
<P>
   French emerged from this journey with changed perceptions about
life and death.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming sick, she had left written instructions _ a
living will _ that she didn't want any extraordinary means to keep
her alive. But her son, Rob, refusing to believe she wouldn't
recover from her coma, wouldn't authorize pulling the plug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you've never been sick, the thought of being sick
is enough to make you want to die,'' she says of her reasons for
the living will. ``That you might not be able to digest your food
or excrete by yourself is so horrifying, you think you want to pull
the plug. When it actually happens to you, you have a different
view. Most of us cling to life ferociously.''
</P>
<P>
   And she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was quite prepared to die,'' she recalls. ``I had
some important work (already done), my children were grown and
didn't need me. But I didn't let go.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, French would visualize herself free of cancer, a
process she credits with helping her make it through.
</P>
<P>
   She also credits heredity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's my father's genes and the love people gave me,''
she says. ``And if I had anything to do with it at all, it probably
was through my powers of visualization. But I'm not sure I had
anything to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   She is sure she had something to do with getting sick in the
first place. She had been smoking a pack of cigarettes a day since
she was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, doctors and friends urged me to quit,'' she writes,
``but I rationalized. There was no cancer on either side of my
family, and beyond that, I couldn't believe that an activity I
enjoyed so much could harm me.''
</P>
<P>
   She is grateful that she is relatively well today. But she
suffers many residual effects of her illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't walk very well. I don't feel my feet. It makes walking
a little tricky. My heart is not great, but these are things you
can really live with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still do almost everything I wanted to do. One thing
that's sort of impossible is the kind of travel I like to do. My
immune system is compromised and there are lots of foods I can't
eat.''
</P>
<P>
   And she has noticed that her children are progressively
forgetting more and more details of her ordeal as she continues to
remember with greater clarity.
</P>
<P>
   French has a simple explanation for this.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went through it so bravely, I don't think they can bear
to remember,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was only dying. It is terrible to watch somebody you love
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
