<HEADER>
A1747 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-DANJENKINS01     09-30 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-DANJENKINS01 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some good bad fun with Dan Jenkins
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The good news is that even though Dan Jenkins
has sworn off all the fun stuff that's bad for you, his fictional
characters have not. (One of the myriad advantages of being a
fictional character is you don't have to watch your cholesterol.)
The usual suspects in his new novel, ``Rude Behavior,'' have been
with him since 1972's ``Semi-Tough.'' And although they're older,
they're unrepentant in their personal habits: They smoke, drink,
inhale slabs of red meat, drive drunk and make ethnic jokes. They
litter.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, a Fort Worth native who now splits his time between
Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla., and Manhattan, has survived decades of not
dissimilar behavior. Jenkins was one of the handful of star scribes
that made Sports Illustrated a high-flying magazine. ``SI was a big
drinking place and we socialized a lot, and we had huge expense
accounts and ran around the world with rich and famous people and
it was fun,'' says Austin's Bud Shrake, a friend and former
colleague of Jenkins'.
</P>
<P>
   The pace is a little slower for Jenkins these days. He still
writes a column for Golf Digest and covers the major tournaments
for the magazine. Books have come out of him with regularity, too _
15 in all. ``Semi-Tough'' became the cornerstone of a trilogy, and
Jenkins isn't sure he's done with these characters yet. The book
follows Billy Clyde Puckett, now retired from both football and,
more recently, the broadcast booth, in his efforts to win an NFL
franchise for a team he dubs the West Texas Tornadoes. There is a
lot of cussing, a lot of impolite remarks, and a lot of the action
takes place in barrooms. That's how you can tell it's a Jenkins
book. Politically correct it's not, but then satire never is.
People are still hollering about a certain word Mark Twain used
abundantly in ``The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn,'' after all.
</P>
<P>
   We caught up with Jenkins at his Florida home, the morning after
Mark McGwire's historic 62nd season home run. You could tell it was
a big deal, because Jenkins _ whose attitude toward baseball can
most charitably be described as ambivalent _ watched it. Or at
least parts of it. What follows is an edited transcript of that
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Mark McGwire _ did you watch? Do you care?
</P>
<P>
   A: I flipped over every time he came up to bat. I was watching
tennis. So I saw him walk and hit a home run. That was a great
moment, really. I like baseball when they get down to it and
there's something special going on. And I don't care how many
steroids he takes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you feel about the new book?
</P>
<P>
   A: It took a little longer to do this one because I had some
health problems, but I like it. It's these characters I've had for
a few years. I started on this book four years ago, and I keep
going to golf tournaments, and then I had some health problems. I
had a bypass, had a gall bladder out and all those things that
happen to guys when they get older. It just delayed getting over to
the word processor. Novels are hard but fun. They're fun because
you don't have to ask anybody anything, unlike journalism. You just
make it up.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've had these characters a long time.
</P>
<P>
   A: 1972 with ``Semi-Tough.'' These are characters I know pretty
well. I guess there's a lot of me in all of them. There are certain
ideas I like to express from time to time. There's probably more of
me in Big Ed. Everybody thinks I'm supposed to be Billy Clyde.
</P>
<P>
   Q: They're not exactly politically correct.
</P>
<P>
   A: Well they're not supposed to be. Political correctness is my
sworn enemy. But that's fun, though.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you worry about being accused of ethnic insensitivity, or
has it happened so often you don't notice any more?
</P>
<P>
   A: I never worried about that. You may find this hard to
understand, but I believe this book is more politically correct
than people think. The women are always smarter and the black guys
always win. One of the nicest compliments I ever got was when
``Semi-Tough'' came out and I got a note from Alex Haley, who said,
``I want you to know this is the most anti-racist book I've ever
read.'' I'm used to being called a racist. I know that going in.
But I usually get pretty good reaction from people I consider
intelligent. I hope people buy it because it's funny.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was the section on how to tamper with airplane lavatory smoke
detectors so you can sneak cigarettes taken from direct experience?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't smoke any more. I had to give it up. But I started
thinking, If I did smoke, what would I do? Although I did know a
Hollywood guy, an agent, who told me to take the cellophane and the
Scotch tape and put it over the smoke detector in the john.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Speaking of Hollywood, you've had some close calls. How does
a writer survive out there?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can't. If they offer you money, take it. And you have no
control. Bud Shrake and I have had a lot of dealings with
Hollywood. It's been fun, but it's also been agony and you just
never win. They keep giving you money for development, and you just
think, (use) me again. Give me another $100,000 to not make my book
into a movie. But the thing about it is, it's all such a committee
deal out there. The only time the movie is yours is in the first
draft. But they've never shot a first draft of anything in the
history of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After so many decades and pieces, how is it you have anything
to say about golf?
</P>
<P>
   A: I do a monthly column and the four majors (tournaments) and
that keeps me off the streets. I get to go to the things and hear
lines I can steal for my books. I've now been to more major
championships that anybody that lived, I'm certain. I've been to 47
straight Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few of the old guard like Frank DeFord have returned to
Sports Illustrated. Would you ever consider that?
</P>
<P>
   A: When I left, I left. No, I'd never even consider it. It's not
run by intelligent human beings any more. It's not a writer's
magazine, it's an editor's magazine. We always thought we were
doing journalism when we were there. I don't know what they think
they're doing now. They target a younger audience. It's got that
comic book look to it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what do you read?
</P>
<P>
   A: I read the New Yorker, I take Vanity Fair, I read almost
anything that'll help me impeach Clinton, I take The New York Times
_ Maureen Dowd is my favorite writer in America. I read a lot of
World War II stuff, anything I can get my hands on about the Civil
War, I read all the James Lee Burkes and all the detective writers
for fun, but I read for recreation. I re-read a lot too, people
like Raymond Chandler. I don't read literature. You'll never catch
me with a Cormac McCarthy in my hand, or Updike. I looked at that
Modern Library list (the controversial list of the 20th century's
100 best novels written in English) and figured I'd read about 11
of them and hadn't heard of about 20 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much are you on the road?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I go to those golf tournaments, and we have an
apartment in New York, and we go back to Fort Worth. I travel more
than most people. The 23 or 24 years I worked for SI, I was gone
every other week. Having traveled all my life, it doesn't seem like
I'm traveling at all.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did the road take its toll on you physically?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it did, but I'm 67 years old. I've had bypass, I've
had hernia operations, dental implants, eye problems, all that
stuff catches up with you. It kind of hit me all at once. You pay
for your sins _ you pay for your fun, really. So I'm leading a
clean life now, got my golf game back now where I can break 80.
Life is good. All I miss is cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: People still think you live in Texas, even though it's been
decades.
</P>
<P>
   A: Ten years after I left the (Dallas) Times Herald, guys still
talked about how I had a column there. Most people don't leave, and
they don't think anybody else leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the next book?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've read so many bad golf books lately. They're all full of
Zen. I'm gonna write a thin, funny golf novel. I wrote one comic
golf novel, ``Dead Solid Perfect,'' but it was before the golf
boom. And somewhere down the line I'd like to write a memoir.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Thanks for the time. Any parting shots?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nah. If you need anything else, just make it up.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Beach writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
