<HEADER>
A1748 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINDLE-BOOKREVIEW01-C     09-30 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDLE-BOOKREVIEW01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author Windle retraces Texas Hill Country steps
 &HT;    Embargoed for 10/1
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The cool, clear Blanco River and the limestone
bluffs of Central Texas provide a pleasing setting for Janice Woods
Windle's new historical novel, ``Hill Country.'' Her first novel
since ``True Women,'' this one takes up where that one left off.
Published by Longstreet, it's a seductive mix of family stories and
pure fact.
</P>
<P>
   The central character is the author's grandmother, Laura Hoge
Woods, who grew up in the pioneer days of the 1870s and lived to
age 93, long enough to see the son of her close friend Rebekah
Baines Johnson become President of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The episodes in 'Hill Country' are true,'' said Windle,
speaking slowly and deliberately. ``The dialogue, of course, is
made up. There are a lot of thought patterns in the book. There's
no way of knowing what somebody is thinking. So that makes it
historical fiction, which is kind of its own unique little genre
and has the best of both. You can be very nonfiction and very
fiction _ whichever side of the rope you choose to jump on.''
</P>
<P>
   She jumps on both sides. Windle admits the first part of the
novel is more myth; the second part, historically accurate.
Interspersed with the story are family photos and some typed pages
left behind by Laura late in life. But how much is true?
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for example, the scene where 14-year-old Laura meets
Herman Lehmann, a white boy captured by the Apaches who had spent
nine years with them before coming home. A romance begins as they
bathe in the dinosaur footprints of the Blanco River: ``Laura
lowered herself into the footprint. She was several feet away from
where Herman lay in the other footprint made by the monster's
passing, yet she felt connected to the wild boy by the light that
passed between their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a Herman Lehmann who lived with the Indians, and
Windle depicts him according to local legend. There are dinosaur
footprints in the Blanco River. Laura Hoge knew of Lehmann and
spoke admiringly about him. But did they ever meet? Was there a
romance?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she had a real fascination with him as a young girl,
and they were about the same age,'' Windle said with a slight
smile. ``Now whether she had a big romance with him or not _ I
don't know that. Come closer in time and I can start to verify a
lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   You may remember Windle as the accidental novelist who in middle
age started out years back to write a family cookbook and ended up
in 1994 with a best-selling book, followed by a TV mini-series. It
did not hurt that she spent her childhood reading historical
novelist Irving Stone.
</P>
<P>
   She has now taken what her first publisher, Putnam, edited from
that book, researched more and created this new novel based on that
storyline and her grandmother's autobiography. Her grandmother had
started to write a book and left it, typed on a blue Olivetti
purchased for that purpose, behind in a tin box marked, ``For
Janice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I first thought the book 'True Women' would end with Laura's
story,'' Windle said. ``I wanted to go all the way through Suffrage
and show women as active participants in Texas politics and
decision-making today.'' So what to the author seemed at first a
crushing defeat _ the paring of the Laura narrative from 'True
Women' _ she recreated as a longer, more imposing story. ``It's
good it worked out the way it did,'' she says, ``because I found so
many more things.''
</P>
<P>
   Windle is quick to share the credit with those who helped with
stories about her grandmother's life and the Blanco area. Though
the author lives in El Paso, she returned to the Hill Country to
talk about her book.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed at the historic Blanco County courthouse recently,
she introduced Foster Carroll Smith, a storyteller and former high
school teacher, who showed her the dinosaur footprints and told her
stories of Lehmann and of Al Lackey and how he came to be hanged on
a tree overlooking the road to Johnson City _ U.S. 281 today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This old Lackey came home one day and his daughter was sitting
on the front porch nursing the baby. He shot his daughter _ the old
son of a gun did that,'' Smith said, ``and later he took his pocket
knife out and s throat, but he didn't cut deep enough. He
went out, got on his horse...then the posse got him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time my husband brought me to Blanco, we went out
the the old Woods home,'' said Windle's mother Virginia Woods, who
lives in Seguin and contributed to both novels. ``My husband's
sister Agatha was along and she showed me the old hanging tree.
'Remember how fast we used to run past it going to school?' she
asked him.''
</P>
<P>
   A cousin of the author, Doyle Hoge, has driven over from
Kerrville, to talk about Old Boomer, the gun Laura's mother wields
against the Indians in ``Hill Country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have that shotgun,'' Doyle says. He remembered his
great-grandmother, Laura's mother, telling about two Indian raids.
``The men were all out working horses, or were away from the
ranches,'' Doyle said. ``Little Mattie (Grandma) Hoge said they had
been instructed to go to the river, to hide in a cove down there
when the Indians came. It was just really interesting to hear that
from someone who was part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Blanco, Laura and Rebekah Johnson grew up across the river
from each other. They grew to be close friends, and this is an
important part of the narrative. Standing in front of what was once
Rebekah Johnson's home, Janice points down to where her grandmother
lived. ``If you cut across _ the Woods property ran down to the
river...''
</P>
<P>
   In the foreword to the novel, the author describes being a child
in Seguin in 1948 when Lyndon Johnson arrived in a helicopter:
``Each time the Johnson City Windmill prepared to land, Lyndon
would throw his hat to the crowd and his advance man Jake Pickle
would retrieve the hat by offering a dollar for its return. People
always gave the hat back. My grandmother Laura Woods is probably
the only one who did not.''
</P>
<P>
   For the latter part of the book, Janice's mother was a source,
as was the former first lady, Lady Bird Johnson. ``Mother and my
father were on the porch in Johnson City when LBJ decided to run
for office for the first time,'' Windle said.
</P>
<P>
   The author, who recently turned 60, said she was born when Laura
Hoge Woods was 66. ``I knew her very well and spent a lot of time
with her. She told me a lot about herself, and she left notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that Janice Woods Windle's zeal for research and her
flair for dramatic incidents, and you have an engrossing novel that
could make the Hill Country even more of a tourist lure.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Morris is a staff writer for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
