<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This just in....
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Announcer: We interrupt this program for
News Center 911's continuing coverage of ``Hurricane Georges _ Palm
Beach County Under Siege.'' Now, with the area's only Double-Dutch
Doppler, Accu-Tracku Pinpoint Weather, here are anchors Chandrell
Scratchit and Laurel Annoy. Scratchit: As Hurricane Georges pounds
the Mississippi Delta, Palm Beach County wonders, ``Are we out of
the woods yet?'' Hello, I'm Chandrell Scratchit. Annoy: And I'm
Laurel Annoy. Welcome to live, exclusive, continuing team coverage
of Hurricane Georges. Let's go right to the weather center with
John Tenderloyns, who's been up for six straight days now
monitoring this dangerous, monster storm. John: (unshaven, fidgety
and blinking furiously) As you can see from this satellite picture
taken in Deep Space, here's South Florida, and here's Biloxi,
Mississippi. It's easy to think of Hurricane Georges as 800 miles
away from us and fading. But if you look at this space picture, you
can see just how close we are to this killer storm. Sackitt: Sorry
to break in, John, but we have a live, exclusive report from
Tiffany Pie, who's battling breezes in Boynton. Tiffany: It might
look sunny and pleasant here, Chandrell. But moments ago, the wind
kicked up, registering nearly 17 miles an hour on my hand-held
anemometer. Annoy: Please, be careful, Tiffany. Tiffany: As the
camera pans behind me, you can see this house here has significant
palm frond damage. One of these fronds dropped in the past hour.
The sound was just . . . Scratchit: Excuse me, Tiffany. The lawn
seems pretty wet, too. Is that from a feeder band packing winds
with a powerful punch? Tiffany: No, actually, the homeowner was
running his sprinklers this morning. Annoy: Tiffany, we're going to
have to break away. Our team coverage continues with Rachele
Quixote, who is standing by outside Forest Hill High School.
Quixote: As you can see, the school is closed today, the parking
lot empty, and an eerie, eerie calm has descended here. Annoy: Wow,
that's eerie. Some might say that schools are closed today for a
Jewish holiday, rather than the hurricane. Quixote: That may have
played into the decision. But sources tell me school officials are
considering closing again this weekend. So concern is still a . . .
concern. Scratchit: Will we ever get free of the wrath of Georges?
For more on that, here's John in our Accu-Tracku Weather Center.
John: According to the cone of probabilities, and the lack of
upper-level shearing, we're still in a wait-and-see mode here.
These storms are very unpredictable and . . . Annoy: Excuse me,
John. We need to break in, as our live, continuing team coverage of
Hurricane Georges moves to reporter Juan Carlos Youngmother, who's
standing by with a live, exclusive interview at the Home Depot on
Lake Worth Road. Youngmother: I'm here with Jim Bob Gingivitis, a
Palm Beach County survivor of two near-misses. Mr. Gingivitis, you
were here during Hurricane Andrew six years ago and Hurricane Erin
three years ago. Gingivitis: Yeah, my plastic garbage can got
knocked over with Andrew, and the sky got pretty cloudy when Erin
missed us. Youngmother: And now, Hurricane Georges almost lashed
you with its tornadic activity and well-formed eye wall. Jeez!
Gingivitis: Listen, I'd like to talk, but I've got a bunch of
batteries and plywood to return, and the line's kind of long.
Scratchit: Excuse me, Juan. But we're going to break away to
Claudia Shefley, who's at Emerald Dunes golf course with the
county's emergency management director. Claudia: Bill O'Brien has
just shanked a five-iron shot into the those trees over there. He's
in the woods looking for his ball. Annoy: So there you have it: Not
out of the woods yet. Stay tuned for constant updates. Now, back to
our regular programming, ``Clinton: Presidency in Crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino's column appears in The Palm Beach Post, West
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
