<HEADER>
A1753 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-WELFSIDE01-COX     09-30 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-WELFSIDE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It pays to work for a company that's partnership-wise
 &HT;    By William Cooper Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When contract talks stalled on Palm
Beach County's welfare reform project, Lockheed Martin IMS got help
from a friend in the sugar industry.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Dominicis, vice president of Florida Crystals Corp. and a
member of the Workforce Development Board, guided through a deal
that ended six months of negotiations on how to administer the
county's $4.1 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin reached out to Dominicis, executives there say,
because he works for a company that understands private-public
partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   Dominicis spoke up for Lockheed Martin when it appeared the
Workforce Development Board _ which oversees local welfare reform _
was setting the company's contract so low that it would cut into
Lockheed Martin's profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to get to the point where you're being unfair
to your partner,'' Dominicis said. ``You've got to come up with a
reward system that is going to serve as a strong incentive.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin wanted to collect 61 percent of the money it
gets for each client before that client landed a job. The money
covers pre-employment services such as registering clients,
evaluating them and referring jobs to them.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin would collect the balance in phases once the
person got a job and stayed employed for six months.
</P>
<P>
   But the state said the company could get only 40 percent of its
money up front.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Montgomery, the Workforce Development Board's executive
director, thought Lockheed Martin should get the remainder of its
money in four increments: once a person found work and once he or
she stayed employed for 60, 90 and 180 days.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't good enough. Lockheed wanted the entire 60 percent
once a client found work. Executives didn't want to bear the risk
of clients not keeping their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   After six months of talks, Lockheed Martin had grown frustrated.
Out of 10 welfare contracts around the state, Palm Beach County's
was the only one that was unresolved, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin began lobbying board members. It also brought in
corporate executives such as Gerald Miller, the designer of welfare
reform in Michigan who now leads the company's effort.
</P>
<P>
   Miller threatened to lay off employees because the local
committee kept pushing for a bare-bones contract. Lockheed Martin
argued that getting less money up front might lead to cash-flow
problems.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sept. 17 Workforce Development Board meeting, Dominicis
convinced Lockheed Martin to revise its proposal: It would still be
paid in four phases, but it would get more money for each phase.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials agreed.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, Lockheed Martin executives wrote down the
amounts they wanted to receive for each phase. They handed their
proposal to Dominicis. While the board was discussing other
business, Dominicis walked the proposal over to several board
members, kneeling down and showing it to them. After making the
rounds, he brought Lockheed Martin's proposal up for a full board
vote.
</P>
<P>
   It passed.
</P>
<P>
   Dominicis believes the deal balances the Workforce Development
Board's interests with the company's desire to make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're partners'' he said. ``Business people are used to
negotiating under tough conditions. This is compromise on a
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's not the deal the company wanted, it seemed the only
way to put an end to the lengthy negotiations, said Roger Carlton,
head of Lockheed Martin's Florida operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have time to argue,'' Carlton said. ``It's a
proposal that we think is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   William Cooper Jr. writes for The Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
