<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1754 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELFARE01-COX     09-30 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defense contractor making big profit from welfare reform
 &HT;    By William Cooper Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Congress passed welfare reform in
1996, it opened up a $250 billion industry to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Its thinking: that companies could move people off welfare
cheaper and faster than government.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin IMS has turned that idea into a booming
business. In two years, the nation's largest defense contractor has
won 20 welfare contracts to move recipients into the workplace in
five states, including Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has been the most lucrative, awarding the company $54
million in contracts. That includes $4.1 million in Palm Beach
County.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for Lockheed Martin, the stakes are even higher here. The
company wants to take over the county's entire welfare system.
Lockheed Martin would calculate and issue benefits _ now done by
the state _ in addition to administering Palm Beach County's
welfare-to-work contract. Florida has applied to the federal
government on Lockheed Martin's behalf and is awaiting approval.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin's efforts are being watched nationally: Private
companies haven't been in the welfare business long enough to
determine if they can, indeed, save taxpayers money. And if
Lockheed Martin gets the OK to run Palm Beach County's entire
system, it will be the first private company in America to do so.
subhead
</P>
<P>
   Under welfare reform, people can only stay on the rolls for two
consecutive years before they have to get a job. Otherwise, they'll
lose their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Lockheed Martin comes in. It says it can help
people get jobs by:
</P>
<P>
   _ Processing applicants.
</P>
<P>
   _ Assessing their education and job skills.
</P>
<P>
   _ Helping them get more education or job training.
</P>
<P>
   _ Giving them job referrals and tracking their progress.
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach County, the company could earn up to $3,338 per
welfare recipient doing that. It will get 40 percent of its money
up front; the remaining 60 percent will be paid out in increments
based on whether the person holds a job for 60, 90 and 180 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business is not a complicated business,'' said Gerald
Miller, who leads Lockheed Martin's welfare-to-work venture
nationwide. ``Our success comes one person at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach County, Lockheed Martin hopes to work with 4,693
welfare recipients and 300 new applicants each month.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, it will handle about 70 percent of the state's
welfare clients. That includes Miami-Dade County, where it has a
$25 million contract to assess recipients' skills, find them jobs
and do follow-up training. That contract represents 25 percent of
the state's entire welfare population and is the country's largest
welfare-to-work contract. subhead
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Tom Rossin, D-West Palm Beach, said the success of
welfare reform shouldn't be measured by cost alone, and it's too
early to say whether reform is paying off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a perception that when you change the function of
government, people think that it's going to be cheaper,'' said
Rossin, chairman of the Senate's children families and seniors
committee, which will review the impact of welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, welfare costs taxpayers $250 billion annually.
Companies like Lockheed Martin hope to get a piece of the 10
percent that analysts say will pay for administering the
welfare-to-work effort. That could be as much as $25 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty obvious business decision to enter the market,''
said Courtney Purrington, a Harvard Business School researcher
studying the company's role in welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a move Lockheed Martin has been preparing for. The
company has spent the past decade moving away from defense and into
services, Purrington said.
</P>
<P>
   By winning contracts to manage municipal parking systems,
chasing ``deadbeat parents'' for child support payments and
operating highway toll booths, Lockheed Martin was perfectly
positioned for the political shift in welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The company has used good marketing and hired what Purrington
calls ``subject matter experts.'' He defines them as former human
services officials who are tops in their fields with
well-established contacts.
</P>
<P>
   That's why hiring Gerald Miller, the mastermind of welfare
reform in Michigan, was critical. He joined Lockheed Martin a month
after the president signed the welfare reform act.
</P>
<P>
   As former director of Michigan's Department of Social Services,
Miller crafted some of the first welfare reforms in the nation. He
later was appointed by former U.S. Senator Bob Dole to the Welfare
Indicators Advisory Board, which made recommendations to federal
lawmakers on national welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   The shift to welfare services also helps Lockheed Martin's
parent company, which specializes in military contracts, said Paul
Nisbit, a defense industry analyst. According to Nisbit, the
information services subsidiary _ which handles the welfare
business _ is Lockheed Martin's fastest growing division.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a high-growth business. It can be profitable, if run
well.''
</P>
<P>
   William Cooper Jr. writes for The Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
