 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 404 - September 30, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 404 - Sept. 30, 1998 We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. BLOOD MONEY : HOLLYWOOD'S FASCINATION WITH SERIAL KILLERS
When the film ``Psycho'' first appeared in 1960, moviegoers were
stunned by Norman Bates, the seemingly gentle, mother-obsessed
innkeeper who kept having fatal encounters with visitors to his
roadside motel. But nearly 40 years later, Norman Bates doesn't
seem all that odd - at least compared with his murderous friends at
the local multiplex cinema. Love it or hate it, the serial killer
genre is booming again, with a spate of new films in release,
production or active development. Perhaps most prominently,
Universal Pictures has scheduled a December release for Gus Van
Sant's remake of Hitchcock's ``Psycho,'' this time with Vince
Vaughn as Bates. By Pat H. Broeske. From The Hollywood Reporter.
1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   2. PRACTICALLY MAGICAL : SANDRA BULLOCK Anyone who felt sorry
for Sandra Bullock after the epic crash of ``Speed 2'' last year
should save their tears. Bullock rebounded nicely with this
summer's ``Hope Floats'' and is excited about her latest film,
``Practical Magic'' (she stars with Nicole Kidman as sisters who
have sorcerous powers and a family curse : Any man who falls in
love with either sister is guaranteed to die young.) In this
interview Bullock talks about the new movie, why she has only one
regret about ``Speed 2,'' how leaving Hollywood for Texas has
helped her get her act together and how she answers rumours about a
romance with her ``A Time To Kill'' co-star Matthew McConaughey. By
Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
FACE VALUE : BEWITCHING SANDRA BULLOCK Vance Lehmkuhl offers an
intriguing cartoon of Sandra Bullock, depicted as a
``Bewitched''-style witch in her upcoming film, ``Practical
Magic.''
</P>
<P>
   4. BILLY CRUDUP INTERVIEW Sex, tragedy and an Olympic athlete:
It's no wonder Hollywood loves legendary long-distance runner Steve
Prefontaine's life story (the athlete died in a 1975 car accident
at the age of 24.) Two films have been made about him in the last
two years. Actor Billy Crudup finds himself in the nerve-racking
position of starring in ``Without Limits.'' In this interview,
Crudup talks about his portrayal of Prefontaine, his fear of
attending the premieres of his films and his stage work. By Dana
Wood. W Magazine. 1,000 words + photo.
</P>
<P>
   5. BEN STILLER INTERVIEW Ben Stiller seems to be on movie
screens everywhere this year, in films ranging from the
controversial ``Your Friends and Neighbours'' to the riotous summer
hit ``There's Something About Mary.'' This month Stiller, best
known for his comic roles, delivers a searing performance in
``Permanent Midnight,'' the true story of a heroin-addicted
television writer in Los Angeles whose life spirals out of control.
By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   6. YEAR OF THE CROW As her third album, ``The Globe Sessions,''
hits record stores, singer Sheryl Crow is hard-pressed to match the
success of her first two albums which made her one of America's top
female pop stars. In this interview Crow talks about the new album,
the special song Bob Dylan wrote for it, why she's cutting back the
hard-partying lifestyle which she once enjoyed and how, at 36, she
finds herself dreaming of a family of her own. By Bonnie Siegler.
1,400 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
LEELEE SOBIESKI'S DATE WITH STARDOM In a few short years - she's
only 16 - Leelee Sobieski has married Elijah Wood in ``Deep
Impact,'' co-starred with Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman in Stanley
Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' and is now tackling her biggest role
in the Merchant-Ivory film ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries.'' In
this interview she talks about her dazzling beginning, how she
handled her jitters during her first sex scene, why she's not
intimidated by the big name actors she has worked with and her
personal impressions of Cruise, Kubrick and ``Soldier's Daughter''
co-star Kris Kristofferson. By Jeanne Wolf. 1,400 words + photo.
(Not available in England.)
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
DEFINING THE DIVINE MISS M The song may be from 1935 or 1955 or
1998, serious or sad, but if Bette Midler likes it, she's going to
sing it and nothing is going to stop her. Where other artists might
lay claim to versatility, 'the Divine Miss M' simply defines it.
``I feel bad for people who only like one kind of music,'' she
says. By Steve Morse. BPI. 700 words.
