<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1758 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE     09-30 1536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported recently that neither President Clinton nor his
wife owns a home. But I have read elsewhere, maybe in The Wall
Street Journal, that Clinton's Hollywood friends had chipped in to
buy a home for him, and it was more than $1 million. Can you
clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: A rumor such as you describe was reported by gossip columnist
Liz Smith, who said that she could not vouch for its accuracy.
Given the mutual affection between Hollywood show business and
Clinton, such scenarios have been widely speculated upon in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that Vernon Jordan and the fiance of Monica
Lewinsky's mother either are, or have been, business partners?
Couldn't this explain the
</P>
<P>
   connection between Jordan and Lewinsky other than through the
White House?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lewinsky got her White House internship through the
recommendation of family friend Walter Kaye, a retired insurance
executive who has donated more than $300,000 to the Democratic
Party. But, yes, there has been a connection between Jordan and R.
Peter Straus, the owner of radio stations and small newspapers in
New York state who married Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis, earlier
this year. As reported in USA Today, Straus and Jordan joined
forces in 1983 in an unsuccessful attempt to buy a classical music
station in Washington. And Jordan was a eulogist at the 1995
funeral of Straus' first wife.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has Vice President Al Gore ever held a job and been on a
payroll like an ordinary citizen?
</P>
<P>
   A: Gore served in the Army from 1969-71. He then operated a
homebuilding and land-developing business in his home state of
Tennessee, according to the Almanac of American Politics. From
1973-76, Gore was an investigative reporter for The Tennessean
newspaper in Nashville. He also has worked as a tobacco farmer. In
1976, he was elected to Congress for the first time, opening his
career as a federal officeholder.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that when Babe Ruth was playing baseball, a hitter
could bounce a home run out, but now it would be considered a
ground rule double? If so, did Ruth get some home runs like that
during his record season?
</P>
<P>
   A: The answer to the first question is yes. Balls that bounced
over the fence in Babe Ruth's day counted as home runs instead of
ground rule doubles. But none of Ruth's homers during the 1927
season, when he hit 60, bounced over. They all cleared the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are gambling casinos in states like Mississippi required
to be on water?
</P>
<P>
   A: States like Mississippi and Iowa, which permit casinos, were
looking for ways to boost tourism and generate money to run their
governments. Proponents harkened back to the days of riverboat
gambling on the Mississippi River as a natural tourism draw, said
Charles Patton, executive director of the Mississippi Gaming
Commission. Basing casinos on water creates a zoning tool that
allows governments to keep gambling houses off land, Patton said.
In Mississippi, for example, casinos must float on the Mississippi
River or its tributaries, or in the Gulf of Mexico. Casino
applications are reviewed by local governments as well as the
state-run Gaming Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Rep. Alcee Hastings (D-Fla.) launched an aborted effort to
impeach Kenneth Starr. As I recall, he himself was impeached as a
federal judge. Can you refresh my memory about that case?
</P>
<P>
   A: The House impeached Hastings in 1989 for ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' in connection with an alleged bribe of $150,000
while he was a federal judge. He then was convicted in the Senate,
which found that he had engaged in a ``corrupt conspiracy.'' It was
the only time a federal official was removed from office for a
crime of which he had been found not guilty by a trial jury.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings challenged his conviction, saying the full Senate must
hear the evidence and return a verdict, instead of a 12-member
Senate committee whose work was ratified by a Senate vote. In
September 1992, U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin, in agreement,
reversed the Senate's conviction. Lawyers for the Senate argued
that Sporkin lacked authority to review the Senate's action, but
the judge disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1992, Hastings was elected to Congress. In 1993, he
was quoted as saying, ``I'm not a vengeful person; I get on with
life. I didn't come here with my arms and my elbows flying. I came
here to work. . . . I've met with nothing but pleasant exchanges. .
. . I bring with me the added notoriety of being impeached and
removed by the same body that I now get to serve in. That in and of
itself is a made-for-TV movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happens to cruise ships in the Caribbean when a
hurricane is in the area? Do they change their itineraries?
</P>
<P>
   A: The modern technology for tracking weather patterns is so
advanced that cruise companies are able to monitor the situation
and make any necessary itinerary adjustments before ships leave
port, said Meredith Marks, spokeswoman for Cruise Lines
International Association in New York. So the ships are unlikely to
be caught in open water with a hurricane brewing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who was the last Major League baseball player to achieve the
Triple Crown?
</P>
<P>
   A: It has been more than 30 years since anyone has won the
Triple Crown (leading a league at the end of the season in the
three major hitting categories in official records: batting
average, runs batted in and home runs). He was Carl Yastrzemski of
the Red Sox in 1967. The last one in the National League was Joe
Medwick of the Cardinals in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that the son of Fox News anchor Brit Hume
recently committed suicide, but I didn't see anything in the news
about it. Do you have any details about his career and about his
death?
</P>
<P>
   A: The suicide of Sandy Hume, 28, at his apartment in Arlington,
Va., occurred the night of Feb. 22. It was reported in the
Journal-Constitution and elsewhere Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   An article April 27 in The New Republic sheds some light on his
situation. A reporter at The Hill, a Capitol Hill newspaper, Hume
became famous when he detailed the attempted coup against House
Speaker Newt Gingrich last summer. Acclaimed as a rising star by
The New York Times, Hume was offered a job by U.S. News &AMP; World
Report and The Weekly Standard.
</P>
<P>
   According to The New Republic, Hume was a recovering alcoholic
who kept a photo from when he had hit bottom to remind himself of
what he once had been. The night before he died, he was reported to
have been drinking with high school friends. While speeding home he
was chased by police, caught, and jailed. When he tried to strangle
himself at the jail, he was taken to D.C. General Hospital, where
he convinced the staff to let him go. When he returned home, he
wrote a note saying how sorry he was, and shot himself in the head.
</P>
<P>
   As reported by the Journal-Constitution, Gingrich, after Hume's
death, released a statement saying the young reporter had
``remarkable talent and unlimited potential'' and possessed a
``rare ability to make people want to open up to him.'' That,
Gingrich added, was why so many people respected him as a reporter
``and loved him as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: The recent Miss America pageant has me wondering about Bess
Myerson. What has become of her?
</P>
<P>
   A: Perhaps the most celebrated Miss America of all time, she was
a graduate of New York's Hunter College when she won the pageant in
1945. Though she faced anti-Semitism herself, she spent her year as
Miss America campaigning against prejudice in schools. In 1947, she
performed as a concert pianist in Carnegie Hall, and she went on to
have a high-profile political career, serving as consumer affairs
commissioner for New York City from 1982 to 1987. She has been
hailed as a generous donor to the Holocaust Museum of Jewish
Heritage in New York, donating more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But her life hasn't been trouble-free. In 1988, Myerson pleaded
guilty in Williamsport, Pa., to shoplifting $44.07 worth of
merchandise from a department store. She was fined $100 plus $48.50
court costs. That same year, she was acquitted by a New York jury
of bribery, fraud and conspiracy charges that claimed she had
improperly influenced the judge presiding over the divorce case of
her lover, Carl Capasso. In addition, she was acquitted of an
obstruction of justice charge. She also has endured surgery and
chemotherapy for ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Myerson was married and divorced twice, and has a daughter and
granddaughter. Now 74, she rarely ventures into the public eye,
giving occasional university lectures and doing charity work,
mainly on behalf of Jewish causes. ``This way I feel I am putting
my celebrity to use,'' she once told a reporter. ``Nothing I've
done in the past is as nourishing as my Jewishness. I never left
it, but now I can do it full time.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
