r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE     09-30 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED: Q: The recent Miss America pageant has me wondering
about Bess Myerson. What has become of her?
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the make and year of the automobile on a $10 bill,
and what is the building behind it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The car is generic, and of no specific make or model, said
Claudia Dickens of the Bureau of Engraving and Printing. The
building is the Treasury Department at Pennsylvania Avenue and 15th
Street N.W. in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did the public opinion polls show for President Richard
Nixon's job performance around the time of Watergate, and again
around the time of his resignation?
</P>
<P>
   A: The break-in at the Democratic Party headquarters in the
Watergate building complex occurred June 17, 1972. The scandal
engulfed the Nixon administration during 1973 and most of 1974.
Nixon's approval rating, as measured by Gallup polls, had reached a
high point of 68 percent in late January 1973 after the Vietnam
peace settlement. In Gallup surveys conducted April 6-9 that year,
before Nixon's April 17 news conference at which he said he had
discovered ``major developments'' in the Watergate case, the
approval rating had dropped by 14 points to 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll published June 24 showed a 44 percent approval
rating, the same as it had showed in interviews taken May 11-14 and
again June 1-4. At the end of 1973, his popularity rating slipped
another 2 points, to 29 percent. By late July 1974, as the House
moved closer to a vote on impeachment, Gallup's poll showed still
more slippage, to 24 percent. That was the lowest level. On Aug. 8,
Nixon announced his decision to resign to the American people on
nationwide TV, and he submitted his resignation the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were the accusations against President Richard Nixon in
the articles of impeachment against him?
</P>
<P>
   A: In July 1974, the House Judiciary Committee adopted three
articles of impeachment. The first described Nixon's role in the
Watergate coverup, accusing him of obstructing justice. The second
detailed other abuses of power by the president. And the third
charged Nixon with contempt of Congress for his failure to honor
the Judiciary Committee's subpoenas, mostly for certain tape
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A mentioned recently that a $10,000 Federal Reserve note is
the largest bill in circulation. I thought I once read about a
$100,000 bill. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: The largest note ever printed by the Bureau of Engraving and
Printing was the $100,000 Gold Certificate, Series 1934. These
notes were printed from Dec. 18, 1934, through Jan. 9, 1935, and
were issued by the treasurer of the United States only to Federal
Reserve Banks against an equal amount of gold bullion held by the
Treasury. These notes were used for transactions between Federal
Reserve Banks and were not circulated among the public. And as we
said before, the $10,000 Federal Reserve note and several other
large U.S. bills have been in the process of being withdrawn from
circulation since 1969. The $100 note is the largest being issued
now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is St.-John's-wort?
</P>
<P>
   A: Also called hypericum, it's the name of a group of about 300
species of herbs and shrubs. The name also is applied to a popular
herbal remedy for depression. The ``herbal Prozac'' made the news
recently when the Los Angeles Times reported that several brands
are not as potent as advertised on their labels.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a list of Conference USA members, Q&AMP;A referred to the Army
Cadets. Isn't the team called the Black Knights? A knight wearing
black armor rides a mule at the games.
</P>
<P>
   A: Either nickname is acceptable, said Diane Baker of the U.S.
Military Academy's sports information office. The team is referred
to as the Cadets by Sporting News, Sports Illustrated and CNNSI,
and even the Army ``A'' line (914-938-2769) with recorded
information refers to the Cadets. If you prefer the nickname Black
Knights (or Black Knights of the Hudson), however, you wouldn't be
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I haven't read or heard much about John Glenn's training for
his upcoming space mission. Can you provide an update?
</P>
<P>
   A: Glenn, first American to orbit Earth and soon to become the
world's oldest spaceman at 77, has been immersed since August in a
busy routine at the Johnson Space Center in Houston. Among other
things, he's practicing what to do in an emergency, familiarizing
himself with the space shuttle Discovery and its payloads,
preparing for his medical experiments, and tackling the intricacies
of computers. One of Glenn's crucial projects will be to log
medical data into the laptop computers aboard Discovery _ 16
laptops, more than usual because of all the research on the mission
_ to provide a full account for NASA doctors doing the first
geriatric study in space.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Glenn admitted that he isn't as flexibile
as he used to be. ``I'm slower than them (the six astronauts who
will accompany him) and I don't bend the same directions they bend.
. . . Where they duck and go through, I'm crawling through on hands
and knees to get through certain portholes and things like that,
for access to the orbiter. But that's all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Discovery is scheduled to be launched from the Kennedy Space
Center at 2 p.m. Oct. 29, with landing scheduled for 12:04 p.m.
Nov. 7. The mission will include solar research and experiments for
planned upgrades of the Hubble space telescope. Glenn, a Democratic
senator from Ohio for 24 years, has said he will retire from
politics two months after the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recall that Shirley Chisholm once ran for president, but
she wasn't listed by Q&AMP;A. Can you refresh my memory about her
campaign?
</P>
<P>
   A: As stated, the list was a sample of past women candidates of
their parties. While Chisholm did campaign for the 1972 Democratic
presidential nomination, she didn't win the nomination, so her name
wasn't on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Chisholm undeniably made her mark in politics, however. She
served in the New York State Assembly from 1964 to 1968, and in
1969 became the first black woman in Congress, serving until 1983.
When she sought the Democratic nomination for president, Chisholm
put together a coalition of blacks, feminists and other minority
groups, but the effort failed. She failed even to win the support
of the Congressional Black Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the convention rolled around, a loss already was
assured. Chisholm went to the convention with 24 delegates. In the
end she got 151 votes, released to her by Hubert H. Humphrey and
other candidates who had given up on trying to stop George
McGovern. Despite the reversal, Chisholm and others considered that
her bid could have had a positive impact on future black women
candidates. She compared herself to Al Smith, a Catholic who ran
for the presidency in the 1920s, paving the way for John F.
Kennedy's 1960 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If I remember correctly, after Ronald Reagan left office, a
Japanese company paid him $2 million to make a commercial. What was
that company, and what was its product?
</P>
<P>
   A: When he was actor Ronald Reagan, long before he occupied the
White House, he also was a pitchman for General Electric. But he
didn't do celebrity endorsements after leaving office. You may be
remembering that he accepted $2 million from a Japanese company,
Fujisankei Communications, to give two speeches in Japan, which
resulted in a lot of bad press.
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians, however, have appeared in ads, including
Geraldine Ferraro (Pepsi), George McGovern (Bic razor), Alexander
Haig (Trump Shuttle, an airline operation later taken over by US
Airways) and, most notably, former House Speaker Tip O'Neill
(Quality Inns, Commodore's Amiga computers, Miller Lite beer, Hugh
Puppies shoes, American Express and the Bank of New England).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who are the members of Congress who voted to release
President Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony, and how did
each of them vote? How can we get their addresses?
</P>
<P>
   A: The House Judiciary Committee, with 37 members, voted along
party lines Friday to release the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans: Henry Hyde (chairman; Illinois); James
Sensenbrenner Jr., Wisconsin; Bill McCollum, Florida; George Gekas,
Pennsylvania; Howard Coble, North Carolina; Lamar Smith, Texas;
Elton Gallegly, California; Charles Canady, Florida; Bob Inglis,
South Carolina; Robert Goodlatte, Virginia; Steve Buyer, Indiana;
Ed Bryant, Tennessee; Steve Chabot, Ohio; Bob Barr, Georgia;
William Jenkins, Tennessee; Asa Hutchinson, Arkansas; Ed Pease,
Indiana; Christopher Cannon, Utah; James Rogan, California; Lindsey
Graham, South Carolina; Mary Bono, California.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats: John Conyers Jr. (ranking minority member; Michigan);
Barney Frank, Massachusetts; Charles Schumer, New York; Howard
Berman, California; Rick Boucher, Virginia; Jerrold Nadler, New
York; Robert Scott, Virginia; Melvin Watt, North Carolina; Zoe
Lofgren, California; Sheila Jackson Lee, Texas; Maxine Waters,
California; Martin Meehan, Massachusetts; William Delahunt,
Massachusetts Robert Wexler, Florida; Steven Rothman, New Jersey;
Tom Barrett, Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   To write to a committee member, send your letter to Rep. (Full
Name), U.S. House of Representatives, Washington, DC 20515. By
phone, call the Capitol switchboard, 202-224-3121. END
</P>
