<HEADER>
A1760 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WACKY-COURSES01-COX     09-30 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACKY-COURSES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sexy or sublime, courses are title contenders
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ E.T. and crazy women and rock music.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, University of Texas students are challenging more
than the usual fluff courses of Linear Optimization and the Design
and Analysis of Algorithms.
</P>
<P>
   Peruse the UT course schedule, and you may fall off the couch
reaching for the phone to enroll late in some cool and hot classes.
</P>
<P>
   Cool, as in Professor Paul Harvey's (no, I'm not kidding)
``Search for Extraterrestrial Life.'' Watching a few episodes of
''X-Files'' should give you a head start.
</P>
<P>
   Hot, as in ``Rhetoric of Sexy Girls.'' Got to be curious about
that one.
</P>
<P>
   And what would any self-respecting college student be without an
American Studies class called ``Women and Madness'' or civil
engineering's ``Theory and Behavior of Pavements.'' Imagine calling
Mom and Pop _ the money trees _ and saying, ``Hey, I'm learning why
women are mad and how pavement behaves.''
</P>
<P>
   For a flashback to disco fever, how about ``Earth, Wind, and
Fire'' in the Department of Geological Sciences. Imagine, the 1970s
rhythm and blues group's ``Shining Star'' blaring on the speakers.
Hold on to your Angel Flights, it turns out the professor talks
about global warming, earthquakes and volcanoes. Cute title,
though.
</P>
<P>
   The sociology course ``Proposal Preparation'' must be for single
guys who don't have a clue how to pop the Big One. Paul Castaneda,
editor of the 289-page UT course catalog, however, says the class
teaches students to write proposals for dissertations or grants for
funding research.
</P>
<P>
   Boring.
</P>
<P>
   Some course titles have more pizazz. Like ``Rhetoric of Sexy
Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the course description reads: ``What is a sexy
girl? Who gets to decide? . . . Despite 20th century America's
statutory rape laws, and its loudly proclaimed moral horror at
child molestation, the sexy girl _ from the Guess? Jeans girl to
JonBenet _ continues to fascinate both men and women. This course
proceeds from the assumption that there is no single concrete thing
about a girl that is sexy. Instead, this course proposes that when
we look at, or read about sexy girls we are part of an audience
that can be persuaded, seduced, manipulated, bullied, or excluded .
. . ``
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The title is concise and accurate,'' says Alyssa Harad, an
assistant instructor who is teaching the class for the first time.
``Of course, the title is also an example of this rhetoric and its
power.''
</P>
<P>
   UT officials concede that catchy titles titles help market the
courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for a catchy title,'' says assistant professor
Brenda Kirkland George, who teaches ``Earth, Wind, and Fire'' with
professor Sharon Moser. ``Wind is climate, fire is volcanoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey says while his astronomy class ``Search for
Extraterrestrial Life'' attracts attention, it's serious. ``It's
not pop culture stuff about UFOs and alien abductions. We look at
how our solar system evolved and the formation of life on Earth. We
do discuss the possibility of other life out there,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Other courses are enticing.
</P>
<P>
   A certain Bill might be interested in the speech communication
class ``Lying and Deception.'' Or, the sociology course
``Deviance.'' And while he's at it, he might want to check out
``Male-Female Communications'' in Women's Studies.
</P>
<P>
   For a sense of drama, a linguistics course called ``Language,
Myth and Vampire Legend'' sounds interesting. The Department of
Rhetoric and Criticism shines in this area, according to course
descriptions. ``The Rhetoric of Horror'' looks at why we pay good
money to be frightened, shocked and sickened. ``The Rhetoric of the
Grotesque'' examines why people like Jeffrey Dahmer and ``events
like carnival freak shows and news reports of gory deaths hold our
attention despite our apparent revulsion for them.''
</P>
<P>
   UT, like every other college, also offers the head scratchers.
How many people, if they had a choice, would take ``Fault Tolerant
Computing'' or ``Pseudorandomness.''
</P>
<P>
   Must be for the techies.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Gandara writes for The Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
