<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS_ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ Going back in time at Historic Brattonsville in
McConnells, S.C. The annual Red Hills Farm Day is coming up Oct. 10
as well as Cotton Picking Day Oct. 24 and Corn Harvest and Shucking
Nov. 14, followed by Christmas Candlelight Tours Dec. (Thrasher,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WACKY-COURSES _ A Look through the University of Texas fall
course catalog reveals a minefield of surprises: Rhetoric of Sexy
Girls. Women and Madness. Search for Extraterrestrial Life.
Deviance. Lies and Deception. A look at some of these course titles
and what they really teach. (Ricardo, Austin American-Statesman).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   REAL-LIFE _ Turns out lots of other people had also heard of
Sterling Lord, a prominent New York literary agent who years ago
discovered a young talent named Jack Kerouac. Yes. Sterling Lord is
the man who sold Kerouac's famous On The Road. And he was calling
me. (Minor, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Yep _ books are the perfect prescription for
the tedium of a road trip, or just about anything else that ails
you. Just ask folks at the Children's Health Clinic at Children's
Medical Center, where books are quite literally what the doctor
orders. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   WINDLE-BOOKREVIEW _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The cool, clear Blanco River
and the limestone bluffs of Central Texas provide a pleasing
setting for Janice Woods Windle's new historical novel, ``Hill
Country.'' Her first novel since ``True Women,'' this one takes up
where that one left off. Published by Longstreet, it's a seductive
mix of family stories and pure fact. (Morris, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED. EMBARGOED FOR 10/1.
</P>
