EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Sept. 30, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRFORCE-PILOTS (San Antonio) _ The Air Force faces a serious
shortage of experienced pilots, and it may take a decade to correct
the problem, a top planner says. At this time last year the Air
Force had just 48 fewer pilots than needed. That number now has
grown to 800 fliers. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   METHADONE-REACTION (San Francisco) _ A new White House
initiative to expand methadone treatment for heroin addiction is
getting a warm response from San Francisco health officials, who
say it is precisely in line with their own goals. By ULYSSES
TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GOV (San Francisco) _ The state prison guards' union, a
powerful ally of California Gov. Pete Wilson's and frequent
supporter of tough-on-crime Republican candidates, is supporting a
Democrat, Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, for governor. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   JUSTICE-O'CONNOR (San Antonio) _ Supreme Court Justice Sandra
Day O'Connor encouraged students to meet the challenges of a
changing world at the dedication of the high school named in her
honor. By LUCY HOOD.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CALIF (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Vice President Al Gore spent
24 hours in California collecting campaign money for Democrats and
giving a few tax dollars back _ while bolstering his party's
profile among crucial swing voters in the Central Valley. By ROBERT
SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   PATRONAGE-SUIT (Albany, N.Y.) _ A bitter lawsuit that accused
New York Attorney General Dennis Vacco of turning the Department of
Law into a political patronage mill has been thrown out by a
federal judge. U.S. District Judge Rosemary S. Pooler said Vacco
has the right to hire lawyers who share his political views. By
JOHN CAHER.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-VALLEY (Death Valley, Calif.) _ Click. Click. The sounds
of clicking shutters herald dawn as amateur and not-so-amateur
photographers try to capture the brilliant gold-dust morning of
Death Valley. Despite its reputation as a desert wasteland, Death
Valley actually boasts diverse habitats and experiences for
visitors. By SYD KEARNEY. (Photo available on New York Times photo
service.)
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-VALLEY-SIDER (Amargosa Valley, Nev.) _ Ash Meadows
National Wildlife Refuge, located about 40 minutes from Death
Valley, is a 22,117-acre wetland and upland desert oasis with the
greatest concentration of endemic species in the nation. While
threatened birds are known to haunt this refuge, the endangered
wildlife star here is the pupfish. By SYD KEARNEY. (Photo available
on New York Times photo service.)
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-VALLEY-LOCATION (Undated) _ Where to go, fees and
accommodations at Death Valley National Park. Compiled by SYD
KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HUDSON-POLLUTION (West Point, N.Y.) _ The Hudson River _ the
``river that flows both ways'' _ is now cleaner than it's been in
more than a century, but still is not where it needs to be. Now,
there's no sheen of oil on the water, or odd slick on the shore
left by the tide as there was even a decade ago. By FRED LeBRUN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-OAKLAND (Oakland, Calif.) _ Mark McGwire leaves Oakland and
hits 100 homers in a year and a half. Plainly, there must be
something to being from Oakland that makes it better than being in
Oakland, at least if you're in the baseball business. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ I went to Washington to see the
Vietnam Memorial in 1983, the first summer it was open to the
public. I found some familiar names on the roster of 58,000 dead _
guys I'd known in high school, one from college. I recently
discovered that another classmate of mine was killed in that war.
By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ In about a month I will mark my
49th birthday. Now, instead of wishing for a movie-star husband, a
mansion or world peace as I did when I was a kid, I wish for little
things that don't quite qualify for an official prayer. Things that
would just make me smile if they came true. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   MUNICH-AGREEMENT (San Francisco) _ Today is the 60th anniversary
of the Munich Agreement. Because the Munich Agreement failed so
abysmally to prevent World War II, its primary lesson has always
been the danger of appeasement. Indeed, ``appeasement,'' which used
to mean ``peaceful reconciliation'' _ something noble and positive
_ became, after Munich, a dirty word. By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
