<HEADLINE>
MARKET FOR CHIPS BELONGS TO BUYER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1998 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Competition is a wonderful thing, and nowhere is that more
evident than in the personal computer business. It's brought PC
users breathtaking innovation and power at ever-lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Competition is particularly strong in the microprocessor market.
If you're interested in buying a new computer that uses Microsoft's
Windows 98 or NT as its operating system, you've got an excellent
selection of chips from which to choose.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp. is the market leader. Its competitors develop
powerful processors that undercut Intel's prices in an attempt to
steal some market share. Intel, in turn, has responded by slashing
the prices on its products and producing others that compete
directly in the low end of the chip market.
</P>
<P>
   You, the PC buyer, are the delighted beneficiary. Here's a look
at today's processor landscape:
</P>
<P>
   _ Pentium MMX: Adios, mi amigo! This Intel chip is a case study
in computer-industry obsolescence. Just 18 months ago, this was the
second coming of the Pentium processor. Today, it's yesterday's
news.
</P>
<P>
   Pentium MMX processors are found in some portable computers
running at a maximum 266 megahertz, and in the sub-$1,000 desktop
market with maximum clock speeds of 233 megahertz. They are
perfectly capable of running most software available today, and are
an excellent choice if all you do is word processing, connect to
the Internet and juggle the family finances on your PC. They also
handle most children's educational programs with ease.
</P>
<P>
   But the next generation of high-end games and graphics software
coming in 1999 will bog these chips down. If you're a serious
gamer, or want to manipulate images on a PC, you'll want something
more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pentium II: This is the Intel's current, state-of-the-art
processor, and a compelling choice if you've got the cash. The
newest versions of the chip run at a top speed of 450 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   This is the chip of choice for power users, hard-core gamers and
those who want to be as far ahead of the curve as possible. It's
got the MMX instruction set _ extra code to help with audio and
video _ and a 512-kilobyte cache, a buffer that helps speed data
into and out of the chip.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pentium II will undergo a major change early next year.
A new version of the chip, code-named Katmai, will debut in the
first quarter of 1999. With initial speeds of 450 and 500
megahertz, it will include code that will help improve 3D graphics,
but only if software developers write programs to take advantage of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Also coming next year in the Pentium II family _ chips at speeds
of 600 megahertz and beyond, with larger built-in caches and
increased system board speeds. Current Pentium IIs are plugged into
system boards that send data from other devices to the main
processor at 100 megaherz _ a boost from earlier boards that worked
at 66 megahertz. Sometime in 1999 you'll see system boards that run
at 133.
</P>
<P>
   _ Celeron: These chips got a bad rap when they initially were
offered by Intel, and deservedly so. They lacked a built-in cache,
making them pitifully slow.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest versions, which run at 300 and 333 megahertz, now
have a 128-kilobyte cache. There are other improvements that result
in excellent performance. In fact, this may be one of the best
processor bargains out there.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find these newer Celeron chips in systems in the $1,000
price range, making these great machines for gamers on a budget.
The new Celerons handle power-hungry games like Unreal and Quake II
with ease.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Celeron chips to accelerate to 366, then 400 megahertz
next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ AMD K6/K6-2: The K6 chip is Advanced Micro Devices' answer to
the Pentium MMX from Intel, and the K6-2 is a newer version that
addresses some of the shortcomings of the K6 design in an
interesting way.
</P>
<P>
   The K6 is not as good as Intel's chips at handling
floating-point math calculations, which are used in some 3-D games
and applications. But AMD has jumped ahead of Intel by including a
set of 3-D instructions called 3D Now! _ similar in concept to
Intel's Katmai product _ that developers can exploit. AMD is now
trying to get software programmers, and particularly those who make
3-D games, to take advantage of 3D Now!
</P>
<P>
   To show the possibilities, AMD worked with id Software to create
a special version of Quake II that uses the 3D Now! features. Tests
with this version show that, depending on other variables, the K6-2
chip can outperform some Pentium II systems when 3D Now! is
invoked.
</P>
<P>
   The K6-2 is found in systems that are priced equal to or
slightly less than those that use Celeron or Pentium MMX chips,
making it another good bargain, particularly for gamers. However,
with speeds of up to 350 megahertz and faster versions on the way,
it's also an excellent chip for general computing.
</P>
<P>
   _ MediaGX/MII: Cyrix, now owned by National Semiconductor, has
been selling for some time a chip called the MedixGX. It's
equivalent to the Pentium MMX, and it's found in many sub-$1,000
and even sub-$500 systems. However, I can't recommend this chip.
</P>
<P>
   The MediaGX steals two megabytes from the system's random access
memory for use as video memory. That means if you buy a low-end
system that comes with only 16 megabytes of RAM, you actually are
only able to use 14 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   Given that you can spend a couple hundred dollars more and get a
system that doesn't play cheap tricks with memory, it's best to
stay away from PCs that use this chip.
</P>
<P>
   The MII, however, is another story. It's essentially a beefed-up
version of Cyrix's 6x86 chip that runs at speeds of up to 333
megahertz, with 350 megahertz models on the way. Cyrix has priced
it to be competitive with Celeron and K6 processors, so you're most
apt to find it in sub-$1,000 systems.
</P>
<P>
   While I haven't tried a system that uses this chip, the reviews
of it look good.
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in more detailed information on PC
processors, pay a visit to Tom's Hardware Guide at
www.tomshardware.com. Tom Pabst, a physician who turned his love of
computers into a new career, provides thorough and unflinching
insight. Novices, beware: His site is fairly technical, but is an
excellent resource if you're geek enough to handle it. &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-25-98 1452EDT &QL;
</P>
