<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN, SACHS SHOWS THE RISK OF FORECASTING THE GLOBAL ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Those who still believe the stock market is based on
expert knowledge need look no further than this week's cancellation
by Wall Street's leading investment banking firm, Goldman Sachs, of
a multi-billion dollar share offering to realize how wrong they
are.
</P>
<P>
   Long regarded by their peers as the financial world's most
astute bankers, the firm changed its mind at the last minute
because of unstable market conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But if Goldman, Sachs didn't recognize earlier the signs of
economic trouble waiting to spring, who could have?
</P>
<P>
   A friend who retired last year after a long career on the London
stock exchange told me that he had no more idea of why markets go
up and down than he did when he started out 45 years ago. ``It's
all basically a mysterious phenomenon,'' he contended. ``Experience
doesn't help much.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a good point to remember when, as now, there is constant
discussion of the so-called global economy which half of the
``experts'' warn is headed for a severe recession while the rest
insist such fears are grossly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Federal Reserve lowered the cost of borrowing
money in the United States by one-quarter of a percentage point.
Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan explained the step was taken not so
much to help the still strong U.S. economy as to give a boost to
the flagging global economy.
</P>
<P>
   But does a worldwide economy in that sense really exist?
</P>
<P>
   Asia has been at the epicenter of the financial and economic
turbulence of the past 14 months. Yet, even there, many differences
are evident. For example, Taiwan and Singapore have escaped
relatively unscathed; Hong Kong shows signs of a more vigorous
recovery than initially expected. Australia, now very much part of
the Far East economic network, is doing well.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities are nervous about a monetary crisis in Brazil
which could produce an adverse effect on the dollar and to some
extent hurt American exports. However, even in the best of times,
Brazil is susceptible to financial frenzy, its currency bouncing up
and down like scantily clad Rio carnival performers.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the rest of Latin America is, on average, doing
better than it has since 1945. Mexico, in particular, has displayed
marked resilience following its peso crisis of five years ago _
possibly because it now seems to have a relatively honest
government.
</P>
<P>
   The recent plunge of the ruble was never much more than an
artificial scare, given Russia's tiny share of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Europe continues to insist its economy is picking up
and will go on doing so, as long as the United States doesn't
stumble.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, the United States is confronted by the potentially
overwhelming problem of Japan and its sagging banking system. If
the latter collapses, the term ``global economy'' will acquire a
devastating meaning. But U.S. and other western officials appear
more confident than they were just a few weeks ago that Tokyo will
devise an 11th hour rescue.
</P>
<P>
   None of this guarantees, of course, that a global recession
won't take place.
</P>
<P>
   It simply means that when it does occur, it will probably strike
at a time and from a direction unpredicted by anyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
