<HEADLINE>
SATELLITES GUIDING INDUSTRIES ON THE MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JIM CARRIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving millions of tons of earth around the Black Thunder coal
mine in Wright, Wyo., has come to resemble playing a video game,
except that the score is kept by military satellites high overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the cab of each behemoth D11 Caterpillar, a computer
screen displays a little bulldozer plowing through virtual dirt _
red for what needs moving and blue for what needs covering. As a
global positioning system, or GPS, receiver on the roof tracks the
dozer's movement across the screen, the operator's job, explains
Jim Long, the mine's chief surveyor, is to ``push the red to the
blue,'' creating the color green for the desired grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really slick,'' Long said. ``They don't even have to
look out the window _ except to keep from running over somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Black Thunder, a division of Arch Coal Inc. of St. Louis, will
produce 47 millions tons of coal this year from this one mine,
about 5 percent of U.S. production. And at a time when coal prices
are at a historic low of less than $5 a ton, the GPS gear, linked
to a computer-designed mine plan, helps the company achieve crucial
new levels of efficiency _ whether building roads across the
nine-square-mile site, uncovering coal seams or reconstructing the
original prairie contour once the coal is extracted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the company first put GPS units on its bulldozers in July
1997, we had some increases of 30 percent in productivity,'' Long
said. ``That's a pretty amazing number. It's not that the guy is
moving any more dirt. He's getting it to the right place the first
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Arch Coal is just one of thousands of U.S. companies putting GPS
to work, appropriating a system originally intended for military
navigation and using it for such commercial purposes as mapping
delivery routes, tracking products all the way from factory floor
to retail shelf, and monitoring the whereabouts of mobile workers.
</P>
<P>
   Available for limited civilian use since 1984 but fully
operational only since 1995, GPS technology has become so important
to industry that many businesses now consider it a utility like the
Internet _ an element of information technology helping fuel
America's economic engine.
</P>
<P>
   A Commerce Department study (infoserv2.ita.doc.gov/ot) released
this month estimates that worldwide GPS equipment sales will reach
$4 billion this year, and will double by 2000 and double again, to
$16 billion, by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Japan and Europe, where car-navigation systems
are the main use of GPS technology, the commercial market in the
United States is dominated by mapping and geographic information
systems like that employed by the Black Thunder mine. Even though
GPS gear is installed in virtually all U.S. military vehicles, and
the satellite system is run by the Air Force Space Command in
Colorado Springs, military purchases for GPS now represent just a
fraction of industry sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Military uses are swamped by civilian use,'' said Joe Canny,
deputy assistant secretary of transportation and the principal
staff person on the government's Interagency GPS Executive Board,
which sets the nation's GPS policy.
</P>
<P>
   No one has estimated the impact of GPS on the nation's gross
domestic product, but the figure is presumably ``enormous,'' said
Scott Pace, an analyst at the Rand Science and Technology Policy
Institute and a co-author of the Commerce Department study.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you add up the critical industries _ oil and gas, financial
networks, transportation _ you find that GPS is an embedded
assumption in the functioning in every one of those things,'' Pace
said.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, time.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying atomic clocks that are corrected daily to Naval
Observatory standards, the 24 GPS satellites that orbit the Earth
some 11,000 nautical miles above the Equator are the largest source
of accurate time in the world. Much of the nation's power grid, and
all of its long-distance telephone networks, as well as paging and
mobile phone systems, are kept synchronized via software that
periodically downloads GPS time, said Dennis McCarthy, director of
the Directorate of Time at the Naval observatory in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Naval observatory's time data is available over the Internet
(www.usno.navy.mil) and from computers around the country that
periodically correct their clocks when an orbiting satellite passes
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   And GPS time has become a crucial component of securities
trading and many other forms of financial transactions. The Nasdaq
trading system, for example, relies on a master clock kept in synch
by a satellite dish in Trumball, Conn., which allows every Nasdaq
trade to receive an official time stamp.
</P>
<P>
   The first commercial receiver in 1984 cost $150,000, weighed 100
pounds and was accurate to within 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Today a hand-held GPS receiver costs as little as $100, and the
semiconductor chip sets are small enough that the technology is
finding its way into cell phones. And error-correction techniques
have advanced so that specialized GPS devices can be accurate to
the width of a golf ball.
</P>
<P>
   Such advances have brought all sorts of new GPS commercial and
industrial uses. Backpack GPS units have revolutionized surveying
of construction sites, power lines and boundaries. Creating
accurate control points for such jobs in 1986, for example,
required two workers: one to hold a marked rod and the other to
site direction and elevation through a transit, at a cost of
$10,000 a point. Backpack units worn by a single worker have
reduced the cost to $250 a point, according to the Commerce
Department study.
</P>
<P>
   But in many cases, the business trend in GPS has been away from
the navigational question ``Where am I on earth?'' and toward the
more managerial interrogation ``Where on earth are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Federal Express, for instance, has installed GPS units on its
1,600 long-haul trucks, to track their movements and arrival times.
The trucks' locations are beamed to satellites every 10 minutes,
and computers route that data to destinations so that workers there
can be ready.
</P>
<P>
   Before the GPS units were installed two years ago, Federal
Express made ``educated guesswork,'' according to Charlie Hicks,
who is in charge of ground freight. ``Because of our service
commitment,'' he said, ``it is very important to know when things
are going to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar system, sold by Highway Master Corp. of Dallas for
$2,000 a truck, has been installed on 100,000 trucks around the
nation, including the fleet of Wal-Mart Stores; it can keep track
of average speeds and miles per gallon. The Highway Master system
also incorporates cellular telephones to let fleet operators stay
in even closer touch with their drivers.
</P>
<P>
   GPS is by no means a commercial cure-all. In Denver, where
Yellow Cab, a subsidiary of Stamford Capital, installed a $100,000
GPS-based dispatching system in 1996, at an average cost of $350 a
cab, the company has not yet seen any improvement in dispatching
efficiency, said Michael Brown, the company's director of
information systems. So far, the system mainly just lets
dispatchers know how many cabs are stacked up at Denver
International Airport, Brown said. He added that it probably would
not have much impact on costs and revenues until a related
``closest cab'' dispatcher software program is installed a few
months from now.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver system has had at least one tangible benefit,
however. When a customer tried to steal a cab while the driver was
in a store, the dispatcher radioed the police with the cab's
location and the cab was stopped within two blocks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the Gulf of Mexico, many of the petroleum industry's floating
oil rigs are kept in place over their wells with the aid of GPS
signals. John E. Chance &AMP; Associates Inc., a division of Fegro of
the Netherlands, moves rigs into place using GPS signals, and sets
up on-board computers that keep watch over a rig's precise position
and automatically fire underwater thrusters to move it back into
position if it drifts away.
</P>
<P>
   The labor required to position a rig has been cut in half, said
Jim O'Neal, general manager of Chance's marine group.
</P>
<P>
   Rising civilian and commercial demand for GPS has prompted the
government's interagency board to approve tripling the number of
civilian radio signals coming from the military satellites. The
decision was announced earlier this year, but carrying it out has
been at least temporarily delayed by technical questions, costs and
competition for space on the radio-frequency spectrum. Canny said
the additional signals were expected to be available on new
satellites by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest users of the new signals will be airlines,
employing the Federal Aviation Administration's new Wide Area
Augmentation System. The system is supposed to allow pilots and air
traffic controllers to determine an aircraft's location to an
accuracy of within 25 feet _ enabling planes to save fuel and time
by flying directly between airports rather than along strictly
controlled corridors as they must do now to avoid risk of
collisions. Using existing GPS signals and ground-reference points,
the first phase will be introduced next year.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hollywood has embraced GPS.
</P>
<P>
   In Sylvester Stallone's movie ``Daylight,'' with its climatic
escape from a flooded Holland Tunnel into the Hudson River, the
main characters were shown bursting through the river's surface
from the dark depths below.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Ron Goodman, president of Spacecam, a
special-effects film company in Los Angeles, the river was shot
during the winter without the actors present. A helicopter camera
panned down from the New York skyline as two GPS units, one near
the camera and one on the helicopter's tail, recorded the exact
spatial orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The camera angle and orientation were later duplicated over Lake
Casitas near Los Angeles to film two stunt doubles emerging from
the water. Only later did the actors bubble up in a nice warm
studio tank _ leaving the rest to the special-effects magicians.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-27-98 1845EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
