 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Literature sites shed light on the South 
By Frances Katz  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rich legacy of Southern literature is thriving on the Web.
Choices range from thoughtful, intelligent sites dedicated to some
of the South's most famous authors to journals and publications
dedicated to publishing new authors and fresh looks at the South
moving toward the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   WaySouth (http://www.waysouth.com) describes itself as ``an
Internet journal of original essays and stories from a unique
Southern perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   True to its word, WaySouth stays away from ``magnolia-ridden
cliches.'' Current stories document the hip-hop scene in Atlanta,
the nuances of the Southern accent and a thought-provoking essay
from publisher Grayson Hurst Daughters about George Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   WaySouth is clearly in ancient stages of development, but the
e-zine looks as if it could eventually become a must read for
lovers of literature and the South.
</P>
<P>
   The Brightleaf Review (http://www.brightleaf-review.com/) is the
online version of the print publication. The quarterly publication
features fiction, essays and photographs from well-known and
not-so-well-known Southern writers.
</P>
<P>
   Brightleaf is beautifully designed for the Web with copy and art
in just the right measure. There is also a section of current news
and features planned for upcoming issues.
</P>
<P>
   And, if you'd like to subscribe to the offline publication or
order back issues, you can print out a form to fax or mail back.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Mississippi _ known as Ole Miss in the South _
has an astonishingly complete Web site devoted to the grand old man
of Southern literature, William Faulkner
(http://www.mcsr.olemiss.edu/(tilde)egjbp
</P>
<P>
   /faulkner/faulkner.html).
</P>
<P>
   An excellent resource for both scholars and fans, this
comprehensive site includes everything from a RealAudio greeting
from Faulkner to bibliographies, frequently asked questions,
details of Faulkner's Hollywood years and even a weather report for
the author's fictitious Yoknapatawpha County (it's actually a link
to the Weather Channel's forecast for Oxford, Miss., but why
quibble.). Students will love the extensive commentary and plot
descriptions of all Faulkner's works, trivia questions, parodies
and a wide variety of other information.
</P>
<P>
   The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill also has an
extensive Southern literature project online called Documenting the
American South (http://sunsite.unc.edu/docsouth/).
</P>
<P>
   The DAS database contains resources on Southern history
literature and culture from the colonial period through the early
part of the 20th century. Available for online perusal are slave
narratives, first-person narratives and a large block of Southern
literature.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to navigate the site is to search the collections
by author, even if you are searching for first-person narratives.
The collection is still in the process of being digitized for the
Web, and this seems like the best way to find out what is available
online.
</P>
<P>
   A quick author search turned up narratives with titles such as
``A Virginia Girl in the Civil War,'' and ``Life of George M.
Horton. The Colored Bard of North Carolina: 1797-1883.'' While the
DAS database isn't cleverly designed or easy to navigate at times,
the glimpses of Southern life it provides make it a site worth
investigating.
</P>
<P>
   -- World of Old House: Facing a huge renovation project on that
painfully elaborate Victorian house you couldn't resist? Hang out
here for tips on restoring or simply maintaining your dream house,
heritage building or other example of traditional architecture.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.oldhouses.com.au/
</P>
<P>
   -- Careerbuilder Network: This personalized service provides
free, confidential and immediate access to employment opportunities
on the Web. This site also includes career advice.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.careerbuilder.com/
</P>
<P>
   -- Georgia O'Keefe: This biographical site celebrates one of the
most important American painters of the 20th century, complete with
images of her work. This site is divided into three sections,
covering O'Keefe as a young artist, her relationship with famed
photographer Alfred Stieglitz, and O'Keefe's visits to New Mexico,
which inspired her famous series of paintings depicting desert
terrain and animal skulls.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ionet.net/(tilde)jellenc/okeeffe1.html
</P>
<P>
   -- Food Resource: This comprehensive site promises ``to link as
much food-related information as possible.'' Well, it certainly
does. Browse through the list to find a recipe for alligator or
explore food safety; cook an authentic Hawaiian meal; or learn
about farm irrigation. http://www.orst.edu/food-resource/food.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-28-98 1128EDT &QL;
</P>
