<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS COMPUTERS MAY HINDER STUDENT PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MICHAEL DOUGAN   
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Students who spend too much time trying to learn
their lessons at computers may end up with lower scores on tests,
according to a study released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by the Education Week magazine, indicated
that fourth- and eighth-grade students who spent too much class
time learning math at a computer screen generally had poorer
grades. The reason: some computer time is devoted to goofing
around, according to Craig Jerald, project coordinator for the
magazine's ``Technology Counts '98'' survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might be adding a lot of aimless activities that have
entertainment value but not education value,'' Jerald said. The
study noted a 20 percent drop in test scores for fourth-grade
students who used classroom computers more frequently. Frequent use
of home computers resulted in a 26 percent reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also found that some types of computer training
enhance test scores while others diminish those scores, Jerald
said. Generally, the better the teachers were trained, the better
more the students learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``What mattered in technology was whether teachers had training
in computers and the way they used computers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the study said the average American school has 17 students
per classroom computer. The highest rated state was Alaska, with 9
students per computer, while Louisiana had 25. And 44 percent of
the nation's schools had links to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-29-98 1524EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1202EDT &QL; 
