<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1926 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PRIMAKOV-DOOME     09-30 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRIMAKOV-DOOMED-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMAKOV'S CABINET? IT WON'T LAST LONG 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of the World Leaders Forum.
To publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By BORIS Y. NEMTSOV  
 c.1998 Moscow News  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Under Russia's new prime minister, Yevgeny Primakov, I foresee
an unreasonable financial policy aimed at pumping the economy with
empty rubles. I'm convinced that no structural economic changes
will be possible.
</P>
<P>
   Right now the communists have become the ruling party. They have
all the levers of influence on the country's social and economic
life. So far the only things they haven't gotten their hands on are
the people's basic rights and freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party would love to introduce censorship, and
that's what it will try to do. The communists dream of having
political control over the power ministries and they will spare no
effort to achieve this.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that two years ago Boris Yeltsin became president
under the banner of fighting communist restoration, yet by now he
has voluntarily handed over the economy to them. But Yeltsin has
grown weak. His main task is to hold onto the presidency and
preserve himself as a guarantor of at least those rights and
freedoms that society managed to achieve since the reign of Mikhail
Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   In the past Yeltsin wasn't the kind of person to assume such a
modest role. But people change. Age, health and a person's
surroundings take their toll. By dismissing the ambitious reform
government of Sergei V. Kiriyenko, Yeltsin in effect laid down his
powers as the head of state responsible for Russia's social and
economic development.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think the communist cabinet Primakov has formed will
last long. Primakov, formerly foreign minister and one-time head of
Russia's foreign intelligence service, most likely is around for
the long haul, but his ministers aren't. Primakov is a smart and
talented man who, in moving from the Politburo to Yeltsin's
Kremlin, shows he has learned lessons from life's experiences. I
don't think he'll tie himself to the policies his cabinet will be
conducting.
</P>
<P>
   Certain deputies and ministers will be kicked out of the
Primakov government, and they will be held personally responsible
for the collapse of financial, social and industrial policies. This
is a tactic that Primakov knows well, and is most likely one he
will stick to.
</P>
<P>
   I believe we will see the level of stealing and corruption rise
sharply; budget money will be allocated to departments and
enterprises in an irrational manner. The bankruptcies of many banks
and small and medium-size businesses will leave hundreds of
thousands of qualified people unemployed, and this includes Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The people will be running away from the ruble, and its rate to
the dollar will be unpredictable. The government will try to fix
it, and in so doing it will generate a hard-currency black market.
The rate will jump up and down, and speculators will make a fortune
off it while ordinary citizens will plunge deeper into poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the communist authorities' obsession with printing
new money, next year inflation will fluctuate from 100 percent to
1,000 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The communists could use the people's protests to dislodge
Yeltsin. But right now he isn't controlling the country's social
and economic situations. He is not responsible for wages, pensions,
benefits and the military's salaries. Yeltsin will not be actively
involved in any kind of economic decisions.
</P>
<P>
   If the communists do manage to dislodge Yeltsin, this will
inevitably bring back censorship and control over the most
influential ``renegade'' ministers through political torture and
terrorism. The people can be incited to demand Yeltsin's dismissal
by blaming him for the social and economic problems, but from now
on, in fact, the communists are the ones who are responsible for
setting the country on its course.
</P>
<P>
   In his final speech, former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin,
whom Yeltsin had tried to bring in to replace Kiriyenko, said the
whole situation would end with the power going not to the
communists, but to the radical ultranationalists. This is possible.
It will all depend on the amount of the communists' madness per
unit of time. If the average month salary drops to $3 and the
streets are filled with millions of homeless people, it's very
probable. If we have a more or less balanced policy, we can avoid
the brown shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Initially Yeltsin fought for Kirikenko; he had a hard time
convincing the Duma to accept Kiriyenko and bringing him to the
political stage and so he linked his own fate with Kiriyenko's.
</P>
<P>
   But after Yeltsin himself sacked the Kiriyenko cabinet and
practically kept out of the process of endorsing a new premier, he
made it clear that he is voluntarily tapering his duties.
</P>
<P>
   I consider the Kiriyenko government to have been the best
qualified in all Russia's years of reform. We had a chance to
minimize the financial crisis, but not to avoid it altogether.
Right now, one of the greatest hazards for the country is to
default on the estimated $180 billion in foreign debt. In other
words, for the government to turn its back on its obligations to
the Paris and London clubs of government creditors, the IMF and the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   This default could have been avoided under the Kiriyenko
government by immediately holding talks on the process of
liquidating debts. Under Primakov's leftist, or communist,
government, default is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   I think the Kiriyenko regime was entirely capable of conducting
structural reforms, including the implementation of major
investment projects. It was also capable of making the investment
climate more attractive by improving the tax system and protecting
owners' rights.
</P>
<P>
   These are ideas that will be removed from the lexicon of
Primakov's rule. I think that with Yeltsin's support, the Kiriyenko
government would have been able to hold out, not without a certain
amount of tension and provided that it corrected its mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   I feel that it was a huge mistake on the part of the president
to dismiss the Kiriyenko cabinet. But right now Yeltsin's position
is such that he is unable to provide political protection. And it
was because of this, unfortunately, that the Kiriyenko government
was doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is rapidly approaching the abyss of a national disaster.
Elections to the Duma are not scheduled until December 1999. In the
meantime, we must be prepared for everything.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Boris Y. Nemtsov, first vice premier in charge of industry in
the Russian Federation under Sergei V. Kiriyenko, was also the
governor of the Nizhny Novgorod region and a post-Soviet, liberal,
free-market reform member of President Boris Yeltsin's early
administration. This commentary is adapted from an interview
conducted by Alexander Bekker, a correspondent for the Moscow
News.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
