<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING MY LIFE AWAY FROM TEXAS TO NEW JERSEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I started out in the newspaper business as a sportswriter. My
career goal was to cover major-league baseball, to travel from city
to city with the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness I was a lousy baseball writer.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this an official tip of the cap to baseball writers,
baseball players, baseball groupies and all other individuals who
spend days and weeks on the road in pursuit of their livelihoods or
hobbies. I just came off an 18-day road trip; I'm exhausted and
disoriented, not to mention dazed and confused.
</P>
<P>
   I traveled by car. Big-time sportswriters usually get where
they're going by airplane. To be perfectly honest, I'm not sure
which is worse.
</P>
<P>
   I hate to fly. Too crowded on the planes and in the airports.
Too much time on the ground before.
</P>
<P>
   But cross-country driving has become a challenge of inhuman
proportions. Highway reconstruction. Bad drivers. Overly aggressive
drivers. Road rage.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm getting too old to be putting 4,000 miles on the ol'
Buick in a single trip. Maybe I've lost the edge that makes
spending more than 60 hours behind the wheel seem like a really fun
way to fritter away three weeks in September.
</P>
<P>
   I took a similar trip once before, in 1989, for the same reason:
to watch Miss Texas compete in the Miss America Pageant in Atlantic
City, N.J. Memory tells me that the drive to the ocean and back was
more enjoyable that time, but I wouldn't swear to it.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm starting to whine now. My reason for commenting on the
challenges of roaming the nation's highways and byways is to warn
fellow travelers: Do not, under any circumstances, count on finding
a place to sleep in Arkansas on a night when a hurricane is about
to strike Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Because I left Illinois later than I should have on Saturday, I
decided that I would stop about halfway to Fort Worth and spend the
night. My chosen destination: Forrest City, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Having traveled Interstate 40 through eastern Arkansas on many
occasions, it was my distinct impression that a person could stop
at just about any motel along the way and have no problem finding a
room. I saw no need whatsoever to make a reservation.
</P>
<P>
   But when I asked about a room at the Holiday Inn in Forrest
City, the desk clerk told me that there was no room in the Inn _
and or in any other inn in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to keep going and stop in Little Rock. When I got to
President Clinton's former place of residence, however, I was wide
awake. I have no idea if there were any hotel rooms available
because I didn't bother to inquire. On to Texarkana.
</P>
<P>
   As I pulled into town, I noticed a small pickup on the ramp
ahead of me. I followed the truck as it darted frantically from one
motel to the next, the driver jumping out and dashing into the
lobby and then dashing back to the pickup and speeding to the next
motel.
</P>
<P>
   It quickly became obvious that there were no rooms in these
inns, either.
</P>
<P>
   There's a Shell station just off Interstate 30 on Route 71, and
I stopped there for gasoline and coffee. The attendant, who was in
the second half of a double shift, said he could call a friend at a
nearby motel and try to secure a room for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can usually roust up something,'' he said, ``but I don't
know about tonight. It's been crazy around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Texarkana flooded with hurricane evacuees, he said,
but the rodeo had been in town that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen it like this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I declined his offer to help me find a room. He bought me an
extra cup of coffee and urged me to be careful. I motored on.
</P>
<P>
   It was 8 a.m. or so when I finally rolled into Fort Worth.
Counting coffee breaks and a nap at a rest stop, the 13-hour trip
had taken about 18 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, folks. I used to think this stuff was fun.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
