<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1950 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-30 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING HOPE IN A WALL OF MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Tuesday, over the rumble of late afternoon
traffic, the brass blare of ``Taps'' rang out over a field of
sun-soaked green grass beside the Hudson River. Names had been read
into a microphone. Flags had been lowered. Tears had been wiped
away. And now the wall was moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Not the real wall, of course. That occupies a corner of the Mall
in Washington, just past a powerful bronze statue of grunts in
jungle gear. The real wall is carved black marble, roughly twice
the size of the replica that moves from city to city around
America. The moving wall was last in this town 12 years ago. I went
to Washington to see the real wall in 1983, the first summer it was
open to the public. I found some familiar names on the roster of
58,000 dead _ guys I'd known in high school, one from college.
</P>
<P>
   But I went to Tuesday's ceremony in an effort to find still one
more name. Some months back _ before the first of the year, anyway
_ a woman had called me. She said she'd read in my column that I'd
gone to Temple University in Philadelphia. From my picture, she
said, I looked about the right age to have known her brother, Bill
Geary.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I said, I had. Temple was then and is now a huge, teeming
urban university with tens of thousands of students. But I'd been
an editor on the Temple News, and Bill Geary had been active in
student affairs. He was a tall, ruddy, good-looking guy, immensely
likable.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you're Bill's sister,'' I said. ``What's he doing with
himself these days?''
</P>
<P>
   He was killed in Vietnam, she told me. He'd joined the service
right after graduation as an infantry officer. He'd lasted only a
few months. So, there it was _ still one more person I'd known
who'd died in that war. And here I was, 30 years after the fact,
hearing about Bill Geary's death for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't fight in Vietnam. I spent active duty in an Air Force
uniform stateside, putting out a military newspaper. I viewed that
war then and now as the product of tragically flawed thinking. If
there'd been a genuine threat to this country's safety, as there
had been in my father's war, they couldn't have handed out the guns
and the uniforms quickly enough. As it was, many people my age saw
Vietnam as a towering mistake, which it indisputably turned out to
be.
</P>
<P>
   But many people saw things differently then _ most, in fact.
Fathers and sons were, as fathers and sons always are, forged by
different experiences. Today, the fiercest conflict between the
generations focuses on the relative merits of the Rolling Stones
and Marilyn Manson. Three decades ago, we lived in grimmer times.
</P>
<P>
   Kids today just don't know _ not the way their fathers and
grandfathers know. To be young today is to live in a fabulous era.
The economy is soaring. Even the poorest among us enjoy a level of
luxury and comfort that no other generation could even imagine.
Most crucial, though, young men aren't being dragged off to
pointless, futile struggles with the Ho Chi Minhs of the world.
They don't even have to troop off to just and unavoidable war
against the likes of an Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   That wall is important for a good many reasons. It represents
honor and patriotism and sacrifice. But it also represents the
needless loss of nearly 3 million years of human life. I took
comfort in only one thought Tuesday, as I tried and failed to find
Bill Geary's name among the missing multitudes.
</P>
<P>
   My son is a college senior. As a middle-aged man, he'll conduct
no such search of his own.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
