<SLUG> BC-MUNICH-AGREEMENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 MODERN WORLD CAN LEARN LESSONS FROM 1930s APPEASEMENT  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA BASS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sixty years ago, Great Britain and France signed
the Munich Pact in an attempt to appease Nazi Germany by selling
out Czechoslovakia in exchange for peace. A few months after the
agreement was signed, Adolf Hitler's Panzer divisions rolled into
Poland, launching World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Munich Pact failed so abysmally to prevent war, its
primary lesson has always been the danger of appeasement. Indeed,
appeasement, which used to mean ``peaceful reconciliation'' _
something noble and positive _ became, after Munich, a dirty word,
so that today appeasement means caving in to a bully, usually out
of cowardice but sometimes simply out of stupidity or naivete.
</P>
<P>
   But the lessons of the Munich Pact go far beyond the obvious
hazards of appeasement. They are embodied in the words of Neville
Chamberlain, the British prime minister, and the driving force
behind the accord. It was Chamberlain who, three days before
signing the agreement in Munich, Germany, dismissed the troubles in
Czechoslovakia as ``a quarrel in a faraway country between people
of whom we know nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The world would pay a steep price for this arrogant
indifference.
</P>
<P>
   The ``quarrel'' between Germany and Czechoslovakia, simmering
for some time, came to a boil on Sept. 12, 1938, at the annual
Nuremberg Rally. Here, under the usual spotlights and before the
usual shrieking crowds, Hitler made an impassioned and threatening
speech, screaming that Czechoslovakia must hand the Sudentenland
over to Germany or face war. Violent street-fighting broke out
throughout the Sudentenland the following day, urged on by the
resident Nazis; the Czechs sent in troops and declared martial law.
Hitler looked ready to march straight into Prague, and Europe
looked ready to plunge into its second war in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   At this point _ Sept. 15 _ Chamberlain intervened, offering to
fly to Germany and meet with Hitler at Berchtesgaden.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain eventually made three trips to Germany, each time
assuring Hitler that while Great Britain would look unfavorably
upon a German invasion of Czechoslovakia, there would be no problem
with a negotiated settlement. In other words, Hitler could have
whatever he wanted as long as he didn't go to war to get it.
</P>
<P>
   France, which actually had a military alliance with
Czechoslovakia, eagerly seconded him. Arrogance and indifference to
the Czechs won out, and the Munich Pact was signed by Hitler,
Chamberlain, Benito Mussolini of Italy and Premier Edouard Daladier
of France just before 2 a.m. on Sept. 30, while Europe slept.
</P>
<P>
   Munich was the final nail in the Czechs' coffin. Less than six
months later, Hitler took over what bits and pieces of
Czechoslovakia remained after the loss of the Sudentenland and
absorbed them into the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Czechoslovakia disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   France and Britain had what they wanted: peace.
</P>
<P>
   But not for long. By showing Germany how far they were willing
to go to keep themselves out of war _ so far as to swallow the loss
of a friendly, though ``faraway,'' country _ Britain and France had
merely encouraged Hitler to find other countries to pillage. Next
up was Poland. This proved to be one faraway country too many for
France and Britain; they supported their ally, and World War II
began on Sept. 1, 1939.
</P>
<P>
   The Munich Pact sacrificed a nation whose only crime was that it
was weak, threatened, and far away. Today such countries abound,
especially since the fall of the Soviet Union. No nation _ not even
one as powerful as the United States _ can plunge aggressively into
every regional conflict. At the same time, Munich teaches us that
an arrogant disregard for the fate of ``faraway countries'' because
of preoccupation with other concerns _ the economy, presidential
scandals, military timidity _ can be expensive, not only in terms
of war and peace but also in terms of (if it still matters our
national honor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cynthia Bass is the author of ``Sherman's March'' and ``Maiden
Voyage.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
