<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 McGWIRE, SOSA `TIE' IS IN THE STARS  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Star bright, star light. First star I see
tonight. Wish I may, wish I might, have the wish I wish tonight.
</P>
<P>
   In about a month I will mark my 49th birthday, an age that
should make me an unlikely candidate for sing-songy childish rhymes
and wishing on stars. But the fact is, I still recite that rhyme in
my head whenever I see the first star of evening. (A stack of hay
bales compels me to a similar, though decidedly Midwestern chant.)
</P>
<P>
   The only difference now is, instead of wishing for a movie-star
husband, a mansion or world peace as I did when I was a kid, I wish
for little things that don't quite qualify for an official prayer.
Things that would just make me smile if they came true.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the month of September, my star wishes (and hay
wishes) were for one thing: That the professional baseball home-run
race between Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa would end in a tie.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the final weekend, it looked as though my wish might
be granted: both men had 66 dingers each. But, apparently, the
baseball gods are on a different frequency than hay bales and the
first evening star. McGwire won it outright with 70 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I love ties. They're one of the few experiences in life
in which two entities can bust their butts against each other _ yet
one doesn't have to end up being ``the loser.''
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that pro football and maybe society in general would
be better off if all that ``sudden death'' _ what a perfectly nasty
term _ were banished forever and tie games were reinstated. Yes,
yes, yes. I know that means we could end up with two Super Bowl
champions. Like that would really sully the purity of the event,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Even when I was writing about sports for a living and pretending
to hate ties (Who could afford to be a woman and a sissy?), I
secretly despised the tired cliche: ``A tie is like kissing your
sister.'' It's such a narrow-minded, exclusively male view; nobody
ever says a tie is like kissing your brother. And it objectifies
and puts down females: The whole analogy presupposes that your
sister is standing there, passively offering herself to be kissed.
</P>
<P>
   But as early as 1966 I learned not to talk that way because real
sports fans are supposed to hate ties. In an unofficial national
championship game that year, Ara Parseghian, the revered football
coach at unbeaten Notre Dame, chose to carefully grind out the
clock and take a 10-10 tie with unbeaten Michigan State rather than
risk a possible interception and loss.
</P>
<P>
   For this, Parseghian was thoroughly vilified. Many of the
nation's sports writers labeled him a coward and, for awhile, his
name was synonymous with no-guts play. Anyone who took a
chickenbleep route to victory was said to be ``doing a
Parseghian.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest I mislead, I'm not lobbying for a world of nothing but
ties. The entire baseball season might consist of about 11 games if
we did that. I just wish that when they occur within the original
rules of a game, we'd have a celebratory attitude about them; we'd
see them as a good thing, not some missed opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   I'm happy to say that McGwire and Sosa have managed to promote
this spirit more than any athletes I have ever witnessed. Because
they were both so hard-working, gracious and generous during their
contest _ and so lovable in their different ways _ no favorite
emerged. Much as you liked McGwire and wished him well, you didn't
particularly want to see him succeed at Sosa's expense. Or
vice-versa.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as the home-run derby wound down to its last weekend, I
was amazed and delighted to find all sorts of people talking about
a tie, hard-core sports fans _ men even _ speaking aloud about
their hope that somehow both the Cardinal and the Cub could
``win.''
</P>
<P>
   So, who knows? Maybe this past September, as the first evening
star rose and shone all over the USA, I wasn't the only aging
boomer looking up and asking for a little mojo action in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
