<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-VALLEY-SIDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OASIS PROVIDES HABITAT FOR THE ENDANGERED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT photo service) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMARGOSA VALLEY, Nev. _ For the visitor, it is a welcome
swimming hole in the middle of the Nevada desert.
</P>
<P>
   For at least 24 plants and animals, it is the only place on
Earth to live.
</P>
<P>
   Ash Meadows National Wildlife Refuge, about a 40-minute drive
from Death Valley, is a 22,117-acre spring-fed wetland and upland
desert oasis with the greatest concentration of endemic species in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   While threatened birds such as the bald eagle, white-faced ibis,
Western burrowing owl and peregrine falcon are known to haunt this
refuge, the endangered wildlife star here is the pupfish. Three
types of this tiny fish, which tops out at 3 inches long, are found
within the refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers direct visitors to the springs where pupfish can be
viewed. The shallow springs are fed with fossil water so clear that
it reflects the blue of the sky and the green of the algae on which
the small fish feed. During breeding season in the spring, the male
pupfish are a striking blue.
</P>
<P>
   At the refuge headquarters, a raised boardwalk takes visitors
through a desert marsh to Crystal Springs, where the fish are so
small that most fish-spotters walk away frustrated. The fragile
plant life of this area also gives cover to many types of birds
including ducks and quail. And almost everywhere you look hides a
rabbit's tail.
</P>
<P>
   No admission is charged at Ash Meadows National Wildlife Refuge.
The park is open dawn to dusk, and it does not permit overnight
camping. Visitors can swim and picnic at Crystal Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   For information, write to Refuge Manager, Ash Meadows National
Wildlife Reserve, P.O. Box 115, Amargosa Valley, Nev. 89020; or
call 702-372-5435.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
