<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1968 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-VALLEY-ART-HNS &LR;      09-30 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-VALLEY-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ITS INHOSPITABLE CLIMATE, DEATH VALLEY YIELDS TREASURES FOR
THE EYES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT photo service) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEATH VALLEY, Calif. _ When the sun finally inches over the
horizon on a recent crisp morning, a classic scene is revealed. The
apexes of a dozen honey-colored sand dunes are topped with
photographers.
</P>
<P>
   It is time to go to work at Death Valley National Park; the
light is changing, and swiftly. From an amber glow to the brilliant
sparkle of gold dust, the sky's light evolves. Distant mountains
appear black, then rusty and red. It's lavender and pink, too,
before the sun bakes the hills to a color of corn.
</P>
<P>
   The sounds of clicking shutters herald dawn. A body will rise.
Click, click. The photographer then settles back onto the sand to
await the next graduation of color. Click, Click. It is a clicking
chorus in the Mojave Desert.
</P>
<P>
   In these seemingly wide-open spaces, latecomers are not
embraced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Move along,'' says a dune-top photographer to a
camera-wielding tourist who has stumbled into his perfect picture.
Some of the photographers wave wildly at the post-sunrise
intruders; others offer exasperating sighs that, in the still of
the morning, echo across the sand and warn away the tardy like a
coastal foghorn.
</P>
<P>
   It is an ad hoc club: a click clique. Its members the
curmudgeons who made pre-dawn pilgrimages into the desert. Having
staked their claim _ at least temporarily _ these amateur and
not-so-amateur photographers guard their ground with the ferocity
of the miners who, a century earlier, scooped silver and other
metals from this land.
</P>
<P>
   Like the cranky, pre-dawn photographers, Death Valley has never
been known for its hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, midday temperatures average more than 110
degrees. The average yearly rainfall is less than 2 inches. The
area's chief inhabitants are kangaroo rats, rattlesnakes and
ravens.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, Death Valley is becoming a year-round vacation
spot. Superintendent Richard Martin said more than 75 percent of
the park's visitors come from abroad and ``many come specifically
to experience the extreme heat in the valley during June, July and
August.''
</P>
<P>
   Different heatstrokes for different folks.
</P>
<P>
   November through March are the most comfortable months for
visitors, with daytime temperatures ranging from 65 to 80 degrees.
Nighttime lows, accompanied by an explosion of stars, hover in the
low 40s.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its reputation as a desert wasteland, Death Valley
actually boasts diverse habitats and experiences for visitors. To
really explore its more than 3.3 million acres, vacationers should
allow three or four vacation days for the park.
</P>
<P>
   At the main ranger station at Furnace Creek, information is
available about evening programs, guided walks, day hikes and
driving tours. A small museum also explains the area's complex
geology. (Death Valley is not really a valley but a graben, created
by movement along fault lines. Some movements create mountains; at
other times grabens are formed.)
</P>
<P>
   Hiking and biking are extremely popular, but the
less-than-athletic can find ample opportunities to explore the
diversity of the largest national park in the lower 48 states
through a series of driving tours. A four-wheel-drive vehicle can
enhance your visit, as many roads are unpaved and require high
clearance.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to heed park safety regulations and suggestions. The
terrain and temperatures of Death Valley do not accommodate
foolishness.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some highlights of a visit to Death Valley National
Park:
</P>
<P>
   _ Death Valley Scotty may be the most flamboyant character in
this history of Death Valley. His real name was Walter Scott, and
during his life he pursued many careers, including work as a cowboy
in a wild west show and as a gold prospector.
</P>
<P>
   His lasting legacy is Scotty's Castle, although Walter Scott
never put a penny of his own in the place. The $2 million home was
built in the late 1920s by Chicago businessman Albert Johnson, who
invested heavily in Scotty's gold-mining adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Park rangers dressed in period costumes share many of the
fascinating stories about the friendship between the colorful Scott
and the devout Johnson. The rangers assume the roles of characters
in Scotty's life as they guide visitors through the mansion. A
short, steep walk leads to the graves of Scotty and his beloved
dog, Windy. The dust-blown gravesite overlooks ``his'' castle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mind your step at the Devil's Golf Course, a salt flat that
has earned its name from a suggestion that ``only the devil could
play golf'' on its sharp white crust. It is 200 spiny miles of
sodium chloride, the remnants of a shallow lake that evaporated
about 2,000 years ago. Nearby is a shallow salt-flat pool known as
Bad Water. At 282 feet below sea level, it is the lowest point in
the Western Hemisphere. Take a walk out into the flats to ponder
the the park's desolate vistas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Among remnants of Death Valley's silver mining days are the
Wildrose Canyon charcoal kilns. These large beehive-shaped
structures _ about 25 feet high and 30 feet around _ were used in
the production of charcoal.
</P>
<P>
   The coal was shipped out of Wildrose Canyon about 25 miles to
the west side of Panamint Valley, where the Minnietta and Modock
silver mines were located. The miners needed the coal to use in the
smelting process.
</P>
<P>
   Snow often blankets this part of the park until mid-April,
making the road to the kilns impassable.
</P>
<P>
   _ At Salt Creek, a boardwalk accommodates a half-mile
interpretive trail that zigzags over a shallow stream. Here
visitors can see the endangered pupfish and other wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The pupfish is the sole survivor of the evaporation of the great
lakes that covered this area more than 20,000 years ago. Nine types
of pupfish can be found in Death Valley. Each type has a special
adaptation that has allowed it to survive in its niche of the park.
</P>
<P>
   As salty as the ocean, the water at Salt Creek gets as hot as
100 degrees in the summer and cools to near freezing during the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Volcanic deposits ``paint'' the rock at Artist's Palette,
which is accessed on a lovely one-way and often steep drive. Iron
salts yield the reds, pinks and yellows in the vista; decomposing
mica generates the green cast; and manganese provides the purple
hues.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, the drive also reveals blankets of wildflowers.
The Panamint daisies are particularly pretty against the black soil
and rock. All the little yellow faces pointed toward the sun
resemble worshipers in a cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   _ Death Valley may be best known for its borax mining industry.
The free Borax Museum is located at the Furnace Creek Ranch
complex. The museum is housed in the oldest wooden building (1883)
in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Composed of boron, sodium, oxygen and water, borax is found in
dry lake beds. It has been used for centuries in the manufacturing
of glass and enamel; it also makes a good cleanser.
</P>
<P>
   Harmony Borax Works was a large operation that included many
stone, adobe and wooden structures, a boiler and many
crystallization tanks. The mining operation ended in 1888, but
remnants can be seen in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Most notable among the artifacts in the park are the huge wagons
that were pulled by teams of 20 mules. These 20-mule teams pulled
wagons loaded with 10 tons of borax and a 1,200-gallon tank of
water. Their route was a harsh 165 miles, covered in 10 days, to
the rail town of Mojave.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't be put off by cranky photographers. Death Valley's sandy
dunes are too terrific a site to bypass, and the velvety mounds of
gold offer hidden treasures to the keen eye.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the tracks of the park's many full-time residents:
bobcat, raven, coyote, lizard and road runner. Thousands of tiny
trainlike tracks crisscross the dunes. They are the tracks of a
tiny beetle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Perhaps the most popular spot in Death Valley National Park is
Zabriskie Point. It also may be the most photographed. Its
mustard-colored hills, wavy rock and glorious sunrises make it a
favorite with those early-rising photographers. By the time the sun
peaks over the horizon, dozens of tripods line the viewing wall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
