u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-CHRETIEN-BOS &LR;      09-30 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CHRETIEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LATE STORM MAY ENGULF CHRETIEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ He's the man who blithely led Canada to the brink of
collapse, pooh-poohing the threat posed by Quebec's separatists
right up until the stunning 1995 referendum in which the
French-speaking province came within a hair's breadth of seceding.
</P>
<P>
   He's the man who in recent weeks has responded with a shrug as
the value of the Canadian dollar went south with a vengeance,
plunging to its lowest depths in history.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Chretien, Canada's 64-year-old prime minister, is also the
man who has turned his back on many of the important pledges that
propelled him to the helm of government in 1993, refusing to
abolish the despised federal sales tax and committing the country
to the North American Free Trade Agreement that he so vehemently
assailed while seeking office.
</P>
<P>
   So, are outraged Canadians baying for his political blood?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. Or, at least, not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years, and he's still riding high,'' said Bob Richardson,
senior vice-president of the Angus Reid Group, a Toronto-based
polling firm. ``He's certainly enjoying the longest run of
popularity of any prime minister in this half-century.''
</P>
<P>
   But now a tempest is brewing in Parliament that might engulf the
folksy little guy from Shawinigan, Quebec, as Canada's most durable
politician loves to style himself. Opposition figures from both the
left and right are furiously seeking to transform an obscure
dust-up between Mounties and protesters at an international summit
in British Columbia last year into a full-blown assault on
Chretien's judgment and principles.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs they might succeed. Chretien, like his American
golf buddy besieged in the White House, is suddenly coming under
daily attack on front pages and on Parliament Hill not for his
policies but for his character.
</P>
<P>
   Critics charge that his apparent instructions to the Royal
Canadian Mounted Police to rigorously suppress any protests against
Indonesian dictator Suharto at the 1997 Asian Pacific Economic
Co-operation, or APEC, summit at the University of British Columbia
last November represented a serious violation of Canadian
constitutional guarantees of freedom of speech and freedom to
express political views.
</P>
<P>
   Student leaders were arrested simply for planning peaceful
protests. And those who attempted to hoist placards deploring
Suharto's oppressive rule were subdued with pepper gas and chased
away. The crackdown has become the focus of a massive federal
inquiry that shows sign of switching focus from the actions of the
Mounties to questions about Chretien's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This being Canada, there will be no sex scandal, no lurid
expose of our top politician's private life, no minute examination
of his moral fitness to hold high office,'' declared the Ottawa
Citizen in a front page analysis.
</P>
<P>
   But the prime minister's political enemies, the article went on
to say, are determined ``to put the lie to Mr. Chretien's image as
a competent manager and kindly favorite uncle, revealing what they
see as the real Jean Chretien: an incompetent, heartless, arrogant
bully.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a tall order. No other leader has flourished in Canadian
national politics for so long and so prominently as Chretien, a
Liberal Party stalwart first elected to Parliament when John F.
Kennedy was in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   That was 1963. Since then, Chretien has held nearly every
important cabinet post. He became prime minister for first time in
1993, after the Liberals not only defeated but virtually destroyed
the only other major party in Canada, the Conservatives. His
government won reelection last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stock just keeps getting higher and higher, at least among
ordinary Canadians,'' said Senator Sharon Carstairs of Manitoba, a
longtime political ally. ``He possesses prodigious energies, and a
genuine common touch.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been controversies aplenty during Chretien's five
years in the top office. Until now, however, none has personally
targeted Chretien.
</P>
<P>
   But last week the blasts came hard and fast as critics assailed
the prime minister's alleged orders to suppress protests at the
economic summit ``at any cost'' in order to spare Suharto
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did the prime minister trample on the political rights of
Canadian citizens in order to protect some Asian dictators?''
demanded Preston Manning, leader of the opposition Reform Party.
``Canadians want answers.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't necessarily so. If APEC-gate, as the controversy has
inevitably come to be called, has anything in common with the
Monica Lewinsky scandal, it is that most Canadians seem indifferent
to the affair, dismissing it as just the usual noxious political
noise emanating out of Ottawa. Public opinion surveys give Chretien
approval ratings of 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority like him, warts and all,'' stated prominent
political columnist Jeffrey Simpson in the Toronto-based Globe &AMP;
Mail. ``This kind of assault hasn't succeeded yet, and likely won't
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nontheless, Chretien may be subpoened and forced to testify
before a commission investigating the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Chretien is in many ways the most unlikely of political
leaders. Deaf in the right ear, afflicted by a facial paralysis
from childhood that gives his expression an almost sinister cast,
he speaks out of one corner of his mouth in a syntax that might
most kindly be described as garbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people just seem comfortable with him,'' said Richardson,
the pollster. ``He doesn't seem splashy or on the make. He's a
low-key guy who seems to get the job done. Canadians see Jean
Chretien as a guy they could invite over for a back-yard
barbecue.''
</P>
<P>
   Chretien was born and grew up in the gritty mill town of
Shawinigan, in Quebec's blue-collar French heartland, the 18th of
19 children born to Wellie Chretien and Marie Boisvert-Chretien.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief stint practicing law in his hometown, Chretien was
elected to Canada's Parliament at age 29. When he took his seat in
the House of Commons he spoke hardly a word of English.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ironies, even tragedies, of Chretien's career is that
he is today admired and even loved throughout English Canada, but
despised in his native Quebec, partly for his bumpkin image but
mainly because the ardent federalist is perceived as a betrayer of
the centuries-old separatist dream of a French-speaking republic
straddling the St. Lawrence River.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian commentators regularly carp that Chretien seems to have
no vision for Canada, no set of policies that reflect any values or
dreams to distinguish him even from his Conservative Party
predecessor, Brian Mulroney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balancing the budget deficit was worthwhile, but dreams and
visions need braver dimensions,'' said historian and author Peter
C. Newman. ``There is no sense of expansiveness ... in his social
and political horizons. Nada.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Chretien is the prime minister upon whom history has thrust
the chore of guiding Canada's through what may be remembered as the
country's most perilous passage.
</P>
<P>
   There will likely be another Quebec referendum on independence,
and a victory by the separatists _ thought to have at least a 50-50
shot _ would split the country in two.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, even if Quebec stays in the fold, Canada is a country
that is dangerously fracturing along regional fault lines.
Chretien's Liberal Party may hold the majority of seats in the
House of Commons, but that's only because the party so totally
dominates the most populous province, Ontario, which guarantees it
enough seats to control Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the Liberals are in rout or barely holding their own
while the Conservative Party _ Canada's equivalent of the
Republicans _ is in tatters, a minority party controlling just 20
seats in the national body.
</P>
<P>
   The western provinces, represented by the American-style
conservatives of the Reform Party, which has virtually no support
outside British Columbia, Alberta and Saskatchewan. Most Quebec
seats are held by the Bloc Qubecois, the national arm of the Quebec
independence movement, dedicated to tearing Canada apart. The
impoverished maritime provinces, profoundly alienated from the
political mainstream, are represented by a hodgepodge leftwingers
of the New Democratic Part, the few surviving Conservatives and
some Liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Canada is a far more decentralized country than the United
States, and these days some of the country's great institutions are
foundering, from the disgraced military to the economically
debiliated national health care system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's well and good to talk about leading the country
forward,'' said Carstairs. ``But Jean Chretien's more pressing
challenge is just holding Canada together under a federal
government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
