<HEADER>
A1987 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-30 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWAMI PREACHES MESSAGE OF LOVE, COMPASSION, SEXUAL CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the 1960s when he was a student leader at Princeton
University, Hindu Swami Krishnapada, then known as John E. Favors,
would survey the crowds as he spoke at civil rights rallies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be looking at the audience and thinking about who I was
going to have sex with that night,'' Krishnapada said, during an
interview in Boston, where he was offering spiritual teachings.
</P>
<P>
   He was student body president and a leader in the Rev. Martin
Luther King's Southern Christian Leadership Conference. His renown,
he says, made sexual conquests fairly easy. ``I was very
promiscuous,'' Krishnapada, 48, recalled.
</P>
<P>
   One day, however, it occurred to him that his sexual escapades
were ``hypocritical.'' He said he realized that ``as a leader I was
supposed to serve people and not have people serve me or take
advantage of them.''
</P>
<P>
   That was about 25 years ago. He has not had sex since. His
embrace of celibacy was part of a spiritual transformation for
Krishnapada that has made him into a popular spiritual teacher who
is constantly on the road preaching a message of love, compassion
and sexual control.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the greatest problems in the world today is the
impotence of our leaders at all levels of society,'' Krishnapada
writes in his recently published new book, ``Spiritual Warrior II:
Transforming Lust into Love.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the book grew out of the charges of sexual
misconduct against President Clinton levelled by Paula Jones, and
became rather more timely once Clinton's sexual indiscretions
snowballed into the crisis threatening his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders, Krishnapada writes, ``have been unable, or unwilling,
to conquer their lust. In particular, they have not learned how to
use sexual energies in a constructive way and so cannot master the
self-serving attachments that stand in the way of a more selfless,
spiritual expression of love.''
</P>
<P>
   He disputes suggestions by some political pundits that Clinton's
private matters have little to do with his public behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The private life of a leader is more important because it's a
more accurate reflection of who he is and what his values are,''
argues Krishnapada who has discussed spiritual matters with several
world leaders, including South African President Nelson Mandela.
``His public life is more of a performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Krishnapada grew up in a devout evangelical Baptist family in
Cleveland. Although he was a psychology major in college, he said
he became frustrated with the discipline because it could not
provide him a clear understanding of human experience.
</P>
<P>
   So Krishnapada spent a year meditating, reflecting and exploring
different religious sources. Eventually, he found spiritual comfort
in the 5,000-year-old Bhagavad Gita. He also became a follower of
Swami Prahbupada, founder in 1966 of the Hare Krishna movement.
</P>
<P>
   Krishnapada quickly found success in his new spiritual niche and
rose to the the level of swami _ a term referring to someone who
mediates between the worldly and the divine. As a swami,
Krishnapada was required to become celibate.
</P>
<P>
   ``True celibacy is one of the greatest expressions of freedom,''
he says. ``When one is no longer controlled by one's senses or
genitals it's amazing because you can begin focusing not on your
needs but on the needs of others. It's given me a better ability to
serve others.''
</P>
<P>
   Krishnapada also is the only African-American guru in Vaishnava,
a branch of Hinduism.
</P>
<P>
   He makes clear that he isn't opposed to sex. He just believes
that society today equates sex with love. And lust is dangerous, he
says, because it goes beyond just a craving for sexual
gratification.
</P>
<P>
   A key teaching in the Bhagavad Gita, Krishnapada notes, is that
lust, whether it be a desire for sex, money or power, is the cause
of all the world's problems. It can lead to war, human oppression
and the downfall of leaders and nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lust, the relentless pursuit of personal gratification at all
costs, which is promoted by the mass media, is destroying
humanity,'' Krishnapada said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reader Comments
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bitzer wrote to comment on our recent column on a book
written by Luna Tarlo, ``The Mother of God,'' which is critical of
her son, Andrew Cohen, a spiritual teacher who lives in Lenox.
Bitzer writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had the good fortune of knowing Mr. Cohen for many
years and wanted to add my voice of praise for him to that of New
York City psychologist Elizabeth Debold whom you quoted in your
article. Contrary to Luna Tarlo's portrayal, Andrew Cohen is a man
of unparalleled integrity, possessed with a passionate and wholly
unselfconscious care for the welfare of others. He is also well
known and respected within the spiritual world for his vocal and
public stand against corruption and abuse of power among spiritual
teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, with respect to Luna Tarlo's depiction of him in her
recent book, I can only say that nothing could be farther from
reality. Your readers should definitely proceed with caution.''
</P>
