<SLUG> BC-BANKBOS-BRAZIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKBOSTON STICKS TO LATIN EXPANSION STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAO PAULO _ Amid the imposing skyscrapers that line Avenida
Paulista sits a small, elegant building that looks like a small
version of the White House flanked by palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   The eye-catching structure stands out on the crowded avenue, one
of Sao Paulo's most coveted addresses. But it is also noticeable
because of the large green sign above it that bears the open-winged
eagle logo of BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   Opened two weeks ago, the building is the newest BankBoston
branch here and a visible symbol of the bank's presence in Latin
America's largest country, a stake that is growing despite a world
economic crisis that threatens to spread to the region and has
already frightened investors here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bank does well in crisis because our income sources are
diversified and because people here see us as a prestigious and
safe American bank,'' said Geraldo Carbone, president of
BankBoston's Brazil operation.
</P>
<P>
   The branch on Avenida Paulista _ across the street from the
Central Bank of Brazil and a block from the Sao Paulo Museum of Art
_ is one of 52 BankBoston branches in Brazil. The bank has been
opening new locations throughout the country at the rate of one a
week, mostly in upscale commercial and residential areas.
</P>
<P>
   Such rapid growth is in keeping with the aggressive $100 million
strategy aimed at strengthening the bank's operations in Brazil and
other Latin American countries. The plan, announced a year ago by
BankBoston president Henrique Meirelles, who had run its Brazilian
operation, has focused on building retail business and new
fee-based services like financial management in underserved markets
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   But while BankBoston earns about 20 percent of its profits from
its extensive Latin American business and forecasts increases for
1998, its stock has taken a pounding. Fearful investors are fleeing
emerging markets in the face of the economic contagion that has
spread from Asia to Russia and now threatens Brazil and other
countries in the region. BankBoston shares have dropped 37 percent
since July, shrinking the market value of the stock by nearly $6
billion. The stock closed Tuesday at 35 5/8, up 5/8 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Brazilian stock market has lost more than 30
percent of its value since the beginning of the year, and more than
$20 billion in foreign capital has left the country in search of
safer harbors.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston officials say that despite concerns of financial
instability in Latin America, they are following a more
conservative expansion strategy compared to other, larger banks.
</P>
<P>
   Like other foreign institutions, such as Citibank and Spain's
Banco Santander and Banco Bilbao Vizcaya, all of which have been
expanding their lending and retail business here, BankBoston's
strategy in Brazil has been to target an upper middle class that is
small but growing.
</P>
<P>
   In order to open an account, customers must have a minimum
salary roughly equivalent to $4,000 a month, more than twice the
country's median wage. Credit card and loan applicants must have
extremely strong credit histories and assets that demonstrate an
ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our target customers give us four times more revenue than the
typical bank customer in the mass market,'' said Marcio A.T.
Linares, vice president of retail banking.
</P>
<P>
   In return, BankBoston's 360,000 customers here get a level of
service unusual for banks in this region: sparkingly clean branches
with marble staircases, dozens of personal bankers and financial
advisers, and tellers reserved for BankBoston depositors. (In many
Latin American banks, tellers also serve noncustomers who use banks
to pay utility bills.)
</P>
<P>
   The bank also has imported concepts such as automatic teller
machines and telephone and computer banking. It recently began
offering car financing programs through selected dealers and a
shared credit card with General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston is also developing a mutual fund business that
invests mostly in Latin American firms using local currencies, a
service that has given the bank a strong indigenous brand name. The
bank manages about $5 billion in assets in Brazil and another $1.3
billion in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key in emerging markets is to be disciplined and to
realize you can't be everything to everyone,'' said Ricardo Augusto
Gallo, BankBoston's executive vice president for investment banking
in Brazil. ``We're not a typical type of global bank that's spread
out in hundreds of countries because we're concentrated here.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank opened its first Latin American office in Buenos Aires
in 1917 to help New England wool merchants and has maintained a
strong operation in Brazil for more than 50 years. Today, it has
over 150 locations in Central and South America and in the
Caribbean that generate nearly $1 billion in revenue. But even
analysts who generally support the bank's expansion in Latin
America caution that there are risks.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America's middle class has blossomed since the region's
last financial crisis in 1994, thanks to relatively stable
currencies and lower inflation. But the deepening world economic
crisis threatens to cast the region into turmoil again.
</P>
<P>
   A study released by the Institute of International Finance, a
Washington, D.C.-based banking industry group, predicts that Latin
American deficits will surge this year to $70 billion from $57
billion last year mostly because of the economic downturn. The
Inter-American Development Bank also estimates Latin America's
regional gross domestic product will fall to 3.5 percent this year
from 5.1 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, some observers expressed concern about
BankBoston's future earnings in the region. ``We need reassurances
that the earnings will be there while they're on the express track
to rapid deployment,'' said Thomas McCandless, senior banking
analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer &AMP; Co, Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But McCandless and others say the bank appears well-positioned
to withstand the current economic turmoil just as it has endured
past crises in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been in Latin American for a long time,'' McCandless
said. ``I think they know what to expect in situations like this.
They've been able to weather the storms in the past. There's no
reason to expect it will be different this time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
