<HEADLINE>
A BRITISH VOTE FOR CLINTON'S SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are 70,000 Albanian villagers, from newborns to frail
elders in their 90s, huddled in the soon-to-be-snow-covered hills
of Kosovo, fearing slaughter by the Serb ethnic-cleansers.
</P>
<P>
   NATO warns it may shortly bomb the marauding army of Slobodan
Milosevic, Europe's latest Ghengis Khan. There is a new man taking
over the show in Germany, Europe's most important economy. Japan?
Still in the ditch. The rest of Asia? An economic basket case.
Iraq? Stiffing UN weapons inspectors. The other terror regimes? On
the move again.
</P>
<P>
   Russia? That wobbly giant is decomposing again, with nukes and
nuke-makers up for grabs. When it comes to all this and Northern
Ireland, the Middle East, or rescuing the International Monetary
Fund's vital role in propping up the planet's shakiest national
economies, the one man with most potential to determine the outcome
is otherwise occupied with Monica-business.
</P>
<P>
   With the practiced understatement for which Great Britain's
diplomats are noted, the British ambassador to the United States
Monday chose his words carefully for a Kennedy School lunch at
Harvard: ``Your friends and allies abroad would wish this thing
would pass rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes two of us, Mr. Ambassador. In an interview earlier,
Sir Christopher Meyer expanded on the theme: ``I think it is
perfectly possible for President Clinton and his people to give
leadership and be active in foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a relief. Because with Boris Yeltsin in his usual
position, on the ropes; with Japan's government paralyzed as usual,
with Asian prospects melting down, and with Helmut Kohl's election
defeat in Germany, the world's supply of leadership is at a low
ebb.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, who had been defeated Tory Prime Minister John Major's
press spokesman before being drafted for ambassadorial duty in Bonn
and then Washington, says his government's thorniest problem with
the United States in bilateral terms is the airline beef about
landing rights at Heathrow.
</P>
<P>
   But Britain sees Europe's biggest problem right now as the
70,000 endangered refugees of Kosovo. He recalled the Russian term
for the bitter weather that has dictated events to generals and
diplomats in Central Europe for centuries: ``General Winter.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jim Morrison and the Doors would say, ``Winter's coming on.''
The world can't stay on hold while the Republicans in Congress try
to fricassee the Clinton presidency. Her Majesty's Government,
Meyer said drily, would ``not want appalling scenes of refugee
misery in the snowy hills of Kosovo and Albania.'' With a UN
Security Council vote last week upbraiding the Serbs for
intercepting refugee aid. ``NATO is now organized to act militarily
on very short notice indeed,'' warned Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair is on the phone so frequently
with Clinton, shrugged Meyer, that the Downing Street demand for
diplomatic follow-up is ``insatiable.'' As the man called upon to
explain to Blair's regime what is going on in Washington, Meyer
appropriated the Yogi Berra aphorism that ``it's never over till
it's over.'' In D.C., said Meyer drolly, ``It appears to be never
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheerfully embracing the traditional definition of an ambassador
as ``an honest man sent to lie abroad for his country,'' he
recalled for host Joe Nye, the Kennedy School dean, how he had been
a fellow 10 years earlier at Harvard's Center for International
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   An ambassador is supposed to be ``a pundit, a saloon-keeper, and
a lobbyist,'' said Meyer, and he expanded on the ambassadorial role
in the Internet age. The lines between foreign and domestic policy
are blurred in all the industrial nations. Economics and diplomacy
are now similarly parts of the same whole, with traditional
distinctions blurred.
</P>
<P>
   And much of what used to be the traditional bilateral diplomacy
_ one country dealing directly with another _ has given way to
multilateral negotiations where whole armfuls of nations have to be
consulted on thorny technical matters involving trade, the
environment or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer was upbeat about Northern Ireland's peace prospects. ``I
don't quite see what the deal will be _ but I think there will be
one. There would be a huge reaction from both sides if the
politicians screw this up.''
</P>
<P>
   The decommissioning of arms caches hidden by the paramilitaries
will be a thorny task for the Irish and British governments, said
Meyer. There was a difference between how Major and Blair
approached the problem. For Major, demanding the IRA give up its
weapons was ``an iron condition,'' but for Blair, who defeated
Major in a landslide election (179-seat majority in Parliament)
that left doubt of Labor's mandate, coming to terms with an IRA
that had surrendered all its weapons was ``not an iron condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said he is still ``astonished'' at the progress that was
made in Ireland with the good offices of America's George Mitchell
as umpire of the talks. And he suggested that Bill Clinton remains
a pivotal figure in world economic and diplomatic affairs, despite
the political Monica Meltdown in D.C.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke Monday, Clinton was brokering another
Israeli-Palestinian summit in the White House office his enemies
want him to vacate early. Your president, Meyer reminded Americans
wryly, is still the figure who can make other nations do what they
would otherwise not do on their own.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
