<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SENATE FIGHT BECOMES A BATTLE FOR UPSTATE VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEEKSKILL, N.Y. _ Alfonse D'Amato has figured out how to win
re-election to a fourth term as US senator from New York State _
attack New York City.
</P>
<P>
   For a Brooklyn native, it seems a strange stratagem. But it just
might work.
</P>
<P>
   When most Americans think about New York politics, they picture
liberal Democrats, blacks, Jews, and New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The reality, however, is quite otherwise. The decisive
constituency here tends to be conservative, Republican, white,
Catholic, and is based in large part outside the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   This electoral gulf between New York City and the rest of the
state is as vast and virulent as any geographic, political, or
cultural divide in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to understanding everything in New York,'' pollster
John Zogby emphasized, ``is understanding that, historically,
culturally, we are two warring nations: upstate on one side, New
York City on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's idea for beating his challenger, US Representative
Charles Schumer, a Jewish Democrat from Brooklyn, is to intensify
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's response has been to join the fray. The resulting
contest, which recent polls peg as too close to call, could be the
bloodiest here in years.
</P>
<P>
   Its direction became clear in a TV commercial D'Amato aired last
week, but only ``upstate,'' outside New York City and its
surrounding suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, blaring the music from ``Jaws,'' shows a school of
sharks swimming past the Manhattan skyline, headed upstate. ``The
New York Democrats just picked New York City liberals for every
statewide office,'' the announcer broods. ``You know what that
means, increased taxes for us, increased spending for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In another ad, Schumer is described as a ``Brooklyn liberal
Democrat,'' who has no interest in anything west of the Hudson
River.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem an odd move for D'Amato, who retains his Brooklyn
accent though he lives in suburban Island Park. But the message
resonates among its target audience, whose ideology D'Amato mainly
shares.
</P>
<P>
   It is a brand of voter you do not have to venture far outside
the city to find. Peekskill, a town of 20,000 people, is just 50
miles north of New York City, hardly fitting most definitions of
``upstate.'' But when it comes to how people think about issues,
life, and, more to the point, about New York City, Peekskill might
as well be on the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Wood, a waitress at the Royal J Cafe, has lived in
Peekskill for 21 years, but boasts she has never set foot in New
York City. ``It seems to me we've been carrying that city,'' she
moaned. ``They wanted to split off a while ago. We should have let
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Steffens, a taxi driver, said much the same: ``We look at
New York City as users, leeches, the squeaky tire. New York City
always seems to get what it wants, while we're treated as
second-class.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Upstate has long seen New York City as a drain,'' noted Hank
Sheinkopf, a Democratic political consultant in Manhattan. ``People
there believe the only reason they're paying such high taxes is for
New York City welfare clients.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, a new study by the Rochester-based Center for
Governmental Research concludes New York City pays more in state
taxes than it gets back in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the perception is powerful. New York City has nearly
three times as many welfare recipients as the rest of the state.
Meanwhile, upstate towns are in far worse economic condition. The
Wall Street boom that lifted the city out of recession did little
to revive upstate.
</P>
<P>
   Some see an ethnic element sharpening this resentment. ``When
D'Amato calls Schumer a `Brooklyn Democrat,''' Sheinkopf commented,
``he knows the common view is that two kinds of people live in
Brooklyn _ black people and Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Democratic Party has responded to the shark ad by
purchasing air time to show it on New York City stations, with a
label reading, ``The ad Al D'Amato doesn't want you to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schumer will have to take the brunt of his battle into
the heartland, because upstate is where the votes are.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac College Polling
Institute, noted, ``There used to be a rule of thumb. If a Democrat
carried New York City by 500,000 votes, he was home free.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the 1994 governor's race, Democratic incumbent Mario
Cuomo won New York City by 600,000 votes, but lost the election to
Republican George W. Pataki, whose previous job was mayor of tiny
Peekskill.
</P>
<P>
   What has changed in the last decade is that fewer people in New
York City are voting. Frank Mauro, director of the Fiscal Policy
Institute, near Albany, said, ``Turnout has declined so much, it's
boosted the importance of the rest of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994 election, New York City, with 40 percent of the
population, provided just 28 percent of the voters. Upstate
supplied 42 percent of the voters, and the increasingly Republican
suburbs 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That election marked another watershed. It turned the
upstate-downstate divide into a political powderkeg. Not only did
Cuomo win big in New York City, he lost big every place else,
carrying just one of the state's 57 other counties, Albany, and
there just barely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pataki's election,'' Mauro said, ``shows it's possible to win
without doing well in New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's shark ad suggests he has learned that lesson.
</P>
<P>
   A poll, released last week by Quinnipiac College, shows, in the
state overall, Schumer with 44 percent and D'Amato with 42 percent
_ basically, because the margin of error is 4 percent, a tie.
</P>
<P>
   However, in New York City, Schumer trounces D'Amato, 60 to 31.
Upstate, D'Amato wins but not so decisively, 46 to 36. In the
suburbs, where D'Amato lives, he leads by a bit more, 50 to 37.
</P>
<P>
   An important detail in this poll is that, in New York City, only
6 percent of respondents have not made up their minds. However,
upstate, 16 percent are still undecided. And the political wisdom
says the best way to win them is to foster their deep resentment of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why D'Amato has started these ads saying Schumer
wouldn't know anything above Yonkers if it bit him,'' Carroll said.
``The problem is that Schumer really is not your standard knee-jerk
New York City liberal, which is why D'Amato is trying to paint him
as one.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer is fighting back on this front, too, releasing ads, all
over the state, calling D'Amato a ``liar'' on both of their
records, a charge that has raised eyebrows for its bluntness.
</P>
<P>
   This is a race that has won the tag as ``The contest of the two
`L' words: liberal and liar.'' Whoever wins will likely represent a
state in which the fissures that long have divided New York State
are deeper and more jagged than ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
