<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MACDONALD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADVISER HAS PREACHED THROUGH THE PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Mass. _ At age 4, when many boys were playing with
trucks and pop guns, Gordon MacDonald was playing in the pulpit of
his father's Baptist church _ pretending to be a preacher.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is fitting that the same boy grew up to be pastor of
one of New England's most successful churches, Grace Chapel, where
as many as 4,000 people pass through the doors on Sundays and cause
near gridlock on the surrounding streets following
standing-room-only weekend services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost feel like I was bred to be a pastor,'' said
MacDonald, 59, sitting in the spacious corner office inside the
building that houses the church's staff of 36.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald and Grace Chapel have been thrust _ somewhat
reluctantly _ into the national spotlight now that MacDonald has
agreed to be one of President Clinton's three spiritual advisers.
Seeking solace and restoration within his Southern Baptist roots,
Clinton sought out MacDonald in part because the two men share a
similar painful experience _ a fall from grace caused by an
extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it's like to screw up, and I also know what it's
like at the deepest, darkest moment in your life to sense God
saying, `You want to come back and try again?''' said MacDonald,
shortly before dashing off Friday to catch a flight to Lancaster,
Pa., for a speaking engagement. He has declined to discuss his
conversations with Clinton, but says he will be meeting with the
president or talking to him by phone at least once a week.
</P>
<P>
   As MacDonald begins his effort to counsel the president, he is
nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may seem calm to you, but I'm honestly pretty scared,'' he
said, because of the public scrutiny he, his family, and his church
could become subjected to.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island, N.Y., native had for years enjoyed renown
beyond Grace's walls, emerging as a national leader among
evangelical Christians and as a highly sought-after motivational
speaker who regularly hits the road to preach.
</P>
<P>
   These days he is much in demand among a decidedly different
crowd, the news media. MacDonald guesses he has turned down more
than 100 interview requests from journalists who want to know what
it is like to be spiritual counselor to the president.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald used his own experience of wrongdoing, repentance, and
sin as the basis for a 1988 book, ``Rebuilding Your Broken World,''
which has become a primer in the Christian world on how to overcome
personal failure. It was through the book that Clinton came to know
and befriend MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
   At Grace Chapel, MacDonald has helped build an
interdenominational Christian church nationally known for a high
level of lay involvement, a strong emphasis on following Jesus and
the Bible, &UR;  &LR; and a deep commitment to social justice, borne out by
the more than $1 million the congregation grants every year to
dozens of ministries, ranging from soup kitchens to homeless
sheters.
</P>
<P>
   But MacDonald resists any portrayals of him as a gifted
Christian leader or pastor. He credits the church's success to the
people who keep Grace humming seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming here was like getting on top of a horse that just
wanted to run,'' he said. ``This is a lay person's church. It has
my fingerprints on it, but it's the laity that provide the energy.
It takes 1,100 volunteers a month to keep this place going. I would
be a fool if I took credit for what this church has become.''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald's modesty aside, many people at Grace say the pastor
has had a major impact on the church's evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Holly O'Toole, 39, of Bedford, says MacDonald's powerful sermons
linking Scripture to contemporary issues helped make her become an
evangelical Christian two years ago when she first attended a
Sunday service.
</P>
<P>
   ``God used Pastor MacDonald in a very powerful way in my life,''
said O'Toole, who gave up a six-figure salary at John Hancock
Insurance Co. to work at Grace Chapel as director of ministry
mobilization. ``I was very lost, very confused, and feeling very
dissatisfied with my life. And God used Pastor MacDonald through
his preaching to draw me into the light of God.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a difficult road back to the pulpit for MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, his world fell apart after he publicly admitted that he
had committed adultery, an offense that has brought public disgrace
to many evangelical leaders in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Three years earlier, MacDonald left as senior minister at Grace
Chapel to take on more high-profile roles in evangelical
Christianity as president of InterVarsity Christian Fellowship and
chairman of World Vision, an international relief agency.
</P>
<P>
   But revelations about MacDonald's infidelity left him without a
job, humiliated, and with little hope of reclaiming his status as a
Christian leader.
</P>
<P>
   It was the congregants at Grace Chapel, who had hired MacDonald
as a 32-year-old visionary in the early 1970s, who reached out to
bring MacDonald back into the Christian fold, first by providing
rigorous counseling, and then by asking him to become, once again,
the church's senior pastor five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald rebuilt his career through the support of three
spiritual advisers who were chosen by the elders at Grace Chapel.
Among evangelical Christians, such counseling, widely known as
``accountability circles,'' is commonly used to pray for and
support people in trouble, usually men.
</P>
<P>
   Now MacDonald is part of Clinton's accountability circle, &UR;  &LR; along
with the Rev. Tony Campolo, a professor at Eastern College in
Pennsylvania, and the Rev. J. Philip Wogaman, pastor of the United
Methodist Church where the first family often worships.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald's ordeal and the way he was willing to face his
crucible and emerge a stronger and more faithful Christian has
earned him widespread respect not only among congregants at Grace,
but among many Christians nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the brightest, clearest-thinking people I've ever
worked with,'' said Paul Borthwick of Lexington, an adjunct
professor of Christian mission at Gordon College in Wenham who
worked at Grace Chapel for 18 years. ``He's able to connect with
the person in the pew. When he speaks to a large group, say 1,000
people, 1,000 people might think he's their best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Rebuilding Your Broken World,'' MacDonald acknowledges that
``for the rest of my life I will have to live with the knowledge
that I brought deep sorrow to my wife, to my children, and to
friends and others. ...'' His marriage survived the affair, and he
characterizes his relationship today with his two children as
``stronger and filled with more love.''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald's friends say his travails have helped make him an
even better minister. ``He's brought an atmosphere of mercy to
people who are seeking, people who are broken, without compromising
the clear teaching of Scripture,'' said Mary Ann Mitchener,
minister of urban outreach at Grace Chapel and a friend to
MacDonald and his wife, Gail, for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald knows there are critics who say he, Campolo, and
Wogaman are being manipulated by the president for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   But he, and those who know MacDonald concur, is not about to
offer Clinton quick absolution. Without going into details,
MacDonald suggested he will treat Clinton as he would anyone in
trouble who seeks &UR;  &LR; his counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This person needs to go backwards and understand what are the
pathways that led him to commit this action,'' MacDonald said.
``When we talk about healing and restoration, we also have to deal
with how does a person get forgiveness. Does it require loss of a
job, financial restitution, some kind of probation? It doesn't
happen with the snap of a finger, and it requires a lot of work and
commitment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
