<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SLOW GRIND OF JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- In the city and county of San Francisco, jury
duty is not easy to avoid or endure. Motions, objections, and
exhibits flow across the jury's ken like molasses or mucilage. The
few advantages include missing national legal moments more
titillating and more depressing.
</P>
<P>
   For months, I have been a bystander, opinionless among the
teeming crowds running toward the defense or prosecution of
President Clinton. I am merely puzzled at how this man causes so
much adulation and so much anger.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed solutions to his woes are more interesting and more
revealing of the national character than the president's
``inappropriate conduct.'' More than 200 newspapers have called
upon him to resign, an astonishing number. This editorial rush to
judgment rejected the presumption of innocence. Disgust defeated
discretion and prudishness overwhelmed prudence, all stirred by the
American libido for hygiene.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy is often messy and ponderously slow. ``Delay is
preferable to error,'' Thomas Jefferson told George Washington in
1792. But today's Americans prefer tidiness and speed. This
explains another extraordinary delusion known as ``Censure Plus,''
a hygiene product that could have been marketed by Procter &AMP;
Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fairness to the president'' is the motivation behind this
hasty move. But was Clinton being fair when he lied for seven
months? ``Make this go away'' is the mantra. ``I think it's
debilitating for this country,'' says Senator Tom Harkin of Iowa,
defending the president. But the Founding Fathers were not
squeamish about impeachment. They thought it could be invigorating
and cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution designed its checks and balances to be slow and
cumbersome, not anticipating television's need for a sound bite.
The Censure Plus caucus seeks to avoid impeachment hearings. Are
the charges trivial or serious? The House Judiciary Committee will
decide first, its 37 members deliberating in public, bound by the
necessity to seem fair. Republicans will have the incentive of
their leadership's suicidal tendencies in recent years. Democrats
will have the incentive of the November elections, which will
likely mean fewer Democrats in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee members do not prosper in the food-fight
environment of television talk shows, but in doing their
constitutional duty, they can. The committee shone in the
impeachment hearings on President Nixon in 1974. ``If we aren't
credible, what we're doing amounts to nothing,'' chairman Henry
Hyde said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Television can distort judgment. I did not watch the famous
videotape of President Clinton's Aug. 17 testimony before a federal
grand jury. People who saw it told me ``he looked good.'' He always
looks good on television, especially when his co-stars are the
cronies of his favorite foil, Kenneth Starr. His testimony had all
the anticipation and excitement of a playoff game. Its afterglow
boosted his poll ratings (as widely watched televised performances
by presidents usually do).
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's demeanor changed from contrite to chipper, based on
this temporary wave of emotion. And it is temporary, because he
will not publicly answer questions on this subject again for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   That time could be during the ``closer look'' that Hyde promises
in the impeachment hearings. That's what the Constitution calls
for, the law moving slowly.
</P>
<P>
   In a civil trial here, every day seemed like a month in San
Quentin. When the judge asked about prior courtroom experience, I
said I had been a litigant many times but never a plaintiff. Still,
I was chosen to serve.
</P>
<P>
   In the jury room, the plaintiff's frequent lawsuits suggested
that he seemed to treat litigation as a hobby. We deliberated 11
minutes before finding for the defendant, a corporation he sued for
unconvincing reasons. The law may move slowly, but justice delayed
is justice denied.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
