<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI HAS SOME EXPLAINING TO DO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tell it to the employees of Gillette in South Boston, Governor
Cellucci. Or to the computer workers just pink-slipped from ADE of
Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   Tell it to the hundreds of former Digital workers in
Marlborough. Or to the 350 people laid off from Stratus Computer in
the same town.
</P>
<P>
   Tell it to the factory workers at Raytheon in Andover. Or to the
675 computer-chip makers facing layoffs by Intel in Hudson, your
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Tell all the newly unemployed workers at Teradyne in Boston
about the vigorous economy in Massachusetts and the state's
record-low unemployment rate. Take a page from your stock campaign
speech to reassure all the freshly ``downsized'' employees from PRI
Automation in Billerica that the Commonwealth is bursting with new
job opportunities for them.
</P>
<P>
   On a single block of my suburban town alone, no less a corporate
giant than Sam Goody is in search of salesclerks; no less a growth
concern than CVS Pharmacy is in need of register ringers!
</P>
<P>
   In Cellucci campaign circles, the Commonwealth is still
experiencing the Massachusetts Miracle, an economic recovery
impervious to a skittish stock market, a national political
scandal, and overseas economic instability.
</P>
<P>
   The economy is so good, the strategy seems to be, that there is
little need to discuss it at all. Why not make the race for
governor of Massachusetts this fall a referendum on the death
penalty or a plebiscite on mandatory testing of public school
teachers, instead?
</P>
<P>
   Two new economic studies released in recent days suggest exactly
why not. Both studies contend that the gap between rich and poor in
Massachusetts is growing.
</P>
<P>
   US Census figures released last week show an increasing number
of people in the state slipping into poverty, data that are
especially alarming given just how low a family's resources must
fall before the federal bureaucracy will classify a family as poor.
The poverty line is drawn at the absurd level of $13,650 for a
family of three, $16,400 for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   No one reasonably believes that any family living in Boston
could meet its basic needs with an income so low. A new study by
The Women's Educational &AMP; Industrial Union in Boston found
low-income families were forced to spend half of their income for
housing and child care alone. At least 40 percent of those families
were unable to earn enough money to come close to achieving
economic independence _ the much-touted goal of the Cellucci
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's neglect of the child-care needs of
low-income working parents, especially working mothers,
demonstrates the governor's failure to address some of the most
fundamental issues facing poor women. An estimated 13,000 children
continue to languish on waiting lists for chronically underfunded,
state-subsidized child care. An administration that prides itself
on having forced poor mothers out to work still can't find the
resources to help them care for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in Paul Cellucci's campaign against Democrat Scott
Harshbarger, a commitment to affordable child care, health care,
and further education for low-income wage earners takes a backseat
to calls for an income-tax rate cut designed to benefit more
affluent voters.
</P>
<P>
   The general election cycle completes its turn in five short
weeks, though the Commonwealth's voters seem to have barely
registered the fact that there is a gubernatorial campaign.
</P>
<P>
   We can spend the next several weeks debating the emotional, the
marginal, and the polarizing. We can trash our teachers, clamor for
capital punishment, demand a tax-refund check. Or we ask some
tougher questions about where we are and where we are headed in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Who is going to re-train the semiconductor industry's laid-off
workforce now that the international demand for computer-chip
equipment has slowed because of the Asian financial crisis?
</P>
<P>
   How are we going to address the housing needs of working
families who find themselves priced out of the market in one
community after another?
</P>
<P>
   Where are laid-off manufacturing workers going to find jobs with
comparable salaries in an economy with a surplus of minimum-wage
work for salesclerks and waiters?
</P>
<P>
   What kind of economic-development planning is being done to
ensure that entry-level workers, whether welfare mothers or high
school graduates, acquire the necessary skills to share in good
economic times?
</P>
<P>
   Sometime before Nov. 3, do tell us, Governor Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
