<SLUG> BC-MONICA-MONIKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOUR NAME IS MONICA, YOU ARE NOT AMUSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Until now, it was such an obscure name in America.
Quick: Name another famous stateside Monica. Monica Seles, the
tennis player, is from Yugoslavia. The late Monica Dickens, the
novelist, was English. St. Monica, the mother of St. Augustine,
lived in North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an uncommon name and I was always very proud of it,''
says Monica Kearney, a 44-year-old administrator. ``The reaction of
other people was usually `Oh, that's an unusual name. How
lovely.'''
</P>
<P>
   And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Kearney replies darkly, ``it's trash.''
</P>
<P>
   These are indeed unsettling times for many women with the Monica
moniker. Monica Veneziano, a mind-body therapist, drives into an
auto body shop and the proprietor declares loudly, ``Hey, you've
got that name!'' Monica Megivern, a psychologist, orders groceries
and the clerk offers sympathy because Megivern has ``that terrible
bad girl's name.'' And Monica Constantini, a preschool teacher,
asks for a friend on the phone and hears the wise guy on the other
end announce that ``it's Miss Lewinsky on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks are even making remarks to 82-year-old Monica Piacentini.
``They'll say something like `Oh, are you related to her, dear?''
laments Piacentini, who was named for her grandmother. ``Then
they'll laugh. It used to be it was a name you never heard of,
because they're weren't many Monicas. Now there's one too many.''
</P>
<P>
   One non-Monica is so outraged by what she calls ``the pangs and
arrows of outrageous fortune'' that have befallen these ``innocent
good women'' that she has formed a support group for them. L. Mandy
Stellman, along with another Milwaukee attorney, Alan Eisenberg,
has founded Monicas With Attitude to help resurrect what the pair
feels is a good name gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard from maybe 100 Monicas around the country, and an
overwhelming number want to participate in whatever we do,'' says
Eisenberg, who describes himself as a lawyer, real estate broker,
author, and radio broadcaster (as well as a former comedian and
nightclub singer). ``People are making jokes about Monica
(Lewinsky), but I don't hear other Monicas laughing. It's a form of
woman bashing, and it's got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   And the thing is, as Monica McDermott points out, Monica was
just beginning to come into its own as a name. McDermott cites the
fact that two current television shows, ``Friends'' and ``Touched
by an Angel,'' have lead characters named Monica. (Meanwhile a
17-year-old singer named just plain Monica _ like just plain
Madonna and just plain Cher _ has a hit album.) ``The name was
starting to become more popular, like a trend,'' says McDermott,
who is a goldsmith. ``Now, I'm not so sure. But maybe any kind of
publicity is better than no publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   That's definitely not the opinion of Monica Armstrong, an
engineering administrator. Armstrong declares herself annoyed both
by the sudden infamy of her given name as well as by the kind of
low-level humor that accompanies its mention these days. ``It's
nothing graphic,'' she says of comments she has to endure. ``Mostly
it's little side remarks, or men who want to tell me the latest
Monica joke that's a shade off-color.''
</P>
<P>
   Most comments indeed seem to be harmless, if a little dopey.
``They usually come from older men, and they're usally
`nudge-nudge' types of things,'' explains Monica Parker, a
29-year-old public relations consultant. ``It's usually `Hey, it
must be kinda hard to have that name, eh?' Nudge-nudge. But the
husband of a woman I work with did make up a nasty little rhyme:
`Monica, Monica, come play my harmonica.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Monicas, however, think Monica Lewinsky has done them
wrong. ``I like the attention,'' says Monica McClaren, a substance
abuse counselor. ``People might make little jokes about sex, you
know, but I don't mind. In fact, I think this is definitely the
year of the Monica. I think lots of people will be naming their
daughters Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   That will be the test, of course. Check in with your local
kindergarten in five years to see if there are many _ or any _
little Monicas running around the room. ``My own feeling is that
people won't be naming their daughters Monica for a while,'' says
Monica Graham, a social worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not many ever did,'' adds this particular Monica.
</P>
</TEXT>
