<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE CIVILITY? ACTUALLY, WE NEED LESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has become commonplace to bemoan the lack of civility in our
society. Congress, hilariously, convened a retreat on the subject.
A wealthy New England family has coughed up $35 million to endow
The Institute for a Civil Society, in darkest Newton. I attended a
lecture by the Institute's president a few months ago. She wanted
us all to get along. She sounded very sincere.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem with modern society is that there's too much
goddamned civility. And the worst culprit is the lily-livered,
libel-fearing, invective-free press. Where are the thunderers of
grand, denunciatory prose, like H.L. Mencken? What pre-millennial
scribbler could even clip the quill of today's column subject, the
greatest newspaperman who ever lived _ Ambrose Bierce?
</P>
<P>
   When did I first fall in love with Bierce? Probably under the
pen of the great Carey McWilliams, whose 1967 biography of the San
Francisco calumnist, sorry, columnist is periodically re-issued. I
fell in love again while unwinding at Stanford University two years
ago. Perusing a monograph of the university's founder, the robber
baron/railroad magnate Leland Stanford, I learned that Bierce
routinely vilified him in the San Francisco press as ``$tealin'
Landford.'' How apt. How naughty. How Bierce.
</P>
<P>
   Although more than eager to air out his enemies' dirty laundry,
Bierce guarded his own privacy and left no autobiography. Now,
David Schultz and S.T. Joshi have arranged fragments of Bierce's
writings into an autobiographical narrative. I am borrowing wildly
from their new book, ``Ambrose Bierce: A Sole Survivor,'' just
published by the University of Tennessee Press.
</P>
<P>
   There are simply too many reasons to love Bierce. A prolific and
brilliant newspaper writer, he also compiled the magnificent
``Devil's Dictionary.'' (Sample definition: ``Saint; a dead sinner,
revised and edited.'') Bierce was also a successful short story
writer and cold-eyed chronicler of the horrors of the Civil War.
His famous, chilling report, ``What I Saw of Shiloh,'' anticipates
Hemingway, Robert Graves, Paul Fussell and even ``Saving Private
Ryan.'' Bierce's most recent biographer Roy Morris Jr. calls it
``the working prototype of all modern war literature, at least as
seen by Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bierce loved to inveigh. He loathed California's ``rail
rogues,'' and after hectoring Stanford to his grave, Bierce started
in on his partner, Collis P. Huntington. Dispatched by Harvard
dropout William Randolph Hearst to Washington, Bierce led a
battalion of Hearst writers, photographers and cartoonists on a
campaign ``of unremitting ad hominem assaults on Huntington,''
according to Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Huntington had journeyed to the nation's capital to seek
Congress's forgiveness of his railroad's $75 million debt. Once
Bierce's broadsides started to sting, the railroader offered to buy
him off, noting sardonically that ``every man has his price.'' ``My
price is $75 million,'' Bierce retorted. ``You may hand it over to
my friend, the Treasurer of the United States.'' No Archer Daniels
Midland endorsements for my man Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mencken, Bierce despised Boston (``the anus of America,''
quoth the Sage of Baltimore). A wounded Civil War hero and veteran
of its bloodiest campaigns, Bierce reviled Boston's literary
tastemakers as pasty-faced parlor pansies who sat out the defining
conflagration of their time. He derided Atlantic Monthly editor
William Dean Howells and Henry James as ``Miss Nancy Howells and
Miss Nancy James ... two eminent triflers and cameo-cutters in
chief to Her Littleness the Bostonese small virgin.''
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason, Bierce was jealous and dismissive of
Stephen Crane, hailed as the definitive interpreter of a war that
ended before his birth. Likewise, he never had much use for the
non-combatant Mark Twain. (Like Howells, Twain admired Bierce.) He
joined Twain, Winston Churchill, and my friend John Spooner in the
ranks of writers who reviewed their own books, under a pseudonym _
but with a twist. Bierce trashed his own book as ``a high-handed
outrage, a criminal assault upon public modesty, an indecent
exposure of the author's mind.'' (!)
</P>
<P>
   It is said that if you stand at the river bank long enough, you
will have the satisfaction of seeing your enemies' corpses float
by. Such moments afforded much ghoulish satisfaction for the
contentious Bierce. He came to despise his longtime publisher,
Frank Pixley, who committed two cardinal, Bierce-ian sins. Pixley
lied about his Civil War record, and he owed the writer money. When
Pixley died, Bierce dispatched him with the shortest, nastiest
obituary on record: ``Here lies Frank Pixley _ as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Come back, Ambrose. We need you, now more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
