<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCE-PILOTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE OFFICIAL WARNS OF CRITICAL PILOT SHORTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Air Force faces a serious shortage of
experienced pilots, and it may take a decade to correct the
problem, a top defense planner said.
</P>
<P>
   Only one in four Air Force pilots have taken lucrative bonuses
to stay in the service. At this time last year the Air Force had
just 48 fewer pilots than needed. That number has now grown to at
least 700.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated overseas tours and the allure of high-paying jobs at
commercial airlines are most often blamed for the shortage. The
shortage could grow to nearly 2,000 pilots by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say we're going to a situation that is four times worse
than we've ever seen in the history of our modern Air Force,'' said
Col. Jim Green, director of assignments at the personnel center at
Randolph Air Force Base near San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Green said the pilot shortage is ``serious. It's real serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after the Joint Chiefs of Staff told the Senate Armed
Services Committee Tuesday that the military services face critical
personnel shortages and budget problems, Green laid out a grim
scenario for the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   The service expects to lose 1,951 pilots by 2002, reducing its
strength to about 11,000 fliers. More than a third of those leaving
will be fighter pilots, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Air Force will train 900 active-duty pilots this
year, 1,025 next year and 1,100 into the next century, the new
fliers will have less experience than those quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Retention rates for enlisted personnel, who make up 80 percent
of the Air Force, also have slipped. Green said ``they're at the
caution-light level right now, not at the red-light level.''
</P>
<P>
   Green stressed national security will not be jeopardized by the
loss of veteran pilots such as aircraft commanders and flight
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   A typical Air Force squadron has 18 fighters and 25 pilots.
Though full squadrons will continue to fly, he said, they may not
be staffed at 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been mandated to keep the cockpits full and we've been
successful doing it. But what we're worried about is being able to
continue doing that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running out of bodies,'' he added. ``Something's going
to have to give.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives such as Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, have
called for an infusion of military spending to reverse the nation's
readiness problems. Speaking Tuesday after Senate passage of a
$250.5 billion defense appropriations measure, she said: ``I remain
very concerned about the overall state of readiness of our military
forces, and this bill does little to address the problem
directly.''
</P>
<P>
   While top Pentagon leaders have called for boosting the
Pentagon's budget by as much as $15 billion in the new fiscal year,
the Air Force faces a different numbers game.
</P>
<P>
   The service can neither produce enough new pilots nor convince
its veterans, most of whom have eight to nine years' experience, to
stay in uniform through their 14th year of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see us getting healthy again until the 2010 time
frame, and maybe not even then,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   To entice aviators to remain in the service, the Air Force has
reduced the amount of time pilots are temporarily deployed overseas
and boosted bonuses to $110,000 over five years. But the Air Force
is still seeing its best cockpit commanders bail out.
</P>
<P>
   Many are leaving for the chance to cash in on the commercial
airline industry, where there is a major demand for experienced
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Green considers airline hiring the major factor in the loss of
Air Force pilots, but conceded that a four-fold rise in overseas
deployments also was playing a role.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
