<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO HEALTH OFFICIAL BACKS WHITE HOUSE POLICY ON
METHADONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A San Francisco health official welcomed a new
White House initiative to expand methadone treatment for heroin
addiction, saying it is in line with the city's own goals.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the city Board of Supervisors passed a resolution
asking the federal government for a waiver so that doctors, with
training, could prescribe the synthetic narcotic designed to reduce
the craving for heroin. Currently, strict regulations prevent
anyone but specially-licensed clinics from dispensing it.
</P>
<P>
   Barry McCaffrey, the White House drug policy director, said
Tuesday there are plans to begin training programs for physicians
to become accredited to prescribe methadone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an area where there are too many regulations,'' said
Barbara A. Garcia, director of community substance abuse services
for the San Francisco Department of Public Health. ``This puts us
in a very, very opportune situation in terms of our ability, on a
local level, to push this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   About 1,800 people are being served at five methadone clinics in
the city, each governed by a complex web of state and federal
regulations. Another 415 are on a waiting list for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   More people will choose methadone, Garcia said, if they know
they can get it confidentially through their own doctor. It could
also lead to better medical care for conditions that often crop up
in injection drug users, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Garcia anticipates it will be at least a year and maybe
longer before regulations can be rewritten on both a state and
federal level to make methadone access easier.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the National Institutes of Health issued as
sharply-worded report saying the nation's heroin addiction policies
are outdated and that plenty of evidence exists that methadone
works well.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment remains controversial, however. New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani has said it only swaps one addiction for another
and announced a plan in that city to get users to quit. A few
states have no methadone clinics at all.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly cost for treatment is usually about $3,400 a year
per person and involves frequent visits to the clinics. Medi-Cal,
California's health insurance for the poor, pays for its members to
receive methadone, but some people pay for it themselves, Garcia
said. She said they are able to do that because methadone
stabilizes addicts and allows them to retain jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, San Francisco intends to provide treatment,
including methadone, on demand for all addicts. That goal remains
years away, Garcia said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
