<HEADLINE>
POLLUTION FLOWS AT US-MEXICO BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i, a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN AGUSTIN, Mexico _ Some &UR;  &LR; nights the stench of sewage and
chemicals from the canal running through this dusty border town is
so nauseating that Manuel Robles and his family cannot sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see all kinds of dead fish in there,'' Robles, 57, a
teacher-turned-environmental activist, said of the leather-colored
water that flows swiftly from the factories and neighborhoods of
Ciudad Juarez, about 15 miles away. ``Government people come here
and talk about cleaning it up. But it's still here, where everybody
can smell it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of environmental problem that government
officials in Washington and Mexico City promised to address five
years ago when they were promoting the idea of a North American
Free Trade Agreement among Mexico, Canada, and the United States.
To prove their commitment to clean up the border, negotiators
signed a separate environmental agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But along this stretch of the Rio Grande and through most of the
2,000-mile US-Mexico border, it is hard to find much improvement.
Instead, several residents, activists, and government specialists
acknowledge that in many ways the border is worse off today than it
was before NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, I'd say the promises made for cleaning up the area
have not been fulfilled, and one area that has really suffered has
been the area around Juarez,'' said Richard Boren, 41, coordinator
of the Southwest Toxic Watch, an environmental group based in El
Paso.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt NAFTA has brought more economic activity to
Mexico, even from faraway places like Massachusetts. Last year Bay
State exports to this country rose to more than $440 million, up 33
percent since 1993, the year before NAFTA went into effect,
according to a report prepared by the Washington-based Trade
Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious sign of the new business wave is among the new
factories owned by or performing work for US corporations. Known by
their Spanish name, ``maquiladoras,'' these factories benefit from
cheaper labor costs and provide jobs for thousands of Mexican
citizens. Although these ``twin plants'' existed long before NAFTA,
their popularity with multinational corporations has spawned
hundreds of facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But their explosive growth, along with the arrival of thousands
of new immigrants to the border region looking for jobs, has hurt
an environment that was, by most assessments, damaged before NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA proponents argued that the agreement would encourage more
companies to build these assembly plants in Mexico's interior. But
largely because of its proximity to the United States, where the
finished products are sent, the border has absorbed most of the new
maquiladora construction.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,000-mile border area holds about two-thirds of Mexico's
4,010 maquiladoras, according to figures from the country's
commerce and industrial agency. The remaining third are in interior
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Ciudad Juarez, for example, is Mexico's fourth-largest city with
a population of about 2 million people and sits adjacent El Paso,
Texas. The city is home to about a quarter of Mexico's
NAFTA-related factories, but it still does not have a water and
sewage treatment system.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the city's raw sewage and runoff from the factories flow
into six open canals. It is believed another 50 million gallons of
untreated waste is dumped every &UR;  &LR; day into the Rio Grande.
Government officials say plans for a new treatment plant
were &UR;  &LR; approved four years ago, but were postponed because of the
economic crisis that hit the country in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A design for a $30 million plant has just been approved. But one
local government administrator, mindful that the Mexican peso again
has shown signs of volatility, wonders whether history might repeat
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a tragedy if we have to cut the budget again and
stop this project,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``We're at the mercy of our peso, but I don't know how
much longer people can wait for clean water.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics also said the two agencies created by NAFTA to develop
more binational cleanup projects have done little to help. The
Border Environment Cooperation Commission, which is headquartered
in Juarez, Mexico, has been slow to approve initiatives. Meanwhile,
the Texas-based North American Development Bank, which is run by
Treasury officials of both nations, has been hamstrung by internal
dissension.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at both agencies insist that more cleanup projects
are on the way. Eleven environmental initiatives totaling $3
billion _ most of them for waste and water treatment _ have secured
financing or are already under construction, according to NADBank
documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand people's desires to see things done quickly, but
we'd rather see projects that are planned and built carefully,''
said Linda Taylor, a New Mexico environmentalist and member of the
BECC board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'd say the border environment has worsened,
especially with the maquiladoras, but I think there'll be
improvement in the future,'' she added, referring to 23 projects
the commission has certified.
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA supporters also said tougher environmental laws that took
effect with the agreement have helped improve some border
communities. In Matamoros, a Mexican town across the bridge from
Brownsville, Texas, an area once dubbed ``Chemical Row'' has
improved gradually.
</P>
<P>
   Amid growing outrage from activists and community leaders, the
area's worst polluters were driven out and many remaining companies
have installed their own treatment systems. Even some of the newer
factories in Juarez have new recycling programs and are teaching
employees better ways to dispose of waste.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the problems along this corner of the border appear to
outnumber the solutions. There is the electrical substation outside
El Porvenir, Mexico, where drums of toxic fluids and old
transformers sit unwatched near a residential neighborhood. There
is the landfill in Sunland Park, N.M., only a few miles from the
border, where residents say dumping goes unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the danger, many residents say, that this part of
the border is drawing more waste rather than eliminating it.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Blanca, Texas, a sleepy town of 700 residents that lies
in a desert valley 80 miles east of El Paso, is home to the
nation's largest sludge dump. About 250 tons of waste arrive almost
daily by train, much of it from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the area's dry terrain, Texas has also proposed a
low-level radioactive waste site 5 miles away, 15 miles from the
Mexican border. The waste would come from Texas, Vermont, and
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the planned waste site say the dump will not harm
the environment. But opponents say the site lies near an earthquake
fault line and that its presence would reinforce the idea that
poorer and mostly Hispanic border residents can be exposed to such
a risk.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal has drawn together an unusual alliance of Mexican
and US residents in opposition to the project, which has been
approved by Congress and is awaiting final word from President
Clinton and the Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Natural Resources Conservation Commission will make
its final decision on the waste dump on Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Mexican government officials had offered only
minor resistance to the proposal. But earlier this month, Mexico's
environmental secretary, Julia Carabias, asked US officials to
reconsider the site's location.
</P>
<P>
   That is little comfort to Robles, the environmental activist,
who still runs San Agustin's only library and museum, even though
his government pay was cut off in February. He believes the act was
in retaliation by local government officials angry with his work
with the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole area is like one human body,'' Robles said while
moving along the foul-smelling canal. ``The parts of this body are
getting sicker. And unless something happens soon, the whole
beautiful body will suffer terribly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
