<HEADLINE>
THE WORK OF `60 MINUTES'; A WORKDAY OFF, FOR VOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spawn of ``60 Minutes'' is all across the prime-time
landscape this season, with one TV newsmagazine after another
popping up on the tube. In that context, a piece in the October
issue of Brill's Content should open some eyes by revealing how
many showbiz values surround even the best broadcast journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Lando, who left ``60 Minutes'' in 1997 after working there
for 27 years as a producer, crosses swords in Content with Don
Hewitt, executive producer of the venerable CBS newsmagazine. It
gets nasty and personal, with charges of breach of duty and
who-makes-how-much flying around, but it begins on a matter of
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Lando argues that ``60 Minutes'' employs the same ``devious
system'' as the one that blew up in CNN's face last summer with
``Tailwind'': namely, using famous correspondents as window
dressing on stories that are largely discovered, reported, and
written by producers. ``You'd think that the show that prides
itself on revealing hypocrisy and cant, on uncovering deceptions,
would be all for truth in packaging when it comes to itself,''
Lando writes. ``It's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the fabled ``60 Minutes'' interviews ``are often pure
shadow play,'' Lando writes, with correspondents feigning shock at
revelations about which they have already been briefed by
producers. Lando calls on ``60 Minutes'' to explicitly acknowledge
_ on the air _ the ``key reporting role'' played by producers and
associate producers.
</P>
<P>
   Don Hewitt talks back in Content, with his usual gusto. In
between some personal shots at Lando, Hewitt points out that ``60
Minutes'' correspondent Mike Wallace fully detailed the role
producers play in his book ``Close Encounters'' 13 years ago, and
notes that ``60 Minutes'' was the first broadcast to credit
producers at the beginning of each story rather than the end.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it's hard to disagree with Lando's overall point,
which is that ``60 Minutes'' _ and other TV newsmagazines _ are
happy to leave the impression that all those hard-hitting exposes
are the work of their million-dollar correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On primary day, after a long day at work, I headed directly to
my local polling place, only to arrive just seconds after the polls
had closed.
</P>
<P>
   My own fault, of course. I shouldn't have waited till the last
minute to vote, one of the solemn duties of citizenship. But, as
happens to a lot of us these days, life got in the way. Anyway, the
experience left me receptive to Martin P. Wattenberg's modest
proposal _ advanced in the October Atlantic Monthly _ that election
day be made a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
   In giving people more time to vote, Wattenberg writes, ``This
would send a strong signal about the importance our country
attaches to voting.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, his proposal seems radical, and might be seen as just
giving apathetic nonvoters another day off. But nothing else seems
to be stemming the trend toward abysmally low turnout in American
elections. Even after the much-ballyhooed ``motor voter'' law went
into effect in 1993, Wattenberg points out, turnout for the 1996
presidential election fell below 50 percent for the first time
since the 1920s. Between one-third and one-half of eligible voters
cast ballots in congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   And given the way Generation X seems to have tuned out politics,
the future seems even grimmer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In India, bribes are called ``efficiency money.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just one of the piquant details in Edward Hoagland's
story in the October Outside of his trip to Arunachal Pradesh, a
remote, roadless, and politically charged region of India that is
home to a variety of hill tribes.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye both poetic and comprehensive, Hoagland takes the
reader across the creaky bridges and washed-out mountain roads and
into the villages of Arunachal Pradesh. Hoagland describes with
matter-of-fact respect the indigenous people he meets, some of
whose customs and garments may seem outlandish to Westerners.
</P>
<P>
   Hoagland has always been one of those writers who can stop a
reader in his tracks with bravura prose, and those gifts are on
display again here: the mountains are ``molor and uninviting, the
weather lawless,'' rivers have ``carved giddy, green, orchestral
valleys,'' his ``wristwatch-and-monotheistic rigidity'' is relaxed
in the presence of ``people who live by the sun, stars and
fire-flicker from birth to a quiet grave.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Gamson discerns something a tad hypocritical, or at least
contradictory, in our reaction to ``The Truman Show,'' the Jim
Carrey movie about a man whose life, unknown to him, is a
television show.
</P>
<P>
   The film has been acclaimed for dramatizing the extent to which
our privacy has been invaded by the media culture, Big Brother, et.
al. Yet in a shrewdly observant essay in the November-December
issue of The American Prospect (available Monday on newsstands),
Gamson points out that nowadays, ``there are more than enough
people willing to invade their own `privacy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He cites such spectacles as the woman who gave birth on the
Internet last summer, along with the growth in ``reality
television'' fare like MTV's ``Real World,'' HBO's ``Taxicab
Confessions,'' ``America's Funniest Home Videos,'' and ``The Jerry
Springer Show.'' These shows, Gamson writes, succeed because we
live in a culture that ``rewards the looked-at.''
</P>
<P>
   The casualty of this obsession is not a minor one: ``a life you
recognize as authentically your own because it is not there for the
entertainment of others.''
</P>
</TEXT>
