<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2045 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOM-TRIATHLON-ART-BOS     09-30 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-TRIATHLON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHERINE JONES GETS A BELATED SHOT AT THE IRONMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Includes Triathlon facts text table.   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, Mass. _ Cathy Jones had mixed emotions when she
learned in May 1997 that she was pregnant. Of course she was
ecstatic, but the news put a damper on her dream to finally run in
the Ironman Triathlon in Kona, Hawaii, that fall. Skill was with
her when she had finished a triathlon to qualify, then luck was
with her when her name was picked as a winner in the 3,000-person
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   But that was two weeks before Jones, a doctor with the Wachusett
Emergency Physicians Group, got the news of her pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, out of indecision or denial, she kept riding, biking, and
swimming all summer until finally, just before the deadline last
August, she admitted to herself and to the race organizers that she
couldn't compete after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been 28 weeks pregnant,'' said Jones, who asked
if she could defer her entry for a year but was told she had to try
again.
</P>
<P>
   Fate was with her again. When Jones threw her name in the
lottery this year, she was chosen again. Her husband, Eric Dickson,
on the other hand, has tried to beat the odds for three years with
no success _ only 150 are chosen from the 3,000 hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   So on Saturday, Jones, 35, will compete in the 20th edition of
the Ironman race that starts at 7 a.m. and includes a 2.4-mile
ocean swim, a 112-mile bike ride, and a 26.2-mile run. Eric and son
Killian _ now seven months old _ will be watching and pulling for
Mom to finish under the 17-hour limit.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Jones will not be a newcomer to the race in Hawaii.
She was there three years ago, not competing, but working the
medical tent. She tended to athletes whose bodies had trouble
withstanding grueling events back to back to back, in 90 degree
heat over tar-topped roads. The tent is situated where the bikes
are set up, which is also the finish of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being depressed or horrified by the collapsing bodies
she saw that day, Jones was invigorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very exciting place,'' she said. ``There's a lot of
energy and enthusiasm in the air there, and great people. Most of
the athletes were dehydrated and needed IVs, and then got back in
the race.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where it's necessary to know two things about Jones: As
an emergency-room physician, she's no stranger to trauma, and as a
former college record-holder in swimming, she's no stranger to
competition. Athletics and medicine have been constant themes in
her life.
</P>
<P>
   Jones grew up in Framingham and was on the swimming team at
Framingham North high school. Then at the University of New
Hampshire, she continued swimming and set school records (since
broken) in the 1,000 freestyle and 1,650 freestyle. She also
started running to keep in shape during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1985, Jones worked in the ultrasound lab at
the Lahey Clinic for four years before entering the University of
Massachusetts Medical School in Worcester. But she didn't take a
break from competing.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's running had escalated to the marathon level (she has
competed in nine Boston Marathons and in the Falmouth Marathon).
She also kept up her swimming, competing in the Boston Harbor Light
and Vineyard Sound swims and ``a couple of open-water marathon
swims.''
</P>
<P>
   She decided about 10 years ago to combine her athletic skills
and start competing in triathlons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started seriously thinking about the Hawaii Ironman about
five or six years ago,'' Jones said. ``I really wanted to do this,
but it always seemed kind of distant.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when she was on a medical rotation in Hawaii,
the prospect seemed a little closer. She was on Oahu, and went to
Kona on the big island of Hawaii to volunteer at the medical tent
on race day.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 race doctors are scheduled to work for a few hours
apiece, but Jones liked it so much, she said, that she ``stayed for
the whole thing, and we finished around 2 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a busy day, but I love medicine, so it was kind of neat
to combine two things I really like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Jones competed in two triathlons that are
about half the length of the Ironman. She ran one in Lancaster,
where she finished fourth in her 35-39 age group, and one in
Medford.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jones got the word last spring that she'll be one of the
1,500 in Saturday's race, she has been juggling training and
competing with being a mother and working eight-hour shifts that
can start at 7 a.m. or 11 p.m. for a week at a time. As a member of
the Wachusett Emergency Physicians Group, Jones works at either
Leominster Hospital or Burbank Hospital in Fitchburg.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's strongest segment of the triathon is the swim but she
has had to sacrifice some of that training for the sake of Killian.
She has forgone open-water swims in favor of laps at the local
YMCA, where she swims in the pool for an hour while Killian is at
the club's day-care facility.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other sports, she said, ``I run when I can and bike
when I can, and I try and do a fair amount of running when I'm
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   So after she finishea a 40-mile bike ride, Jones might go out
for a 5-mile run as she tries to get used to the transitions
athletes must make in a triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   She runs with Killian in front of her in a jogging stroller if
it's a short run _ ``40 minutes or less'' _ and by herself on the
roads of Princeton if it's longer. Training in the rolling hills
near her house in the shadow of Wachusett Mountain should be an
advantage when she gets to Hawaii, she figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The terrain in Kona is not as steep as it is around here,''
she said, adding that the hills aren't her main concern. ``The
biggest thing about the marathon is, it's hot. The pavement is
black tar _ it's hot.''
</P>
<P>
   The biking, she said, will be the hardest leg for her,
especially since she took up the sport only so she could do
triathlons.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good ride for me is about 40 miles,'' she said. ``And I've
done longer rides, but I don't routinely do 100 miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, she said, triathlon biking is a lot different than bike
racing, because while you are surrounded by other cyclists, you
have to ride individually, as you would in a time trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's illegal to ride in a pack, and there is no drafting, no
teammates,'' Jones said. ``So it really is a different sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the training Jones has been doing _ running on the
hills, riding in the heat, and swimming in the pool _ she is aware
that a large part of the Ironman is enduring the psychological
test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any race that's 14 hours long, a significant part of it is
mental,'' she said. ``But first off, I'm hoping to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   And she remains upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' she said. ``It's a
once-in-a-lifetime experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, she hopes to stay away from the place where she first
witnessed the Ironman:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to avoid the medical tent.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ironman Triathon facts &QL; 
 &QL; 
--What: 2.4-mile ocean swim, 112-mile bicycle race, 26.2-mile run. &QL; 
--When: Saturday, Oct. 3, 7 a.m. &QL; 
--Where: Kailua-Kona, Hawaii. &QL; 
--Who: A field of 1,500, including competitors from 50 states and
50 countries, will compete in the 20th edition of the race. &QL; 
--Local competitors: In addition to Princeton's Cathy Jones, some
of the 19 athletes from Massachusetts include: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Martha Sorensen, 32, of West Chesterfield, the seventh female
finisher last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Dave McGillivray, 44, of Middleton, technical director of the
Boston Marathon who will be running his 10th Ironman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Michael Sullivan, 40, of East Bridgewater, a mounted bike
officer with the Brockton police. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Leon Okurowski, 55, of Lincoln, who is using his participation
to raise funds for the Joslin Diabetes Center. &QL; 
--Miscellany: Race was founded by John Collins, who proposed a
combination of three Hawaiian races to settle a debate he was
having with friends about which sport had the most fit athletes.
The winner, Collins decided, would be called the ``Ironman.''
Fifteen competitors started the first race; Collins and 11 others
finished ... Total purse is $250,000; the first male and female
finishers receive $35,000 ... Men's record is held by Luc Van
Lierde, with a time of 8 hours, 4 minutes, 8 seconds in 1996 ...
Women's record is held by Paula Newby-Fraser, 8:55:28 in 1992 ...
Average temperature for the race ranges between 82 and 95 degrees.
Humidity hovers around 90 percent, and crosswinds on bike course
can gust as high as 60 miles per hour. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
