<HEADLINE>
BLEAK PROFIT PICTURE LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any experienced investor will tell you that interest rates and
company earnings are the real forces behind stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   You got the Federal Reserve's tepid good news on rates Tuesday.
Now get ready for a bleaker profit picture.
</P>
<P>
   Companies nationwide are preparing to report earnings for the
quarter ending Wednesday, and the forecasts are not encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a survey of Massachusetts' 100 largest public
companies, based on stock brokerage forecasts tracked by First Call
Corp. of Boston, found about 40 percent were expected to report
lower profits or greater losses than those recorded in the same
quarter in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A similar pattern is taking place among the country's leading
companies that make up the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, according
to First Call. As a group, they are forecast to report earnings 1
percent lower than year-ago profits, the first such decline
recorded since the recession of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The forecasts of brokerage analysts collected by First Call
usually measure the results of continuing operations and do not
include one-time gains and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had forecast a third-quarter earnings increase of 10
percent at the beginning of July, but have been cutting predictions
ever since. Their consensus forecast for the fourth quarter still
calls for an unrealistic 9.5 percent earnings increase, according
to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as analysts are going to have to substantially reduce
short-term estimates, it's going to keep pressure on the market,''
said Charles Hill, director of research at First Call. ``It's hard
to see the market going up when estimates are going to have to be
cut to the degree we expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Actual third-quarter earnings reports will be issued over the
next three or four weeks. Usually the worst news comes out early,
in the style of Gillette Co.'s third-quarter warning Monday.
Analysts cut their consensus forecast Gillette earnings for the
quarter by 10 cents per share Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Bay State firms are expected to report strong
earnings growth, including Biogen Inc., the Cambridge-based
biotechnology company; Keane Inc. of Boston, a software services
firm; and Carematrix Corp., the Needham-based owner of senior
living services.
</P>
<P>
   But more are expected to report significantly lower
third-quarter profits. Teradyne Inc. of Boston, which makes
semiconductor test equipment, is forecast to earn less than half
its profits of the third quarter of 1997. PRI Automation Inc. of
Billerica, which also serves the semiconductor industry, is
predicted to lose money in the quarter, off from a healthy year-ago
quarterly profit.
</P>
<P>
   Many other technology firms are in the same boat. Millipore
Corp., Data General Corp., and Analog Devices Inc. are part of a
larger group of Massachusetts technology companies with lower
earnings forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The declining profit predictions are hardly limited to the tech
sector. Companies in a variety of industries such as Reebok
International Ltd., New England Electric System, and Stone &AMP;
Webster Inc. are all expected to earn less money.
</P>
<P>
   Many US firms are struggling with an inability to raise prices
while some costs, particularly payroll expenses, rise. By some
accounts, that spells more trouble ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before our very eyes, we are entering into a profits recession
that will last as long or longer than a traditional recession,''
said Edward G. Riley, chief investment officer at BankBoston Corp.
``That means corporate earnings will decline for at least two
consecutive quarters, if not three or four.'' Another opinion: The
news is bad but most of the pain has already been inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   John Ballen, president of MFS Investment Management, points to
Gillette as an example. Gillette shares only fell by about 6
percent Tuesday, after the market had digested bad news from the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Investors never really believed Wall Street forecasts about
Gillette and had already knocked the stock down by about 40 percent
from its peak, Ballen said.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news already has been figured into the price of many other
stocks besides Gillette, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the stock market relative to interest rates,
it's projecting low single-digit earnings growth next year, much
less than Wall Street estimates,'' Ballen said.
</P>
<P>
   Much, much less. The First Call survey of analysts calls for
corporate profit growth of 14.3 percent in the first quarter of
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outrageously high,'' said Hill. And sure to come down in the
months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
