<HEADLINE>
HIXON OPTS OFF US FIELD HOCKEY TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a surprising move, 1996 Olympics coach Pam Hixon has resigned
as coach of the US women's national field hockey team, citing
philosophical differences with the sport's governing body.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not see eye to eye,'' said Hixon, who as coach at the
University of Massachusetts before accepting the national-team post
led the Minutewomen to 13 consecutive postseason appearances.
``They were totally results-oriented. I have a different philosophy
in terms of development, which means you don't always get
results.''
</P>
<P>
   A parting of the ways, the Framingham, Mass. native said
Tuesday, was best for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The issue apparently heated up after the US, coming off a bronze
medal in the 1994 World Cup and a fifth-place finish in the 1996
Olympics, finished eighth out of 12 teams in May's 1998 World Cup.
By several accounts, the governing body expected better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Following the World Cup, I think it was time to make some hard
decisions,'' said Hixon, who lost the core of her team to
retirement after Atlanta. ``I thought the team did fine. Would we
have liked to have done better? Absolutely. But I know we were
competitive with the teams we should have been competitive with.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory at next summer's Pan American Games would
automatically send the US team to the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, and
Hixon remains optimistic. ``I think the team is in position to win
the Pan Ams,'' she said. ``The young talent is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Since resigning in late July, Hixon has been concentrating on
her White Mountain Sports Camp, which offers developmental programs
and clinics in field hockey. Based in Amherst, Hixon recently
opened a second office in the Washington, D.C., area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely happy,'' said the 1973 graduate of Springfield
College. ``Doors are opening every day.'' Hixon said she may also
do some consulting and TV commentary as well as expand the camps to
include other sports, such as lacrosse and golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Field hockey has been so great to me, to keep that going and
continue to give something back to the sport is important, but
other things in sport are attractive to me to explore, as well,''
said Hixon.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued by the United States Field Hockey
Association, executive director Jane Betts said: ``We certainly
thank Coach Hixon for all her efforts and wish her only the best as
she moves on to handle her developing business interests.'' A
worldwide search is under way for her replacement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Freeman-Young victorious
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Freeman-Young, of Newton, Mass., has returned
victorious from England, where her team of four Americans won the
Young Cup in tennis. The women, all in the over-40 division,
defeated teams from Canada, Australia, and South Africa on their
way to winning the Cup. The captain of the team was Peggy Michel
Michel, a former doubles' champion at Wimbledon. Also competing in
England was Lillian Peltz Pito from Revere, who played with a team
in the over 45-division for the Margaret Court Cup ... The New
England Blizzard has signed Michelle Campbell as a replacement
player until Kara Wolters returns to the lineup. Campbell, a
graduate of the University of Southern California, played with the
Philadelphia Rage last season. Wolters, who underwent shoulder last
July, is expected to return to practice fulltime by late October.
The Blizzard's first game is Nov. 5 ... The Female Athlete Inc., a
catalog company, is now on the web at www.thefemaleathlete.com ...
Salve Regina University in Newport, R.I., will add women's ice
hockey as a varsity sport in 1999, and is seeking a head coach ...
A traveling mural in honor of the Ivy League's silver anniversary
celebration of women's sports will be on display at Harvard's Murr
Center through Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe staff writer Susan Bickelhaupt also contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
