<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CRANBERRIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM FINDS NICHE IN MAPPING DATA FOR CRANBERRY GROWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Ore., Wash, Wis., Mich., British Columbia)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAREHAM, Mass._ A part of the Massachusetts landscape since
Colonial times, the business of growing cranberries has in some
ways changed very little since then. But a collaboration between a
cranberry grower and a software consultant is changing that.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, when Deborah Burke Beaton first met her husband,
Peter, she was amazed how he carried much of what he knew about his
crops in his head.
</P>
<P>
   Jammed into his brain were all the types of berries that grow on
each of more than 40 properties he owns or manages in nine
southeastern Massachusetts towns, the fertilizers and pest-control
agents that have to be applied to each bog up to 10 times per
season, details about climate and soil conditions and water
chemistry at each location _ the list went on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Being a human database on this scale wasn't easy, said Peter
Beaton, 51, a third-generation cranberry grower. After ``walking
the bogs'' each day, he spent up to three hours each evening making
notes, he said, ``and then I would lose half of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Deborah Beaton, 40, a former research entomologist at the
Lakeville headquarters of Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc.: ``I knew
there had to be an easier way.''
</P>
<P>
   And there was: a customized computer program that links an
off-the-shelf software product, MapInfo, with the database
capabilities of Microsoft's Excel. The result is CranInfo, an
application especially suited to this niche agricultural sector,
which Beaton and her business collaborator, software consultant
Kevin Hanron, 42, plan to begin marketing this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Computers have had a place on most farms for years. Dairy
farmers use them to calculate diets for their cows to boost milk
production. Wheat farmers load their hard drives with weather and
climate data, market news, and dozens of other inputs, to build
yields and determine when to harvest.
</P>
<P>
   But with only about 1,000 cranberry growers in the United States
_ about half of them in Massachusetts _ this industry, whose
product is synonymous with Thanksgiving dinner, was an easy one for
larger software developers to overlook or ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Still, individual growers have explored the field on their own,
often eagerly. One is Gary Garretson, of Carver, also a
third-generation grower, who has installed remote sensors in his
200 acres of bogs to monitor soil and climate conditions as part of
a program to fend off insects and plant diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Loading this data into a software mapping application called
ArcView, Garretson keeps a running record of his integrated pest
management program, a holistic system that combines use of chemical
and biological agents with ecological techniques, such as the
introduction of bluebirds to eat insect larvae.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Deborah Beaton and Hanron, founder of Charles River
Technologies Inc., a Wellesley consulting firm, who may have done
the most to drag the industry into the computer age.
</P>
<P>
   Their story begins with Beaton's earlier introduction to
MapInfo. The software is made by a Troy, N.Y., company of the same
name and was introduced in 1986 as a tool for displaying
demographic data for use in marketing and sales. Its uses have
multiplied since then, including versions that analyze crime data
and select the best sites for cellular telephone antennas.
</P>
<P>
   Beaton had seen MapInfo used by marketers at Ocean Spray, and
she liked how it could superimpose outlines of any shape, from a
house lot to a town boundary, onto existing maps. Even before
meeting Hanron, she used it to draw simple maps that field crews
could use to reach hard-to-find bogs.
</P>
<P>
   But CranInfo's genesis dates to April 1997, when Hanron, who is
MapInfo's New England representative, gave a demonstration that
Deborah Beaton attended at Ocean Spray's offices. Afterward, she
and Hanron talked and agreed on a partnership to develop a
comprehensive software application for cranberry growers.
</P>
<P>
   Beaton and her husband provided the first-hand knowledge about
cranberries; &UR;  &LR; Hanron provided programming skills needed to
customize his product.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a program that displays information on
easy-to-read maps. Printed out, these can be used by a grower or a
field foreman or a helicopter pilot to see what work is needed
where, in detail down to how many pounds of fertilizer to apply.
</P>
<P>
   Beaton and Hanron often worked by trial and error, taking some
wrong turns along the way. One early version was built around the
navigational data that helicopter pilots get from global
positioning satellite receivers aboard their craft.
</P>
<P>
   But when they tried linking cranberry bog maps to this data, the
system couldn't tell whether the longitude and latitude coordinates
were north or south of the equator. ``The bogs ended up in Africa,
not in North America,'' Deborah Beaton said.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, however, CranInfo's bugs were worked out. Now it can
display maps of a wide region, zoom in on local topography, then
focus on a bog as small as a tenth of an acre, smaller than a city
house lot.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, the system can display production records for
individual bogs, accounts of past soil treatments, and season-long
work schedules, including amounts of materials needed.
</P>
<P>
   CranInfo so far has five users, including Peter Beaton's
Cranberry Growers Service, which manages bogs owned by absentee
landowners, as well as the family's own cranberry plantings.
</P>
<P>
   That number is expected to grow rapidly as Hanron and Deborah
Beaton begin marketing the product nationwide this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Early publicity in agricultural and software publications has
already prompted inquiries from growers in Oregon, Washington, and
British Columbia, Hanron said. A basic version of CranInfo,
customized for managing about 30 acres of bogs, will cost about
$2,500, he said. At that price, he said, growers with smaller
holdings probably won't find CranInfo worth the expense.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Beaton said helicopter pilots tell her that CranInfo's
most useful feature may be its ability to print a one-page work
order, with a map, that details exactly what they need to do and
where.
</P>
<P>
   Accustomed to getting their instructions orally or on
hard-to-read hand-drawn maps, the pilots say this order form should
cut down on disputes over whether work was carried out correctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' said Gene Ray, a helicopter pilot for Firefly Inc. of
Carver, ``when someone comes in and says, `You screwed up,' you can
pull it out and show them what they said.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Deborah Beaton: ``When this was all written down on the
back of a Dunkin' Donuts bag that later got tossed in a corner of
some pilot's hangar, it wasn't doing anyone any good.''
</P>
<P>
   Garretson said he envisions a time when software will automate
aerial applications. ``Our goal,'' he said, ``is to be able to give
this data to the pilot on a disc'' and then let the GPS guidance
system take over the actual application process.
</P>
<P>
   Growers say it's too early to know whether this technology will
improve profits. But Garretson said he now has more time to begin
overdue renovations on his buildings. Peter Beaton is now spending
some evenings working on a long-postponed plan to replant his bogs
with more productive berry varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Beaton is also glad to have shed the burden of having to know
everything. ``There are limits to how much one can remember,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
