<SLUG> BC-FBN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PATRONIZING THESE SAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Tuesday was a holy day for the Patriots'
coaching staff. It was all Saints day.
</P>
<P>
   While their players basked in the beauty of a crisp and clear
New England fall day, the coaches did what they do every Tuesday.
They turned themselves into 15 mushrooms, surfacing only for a
lunchtime jog (Paul Boudreau, Carl Smith, Steve Walters, Dante
Scarnecchia) or an hourly smoke (Ernie Zampese).
</P>
<P>
   Around the NFL, Tuesday is the day when the grand plan is laid
out, and nothing changes that. Not bye weeks or fall sunshine or
even baseball playoff games. So Tuesday may have been a high
holiday for Red Sox Nation but it was simply all Saints day for the
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   For most of their history, the Saints didn't require much in the
way of preparation. With the exception of the few years Jim Mora
had them in the playoffs, you could put a checkmark by the Saints
on your schedule when it came out and assume that you were
guaranteed at least one victory. In some seasons, half a day might
have been enough preparation if you had the Saints marching in.
</P>
<P>
   But this year they are 3-0 and tied with the San Francisco 49ers
atop the NFC West. Admittedly, those victories came against a
less-than-fearsome collection of opponents (St. Louis, Carolina,
and Indianapolis) that is at the moment an aggregate 1-10, but
coaches worry a lot. So while most of New England frets about the
Red Sox, Pete Carroll and his staff fret about the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell is not a worrier by nature
but he spent a dozen hours studying a quarterback named Danny
Wuerffel who can't throw but always seems to win and Wuerffel's
favorite targets, Andre Hastings, Sean Dawkins, and rookie tight
end Cameron Cleeland, who has played like a guy who wants to become
famous for something more than being hit in the face with a sock
full of nickels.
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell and his assistants worried about a running back named
Lamar Smith who is six months removed from spending evenings in a
jail cell, and they worried about a young, aggressive offensive
line anchored by an All-Pro left tackle named Willie Roaf and
bookend guards the size of the anchor on an ocean liner.
</P>
<P>
   By midday, they had formulated their plan and met with Carroll
in a stuffy office without windows. This was just about the time Mo
Vaughn was blasting a three-run homer to put the Red Sox on top of
the Cleveland Indians, 3-0, in the first inning. All of New England
saw that blast or at least heard Jerry Trupiano's ``Way back!'' _
all except the 15 worriers in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall, offensive coordinator Zampese worried, too, but
that's his nature when he's preparing his quick-passing game for a
bombing run. This day, he had more than usual to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, he had to worry about Joe Johnson, a
defensive lineman who said all summer he wouldn't play for the
Saints but finally showed up and is playing like the devil.
</P>
<P>
   And he worried about a longtime quarterback-destroyer named
Wayne Martin who is now working from the tackle position, and a new
quarterback-killer named La'Roi Glover who was rejected by the
Oakland Raiders three years ago and now is looking like a star on
the rise with a team-leading four sacks. Glover's presence in the
Saints' lineup and not the Raiders' says as much about Oakland's
present predicament as it does about New Orleans's sudden success.
</P>
<P>
   When Boudreau, New England's line coach, and Zampese finished
figuring out how to arrange pass-protection schemes, Zampese moved
on to mobile linebackers like Kevin Mitchell and Keith Mitchell
without listening to Joni Mitchell in the background as mood music.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Zampese got to the people he most wants to beat this
Sunday. He got to a headhunting safety named Chad Cota, who likes
knockouts more than Mike Tyson does, and a cornerback Carroll is
familiar with named Tyronne Drakeford, who played for Carroll in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, they all worried together about Mike Ditka
because after a slow start last season, it seems he may have found
his coaching sea legs again. Somehow Ditka has gotten the hapless
Saints afloat and playing Bears-style football, which means alley
cat football. Even though no one is ready to say these Saints
resemble Da Bears of 1985, they're 3-0 on the schedule and hence a
source of concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Saints have found the formula of playing good defense,
running the ball, and controlling their turnovers,'' Carroll said.
``That's how they're winning. Ditka has chosen players that
complement his approach. He's got real attitude guys.''
</P>
<P>
   As in bad attitude guys. Guys who come to play with bad
intentions. Guys who make football coaches worry even on the most
beautiful of days.
</P>
<P>
   What the worriers in Foxborough understood by the end of all
Saints day was that New Orleans is a team that is young and fast
and aggressive and hasn't been taught yet where its place is. These
Saints really believe they are a 3-0 team, which, if true, would
make them a playoff team, which, if true, would make Ditka not only
a Saint but also a miracle worker.
</P>
<P>
   But over the next month, these Saints may again become the Aints
after playing New England, San Francisco, Atlanta, and Tampa Bay,
because those opponents will tell them more than the Rams,
Panthers, and Colts have. Knowing that, on a beautiful fall day
made not for sitting in a darkened coaches room but for sitting
outside with a portable radio listening to the Red Sox, the
worriers who work for Carroll labored to become the first team to
ruin the Saints' self-image.
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell and his staff assembled attack plans, deciding just how
much pressure it would take to snap young Wuerffel. Zampese went
over his list of pass plays short and long before presenting his
ideas to Carroll on just how many throws it would take to blow the
roof off the Saints' undefeated defense if not the Superdome
itself.
</P>
<P>
   It was a busy day on a beautiful day spent studying a team they
knew little about. It was the kind of day understood by no one but
the 15 men locked in tiny offices at Foxboro Stadium, living in a
world all their own.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been a glorious Tuesday in New England and a
glorious playoff day in Cleveland, but it was all Saints day in
Foxborough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
