<HEADLINE>
HISTORIC HUDSON RIVER ENJOYS CLEANER TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED LeBRUN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ While the early-morning mists still shrouded
the Hudson River far below, a wave of gray cadets silently passed
by Taylor Hall on the way to classes.
</P>
<P>
   Unsmiling, moving at a uniform speed, with only a word or two
spoken for every dozen that passed. It's odd to think of them as
teen-agers with the solemn bearing of men and women three times
their age.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed from the river, the military academy at West Point is
first an imposing citadel resting on bedrock at the lower river's
narrowest point. Here the Hudson takes a sharp turn where British
sailing ships of war could not hold the wind. A critical strategic
position that with the addition of a famous linked chain across the
river in all likelihood saved our War of Independence. Such is the
importance of the Hudson River to our nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   The promontory view from West Point looking upriver and across
to the equally high bluffs of Constitution Island is the most
breathtaking on the river. In the lightening gloom of early
morning, it is the stuff of goose bumps and poetic description.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Cole, founding of the Hudson River school of painting
(his Catskill home and studio were just a short walk from the
river), was also struck by the Hudson at first light. ``The mists
were resting on the vale of the Hudson like drifted snow.''
</P>
<P>
   But much can be hidden by a romantic misty vale.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were kids, we'd go up to Tompkins Cove,'' white-haired
Daniel Donnelly said, pointing a little downriver from our berth at
the Garrison Yacht Club, which is directly across the river from
West Point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were swimming in human excrement,'' he said, wrinkling his
nose.
</P>
<P>
   Donnelly, in a starched white shirt, tie, and striped suit
pants, is a lawyer who specializes in aviation law and his offices
are a hundred yards from the riverbank. He was there discussing a
case with another lawyer, Robert Murphy, wearing an almost
identical uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Columbia University in the '70s, Murphy said with a
smile, ``and played baseball there. I remember watching the crews
down below in the river rowing away. They had to be careful because
if they fell in they had to take a chemical bath.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Donnelly, Dan's wife and secretary, later said that those
same crews that fell in were required to take antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the years just before the effects of Gov. Nelson
Rockefeller's $1 billion Pure Waters Bond Act of 1965 kicked in
were the river's lowest ebb relating to water quality. Bond act
money and the resolve of genuine Hudson River heroes like Bob
Boyle, John Cronin and the Hudson River Valley Greenway began to
turn the tide.
</P>
<P>
   The ``river that flows both ways'' is now cleaner than it's been
in more than a century, but still is not where it needs to be.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's no sheen of oil on the water, or odd slick on the
shore left by the tide as there was even a decade ago. Swimming in
the Hudson may not be as dramatic as it once was, but it's a lot
safer and more fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
