<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2101 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPERA-FRISCO-SPI &LR;      09-30 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-FRISCO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARM DEBUT FOR PREVIN'S `STREETCAR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By R.M. CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Part of the excitement of opera in
turn-of-the-century America is the increasing abundance of new work
to be seen, to be heard, to be digested.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone is doing it, in one form or another, but few premieres
have had the sex appeal of Tennessee Williams' ``A Streetcar Named
Desire'' set to music by Andre Previn at San Francisco Opera this
month.
</P>
<P>
   With the vivid personalities the playwright conjured up for his
play _ two of whom are virtual icons in America's theatrical
imagination _ the smoky, heat-filled ambience of New Orleans and
the tragic pull of the narrative, the play is a natural for lyric
muse. And while ballets have been based on the Williams text, no
one attempted an opera until Previn.
</P>
<P>
   Some have called Previn's opera the best in more than two
decades, while others have decried its too-free adaptation of mixed
musical sources and lack of Southern verisimilitude.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a weak second act that just trips along, anxious to
keep up with the flow of Williams' words, the opera has a firm grip
on our consciousness with telling characterizations, a score that
punctuates with color and exclamation points and moments of stark
horror and sadness. Previn gives Blanche all the arias the deluded
lady of the Old South could ever want, but none to Stanley because
the composer thought the rough and tumble guy wasn't the sort to
sing arias. Previn is sparse with duets, curiously, but those few
work with surprising power.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Previn has written an opera that sits nicely in the ear.
It can move speedily along, but then slow down to savor the moment.
The composer has taken our pluralistic age at its word and borrowed
from many, including two 20th-century Russians, Prokofiev and
Shostakovich, bits of Richard Strauss and occasional hints of jazz,
not well played by the orchestra. On occasion, Previn stoops to
movie music cliches. Philip Littell's libretto is faithful to
Williams' text, but does not illuminate it.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Yeargan's set _ the Kowalskis' two-room apartment evokes
the French Quarter deftly. For variety, it revolves. Thomas J.
Munn's lighting design is equally effective.
</P>
<P>
   One could not ask for a better cast: Renee Fleming as Blanche;
Rodney Gilfry, Stanley; Elizabeth Futral, Stella; and Anthony Dean
Griffey, Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming's Blanche sits at the very heart of the opera. She is
given a good share of the best, the most poetic music, which she
delivers with eloquence. Admittedly, she is neither Jessica Tandy,
who created the role on Broadway, nor Vivian Leigh, who appeared in
the movie, but she sings with beauty of tone and acts in an
appealing manner.
</P>
<P>
   Gilfry looks like a Stanley, big and muscular and brash. He has
a strong stage presence, full of masculine pride and threatening
gestures. But he is given little to do vocally. Futral has a sweet
soprano and a sweet, loving presence, which makes her a good
counterpoint to her older sister, Blanche, and her husband,
Stanley. Griffey makes for a pitiful, and well-sung, Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   There has been considerable criticism on how well the opera, and
the accents of its principal characters, suggest the South. On that
subject, I cannot offer an opinion. But I did ask the opinion of
the music critic for the Times-Picayune, New Orleans' leading
newspaper, at the performance. He said he thought the negative
comments were not justified.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra, conducted by Previn, was disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Puccini's ``Turandot'' formally opened the season earlier this
month. The production, designed by David Hockney, became celebrated
the moment of its premiere five years ago at Lyric Opera of
Chicago, a co-producer with San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The English artist is no stranger to the theater, having
designed a number of operas since his first, a wondrous ``Magic
Flute'' in 1978 for Glyndebourne Festival. I have seen a good share
of them in various places, and none follows a formula. Always, a
seemingly wild, but in fact calculated, imagination rules.
Convention is thrown out and invention summoned.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Turandot,'' the expected is banished. Hockney's line is
long and sweeping in the first act and elusive in the third. His
palette is vivid, electric, almost overwhelming. Chinese reds at
their most intense are paired with unlikely blues and purples to
create stirring sensations, while gold and celadon are joined for a
softer but no less striking contrast.
</P>
<P>
   All of Hockney's visual genius is joined by Ian Falconer's bold
costumes that equally dispense with the ordinary, however opulent,
and Munn's superb lighting design.
</P>
<P>
   The production is so strong, the musical forces seem less
important. In San Francisco, they were. The cast was strong but not
subtle. The German soprano Gabriele Schnaut sang the title role.
With her voice, she is a steamroller that always can be heard
despite competition from a big orchestra and chorus. She can sing
softly, but rarely did. The Canadian tenor Richard Margison sang
the role of Calaf with equal heft, but little grace in his musical
phrasing. The Slovakian soprano Andrea Dankova was a tender Liu.
The Ping, Pang and Pong of Earle Patriarco, Dennis Petersen and
Matthew Lord were terrific. Marco Armiliato, from Genoa, conducted
vigorously, and stage director Garnett Bruce moved people around
with alacrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arabella,'' also being performed this season, was the last
collaboration between Richard Strauss and Hugo von Hofmannsthal. It
is a cream puff of an opera, at once elegant, amusing and happy.
While it is one of Hofmannsthal's finest creations, it is not one
of Strauss'. In spite of dry patches, it has much memorable music:
Strauss at his most sublimely lyrical.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has done the opera once before, in 1980, with Kiri
Te Kanawa in the title role. She was at her best, beautiful and
persuasive, the music pouring out of her in long, seamless phrases.
Janice Watson, an English soprano, is not Kanawa's equal, but she
has a handsome voice and stylish manner. Mary Mills was all fervent
charm as Arabella's younger sister, Zdenka.
</P>
<P>
   Mandryka, the Croatian landowner who loves Arabella as she does
him, was sung by the noted German bass-baritone Franz Grundheber.
His voice is more gritty than beautiful, thus right for the part.
More important is his singing, which was impassioned and
intelligent. The rest of the cast did their parts well, and
Scottish conductor Donald Runnicles, music director of San
Francisco Opera since 1992, gave life and energy to the whole
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The production from Covent Garden looks good and suits the
period. David Edwards directed with sympathy and attention to
detail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
