<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MASSACRE (Prstina) _ Developments in the aftermath of the
massacre by Serb soldiers of ethnic Albanian civilians. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-AIDS-VACCINE (Kampala, Uganda) _ In Uganda _ a country
struggling valiantly to cope with an AIDS epidemic that has
infected 20 percent of its population, desperate Ugandans clamor to
participate in an AIDS vaccine trial. In the past, ethical
guidelines have made it clear that vaccines should be tested where
health care is excellent before they are ever used in places
without a safety net, like Uganda. Now, for the first time, the
international medical community has set aside that requirement.
``We are the people with the problem. Why should Americans
undertake risky research on themselves for a problem they don't
really have? That would make them the guinea pigs. The risk belongs
here, where the people are dying,'' said one researcher. By Michael
Specter. A Special Report.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Developments in Russia a day before the new
economic plan is to be announced. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BLOOD (Beijing) _ In China, fearful of AIDS, a new law
takes effect Thursday banning the buying and selling of blood. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-FRANCE (Paris) _ Chancellor-elect Gerhard Schroeder
meets with French President Jacques Chirac. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ On the heels of a report that Iraq
is close to having nuclear weapons, the Iraqi foreign minister
addresses General Assembly. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
