</P>
<P>
   (See also SURPLUS-IMPACT, under Financial)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments in Congress on the
allegations against the president.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCHIPPERS (Washington) _ A profile of David P.
Schippers, chief counsel on the House Judiciary Committee. By
Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-CIVIL-RIGHTS (Los Angeles) _ In what is believed to be the
largest civil rights judgment against law enforcement in
California, Los Angeles County has paid nearly $24 million to 36
people who sheriff's deputies arrested, and in some cases beat,
during a bridal shower in 1989. By Verne G. Kopytoff.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHWAY-GUARD-RAILS (Detroit) _ The Federal Highway
Administration is banning as of Thursday all further installations
of two popular kinds of guard rails along Federally financed
highways, after determining that the guard rails cause high-riding
pickup trucks and other vehicles to roll over during tests. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Third Quarter Package &LR;
</P>
<P>
   QTR-WINNERS (Undated) _ The winners and losers on the stock
market during the third quarter. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   QTR-DEALS (Undated) _ The leading underwriters and dealmakers in
the quarter. By Peter Truell.
</P>
<P>
   QTR-MUTFUNDS (Undated) _ Mutual fund flows in the quarter. By
Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hedge Fund Bailout &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT (Undated) _ Developments in the bailout of
Long-Term Capital. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-REGULATE (Undated) _ Should hedge funds be forced to
disclose more, and to whom? Are other limits warranted? Advancing
Thursday's congressional testimony by the Fed's Greenspan and
others. By Leslie Wayne and Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other financial &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SURPLUS-IMPACT (Washington) _ We've got a budget surplus. So
what difference does it make? By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   LENDING-SLOWDOWN (Undated) _ The United States is starting to
feel the effects of a lending pullback. The pinch, still quite
mild, is almost entirely on businesses, not consumers. Commercial
banks, investment firms, Japanese banks that lend in America and
the millions of people who purchase corporate bonds are all
becoming a bit more tight-fisted _ demanding slightly higher
interest rates, and sometimes refusing to lend as much as before.
The caution predates the Russian debacle, where some of the world's
biggest banks suddenly lost money. But Russia appears to have
strengthened the resolve to filter out potential deadbeats. And the
near collapse of Long-Term Capital has added to the nervousness
about lending. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   SAUDI-OIL (Undated) _ Folo reports that American oil companies,
after more than two decades in exile, are being asked by Saudi
Arabia to submit proposals to once again help the kingdom with its
massive oil and natural gas reserves. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-NAMES (Washington) _ The administration hopes to wrap
up a compromise plan that would establish an independent non-profit
organization to oversee addresses on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-DATA (Tokyo) _ Sony and Toyota team up with a relative
unknown, Internet Initiatives Japan Inc., to create a company that
will offer Japanese companies a cheaper way of sending data over
telephone lines. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By
Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   William Safire's ``Essay'' and Bob Herbert's ``In America'';
details to come.
</P>
