<P>
   ALICE-Q&AMP;A &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ In a Q&AMP;A, celebrity chef Alice Waters _ earth mother
to a generation of organic foodies _ talks about eating healthy,
mealtime rituals, the future of the planet _ and the one and only
time she ate at McDonald's. By PAUL BOURGEOIS. Story will move in
``d'' food category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES-BUNDY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ A reader recently wrote looking for the recipe for a
Norwegian cream cake to make for her husband for his birthday.
Lucky man. ``Blotkake'' is one of the marvels of Scandinavian
cooking. By BEVERLY BUNDY. Story will move in ``d'' food category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANDERSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Like a wise old Indian scout surveying hoofprints in
the sand, mothers know. Like a meteorologist watching a barometer
fluctuate from high to low, mothers know. Like a pathologist
observing microscopic images of cells, mothers know. By MONICA
FRAZIER ANDERSON. Story will move in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FELICITY-TV &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``Felicity,'' which debuted this week on the WB
network and is one of the few series to appear in The Wall Street
Journal and that other journal of pop-cultural analysis, Seventeen,
before it even generates a rating point, earns its hype. It does so
not just for going against the grain but, based on a well-crafted,
crisply written, engaging pilot by filmmaker J.J. Abrams
(''Armageddon''), for being intellectually delicious. By KEN PARISH
PERKINS. Story will move in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WBAP-50THANNIVERSARY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Fifty years ago this week, movie screens in this neck
of the woods offered such new films as ``Homecoming,'' with Clark
Gable and Lana Turner, at the Belknap Drive-In and ``Green Grass of
Wyoming'' (Charles Coburn) at the Hollywood Theater in downtown
Fort Worth. But the real news was on the small screen, which made
its Southwest debut. By PERRY STEWART. Story will move in ``e''
entertainment category for Texas points. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-STEAGALL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Red Steagall is no Garrison Keillor. Steagall, after
all, writes about life out west, not the Lutherans in Lake Wobegon
who populate Keillor's ``A Prairie Home Companion.'' But as it
turns out, the poet/singer/songwriter and chronicler of life on the
range may well be on the way to creating the western equivalent of
Keillor's imaginary radio world at his own broadcast bunkhouse, the
syndicated ``Cowboy Corner.'' About 120 stations from New York
state to Canada's western provinces carry the hourlong program,
which Steagall launched nearly five years ago. By JOHN AUSTIN.
Story will move in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KIRK FRANKLIN-AUTOBIOGRAPHY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``Church Boy'' (Word Publishing, $12.99), Kirk
Franklin's new autobiography, has an amazing story to tell. Nobody
else has come so far so fast _ at least in gospel music _ and
therein lies a tale with as many twists and turns as a novel. By
DAVE FERMAN. Story will move in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ I started out in the newspaper business as a
sportswriter. My career goal was to cover major-league baseball, to
travel from city to city with the St. Louis Cardinals. Thank
goodness I was a lousy baseball writer. Consider this an official
tip of the cap to baseball writers, baseball players, baseball
groupies and all other individuals who spend days and weeks on the
road in pursuit of their livelihoods or hobbies. I just came off an
18-day road trip; I'm exhausted and disoriented, not to mention
dazed and confused. By BILL THOMPSON. Story will move in ``k''
commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
