<P>
   &UR; HEEDING THE SIREN CALL TO DO YOUR OWN THING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,300 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ART FOR PURCHASE: One humorous color shot showing a young boy
operating a lemonade stand for the new century _ equipped with a
laptop computer, a fax machine and a telephone. Available
electronically. &QL; 
 &UR; By LOUIS UCHITELLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneurial spirit is alive and well in both large and
small businesses, reports Times writer Louis Uchitelle in this
cover feature. It's certainly a prime competitive weapon in big
business. Witness Merck &AMP; Company, the giant pharmaceutical
corporation, whose scientists are encouraged to scout outside the
company for promising new research that might lead to a future
drug. Then there are the millions of Americans who believe that the
entrepreneurial spirit resides mainly in small companies with fewer
than 100 employees. Here, self-employment is a big phenomenon,
particularly among workers who have been laid off by corporations.
Uchitelle is a staff writer for The Times.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-DO-YOUR-OWN-THING-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE VALLEY OF THE GOLD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN MARKOFF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Shoch, a Silicon Valley venture capitalist, scans the room
at Bucks, a folksy cafe in Woodside, Calif., and notes that he
recognizes about half the financiers, hardware engineers and
software hackers who are seated. Shoch is doing what he does best:
``surfing,'' or looking for the next big thing in the nation's
technology heartland. What will it be? Is it wireless data? Is the
time finally right for interactive digital television? John
Markoff, a staff writer for The New York Times, reports on the
blinding pace of Silicon Valley and what seems to be everyone's
pastime _ catching the next big wave. Markoff is co-author of the
book ``Takedown: The Pursuit and Capture of America's Most Wanted
Computer Criminal'' (Hyperion, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-THE-VALLEY-OF-GOLD-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STUDENTS AT B-SCHOOLS FLOCK TO THE E-COURSES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,200 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ART FOR PURCHASE: One B&AMP;W photo showing students attending an
entrepreneur class at Northwestern's Kellogg School of Management.
Available electronically. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ETHAN BRONNER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may not be easy to spell, but entrepreneurialism is all the
rage among potential MBAs. Driven by student and alumni demand, no
field is hotter today in business studies. Whereas a generation ago
the goal of top MBA graduates was to join a Fortune 500 company and
climb the corporate ladder, students' most fervent desire nowadays
seems to be to come up with a marketable idea, start a company and
work for themselves. Ethan Bronner, national educational
correspondent for The New York Times and author of ``Battle for
Justice: How the Bork Nomination Shook America'' (Norton, 1989),
explains why in this feature.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-ENTREPRENEURS-101-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIS DREAM IS THAT WE'LL HEAR LITTLE VOICES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,200 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ART FOR PURCHASE: One color shot showing Donald Katz and the staff
of Audible Inc. at their headquarters in Wayne, N.J. Available
electronically. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By TOM REDBURN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Donald Katz, the 46-year-old author of three highly acclaimed
nonfiction books, is a rather unlikely entrepreneur. His
three-year-old Internet start-up, Audible Inc., offers custom audio
information delivered on demand over the Web to portable devices
you can listen to any time and anywhere, say, while jogging or
driving to work. Tom Redburn, the business enterprise editor for
The New York Times, interviews Katz, whose experiences provide
insight into the obstacles and confusions that arise when
nonbusiness types go into business in a big way. Redburn has
written for The International Herald Tribune and the Los Angeles
Times.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-ONE-MAN'S-DREAM-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WANT SOME MILLION-DOLLAR IDEAS? I GOT A MILLION OF 'EM! &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ART FOR PURCHASE: One humorous B&AMP;W illustration depicting a man
showing plans for an idea to a patent officer. Available
electronically. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By NEIL STRAUSS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hakuta's story is inspiring. He's the inventor of the Wacky
Wall Walker, those slime-covered plastic creatures that ooze down
vertical surfaces. The beauty of it is that Hakuta didn't even come
up with the idea: All he did was license the toy from Japan for a
tiny fraction of the amount he made. Now he's a millionaire! There
are a ton of ideas out floating around, reports Neil Strauss. But
who has the time _ and money _ to make them happen? Strauss
doesn't, which is why he is giving away his top 10 get-rich-quick
schemes in this humorous feature for those who want to pursue them:
portable baby sitters ... address books, cell phones and wallets
that beep when they're lost ... public egg banks. Strauss is a
staff writer for The Times.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-MILLION-DOLLAR-IDEAS-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S HER LABEL AND SHE'LL SIGN WHO SHE WANTS TO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ART FOR PURCHASE: One photo of Bettina Richards, the subject of
this feature. Available electronically. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JON PARELES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Bettina Richards was an artist-and-repertory executive for
big recording companies, she didn't like the way they treated
musicians. Her favorite bands were ignored if they weren't best
sellers; one lead singer, who went on to make a gold album, was
told he shouldn't be singing at all. In 1992, she started her own
company: Thrill Jockey Records. It would release music she cared
about and let the musicians decide what to release, how to package
it and run their careers. A profile by Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-STARTUP-MUSIC-LABEL-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
