<HEADER>
A2144 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALICE-Q&AMP;A-TEX     09-30 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALICE-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALICE'S WONDERLAND: Q&AMP;A WITH THE EARTH MOTHER OF ORGANIC FOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the gospel according to Alice Waters, food is the way.
</P>
<P>
   It sustains not only the body, but also the spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Verily, it is the glue that binds together the family, society,
civilization and the life of the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes it a little ironic that the 54-year-old Waters _
founder of the landmark Chez Panisse Restaurant in Berkeley,
Calif., author of five books, earth mother to a generation of
organic foodies _ was in Dallas last week for the 10th American
Airlines Chefs Conclave, a meeting of 15 premier chefs who gather
yearly to talk about ways to improve ... airline food.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Waters? Airline food?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to influence 196,000 travelers a day,'' she said.
``Some of the things I was preaching to them years ago, they are
now doing. They are using more fresh fruit and vegetables.''
</P>
<P>
   A petite woman with bobbed red hair and scant if any makeup, she
floats into the room like an Oriental monk. She is attired in
comfortable peasant slacks. Black. Simple tunic. Black. Simple
sandals. Black.
</P>
<P>
   She smiles serenely before she begins heaving with a deep,
hacking cough. It's a little bug she picked up in Paris (the one in
France).
</P>
<P>
   She was there negotiating for a new restaurant she has been
invited to open at the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   It's something that's liable to start another French Revolution.
Imagine, not just a woman (!), but an American (!) from California
(!) with no formal culinary training (!) setting up shop at the
Louvre (!).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the talking stage,'' she said, but the talk is
``serious.'' In any case, it's a couple of years away.
</P>
<P>
   She's also got another book in the works, the Chez Panisse Cafe
cookbook, due out in fall 1999.
</P>
<P>
   While she was in town, we took the opportunity to chat about
organic food, the future of the planet _ and the one and only time
Alice Waters ate at McDonald's:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where is food in America headed?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think people know that something is wrong. Some foods are
making people sick and unhappy. They are looking for something that
makes them feel good and that tastes good and happens to be good
for them. They are looking for that, and there's a much bigger
picture: They are looking for nourishment and spiritual
nourishment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you see the movement toward healthy and organic food
continuing?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it is a delicious revolution that is happening
because when people get connected with food that really tastes good
and that's good for them, then that lasts. That's something that is
deeply planted inside them, and it's what their body wants. It's
about the quality of your life, because when you buy food from a
farmers market, it's a social event, and eating around a table is a
social gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You make it sound like a religious experience. Like taking
Communion.
</P>
<P>
   A: Of course it is. It brings meaning into your everyday life to
sit at a table and to talk with your friends and your family and to
eat something that's good and to participate in the cooking. You
know, 85 percent of the kids in this country do not have one meal a
day with their family. Now that's a terrible thing. We are in
danger of losing our culture.
</P>
<P>
   Food is about everything. That's the message. It's the
relationship to agriculture, to family, to everything.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We've gotten away from that. How do we get back?
</P>
<P>
   A: Once you give people things that were picked when they are
alive, when they are completely ripe ...
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who has the time?
</P>
<P>
   A: People have to start to make time. Bringing people into the
circumstance of a farmers market is very seductive, and I feel like
we have to think about what is locally grown, what is seasonally
ripe, and we have to focus on that first. It leads us to the people
that care about our nourishment, and the people who care about the
land. We aren't led to the manufacturers who care about making
money on bad habits.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Eating fresh and organic produce is probably easier in
California.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it is, but it's a matter of focus. It's a matter of
planning ahead and thinking about what's available. Lots of things
grow in the colder places, too. You can do it anywhere. You just
have to focus.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The push in recent years has been to more convenience foods.
</P>
<P>
   A: We have to understand that convenience is not what we're
after.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did we go wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's because of the way that food is distributed. It's the
television, it's the deep freeze, the transportation, it's the
shipping things from one country to another. It has taken away from
seasonality. We don't know what fresh is anymore. We don't know
what ripe is anymore. We sort of eat these mediocre fruits and
vegetables all year long instead of waiting for when they are
really ripe and special.
</P>
<P>
   And this consumerism _ we feel like everything has to get bigger
and better and stronger.
</P>
<P>
   It's about understanding where the meaning and the value is. I'm
not ready to go back into a hut, or grow everything myself. There
have been incredible advances in agriculture that could change the
deserts into gardens of Eden. We need to teach people about
farming. Everybody needs to know how important farming is.
Corporate farms are about profit, and we have to treasure these
farmers who are doing it the right way, and to encourage young
people to be farmers. We have to give it more status and
appreciation and offer them more money for doing what they are
doing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can you turn people from the dark side?
</P>
<P>
   A: Through food. People have to get involved in shelling the
peas. The pleasure is in the doing. If I didn't shell the pea, I
can't appreciate what that is.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you a zealot?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm in the lunatic fringe.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you happy?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm very, very overworked right now because I can't say no,
and that's a big problem. I have to think about how to do this,
because my life is going to fall apart unless I can learn to say
no. I can't resist the opportunity to talk about this. I want to
talk to the biggest audience.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Tell us about the restaurant at the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think it would be like Chez Panisse. I would want it
to express almost in a didactic way this philosophy, and that maybe
we should think of it as art in the form of a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   I was thinking of going to work with a Japanese designer who
could, you know, short of having a cow in there and milking it,
have a way that people interacted with food, that they understood
where it came from and how important it is to take care of the
land.
</P>
<P>
   Eating is an agricultural act. You do more by eating than just
nourishing yourself. You are really taking care of the planet, and
you are thinking about the future for our kids.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
