<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN01-COX     09-30 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: A prized publisher
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ The Lufkin Daily News has dedicated a new
flagpole in memory of Thomas R. Meredith, complete with a granite
marker that notes his tenure as publisher, 1965-78.
</P>
<P>
   Tom was a young man in his mid-30s when he was named to head up
the newspaper by its new owners, the Fentress group, headquartered
in Waco, where Tom grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Up until then, the Lufkin paper had been controlled by the
powers-that-be locally, same folks who owned the biggest bank, the
TV-radio station, the paper mill, sawmill, foundry and most
everything else worth having hereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   When the patriarch, Ernest L. Kurth Sr., died, his heirs began
selling off holdings in order to deal with the death taxes. The
newspaper, which had never been all that profitable, was among the
first to go.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the old owners had sold the paper, cashed the checks
and spent the money, some of them seemed still of a mind that they
had a right to run the paper, same as they always had.
</P>
<P>
   They tried to run Tom Meredith. When that didn't work, they
tried to run him out of town. That didn't work either.
</P>
<P>
   The Waco headquarters backed him all the way, despite anonymous
hate letters, boycotts and other threats of economic reprisal.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Meredith, a good newspaperman and a good manager, made the
Lufkin newspaper into a money-maker. He later showed me a note he
had received from the president of the company after his first
successful year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You deserve a fanfare of no less than 76 trombones,'' it read.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd have put it closer to 76,000.
</P>
<P>
   Tom named me editor of my hometown newspaper when I was 28 years
old. He'd been impressed by stories I'd been writing as
correspondent for the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the story in my paper and it gives one side,'' he told
me. ``I read the same story you wrote for the Chronicle and it
gives both sides. That's what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   We were a great team. I took all the credit and he took all the
flak. My back was never to the wall. He was always behind me,
between me and the wall.
</P>
<P>
   He backed me up not just when I was right but, more importantly,
when I was wrong. That's the way Tom was. Right or wrong, I was his
editor.
</P>
<P>
   It was during those years that the Lufkin paper won the Pulitzer
Prize for Meritorious Public Service, the same award the Washington
Post had received for Watergate. Had it not been for Tom Meredith,
there never would have been a Pulitzer Prize for the Lufkin Daily
News.
</P>
<P>
   The paper won for its investigation of the recruitment and death
of a Lufkin Marine. Tom was very much pro-military. He had twice
served his country in uniform, at the end of World War II and again
during the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   But Tom, God bless him, had an inborn sense of right and wrong.
As always, he backed us all the way, and it wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   Tom told this story of the day a local lawyer, who had served
with the Marines in the Pacific, took exception to our stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether to simply cancel my subscription or come
over there and stomp your butt,'' he informed the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Tom replied, ``I don't normally encourage people not
to take the paper, but given that choice ...''
</P>
<P>
   Some time later, after reforms in recruitment and basic training
had resulted from our stories and no less than the commandant of
the Marine Corps said the Corps was getting well because of them,
the same lawyer wrote a note of apology.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, leaders of the community, some of the same ones who
once opposed Tom's leadership at the Lufkin Daily News, joined in a
banquet at the civic center honoring the newspaper when it received
the Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   By then the Lufkin Daily News had been sold to Cox Newspapers of
Atlanta, and Tom was soon promoted to publisher of the Longview
(Texas) News-Journal, an operation twice the size of Lufkin.
</P>
<P>
   This time he was warmly welcomed by the establishment, and
almost immediately elected president of the Longview chamber of
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Tom, who had managed his own affairs as successfully as the
newspapers he ran, was able to retire at age 60. I was honored to
emcee his retirement banquet. A plane load of Cox dignitaries came
to honor him.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years later, sad to say, we returned to Longview to
pay tribute to him one last time. Tom, at age 64, was dead of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   There are still publishers like Thomas R. Meredith, but fewer
all the time. They hardly make 'em like him anymore.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
