<P>
   JOURNAL-DOMINICAN _ POLO, Dominican Republic _ As I trudged up a
dusty street in this impoverished town of ramshackle wooden houses
-- where 30 people died, nearly one-fifth of Hurricane Georges'
victims in this small country -- I thought about my 9-year-old
daughter, Margaret. For most of her life I have tried to impress
upon her how incredibly lucky she was to have been born an
American. It's not that I want her to feel superior, it's that I
want her to realize that when things seem difficult in her life --
if a meal is an hour later than usual and she claims she's starving
-- her minor inconveniences pale against the sufferings of many in
this world. In Polo, I gathered first-hand knowledge of that
suffering. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
