<P>
   MIAMI _ Miami University (of Ohio) is the latest public
university to be drawn into a nationwide controversy over the
allocation of mandatory student activity fees to campus religious
groups. A coalition of four Christian organizations and 11 students
filed suit Tuesday in U.S. District Court in Cincinnati, claiming
that Miami's procedures for funding religious organizations are
unconstitutional. They contend that Miami does not provide equal
funding to religious organizations and that students are required
to subsidize groups they disagree with. Miami officials insist that
student organizations are funded fairly and legally and that
religious organizations are treated the same as campus political
groups. Two of the student organizations, including one called For
the Love of God, received some student-activity funds last year.
``This is not about access to funding. It's about using mandatory
fees to support religion,'' a Miami spokesman said. (Fisher, Dayton
Daily News).
</P>
