<HEADER>
A2163 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIMSUM-FOOD-AZR &LR;      09-30 1847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIM SUM CHEFS `TOUCH THE HEART'  
 (ART ADV: PHOTOS HAVE BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
 SUM-FOOD-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER CUSHMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Do you have the meatloaf and mashed-potato blues? Is
your palate craving something decidedly different? Now may be the
time to consider giving Chinese dim sum a try.
</P>
<P>
   Dim sum is small, flavorful pockets of pleasure made from
hundreds of combinations of meats, seafood, vegetables and sauces.
It is steamed, fried, baked or grilled, and ranges from the exotic
_ such as sweetened chicken feet, steamed duck web and beef tripe _
to the more mundane dishes of lotus leaf rice or steamed barbecue
pork buns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dim sum is not just one thing, it is all kinds of things,''
said Chau Liaw, a chef who has been teaching Chinese cooking at the
House of Rice in Scottsdale, Ariz., for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   One of Liaw's most popular classes is dim sum basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the old people in China, dim sum is very special,'' she
said. ``They get together to relax in a warm place where they drink
tea and eat simple snacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Translated, dim sum means ``touch the heart.'' Americans
interpret it to mean the food touches the heart, Liaw said.
Actually, the name shows deference to master dim sum chefs _ called
``si fu'' _ for wanting to please others by creating the yummy
morsels.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to first experience dim sum is in a restaurant. Dim
sum is a movable feast, literally. Waiters wheel around metal carts
of freshly made dim sum varieties. You take what you want to eat
and wait for the next turn of the cart, filled with different
dishes.
</P>
<P>
   After figuring out what dishes you like, you can start
experimenting with dim sum at home. The first thing to do is take a
trip to your local library for a cookbook or do a search for dim
sum on the Internet to find some easy recipes.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to deconstruct dim sum, Ling Lou, co-owner of Cu-Fu
Gourmet, a dim sum and Chinese restaurant in Chandler, Ariz.,
explained some popular dishes and what they are made of.
</P>
<P>
   Any dim sum restaurant worth its salt will take pride in its
harr kow, a translucent, fresh shrimp dumpling, Lou said. The dough
(a combination of tapioca starch, wheat starch, lard and boiling
water) is very delicate. If the chef makes the dough too soft, the
dumpling breaks. If the dough is too thick, it becomes soggy during
steaming and sticks to the bamboo basket.
</P>
<P>
   Spring rolls are a little easier to make. Spring roll skins are
thin, square wrappers made of flour and water that can be purchased
from an Oriental market. Shredded pork is marinated with a
combination of oyster and soy sauces and added to black Chinese
mushrooms, Chinese cabbage leaves, gingerroot, shrimp, bamboo
shoots, scallion, chicken stock and a little cornstarch. The
filling is placed in the skins, which then are wrapped up and
sealed with a touch of beaten egg yolk. They are then quickly
deep-fried to a light, crispy texture.
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue pork buns are another popular dim sum dish. A basic bun
dough of yeast, flour, sugar, milk and water is formed into a ball
around various fillings _ in this case, diced pork. The slightly
sweet sauce is made with hoisin sauce, oyster sauce, soy sauce,
brown sugar, chicken stock, cornstarch and wine. The buns are
steamed until they are fluffy and light.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one cannot forget the importance of rice in any
Chinese meal. Lotus leaf rice is the centerpiece of dim sum. A
mixture of short-grain rice, dried shrimp, chicken, pork sausage,
barbecue pork and soy sauce is stuffed into the dried, round lotus
leaves (tropical water-lily plants), which are tied with string
into a neat, rectangular package and then steamed.
</P>
<P>
   Bean curd often is found in various dim sum dishes. Bean curd
(tofu) is made from soybeans that first are softened in water and
then crushed and boiled to make milk. The pulp is strained out and
the milk coagulates into curds that are pressed into molds. Bean
curd also can be dried into thin sheets for wrappers for fillings
such as chicken, pork, shrimp and black mushrooms to make treats
such as bean curd skin rolls. You can tell the difference between
spring rolls and bean curd skin rolls because the latter are
deep-fried and then steamed, which give them a wrinkled appearance.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best things about the way Chinese eat dim sum is you
don't have to wait until the end of the meal for dessert. You just
eat sweet delicacies such as baked custard buns or sesame seed
balls whenever the desire hits you.
</P>
<P>
   Custard buns use the same fluffy bun dough of the barbecue pork
buns, but the filling is a mixture of egg yolk, sugar and butter.
Sesame seed balls are an interesting mix of sweet rice dough and
dried red beans that are cooked slowly for at least five hours with
sugar until they turn to a thick red paste. The paste is smeared
into the dough, which is rolled into a ball and then sprinkled with
toasted sesame seeds and deep-fried in a wok.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken feet are an extremely popular dim sum dish in Asia. Not
surprisingly, they don't fare particularly well with Americans, Lou
said. Simply prepared, chicken feet are cooked in a black-bean
sauce. The proper way to eat them is to put the entire foot in
one's mouth, suck off the meat and spit out the bones.
</P>
<P>
   Lou doesn't recommend that people try the chicken feet unless
they are very brave. Instead, she steers newcomers toward the
dumplings, steamed buns and pastries.
</P>
<P>
   A dim sum aficionado, Lou dispenses advice about the Chinese
delicacies whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have never had dim sum, give it a try,'' Lou said.
``Everything is very fresh, very delicious. Don't be afraid to
experiment with food. You may find you really like it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Spring Rolls &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``Classic Deem Sum'')
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marinade:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons oyster sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Shao Hsing wine or dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Filling:
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces pork, shredded
</P>
<P>
   8 dried black Chinese mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   5 Chinese cabbage leaves, green part only
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced gingerroot
</P>
<P>
   1/2 minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces shrimp, shelled, deveined, cleaned and shredded
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded bamboo shoots
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup shredded scallion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornstarch mixed with 1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   20 spring roll skins
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   Combine the marinade ingredients in a medium bowl. Add shredded
pork and mix well. Cover and marinate for 2 hours in the
refrigerator. Soak dried mushrooms in tepid water to cover for
about 30 minutes, or until soft and pliable. When reconstituted,
squeeze out water. Cut off and discard stems and mince caps. Cut
away white part of Chinese cabbage. Blanch green part in boiling
water for 1 minute. Plunge in bowl of cold water to halt cooking.
Drain and squeeze out excess water. Cut leaves into 1-inch strips
lengthwise and shred to make about 1 cup. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare remaining filling ingredients, arranging them separately
on a work platter.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 tablespoons oil in wok over medium heat. Using the steel
spatula, coat the sides of the wok with hot oil. Stir-fry ginger
and garlic for about 10 seconds. Turn heat up high and add
marinated pork. Stir-fry until pork turns white. Add shrimp and
stir-fry until pink. Add mushrooms, Chinese cabbage, bamboo shoots
and scallion. Stir-fry for 2 more minutes. Add chicken stock.
</P>
<P>
   Add cornstarch-water mixture and continue to stir-fry until
liquid thickens. Spread filling on plate to cool to room
temperature. Keep spring roll skins under a damp towel. Remove one
skin and place it on the work surface. Place about 2 tablespoons of
stuffing on the skin about 1 inch from the edge nearest to you.
Fold the near edge over the filling. Fold over the right and left
sides. Roll up and seal with beaten egg. Set aside, sealed side
down, covered with plastic wrap. Continue with the remaining
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Spring rolls may be refrigerated or frozen at this point until
ready to fry.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange spring rolls, paper toweling or wine rack, and utensils
such as wire mesh strainer and cooking chopsticks, in convenient
fashion around the cooking area. Be sure your wok cover and
extinguisher are handy in case of an oil fire.
</P>
<P>
   Add 6 cups of oil to wok. Attach deep-frying thermometer and
heat to slightly above cooking temperature of 375. Add a spring
roll to the oil and fry until golden brown, about 3 to 4 minutes.
Turn several times while frying. Remove and sample. The interior
filling should be heated through. The exterior crust should be
golden brown and not oily or greasy. Adjust time and temperature
and fry the remaining spring rolls a few at a time, replacing one
each time one is removed from the oil. Drain on a wire rack or
paper toweling. Just before serving, you may want to cut the spring
rolls into 3 or 4 bite-size pieces with kitchen scissors. Serve hot
or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 20 rolls. Approximate values per roll: 154 calories, 3 g
fat, 15 mg cholesterol, 25 g carbohydrates, 3.2 mg fiber, 316 mg
sodium, 15 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp Moons
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Classic Deem Sum'')
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces shrimp
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces pork fat, minced fine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely shredded bamboo shoots
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon tapioca starch
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Shao Hsing wine or dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   30 3-inch-diameter round dough wrappers
</P>
<P>
   Shell and devein shrimp. Place in a bowl, sprinkle with 1
teaspoon of salt and mix well with the fingers. Rinse in several
changes of cold water and drain thoroughly. Dice shrimp to large
pea size.
</P>
<P>
   Place shrimp, pork fat and bamboo shoots in a bowl and add 1/2
teaspoon salt. Add sugar, pepper, tapioca starch and wine or
sherry. Mix thoroughly, cover, and refrigerate for 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Soak bamboo steamer in water for about 10 minutes. Place about a
teaspoon of shrimp mixture on a wrapper. Fold in half (making a
half-moon shape) and pinch at the center. Pleat and press edges
together to seal. Work from each end toward center. Form dumpling
into half-moon shape as you pleat. Prepare all of the dumplings in
this manner. Place on an oiled plate, cover with plastic wrap, and
refrigerate or freeze until ready to steam.
</P>
<P>
   Wipe steamer basket dry and lightly oil the inside bottom. Place
hot water in the wok to come within 1 inch of the bottom of the
steamer. Boil over high heat. Have additional hot water on hand to
replenish as necessary. Arrange dumplings in steamer, leaving space
between each. Cover and steam over rapidly boiling water for 10
minutes. Serve with Soy Sauce-Chili Pepper-Oil Vinegar Dip.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 30 dumplings. Approximate values per dumpling: 18
calories, 1 g fat, 13 mg cholesterol, 0.2 g carbohydrates, 0 fiber,
118 mg sodium, 55 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
