<SLUG> BC-DIM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
700-YEAR FAVORITE: CHINESE DUMPLING  
 (WITH DIM SUM AND PHOTOS) 
</HEADLINE>
 SUM-SIDE-FOOD-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER CUSHMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Although many Americans are discovering dim sum, these
delicious dumplings have been an integral part of Chinese culture
for seven centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient art of dim sum began as bite-size snacks for Chinese
emperors during the Sung dynasty (960-1279), according to the book
``Classic Deem Sum, Recipes from the Yank Sing Restaurant in San
Francisco.'' When the Mongols invaded China in the 13th century,
the royal court was forced to move slowly south. It took its
culinary traditions with it. Dim sum's popularity spread with each
stop, where common-folk chefs adapted the rich treats to blend with
their own tastes and food staples.
</P>
<P>
   By 1900, dim sum was the rage in China's southern Guangdong
province. Farmers headed to the scores of teahouses for nourishment
after long days in the fields. Dim sum remained a male-only
tradition for centuries. Over time, however, it filtered into
Chinese homes, where women would cook the treats for their families
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few decades, Chinese restaurants serving dim sum
have flourished in the various ``Chinatowns'' found throughout the
United States. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1448EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2183 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     09-30 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S HOPING HIS BIRTHDAY IS JUST AS SWEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A reader recently wrote looking for the recipe for a Norwegian
cream cake to make for her husband for his birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blotkake'' is one of the marvels of Scandinavian cooking,
showing off one of the country's wonderful dairy products. This is
the country, after all, where if you order hot chocolate in a
restaurant, it appears at your table along with a crystal bowl of
whipped cream to use as topping. (And no nutritional gasps, please.
This is a country with one of the longest life expectancies in the
world.)
</P>
<P>
   This recipe for ``blotkake'' is from a cookbook put together by
Friendship Force, a cultural-exchange program.
</P>
<P>
   BLOTKAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 scant cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 tablespoons liquid: milk, juice, lemonade, white wine,
sherry or liqueur
</P>
<P>
   1 pint whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 cups fresh berries: strawberries or raspberries
</P>
<P>
   Butter bottom of 9-inch springform pan. Beat eggs and sugar
until well-combined. Combine flour and baking powder and fold
gently into the eggs, until batter becomes smooth. Place in pan and
bake for 25 minutes on the lower shelf of a preheated oven at
350-375 degrees. Set aside for a few minutes, then remove cake to
cool on wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   Split cake into two layers and dribble half of the chosen liquid
over each cake half, especially around the edges, but do not allow
to get soggy. Whip cream and add 1 teaspoon sugar. Set aside 1 cup
of berries; cut the rest into small pieces and add remaining sugar.
Spread berry pieces on the bottom layer, add 1/3 of the whipped
cream, top with the second layer and cover the entire cake with
remaining whipped cream. Decorate the top with whole berries.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 427 calories, 25 grams fat, 45
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 190 milligrams cholesterol,
142 milligrams sodium, 54 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``When the Family Gathers'' by Beverlie Reilman (Longstreet,
$16.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   More sweet stuff: Linda Porter of Bedford, Texas, saw our
request for sponge candy and sends the recipe she has been making
for years. She says this candy costs about $4 a pound in candy
stores.
</P>
<P>
   SPONGE CANDY
</P>
<P>
   Yields 10 pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dark corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, syrup and vinegar in saucepan. Cook over medium
heat until sugar dissolves. Continue cooking without stirring until
candy thermometer reaches 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat, quickly stir in baking soda and mix well. Pour
onto a lightly buttered pan or buttered foil. Don't spread. Cool
and break into pieces. Dip in melted chocolate, if you like.
</P>
<P>
   If there are dark spots in the candy after it is broken, it
means the soda wasn't mixed in well enough. The flavor will still
be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 173 calories, 0 fat, 45 grams
carbohydrates, 0 protein, 0 cholesterol, 269 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   REQUESTS: Carol Evitt Stephens of Fort Worth attended Eastern
Hills High School from 1966-68. She writes that the cooks at the
school were wonderful and made terrific cinnamon rolls. Does anyone
have that recipe?
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Adams of Fort Worth would like a recipe for beer batter
for chicken. She used to have the recipe for the batter used at the
old La Barn's on Camp Bowie but has lost it.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Spencer of Fort Worth, is looking to replace recipes for
zucchini boats and stuffed summer squash. Both recipes could be
cooked on an outdoor grill.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Snapka of Arlington, Texas, would like a recipe for divinity
that uses Jell-O to give it a pink or green color and yields a
strawberry or lime flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Bradshaw of Fort Worth, would like a recipe for Wyatt
Cafeteria's pumpkin muffins. She writes that she remembers cutting
out this recipe in October or November 1990.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
