<HEADLINE>
A COMMON FATE IS IN STORE FOR ALL MOMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a wise old Indian scout surveying hoofprints in the sand,
mothers know. Like a meteorologist watching a barometer fluctuate
from high to low, mothers know. Like a pathologist observing
microscopic images of cells, mothers know.
</P>
<P>
   Psychic? No. But like size-9 feet in size-8 shoes on a five-mile
nature hike, some things are just predictable. What do mothers
know? We know when we absolutely, positively, without a doubt, have
no choice but to go to the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it starts with the little things. The warning signs of
impending starvation. First, I run out of pop, cookies and ice
cream. Who cares? It's a bunch of fat and sugar, and the kids
really do need to drink more water.
</P>
<P>
   A few days pass and the children grumble a bit, but there just
aren't enough hours left at the end of my day, so I postpone the
inevitable and make a pitcher of Kool-Aid. Yeah, the colorful sugar
water buys me some time, but then the eggs and milk are all gone.
The natives become restless. They tape a grocery list to my
windshield. It's small. I can see around it. So I drive off and
ignore it for another day. Milk gives me gas, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Soon we're down to those funny little brown slices of bread,
frozen meat and canned goods. I have the best intentions, but after
a full day at the office, I'm just too exhausted to stalk up and
down the aisles of the grocery store in search of macaroni. Yes, I
am aware that some grocery stores deliver to your door, but my
mother taught me to pick fruit the way her mother taught her to
pick fruit, and my great-grandma grew her own fruit. I just gotta
pick out my own fruit, no matter how inconvenient it may be.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the family tires of my pitiful offerings of burgers,
chicken and pizza every night. When I arrive home, they're standing
outside in a picket line blocking the driveway, chanting: ``We want
some real food! We want some slow food!''
</P>
<P>
   I crawl out of the car and throw myself at their feet. ``Please,
please, just give me one more day. I promise I'll go to the grocery
store tomorrow. I will not come home without some brown paper sacks
and coupons.''
</P>
<P>
   They relent and allow me to enter the house. To escape their
hostile glares, I retreat to the bathroom. A few minutes later, I
notice that we are out of toilet tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone bring me a roll of toilet tissue!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, bring me a box of Kleenex, please.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Napkins?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Paper towels?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Then my husband slides an old cleaning rag under the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you crazy? I'd rather have the blow dryer.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly motivated, I grab my car keys and head for the grocery
store. Nine at night is a good time to shop, by the way. No crowds
or long lines. Home again, and the family greets me with cheers and
smiles. As they put the groceries away, I remember that the
weatherman has forecast rain for the next day. As I start to check
the coat closet, my oldest son screams: ``Wait! Mom, don't!''
</P>
<P>
   Too late. Inside the closet are several rolls of toilet tissue,
boxes of Kleenex, paper towels, napkins, and my blow dryer.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, I guess mothers don't always know, after all.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
