<SLUG> BC-BBA-OAKLAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING BEATS BEING A FORMER OAKLAND PLAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Mark McGwire leaves Oakland and hits 100
homers in a year and a half. Sandy Alderson leaves Oakland and gets
a cushy job in the commissioner's office trying to bring Major
League Baseball to Monte Carlo. And I think we all know what
happens next.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Stairs leaves Oakland and becomes Secretary of Health and
Human Services in the Tipper Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   Plainly, there must be something to being from Oakland that
makes it better than being in Oakland, at least if you're in the
baseball business. Thus, it is this fact, rather than any other,
that should puzzle and bother Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann as they
begin their fourth year of ownership of the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   We're not saying that it does, necessarily. Only that it should.
</P>
<P>
   The only real difference between McGwire and Alderson, when it
is all boiled down, is that McGwire never missed a chance to roast
the owners for their seemingly indifferent commitment to the ball
team.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson, on the other hand, never took a chance to do the same.
He would defend Schott and Hofmann's essential strategy of trying
to make a few bucks with a bad product in hopes of offering a shiny
little runabout to an eager buyer, and always found it easy to
gloss over the basic hole in the logic _ that making a few bucks
for the owner only does something for the owner, and a happy owner
is hard to market.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a careful observer knew Alderson's heart wasn't matching
his rhetoric (remember, he cut his teeth in baseball working for
Walter Haas, against whom most any owner would look shrewish and
dim), it wasn't hard to see how the relentless and seemingly
bottomless trail of losses was fouling Alderson's humor. He was the
loyal employee to the end, but he spoke loudest when he left
without saying a single bad word about his former bosses. He said
it with his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland _ Cradle Of Someone Else's Good Time. Again.
</P>
<P>
   There had been rumors that Alderson might at some point be
trying to collect investors to buy the team from Schott and
Hofmann, but nobody will know if Alderson had any luck or whether
he had ever tried. As was the case about the Oakland situation,
Alderson keeps the secrets he wants to keep.
</P>
<P>
   What we know now is, he always wanted to stay in the San
Francisco Bay area because both he and his family loved it so.
Then, he decided to leave. Being third in line for Bud Selig's
cushy chair is, frankly, not that good a tradeoff unless he
adjudged the situation in Oakland (six years of losing, dwindling
crowds and pewter gray atmosphere) had become unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   Schott's answer to this grinding dilemma was at least honest. He
and Hofmann will not spend more than they take in, which means the
payroll is likely to shrink even further next year. He and Hofmann
still are engaged in trench warfare with the Coliseum about the
stadium lease and the broken promises and slights on behalf of the
Raiders. He doesn't have any immediate ideas about how to stop the
fire drill to warmer and happier climes.
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, but if he had a new stadium ... God, it just makes your
head crack open.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Schott's solution is relatively simple, and it doesn't
require moving vans in the middle of the night. First, operate the
team as though winning were the first objective, rather than a very
distant second. Second, keep every good player on site and hire
someone who can find the rest. Third, leave him and those he hires
to do their jobs without let or hindrance.
</P>
<P>
   Schott knows all that, though. Of course he does. Nobody ever
reached Final Jeopardy claiming that either he or Hofmann were
stupid. He said it himself Monday: ``I know that you have to spend
$40 million to put yourself in the arena of real competitiveness.
Sure I can divide the number of victories we had by the money we
spent and say, `Hey, we did a lot better than a lot of other
teams.' That doesn't make me feel any better.''
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't change anything, because that's not how score is
kept. If he wanted to win first, he would have put his and
Hofmann's money where Alderson's mouth was. Even if he had signed
McGwire two years ago, the payroll wouldn't have reached $30
million and the wins-per-dollar figure wouldn't have changed all
that much.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, maybe McGwire wouldn't have hit those 70 home runs
and been declared Lord High Sheriff of the Universe had he stayed
in Oakland. You can't take one set of facts, change a material
detail and expect everything else to stay the same.
</P>
<P>
   But he would have stayed, and nobody can make a sensible
argument saying that his staying would not have been a considerable
improvement, just as nobody can make a sensible argument for the
A's being better off without Alderson. Not the constricted,
frustrated apologist for cheap baseball that he was at the end, but
the bold, aggressive dealer he was in the Haas years, left to
thrive or dive on his own judgment rather than someone else's
mini-budget.
</P>
<P>
   So now the A's start 1999 with Billy Beane unchanged, except for
having half as much money to spend as the Giants, who are spending
about $10 million less than they ought to be for the kind of team
they have. That's no solution, either. That's just the prelude to a
press conference two years down the road, where we learn that Beane
is leaving to become a veejay at MTV. Because apparently nothing
beats being an ex-A.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
