<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIRK-FRANKLIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITH A NEW CD AND BOOK, KIRK FRANKLIN IS UNEASY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kirk Franklin has been doing interviews for two hours now _ and
he's been doing a good job of it, giving erudite, thoughtful
answers to any and all questions.
</P>
<P>
   There is much for the 28-year-old Fort Worth-bred gospel
superstar to talk about: His new CD, ``The Nu Nation Project,''
which features U2's Bono, R. Kelly, Mary J. Blige and Fred Hammond
(among others) as well as his own group, the Family, and God's
Property, the group he shepherded to enormous success last year via
a 2-million-selling debut album, ``God's Property From Kirk
Franklin's Nu Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also his autobiography, ``Church Boy.'' It's a fairly
no-punches-pulled account of growing up poor in Fort Worth, making
more than a few mistakes and finally rising to superstardom.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin is the biggest name in gospel music. But at this
moment, as another interview commences, he may also be the most
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the biggest challenge is, I feel like a fish out of
water,'' he says. ``I'm not built for this stuff: promos and
interviews and autographs and all this. The secular world makes me
uncomfortable. I'm a church boy; I need to be on the corner with a
Bible somewhere. I'll be glad when it's five or six months from now
and the CD's been out a while and this part of it is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin is also truly nervous about ``The Nu Nation Project,''
which brings together all the styles he loves: traditional and
modern gospel, hip-hop, jazz, rock, R&AMP;B. Several times during the
interviews, he asks people if they like the CD. He's more like a
teen-ager who has just cut his first demo tape than a man who has
sold more than 5 million albums.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the nervousness is also because this is his first CD
since a fall from a stage in Memphis in November 1996 left him in
intensive care for days and gave him horrible headaches for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   He says he has no physical problems related to the accident and
views the incident as pivotal to his development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never graduated high school; I never walked across that
stage,'' he says. ``My fall in Memphis was my graduation; it took
me from a boy to a man. When you see death, it changes you.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's another reason Franklin is nervous. He may have
helped gospel cross over to the pop and R&AMP;B markets more than
anyone else in history, but he is well aware that a lot of people
may like the beats but not the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many barriers about what I do,'' he says. ``The
majority of society isn't trying to hear about Jesus. Sex sells.
Women still dance to music that calls them whores. That confuses
me. When a young black man says `Jesus loves you,' people don't
want to hear it. All we're saying is, `Give Jesus a try.' We're not
doggin' anybody out; we're not saying Jesus can beat up on
Buddha.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lean on Me,'' the CD's flagship single, includes vocals from
Bono, R. Kelly, Mary J. Blige and Crystal Lewis. ``When you get
some big hitters on a record, more people listen,'' Franklin says.
``It's a tool. The purpose never changes, but the tools do. For me,
it was a song about issues that as Christians we don't deal with.
In church, we can be so busy shouting, we can not recognize that
the person next to us is dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin recruited friends Kelly and Blige, and Bono was
suggested by producer Jimmy Iovine, who has worked with U2.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in high school, U2 was the group,'' Franklin says.
``I was going to the Professional Youth Conservatory, and I was the
only black kid there. A guy named Perry loved U2, and they have a
very spiritual thing. Jimmy suggested Bono, and I was like, `Get
outta here.' I was honored to have him. We flew to Dublin, and he
recorded his song.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin was only in Ireland one day, however. He flew in, got
Bono's vocals and flew back. Why? The next day was his daughter
Kennedy's birthday, and he wasn't about to miss it. Franklin says
his family _ wife Tammy and children Kerrion, Carrington and
Kennedy _ are the most important part of his life, because he
realizes that however famous he is, he won't always be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's your life,'' he says, pointing at a copy of the new
CD lying on a table, ``you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
