<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKLIN-CHURCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIRK FRANKLIN TELLS HOW HE OVERCAME
</HEADLINE>
 BOY-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did well in the NFL for a few seasons? You get a book.
</P>
<P>
   Did well at the Olympics? You get a book.
</P>
<P>
   Had an affair with your father or a famous writer, or want to
whine about how many drugs you hoovered and how hard your poor
little life is? You get a book.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, most of it, all feeding our insatiable need for yet
another personality to examine for a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Church Boy'' (Word Publishing, $12.99), Kirk Franklin's new
autobiography, flies in the face of all that, mainly because at age
28 the Fort Worth gospel superstar has an amazing story to tell.
Nobody else has come so far so fast _ at least in gospel music _
and therein lies a tale with as many twists and turns as a novel.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Church Boy,'' which Franklin dictated to ghost writer Jim
Nelson Black during the 1997 international Tour of Life, he talks
candidly about being adopted by his aunt, Gertrude Franklin, when
his teen-age mother, Deborah, was unable and unwilling to take care
of him. He talks about being teased because of his small size and
his love of church, and abouy a wild spell as a teen that included
smoking marijuana and briefly being homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin wrote this, he said, to ``share my junk,'' to show how
God can take self-esteem problems and internal struggles and use
them to the greater good.
</P>
<P>
   Reading ``Church Boy'' is a lot like kicking back and talking
with Franklin _ and, at the same time, like listening to him preach
in concert. He will always emphasize that God is working in
people's lives, whether they know and admit it or not, and such is
the case here.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
