<SLUG> BC-JUSTICE-O'CONNOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE O'CONNOR DEDICATES TEXAS SCHOOL NAMED IN HER HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LUCY HOOD  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor
encouraged students to meet the challenges of a changing world at
the Tuesday dedication of a high school named in her honor.
</P>
<P>
   She used her life and the strides made by women as an example.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, the first woman named to the Supreme Court, recalled
her graduation from a high school in El Paso named after Texas
colonizer Stephen F. Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, women did not hold public office and no
self-respecting Texan would name a school after a woman,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, 68, graduated from the law school at Stanford
University in 1952. Despite an initial job offer as a legal
secretary, she went on to become an assistant attorney general in
Arizona and a state senator before President Ronald Reagan named
her to the Supreme Court in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``In less than one generation, conditions for women in the
United States have changed dramatically,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said it was the responsibility of today's young people to
meet contemporary challenges by contributing to society.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will have to know how to build new institutions to meet
the needs of the 21st century,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said she was honored that students chose her name for
the new Northside District high school. ``You can't imagine what a
special day this is for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first high school in the nation that carries
O'Connor's name.
</P>
<P>
   All high schools in the Northside District are named for Supreme
Court justices and students vote to select the name. Superintendent
Ed Rawlinson said the students voted overwhelmingly to name the
school for O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Harle, a junior at the school who introduced the
Supreme Court justice, said she was motivated by O'Connor's
selection as the first woman on the Supreme Court _ as well as
another factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't leave out the fact that she's a native of Texas,''
Harle said.
</P>
<P>
   The $28.6 million school opened in August with 1,848 students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
