<P>
   NY-RED-HOOK (New York) _ The Red Hook section of Brooklyn has a
spring in its step. But will it falter under 10,000 tons of the
city's waste a day? The old 48-acre Todd Shipyard here is one of
sites three in Brooklyn and one in the South Bronx that are
reportedly being considered for a garbage transfer station. By Anne
Raver.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   POLLOCK-KRASNER-HOUSE (The Springs. N.Y.) _ A tour of Eastern
Long Island's primary art-history attraction, the Pollock-Krasner
house. By Bob Morris.
</P>
<P>
   LAB-ANTI-MALL (Costa Mesa, Calif.) _ At one entrance to the Lab
Anti Mall stands a whimsical sculpture combining a head of Buddha
with a disco-style mirror ball. New Age spiritual, 1970s revival _
they sell it all here. The Lab, opened in 1994, the brainchild of a
developer named Shaheen Sadeghi, who came to the project with a
background in beach wear and a business degree, is postmodernist
retailing. Just as advertisements joke about advertisements, this
is a mall that jokes about malls. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKER-HOUSE (Pasadena, Calif.) _ At a $1,000-a-plate benefit
on Oct. 1 with the actor Brad Pitt as host, this city will toast
the restoration of a national treasure, the Robert R. Blacker
House. The house is one of the celebrated Ultimate Bungalows
designed at the turn of the century by the Arts and Crafts
architects Greene &AMP; Greene. By Joseph Giovannini.
</P>
<P>
   HARR-HOUSE (Northampton, Mass.) _ Jonathan Harr is a homebody.
His world by day _ and most nights _ is a book-lined study at the
front of a turn-of-the-century Victorian house in this college
town. In his study, Harr spent eight years writing ``A Civil
Action,'' a nonfiction blockbuster that has sold a million copies
since its publication in 1995. By Julie Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MORTGAGE-RATES (New York) _ How loooooooow can they go? With
the rates for many mortgages a full percentage point below where
they were a year ago, prospective co-op and condominium buyers in
Manhattan are asking their mortgage brokers whether they should
take the plunge or wait until the stock market _ or interest rates
_ take another dive. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
