<HEADER>
A2286 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANKLIN-CD-TEX     09-30 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKLIN-CD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANKLIN FUSES STYLES INTO A STELLAR `NU NATION'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kirk Franklin
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nu Nation Project''
</P>
<P>
   Gospo Centric Records
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 1/2 out of 5 stars various styles that, as always, is
the underpinning for his message of love for God.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to appreciate how good this CD is unless you listen to
most other modern gospel music. Dozens of acts have sprung up in
Franklin's wake, trying to improve upon his hip-hop-meets-gospel
formula.
</P>
<P>
   Most sound like pale imitations _ and none is going to catch him
now. This album encompasses modern gospel, touches of '40s jazz,
some hard-rock guitar worthy of Prince's ``Purple Rain'' era, lush
orchestral work, easygoing pop/funk, and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin has never ranged so far afield, but ``Project'' never
sounds like a confused mishmash; he uses both the Family and God's
Property as the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   He has also never used so many guest artists, but here again,
it's not just a matter of getting famous names to sing with him;
it's a matter of integrating them into the songs. ``Lean on Me,''
featuring R. Kelly, Mary J. Blige, Bono and Crystal Lewis, will get
the most attention. But ``Something About the Name Jesus,'' which
features Rance Allen and Men of Standard working with the Family,
is as worthy an example.
</P>
<P>
   At its base, though, ``Project'' is about good ol'
Sunday-morning gospel _ updated and retooled for the late '90s, but
still tied into the sounds of uplifted voices bolstered by piano
and organ.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Revolution'' and ``Riverside'' Franklin weaves together
lyrics and hip-hop beats to hypnotic effect, like a church service
when everybody gets happy and nobody wants the song to end.
</P>
<P>
   And that, really, is Kirk Franklin's finest quality: He's rooted
in the church, but he knows about the street. More than any of his
previous albums, ``The Nu Nation Project'' is a complete work, one
in which he has truly said his piece.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1601EDT &QL; 
