government was going to pay for 75 percent of the costs, but the
severity of the damage required an increase. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   MAINE -- OUTLOK. The siege mentality has enveloped the Capitol
as the Lewinsky scandal passes the eight-month mark. Along the way,
Maine's lawmakers have seen their political agendas dwarfed by a
steady dose of sex revelations involving President Clinton and now
members of Congress. They are a frustrated group, at the same time
urging caution and fairness about the allegations and hoping that,
above all else, it will be resolved quickly. In the meantime, they
try to go about their daily business. Kane
</P>
<P>
