<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELICITY-TV-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FELICITY' LIVES UP TO ITS HYPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a moment early on in ``Felicity'' that topples
expectations so thoroughly that it left me wondering whether its
creators were psychologically fit or simply naive in the ways of
network television.
</P>
<P>
   Felicity Porter (Keri Russell), the harried heroine of the most
dissected new TV series since ``NYPD Blue'' introduced a parade of
bare bottoms, asks her chiseled-face classmate Ben Covington (Scott
Speedman) to sign her high-school yearbook. ``Can you give me a
minute to do this?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   As he drops to the grass and begins to write ... and write ...
and write, the camera locks in and stays put. Felicity creeps
tentatively and awkwardly around him. She kneels, stares at the
ground, looks away. Is she excited or bewildered?
</P>
<P>
   I've watched this scene numerous times trying to figure out its
surreal attraction, and to marvel at Russell's facial aerobics. My
conclusion is the obvious: It speaks without saying anything. This
is a stylistic trick we readily accept in films but question in
prime-time TV, where a stately pace can be jolting and, in the age
of the remote control, cinematic suicide.
</P>
<P>
   This is partly why ``Felicity'' has become one of the few series
to appear in The Wall Street Journal and that other journal of
pop-culture analysis, ``Seventeen,'' before it even generates one
rating point.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, ``Felicity'' earns its hype for not just going
against the grain but, based on a well-crafted, crisply written,
engaging pilot by filmmaker J.J. Abrams (''Armageddon''), for being
intellectually delicious.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing to concern me is that everything I've read thus
far has been based on the pilot. The real test for dramatic serials
comes over a matter of weeks, after viewers have decided whether
returning is worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   If only from the saturated media coverage ``Felicity'' has
received, you probably know the basics: smart high school grad
ditches plans to attend Stanford (pre-med, all expenses paid
courtesy of Dad) and instead heads for the fictional University of
New York.
</P>
<P>
   As we learn from ``Felicity's'' voice-over (oh, you know it's
serious if there's a voice-over), she's a doctor's daughter with an
artist's soul, a young mind wanting and needing to color outside
the lines. She's never done anything impulsive; Dad has guided her
life up until this point.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, she begins assembling a support system, people who
in the pilot are merely character sketches. Noel Crane (Scott
Foley, fresh from a recurring role in ``Dawson's Creek'') is her
student resident adviser, geeky but cute and clearly nuts about
Felicity.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Emrick (Amy Jo Johnson) is a friend she meets while
sobbing in class. doesn't show up in the pilot but is listed in
press materials as ``a native New Yorker overly confident and
aggressively opinionated (who) shocks Felicity with her
freight-train personality.'']
</P>
<P>
   Pretty boy Ben is among the A team, too, and is a pivotal part
of what is becoming a WB signature element: the love triangle. (See
``Dawson's Creek, Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and the new ``Hyperion
Bay.'')
</P>
<P>
   Through the eyes of Felicity, we are supposed to learn about
college life, young love and lingering pain, that life is like
physics: Nothing really happens without effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicity'' will hinge on whether the drama offers characters
and not caricatures, crisp dialogue and not cliches, realistic
situations that don't fall into unhip pretentiousness.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Russell isn't enchanting. Having been in her share of
flops (see ``Malibu Shores'' and a batch of so-so made-for-TV
movies), she is trumpeted as an overnight sensation. This is an
insult. She's merely a good actor sinking her teeth into better
material.
</P>
<P>
   Russell manages to establish believability in a complicated
character who is so nervy and vulnerably ambivalent that she'd
probably psychoanalyze the nutritional value of a Happy Meal.
</P>
<P>
   Watch Russell's expressions as the camera pans on her during
emotional conversations, mostly with the university counselor, her
parents and Ben.
</P>
<P>
   Describing it earlier as facial aerobics isn't being cute; it's
the best way I can explain how she's one of those gifted actresses
able to say so much by saying absolutely nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You provoke me,'' Ben tells her near the end of tonight's
pilot. ``You make me think about things that I never think about.
Without saying anything. Just by the way you look at me.''
</P>
<P>
   You, too?
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/
</P>
</TEXT>
