<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2397 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WRITING-RECOGNITI     09-30 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WRITING-RECOGNITION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLEASHING THE POWER OF THE PEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ore., N.Y., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dr. Oreste Bruni rushes around the emergency room at the
Massapequa General Hospital in Seaford, N.Y., hands-on medicine is
not his only occupation. Like all doctors in that fast-paced world,
he's busy taking notes _ notes to guide later treatment and help
insure payment for both him and the hospital. Such notes can even
become vital evidence if a malpractice suit is filed.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 90s, Bruni tried to move into the electronic age by
taking notes on laptop computers that used special screens and pens
rather than keys for entering text and commands. He bought and
tried four different models, but their awkward weight, size and
shape ultimately forced him to abandon them all.
</P>
<P>
   Bruni has returned to taking notes with a ballpoint pen and a
standard yellow notepad, 8{ by 11 inches, but there is a
difference. Since last spring, he has been slipping those pads onto
a clipboard that silently creates an electronic version of his
medical charts as he writes with ink on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Then, if Bruni chooses, handwriting-recognition software takes
those electronic records and translates them _ more or less _ into
text that can be handled by a word-processing program.
</P>
<P>
   He has switched to one of the devices that is making people take
a new look at word-recognition software: the Crosspad, developed by
International Business Machines and the pen maker A.T. Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Handwriting-recognition software has generally been tailored for
either large- or small-scale use. Huge systems are used by large
corporations and agencies like the United States Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, personal digital assistants like 3Com's Palm
Pilot offer limited recognition ability. The Crosspad's Ink Manager
software and Smart-writer by Advanced Recognition Technologies are
trying to bring some of the more advanced features of larger
systems to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The Crosspad, the latest attempt to link handwriting and
computers, uses a pen with a miniature radio transmitter. While the
user writes in ink, the pen beams its movements to a computer in
the clipboard, which assembles the data into a digital image of the
scribblings.
</P>
<P>
   The Crosspad has enough memory to hold an electronic record of
more than 50 written pages. The computer files can be uploaded onto
any computer that has a Pentium processor and runs Windows 95 or 98
or NT.
</P>
<P>
   IBM and Cross hope that the Crosspad, which came on the market
in the spring, will join PDAs like the Palm Pilot as a
handwriting-recognition gadget of choice for well-heeled executives
and professionals.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cross introduced a smaller, lighter model that uses
steno-size notebooks. IBM and Cross officials say they expect other
companies to have Crosspad copycats available by spring.
</P>
<P>
   The pages captured by a Crosspad are like fax images in a
computer _ they are graphical depictions of text and drawings, not
text that can be manipulated by a word-processing program.
</P>
<P>
   The Crosspad includes handwriting-recognition software to
convert such notes into text, but such software tends to make a lot
of errors, depending on the handwriting. One early
handwriting-recognition product, the Newton from Apple, became
widely known after it was parodied in the Doonesbury comic strip
because of the comical errors its software sometimes produced.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Pilots and similar PDAs also offer handwriting recognition,
but users must write in special script with a stylus on small
liquid-crystal-display screens.
</P>
<P>
   James Landay, a professor specializing in user-interface
research at the University of California at Berkeley, said that
with PDAs, ``the screen resolution is pretty poor and you're
writing on something smaller than a Post-It note.'' He is now
trying a Crosspad.
</P>
<P>
   Pen-based laptops have evolved as heavy-duty tools for
professionals in the field. They tend to have a short battery life
and slippery writing surfaces. One pen-based Thinkpad that IBM
marketed in hospitals weighed nearly seven pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurses weren't going to carry it around all day unless they
were ex-East German swimmers,'' recalled Krishna Nathan, who
studies handwriting recognition at IBM's Thomas J. Watson Research
Center, where he is the laboratory's senior manager for consumer
devices.
</P>
<P>
   IBM changed its thinking with the Crosspad. ``We were focusing
on trying to solve the problem of the pen and forgot about
everything that paper's really good at,'' Nathan said. ``After all,
paper offers the ultimate in portability.''
</P>
<P>
   The Crosspad's main advantage over paper alone is the ability to
search for bits of information in notes and retrieve them. Crosspad
users can circle words to make them keywords that can be searched
for later.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate prize, of course, with products like the Crosspad
is the ability to translate notes into standard computer text. The
Crosspad comes with IBM Ink Manager software to do that.
</P>
<P>
   One person who uses the handwriting-recognition software to
convert his Crosspad notes into text is Marc Demarest, chief
executive of DP Applications, a software developer in Portland,
Ore. He immediately converts all his notes into text and stores
them in programs like Microsoft Word, he said, never saving the
graphic images of his writing.
</P>
<P>
   But neither IBM nor Cross seems willing to trumpet the ability
to transform notes into computer text. Officials in both companies
vividly remember the mockery directed at other ambitious
handwriting-recognition claims and are cautious about claiming too
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would describe Crosspad first and foremost as a note-capture
and note-management device,'' said Brian Mullins, director of
marketing for the Cross Pen Computer Group. ``The level of
satisfaction with our product for handwriting recognition is all
over the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the disclaimers, the Crosspad is clearly, along with
PDAs, the latest in a series of steps to restore respectability to
handwriting recognition.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nathan says sorting out pen scratches is a more difficult
problem than its sibling software challenge, voice recognition.
``Speech has evolved as a means of communication,'' he said.
``There's no point in me making sounds if you can't understand
them. But when we come to writing, we do not tend to write for
others, we tend to write for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   An unscientific survey of 400 executives by Cross found that 49
percent of them had trouble reading their own handwriting.
</P>
<P>
   As people use computers more, the handwriting problem becomes
more difficult. In two decades of grappling with the problem,
Professor Sargur Srihari, director of the Center of Excellence for
Document Analysis and Recognition at the State University of New
York at Buffalo, has noticed a steady decline in the quality of
handwriting, at least in affluent nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems there is less of an emphasis on it because of
computers,'' Srihari said. ``There is a sense that the classroom
time that was once devoted to penmanship is now devoted to
keyboarding.''
</P>
<P>
   But handwriting remains overwhelmingly the favored method for
taking notes at business meetings, in schools and for many job
activities. The Cross survey found that 72 percent of its
respondents still took handwritten notes on paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my world, there is nothing more annoying than someone in a
meeting banging away on a laptop keyboard _ rat-a-tat-tatting on
the damned thing,'' Demarest wrote in an e-mail message. ``It's
intrusive, ostentatious and ultimately stifles the free flow of
conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Software for handwriting recognition uses vast digital libraries
of writing samples. Complex pattern-recognition algorithms _
mathematical approaches to the problem _ sort through the samples
and develop statistics on the most likely forms letters and numbers
take.
</P>
<P>
   Handwriting recognition works reasonably well if users print
carefully in capital letters (called discrete handwriting) and
limit the amount of text. The Palm Pilot solves the problem by
having people learn to write in a special manuscript-type script it
calls Graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Casio's Cassiopeia E-10, which uses Microsoft's Windows CE
operating system, has a slightly more sophisticated
handwriting-recognition program known as Jot, from the
Communication Intelligence Corp. It recognizes characters that more
closely resemble standard printing and allows users to make notes
anywhere on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing individual letters and numbers is the easy part.
``Computers are pretty good today at individual recognition of
shapes in isolation,'' Srihari said. ``Recognizing words is where
they fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Handwriting-recognition programs that are more ambitious than
those found in most PDAs use two techniques simultaneously to
translate scribbles into words and sentences. The holistic approach
tries to pluck out entire words that match dictionary entries.
</P>
<P>
   Analytical algorithms break down pen strokes into fine divisions
to discover, using probability, individual letters that can then be
assembled into words.
</P>
<P>
   Handwriting-recognition programs must be trained to read a
specific user's writing style. The Crosspad's Ink Manager software
requires a tedious teaching process. The user copies such phrases
as, ``Do you know why America presently accounts for about 50
percent of world tuna consumption?'' IBM says Ink Manager can be
fully trained in about a half-hour. Demarest said he had toiled
with it for about 10 hours and wound up with an astounding accuracy
rate of 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mullins, the person at Cross responsible for selling the
Crosspad, says the recognition software often fails him. ``I have
terrible handwriting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After training the Crosspad software for a half-hour, I entered
some of the interview notes for this article but had little
success. ``They were very heavy'' was rendered by Ink Manager as
``REX we in lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Large sections of notes looked as if they had been written in a
long-forgotten language with a few contemporary English words.
</P>
<P>
   Crosspad is not the only product Cross offers with handwriting
recognition. The iPen Pro, a digital writing tablet that connects
to Windows-based PCs, is supplied with Smartwriter. Like Ink
Manager, Smartwriter requires training, although the company,
perhaps optimistically, says the process can be completed within
five minutes. Unlike the IBM software, Smartwriter converts each
word into text as it is written.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl for handwriting recognition might well be the
next United States Census, in 2000. The Census Bureau plans to
process all 1.4 billion personal and business forms electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Using a handwriting-recognition system developed by Associated
Solutions of Dallas, the bureau is hoping for 98 percent accuracy.
If the software can do that, the census may finally eliminate the
sour taste Apple's Newton brought to handwriting recognition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
