</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WBAP-50THANNIVERSARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WBAP CELEBRATES 50TH ANNIVERSARY AS SOUTHWEST'S FIRST TV STATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PERRY STEWART 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifty years ago this week, movie screens in this neck of the
woods offered such new films as ``Homecoming,'' with Clark Gable
and Lana Turner, at the Belknap Drive-In and ``Green Grass of
Wyoming'' (Charles Coburn) at the Hollywood Theater in downtown
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   That same evening in 1948, the 1935 Leslie Howard opus ``The
Scarlet Pimpernel'' was showing on several hundred smaller screens.
</P>
<P>
   It may not have seemed so at the time, but the big show was on
the small screen. Or, rather, the big show WAS the small screen.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Sept. 29, 1948, WBAP-TV signed on the air as the
first TV station in the Southwest. Announcer Frank Mills pronounced
the call letters. Then there were welcoming remarks by station
founder and Fort Worth Star-Telegram Publisher Amon G. Carter Sr.
and station director Harold Hough. The Star-Telegram owned WBAP
radio and WBAP-TV (now KXAS/Channel 5).
</P>
<P>
   Those formalities accomplished, fiddler Mel Cox and his Flying X
Ranch Boys struck up a lively country-western tune on the state's
first locally sponsored and locally produced variety show.
</P>
<P>
   Although this was the ``official'' inaugural of WBAP-TV, the
first public images over the new station were telecast two days
earlier, when President Truman's re-election campaign train stopped
briefly at the T&AMP;P terminal in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our true license date wasn't until Sept. 29, but President
Truman was coming to town on the 27th,'' Mills recalled. ``Someone
said, `Mr. Carter wants to televise the president's visit.' So, OK,
that was that. We would find a way to put that on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The loophole was that the Truman telecast was called a ``test,''
said Lee Elsesser, producer of various events and telecasts linked
to the 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people saw the president at the train station than on TV,
because there weren't that many TV sets in town,'' Elsesser said.
</P>
<P>
   The sets would come, however, and within a half-dozen years the
programs would be broadcast in color. Carter pulled the switch that
transferred Channel 5 to color May 15, 1954.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of programming at WBAP-TV may have seemed bland to
those 1948 viewers. But there was plenty of drama behind the
cameras. During the executives' introductory remarks, a truck ran
into a utility pole near the station, knocking out power for 17
frantic minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The horror wasn't over. Reels of ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' were
improperly cued, so when the movie began, the picture was upside
down and backward _ running from end to beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's not surprising that, as the Star-Telegram noted in
its coverage of the big day, ``The station will not be on the air
Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   Channel 5 returned Friday, though, with NBC news at 7 p.m., the
redoubtable Flying X Ranch Boys at 7:10, and, at 7:45, a high
school football game between Paschal and Amarillo. The station was
on the air about four hours per evening, Wednesdays through
Sundays. And, the newspaper article added:
</P>
<P>
   ``Test patterns will be aired 15 minutes before program time, in
addition to tests from 10 a.m. to noon and from 3 p.m. to 5 p.m.
Monday through Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're over 45, you probably recall that people really did
tune in those test patterns and use them to adjust their sets. Some
people also turned up the volume so they could hear the piercing
audio tone. (''Yep, sound's workin' OK. We should have a rasslin'
match in a couple a hours.'')
</P>
<P>
   WBAP-TV did, indeed, telecast wrestling matches from its trusty
remote truck. On a higher plane _ intellectually and celestially _
the station premiered ``Weather Telefacts,'' the region's first
professional weather program, on Halloween night, 1949. The
weathermen were Bob Denney, Walter Porter and a youngster named
Harold Taft. Taft went on to become a cherished institution who, at
the time of his death in 1991, was arguably the most popular on-air
figure in Channel 5 history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, WBAP-TV was sold to Lynn Broadcasting. Because the
station no longer shared a common owner with WBAP Radio, one had to
change its call letters. The TV operation became KXAS. NBC now owns
KXAS/Channel 5.
</P>
<P>
   WBAP plunged fearlessly into local programming. A popular entry
of the 1950s was a teen variety show sponsored by Foremost milk and
featuring a fresh-faced collegian named Pat Boone _ who commuted
from Denton, where he was a student at North Texas State University
(now the University of North Texas). Luther Adkins, a retired
Star-Telegram vice president who held a number of administrative
and on-air posts at WBAP-TV, recalled:
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat and his wife, Shirley, already had the first of their
girls then. So after every show, Pat would gather up all of the
milk product that was used in commercials and race back to Denton
with it before it spoiled.''
</P>
<P>
   Amon Carter and his new TV station did not have to outrun a lot
of other folks to get on the air first. In 1948, television was
still regarded as radio with pictures, a quaint toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought that Mr. Carter started the station
just so he could be the first,'' Elsesser said. ``They never
thought television could make any money.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
