<HEADLINE>
GORE CAMPAIGNS FOR DEMOCRATS IN CALIFORNIA'S CENTRAL VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Vice President Al Gore spent 24 hours in
California collecting campaign money for Democrats and giving back
a few tax dollars, while bolstering his party's profile among
crucial swing voters in the Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hollywood celebrities and Beverly Hills millionaires
may finance their campaigns, California Democrats and Republicans
know the only way to win Nov. 3 is to court middle-class voters
from Fresno to Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   After raising $750,000 for Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, the Democratic
gubernatorial candidate on Monday, the vice president spent a few
hours Tuesday in the state's heartland, where he announced $1.9
million in grants to help the police fight domestic violence,
toured a high school and helped raise money for other Democratic
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   At an evening fund-raiser in Sacramento, Gore criticized the
Republican-led Congress for its partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing they can agree on is personally attacking the
president of the United States,'' Gore told the $500-a-plate dinner
in Sacramento for Phil Angelides, who is running for treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the Congress of the United States ought to get on
with the business of the people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in Sacramento, Gore announced federal grants that would
unleash ``the crime-fighting power of community policing on the
scourge of domestic violence.'' Gore also announced a $20.2 million
grant to extend the city's light rail system.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dan Lungren, the Republican gubernatorial
candidate, called Gore's grant announcements election-year
largesse. ``It's Christmas,'' he said. ``Santa Claus is coming to
town. He's going to leave goodies all around the place. They don't
give it away on who's naughty or nice, they just do it on who's
going to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who took no questions from reporters, had traveled to
Sacramento from Fresno with former Assembly Speaker Cruz
Bustamante, who is running for lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising trip helps Democrats in several ways, not just
by raising money. Although the vast central spine of California is
home to only about 20 percent of the state's voters, the electorate
there is considered crucial to Davis and Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republican Southern California voters are checkmated by
Northern California Democrats,'' said Tim Hodson, executive
director of the Center for California Studies at California State
University at Sacramento. ``The balance tips in the Central
Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a Democratic stronghold, the vast farming and sprawling
suburban communities of Central California are about evenly divided
between Republican and Democratic voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
