<SLUG> BC-CIR-VIRTUAL-MANNEQUIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FASHION DREAM STAYS OUT OF REACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To a casual observer, the items inside the cardboard box I
hauled to the post office the other day might have seemed mundane:
a pair of jeans, a bright-colored tank top, black sneakers. But to
me, the box was full of disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was either the wrong size or the wrong cut or had
cheap rubber soles. The contents represented yet another setback in
my attempts to buy clothing that flatters rather than ridicules.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that's not the whole truth. Like so many statements
made on the highly charged subject of personal fashion, that was an
obfuscation. The truth? I am not willing to settle for flattering:
I want clothing that will make me look like Audrey Hepburn.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have entered a murky area of human need, where reality
and fantasy collide and people standing in front of a mirror fudge
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, I know I look nothing like the gamin actress _ nor
must I to fulfill the basic requirement of swathing myself in
appropriate fabrics to withstand the elements. But I harbor
fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   To try to preserve them, I rely on photos of how clothes look on
models in mail-order catalogs, instead of trying them on myself in
harshly lit dressing rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But the clothes often look different on me than on the catalog
models. That is why I got excited the other day about a new
software tool called Fashion Trip, which promised to let create an
on-screen mannequin in my own image.
</P>
<P>
   Then I could log on to a Web site to superimpose garments from
nearly 40 designers and manufacturers like Levi's, Esprit and
Jessica McClintock onto the mannequin before deciding whether to
purchase the clothing on line.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion Trip, developed by Moda CAD and distributed by Sierra
Online, was scheduled to go on sale for $39.95 in stores nationwide
Wednesday. But I got a review copy last week because I could not
wait: I had begun to imagine a program that would enable me to
create a personal database _ height, weight, age, measurements,
aversions to certain fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   I admit that on one level, I was fantasizing about finding a
dress that would scream ``Holly Golightly'' when draped across my
personal mannequin.
</P>
<P>
   But I also saw the possibility of a greater good. At its best,
the Internet is capable of smashing old paradigms about business
and life styles.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe Fashion Trip would be the first of a new generation of
software that would upend ideas about shopping, liberating untold
millions from the pain of wearing _ or at least buying _ clothes
that don't fit well.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the potential usefulness of that kind of product for,
say, parents shopping for school clothes. Instead of spending a
long afternoon at the mall with squirming offspring, the parent
would type in a child's measurements and shop on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Or think what a boon that could be to homebound shoppers unable
to get to the nearest mall.
</P>
<P>
   I held on to my high hopes, even after I opened Fashion Trip and
saw that it was aimed narrowly at shoppers 15 to 28 years old, a
group that has not included me for eight years. I knew I would
never use the program's chat feature to discuss clothes with other
friends logged onto the Moda CAD servers.
</P>
<P>
   I was willing to overlook the historical fashion facts sprinkled
throughout the technical manual: ``Body paint _ a late 60s
`futuristic' product _ was made so girls might coordinate their
skin color with the color of their miniskirts.''
</P>
<P>
   But then reality hit hard. As soon as I clicked on Expert Advice
to create my profile, I saw that the options for customizing the
mannequin were very limited. Faced with a choice of five body types
_ all of which looked like headless Barbies _ I gamely studied
them.
</P>
<P>
   Squinting, I could see how the bottom half of my body looked
like one of the types, the top half like another. I created two
profiles. I could try shirts on one, pants on another.
</P>
<P>
   Next I had a choice of five skin colors, ranging from light
beige to dark brown. Finally, the program asked my birthdate.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I clicked on Designer Picks to see which styles were
deemed most appropriate for the two Barbies. For the smaller-boned
one, a Silver Tab V-neck sweater (colors: camp green or ice) was
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   ``A slim fit V-neck sweater combined with hipster boot jeans
will be your fave uniform to throw on,'' the program assured me.
For the slightly fleshier Barbie: soft tailored jackets, but no
pointy shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I clicked on Fashion Tips, to be told, ``Do not buy
something you suspect may be hideous just because (a) it's cheap,
(b) it makes you look 10 lbs. thinner or (c) your best friend has
one just like it and it looks amazing on her.''
</P>
<P>
   I seemed to have run out of customization options. That was it?
I had the sinking feeling that anything I bought using this program
would end up in a box marked ``Return.`` After all, I didn't
resemble the Barbie bodies any more than I resemble catalog models.
</P>
<P>
   I phoned Moda CAD to see if the next generation of Fashion Trip
might offer a richer shopping experience. Moda CAD's vice president
of marketing, Linda Freedman, assured me that the technology exists
to create a fully customized profile, based on height, weight and
more specific body measurements. It would even be possible to scan
my photo into a correctly sized on-screen figure.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryan Weisberg, a Moda CAD senior product manager, said that
it probably wouldn't do any good if the software allowed a user to
create a more customized profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all goes back to the manufacturers,'' he said. ``The
manufacturers don't have products with customized breakdowns of
measurements.''
</P>
<P>
   I then wondered aloud about the possibility of a feature that
would enable a user to type in the name of the celebrity that the
shopper would most like to resemble. ``Maybe the software could
sort the available merchandise based on how well it fit the
criteria of the shopper's mental image,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   Or _ I just had a brainstorm _ what about adding one little
button that says, ``Click here for clothes Audrey Hepburn would
wear''?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm writing all this down,'' Ms. Freedman said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason I didn't buy the Silver Tab V-neck or any
other merchandise offered on Fashion Trip was that I didn't know
whether it would flatter me _ or even fit. But you know that's not
the whole truth. In the end, I just couldn't picture Audrey Hepburn
in hipster boot jeans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
