<HEADLINE>
STEAGALL AIRS `A BUNKHOUSE COMPANION'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN AUSTIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Red Steagall is no Garrison Keillor.
</P>
<P>
   Steagall, after all, writes about life Out West, not the
Lutherans in Lake Wobegon who populate Keillor's ``A Prairie Home
Companion.''
</P>
<P>
   But as it turns out, the poet/singer/songwriter and chronicler
of life on the range may well be on the way to creating the western
equivalent of Keillor's imaginary radio world at his own broadcast
bunkhouse, the syndicated ``Cowboy Corner.''
</P>
<P>
   About 120 stations from New York state to Canada's western
provinces carry the hourlong program, which Steagall launched
nearly five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The show blends western songs, chats with Reba McEntire, cowboy
poet Waddie Mitchell, Michael Martin Murphey and kindred
entertainers, and reminiscences and stories from real-life
ranchers, brand inspectors and wranglers. ``Cowboy Corner'' has
also included coups such as Steagall's interview with actor Ben
Johnson, thought to be the last before Johnson's death.
</P>
<P>
   Although Steagall produces ``Cowboy Corner'' at his 75-acre
spread near Azle, Texas, the action takes place in an imaginary
bunkhouse populated by a couple of cowpokes named Buck and Badger.
There's also a dog. They never speak, but Buck and Badger do
chuckle occasionally. The dog exists only as a taped sound effect,
but apparently it's pretty believable.
</P>
<P>
   Steagall said his producer once substituted a more aggressive
dog-bark sound effect for the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two different people called the same day wanting to know what
happened to the other dog,'' said Steagall, who ranges far and wide
with his digital audio-tape recorder to capture the interviews and
stories he brings back to Texas and weaves into the ``Cowboy
Corner.'' ``I tell you, if you listen to our show, you'll think
it's live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cowboy Corner'' executive producer and co-owner Stuart Balcom
said cowboy protocol is strictly observed, although there's no real
bunkhouse or buckaroos.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman has never stepped foot in the bunkhouse,'' Balcom
said. ``When we interviewed Reba McEntire, we interviewed her on
the front porch.''
</P>
<P>
   And contrary to what city slickers might think, there's still
western legend and lore left to explore. Steagall figures that
three-quarters of a million North Americans make their living on
horseback.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't see 'em from the freeway,'' Steagall said.
</P>
<P>
   Steagall said ratings are good, and figures that ``Cowboy
Corner'' will find an audience wherever listeners long for
wide-open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image of the West is very important to Americans,'' he
said. ``They dream of room. They want to get out in the open. They
want space.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
