<HEADLINE>
JUDGE THROWS OUT LAWSUIT AGAINST NEW YORK ATTORNEY GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A federal judge has dismissed a bitter and
protracted lawsuit that accused New York Attorney General Dennis
Vacco of turning the Department of Law into a political patronage
mill.
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Rosemary S. Pooler said in a decision dated
Monday that even if former assistant attorneys general Meredith H.
Savitt and Sue H.R. Adler were ousted for political reasons, as
they alleged, Vacco has the right to hire lawyers who share his
political views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public employees do not have an absolute right to be free of
patronage dismissal,'' Pooler wrote in a 28-page decision. ``If
party affiliation is an appropriate requirement for the effective
performance of a public office, the employer may make an employment
decision based on party affiliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Adler and Savitt, who are not Republicans, had the
authority to act and speak for the Republican attorney general,
there is a ``rational connection between shared ideology and ...
job performance,'' the Syracuse-based judge ruled. Pooler noted
that while Vacco ``contended vigorously that all his employment
decisions were based on merit,'' he then argued in court that the
``constitution permits him to hire and fire (assistant attorneys
general) for political reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Adler/Savitt case was one of 14 lawsuits sparked by Vacco's
1995 purge of the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   After winning election in 1995 as the first Republican attorney
general in 16 years, Vacco fired approximately one-third of the 450
staff lawyers, prompting a plethora of lawsuits alleging political
bias.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the lawsuits has succeeded _ three are still
pending _ the litigation has repeatedly embarrassed the Vacco
administration, while providing the incumbent's opponent _ Eliot
Spitzer _ in this fall's election with a steady stream of material
for political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Documents unveiled as a result of the lawsuits showed that
Vacco, who initially claimed that politics had no bearing on his
hiring and firing decisions, hired several lawyers who had been
recommended by Republican politicians. While many of the hirees
recommended by GOP powers had outstanding credentials and
ultimately received stellar performance evaluations, others had, at
best, meager qualifications and performed poorly.
</P>
<P>
   In one example, an attorney recommended by a Republican judge,
and described as intelligent, politically active and ``strikingly
attractive,'' was later criticized in an employment evaluation for
failing to ``understand the subject matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The litigation also revealed that Vacco's top assistant, William
F. Flynn, failed the state bar examination eight times,
misrepresented his credentials and may have practiced law before he
was legally entitled to do so, and that Vacco retained one lawyer _
rated poorly by his own evaluators _ because he said hello in an
elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Vacco's own conduct _ in particular, smart-aleck
responses to questions in a deposition _ prompted a judge to impose
financial sanctions of several thousand dollars, an expense that
the attorney general passed along to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Pooler, in her decision, upheld the sanctions against Vacco.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Vacco camp was elated with Pooler's decision,
although, given the history of similar cases, hardly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said from the start that these lawsuits were meritless
and politically motivated,'' said Chris McKenna, spokesman for the
attorney general's office. ``The fact that a federal judge has
carefully reviewed each and every charge ... and rejected every
single one of them proves that point. We have maintained all along,
and continue to maintain, that nobody's political affiliation
played any role in hiring and firing decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Savitt said she was considering an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case was filed because of a principle,'' she said. ``I
believe the principle of standing up for what is right and decent
was upheld by the court. I will always be able to tell my children
I did what was right. Mr. Vacco ... cannot say the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Vacco has described his hiring practice as ``imperfect'' and has
acknowledged mistakes were made. However, he repeatedly points to
his office's record in court as evidence that the staff as a whole
is functioning at the highest level of professionalism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1654EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2448 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-JIGSAW-GAME-ART-N     09-30 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-JIGSAW-GAME-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSIC CARTOONS TAKE AN INTERACTIVE TURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eh, what's up, Doc?
</P>
<P>
   Jigsaw puzzles _ Looney Tunes Cosmic Capers Animated Jigsaws, a
puzzle collection culled from the intergalactic travels of Bugs
Bunny, Daffy Duck, Porky Pig and Marvin the Martian. Snap the
puzzle pieces together, and the image becomes an animated cartoon
from the Warner Brothers vaults.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing ``Duck Dodgers in the 24{th Century'' fragmented,
reconstituted and animated on a computer monitor, one realizes that
a bunch of deranged 40-something cartoon characters are the
vanguard of convergence.
</P>
<P>
   But then, we already knew that.
</P>
<P>
   As with any toy transported from the physical world to the
computer screen, there is the question of whether a digital
interface adds anything to the experience. In this case, it does.
Putting together a jigsaw puzzle, particularly the cardboard
variety, is an abstract undertaking. It's about memory and spatial
perception and pattern recognition.
</P>
<P>
   You sort things by color, find the corners, assemble the edges,
put together the obvious clusters, then fill in the gaps. When you
snap two pieces together, the primary payoff is the ``aha''
realization that they fit, followed by a tactile sense of
completion when you mash them together with your thumb.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual version elicits the same puzzle-assembly behavior.
(Those sorting strategies are so universal and instinctual, one
half-suspects that a jigsaw gene is lurking somewhere in the cipher
of human DNA.) The ``aha'' moment is identical.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of tactile feedback, there's a sound effect to punctuate
the moment when pieces lock together. Essentially, it's the same
kind of payoff _ some sensory reassurance that the pieces fit, a
validation of your insight. In digital translation, a jigsaw puzzle
doesn't lose much.
</P>
<P>
   And it gains a lot. For one thing, it's replayable. Unlike the
cardboard image, which loses all attraction once it is assembled,
the digital image can be recast as a different puzzle (or displayed
as computer wallpaper).
</P>
<P>
   There are 48 different patterns, from conventional cut-out
shapes to square and round configurations, which are surprisingly
difficult because they lack the usual interlocking puzzle parts.
This game makes you realize how much ``pure logic'' really comes
down to habit.
</P>
<P>
   The puzzles are two-sided, so if you get stumped, you can always
flip the thing over and work on the other image. If you get too
frustrated (or just want to see the cartoon), there is an ``instant
solve'' option.
</P>
<P>
   There's also an Auto Place feature that flings pieces together,
one at a time, with the appropriate gutbucket sound effects. Click
repeatedly and the puzzle pieces whirl and zing their way across
the screen as if by magic, leaving the last piece poised like a
bonbon to be placed, ever so delicately, in the remaining gap.
</P>
<P>
   So you can have 20 puzzles auto-assembled except for the last
piece and finish each one in rapid succession. It's like eating all
the green M&AMP;M's in the candy bowl: an innocent activity, but
nonetheless decadent (not that I have ever done this).
</P>
<P>
   Any of these puzzles can be scaled up and down the difficulty
scale, from level one (five pieces, mildly challenging to a
preschooler) to level five (hundreds of pieces, which can occupy an
adult for almost an hour).
</P>
<P>
   The program even has two interfaces, one with pull-down menus,
presumably for adults, and the other with large cartoon icons, for
kids.
</P>
<P>
   Because children are more intelligent, sophisticated and
knowledgeable about computers, their interface is superior in every
way. Instead of a tedious pull-down menu bar that says Flip All
Pieces Over, there is a spatula with a fried egg on it and a sound
clip of Pepe Le Pew (``I em fleeping for you, mah leetel
flapjack!'').
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hitting ``P'' for a random puzzle, you can click on a
large yellow gift box. And at the end of the day, it is simply more
satisfying to break emergency glass at the behest of Foghorn
Leghorn than it is to scroll down to Solve Puzzle F4.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are the cartoons themselves, classic pieces of
animation that connect the current generation of children to
preceding generations. Baby boomers saw these cartoons broadcast in
the 50s. Generation X saw them in Saturday morning reruns.
</P>
<P>
   Today's 8-year-olds see them in 12-second snippets on a computer
screen. In 2030, children will be watching them on animated posters
affixed to their bedroom walls.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Marvin the Martian will outlive us all. He will
endure because there's something about a Warner Brothers cartoon
that doesn't mind being frozen, chopped up, shuffled and pasted
onto anything. These characters have transcended their original
context, television. They don't need any sort of context now. They
just float.
</P>
<P>
   In Cosmic Capers, they create a bridge between two kinds of
moving image: the noninteractive image on television and the
computer image, which can be assembled, disassembled, turned upside
down, rotated and otherwise manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   The digital image is three-dimensional; you can flip it over and
see that the back is different from the front. It is something you
can literally construct, which is the whole point of the game. Or
deconstruct.
</P>
<P>
   The digital image is about leaning forward. The television image
is about leaning back. And it reveals a lot about grown-up media
habits that the former is a means to the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Solving puzzles is a highly interactive way to process images.
And as a reward, you get to kick back and watch television. The
implicit message is that interactivity is work and passive
viewership is more fun, when in fact, for anyone under 18, the
opposite is true.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, Cosmic Capers is a very influential kind of toy
because it changes one's way of thinking about television. If you
can take something apart and put it back together again, it's
yours. You control it, and you will expect to control it the next
time you see it.
</P>
<P>
   Every television image becomes a potential Humpty Dumpty _
something to be broken and reassembled at will.
</P>
<P>
   And like Humpty Dumpty, it can never be put all the way back
together, not in a child's mind, not after you've seen it shattered
repeatedly on a computer screen. A remote control teaches you that
the television image can be interrupted. A Looney Tunes animated
jigsaw teaches you that the television image can also be violated.
</P>
<P>
   Programming executives, be vewy, vewy afwaid.
</P>
<P>
   (Southpeak Interactive, CD-ROM for Windows 95 and 98, $19.95;
recommended for all ages.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
