<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2494 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-PINBALL-NYT &LR;      09-30 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PINBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINBALL STILL ALIVE IN AN ELECTRONIC WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Nev., Calif., Ill.)   (af)  
 By BRIGID BUCKMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an age of video games, home computers and virtual-reality
snowboarding at the mall, pinball games may sound like something
from the 50s, or from, at best, the glory days of the Who and its
rock opera, ``Tommy.''
</P>
<P>
   But pinball, like ``Tommy,'' revived on Broadway a few years
ago, has survived.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, there was some worry about its future. Beaten
down by the advent of the video-game craze spearheaded by games
like Pac Man and Space Invaders in the early 80s, by 1984, pinball
controlled only 5 percent of the coin-operated game market it had
once dominated.
</P>
<P>
   Though both video and pinball games were using digital
computerization (pinball went solid state in 1977), video had
captured the imagination of the markets' quarter poppers and was
poised to deliver an animated death kick to an American
recreational icon.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the third annual Pinball Fantasy _ a combination of
trade show, collectibles and competitions _ drew 1,200 people to
the Riviera Hotel in Las Vegas, Nev., and the evidence of pinball's
survival was loud and flashing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, according to Vending Times, which tracks the use of
coin-operated games, by 1994 the silver ball had rebounded for a 38
percent take of that market, roughly $2.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The future is not assured. Home game consoles and the Internet
have eaten into pinball's market share as more people choose home
entertainment over visits to bars and bowling alleys, pinball
machines' more lucrative locations. But the 1997 figures were still
strong, at $1.7 billion, roughly matching the coin-operated video
market's take.
</P>
<P>
   Pinball's successful retaliation against the video threat was a
result of a number of design developments, said Joe Kaminkow,
executive vice president of engineering and design for Sega
Pinball.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of multiball bonuses, gadgets like trap doors and
moving hands that grab the ball, three-dimensional play fields
embellished with ramps and ball traps, and most important, the
introduction of a dot matrix animation system that feeds scoring
and strategic information to the player in a display above the back
glass, gave the ailing market a boost. The dot matrix display unit,
now a mainstay, was first seen in a game called Checkpoint in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Kaminkow, the designer of Checkpoint, explained the effects dot
matrix had on the game. ``Dot matrix allowed you to get information
to the player in a different way with pictures, and it also allowed
us to explode our scoring band,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The scoring band, denoted in the graphics display above the
backglass was once limited to five- or six-digit point tallies but
became capable of delivering scores in the hundreds of millions.
Fast-paced graphic effects combined with huge scoring possibilities
rallied players back to pinball en masse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compact-disk sound quality via a digitally compressed system
became the status quo in 1993, further enhancing the ever-evolving
three-dimensional play field designs. Pinball games like Sega's
latest, ``Lost in Space,'' usher the player through a jamboree of
lightning-quick, sound-intensive stimuli as gravity maneuvers the
80-gram silver ball toward the ball drain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is this mosaic of technology too much to absorb for the average
player? Apparently not, given the lines of people waiting to play
X-Files, Champion Pub and other top-of-the-line pinball games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Shelley Glazer, 41, a dermatologist from Oakland, Calif.,
enjoys the newer designs. ``The more challenges to figure out, the
better,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Zwas, 25, a technical writer from Ithaca, N.Y., went to
the pinball show in Las Vegas to check out the assortment of games.
Zwas, like Dr. Glazer, preferred the modern, multifaceted games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about the new ones is that they're fast and
exciting, and when they're done well, they're really
entertaining,'' Zwas said. But despite his preference for high-tech
action, he shuns videos, he said, favoring the physical action of a
good game of ``pin.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two manufacturers responsible for all pinball machines
currently being produced _ Sega Pinball of Melrose Park, Ill., and
Williams Electronics Games in neighboring Chicago _ both had
designers at the event.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for a way to take pinball to its next level (as Harry
Mabs did for the industry in 1947 with his flipper invention, which
made all machines built up until that time obsolete), both
companies looked to players in action for inspiration. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jon Norris, one of Sega's top designers as well as an acclaimed
pinball wizard, is hard at work on Sega's hush-hush Project X.
Likewise, Williams Electronics Games is preparing to deliver its
covert Project 2000 in early 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players are speculating that anticipated designs may borrow from
pinball's rival, video, by working a monitor into the back glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give them something they can't have at home,''
said Louis Koziarz, a pinball software engineer at Williams. ``It's
one thing to play the pinball simulation on your PC, but to have
jumping Martians and a saucer that shakes things, moves and talks,
that's the real magic.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If pinball seems complicated enough without further digitized
enhancements, worry not. The basic principles have remained the
same. Flippers are your friends, gravity your enemy; keep your eye
on the ball and be sure not to tilt.
</P>
<P>
   And for when you're aiming for that high score, Kaminkow offered
this age-old strategic advice: ``The most important thing to
remember about pinball is shoot the blinking light.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
