<SLUG> BC-PASSPORT-AIDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESSED TO EXCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was a fashion fantasy, from the glitzy
over-the-top clothes to the costumed dogs to the fireworks
exploding overhead and on stage like a Fourth of July spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Passport '98, sponsored by Macy's and American Express, raised
$2 million last week for AIDS/HIV and gave the hipsters and
philanthropists of Los Angeles and San Francisco a night of fantasy
and fashion. Think of a haughty New York runway show, a sassy Las
Vegas revue and Disneyland's Main Street Electrical Parade and,
well, you've got the idea. There were major stars, familiar faces
and sports figures on the stage and in the seats, but the hosts _
Elizabeth Taylor, Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson and k.d. lang _ were the
big draw.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Barker Hangar at Santa Monica Airport on Saturday
night, a sold-out audience of 2,800 screamed when Johnson came out
and asked them if they were ``dressed to impress.'' They screamed
again when lang and supermodel Christy Turlington were introduced,
but gave a standing ovation in silence to Elizabeth Taylor as she
made her way to the podium on the arm of Johnson. Although she
looked tiny and frail, her message was loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here for those from whom we've turned away,'' she said,
reminding the audience and the press that more research and
services to stop new AIDS infections are needed. But her comment,
``Now is the time for guts and God,'' brought the house down.
</P>
<P>
   The show began with a dark and stormy special-effects scene, and
out of the mist, male models paraded the stage dressed in
head-to-toe black. Before Passport '98 finished with swing dancers
in bobby socks, we were treated to lang's Tom Jones-esque
performance of ``What's New Pussycat,'' Mickey and Minnie Mouse
doing magic tricks, and a bunch of models in Levi's new dark denim
jeans carrying construction supplies. In a reversal of construction
site roles, the women in the audience provided whistles and
catcalls.
</P>
<P>
   As always, the Passport show is provocative in its presentation,
and the Calvin Klein underwear parade with models stripping off
their T-shirts and tossing them into the audience was a crowd
pleaser.
</P>
<P>
   More serious fashion was provided by Hugo Boss, Elie Tahari, and
L.A. designer Shelli Segal of Laundry, followed by whimsical hats
by Marsha Akins and a Bohemian rhapsody-themed finale that featured
lavish and eccentric gowns with feathers, fringe, lace and velvet
designed by Emanuel and Jessica McClintock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2518 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKTALK-LOWTECH-LADN     09-30 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTALK-LOWTECH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN BEHIND BOOKTALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's about as low tech as high tech gets: Call a
number, punch in a few digits and hear top authors talk about their
newest books. It's BookTalk, the little feature that runs on the
Sunday book pages of 34 papers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The service itself is simple. Angelenos can call BookTalk at
(818) 788-9722 or (310) 582-8820 to listen. Every week, papers list
codes for up to 25 new books, chosen from a broad smattering of
genres, said company founder David Knight, whose office is in
Sherman Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Dial and listen. Simple.
</P>
<P>
   Free, too, unless you're calling long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, there are real nuggets, such as former
sportswriter Dan Jenkins (at code 4206) talking about his ``Semi
Tough'' quasi-sequel, ``Rude Behavior,'' with protagonist Billy
Clyde Puckett now general manager of an expansion football team.
</P>
<P>
   As Jenkins says in his rich Texas drawl, ``the characters are
about as politically incorrect as they can be,'' and proves it with
a character's great line about marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Though the service tapes a wide variety of authors, well-known
writers, especially of fiction, draw the most interest. Just as
importantly, Knight said, well-spoken authors really can help their
own book's cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Authors who are good speakers without a doubt do better,''
Knight said. ``People will tell their friends to call. If the
author has a good voice, we know it will do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Other recent good listens include Richard Preston, whose
nonfiction ``The Hot Zone'' briskly detailed the horrors of the
ebola virus, talks about the cloak-and-dagger source work he had to
do to research his first novel, also about a killer virus, ``The
Cobra Event'' (at code 2850).
</P>
<P>
   And Peter Craig's comments about his ballyhooed novel of a
severely dysfunctional Hollywood clan led by a fading male movie
star, ``The Martini Shot,'' (code 4961) are all the more intriguing
for Craig's disclaimers that it's not mere thinly veiled
autobiography. Craig's mother is Sally Field, and her longtime beau
was Burt Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Among others who have attracted a lot of callers over the years
are George Plimpton, Amy Tan, ``Galloping Gourmet'' Graham Kerr and
former ``Avengers'' star Patrick MacNee, Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   About the toughest recording session was one with Dr. Ruth
Westheimer, whose heavy German accent forced five takes, Knight
said.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners can go to a specific code, or hit the browse function
to listen randomly. The calls are limited to 15 minutes, because
Knight found some listeners stayed on so long at night that they
fell asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, who describes himself as a ``big book lover,'' said he
started the service as a way to tell friends about books he liked.
Since then, it has grown and prospered into a busy little business,
with 30,000 to 35,000 calls a week around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's considering adding some actual high-tech touches to the
service.
</P>
<P>
   Pasadena-based Internet service provider Earthlink Networks, for
instance, has cut a deal to give new customers any book on BookTalk
in exchange for signing up. And Internet booksellers have been
inquiring about incorporating the audio into their sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been a nice little service based in the Valley,''
Knight said. ``I thought there'd be another book line out there,
but in all the years since I've been doing it, I've never heard of
another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1711EDT &QL; 
