<HEADER>
A2527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAB-ANTI-MALL-NYT &LR;      09-30 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAB-ANTI-MALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE ALIENATION SELLS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COSTA MESA, Calif. _ At one entrance to the Lab Anti Mall stands
a whimsical sculpture combining a head of Buddha with a disco-style
mirror ball. New Age spiritual, 1970s revival _ they sell it all
here.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Paul and I agreed to meet by the sculpture. As I
waited, I noticed the word ``Feel'' painted in huge letters on the
adjoining wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Lab, opened in 1994, the brainchild of a developer named
Shaheen Sadeghi, who came to the project with a background in beach
wear and a business degree, is postmodernist retailing. Just as
advertisements joke about advertisements, this is a mall that jokes
about malls.
</P>
<P>
   Paul belongs to the target demographic for the Lab. A wry, not
to say cynical, Gen X'er, he works in software and on weekends
pursues recondite interests in Betty Page pinups and rockabilly
revival music. ``I like strange subcultures,'' he told me when he
invited me to the Lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, like a regular mall, they're trying to get you to
spend money, but they try to make you feel hip and trendy,'' Paul
explained. ``Have you seen the book `Commodify Your Dissent?' It
has some eye-opening material about how the marketers have adopted
alternate life styles to sell goods.''
</P>
<P>
   As I waited for Paul to arrive, I thought that the Lab's central
lounge, with its seedy furniture, was just the place to read that
book, edited by Thomas Frank and Matt Weiland (Norton, 1997), a
collection of essays about the commercial co-opting of
countercultures.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this was no more news than Jimi Hendrix music tracked
onto Pontiac Sunfire commercials, especially at the Lab, a
converted canning factory where the ambiance is decay _ bare
plywood, exposed rebar reinforcing steel and cracked concrete. But
vines and flowers grow over everything.
</P>
<P>
   I visited the Lab when it opened and expected it to have faded
by now. Its esthetic was then part grunge, part ``Road Warrior'' _
a postapocalypse, postindustrial vision of the future now situated
well in the past. But the Lab has survived changing countercultural
trends and updated its own market. Several stores have given way to
new ones _ beads have been replaced by sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   The anchor tenant is Urban Outfitters. This year, its grungy
graphics have been replaced with a modern sans-serif typeface.
Other enterprises include a Tower Alternative _ emphasizing
nonmainstream CD's and books, along with a skateboard shop and a
sunglasses store called Nana. A store called Decor Deluxe offers
secondhand furniture, as well as such objects as velvet paintings;
it also offers a bridal registry. At the two ends are a new Cuban
restaurant, Habana, and a cafe called the Gypsy Den.
</P>
<P>
   Can ruins fall into ruins? Part of the answer I found in
``Commodify Your Dissent,'' which in a critique more Mencken than
Marx argues not only that marketers sell alienation and cynicism
back to the alienated but also that it's important for commercial
culture to create subcultures, then process them through the system
as fast as possible, leaving few remainders to discount.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the book, I noticed with a start a reference to this
place itself. In an essay on wealthy Orange County, Calif., ``The
Gaudy and the Damned,'' Tom Vanderbilt argues that the Anti Mall is
as paradoxical there as the county's private prosperity and
political bankruptcy. But I thought the opposite: only the very
wealthy could afford the indulgence of decrepitude, like artificial
romantic ruins in an English garden.
</P>
<P>
   And only the very cynical can afford the luxury of this much
anti-luxury. What is really for sale at the Anti Mall is attitude _
the retailers' visual acknowledgment that we know you know we are
selling you. For a generation that grew up on Pop Tarts and Wacky
Packs and Gerald Ford as both President and ``Saturday Night Live''
joke, that's more of a comfort _ a more welcoming ambiance _ than
any number of food courts or sitting lobbies. Irony is the means by
which the huge lumbering machinery designing and marketing goods
around us not only disarms resistance to consumerism but actually
grows stronger with homeopathic doses of it.
</P>
<P>
   Paul reminded me that there are real and very slick malls, like
South Coast Plaza just a couple of miles away. What, I asked him,
would happen if a real mall and an anti-mall should meet? Perhaps,
he said, they would cancel each other out, like matter meeting
antimatter. Or possibly produce a synthesis stronger than either.
</P>
<P>
   As I left, I noticed that the ``Feel'' sign continues on the
ceiling and opposite wall, so that the whole motto reads ``Feel
Real Good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
