<HEADER>
A2537 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SAVING-ROCK-ART-A     09-30 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SAVING-ROCK-ART-ART-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING SOFTWARE TO MAKE A RECORD OF INDIAN ROCK ART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wyo., N.M., Ariz., Co.)   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)(mk) 
 By MINDY SINK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBOIS , Wyo. _ Software can sometimes be put to unexpected
uses. A database system originally designed to create a variety of
maps, some to aid in urban street planning, is enabling researchers
and archeologists to create a permanent record of American Indian
rock art.
</P>
<P>
   What must have seemed permanent centuries ago is now vanishing
because of erosion and vandalism. ``The United States has a
marvelous heritage of rock art, but unfortunately it's being
destroyed at a phenomenal rate,'' said Evelyn Billo, founder and
chief executive of Rupestrian Cyber Services. (Rupestrian is
derived from the word rupes, Latin for rock.)
</P>
<P>
   The company is designing a database to record, preserve and
share information about some rock drawings _ called petroglyphs _
which are sacred to the Eastern Shoshone and Northern Arapaho
tribal members who live near here on the Wind River Reservation.
Rock drawings, mostly images of animals, birds and other objects,
were methodically pecked out on stone surfaces using sharp rock
tools to convey messages of spiritual journeys or other mysterious
meanings.
</P>
<P>
   Using a program called Arc View, from Environmental Systems
Research Institute, Ms. Billo is helping archeologists and
preservationists to create a CD-ROM with satellite maps that
provide aerial and topographical views of the valley where the
petroglyphs are, photographs and drawings that can be successively
layered and text of data accumulated at the sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a filing cabinet approach,'' said Larry Loendorf, a
research professor of archeology at New Mexico State University and
one of the creators of the project. ``Once it's established, we can
keep adding to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The intent is not to release the CD-ROM to the public but to
make it available primarily to those with a vested interest _ the
American Indians whose cultural history was etched into the
relatively soft sandstone rocks of the region and others interested
in conservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might indeed be the first program used for the people
whose ancestors made the rock art,'' said Sharon Urban, secretary
for the American Rock Art Research Association in Tucson, Ariz.
``It can also be useful for land management techniques and
visitation impact to the sites.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the varied land interests at stake, vandalism,
natural erosion and other factors are working against
conservationists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complicated, complicated issue as to how to protect the
rock art,'' Ms. Billo said. ``Any site that can be reached by car
has been shot up'' _ a reference to how some people use the
drawings for target practice. ``Mistakes have been made _ people
would use chalk to outline the drawings so they would show up in
photographs, or do rubbings right over the rock face, but now we
know just the oil from our hands can affect them.'' Graffiti is
also a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Digital photography and successive image layering, done by Ms.
Billo and Robert Mark, chief scientist of Rupestrian Cyber Services
(www.infomagic.com/rockart), allows scientists and educators to
view changes in the rock surface with a simple mouse click.
</P>
<P>
   Using several commercially available software programs, Mark has
created a system of morphing old images with new. For example, a
color photograph taken in 1984 of a drawing of an owl can be
layered with a color photograph taken last month to clearly show
changes in the rock face. In some cases, growth of lichen over the
surface may obscure a drawing or cause the disappearance of more
detailed features of the drawing.
</P>
<P>
   These subtle changes over time can be readily seen when someone
clicks on the left side of the image in a red box for ``1984,''
then on the right for ``1998,'' going back and forth between the
two images.
</P>
<P>
   A database user could begin with the topographical or contour
map, which has some shaded relief, and click on one of the dozens
of white or red dots that indicate individual petroglyphs. Once the
selection is made, the user will be able to view a color
photograph, a tracing (done with string grids, not rubbings) or a
collection of photographs. Along with the image there will be
measurements of the actual drawing, its new ``serial number'' and
any available archaeological data or interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   The project is concentrated on the petroglyphs in only one
valley in western Wyoming, just beyond the shadow of the Grand
Tetons. The petroglyphs site here was put on the National Register
of Historic Places in 1990, and that status helped gain some of the
$26,000 in grants used for this project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately we want to have this database available in three
locations _ the Dubois Museum, the school at Fort Washakie on the
reservation and the University of Wyoming in Laramie,'' said Sharon
Kahin, director of the Dubois Museum here, and one of the creators
of this project. ``Maybe we could get Indians involved in recording
their own rock art, or interested in archeology.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But it won't be on the Web. ``If we put this on the Internet, it
would bring hordes of people out here who might not just be
satisfied with looking at it,'' Loendorf said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the petroglyphs are held sacred by some. ``Like
religions, you have to respect the Bible, the spirit, when you go
into the church you have to be quiet to show respect for the
faith,'' said John Tarnesse, a Shoshone tribal member and spiritual
leader. Tarnesse, 52, spoke recently at the Aurora History Museum
in Aurora, Co., in conjunction with a photography exhibition,
``Sacred Sites: Journeys of the Spirits,'' about the petroglyphs of
Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Others see the cultural history that was carved in stone
thousands of years ago as a disappearing resource, like a native
language. ``When these elders are gone with that knowledge, what
will today's high-school youngster know about the petroglyphs
except that they shouldn't be tampered with?'' said Barbara Sage, a
65-year-old Shoshone rancher. ``With this new process of preserving
the petroglyphs they can learn what petroglyphs mean, when they
came into existence, who did them and why, about traditional
cultural values.'' There is also the possibility of learning more
about the migration patterns of earlier tribes with
cross-referencing details of specific rock art drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Working in conjunction with educators from the reservation,
Loendorf and Ms. Kahin have organized field trips for local
students.
</P>
<P>
   Students from St. Stephens High School on the reservation
visited the petroglyph site this week _ most for the first time.
``It was pretty cool to see they were out there making stuff, to
see what they saw, were thinking, their myths, legends,'' said
Andrew C'Hair, a Northern Arapaho and a 16-year-old sophomore at
the school.``It made me feel proud to be an Indian.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
