<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2538 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     09-30 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC PARTY HAS A PROBLEM: HIS NAME IS BILL CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For Release Sunday, Oct. 4)   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the intensifying frenzy over Bill Clinton's
ethics and morals _ or the lack thereof _ there are as yet no
credible heroes or heroines. But there are villains and there are
victims.
</P>
<P>
   To millions of Americans, Clinton himself is the arch-villain,
the reckless leader whose disgraceful antics precipitated the
scandal that has totally dominated governmental proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But to many Clinton supporters, the main villain is independent
counsel Kenneth Starr, who _ like Javert in ``Les Miserables'' _
has been relentless in his pursuit of a 1990s Jean Valjean: Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate for villain is Linda Tripp, who
surreptitiously recorded the sexual revelations of her then-friend,
Monica Lewinsky, and turned the tapes over to Starr. She is to the
Clinton faithful a reincarnation of Charles Dickens' Madame
Defarge, the French revolutionary who bellowed her approval as the
guillotine severed one head after another.
</P>
<P>
   As for the victims, the foremost is the institution of the
presidency. It is tarnished and in Clinton's embattled hands, it is
weakened.
</P>
<P>
   The American people also are victims. They deserve better
conduct by a president who lied under oath about his relations with
a young White House intern. They also deserve better that they've
received from a special counsel who, after an investigation of more
than four years and the expenditure of more than $40 million, is
proposing impeachment of the president on the narrow issue of
perjury and possible obstruction of justice regarding a sexual
encounter that only surfaced publicly nine months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although she is a wise and worldly woman who has suffered
through her husband's infidelity for many years, it is difficult to
determine whether Hillary Rodham Clinton is a victim. She is quite
adroit at hiding her true feelings while defending her husband and
pursuing her determination to continue to enjoy the power and
influence that accrue to a first lady.
</P>
<P>
   A true victim, however, is her daughter, Chelsea, who is
pursuing academic achievement at Stanford, while watching from afar
the disintegration of her father's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the Democratic Party, which could be a very big
loser. It is the world's oldest and most successful political
party, tracing its heritage back to Thomas Jefferson and Andrew
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   It has known both the grandeur of victory and the shame of
failure.
</P>
<P>
   One illustrious Democrat, Woodrow Wilson, was the founding
father of the enlightened internationalism that was rejected by the
isolationists of his day but has been the basis of American foreign
policy since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Another illustrious Democrat, Franklin D. Roosevelt, changed for
all time the relationship between the people and their government.
Many of the reforms of the New Deal, including Social Security,
remain as integral parts of our system.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats cannot, however, point with much pride to the refusal
of their liberal wing to recognize the evil of Soviet communism in
the 1940s or their stewardship of the war in Vietnam in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The problem facing Democrats now, however is not the past, but
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the party's current leaders fear they will be pummeled
by voters in November just as Republicans were in 1974 after
Richard Nixon's forced resignation. In that election, the GOP lost
five seats in the Senate and 48 in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the debilitating scandal, this should be a
rather hopeful time for Democrats. The president's official
performance continues to command the support of a majority of the
American people. Until fairly recently, it even appeared that
tradition might be broken this year and that the Democrats, who
control the White House, could gain enough seats in November to
reclaim control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   But those rosy dreams have been dashed by the very man who
helped create them: Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies a paradox. Clinton helped perform cosmetic surgery
on the party, replacing its old big government, high spending face
with a moderate balance-the-budget, cut-welfare-spending visage. On
his watch, the country has achieved a credible record in the
domestic arena and some worthwhile accomplishments abroad,
including a peace agreement in Ireland and movement toward a peace
agreement in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the first president since Lyndon Johnson, 29 years
ago, to produce a balanced budget. Jobs are plentiful and the
number of individuals living below the poverty level has declined
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   But to many Democrats seeking election or reelection to
Congress, Clinton now is a political liability. Where they once
welcomed him into their states and districts, they now shudder at
the thought of him making an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   His obfuscation in describing his liaisons with Lewinsky was, as
Winston Churchill once said of the Soviet Union, ``a riddle wrapped
in a mystery inside an enigma.'' It was meant to confuse and
confound _ and it did so.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, like the Republicans, are well acquainted with
defeat. Previously, they have suffered through long periods of
drought, decreed by American voters.
</P>
<P>
   The longest was from the election of Abraham Lincoln, the first
Republican president, in 1860 to that of Democrat Grover Cleveland
24 years later. From 1860 to 1892, a period of 32 years, the GOP
controlled the Senate, although the Democrats sporadically
prevailed in the House.
</P>
<P>
   In the current crisis, some of the party's most prominent
leaders have been caustic in their criticism of Clinton's conduct
and have suggested that he resign.
</P>
<P>
   There is no escaping the fact that the Democratic Party has a
major problem and his name is Bill Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
