   FBN-BENGALS-SIMMONS _ CINCINNATI _ The timing of the bye week
couldn't be better for Bengals linebacker Brian Simmons. The
6-foot-3, 233-pound rookie is due to make the first start of his
NFL career against Pittsburgh on Oct. 11. He replaces Tom Tumulty,
who suffered torn left knee ligaments in a 31-24 loss at Baltimore.
(Ludwig, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-OSU-KATZENMOYER _ COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Like a turtle coming out
of its shell after a bad storm, Ohio State linebacker Andy
Katzenmoyer has slowly begun to poke his head out to face the media
he feels rained down hard on him earlier this year. (Vinella,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-MCGWIRE-MEMORABILIA _ Mark McGwire's historic season ended
Sunday in St. Louis. The chase for his 70th home run started Monday
in Fort Lauderdale on the second floor of a Las Olas Boulevard bank
building. That's where the Law Office of David Kraythen, which
specializes in medical malpractice cases, suddenly became the
negotiating backdrop for perhaps the most prized piece of
memorabilia in sports history. (Capozzi, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-ICE-BATS _ AUSTIN _ Speed. Discipline. Hard work and fun.
Those are the attributes Al Tuer wants to use this season as the
new head coach of the Austin Ice Bats. ``I'm a demanding person and
a demanding coach,'' the soft-spoken Tuer said at a news conference
recently at the Radisson Hotel downtown. ``I like to have my fun,
but I also enjoy winning and I enjoy working. I think the only way
to have fun is to win.'' (Tennant, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
