<HEADER>
A2546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RED-HOOK-ART-2TAKE     09-30 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RED-HOOK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP FROM THE RUINS, RED HOOK FIGHTS A DUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sun was setting like a fat tomato behind the
Statue of Liberty just as Armando Babillo hooked a 20-inch sea
bass, flashing silver in the light, from the end of the new $3
million Louis Valentino Jr. Pier at the end of Coffey Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vivo en el proyecto de Red Hook,'' Babillo said, adding
proudly, ``We will have this for Sunday dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gonzalez, from East New York, held his hands wide to
describe the 29-inch bluefish he'd caught the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and I ate the whole thing ourselves, at her house on
Pioneer Street,'' said Gonzalez, 36, a carpenter, who learned to
fish right here on Buttermilk Channel. He looked out over the
velvety water as a Staten Island ferryboat steamed by and said,
``They fix it up, and then they make it smell like garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who grew up on Pioneer Street, used to paint ships at
the old 48-acre Todd Shipyard 10 blocks away. The site is one of
three in Brooklyn and one in the South Bronx that are reportedly
being considered for a garbage transfer station after the Fresh
Kills Landfill on Staten Island closes in three years. The site
could handle 10,000 tons of the city's waste a day. A decision is
expected in about a month.
</P>
<P>
   The specter of all that garbage looming over Red Hook's
renaissance has natives and newcomers alike shaking their heads.
Sandra Phillips, who grew up on her grandmother's little farm in
Barbados, bought a house on Dikeman Street for $110,000 a few years
ago with her husband, Henry Morales. They renovated it themselves,
and now the backyard is stuffed with plants, from peach trees to
cannas, which have a tropical look.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips arrived in Red Hook a century after its glory days
as a shipping center. It is coming back from a long slide into ruin
as an industrial wasteland and a haven for drug dealers. There is a
sense of adventure, as people renovate houses and lobby for
waterfront parks. And risk, too, as they push out drug dealers and
illegal dumps.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate is booming. Light industry is moving onto the old
restored piers. A bank, a pharmacy and three cafes have just
opened. Red Hook has a spring in its step. But will it falter under
10,000 tons of waste? In the Hook, which has fought off 13 trash
stations in the past, people can't afford to be defeatist.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed site for the latest station is a block from a new
esplanade that extends about a quarter-mile into the Erie Basin. On
weekends the walkway, which includes a bike trail, is lined with
people of all ages, fishing and crabbing, or simply watching sturdy
work boats churning past.
</P>
<P>
   The station would lie across the street from 69 acres of fields
used by soccer and baseball teams from all over the city. The
running track and grassy park, shaded by sycamores, is a favorite
picnic ground for thousands of residents from Red Hook Houses, just
two blocks north.
</P>
<P>
   There is new playground equipment in the courtyards of Red Hook
Houses. An alternative school for children interested in science
and the environment just opened in a wing of Public School 27 on
Columbia Street, and children have already been down on the new
pier taking samples of the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems shameful that the city would spend all this money to
lift up the community and make people feel good, and then hit them
with a lightning bolt like this,'' Ms. Phillips said of the
proposed garbage site. (Asked if Red Hook would get the transfer
station, Paula Young, a spokeswoman for the Department of
Sanitation said, ``It's premature to comment.'')
</P>
<P>
   Like other newcomers to this little peninsula, Ms. Phillips was
drawn by the salty air and the light, the old stories of Red Hook's
heyday, with ships visiting from all over the world. About 12 years
ago, her family moved into a little basement apartment on King
Street, which abuts Red Hook Houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were shootings almost every night, like the OK Corral,''
said Ms. Phillips, whose daughter, Pearl, was at P.S. 15 when the
principal, Patrick Daly, was killed in a drug-related shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she and Morales bought their house on Dikeman
Street. ``It was the feel of the place that I loved,'' she said.
``It was like a village. I liked the sound of the wheels going over
cobblestones. And you could smell the river. I liked talking to the
old people and envisioning how it was back then.''
</P>
<P>
   How it was a sailors' town, with boarding houses, and bars at
the end of every street. How you could buy a live chicken and have
your hair done on the same block on Van Brunt Street. How people
watched out for each other: if children got into a brawl, their
mothers knew about it before they got home.
</P>
<P>
   The old-timers tell of Red Hook's ruin, too. First came the
Gowanus Expressway, cutting it in half in the early 1940s. Then the
sewer line, so long in the making that people called it the Trench.
</P>
<P>
   The waterfront fell apart when ships began carrying
containerized cargo and moved to deeper ports. Whole blocks of
houses were razed for a Red Hook container port that never
materialized. But the exodus had begun. Red Hook Houses, originally
built for local working people, was converted to subsidized
housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was white flight in the late 1950s and 1960s,'' said
Frank Manzione, a real-estate agent who grew up on Hamilton Avenue.
``Businesses began to leave. People started selling property very
cheap, or renting it and not doing the repairs. By the 70s and 80s,
it was a drug place.''
</P>
<P>
   The neglect that made the old houses and industrial spaces dirt
cheap attracted a few hardy souls. Florence Neal and Scott
Pfaffman, both artists, bought a three-story former haberdashery on
Van Brunt Street for $2,500. With six years of ``sweat equity'' _
about $175,000 worth _ they made it livable. They got to know their
neighbors, too, even those on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   There were shootouts in front. The two artists eventually
divorced, Pfaffman moving to Coffey Street, but the Kentler
International Drawing Space that they founded now thrives in the
storefront below. Artists from Venezuela, Mexico, Holland and Italy
show there, and there are poetry readings and live performances.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other artists and actors trickled in, like Bettina Magi, a
painter, who was first drawn to Red Hook by the gallery, and then
by Sonny's, the old sailor's bar on Conover Street, where there was
good music and conversation. Ms. Magi bought a little brick row
house on Coffey Street for $85,000. The house had a little
south-facing yard, but inside it was nothing but debris, peeling
paint, linoleum, dark paneling and roaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the first morning, at 4 a.m., tractor-trailers started
coming down the cobblestones,'' she said. ``There's a box warehouse
next door.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Red Hook in a nutshell. The industrial buildings give it
a virility that artists love. But the manufacturing zone means
truck traffic _ and garbage sites like the one that already exists
on Court Street.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Magi, who teaches art, is renovating. She has taken down
walls and plastered the others white, and has put in a hardwood
floor and a skylight. Down on the garden floor, a tenant, Richard
Dennis, a painter and carpenter, has ripped out the south wall to
open the view to the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, who comes from Pennsylvania, has turned the backyard
into a small farm and built a sleeping shed in the back of the
garden that his friends call ``Africa'' because of its mosquito
netting.
</P>
<P>
   This same spirit of adventure shows at Michael Goodall's
sprawling house and quarter-acre backyard on King Street. Goodall
bought the house for $30,000 about two years ago. Originally a
sailors' boarding house, it was a labyrinth of 28 rooms, decayed
pipes and wiring, and an old furnace stripped of copper fittings by
crack addicts.
</P>
<P>
   Goodall did most of the renovations himself and got to the
garden when he could. The old apple tree was in desperate need of
pruning. He dismantled an above-ground pool, dug a pond and built a
waterfall. The backyard is now a habitat for water lilies, frogs
and birds.
</P>
<P>
   The block feels a lot safer now. And records at the 76th
Precinct, which includes Red Hook, show that serious crimes have
declined steadily for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Goodall isn't surprised that Red Hook might get the city's
garbage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at a map, Red Hook looks pretty good for a
transfer site,'' he said. ``It's right on the water. The highways
are right there. You can just see some intern in the mayor's office
saying, `And there are only 14,000 people there.' That's not going
to put a dent in anybody's election.''
</P>
<P>
   New businesses continue to move into the renovated warehouses on
two piers owned by Gregory O'Connell, a former police detective. He
bought them about 10 years ago, along with 28 acres of waterfront,
from the Port Authority, in a $500,000 deal that required him to
provide waterfront access for the community. Part of the Beard
Street Pier is used for art exhibitions and live performances, and
one side of the pier has just been opened as a public walkway.
</P>
<P>
   Some newcomers, like Story Mann and his wife, Melina
Finkelstein, are taking a wait-and-see approach to buying. ``You
going to pay what they're asking (italics)now?''(end italics) asked
Mann, a carpenter from North Carolina. ``And then pay for a dump?''
</P>
<P>
   Mann may be the lone voice of caution.
</P>
<P>
   Manzione, the realty agent, said: ``About a year ago, we made
our first $220,000 sale on a residential house in Red Hook. It has
charm and a beautiful English-style kitchen and a big backyard. All
the houses in Red Hook are not going to shoot up to that price, but
it suggests what a new house could go for.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, a three-story frame house in Red Hook could be had for
$30,000 to $50,000, Manzione said. ``But you'd have a hard time
getting a mortgage,'' he said. ``It would be a hard thing to prove,
but banks were redlining.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, a house like that was selling for more like
$100,000, Manzione said. ``Now it might start at $150,000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But getting a developer interested in building a block of
houses under the shadow of a dump is a hard sell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So down on Van Brunt Street, the battle goes on. A yellow ``Stop
the Garbage'' poster is taped to the glass of Amandola Grocery. Sue
Amandola, whose grandfather came here from Italy in 1894, never
misses a demonstration. ``I've given out pamphlets,'' she said.
``I've taken signatures.''
</P>
<P>
   And she goes down to the new pier almost every night, for the
sunset. So does Ms. Magi.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I come home from work, I always stop and look at the
water,'' she said. ``I think of my father coming here, through
Ellis Island. The Statue of Liberty is kind of like a Madonna to
me. And she's looking at Red Hook, not Manhattan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
