<HEADER>
A2558 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     09-30 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC; HOW TO CUT WOOD, TILE AND MASONRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: How-To drawing is being sent to NYT graphics and photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most household cutting jobs consist of slicing through paper,
cloth or wood. Do-it-yourselfers can easily handle these cutting
chores although sometimes cutting lumber to size can present
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Consider plywood, for example. It's easy to cut but often the
saw splinters the wood and leaves an unsightly edge as it cuts. One
way to avoid this is by putting a strip of masking tape along the
cut line and then sawing through the tape and board at the same
time. Another way to get a clean cut is by scoring the cut line
with a sharp utility knife before cutting.
</P>
<P>
   If you're using a hand saw, the good side of the panel should be
up. The saw will splinter the bottom, i.e. the bad side, as you
push down. The reverse is true if you cut plywood with a circular
saw. The good side of the panel should be down because the sawblade
cuts as it comes up. You will also get a smoother cut with a
circular saw if you use an 80-tooth carbide blade in the saw.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting down the center of a full 4 feet by 8 feet sheet of
plywood can be awkward because you have to reach off balance to
make the cut. The job can be made easier if you lay a few 2 by 4's
on the work floor first, then position the plywood panel on these.
The 2 by 4's should be parallel to the cut. Adjust the depth of the
blade on your saw so it just goes through the plywood. Now you can
push the saw as you kneel directly on the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting through masonry and ceramics is difficult because these
materials are hard and they require special tools or cutting
blades. You can cut into a concrete block, or paver, with your
circular saw, provided you use a masonry blade. Do not attempt to
cut completely through a thick block of concrete, instead slowly
cut a groove about 1/2-inch deep on all four sides. Then use a
heavy hammer to break the block in two. This will leave a rough
surface at the break.
</P>
<P>
   If you require a clean cut, you can rent a concrete saw fitted
with a diamond cutting blade. It can cut to a depth of four inches.
Sawing through concrete creates a lot of dust and noise. Try to
work outdoors whenever possible and be sure to wear appropriate
eye, hearing and dust protective gear.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a special saw or blade to cut bricks, but there
is a knack to doing it. An experienced mason can cut a brick in
half simply by whacking it with the edge of a heavy trowel. This
technique takes a bit of practice to master. Most do-it-yourselfers
will find it easier to break the brick by striking it with a hammer
and wide masonry chisel.
</P>
<P>
   There is another technique for cutting a brick. Score a groove
about 1/8-inch deep in the top of the brick with a cold chisel.
Place the brick on a half-inch dowel or pipe, grooved-side up, so
the dowel is directly under the groove. Press down on both ends of
the brick to snap it in two.
</P>
<P>
   Tile installations always require trimming a few full-sized
tiles into narrower widths. Professional tilers use a wet saw for
this. The tool has a circular diamond blade. A water jet directed
at rotating blade cools it and washes away tile debris.
</P>
<P>
   This tool is particularly effective for cutting thin pieces of
tile. It also leaves smooth edges at the cut. This is important if
those edges are to be left exposed. The wet saw is essential for
cutting tiles made of marble and stone. A cutting saw can usually
be rented at tile suppliers, but it can be expensive. Also the tile
saw is big and requires two people to move it to the job site.
</P>
<P>
   Do-it-yourselfers may find it easier and more economical to rent
a snap cutter. Strictly speaking, the term ``cutter'' is a misnomer
because the tool does not actually cut the tile. Instead, it breaks
it along a scored line.
</P>
<P>
   Snap cutters are available in various configurations, but they
utilize the same cutting principle. The tile is placed on the bed,
over a raised cutting bar.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp cutting wheel is drawn across the tile face. The wheel
does not cut the tile but only scores the surface. Pressing down on
the cutting arm puts pressure on the edges of the tile. On either
side of the cutting bar are soft rubber pads that ``give'' when
pressure is applied. The pressure on the tile ends makes it snap at
the cutting bar. If the break leaves a rough edge, you can smooth
it with a rubbing stone. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
