<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How can people find out if their home computers have a Year
2000, or Y2K, problem?
</P>
<P>
   A. Even if you don't have an aging mainframe machine sitting in
your living room, Y2K compliance is still important. One way to
check out your system and software before the big day is to list
all your computer equipment and programs according to the company
that made each item. The Vendor 2000 site has a lengthy list of Y2K
compliance information submitted by computer and software companies
(www.vendor2000.com). If you don't see an item, you may want to
visit that company's Web site for news on Y2K upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Tech Net has a list of the company's products and
how they comply with the problem (www.
microsoft.com/technet/topics/year2k/default.htm). Apple Computer's
Y2K Web page (www.apple.com/macos/info/2000.html) boldly states
that Macs and most Mac software can handle dates ``for the next
27,940 years,'' but it posts steps for testing Mac programs. The
Year 2000 Information Center is a good place to find out more about
the problem (www.year2000.com).
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
