<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-HARR-HOUSE-ART-N     09-30 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-HARR-HOUSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS A DARK AND STORMY REWRITE ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Jonathan Harr is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (nk) 
 By JULIE MICHAELS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHAMPTON, Mass. _ Jonathan Harr is a homebody. His world by
day _ and most nights _ is a book-lined study at the front of a
turn-of-the-century Victorian house in this college town. In his
study, Harr spent eight years writing ``A Civil Action,'' a
nonfiction blockbuster that has sold a million copies since its
publication in 1995. The story of an ambitious lawyer with a
passion for social justice, Harr's book follows a lawsuit against
two companies accused of dumping toxic wastes and causing leukemia
in children in Woburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A meticulous reporter with a novelist's gift for narrative, the
author fashioned a legal thriller out of an enormously complex
case. Even John Grisham, master of the genre, has called the book,
published by Random House, ``the most compelling chronicle of
litigation'' he has ever read.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood agreed. Harr sold the film rights to Robert Redford
and the Walt Disney Co. for $1.25 million. The film, starring John
Travolta, is to open on Christmas Day. For Harr and his wife,
Diane, the windfall was a happy ending to years of struggle. His
$80,000 advance petered out long before the manuscript was
completed. To get by, they relied on Mrs. Harr's salary as a
part-time art teacher. Their one buffer against hard times was
their house.
</P>
<P>
   Within walking distance of Northampton's trendy downtown, the
house sits on a sleepy, tree-lined street, its wraparound porch
reminiscent of an Andy Hardy movie. The couple bought the place for
$86,000 in 1981. But with interest rates at 17 percent, they could
afford it only by converting the upstairs into two rentals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated being a landlord,'' Harr, 49, recalled during a
late-summer lunch at his house. ``We had only one thermostat, which
meant we paid for the heat. I'd lie in bed at night, hear the
furnace turn over and listen to my money going up the chimney.''
</P>
<P>
   As Harr struggled with his book, he never dreamed of having a
best seller, much less a movie sale. He hoped ``A Civil Action''
would earn enough for a new roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go from $2,500 in the bank to $1.25 million, a
strange delirium sets in,'' he said, reaching down to pet his
creaky basset hound, McPhee (named for the nonfiction master John
McPhee). Finally they asked their tenants to leave, then moved out
themselves, for six months of renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had two priorities: Harr's office and the kitchen.
Although south-facing, the office was darkened by the overhanging
porch. During endless months of reading and annotating court
documents _ stacked up, they'd have stood as tall as a three-story
building _ he had longed for light. ``I look back,'' he said, ``and
it seems to me it was always winter, always dark. I felt I had
lived eight years in a cave.''
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't in his cave, Harr was in the kitchen. Both Harrs
are passionate cooks, as evidenced by a garden heavy with ripe
tomatoes and the chilled orange-and-carrot soup Mrs. Harr had made
for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   In preliminary interviews with architects, the kitchen expanded
and contracted, the study moved upstairs and down. But it wasn't
until the Harrs met Tom Douglas, of the Northampton firm bearing
his name, that they found someone who shared their vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great house,'' Douglas said, ``but the interior was
chopped up into a bunch of small, dark rooms.'' By moving a
staircase and consolidating some rooms, the architect was able to
open up the downstairs area. An addition at the rear _ what Mrs.
Harr calls the ``Victorian ranch'' wing _ was rebuilt with a guest
bedroom, a bath and an expanded dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas left the study at the front of the house. He solved the
light problem by linking the room via an open arch to the former
living room, now a library. The area is flooded by light from a bay
window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, I envisioned a more formal room, with a library
table and chairs,'' Douglas said. But Harr's work habits required a
couch. He does his best thinking _ and his best worrying _ lying
down.
</P>
<P>
   Like any struggling writer, Harr worried constantly about money.
Midway through the book, broke and mired in rewriting, he
considered applying for a job at a Burger King. That goes a long
way toward explaining his Depression-style spending habits. But he
couldn't resist splurging on the new kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Anchored by a 48-inch professional Viking stove and a Sub-Zero
refrigerator, it is designed to accommodate two cooks working side
by side. One wall is lined with pale maple cabinets, specially
designed by Lance Hodes of Haydenville (Mass.) Woodworking and
Design. The black counter tops are made of Ashfield schist, a local
slate.
</P>
<P>
   But some costs Harr could not countenance. For the kitchen,
Douglas chose a handsome German faucet by Grohe but didn't note
that it listed for $600. Harr rejected it. ``But it haunted me,''
the architect said with a laugh. ``At every meeting that followed,
Jonathan always managed to bring up the Grohe faucet.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Harr cheerfully conceded that she learned early on not to
miss meetings with the architect. One time, Harr eliminated a
shower in the master bath and counters of crow's-foot schist, a
spectacular black slate with pale flecks that mimic avian
footprints. ``I made him put them back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas confessed that his greatest concern was Tracy Kidder,
the Pulitzer Prize-winning author, who is Harr's best friend and
Northampton neighbor. Kidder wrote ``House,'' an account of the
design and construction of a house in nearby Amherst _ and the
disputes and misunderstandings that occurred as it went up. ``Any
architect would be nervous if he knew the guy who wrote `House' was
scrutinizing his drawings,'' Douglas said.
</P>
<P>
   He need not have worried. The Harrs, who spent $300,000 on the
project, said they are delighted. Over lunch, the couple spoke of
their old house _ its faulty wiring, its old furnace _ the way one
would speak of an old friend. They bickered good-naturedly over who
saw it first and just how much they charged in rents. Finally, Harr
escaped to walk McPhee, while Mrs. Harr offered an upstairs tour.
</P>
<P>
   The larger apartment has become a second guest room and the
master bedroom suite, with its fancy counter tops and walk-in
shower. The second apartment became Mrs. Harr's studio. Then she
opened a door to reveal that apartment's old kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided we'd keep it,'' she said, ever the pragmatist.
``Jonathan wants to write another book, and you never know _ if we
need the income, we can always rent it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
