<SLUG> BC-WHAT-WE-BELIEVE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD RELIGIONS: THIS WEEK, CONFUCIANISM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORIGIN: Confucianism is based on the teachings of a Chinese
philosopher, Confucius, born in Shantung province in 551 B.C.
Confucius first devoted himself to learning, but at age 30 began
teaching that social reformation could be brought about by the
reformation of the individual. By the time of his death in 479
B.C., he had acquired many followers.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTRINE: Ideally, a ruler would be a sage, one who has mastered
the ``li'' _ rites and ceremonies preserving the five cardinal
relations: sovereign and subject, father and son, elder and younger
brother, husband and wife, friend and friend. (His teachings on
filial piety popularized the practice of ancestor worship.) The
sage, or ruler, would then be a model for the masses, appointing to
prominence only those who are models of ``te'' (virtue). All people
could then emulate the models and acquire the highest level of
moral development (''jen,'' or humanity). One of the best-known
sayings that expresses Confucius' philosophy is: ``Do not do to
others what you do not want them to do to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Confucianism became the official orthodox position during the
Han dynasty (206 B.C.-220); however, it fell into decline for about
600 years. Neo-Confucianism, which showed Taoist and Buddhist
influences and sought to transform the human mind into the Mind of
Heaven _ the state of perfected excellence _ gave Confucianism a
new lease on life.
</P>
<P>
   Although Confucian orthodoxy has survived in Taiwan, only in
Hong Kong and among Chinese scholars working in the West is there
serious, ongoing Confucian philosophy. Traditional Chinese ethics
still stem from the teachings of Confucius, however.
</P>
<P>
   MEMBERSHIP: About 5 million worldwide, with more than 99 percent
residing in Asian countries; 27,000 in North America.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNIFICANT WRITINGS: Two of 13 classics are The Analects of
Confucius, a compilation of his sayings, and the Meng-tze, a
compilation of the teachings of his follower, Mencius.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: The World Almanac, 1998; Eerdmans' Handbook to the
World's Religions; The Geography of Confucianism Web site
(www.morehead-st.edu//people//t.pitts//confucs.htm)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
