<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLLACK-KRASNER-HOUSE     09-30 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLACK-KRASNER-HOUSE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN:N.Y.)  
 NOW PLAYING AT HOUSE MUSEUMS: THE TELL-ALL TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They weren't interested in going to the beach because they don't
like sand. We'd already eaten lunch and gone window shopping in
East Hampton. All right then, why not take Mom and Dad on a tour of
Eastern Long Island's primary art-history attraction, the
Pollock-Krasner house? It's going to be a big year for Pollock, I
explained, with the retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art in
November. Without much enthusiasm, they agreed we should check it
out.
</P>
<P>
   We pulled up to the little 1879 farmhouse on Fireplace Road in
Springs, where Jackson Pollock and Lee Krasner lived _ now a
National Historic Landmark _ and signed on for a house tour.
</P>
<P>
   It was a beautiful day, and the setting, with a view of the
wetlands and Accabonac Creek, was picturesque. Still, a gloomy look
was coming over their faces. My parents aren't what you'd call
Pollock people. To them, Pollock, like Kerouac, Ginsberg and Elvis,
was about everything that went wrong with American culture in the
postwar era. To hear them, you'd think he was an extortionist, not
an Abstract Expressionist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely hate his work,'' said my mother, a retired
librarian. ``A child could splatter paint like that, too, and the
critics could as easily call it art.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about him was crawly-creepy,'' added my father, who
used to practice law.
</P>
<P>
   It was going to be an upbeat tour, I could tell.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd that pulled up in Jeeps and tiny convertibles didn't
look like tourists. They were chic New Yorkers in black, all
seeming to have perfected an ``I identify with Abstract
Expressionism'' attitude. Our guide, a retired nurse, didn't offer
any of her own opinions about the artist. But she sure did come up
with some facts.
</P>
<P>
   The fact, for instance, that Krasner appreciated the location of
the house (she and Pollock moved there from Greenwich Village in
1945) because it was a mile to the nearest bar _ they didn't have a
car when they first relocated from the city. And the fact that
Pollock was drinking with his mistress when he crashed his car into
a tree in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly,'' Dad said, ``this isn't Norman Rockwell's house.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in an age of tell-all memoirs and scurrilous social
histories _ the latest rehashing of Pollock's death can be found in
``Philistines at the Hedgerow: Passion and Property in the
Hamptons'' by Steven Gaines (Little, Brown, 1998) _ it makes sense
that guides at house museums would get with the program. And while
some still strain out the pulp in order to present a smooth
historical portrait, others are more inclined to tell all. Even if
the walls don't speak, the guides will.
</P>
<P>
   At Beechwood, in Newport, R.I., tourists are shown a photograph
of William Backhouse Astor Jr.'s sailing vessel, the Nourmahal,
which, it is explained with some winking, is Arabic for ``Light of
the Harem.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sunnyside, in Tarrytown, N.Y., where Washington Irving lived
as a confirmed bachelor, an ``interpreter'' discussed the
middle-aged writer's fondness for much younger women.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor to the Franklin Delano Roosevelt residence in Hyde
Park, N.Y., recalled the offhand joke of a guide about a back door
used by certain women who called on FDR.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the guides don't volunteer much, they're pushed by
visitors, with Kenneth Starr-like vigor, to tell all. ``The Jack
the Dripper questions are the worst part of giving tours,'' Helen
Harrison, curator of the Pollack-Krasner home, told me. ``But what
can you do? Some visitors relate to people more easily than they do
to art.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't always easy to handle. For instance, the Walt Whitman
birthplace in Huntington Station, N.Y., has been accused of
``erasing history'' by one gay group for not bringing up Whitman's
homosexuality on the tour. ``With us, it's don't ask, don't tell,''
said Kay Carroll, a guide there. ``But if it's relevant to a
visitor, we try to answer questions, and we have books that address
Whitman's sexuality in the gift shop.''
</P>
<P>
   At Hyde Park, Scott Rector, who trains guides, has noticed an
increase in probing questions. ``We tell visitors that we prefer to
stick to what we know from our own research,'' he said. In this
case, it does not include anything about the fidelity of FDR or his
wife. But when ``Empty Without You'' by Rodger Streitmatter (Free
Press) hits bookstores this fall, guides are bound to face more
questions: The book features the romantic-sounding correspondence
between Eleanor Roosevelt and Lorena Hickok.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I say to visitors who ask is that Eleanor Roosevelt
enjoyed people,'' Rector said. ``If a visitor is adamant about
something, I say I'll have to look into it. You never know who else
is on the tour, and you don't want to offend anyone, especially
members of the Roosevelt family.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at Monticello, what some people now think of as a
hotbed of innuendo, guides are facing more questions about the
sexual relations between Thomas Jefferson and Sally Hemings, a
slave. Their response is that there's no definitive answer yet, and
that there may never be one. Elizabeth Dowling Taylor, the head
guide there, attributes the increased interest to ``Jefferson in
Paris,'' the 1995 Merchant-Ivory film, as well as to the general
climate of the times. ``We're moving away from the `great man'
approach to history and getting more into personal history,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Less salacious but equally provocative is the revamped image of
305-year-old Philipsburg Manor, which now emphasizes contributions
of enslaved Africans, and Van Cortlandt Manor, where guides
disclose how strangers shared beds at the tavern. Burns Patterson,
a spokesman for Historic Hudson Valley, which owns both, explained:
``We need to make sites exciting and can't rest on a tour that was
written 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   So many homes, so many intrigues.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Did Charles Dodgson photograph any of his young Alices in his
home in Oxford, England? What do the guides at Georgia O'Keeffe's
adobe residence in Abiquiu, N.M., think about the recent searing
biography by Jeffrey Hogrefe, who contends that the artist
``shamed'' the local church into selling her the house? What do
they say at Nixon's birthplace in Yorba Linda, Calif.? And whatever
are they saying at the White House these days?
</P>
<P>
   These thoughts were crossing my mind, like so many squirrels in
the attic, as our soft-spoken guide stood on the lawn, fielding
tawdry questions about Pollock. Finally, after the litany had
ended, she invited us into his studio to turn our attention to what
really mattered _ his art.
</P>
<P>
   Before stepping in, we had to remove our shoes and put on
special foam slippers to avoid marring the paint-splattered floor
of the barn. My parents rolled their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not taking my shoes off,'' Mom said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll go wait in the car,'' my father added. ``There's a
ball game on the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, their curiosity got the better of them. Once inside,
they walked around, inspecting the space where so many monumental
works had been dribbled and poured. There were rusty coffee cans
with paintbrushes, old tubes of pigment, pieces of colored glass _
in short, a raw environment where important ideas were born.
Although the preserved splatterings on the floor didn't teach my
mother anything at all (a mess, after all, is a mess), what did
interest her was an article from a 1949 Life magazine, mounted on
the wall. It described Pollock as a ``shining new phenomenon of
American art.'
</P>
<P>
   When the guide informed us that this article was responsible for
making the artist into an international figure, my mother let loose
with a happy ``Hmmph!'' Here was evidence that this splatter-happy
man's status was about the media, not his talent. ``The critics can
do so much for a career,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the little shingled house next to the barn, an old hi-fi
was playing one of Pollock's jazz albums. I couldn't help wishing
that the orderly home I grew up in had been more bohemian, like
this one. My parents fell quiet as the guide pointed out what she
felt was significant: a human skull that Pollock stole from the Art
Students League, a rusty anchor scavenged from the beach and a
monumental abstract painting by Krasner, who spent most of her life
promoting her husband's career and memory.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, the guide showed us the tiny room Krasner used as her
studio while Pollock was alive. And in the master bedroom, where an
old electric clock still kept time, she told us that Krasner (who
lived in the house until her death in 1984) had installed the big
bed after Pollock died. When he was alive, they had twin beds. No
comment besides that.
</P>
<P>
   Later, someone noticed a copy of ``Finnegans Wake'' on a
bookshelf and remarked that the couple must have been intellectual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that,'' the guide said. ``The bookmark is
only on page three.''
</P>
<P>
   A drop-leaf table, an elliptical mirror, a collection of
seashells. There wasn't much to see inside the Pollock-Krasner
house, just the modest environment of two people who lived for art,
not things. My parents listened to the guide (who later confided to
me that she thought Pollock must have been ``a horror to live
with'') speak in measured tones about his Jungian therapy and, over
and over again, his drinking. Yet, in the end, they left thinking
about Krasner, who surely would have had things to discuss with
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``She promoted her husband for her entire life,'' Mom said, as
we got into the car, ``even when she knew he was unfaithful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so stable and so selfless,'' Dad said. ``And she
painted beautifully, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As we drove away from the historic house of creative bedlam, I
felt purged of my desire for a bohemian lineage. ``Compared to
that,'' Mom said, ``I guess our house is pretty boring, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   I nodded. ``Thank goodness,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pollock-Krasner house is open Thursday, Friday and Saturday
by appointment. Information: (516) 324-4929.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
