<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MORTGAGE-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORTGAGE DEBATE: WAIT OR SEIZE THE MOMENT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How loooooooow can they go?
</P>
<P>
   With the rates for many mortgages almost a percentage point
below where they were a year ago, prospective co-op and condominium
buyers in Manhattan are asking their mortgage brokers whether they
should take the plunge or wait until the stock market _ or interest
rates _ take another dive.
</P>
<P>
   The answer depends on whom you talk to. The heads of New York
City's two biggest mortgage brokerages _ Skyscraper Mortgage and
Manhattan Mortgage _ give intriguingly different advice.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Bader, the chief executive of Skyscraper Mortgage, said he
tells clients who don't have to buy now to ``hold off for six
months.'' Bader, who wrote $750 million in mortgages last year,
predicts that real-estate prices in Manhattan will soften further _
financial parlance for ``go down'' _ and that mortgage interest
rates will also decrease.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Dow Jones industrial average's 512-point plunge on
Aug. 31, Bader has been besieged with calls from nervous buyers.
His purchase business _ as opposed to the refinancing of existing
mortgages to take advantage of the low rates _ is down 35 percent
from what it was in September 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his chief competitor, Melissa Cohn, the president of
Manhattan Mortgage, said that the number of customers applying
through her company for a new mortgage, not a refinance, has stayed
almost the same. What have changed are the percentages those new
mortgages represent.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, new mortgage applications made up 76 percent
of the company's $800-million-a-year business. This September, new
buyers made up 59 percent. The number of refinancings almost
doubled _ from 24 percent in September 1997 to 41 percent last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cohn is advising buyers to seize the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to predict the future,'' she said. ``First,
the apartment you love may not be there in six months. Second,
nothing says that prices _ after one month of softening _ may not
turn around and start going up again. And third, interest rates
could go up.''
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy between the Skyscraper figures, which show a
significant drop in applications to buy, and those from Manhattan
Mortgage, which show about the same number of applications, can be
readily explained. Skyscraper, Bader said, owes 80 percent of its
business to Wall Street _ brokers, bankers and lawyers. Only 40
percent of Manhattan Mortgage's business comes from Wall Street,
Ms. Cohn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people closest to Wall Street _ the high-flying folks _
may not be coming into the marketplace,'' said Keith Gumbinger, a
vice president with HSH Associates, of Butler, N.J., a financial
publisher that surveys lenders across the United States. ``Whereas
people not connected with it, more middle-market folks, just don't
notice any difference.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who have decided to buy, Bader, Ms. Cohn and other
mortgage brokers surveyed this week offered the following advice:
</P>
<P>
   If you're wondering whether to go for a 30-year fixed mortgage
or one of the tailor-made five-, seven- or 10-year adjustable
mortgages _ in which the interest rate remains fixed for the first
five, seven or 10 years and then adjusts relative to the prevailing
rates _ consider this. Current 30-year fixed-mortgage interest
rates, which were around 6.69 percent Wednesday, according to HSH,
are the lowest in three decades. So if you're a bit of a gambler,
or if you know you're going to live in your new house for, say,
exactly 10 years, you'll pay less per month with a 10-year
adjustable.
</P>
<P>
   Match the product to the time frame, brokers say. They agree
that if you need a $300,000 mortgage, you'll pay $120 less a month
in the first decade of a 10-year adjustable than for a 30-year
fixed.
</P>
<P>
   But with the rates for 30-year fixed loans so low, some buyers
may prefer to pay the extra and relax. After all, over the next 30
years, rates will almost certainly go up. (Remember when mortgages
hit 16 percent during the Carter administration?)
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that with all the uncertainty, you feel most
comfortable by jumping into a 30-year fixed,'' Gumbinger of HSH
said. ``It provides the most stability, but you'll have to pay for
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
