<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2615 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX     09-30 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jesus Principle''
</P>
<P>
   By Charles R. Wade and Lee and Carol Bowman
</P>
<P>
   Clear Stream Publishing, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   ``Reinventing American Protestantism''
</P>
<P>
   By Donald E. Miller
</P>
<P>
   University of California Press, $27.50
</P>
<P>
   There's theory, and then there's practice. Charles R. Wade is
telling us how ``to'' do church, and Donald E. Miller is telling us
how some people ``do'' do church.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Jesus Principle,'' Wade _ with the help of Lee and
Carol Bowman _ presents his theology of how to build churches in
the likeness of Christ: ``When the church, `the Body of Christ,'
worships, evangelizes, disciples, ministers, and creates
fellowship, it is doing ... what Jesus did when he was here on
earth, and what he is doing today as he fills the congregation of
believers with his Holy Spirit. ... The church learns to behave as
Jesus behaved. That is the `Jesus Principle.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After perceptively dissecting the nature of Christ and the
church, the Texas minister examines five congregational activities
as well as practical aspects of congregation-building. He is
particularly concerned about ministry to the marginalized, and his
ideas about church vision and personal ``calling'' echo those in
``Experiencing God.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade's decades of ministry experience have obviously provided
him with a wealth of insight. ``The Jesus Principle'' contains
thoughts that will be valuable even to those who don't fully agree
with its moderate Southern Baptist author.
</P>
<P>
   Donald E. Miller, meanwhile, is certainly not a moderate
Southern Baptist, and neither are the believers he has studied; but
anyone interested in the changing face of religion would do well to
pay attention to his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we are witnessing a second reformation that is
transforming the way Christianity will be experienced in the new
millennium,'' the University of Southern California professor
writes. ``Reinventing American Protestantism'' is a study of ``new
paradigm churches'' that have combined conservative theology, an
emphasis on cultural relevance, and an informal and charismatic
style of worship and organization.
</P>
<P>
   These movements are plainly successful in ways that mainline
denominations are not, Miller says. That is an interesting
observation, because even though his study is arguably sympathetic,
the author is a liberal Episcopalian who makes it clear that he
does not buy into his subjects' theological package. ``Reinventing
American Protestantism'' is a highly readable study that may prove
particularly interesting to those interested in
``nondenominational'' Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
