<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      09-30 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Oct. 1, 1998, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early Wednesday morning bands of thunderstorms spawned several
tornadoes across northern Florida as the ghost of Hurricane Georges
drifted slowly toward eastern Georgia. Early Thursday morning,
showers and isolated thunderstorms will speckle the Southeast
Coast. The precipitation will end by afternoon as the remnant
moisture of Georges finally pushes out to sea. Meanwhile, sinking
currents of air in the wake of the system will promote mainly sunny
and very warm conditions from the southern Mississippi Valley to
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   A band of clouds and isolated thundershowers will accompany a
sharp cold front moving south from the Ohio Valley Thursday. Gusty
winds from the northwest behind the front will import the chilliest
air so far this season into the upper Middle West and interior
Northeast. As the unseasonably cold air gathers moisture in transit
across the still tepid waters of the Great Lakes, roiling cumulus
clouds will form downwind of the Lakes. A few of these clouds will
produce brief, gusty showers of rain, especially east of Lake
Ontario Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Showers will develop over the Front Range of the Rockies and
west-central Plains Thursday as winds from the east moisten upon
ascending the sloping terrain. The showers could turn heavy for a
time as a jet stream disturbance approaching from the central
Rockies intercepts the moist air mass.
</P>
<P>
   Onshore breezes will direct damp and cool air into the Northwest
Coast while generally dry conditions cover eastern sections of
Washington and Oregon. The Southwest will remain mainly sunny and
warm, though patchy clouds will cover the California coastline.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Focus: Memorable Storm &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges was a memorable storm. The first advisory for
a tropical depression came near 25 degrees west longitude,
unusually far east in the Atlantic. As the developing system
approached the Lesser Antilles, its top sustained winds reached 150
mph. Though the storm weakened near longitude 60 degrees west, it
marched onward, successfully negotiating the mountains of Puerto
Rico and the lofty peaks on Hispaniola. It then hit Cuba before
battering the Florida Keys and intensifying over the Gulf of
Mexico. The storm then dumped up to 30 inches of rain on parts of
the Gulf States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2620 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TRADING-TIPS-NYT &LR;      09-30 0254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TRADING-TIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY-TRADING TIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CIR-TRADING-ONLINE, CIR-TRADING-SITES)  
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Day trading isn't for the faint-hearted. Like other forms of
investing, it doesn't come with a guarantee that future returns
will mimic any favorable ones of the past. And because day trading
is highly speculative and can easily swallow up large chunks of
cash, experts say it's not an appropriate investment strategy for,
say, savings for retirement or college.
</P>
<P>
   Getting started can be hideously expensive as well. For example,
while some day-trading firms let a customer get started with just
$25,000 in an account, Broadway Trading requires a customer to have
at least $75,000 in a trading account.
</P>
<P>
   Several day-trading firms say that even well-padded investors
can expect to wait six months before they begin making money. And
while they're waiting, it's common to lose tens of thousands of
dollars. For that reason, some firms, like All-Tech, recommend that
new day traders trade only in lots of 200 shares at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Other costs can add up quickly as well. Investors who trade full
time from home, for example, can expect to pay an extra $400 to
$700 a month in phone costs alone, as part of dialing into a
company's trading system.
</P>
<P>
   To cut connection costs, some day-trading firms, like All-Tech
Investments, offer their proprietary services through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure reliability, the firms will also recommend an Internet
service provider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
