Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (United Nations) _ U.N. Security Council schedules
emergency meeting on Kosovo on Thursday as several countries and
secretary general voice outrage at report of new massacre. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With: KOSOVO-MASSACRE (Prstina, Yugoslavia) _ Developments in
the aftermath of the massacre by Serb soldiers of ethnic Albanian
civilians. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   SURPLUS-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton announces that
the government will end the fiscal year with a budget surplus of
about $70 billion. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With: SURPLUS-IMPACT (Washington) _ So where's the payoff? To
some degree, the answer is straightforward: Interest rates are
lower than they would be otherwise, a development that has helped
push unemployment down and the stock market up throughout much of
this decade. But even now, some economists think the benefits from
fiscal prudence have been overstated and wonder whether the
projected surpluses will materialize if the economy should slip
into recession. By Richard W. Stevenson. 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCHIPPERS (Washington) _ A profile of David P.
Schippers, chief investigator on the House Judiciary Committee. By
Lizette Alvarez. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-AIDS-VACCINE (Kampala, Uganda) _ In Uganda _ a country
struggling valiantly to cope with an AIDS epidemic that has
infected 20 percent of its population, desperate Ugandans clamor to
participate in an AIDS vaccine trial. In the past, ethical
guidelines have made it clear that vaccines should be tested where
health care is excellent before they are ever used in places
without a safety net, like Uganda. Now for the first time, the
international medical community has set aside that requirement.
``We are the people with the problem. Why should Americans
undertake risky research on themselves for a problem they don't
really have? That would make them the guinea pigs. The risk belongs
here, where the people are dying,'' said one researcher. By Michael
Specter. A Special Report; 2,200 words. With map and photos.
</P>
</TEXT>
