<HEADLINE>
HANDY INTERNET  
 WATCHING RADIO  
 CYBERSCHOOL  
 COSTLY KEYWORD  
 WORLD WIDE WAIT  
 PC LEMONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This just in from the World of the Incredible Shrinking
Computer: A Berkeley, Calif., company is testing software that
handheld computers can use to surf the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The new browser, brazenly squeezing in where even Netscape's
Navigator and Microsoft's Internet Explorer have not dared to
tread, is called Proxiweb. It essentially captures Web page images,
then shrinks them to a size and format viewable on the very small
screen of a Palm Pilot or a Windows CE computer.
</P>
<P>
   But are the Web faithful prepared to do their thing on such tiny
devices? ``It's not our world view that people will want to do a
search for `sea cucumber' while sitting on the bus,'' said Tara
Suan, spokeswoman for Proxinet Inc., makers of the diminutive
browser. ``But we do think people may want to access personalized
services like e-mail or My Yahoo.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus scenario, indeed the Proxiweb model in general, relies
on the growth of wireless modem technology for hand-held personal
computers, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company, which is beta testing the software, said
it hoped to sell a commercial product by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, searches for sea cucumbers will have to be done
on the desktop, laptop or the old-fashioned way, in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   New Web Radio Will Show Animation to Go With Music
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere around the nexus of MTV, radio, the Internet and the
late-night laser show at the Planetarium exists FlashRadio, which
its marketers are calling a new concept in radio. FlashRadio
(www.flashradio.com), which is scheduled to debut Thursday,
presents five channels of different music themes, including pop,
alternative and urban. The added touch is that while the music
plays, the monitor fills with a continuous animation show (the
images are not tailored to the individual songs, but to the
channel's ``mood.'')
</P>
<P>
   The station is the product of a joint effort between Sonicnet
(www.sonicnet.com), the popular music entertainment site,
Macromedia (www.macromedia.com), which makes animation software,
and Intel Corp. Nicholas Butterworth, the 30-year-old president of
Sonicnet _ a division of TCI Music _ conceded that there were
already a lot of radio stations on the Internet. ``They have been
great to listen to, but boring to watch,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   How much fun FlashRadio will be to watch may depend on the speed
of your processor. Butterworth noted that a Pentium II processor
was needed for optimal viewing. That is a vast minority of home
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Some Stanford Students Go Deeper Into Cyberspace
</P>
<P>
   Students entering the electrical engineering master's degree
program at Stanford University last week may hold some future class
reunion in an Internet chat room. That would seem about right,
given that some of the students will take all their classes, turn
in all their homework and hold all class discussions online.
</P>
<P>
   Taking courses via the Net has become increasingly common, and
Stanford now is permitting some students to graduate with a
prestigious Master of Science degree without ever leaving the
comfort of their desktops.
</P>
<P>
   The program extends into cyberspace a 30-year tradition at
Stanford of distance learning, which typically has been
accomplished by sending videotapes of classes to remote students.
In the case of the Net, the university will stream the video onto
the Web for student access.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of caveats. To be eligible, students must
work at one of roughly 300 high-tech companies affiliated with the
electrical engineering program. Also, students who participate
online will pay more than their on-campus classmates _ an academic
unit taken via the Internet costs $844, 40 percent more than the
cost of attending classes in the flesh, said Andy DiPaolo,
executive director of the Stanford Center for Professional
Development.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, this new generation of online study would seem to
demand a commensurate advance in student excuses for late work.
Possibilities: ``Professor, the dog ate my modem,'' or ``My
computer contracted a virus. I'm e-mailing a note from tech
support.''
</P>
<P>
   This Space Available on AOL Starting for a Mere $25,000
</P>
<P>
   For the Web surfer who has everything, the new Neiman Marcus
Christmas catalog offers an exclusive spot on the menu of America
Online. The price tag: just $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that is the minimum bid in the auction for the spot,
which AOL calls a ``keyword.'' Typically, these keywords are saved
for general categories such as ``sports,'' or ``news,'' or
sometimes are used to advertise online events for celebrities like
the Spice Girls. The keyword up for auction will be the first
assigned to a regular Joe or Jane, albeit one with some big green
to toss around.
</P>
<P>
   The winning bidder will get a new computer (perhaps not a big
bonus for someone with $25,000 to spare on a Web site) and help in
designing the content to which the keyword will be linked. There
are some restrictions, however, in that the bidder can use the
keyword only to link to personal content, not for business. The
keyword will be active for one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a vanity license plate,'' said Ginger Reeder,
spokeswoman for Neiman Marcus Direct, who knows how to wring an
analogy out of the ``information superhighway'' metaphor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A New Way to Kill Some Time While Web Pages Download
</P>
<P>
   A San Francisco company wants to capitalize on two rampant
conditions in modern culture _ the World Wide Wait and narcissism.
</P>
<P>
   The World Wide Wait is what some people call the sometimes
excruciatingly slow time that it takes for Web pages to download
for viewing on screen. The Zing Network Inc. (www.zing.com) has
developed a technology that allows Web surfers to scan in and stare
at pictures of themselves, or their families (or their pets) to
pass the downloading downtime.
</P>
<P>
   This interlude is one of several entertainment options offered
by Zing to mitigate the World Wide Wait. The company has signed
deals with Rolling Stone Network, Surfer Magazine and Universal
Studios to provide other images for viewing during the loading
time. Steve Guttman, Zing's executive vice president for marketing
and business development, said the images _ such as still shots of
movie monsters from Universal Studios _ will appear on a monitor
between the time a user calls up a Web page and the time text and
graphics appear.
</P>
<P>
   A survey this year in which Zing participated found that home
modem users wasted 2.4 billion hours a year waiting for content to
download.
</P>
<P>
   So then, these images are somehow enhancing productivity?
</P>
<P>
   Guttman says yes, but he notes it will also cost users a little
bit of attention, as one of every 10 Zing spots will eventually be
advertising. ``Our feeling is if you can make a fraction of that
time more interesting to people they should shower you with money _
I mean, respect,'' Guttman said.
</P>
<P>
   High Failure Rate for New PCs Found in a Magazine Survey
</P>
<P>
   Imagine driving off the lot in a brand-new car only to find that
the radio does not work, the tires are falling off and the steering
wheel will turn only left.
</P>
<P>
   Windows magazine says that situation is analogous to the one
faced far too often by purchasers of new computers whose machines
are dead on arrival.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 6,000 of its readers, published in the October
issue, found that 13 percent of their new computers had come out of
the box with a major hardware failure, most often the modem, hard
drive or monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of performance in any other industry would be
totally unacceptable,'' said Mike Elgan, editor of Windows. ``If 13
percent of refrigerator users couldn't use their new
refrigerator,'' the companies would not survive.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Hewlett-Packard Co., Larry Sennett, does not
like the comparison. He said one reason for the high failure rates
of computer components was that they were ``pretty complex pieces
of electronics.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard fared better than others in the Windows survey.
Respondents reported a problem with that company's PCs at an 8
percent rate, with Dell and Gateway next best at 9 percent. At the
other end of the spectrum were NEC, Packard Bell and AST, each of
which had problems in more than 13 percent of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Sennett said the survey, which included users of both home and
business desktop computers, might indicate that the push for less
expensive PCs meant less is being spent by manufacturers on
components. Meanwhile, he offered one solution that sounded
surprising given his position as editor of Windows: Buy an iMac.
``It's a good solution for a lot of people,'' he said, ``especially
novices.''
</P>
<P>
   As an aside, it appears that CMP Media Inc., which publishes
Windows magazine, wanted to eat its cake and have it too. In a
press release, CMP heralded the findings of the survey about the
high PC failure rates, but mentioned only those companies that
fared better than average. CMP apparently did not want to upset the
other computer companies that advertise in the magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
