<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta gets a feel for New York warm-up
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along with Broadway-caliber excitement, ``Elaborate Lives''
brings to Atlanta another peculiarly New York tradition: the
three-week preview period.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was only a few years ago that the Alliance Theatre
increased its preview performances from two to five, patrons began
to query the Journal-Constitution a few days after ``Lives'' began
previews Sept. 17, ``Where's the review?'' The answer is that it
will appear Oct. 8, the day after the musical's opening, for only
by that time will the creative team finish its tinkering and lock
in the production for the public record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays three weeks is not perceived as a long time here,''
said longtime New York theater publicist Richard Kornberg. ``So
many journalists worldwide are waiting for word on `Lives' that
Disney's going to make darn sure it's ready to open.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who have e-mailed critiques to the Journal-Constitution
seem to find performances more memorable if there's a glitch _ such
as the stalled pyramid that made an inconvenient humming sound
during one musical number.
</P>
<P>
   New York producers dramatically expanded previews in the 1980s,
partly to wrestle with more technically complex productions and
partly to minimize the risk of critical pans. ``There's a constant
tension between critics and producers over the length of
previews,'' said Jeremy Gerard, an editor at New York magazine and
former chief drama critic at Variety. Recalling a major bomb of the
early '90s, he said, ``After `Nick and Nora' dragged out previews
nine weeks (in the early 1990s), a lot of us (critics) swore,
`Never again.'''
</P>
<P>
   But since then few producers have tried to push previews beyond
four weeks, Gerard adds, ``because advertising has gotten so
expensive, they've gotta take their chances on the free publicity
of a review.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
