<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-RAP01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quest stops short of great goodbye
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eight songs into this, Phife Dawg says, ``You don't stop, and
you don't quit/unless you're in the studio doing whack.'' Maybe
that's why A Tribe Called Quest is calling it quits.
</P>
<P>
   Not that ``The Love Movement'' is ``whack'' _ or just terrible.
The pioneering trio's supposed adios to hip-hop (at least as a
group) holds up to the same musical standard set when Tribe hit the
scene eight years ago and went on to brilliantly meld rap's street
grittiness with the smoothness of some jazz. They must have known
that, because Tribe even includes the breezy instrumental track ``4
Moms,'' a rarity on an album in this genre.
</P>
<P>
   But, lyrically, it gives little indication why Q-Tip, Phife Dawg
and Ali Shaheed Muhammad will be missed. They must have known that,
too, because Tribe spends 3 minutes and 18 seconds basically saying
let's get things going (``Start It Up'') and then follows with a
lot of shorter, underdeveloped songs that are rarely reflective of
their capacity for intelligent wordplay. It's like midway through
``Like It Like That'' or ``Common Ground'' someone said, ``Oh, just
forget about it. We've got a hook and a groove.'' So instead of a
great goodbye, we get a danceable ``See ya!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love Movement''
</P>
<P>
   A Tribe Called Quest. Jive. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Goo-goo-eyed groove music.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
