<HEADER>
A2665 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-HIGH-CULTURE-3     09-30 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-HIGH-CULTURE-3TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MEDICI BEHIND DISNEY'S HIGH ART 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4)
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.Y., Mass., Mo., Ohio, Conn., Minn.)   (af) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ On a wall facing Michael Eisner's desk in the
sitting room outside his airy office at the Walt Disney Co.
headquarters hangs a single storyboard _ 18 feet long, 2{ feet high
_ with black and white and color pictures of events of the past 50
years and typeset story lines explaining them.
</P>
<P>
   In an entertainment colossus with $22.5 billion in revenues last
year, there is no shortage of storyboards to go around, so it's
interesting that the one hanging there is for a choral symphony by
the contemporary composer Michael Torke, one of two such
compositions that Eisner commissioned to mark the millennium. It
was an idea that came to him while attending Mahler's Symphony of a
Thousand at Carnegie Hall in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Like Coke or McDonald's, the Disney name and brand is so
implanted in the culture of the nation and the world that to say
the word is to evoke a wholly defined universe _ in this case
Disney's familiar panoply of antic, animated icons and competent,
comforting family entertainment. To some they add up to
imaginative, benign, pop culture marvels. To others, they're just
superficial cultural junk.
</P>
<P>
   But the storyboard outside Eisner's office is a window onto
another side of the Mouse. Seemingly unnoticed, under Eisner's
watch, Disney has become a purveyor of what can only be described
as high culture.
</P>
<P>
   Such work is, and will surely remain, a small part of the
far-flung empire of Disney and Miramax, ABC and ESPN, Tokyo
Disneyland and the Mighty Ducks. Some argue that it is totally
consistent with the company Walt Disney created.
</P>
<P>
   But almost all the more rarefied projects reflect the tastes of
Eisner, Disney's chairman and CEO, and they are revealing glimpses
into the mind and instincts of a man who can shape culture on a
global basis like perhaps no other person in history.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, whose public profile usually plays out in high-stakes
deal making or ferocious corporate jousting, like his messy
divorces from the former Disney titans Jeffrey Katzenberg and
Michael Ovitz, is first and foremost a businessman responsible to
Disney's shareholders. But he is also a man with deep instincts
about culture, shaped by a Park Avenue upbringing that was informed
by sophisticated experiences with architecture, theater, music and
art.
</P>
<P>
   With Disney's resources and reach, Eisner is playing a role more
like arts patrons or imperial business tycoons of the past than
today's cautious, faceless corporate donors, one that ventures
toward the social engineering of the company's Celebration
residential community in Florida as well as artistic pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think back on European history and the support the
churches gave to art and music that later spilled over to the
Medicis,'' said Aaron Jay Kernis, who won a Pulitzer Prize for
music this year and is the other composer commissioned to develop a
choral symphony for the millennium. ``What Eisner and Disney are
doing has the potential to be the new Medicis for our time, if done
in the right way for the best of reasons. It could help new culture
flower when what we're seeing is this overwhelming junk culture.''
</P>
<P>
   There are few hard and fast lines between high art and any other
kind, and Disney officials, ever image-conscious, are uncomfortable
with the distinction, seeing in it the implicit notion that on one
side is the good stuff and on the other the shlock. But whatever
you call it, Disney's output now includes much that doesn't fit the
notion of what is, well, Disneyesque.
</P>
<P>
   There are the two choral symphonies by Torke and Kernis. Torke's
work, essentially looking back on the past half century, has a
libretto by Philip Littell. Kernis' looks into the future and has a
libretto by a Welsh poet, Menna Elfyn. The pieces will be
introduced at concerts in New York, with the details still to be
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   There was the decision to bring in Julie Taymor, one of the most
cerebral and innovative theatrical directors and designers, to
transform ``The Lion King'' from the standard Disney animated idyll
into a wonder of contemporary multicultural theatrics and
stagecraft on Broadway. The much-acclaimed renovation of the New
Amsterdam Theater came along as part of the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   There is Eisner's longstanding and enthusiastic support for many
of the most acclaimed figures in modern architecture like Robert
A.M. Stern, Michael Graves, Robert Venturi, Arata Isozaki, Frank
Gehry, Aldo Rossi and others, to create a body of architectural
work unmatched by any company and perhaps by any contemporary
institution, public or private.
</P>
<P>
   There is a long-delayed new version of the Disney classic
``Fantasia,'' in the form of ``Fantasia 2000,'' with six new
symphonic pieces and three revisions of original pieces performed
by James Levine and the Chicago Symphony. Levine and the orchestra
will introduce the music next winter, beginning with concerts at
Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   There is a $25 million donation that will finally allow the
construction of a grandiose Disney Concert Hall in downtown Los
Angeles that was conceived a decade ago with a $50 million gift
from Walt Disney's widow, Lillian B. Disney. There is Disney's
Young Musicians Symphony Orchestra, the new ``Elaborate Lives: The
Legend of Aida,'' getting ready for its premiere in Atlanta, and a
stage version of ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame,'' which will open
in Berlin in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And however one defines her place in the cultural petrie dish,
there is the former New Yorker editor Tina Brown, whose friendship
with Eisner helped lead to her new role heading a media venture
that will include a monthly magazine intended to create films and
television shows for Disney's Miramax subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects the face of Disney to go from Mickey Mouse to
Elliott Carter. Some critics have derided Disney's high culture
borrowings, like the film of ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame,'' as
far closer to base trivializations than high art.
</P>
<P>
   To many people, Disney is and will always be the quintessence of
junk culture, less vulgar than Jerry Springer or the Fox network
but still a greedy mass marketer of sanitized, shriveled
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
