<HEADER>
A2666 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS01-COX     09-30 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio Reviews: The latest word on the latest sounds
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Steve Dollar, Richard L. Eldredge, Shane
Harrison, and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Dizzy Up the Girl''
</P>
<P>
   Goo Goo Dolls. Warner Bros. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Long dismissed as a Replacements clone band, this Buffalo, N.Y.,
trio has lately opted for a more commercially viable sound,
beginning with the 1995 hit ballad ``Name.'' The shift has
continued through this summer's overplayed single ``Iris,'' from
the ``City of Angels'' soundtrack as the group has slowly traded
scruffy guitars and souped-up tempos for stadium-size riffs and
sappy platitudes. The slick tricks continue on the Dolls' seventh
album, which mixes formulaic alterna-rockers (``Broadway,'' ``Black
Balloon'') with overblown lighter-wavers (``January Friend''). The
results are catchy, but indistinguishable from Dishwalla,
Collective Soul or any number of other so-called ``alternative''
acts on the scene today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's Kill Saturday Night''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Fulks. Geffen. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's ``insurgent country'' cover boy, singer-songwriter
Robbie Fulks has distinguished himself as the next big thing in a
genre that's become a vague catchall for any act strong enough to
tote around a pedal steel guitar. How dandy it is that Fulks' third
album and major-label debut leapfrogs out of that rut in a variety
of ways. There's plenty of old-line C&AMP;W stylizing (including the
apostate's anthem, ``God Isn't Real''), but the fun comes with the
distorted guitars of ``Caroline'' and the Byrdsian jangle of ``She
Must Think That I Like Poetry.'' Lucinda Williams makes a guest
appearance, as Fulks channels Elvis Costello on ``Pretty Little
Poison,'' a song in which shimmery pop chops and rebel passions not
only co-exist but break a suave sweat.
</P>
<P>
   -- POP
</P>
<P>
   ``The Apple Bed''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Heyward.15 tracks. Big Deal Records
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   After dazzling listeners with his first solo album, ``North of a
Miracle'' in 1984, the former leader of Brit popsters Haircut 100
has offered frustrated fans only momentary glimpses of his keen pop
sensibilities in the intervening 14 years. Now, here's ``The Apple
Bed,'' which with melodic guitars, gorgeous string quartets, horns
and layered vocal harmonies comes close to being a pop masterpiece.
Like ``Miracle'' which was produced by Beatles ``Abbey Road''
engineer Geoff Emerick, the self-produced ``Apple Bed'' clearly
draws on Heyward's love of '60s pop, but with a '90s sensibility.
How else to explain ``Incredible Agnes,'' a tale of finding love at
the video shop or Heyward's clever insights into his own 1980s pop
stardom, ``The Man You Used to Be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boy With the Arab Strap''
</P>
<P>
   Belle &AMP; Sebastian. Matador. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish combo that saw its sophomore release, ``If You're
Feeling Sinister,'' land on numerous year-end Top 10 lists is a
more mature outfit here. Following an album that drew nearly
universal critical acclaim is not an enviable task, but Belle &AMP;
Sebastian have come through. The childlike jangle and youthful
lyrical concerns of the last record have passed through puberty and
come out the other side with a tad more muscularity. The title cut
comes perilously close to rocking. It also appears that primary
vocalist and songwriter Stuart Murdoch has loosened the songwriting
reins. It's difficult to be sure about that from perusing the CD's
sleeve, though. Belle &AMP; Sebastian inhabits a world where bands
don't go in for heavy-handed promotional hype or even such niceties
as credits. It's a much gentler world than ours, filled with
transcendent music.
</P>
<P>
   -- URBAN
</P>
<P>
   ``Rush Hour'' Soundtrack
</P>
<P>
   Various Artists. Def Jam. 25 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Almost half skits from this record-breaking movie, the other
half songs from urban contemporary stars, the ``Rush Hour''
soundtrack is all fine, although little here is as memorable as a
Chris Tucker screech. But rapper Jay-Z's bouncy ``Can I Get a ...''
and ``Terror Squadians,'' including Big Pun and Fat Joe, loom large
as the better tracks in this sizable collection. Plus, you can file
Case's (``Touch Me Tease Me'') team-up with R&AMP;B vocalist Joe on
``Faded Pictures'' under the pleasant surprise category. As for
``How Deep Is Your Love'' by R&AMP;B quartet Dru Hill and rapper
Redman? Considering their previous work, their efforts here can go
in File 13.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
