<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ROCK01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pop singer wanders into the Gothic mists
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the ashes of a once blazing pyre, the music P.J. Harvey's
making right now is a wind-blown trace marking some powerful,
all-consuming occurrence. The voice on these songs, often
omniscient and a little detached, could belong to a ghost _ a
wandering murder victim from some Appalachian ballad, offering
testimony to those who will pay heed _ or someone recovering from
an alien abduction, or maybe a wan British pop singer, steeped in
the gothicism of Edgar Allan Poe, the primacy of American blues,
the transgressive clamor of Nick Cave and Captain Beefheart and
Pere Ubu.
</P>
<P>
   Polly Jean Harvey's career triumph was her last solo album, ``To
Bring You My Love,'' a cathartic walk with love and death, God and
the Devil, that played like the soundtrack to a virgin sacrifice
(if, say, Joan of Arc was in league with Howlin' Wolf). The
rhetorical tilt to ``Is This Desire?'' already implies a
distancing.
</P>
<P>
   And the new songs Harvey has composed, with a band featuring
various Bad Seeds and Ubu/Beefheart sideman Eric Drew Feldman, seem
to unfold in a pre-Raphaelite waking dreamworld, all funereal and
forboding and full of forking garden paths in which lovely blossoms
wither into twilight.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a song called ``The Garden.'' Along with ``The
River,'' ``The Wind'' and ``The Sky Lit Up,'' and various titles
devoted to women's names (''Angelene,'' ``A Perfect Day Elise,''
``Joy,'' ``Catherine,'' ``My Beautiful Leah''). There's obviously,
you know, conscious artistry going on, but Harvey's not making it
easy for you. Even the haunted lilt she so seductively evokes is
nearly always at odds with deafening bass or keyboard rumbles and
odd, textured layers of sound. Is this a good P.J. Harvey album?
Yeah, it is. Does it matter? I haven't a clue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is This Desire?''
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Harvey. Island. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Once emphatic, the British singer tosses her fans a
question mark.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
