<HEADER>
A2668 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-RAPb01-COX     09-30 0279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-RAPb01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outkast enjoys free rein
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being from and obviously really loving the South has given
Outkast an incredible vantage point from which to view the rap
world, because the Atlanta rap duo isn't caught up in all the East
Coast posturing. But it has the kind of respected sense of its
Southern self that enables Outkast to enlist Staten Island, N.Y.'s
Raekwon of the Wu-Tang Clan for a racing and kinetic ``Skew It on
the Bar-B'' that's surely being played in sports-utility vehicles
tooling Harlem streets.
</P>
<P>
   And, no, Outkast isn't about shooting and robbing like much West
Coast gangster rap, because the life they've detailed on two
previous million-selling records has been about cruising
Campbellton Road in Cadillacs looking for women _ not for a target
for a drive-by. Nevertheless, ``Aquemini'' is heavy on the same
keyboards and Blaxploitation soundtracks that power Dr. Dre.
</P>
<P>
   See, growing up in a region that doesn't have a signature sound,
Outkast feels comfortable incorporating it all. Even better, with
just two lines verbal acrobats Dre and Big Boi can quickly take you
wherever they're at on a particular song: reminiscing about an old
girlfriend (``Da Art of Storytellin _ Pt. 1''), surveying their
surroundings as ghetto superstars (``Return of the `G''') or simply
seeking the ``Liberation'' any listener is sure to find here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aquemini''
</P>
<P>
   Outkast. LaFace. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A combination of Aquarius and Gemini, '70s rhythms
and a lot of sense.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
