<SLUG> BC-DVD-GRAFFITI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disc has the goods on `Graffiti'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two things to recommend the 25th anniversary
re-release of ``American Graffiti'' on DVD. First is the
opportunity to see how the early '70s _ the film came out in 1973 _
viewed the early '60s _ the film is set in 1962. Keep in mind that
George Lucas' nostalgic celebration of a more innocent ``happy
days'' era for teens was released the same year as Martin
Scorsese's ``Mean Streets,'' Nicolas Roeg's ``Don't Look Now,'' and
Marlon Brando in ``Last Tango in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more fascinating is a bonus feature offered only on the
DVD: a 75-minute featurette on ``The Making of `American
Graffiti.''' Lucas is interviewed at length, along with sound
editor Walter Murch (he just worked on the restored ``Touch of
Evil''), writers Gloria Katz and Willard Huyck and all of the
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Among the revelations:
</P>
<P>
   -- Lucas named Paul Le Mat's ``cool'' character, John Milner,
after his filmmaking buddy, John Milius.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jack Nicholson suggested Lucas test Candy Clark.
</P>
<P>
   -- Harrison Ford had to interrupt ``a very successful carpentry
career'' (his words) to audition.
</P>
<P>
   -- Suzanne Somers, who played the role of the unattainable
blonde in the T-bird, recalls that her interview with Lucas
consisted of one question: ``Can you drive?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Making of'' also puts to rest (sort of) an aspect of
``American Graffiti'' that's bothered me for a quarter of a
century. The memorable coda tells us what happened to each of the
guys _ Ron Howard sells insurance; Charles Martin Smith went to
Vietnam, etc. Nothing is said about the girls. Lucas, squirming
ever so slightly a la Clinton during the grand jury videotaping,
says that it was a creative decision, a matter of too many bios _
eight instead of four _ cluttering up the ending. However, Cindy
Williams, who played Howard's girlfriend, has a better explanation.
She says that it reflects the times. That, in 1962 and even in
1973, all girls had pretty much the same future: marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
