<HEADER>
A2670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARTH-SHOTS01-COX     09-30 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTH-SHOTS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GLOBAL CHANGE COMES TO THE INTERNET
 &HT;    Eds: Publishable photos are available at the Web site noted in
the text.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Scientists don't agree on why a 4,600-square-mile
hunk of ice broke away from Antarctica 12 years ago and started
floating northward in the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Some climate researchers think the event may have be related to
global warming, and some glaciologists say the event was part of a
normal cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the glacial ``calving'' - and other examples of
global change - are now within a mouse click of anyone with access
to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Geological Survey page on the Internet
(http://www.usgs.gov/earthshots) presents satellite imagery
collected over the last 30 years to illustrate the changes under
way around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Using images that U.S. Landsat satellites have been beaming back
to Earth since the 1970s, Geological Survey scientists are posting
a series of ``change pairs,'' scans of the Earth's surface that
illustrate before-and-after conditions of key spots.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, a ``change pair'' will include several images
rather than just two.
</P>
<P>
   Deforestation in the Brazilian state of Rondonia in the Amazon
rain forest is ominously evident in two satellite images, one from
1975 and the other from 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier image shows a practically unbroken expanse of forest
in a 150-square-mile area of Rondonia. Only a pair of intersecting
roads appear in the rain forest vegetation, which appears red in
the satellite image.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1992 image shows widespread land clearing along a series
of roads that have been built to intersect with the original
highways.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Quirk, a remote sensing scientist with the Geological
Survey's EROS Data Center in Sioux Falls, S.D., said the Internet
site is getting about 10,000 ``hits'' a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change pairs seem to be kind of like potato chips,'' Quirk
said in a telephone interview. ``You have one and you want another
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The site grew out of a booklet the survey put out several years
ago to take global change illustrations into classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we ran out of booklets, we decided to post the material
on the Internet and start updating it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the booklets and the Internet site are intended to
illustrate ``what's happening on the face of the Earth over time
and how important it is to monitor our environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Earthshots site also includes explanations of the imagery
and descriptions of how scientists read it.
</P>
<P>
   There is no scientific uncertainty about why Africa's Lake Chad
has shrunk in the past 30 years from nearly 10,000 square miles to
just 800 square miles. A combination of drought and irrigation have
all but destroyed the lake, and Earthspots images show the change.
</P>
<P>
   A few thousand miles away, vast areas of coastal mangrove swamps
have been dying on the coast of Senegal. Once thought to be the
result of a disease sweeping through the wetlands, the die-off is
now believed to be caused by the same continental drought that
contributes to the shrinking of Lake Chad.
</P>
<P>
   With less rainfall, rivers are becoming more saline and
mangroves are being poisoned. Earthspots documents the change.
</P>
<P>
   In another area, satellite views show the abandonment of
farmland in Ukraine as a result of the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant accident.
</P>
<P>
   The images show Texas-scale urban sprawl in Dallas-Fort Worth
and San Antonio and changes resulting from the eruption of Mount
St. Helens in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Quirk said he has 10 new sets of imagery nearly ready to add to
the Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of Santiago, Chile, and the successful efforts of the
Netherlands to claim additional territory by diking off the North
Sea will go on line soon, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he has satellite images recorded of a small central
Florida city not long after the opening of Disney World _ to be
compared with those of modern Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
