<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-GRAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shades of gray
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the boardroom to the dance floor, gray takes center stage
as the season's latest must-have color.
</P>
<P>
   Designer Ralph Lauren calls gray ``the neutral for the season''
while Bill Blass dubs it ``the ultimate classic.'' Gray in all its
glorious shades _ from pearl to charcoal _ is a solid choice for
building a chic wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lee Eiseman, a color tracker with the Color
Marketing Group, gray's a good compromise shade. ``It's a softer
color than black,'' she says, ``yet it does everything that black
does.'' And Michele Weston, fashion and style director for Mode
magazine, says gray is an important shade that will continue to be
popular right into spring.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news, since you'll find gray in everything from
wools and cashmere to rayon blends and silk. Gray's an easy color
to dress up or dress down with the flick of an accessory in the
palest pinks or the brightest reds.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Jo Katz, catering director for the Swissotel Atlanta,
owns two pairs of gray trousers and is looking for the perfect
medium-color gray flannels to wear at cocktail parties with a lace
top and striped Armani jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this look,'' says the former fashion model. ``Most
people think of gray flannel only in terms of daytime clothes, but
it's comfortable and unexpected for evening wear.''
</P>
<P>
   To give you some ideas on how to make gray a part of your
wardrobe, we chose two pairs of gray trousers: one charcoal and one
light gray, and paired them with a variety of tops for five
different looks. Don't be afraid to experiment with plaids, stripes
or checks, and for you color-shy dressers, gray's a natural mate
with navys and creams. The most important thing is to have a gray
day!
</P>
<P>
   Suited for the boardroom
</P>
<P>
   Any woman in a gray flannel suit will look snappy in
front-pleated gray wool trousers ($68) and matching one-button
jacket ($128). For a classy touch, add a white pique shirt ($39)
and an Adrienne Vittadini scarf in tones of gray and black ($20),
all from Casual Corner stores.
</P>
<P>
   Brunching in style
</P>
<P>
   To give the charcoal trousers ($68, Casual Corner) a laid-back
weekend feel, pair them with a comfy sweater. Choose a cropped or
hip- or mid-thigh-length sweater from crunchy tweeds to bold
patterns. Our choice is a green-gray wool folkloric pullover
($29.99) worn over a white turtleneck ($14.99). For added warmth,
toss a muffler around your neck ($19.99), then slip into black
ankle boots ($39.99). The boots would also work well with skirts.
All at T.J. Maxx stores.
</P>
<P>
   For cool days
</P>
<P>
   Nothing adds more spice to gray than red. Light-as-air,
single-breasted wool coat ($238) gives a sassy charge to charcoal
gray trousers ($68, Casual Corner). Other go-alongs include: Light
gray wool/cashmere turtleneck ($88) and Nine West's microfiber
black backpack ($69). Top off the outfit with Liz Claiborne's faux
fur black hat ($36) and stay sure-footed in CK's lug sole boots
($110). Faux fur-trimmed gray gloves are $12.
</P>
<P>
   All from Parisian stores.
</P>
<P>
   Dress-up evenings
</P>
<P>
   Gray goes elegant and sophisticated for evenings, when the
trousers are a medium gray wool by ICB ($190). Top the pants with
Helen Wang's lacy-looking gray crochet tank ($110) and matching
cardigan ($140). These tops, also accented with beads, could easily
be paired with velvet or crepe trousers. Elegant accessory touches
include DKNY's pewter high-heeled slides ($178) and a deep gray
velvet bag with jewel handle ($120). Clothes and accessories from
Saks Fifth Avenue. Polish information: 1-877-263-6245.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
