<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2675 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-HIGH-CULTURE-2     09-30 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-HIGH-CULTURE-2NDTAKE-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BURBANK, Calif.: shriveled entertainment.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Disney is so good at being good that it manifests an evil; so
uniformly efficient and courteous, so dependably clean and
conscientious, so unfailingly (italics)entertaining(end italics)
that it's unreal, and therefore is an agent of pure wickedness,''
writes Carl Hiassen in his slender tirade ``Team Rodent: How
Disneyland Devours the World (Ballantine, 1988).
</P>
<P>
   Eisner scoffs at the notion that anything he's doing now is a
radical departure from what Disney has always done. ``I don't see
high art or low art,'' he said. ``If you're an ice skating clown at
an ice show, you're probably the best skater in the arena. To be
broadly commercial, you have to be broadly talented, so nothing we
do now is inconsistent with what Walt did with his early pioneering
work in animation, or with `Fantasia' or with working with
Westinghouse to adapt the technology of his day to his theme
parks.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever distinctions one wants to draw, Eisner has the
capacity to commission culture, to summon up whole worlds of
buildings and art forms and narratives.
</P>
<P>
   The two symphonies, for instance, came about, as Eisner tells
it, when he attended Mahler's Symphony of a Thousand at Carnegie
Hall. Thumbing through the program, he discovered that the symphony
had been commissioned in the 1890s to celebrate the new century. He
decided that Disney ought to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner took his idea to Jean-Luc Choplin, who was hired in 1989
to put on the entertainment at what was then called EuroDisney and
is now known as Disneyland Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Choplin, whose background included stints as artistic director
of La Sainte Baume, an avant-garde music and dance festival in a
former Dominican monastery in Provence, administrator for Roland
Petit's Ballet National de Marseille and managing director of the
Paris Opera Ballet with Rudolf Nureyev, began by listening to 129
modern composers.
</P>
<P>
   He then narrowed the list to four, ranked in order. Eisner
listened to tapes of the four and agreed with Choplin's ranking;
the project went from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of Disney, what you think of is Snow White,
Mickey Mouse and cartoon characters,'' said Torke. ``But I think
the fact that Jean-Luc Choplin came from the Paris Opera Ballet,
had worked with Nureyev, with John Cage and Robert Wilson and many
others, signaled to me that Disney had gotten an ambassador aboard
and that they were very serious about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Choplin said he saw Disney's mission and his own instincts as
entirely compatible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Beethoven, music has been sacred,'' said Choplin, who
has the compact gnomic look of an animated Disney character come to
life. ``But before that, great music was popular entertainment.
Botticelli was designing parades and pageants. Great painters
worked for Queen Elizabeth I to provide pageantry. Or if you go
back to Charles Ives, to Leonard Bernstein, the way Mahler and
Dvorak were inspired by waltzes and popular music, Sibelius, they
were all inspired by popular traditions, by roots. I think we have
explored a lot of one-way streets at the end of the 20th century,
and I think art needs to go back to more popular roots. And roots
are not in the ether; they're in popular culture.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two things may be making good art better commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The first, certainly in architecture, is the rise of
post-modernism. No matter what his tastes, Eisner could never have
made the mute forms of the International School compatible vehicles
for expressing Disney's vision. With the best architects now
working in wildly diverse forms animated by narrative and playful
design, the tides of design and the mission of Disney blend
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   The second is the global growth of a more discerning cultural
marketplace. And just as there's a market for junk, there's now
like never before a mass audience for sophisticated culture, a
lesson brought home on Broadway by Julie Taymor.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Eisner's friendship and alliance with Tina Brown speaks
as much to his business sense as his cultural one. After all, the
thing to remember about Eisner's vision for Disney is not so much
that it's going high end as that it has become omnivorous.
</P>
<P>
   That vision is not a radical departure from Walt Disney's. After
all, his landmark ``Fantasia,'' which brought together the animated
Disney menagerie and Leopold Stokowski, was his conspicuous bid for
high culture approval in a pop culture context. But he consorted
with other well-known artists, Salvador Dali, for example, and very
much saw his work as groundbreaking art that was both serious and
popular.
</P>
<P>
   And while his theme parks will always be seen by many critics as
empires of kitsch, a respected minority viewpoint heralded them as
brilliant evocations of human-scale architecture that in many ways
prefigured a new respect for urbanism amid the relentless rise of
suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   The late architect Charles Moore called Disneyland the ``most
important single piece of construction in the West in the past
several decades.'' The developer James Rouse told an audience at
Harvard in 1963 that ``the greatest piece of urban design in the
United States today is Disneyland.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Disney, nephew of the company founder, said Eisner had Walt
Disney's broad vision but with a very different cultural
sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walt was a guy who was born at the turn of the century in the
middle of America,'' said Disney, the chairman of Walt Disney
Feature Animation and the man who more than anyone brought Eisner
to the company. ``Michael grew up well-to-do in New York, exposed
to very different things. They have many things in common, but in
those ways they are absolutely diametrical opposites.''
</P>
<P>
   As his new autobiography, ``Work in Progress,'' makes clear (the
book was written with Tony Schwartz), Eisner has at least in part
the instincts of a closet highbrow, as quintessentially a product
of the Upper East Side as Disney was of Marceline and Kansas City,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a lawyer, Eisner grew up on Park Avenue in a home
where he was expected to wear a sports jacket to dinner as the
family dined by candlelight. Weekends were spent in Westchester
County at the Bedford Hills estate of his maternal grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Birthdays and anniversaries were celebrated with trips to
Broadway musicals _ ``Kiss Me Kate,'' ``Guys and Dolls,'' ``South
Pacific,'' ``Oklahoma!'' A family friend, Victor Ganz, served as an
informal tutor on art and architecture and once lent the Eisners
Picasso's ``Bullfight,'' which hung for 10 years in young Michael's
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
