<HEADER>
A2676 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-ERINGEL01-COX     09-30 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ERINGEL01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Hollywood's fantasy takes on sweet hereafter
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, sweet mystery of afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   The movies have long loved to tell us what it would be like once
we departed this mortal coil. Heavenly harps, winged angels, puffy
clouds and twinkling stars have generally been the most popular
motifs.
</P>
<P>
   Reincarnation has been a staple, too _ from Spencer Tracy in ``A
Guy Named Joe'' to Richard Dreyfuss in ``Always,'' the remake of
``A Guy Named Joe.'' From Patrick Swayze in ``Ghost'' to Bill Cosby
in ``Ghost Dad.'' But then, the movies do make you immortal, don't
they?
</P>
<P>
   And for some reason _ wishful thinking, perhaps? _ heaven has
always been more popular than hell. Hell, after all, to paraphrase
Sartre, is for other people, not movie stars.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend brings Robin Williams in ``What Dreams May Come.''
Set in heaven, hell and points in between, it's an imaginative and
highly effective mix of tear-jerker and phantasmagoria _ as if
Terry Gilliam had remade ``Ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other cinematic visions of life after death.
Decide for yourself which one suits you best.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Defending Your Life'' (1991) With Albert Brooks and Meryl
Streep. Directed by Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   What It Looks Like: Judgment City, a kind of cosmic way station,
is a mix of a perimeter office park and Disney World _ sort of
every suburban Sunbelt sprawl that ever was, complete with nail
parlors and comedy clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Good News: Brooks discovers he can eat all the pasta and ice
cream he wants without ever gaining weight. He also discovers a
radiant, recently deceased Streep.
</P>
<P>
   The Bad News: As the title suggests, you must go to court and
defend outtakes of your past life so it can be decided whether you
will pass to a higher level or go back to Earth for another try.
Rip Torn plays Brooks' defense attorney.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Made in Heaven'' (1987) With Timothy Hutton and Kelly
McGillis. Directed by Alan Rudolph.
</P>
<P>
   What It Looks Like: Lots of gardens and ponds and bucolic
countryside and cobblestone streets. Actually, it looks a lot like
Charleston, which is where it was shot. Also, you can design your
own heaven. For instance, Maureen Stapleton, who plays Hutton's
aunt, changes her view every day _ the Eiffel Tower one day, St.
Peter's the next.
</P>
<P>
   The Good News: Hutton, who died a hero's death on Earth, meets
McGillis, an unborn soul. They fall in love. And yes, there's sex
in this heaven. Cigarettes, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Bad News: When McGillis gets sent to Earth, Hutton asks to
go back as well. They've got 30 years to find each other or else
live unhappily ever after. By the way, Atlanta plays Earth.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Heart and Souls'' (1993) With Robert Downey Jr., Charles
Grodin, Kyra Sedgwick, Alfre Woodard and Tom Sizemore. Directed by
Ron Underwood.
</P>
<P>
   What It Looks Like: As one character says, ``like the back seat
of a '58 Rambler.'' When a city bus dives off a bridge in 1959,
four disparate souls attach themselves to a nearby newborn, thus,
in the tradition of reincarnation flicks, creating their heaven
right here on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Good News: Through their mortal host, each soul gets to
resolve his or her cut-short life. Example: Grodin gets a chance at
the opera audition he always chickened out of and single-mom
Woodard gets to check on how her boy turned out.
</P>
<P>
   The Bad News: Their mortal host is Downey. Great actor, iffy
health factor.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Heaven'' (1987) With ... anyone from Diane Keaton's
94-year-old grandmother, Grammy Hall, to boxing promoter Don King.
Directed by Keaton.
</P>
<P>
   What It Looks Like: You name it. For her offbeat documentary,
Keaton asked dozens of people what they thought about heaven. The
answers are both sacred and inane.
</P>
<P>
   The Good News: The interviews are interspersed with a
fascinating array of depictions of heaven gathered from features,
television shows and religious programs. The clips range from the
celebrated _ the moving stairway in Michael Powell's ``Stairway to
Heaven'' (also called ``A Matter of Life and Death'') to the arcane
_ a heavenly orchestra from ``The Horn Blows at Midnight,'' a 1945
fantasy starring Jack Benny.
</P>
<P>
   The Bad News: Interspersed with those clips are those
interviews. You might find King's view of heaven interesting, but
do you really care what Peter Sellers' youngest daughter thinks?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
