<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS01-COX     09-30 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Video Reviews: The latest word on the latest sights
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``The Object of My Affection'' (R) _ Based on Stephen
McCauley's novel, this comedy-drama is fashioned as sort of a
modern-day Shakespearean romp of romantic mismatches. Nina
(Jennifer Aniston) gets pregnant by her bossy lover (John Pankow).
She begins to think her new roommate George (Paul Rudd) would make
a better father _ he's polite, single, smart and a babe. He's also
gay. Shimmering with charm and sharp performances, the movie can't
quite overcome a central problem. George and Nina are such bland,
nice nudniks, it's hard to invest in their story. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Spanish Prisoner'' (PG) _ If only writer-director David
Mamet had let someone else direct his mind-game thriller, it might
have the Hitchcockian momentum it badly needs. Even so, the
looks-are-deceiving tale of an inventor (Campbell Scott) drawn into
the world of a wealthy businessman (a terrific Steve Martin) has
sinister elegance. Grade: B +
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Paulie'' (PG) _ A solid, sweet kid flick. Paulie is a
wisecracking parrot (voice by Jay Mohr of ``Picture Perfect'')
separated from his owner, 5-year-old Marie. The bulk of the movie
is Paulie's picaresque adventures as he goes from one owner to
another, trying to find his way back. ``Paulie'' doesn't have the
magic or emotional depth of ``Babe,'' but it's well-crafted and
provides an ending with a lovely twist that can appeal to kids and
adults. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Mrs. Dalloway'' (PG-13) _ OK, so maybe it's impossible to
translate Virginia Woolf's internal monologues into movies. But
director Marleen Gorris (``Antonia's Line'') makes a valiant
effort, following the middle-aged, middle-class Mrs. Dalloway
(Vanessa Redgrave) through a day of bittersweet reflection of the
choices she's made. Natascha McElhone plays Redgrave at a young
age. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Two Girls and a Guy'' (R) _ If you want to see the
narcissistic extent some actors can go to, this is for you. Robert
Downey Jr. blusters through this painfully uninsightful James
Toback film, wherein the actor is confronted by two women (Heather
Graham and Natasha Gregson Wagner) who've just realized they're
sharing the same man. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Chinese Box'' (R) _ A fine cast and a fascinating backdrop,
but not much of a story. In Hong Kong on the eve of the Chinese
takeover, a British journalist (Jeremy Irons) is sick with leukemia
and love-sick for beautiful bar hostess, Gong Li. Grade: C +
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Fallen Angels'' (R) _ Wong Kar-Wai doesn't make movies. He
has visions and throws them onto the screen in anti-narrative fits
and starts. Sometimes you're in the mood for this sort of thing;
sometimes you're not. Full of the director's trademark jump cuts
and neon-headache colors, ``Angels'' (an unofficial sequel to his
``Chungking Express'') is like watching an incoherent student film.
Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
