<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITH FORD SHOWS _ SURPRISE _ DEPTH IN `MAGGIE WINTERS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know if it's a compliment to say that ``Maggie Winters''
isn't the train wreck first envisioned sight unseen. Part of the
trepidation centered on its lead, Faith Ford, who had spent 10
years on ``Murphy Brown'' as Corky, a sometimes-scene stealer whose
one-screw-loose approach to laughs was the object of affection.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapping a sitcom around Corky wasn't appealing, and still
isn't. So ``Maggie Winters'' is clever (not the show, the approach)
in that it gives us bits of Corky and lots of Ford, creating a
character who might actually grow on you.
</P>
<P>
   Ford plays Maggie, newly divorced, unemployed and broke. She
returns to the Indiana hometown she dissed as a dusty little place
that wouldn't let her think.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still stuck in high school, and they want to suck me
back,'` she says of her friends who never left Shelbyville. She
tells her pessimistic mother (Shirley Knight) that she'll be around
for ``six months, tops,'' but we know the sitcom drill.
</P>
<P>
   The premiere episode focuses on her fall from grace and how she
comes to face her friends, her tail wedged firmly between her legs.
Most of the key characters are female, and they're an impressive
lot. Jenny Robertson is amusing as one of her running buddies, and
Clea Lewis is simply wonderful as the geek Maggie doesn't remember.
Never mind. She still hates Maggie for getting all the boys and the
other trappings afforded the girl most likely to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has a hilarious job interview scene with Maggie (she'll be
her boss at a retail store) in which she berates her old nemesis
about ``stealing'' the boy whom she ``like-liked'' in high school.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, ``Maggie Winters'' zips along quite nicely, and a
smarter Ford is certainly a more interesting one.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, CBS could use this softer, sweeter series to offset the
lineup of new shows heavy on testosterone, like ``Buddy Faro'' and
the cartoonish drama with the fat guy chopping and kicking people.
</P>
<P>
   Also premiering this week:
</P>
<P>
   He sees the scumbags, she sees the broken hearts. He's a cop.
She's a public defender. ``To Have &AMP; to Hold'' (CBS) is a romantic
comedic drama that's missing one of its key elements. After two
episodes, it's clear that this is simply a well-intentioned, boring
show that lacks dramatic storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing really happens, except when Annie (the terrific Moira
Kelly) and Sean (Jason Beghe) fog up the windows, which is often,
since they're newlyweds and, as they continue to remind us,
opposites attract.
</P>
<P>
   I can't see ``To Have &AMP; to Hold'' generating much interest, and
CBS might feel the same. To arouse our interest, it sent an episode
scheduled for airing next month. It shows Annie and Sean playing
that newlywed game of consummating their marriage in every part of
the house, including the driveway during a Halloween party.
</P>
<P>
   Sex as drama. Hey, it works on ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Lives of Men (ABC) is a misfire. It's a
character-based comedy with no interesting characters and no
comedy. Peter Gallagher, Bradley Whitford and Mitch Rouse sit
around whining about the state of their lives. All three are
annoying. Skip it and feel better in the morning.  &QL;  .MDRV/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com Ken Parish Perkins can be e-mailed at
kpp &LR; star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
