<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDA-PREPARATIONS-COX     09-30 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDA-PREPARATIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elaborating on 'Aida'
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_Standing on the Alliance Theatre stage as the Elton John
music began during a recent performance of ``Elaborate Lives: The
Legend of Aida,'' actor Hank Stratton suddenly stared at one of his
fellow actors with a worried look. He slowly mouthed three words.
</P>
<P>
   Director Robert Jess Roth, watching from the audience, easily
read Stratton's lips. The three words were ``Oh my God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the translation was: Hank was lost, he had no idea where
he was in the 36 bars of new dance music we had just shoved into
the show that afternoon,'' says Roth, who has worked round the
clock for nine weeks to shape the Disney-Alliance premiere into a
Broadway hit rivaling his 1994 ``Beauty and the Beast.''
Choreographer Matt West turned to Roth and grimly cracked, ``I
think we're in for a rough ride.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stratton _ who plays Radames, the Egyptian soldier
dangerously in love with slave girl Aida, a former princess
captured from his Nubian enemies _ ``managed to stumble through the
number all right,'' Roth adds, ``considering he'd had no time to
digest the new material.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the wild world of theater previews. It's a crucial
time of discovery for the ``Aida'' artists, a necessary phase of
controlled chaos before critics and VIPs arrive for opening night
Wednesday. This is when shows are tweaked, when laughs fail to
appear where scripted or pop up where none was expected. When new
ideas are tested and artists' nerves are tested sorely. This is the
pressure cooker that can yield last-minute triumphs such as the
song ``Comedy Tonight,'' which Stephen Sondheim wrote so quickly in
1962 that he transformed ``A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the
Forum'' from an out-of-town flop into a Broadway hit.
</P>
<P>
   This is also when bugs are worked out of new hardware _ such as
the ``Elaborate'' pyramid, the ultimate balky gizmo. During one
preview, the shape-changing set piece stalled and spewed hydraulic
fluid onto the stage. During another, it produced a distinctly
unmusical hum. But technical glitches by no means predict a bomb:
Witness the ``Titanic'' ship that refused to sink during a preview
but sailed on to win the 1997 Tony for best musical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pyramid involves brand-new technology and we never
expected it to pop out of the box and work perfectly the first
time,'' says Roth, 35. ``I was heartened to read that Michael
Bennett had to cancel some `Dreamgirls' previews (in 1982) because
the famous light towers wouldn't turn. And that show didn't do too
badly.''
</P>
<P>
   As a new stage work without any animated movie to draw from,
``Lives'' requires even more honing than most musicals. Especially
since the Broadway-bound work has a very difficult Disney act to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate to be any show trying to follow `The Lion King'
into New York _ the pressure must be unbelievable,'' says Jeremy
Gerard, an editor at New York magazine and former chief drama
critic for Variety.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Roth, while visibly stressed, also appears to be having
the time of his life. ``What makes it fun is that we're on track _
we're liking what we see,'' says Roth, including, in his reference
to ``we,'' Disney chairman Michael Eisner, who's attended four
previews.
</P>
<P>
   And what did The Boss have to say?
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael cuts through the pleasantries, since we've worked
together a long time,'' says the boyish New York-based veteran of
Disney theme-park shows, ``and he'll often say, `What I don't get,
Rob. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of script doctors, an astute one, Roth says, has been
Atlanta's own Elton John. After seeing a preview, the composer
suggested that the song ``A Step Too Far'' be moved up to the
opening of Act 2, ``Since it's the only song,'' Roth says, ``that
really focuses in on the triangle relationship'' between Radames,
Aida and her romantic rival, Amneris.
</P>
<P>
   The most heavily taxed artist, since previews began Sept. 17,
may be Linda Woolverton, the scriptwriter and Roth's old ``Beauty''
sidekick, who not only attends afternoon rehearsals and evening
previews, but rushes back to her Atlanta hotel during open slots to
type up script changes.
</P>
<P>
   Previews are the time of the unpredictable. Roth got a call on
recent morning from lyricist Tim Rice, the most seasoned member of
the creative team; he wrote 1971's ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' with
Andrew Lloyd Webber. Rice told the director that after seeing a
preview and thinking about it overnight, he'd decided to rewrite
the lyrics to ``Enchantment Passing Through,'' a song he and John
wrote months ago but had never seen onstage. When Heather Headley,
who plays Aida, arrived at rehearsal that day she learned that
she'd be singing new lyrics that evening, and was able to do so
thanks to cue cards taped to the inside wall of the orchestra pit.
</P>
<P>
   Roth sits in the audience every night because, ``I can feel when
people are involved. On Saturday, when Michael Eisner was in the
audience again, there were three women crying so loudly during the
song `Elaborate Lives' that a woman behind them asked them to keep
it down. I was thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   The director finds only one physical defect in the Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no place,'' he exclaims, ``to pace!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
