<HEADER>
A2681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MARSHALL-COX     09-30 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MARSHALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biography eyes revered jurist who helped bring down legal
segregation in America
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Cynthia Tucker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thurgood Marshall, the first African-American to serve on the
U.S. Supreme Court, had a reputation late in life for being gruff
and reclusive. So it is a revelation to learn that for most of his
life he was just the opposite: a gregarious, carousing,
hard-drinking storyteller with a lust for the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Never modest about his role in history, Marshall believed his
contributions to dismantling Jim Crow entitled him to a seat on the
nation's highest court. He used his friendship with President
Lyndon B. Johnson to press his case and called on associates to
lobby the president as well.
</P>
<P>
   Biographer Juan Williams, a Washington Post reporter who wrote
``Eyes on the Prize: America's Civil Rights Years, 1954-1965,''
began frequent interviews with Marshall in 1989, two years before
he retired from the bench. Those interviews, though not especially
revealing, are an important part of the historical record of the
life of the man who, more than any other single figure, destroyed
the legal foundations of segregation in America.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's most famous victory remains the toppling of the
``separate but equal'' doctrine that legitimized segregated schools
_ the 1954 decision in Brown v. Board of Education _ but that case
was just the climax of a decades-long legal strategy waged by the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   Because Marshall worked for the NAACP or its offshoot, the NAACP
Legal Defense Fund, throughout his civil rights career, the book is
also a thumbnail history of the NAACP's courtroom campaign against
segregation, a strategy begun decades before the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr. introduced his philosophy of nonviolent protest.
</P>
<P>
   Williams recounts many stories of Marshall's life as a poorly
paid NAACP lawyer, when he was frequently in the Deep South
defending blacks charged with serious crimes, gathering data on the
inferiority of segregated black schools or giving speeches to raise
funds. Marshall worked with similarly talented and dedicated
attorneys who were always on the lookout for cases that would allow
them to chip away at the legal supports of segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, their grand plans were outdone by comic mishaps, as
when a whining, self-aggrandizing plaintiff _ a black man who had
volunteered to sue the University of Missouri for admission to its
law school _ disappeared before his case worked its way through the
legal system. Without a plaintiff, the Missouri case was lost.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Marshall and his associates simply lost to the
oppressive forces of segregation. In one criminal case in Oklahoma,
a black man was convicted of multiple murder even though two white
felons admitted to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   But it is for their triumphs that Marshall and his colleagues
are remembered, and rightly so, since those cases changed the
country. Slowly but surely, they chalked up victories against
unequal pay for black teachers, the poll tax, the tradition of
banning blacks from juries and, finally, segregated schools.
</P>
<P>
   Though this overly admiring biography does not paint as full a
portrait of Marshall as his place in American history deserves
(Marshall's widow, Cissy, refused to cooperate, as did their
children), it does provide glimpses of the childhood forces that
helped shape his beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Baltimore in 1908 to parents who were ambitious
for their children and their race; they were early activists in the
struggle for racial equality. A childhood spent in integrated
neighborhoods may have shaped Marshall's lifelong belief in
integration as the key to solving the nation's racial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall believed deeply in American jurisprudence, so much so
that he could admire great white lawyers even if they were rigid
segregationists.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, this biography tells too little about Marshall's
complexities, perhaps because Williams was reluctant to delve too
deeply into his subject's considerable flaws. A legendary womanizer
and partygoer, Marshall thought nothing of buying bootleg whiskey
during his trips through the Deep South. That's astonishingly
reckless behavior from a man who knew that Old South authorities
would have used any excuse to discredit him. Yet Williams does not
remark on that recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Williams draw the obvious conclusions from the
evidence: Marshall was probably an alcoholic. The great jurist
died, apparently, as his father had, isolated from longtime friends
by an irascibility and paranoia fueled by drink.
</P>
<P>
   An equally glaring omission lies in Williams' failure to
seriously analyze the criticism that dogged Marshall throughout his
tenure on the high court: a lack of intellectual rigor. Though
Marshall is remembered for championing civil rights and expanding
constitutional protections for criminal defendants and reproductive
rights for women, he was portrayed in Bob Woodward's landmark book
on the Supreme Court, ``The Brethren'' (1979), as lazy and
inattentive. Williams gives that subject short shrift.
</P>
<P>
   His failure to examine the whole man notwithstanding, Williams
has written a highly readable book that establishes Marshall's
place as an architect of America's 20th-century social
transformation.Thurgood Marshall: American Revolutionary. By Juan
Williams. Times Books. $27.50. 459 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A welcome addition to the history of the civil
rights movement and American jurisprudence.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Tucker is editor of The Atlanta Constitution's editorial
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
