<HEADER>
A2682 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-FANS-ONLINE-1STLD     09-30 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FANS-ONLINE-1STLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, FIXING STATE IN LEAD) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Mo., N.Y., Ind.)  
 STARS FANS SITE PAGES  
 (af)  
 By CHARLES BERMANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this summer Carolyn Hack got the thrill of her life.
Carolyn, 15, a high-school student from Overland Park, Kan., was in
line to ride the roller coaster at an amusement park in Kansas
City, Mo., when she and her friends saw the actor Leonardo DiCaprio
emerge from one of the cars.
</P>
<P>
   After the requisite hysteria, Carolyn's response fit a modern
teen-age template: she rode in the same car the actor had sat in;
then she went home and wrote a detailed account of the experience
for her Web site.
</P>
<P>
   If every home will eventually have a home page, it seems that
every fan will have the power to put up a fan site. And while it is
common for celebrities to mount ``official'' sites, it is the
renegade pages that generate lively, unadulterated discussions
about the objects of their affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best fan sites allow people to share something they
experience and enjoy,'' said Brian Bikowicz, whose on-line name is
Megazone and who operates a page about the pop singer Ani DiFranco.
``They let people who enjoy the same thing establish a collective
memory of fandom.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides her own Web site, Carolyn manages an on-line service
called DiCapring (www.sky.net/hack/dicapring.htm), which links
almost 660 DiCaprio-centric sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Web ring creates an on-line community of fan-oriented sites,
pages that have little in common except that they satisfy the
insatiable need to know everything about the celebrity or artist in
question. Visitors to the sites can post rumors, exchange pictures,
argue the quality of DiCaprio's work and generally wallow in the
minutiae of the star's life.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who create fan sites learn in the process how to use
the Internet more fluently and master the technical tools needed to
create a Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Take Darrell Gaskins, 22, an Atlanta computer consultant who
also designs home pages. He had the foresight to register
www.dicaprio.com several years ago, and the site now gets heavy
traffic from fans. But he also uses the site to demonstrate sound
effects and animation tricks as a way to sell his talents to
prospective clients.
</P>
<P>
   It is fitting that DiCaprio, one of the best-known movie stars
on the planet right now, has a strong on-line presence. A search on
his name yields thousands of results. Ms. DiFranco is not nearly as
well known; a similar search turns up a mere 3,500 entries, fewer
than half the number of DiCaprio sites.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. DiFranco's fans are as fervent, and the pages are as
wide ranging. As a favorite among college students, she is partly
responsible for the introduction of a whole generation to the world
of Web design.
</P>
<P>
   Before Ms. DiFranco's recent rise in popularity, it was nearly
impossible to find anything about her in the mainstream media. So
fan pages became the only route devotees could take to learn more
about her _ an artist who is so much of a renegade she distributes
her music on her own label, refusing offers from major record
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Parker, a Columbia University junior, chose Ms. DiFranco
as a subject for a Web-design class assignment because, she said,
``she is a great role model and empowering to women.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parker has let her page (www.columbia.edu/mrp29/music.html)
live on long past the class and still maintains it on the
university's server.
</P>
<P>
   For some builders of fan sites, satire has become the sincerest
form of flattery. Tim Richardson, an independent filmmaker in
Indiana, created a Leotardo DiCappucino page, a sendup of a fawning
fan site, full of the requisite inside references intrinsic to many
Web sites (members.tripod.com/shinoh14/leotardo.html).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hobby,'' Richardson said. ``It's like collecting stamps
or baseball cards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
