<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE04-COX     09-30 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The squeaky hinge: Science-religion war has a long history
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1641, blind and in failing health, Galileo found pleasure in
explaining to his son plans for making a pendulum clock. He had
lost his sight three years earlier, and the Fathers of the Church
concluded that he had lost his faith even earlier. Proving what
Copernicus could present only as theory, he held that the Earth was
indeed not the center of God's universe, motionless as a
chandelier; to the contrary, his telescope told him that the Earth
rotated on its axis every 24 hours and, what's more, revolved
around the sun. And he produced the mathematical calculations to
prove it. There being no corroboration in the Bible, the Roman
Church pronounced his ideas heretical and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Galileo's recantation _ a winking white lie meant
only to placate the authorities _ is well-known and largely
mythologized. The truth is that Galileo died a broken man, a
believer and yet imprisoned during the Inquisition. His books were
censored and burned. ``This universe that I have extended a
thousand times,'' he said, ``has now shrunk to the narrow confines
of my own body. Thus God likes it; so I too must like it.'' But
truth, or the search for it, is not easily imprisoned. A more
secular example of it is the shrunken figure of Stephen Hawking,
confined within a paralyzed body, bereft of all power but that of
his mind, calculating the very beginnings of Time.
</P>
<P>
   Religion's encounter with Reason nearly four centuries ago
closed the door to one world and opened the door to another. The
world in which we live is the one created by science. Religion _ in
the West at least _ has been left to make what accommodations it
can. It was anything but an orderly transfer of power and
authority. Richard N. Goodwin's ``The Hinge of the World'' (Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25) dramatizes, in the form of a play, all that
was at stake. In a subtitle evoking the times, Goodwin calls his
book ``A Drama in Which Professor Galileo Galilei, Chief
Mathematician and Philosopher to His Serene Highness the Grand Duke
of Tuscany, and His Holiness Urban VIII, Bishop of Rome, Battle for
the Soul of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   It was nothing less than that, even if you acknowledge those
quarters of the globe where religion still rules. You could say
that the world stood still while Galileo was proving, against all
scriptural authority, that it in fact moved.
</P>
<P>
   Sparring over the uses of knowledge
</P>
<P>
   In Act 3 of this immensely rich work, the accused Galileo
appeals to his onetime friend Urban VIII:
</P>
<P>
   ``The laws of motion, the language of nature, are all of His
creation. There is no other possibility. Condemn me and little is
lost. Condemn the truth and you dim the glory of our Church, forbid
the knowledge for which God has granted us to rebuild the ruins of
our abolished world.''
</P>
<P>
   Replying, the Pope says in part: ``We are not threatened by
denial. It is worse. You would make God unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   And, moments later: ``You would subdue nature. Our duty is far
more difficult: to subdue man. You would understand nature. I must
understand man, a creature of terrifying disproportions, a Divine
spirit caged with a ravenous beast.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin has given us a meditation not just on the history of
ideas, but on the nature of man. At the dawn of the modern era, the
Renaissance and the Reformation elevated art and learning while
asserting the freedom of the individual over his own conscience.
The institutional scaffolding of the age coming to a close fell
away, the unchallenged authority of the pope along with the divine
right of kings.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding a world in transition
</P>
<P>
   It is poetic coincidence that Galileo was born on the day
Michelangelo died, and that the day of Galileo's death saw the
birth of Isaac Newton. But it is coincidence and nothing more. The
transition from one age to the next is never a clean break. The
first scientists, Galileo among them, were heirs to the Renaissance
and had greater appreciation for mystery and wonder than the
absolutists who feared them and wanted them silenced.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not a heretic, Galileo, one who misreads the faith,''
Urban VIII tells him. ``You are the creator of a whole new faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony of this is that Galileo sought to create no new faith,
but only to make more comprehensible the faith he already had.
</P>
<P>
   More ironic still, science has become its own religion, as smug
in its authority as the pontiffs who tried and failed to subdue it.
It takes a discerning reader to infer from Goodwin's book that the
two, religion and science, are not mutually incompatible. But any
concord between them requires agreement that most truths are
provisional. And with this, perhaps, the acknowledgment that the
mysteries of God's world exist to be understood, not merely
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   This was, after all, Galileo's position, for which he paid
dearly. He did not deny the existence of God. He only believed
there to be mysteries beyond the reach of Rome and reason alike.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
