</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLARDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scents and sensibility: In collard-crazy Carolina, they love
their boiled leaves
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEULAVILLE, N.C._The coastal plain of North Carolina _ Down
East, as Tar Heels call it _ provides an olfactory tour to delight
and defile the nostrils. Driving through the flat countryside east
of Raleigh, you encounter the reek of hog farms, the bouquet of
barbecue joints, the foul belch of paper mills, the sweet pungence
of curing tobacco, the seductive promise of salt water. And if you
happen to stray into Beulaville, a flyspeck on the way to
Wilmington, you encounter a particular aroma that, depending on
your rearing, can seem as agreeable as hickory smoke or as
malodorous as a pigpen. Every Wednesday is Collards Day at
Beulaville's Wagon Wheel restaurant, and people come from miles
around as if lured by the siren stench of boiling greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of folks who aren't from around here can't stand the
smell, but we love it,'' says Mayo Quinn, a local retiree and
Collards Day regular, as she sprinkles her lunch with peppered
vinegar sauce. The green pile on her plate looks like a clump of
damp lawn clippings.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least they don't smell like chitlins,'' a fellow at the
next table chimes in.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never cooked collards and inhaled their potent vapors,
think of that famous scene in Charlie Chaplin's film ``The Gold
Rush.'' The Tramp, on the verge of starvation in the Yukon, boils a
pair of boots and serves the soles like veal cutlets, with laces
for spaghetti. Had he thrown in some fetid running shoes and sweaty
socks, and simmered them all day with no exhaust fan, only then
would the smell have approached the dank, earthy funk of collards
brewing in an open pot. That they taste so much better than they
smell is one of life's happy little mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Boiled greens have to be one of the most characteristic and
stereotypical of Southern foods. Like many of the region's culinary
specialties, they have been much abused _ derided as po-folks'
fare, larded with too much pork, often overcooked to the point of
mush. Yet they endure. While we're more likely to eat raw greens
these days, like the rest of the nation, you'll still find a vat of
steaming greens at just about every buffet and cafeteria line from
Texas to Virginia. Different areas have different preferences:
collards in the Deep South, turnips in the Upper South, mustards
here, kale there, with a little dandelion and pokeweed thrown in.
It's a mighty mess of greens, by any reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the places where greens are prized, perhaps none
celebrates them as fervently as eastern North Carolina. The sandy
loam is perfect for growing large, leafy things like tobacco and
collards, a member of the kale family whose name is thought to be a
corruption of ``colewort,'' a type of cabbage. Though it isn't a
huge commercial crop, everyone seems to grow some collards in the
garden.
</P>
<P>
   In Ayden, the small town that recently staged its 24th annual
collard festival, they even have a garden of verse. The planners
sponsored a collards poetry contest a few years back, and they're
still getting entries. One ode addressed the plant as a woman:
``Colleen, Colleen, my sweet collard green.'' Another mimicked
Shakespeare: ``Shall I compare thee to the turnip green?'' (Given
the gastrointestinal consequences that collards can have, it's a
wonder someone hasn't written: ``Greens, greens, good for the
heart. ...'')
</P>
<P>
   For one weekend in September, Ayden truly is the collards
capital of the world. But for the rest of the year, you'd be
hard-pressed to find a more collardcentric place than Beulaville,
population 1,000, where the Wagon Wheel has been serving its weekly
feast of greens and pork backbone since 1968. Thanks to a couple of
features in Carolina newspapers, Collards Day has become something
of a regional phenomenon, drawing more than 600 customers from as
far away as Charlotte and Winston-Salem. Sometimes whole busloads
of greens lovers pull off N.C. 111 at the yellow frame restaurant
with the emerald awnings. For collards eaters who can't linger, the
management thoughtfully added a drive-through window.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Wednesday, as the line began to trail out the door,
a car turned in, a window lowered and a voice rang out, ``Y'all
don't eat all the collards, now!''
</P>
<P>
   There was little danger of that happening. The Wagon Wheel cooks
500 pounds of collards at a time, a laborious process that takes
all night. Once the kitchen closes after dinner, a graveyard shift
starts trimming greens of their stems and center veins. Next
they're washed repeatedly to remove the grit. Then they're seasoned
and boiled for hours in a broth rendered from the pork backbones.
Finally, they're chopped and mixed with a little cabbage if they
need sweetening. Summer collards, which tend to be tougher and more
bitter, usually need the help. The tender, milder-tasting collards
that grow after the first frost stand on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer the summer collards myself,'' says Zannie Atkinson,
one of the restaurant's founders, who grew up on a farm nearby and
is accustomed to eating assertive greens. Though she sold the
business to her son-in-law years ago, she still comes in once a
week, at age 74, to work until dawn cooking the collards. By the
time the greens are laid out on a buffet table, alongside fried
chicken and candied yams and hush puppies, she's back home catching
up on sleep _ and probably smelling collards in her dreams.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:30, the doors open and Atkinson's 49-year-old son-in-law,
Bo Carpenter, greets the procession: silver-haired ladies,
tractor-capped truck drivers, uniformed deliverymen, wizened old
farmers with sun-creased necks, collard-swallerin' lawyers in
khakis and button-down dress shirts, a dental office staff in
matching smocks with smiling teeth on them. Young and old, big and
small, all coming for greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here because we love old-timey collards, and because we
hate the idea of cooking them,'' says Mary Edwards, a regular from
Beulaville, as she builds a green hillock on her plate.
</P>
<P>
   Behind her in line, one of the lawyers pulls the visitor aside
with a tip: ``Be sure you get Bo to show you his van.''
</P>
<P>
   His van? Carpenter rolls his eyes and motions to follow him out
back, through the collardy kitchen, to the gravel lot. There, on
the back of his shiny black Pontiac Trans Sport SE, a North
</P>
<P>
   Carolina vanity license plate hollers:
</P>
<P>
   ``COLLARDS.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way people around here love greens,'' Carpenter says, ``I
was surprised no one else had applied for that tag.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
