 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Pot liquor'? Don't give the guv any of that
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia Governor Zell Miller ate his share of greens and corn
bread growing up in the North Georgia mountains. In 1982, while
lieutenant governor, he fired off this letter to the editor to set
the record straight on a matter of greens terminology:
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought The New York Times knew everything, but
obviously your editor knows as little about spelling as he or she
does about Appalachian cooking and soul food. Only a culinarily
illiterate damnyankee (one word) who can't tell the difference
between beans and greens would call the liquid left in the pot
after cooking greens ``pot liquor'' (two words) instead of
``potlikker'' (one word) as yours did. And don't cite Webster as a
defense, because he didn't know any better either.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
