<HEADER>
A2687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN04-COX     09-30 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Southernisms a `sight' more than colorful
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when I thought I was learning to speak English, I find I
still have the taint of Creola, Ala. _ or is it South Georgia? _ in
my speech.
</P>
<P>
   I went to the library looking for something on the Coast Guard.
Talk about language, that branch of the service has its own _
colorful, flavorful, special. I'll never forget that when my
teenage son finished his reserve hitch in the Coast Guard, he came
home saying things such as, ``Walk back handsomely.'' I forget what
it means, but it had something to do with handling lines on a ship.
(Notice I said ``lines'' and not rope.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, the day I wanted to learn about the Coast Guard my hand
fell on a book I hadn't seen, titled simply and poetically
``Alabama.'' Naturally I poked around in it looking for Mobile and
found these nice lines: ``Mobile's blithe Mediterranean spirit
still lifts the heart and tempts the flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   The author, Virginia Van de Veer Hamilton, then took up speech.
She said she was talking about Creoles, but the usage she quoted
belongs to a lot of us. For instance, don't we often say ``proud''
when we mean ``glad,'' as in ``I'm proud to meet you''?
</P>
<P>
   We think ``sight'' a good word for ``much,'' as in, ``We've had
a sight of stormy weather.'' Then there's ``chunk'' for ``throw.''
I think the Atlanta Braves probably just throw the ball, but out in
the country we chunk it. Always have.
</P>
<P>
   When your son or grandson brings home a smart girl, we don't
call her ``industrious.'' ``Smart'' says it better. As for ``tote''
instead of carry, anybody who has toted a heavy load, either
physical or emotional, knows ``tote'' is the word.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Hamilton moved along to other usage, I think she had
hit pure country instead of Creole. For instance, don't you know
instead of addressing a letter you ``back'' it?
</P>
<P>
   My son down in Alford, Fla., had a neighbor who wasn't really
confident about reading and writing, and he especially didn't want
to disgrace himself by making a mess of the envelope when he did
the unaccustomed and dispatched a letter. So he asked my son if he
would ``back'' the letter for him. It was really fronting it, but
``back'' is the word we use.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hamilton pointed out that we like to double up on words. I
hadn't noticed it before, but we do say ``womenfolks'' and ``church
house,'' and why not? That's getting really specific. I like
``biscuit bread,'' but stopped saying that years ago. One thing I
don't believe many people have noticed is that ``evening'' for some
of us begins at noon. Not ``this afternoon'' but ``this evening.''
In fact, the first time I heard a woman say ``good afternoon,'' I
fell out laughing. I thought she was some kind of foreigner.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hamilton thought she was quoting Creole speech, but if she
had looked around a little she would have found she was also
quoting pure South. She didn't catch our pronunciation. How could
she? I was a high school student making a commencement speech
before I gave up putting a long ``i'' in night and right. It comes
out with ``o'' overtones. Almost, ``It's a nosse nott out tonott.''
That's not quite right, but you know what I mean. They tried to
speed up and smarten up my speech, but I'm afraid it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   On mature reflection, I think it's a good thing to hang on to
some of our differences. We'll rue the day when we all sound like
television.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
