<HEADER>
A2678 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-HIGH-CULTURE-3     09-30 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-HIGH-CULTURE-3RDTAKE-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BURBANK, Calif.: Michael's bedroom.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At college at Denison University in Granville, Ohio, he started
off pre-med, but soon realized he was more interested in Arthur
Miller, Tennessee Williams and Luigi Pirandello than organic
chemistry. After college, he took off for Paris, intending to be a
playwright. He wrote three plays in three weeks but soon got
homesick for New York and decided he was more suited to a real job
than the life of a creative spirit.
</P>
<P>
   His background may look significant in retrospect, Eisner says,
but there was no conscious design or personal passion that led him
to a career in arts or entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family wasn't part of the entertainment world,'' he said.
``The closest we ever came to being part of the theater world was
when I was growing up: Elaine Stritch once borrowed my mother's
mink coat to wear to the Tonys. My sister collected Playbills, but
half the time I went under duress. I went to the Young People's
Concerts, but it was a nightmare. The other kids were out playing
football, and I was sitting in a tie and jacket listening to
Leonard Bernstein. What happens, I guess, is things do get
absorbed, but there was no inevitability about this.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, his interest in architecture is deep and
passionate. How many other CEOs use the word ``despicable'' to
describe the architecture of the 1960s and '70s? As a youth, he was
entranced by the march of modernism down Park Avenue in skyscrapers
like Mies van der Rohe and Philip Johnson's Seagram Building.
</P>
<P>
   The family friend, Ganz, took Eisner around Rome when he was 18,
giving him a whirlwind tour of every church, statue, museum and
landmark he could find.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A.M. Stern, the newly appointed dean of Yale's School of
Architecture, who has designed buildings for Eisner and now sits on
the Disney board, said Eisner was involved to an extraordinary
degree in both the big picture and the details of what makes a
building work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not an architect or an architect manque,'' he said. ``But
he's a knowledgeable client, the rarest commodity you can find.
He's very visual and imaginatively visual.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, the differences between the cultural instincts of Walt
Disney and Michael Eisner do not necessarily play in Eisner's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Karal Ann Marling, a professor of art history and American
studies at the University of Minnesota, said Disney had a native,
unschooled, intuitive approach to art and an admirable indifference
to the pronouncements of East Coast cultural pooh-bahs.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner's much more self-conscious, as befitting someone who came
out of the '60s and '70s,'' said Ms. Marling, curator of the new
exhibition ``Designing Disney's Theme Parks: The Architecture of
Reassurance,'' which opens on Tuesday at the Cooper-Hewitt National
Design Museum in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find Walt's kind of naivete and willingness to take absolute
risks, high and low, terribly appealing. That's not to say Eisner's
not an innovator or a gifted figure, but he seems more in line with
educated sensibilities and maybe a little less experimental.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Eisner is willing to take risks as well. Roy Disney said
projects like the millennium symphonies might have intrinsic value
as part of the company's commitment to creativity and perhaps the
more subtle virtue of making people unconsciously rethink what the
company is about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll ever make a nickel off the millennium
concerts,'' Disney said. ``But maybe they help us go beyond being
`Disney,' in quotes. There's a downside to being successful. I'm
the last guy to ask about this, because it's my name, but I think
our name means a lot more than what people sometimes assume it
means.''
</P>
<P>
   How far does any of this go? Only an idiot, which Eisner
certainly is not, would try to reinvent Disney. But Eisner has
always been a shrewd marketer with a brilliant sense of what the
public will buy, as evidenced in the shows and movies he has been
involved in: ``Happy Days,'' ``Welcome Back Kotter,'' ``Saturday
Night Fever,'' ``Beverly Hills Cop,'' ``Raiders of the Lost Ark''
and ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Disney says there is less design than happenstance in the
company's evolution. One reason Disney brought in Ms. Taymor, he
said, was that it was so hard to figure out a way to do ``The Lion
King'' onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What were we going to do?'' he said. ``Have a bunch of guys in
lion suits sitting on their hind legs singing songs? We really
needed Julie's reputation for innovation and design and cleverness
and a sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's a grand design at work, you won't hear it expressed
by Eisner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're giving us too much credit for thinking things out and
too little credit for working by instinct,'' he said. ``If high art
means limited art, I'm not interested. That's not what we're about.
If it means better quality and more intelligent, I think that's
what our audience expects from us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
