<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FANNIE_FLAGG-COX     09-30 2609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANNIE_FLAGG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fannie Flagg: Post-`Tomatoes'
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eleven years after a sweet little book called ``Fried Green
Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop Cafe'' became a best seller,
ultimately spinning off a sweet little hit movie and a bustling
business for sweet little cafes that specialize in the title dish,
author Fannie Flagg knew very well what readers wanted from her.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wanted a sequel to `Fried Green Tomatoes,''' she says
on a recent visit to her beloved hometown of Birmingham. ``But I
killed everybody in that. I boiled one person! So I couldn't really
do a sequel.''
</P>
<P>
   Flagg will be in Atlanta on Wednesday to sign copies of her new
novel, ``Welcome to the World, Baby Girl!'' She knows she may have
some explaining to do to the hard-core fans who loved her first two
novels, ``Daisy Fay and the Miracle Man'' and ``Fried Green
Tomatoes,'' which were set in Mississippi and Alabama,
respectively. Not only is ``Welcome to the World, Baby Girl!'' not
a sequel to ``Fried Green Tomatoes,'' it's not even set in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, dual plot lines center on Dena Nordstrom, a blond,
blue-eyed TV newswoman in 1970s New York with a deep, dark secret,
and the quirky townspeople of Elmwood Springs, Mo. Dena's old
college roommate, Sookie _ a wife, a mom and a Kappa forever _
lives in Selma, Ala., providing the lone link to Flagg's typical
turf.
</P>
<P>
   The surrounding cast of characters may not be Southern, but
they're suitably offbeat: ``Neighbor Dorothy,'' for instance,
broadcasts daily live radio shows from her living room. And sweet,
ditsy old Aunt Elner, who ``always smelled like a wedding cake,''
utters everyday pearls:
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor little old human beings. They're jerked into this world
without having any idea where they came from or what it is they are
supposed to do, or how long they have to do it in. Or where they
are gonna wind up after that. But bless their hearts, most of them
wake up every morning and keep on trying to make some sense out of
it. Why, you can't help but love them, can you?''
</P>
<P>
   The prose is unapologetically sentimental, even ``shamelessly
corny,'' as one reviewer wrote in Kirkus Reviews: ``The author
does, however, know how to spin a rattling good yarn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You always worry when an atomic bomb goes off with one book,
and then people wait with bated breath to see what you're going to
do next,'' says author Winston Groom, a lifelong resident of the
Mobile Bay, Ala. area, who has known Flagg for 14 years. Groom
wrote ``Forrest Gump,'' so he knows a little something about the
pressure that comes with writing a popular novel that becomes a
wildly popular movie. ``You can't worry about that,'' he says.
``You just have to write.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fannie isn't going to write the same book over and over again
like some people do. ... And she casts a pretty wide net. She's not
like Tom Clancy _ it's not just men in suits on business trips who
read her books. She draws her readers from all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary _ yet undeniably peculiar _ people are Flagg's bread
and butter. In ``Welcome to the World, Baby Girl!'' as in her
previous two novels, she introduces monumental elements of
friendship, love, race and morality on a distinctly personal level.
The message is small yet universal: People are basically good, and
life is pretty funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is an inner goodness in people, and people who
have it don't even know they have it,'' Flagg says. ``People just
break my heart. They really touch me.''
</P>
<P>
   With red hair and clear blue eyes, Flagg is a youthful 57,
little changed since her 1970s heyday as a comedian and actress on
TV (``Candid Camera,'' ``The New Dick Van Dyke Show''), in movies
(``Grease,'' ``Five Easy Pieces'') and on Broadway (``The Best
Little Whorehouse in Texas''). Now she insists that performing was
simply a sidetrack, a long distraction from her first love of
writing. ``I never felt that comfortable performing,'' she says.
``I never had the need to get up in front of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Flagg has lived in California for decades, but she still wears
her Alabama dialect proudly, tossing in an occasional ``honey'' or
``precious'' where appropriate. She laughs easily, often cracking
herself up with her dead-on impersonations and memorable deadpan.
And she tends to whisper words that are somewhat distasteful: a
homeless man, an older lady. ...
</P>
<P>
   And she loves to tell a good tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to hear the story of how I first met Eudora Welty?
It was 1975, and I had just moved to California and was very
homesick. One day I looked up on an old telephone pole and saw a
flier that said, `Santa Barbara Writers Conference, guest speaker
Eudora Welty.' I thought, oh my God!''
</P>
<P>
   Flagg, who had written countless comedy sketches (for ``The
Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson,'' ``Candid Camera'' and many
other shows) but no fiction, signed up for the weeklong conference
just to get the chance to meet the Southern icon. On the first day,
alongside ``all these educated, intellectual people,'' Flagg
received the major assignment of the conference: Write a short
story about childhood to be entered in the yearly contest, which
Welty would help judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to break out in a cold sweat because I'm dyslexic,
horribly dyslexic,'' Flagg says. ``But I went home and got one of
those little children's notebooks and wrote my story out in
longhand, so that all the misspelled words and bad punctuation
looked like I had done it on purpose. Oh, yes, I was diabolically
clever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, honey, the thing won first prize! And Eudora handed me
my prize. I just went to pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Welty and Flagg struck up a friendship that endures to this day,
and that prize-winning story ultimately became ``Coming
Attractions,'' which was later reissued as ``Daisy Fay and the
Miracle Man'' and spent 10 weeks on the New York Times Bestseller
List. (Welty supplied a note of praise for the book jacket, ``which
didn't hurt one bit, I tell you!'' Flagg says.)
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, Flagg was in New York struggling to finish
writing her second novel, ``Fried Green Tomatoes at the Whistle
Stop Cafe,'' and Welty _ along with a second Southern literary
legend _ again became an unwitting factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing a second novel is terrifying,'' Flagg says, ``because
the first time you write, you don't know what you're doing. But the
second time you write you know you don't know what you're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway I had become very discouraged. ... One day I thought, I
can't write. I'm just giving the whole thing up. And I started
walking all the way up to 91st and Riverside, where my chiropractor
was. On the way, this man _ this homeless man _ looks at me and
says, `You're ugly!' And I said, `Well, thanks a lot! That's just
what I needed to hear today!'
</P>
<P>
   ``I go on to the chiropractor's office and notice that the
regular receptionist was not there _ instead, there was a nice
young man at the desk. Well, I sat down, still ranting about the
strange man in the street. `You know, I'm from Alabama. People have
manners in Alabama.' And this nice young man says, `You know, Miss
Flagg, I'm from Monroeville, Ala., and I just read your first book
and I thought it was great.'''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to say that Eudora Welty was coming to speak in New
York and he happened to have an extra ticket. Would Flagg like to
have it? The short answer was: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time Eudora got through talking that night, all these
New York people, who can be somewhat condescending to people from
the South, were falling all over her,'' Flagg says.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Flagg visited with Welty and then walked into the
lobby, where she spotted the nice young man from the chiropractor's
office, accompanied by an older woman. ``I went over to thank him
so much for the ticket, and the woman reached out her hand and
said, `Hi, Fannie. Harper Lee, Monroeville.'''
</P>
<P>
   And so, in Flagg's fabled life, she spent the evening sharing
drinks and conversation with authors Eudora Welty and Harper Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's not inspiration, I don't know what is,'' she says
with a shake of her head. ``I believe things like that happen for a
reason. I believe that things come to you when you really need
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, she had finished ``Fried Green Tomatoes,''
complete with a blurb on the book jacket from her new friend Lee,
and garnered nice reviews from such newspapers as the Los Angeles
Times, The Washington Post and The New York Times: ``A real novel
and a good one ... (from) the busy brain of a born storyteller.''
</P>
<P>
   With that project behind her, Flagg was ready to begin a new
novel. But when the screenwriter for the movie version of ``Fried
Green Tomatoes'' fell ill, the producers asked her to step in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to do it,'' Flagg says. Nonetheless, she spent
the next three years working with director and co-producer Jon
Avnet, crafting a screenplay that was nominated for an Academy
Award, a Writers Guild of America award and a Scripters Award
(which it won). Still, Flagg wasn't tempted to take on
screenwriting full time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a collaborative effort,'' she says, ``and I don't like
that. If I'm going to go down in flames, I would rather do it
alone. And I think it's because I'm dyslexic that I'm still in such
awe of the novel _ of books. I find that kind of writing so much
more rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking about dyslexia is obviously not something that Flagg
enjoys, but she's learned not to be embarrassed about it. Dyslexia
is a reading disorder characterized by reversals of letters such as
``b'' and ``d,'' words such as ``saw'' and ``was,'' and numbers
such as 6 and 9 or 16 and 61. Dyslexics often have trouble
remembering letters, words or numbers and have a tendency to skip
over or scramble letters, words and sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``My real name is Patricia Neal, and in school I continuously
signed my name Pasty Neal. I never could figure out why I couldn't
spell my own name _ I always felt so stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Flagg was kicked out of the Lavenge School of Tap
and Ballet because she couldn't tell her left from her right and
was messing up all the routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew what all these little things meant. Before
spelling tests at school, my mother would drill me for hours, but I
would get to school the next day and I couldn't retain it. I never
knew what it was, so I always acted silly to compensate. Years
later I went on a TV game show called `The Match Game,' where you
had to write your answers. There again, I would treat my
misspelling as a joke until one day a schoolteacher from St. Louis
wrote me a letter and asked, `How long have you been dyslexic?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never even seen the word, and I was 30-something years
old. I looked it up and took a test, and they said I was severely
dyslexic.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing is not the most logical profession for a dyslexic, but
Flagg has found a way to make it work. She types a chapter and
sends it to a professional typist, ``who knows how to decipher what
it is I'm trying to say.'' The typist retypes it, correcting all
the spelling, and sends it back to Flagg. The swapping continues
until the manuscript is finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write kind of like a quilt,'' Flagg says. ``I have a
clothesline that goes all the way down the hall in my house. I
write a scene and put it on the clothesline. I never really know
what the book is going to be about until I finish it and put all
the pieces together.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``Fried Green Tomatoes'' was a hefty 403 pages;
``Baby Girl'' weighs in at an impressive 467. Both are complex
stories told in snippets, with characters and events jumping around
decades and states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always start out to write a very simple book,'' she says,
feigning exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   Even the ``lonely, hard and heartbreaking'' act of writing
itself has been a source of unmitigated pleasure since 1981, when
Flagg finally dropped her successful career as an actress and
comedian and set her sights on writing for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rough,'' she says. ``I almost lost my house, and I
lived on $50 a week. ... But I was never happier. I can't even
explain it. It was like I had been going from room to room looking
for something, and finally I walked into the right room and said,
`Ah! This is where I belong.'''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Flagg lives in a 1913 frame house with a porch, nestled
amid all the modern, Spanish-style haciendas in Santa Barbara. At
least two or three times a year, she returns to Birmingham to visit
old friends and distant relatives. She also is a frequent visitor
to metro Atlanta, where she made fast friends during the filming of
``Fried Green Tomatoes'' in the summer of 1991 and even considered
buying a house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove a lot of real estate agents crazy, looking at all
these houses,'' Flagg says. ``I haven't given up the idea yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, about an hour southeast of Atlanta, the little town
of Juliette, where most of the filming was done, has been
revitalized as a tourist stop. And a couple of hours west of
Atlanta, in a tiny mining town just outside Birmingham, sits the
Irondale Cafe, the real model for Flagg's fictional Whistle Stop
Cafe, where a weary fry cook prepares 60 to 70 pounds of fried
green tomatoes on a typical weekday _ more on Sundays _ to keep up
with demand.
</P>
<P>
   Flagg's late aunt Bess Fortenberry, the model for the
irrepressible Idgie Threadgoode, ran the cafe from the 1930s until
the early 1970s. Since 1973, Bill and Mary Jo McMichael have run
the cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just adore Fannie,'' says Mary Jo, 66. ``She is such a
sweet, down-to-earth person. I remember way back when she was
co-anchor of the morning show in Birmingham, and I thought she was
the cutest, funniest person I had ever seen! I had no idea she
would be as successful as she's been or that I would actually get
to meet her. Now I feel like I've known her all my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her book put us on the national map,'' McMichael adds. ``We
were already on the local map.''
</P>
<P>
   Flagg's family and friends frequently turn up in her fiction.
Aunt Elner, the sassy, slightly daffy soul of ``Welcome to the
World, Baby Girl!'' really existed (``Oh, honey, I wish I had
thought to bring a picture of her to show you!''), as do Norma and
Macky Warren, a salt-of-the-earth couple who didn't hesitate when
Flagg asked if they objected to her using their real names for the
characters they inspired: `Honey, we'd love to be famous!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited,'' says Norma Warren, 61, who has been
happily married for 43 years to Macky, the actual boy next door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of what appears in the book is quite realistic,'' she
says with a laugh. ``You definitely get the idea of a couple that's
been married for a very long time. I think Fannie's been saving up
stories on us since we first met.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren accompanied Flagg on much of her book tour back in 1987,
when ``Fried Green Tomatoes'' was published. Then, they drove from
bookstore to bookstore in Alabama. Now, Flagg is beginning a
17-city national tour that will include stops in Boston, New York,
Denver, Chicago and Los Angeles. For her, this is the most
nerve-racking part of writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love meeting all the people, but I hate all the flying,''
she says. ``And I never read reviews, because you can really get
your feelings hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be very Christian Scientist about this. I only
see the good, y'all! Because if I don't, I'll just sit down and sob
at these book signings, and that's not what people want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
