<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDA-PREVIEW-COX     09-30 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDA-PREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The look and sound of ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida.''
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE THEMES: Personal love vs. patriotic duty. Enslaved by the
Egyptians, Nubian Princess Aida is singled out by Captain Radames
for her intelligence. He presents her to his betrothed, Princess
Amneris, as a personal servant.
</P>
<P>
   From this position of relative power, Aida schemes to free her
fellow Nubians, including her father. In the process, she and
Radames fall in love. They each face having to betray their own
countrymen or their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   The cast also includes a young Nubian boy slave; Amneris' dad,
the pharaoh; and Radames' father, Zoser, who is scheming to see his
son on the throne of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   THE LOOK: Nile glitz. The set design includes obelisks that rise
from the floor of the stage and descend from the fly space above.
The most impressive, most cantankerous bit of scenery is a
hydraulic-powered pyramid. The unit moves across the stage, raising
and lowering its four triangular sides to create multiple settings
_ including the battleship of Radames, private chambers and, of
course, the climactic pyramid/tomb.
</P>
<P>
   During previews, the pyramid has broken down several times,
causing the actors to continue the performance in a concert
version.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUND: Egyptian power pop. ``Elaborate Lives'' is not
totally sung through like ``Les Miserables'' or lyricist Tim Rice's
collaborations with Andrew Lloyd Webber, ``Jesus Christ Superstar''
and ``Evita.'' But the production is largely driven by the musical
numbers, with minimal dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   THE MUSIC: ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida'' is the second
collaboration between lyricist Tim Rice (``Jesus Christ
Superstar,'' ``Evita,'' etc.) and composer Elton John (``Goodbye
Yellow Brick Road'' and a zillion other pop hits). The pair hooked
up to pen the tunes for Disney's animated film ``The Lion King''
and the subsequent Broadway smash.
</P>
<P>
   Musically, the show shifts between a couple of dominant styles.
Flashy, big-beat rock numbers and swoony, string-glossed love
ballads. In both, you can hear John's songwriting signature. The
up-tempo songs echo the pop hits John recorded in the early to
mid-1970s (there's that rollicking piano of the ``Crocodile Rock''
era). The slow tunes sound similar to the reflective, mature '90s
artist.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight songs (there are 22 songs in all, including four
reprises) show off the title character, Aida, played by Heather
Headley. Her ballad turns _ ``Elaborate Lives'' and ``Easy As
Life'' _ are piano- and string-driven affairs (the former a duet
with Hank Stratton as Egyptian hunk Radames, whose star-crossed
love for Aida propels the story). They represent the emotional core
of the production and aim for a certain divalike grandeur. Headley
also gets to belt out a rousing, gospel-flavored theme, along with
other cast members, on ``The Gods Love Nubia.''
</P>
<P>
   The rock 'n' roll kicks in whenever Radames' evil, power-hungry
father, Zoser _ played by Rich Hebert _ takes the stage. Sherie
Scott, as the spoiled, unhappy Princess Amneris, has a role akin to
a narrator, introducing and closing the show with the song ``Every
Story Is a Love Story,'' a sweeping, melodic scene setter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
