<HEADER>
A2715 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-VIDAL-WIRED-NYTS     09-30 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VIDAL-WIRED-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE VIDAL: ON JFK, SEX, HISTORY &AMP; THE MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By KATRINA HERON  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 World rights excluding Japan  
 &HT;    It was Karl Marx, not Gore Vidal, who said that history repeats
itself _ the first time as tragedy, the second as farce.
 &HT;    But since Vidal has said practically everything else of interest
and wit on the subject, he might as well have said that too.
 &HT;    He has spent a half-century chronicling U.S. history, in the six
linked novels ``Burr,'' ``Lincoln,'' ``1876,'' ``Empire,''
``Hollywood'' and ``Washington, D.C.,'' while also knocking out
thunderous essays, not to mention such hairpin turns as ``Myra
Breckinridge.'' His most recent novel is ``The Smithsonian
Institution.''
 &HT;    One of literature's most caustic and seductive voices, a rich
kid who early on nurtured an acerbic relationship with the spoils
of capitalism, a libertarian's hero but also JFK's intimate _ and
Jackie's brother by marriage _ Gore Vidal has lived an erratically
patriotic life that finally landed him on the Amalfi coast, looking
back at us savages.
 &HT;    What does the future look like from there?
 &HT;    Al Gore is his cousin, which may or may not account for Vidal's
defense of the Internet as an endangered emblem of democracy. Yes,
he has a computer _ and a computer vassal to operate it.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    KATRINA HERON: Today the scientist-nerd has become a new
mythological hero. What's the next station in his journey?
 &HT;    GORE VIDAL: ``Mythological'' is the wrong word. He's not a myth
but a dim fact, like the Forbes list of the Truly Rich and
Infamous. The physical sciences _ not the arts and certainly not
philosophy _ are the central fact of the last three centuries.
Interesting that three writers as different as Martin Amis
(``Time's Arrow''), Tom Stoppard (``Arcadia''), and Gore Vidal
should all be writing about physics as fiction, or vice versa.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Can we learn from history?
 &HT;    A: The United States of Amnesia has a very good reason not to
cultivate a sense of the past, as our crimes against so many people
might make us _ not, God forbid, guilty, but jittery living in a
world where we are, contrary to our unrelenting propaganda,
detested.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Is ``progress'' a fiction?
 &HT;    A: Was the invention of cellophane progress? My father brought
some home for me to look at in the '30s. DuPont had introduced it
and no one knew what to do with the stuff. Now human progress, and
some of my new novel, involves slow alterations of a Darwinian
nature, like the withering away of the little toe or the addition
of a third sphere to the brain. Incalculable.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: You do take the long view, centuries-long at least.
 &HT;    A: I try to imagine it all from the big whimper on, and that
puts our self-important race in a class with the viruses. I do look
_ hope _ for change, but our short known history of 4,000 years or
so tends to be more of the same, with variable interest rates.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: So how does the ``Digital Revolution'' rate in revolutions
the world has known?
 &HT;    A: Revolution, or evolution, or simply the latest gimmick? A
subject I don't ponder. I still want to know what Iago meant when
he said to Othello, ``What you know, you know.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Lots of people have claimed that a Kennedy White House would
never survive in this age of Internet/media frenzy. You're one of
the few people actually in a position to know.
 &HT;    A: Actually, we always thought JFK would be shot _ by an angry
husband. But he was a cooler character than Bill Clinton and I
suspect would have stared down the enemy. Also, if he had to, he'd
take everyone else with him. He would _ and could _ reveal
everyone's sex life, and then the government would fold. He was the
greatest gossip I've ever known.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What's the biggest thing you've changed your mind about over
the years?
 &HT;    A: I was brought up, like all Americans, to believe that we were
a peace-loving country whose bad luck it was to keep getting roped
into other people's wars. Then, while writing ``Empire,'' I
realized to what extent the Spanish-American War was cold-bloodedly
planned, specifically by the assistant secretary of the Navy,
Theodore Roosevelt and by Admiral Mahan, Cabot Lodge, and Brooks
Adams _ New England grandees with imperial longings. These four,
exactly one century ago, maneuvered us into a war with Spain so
that we could steal the Spanish colonial empire.
 &HT;    Looking again at ``Burr,'' ``Lincoln'' and ``1876,'' I saw there
was something big at the core of these narratives, something that
as an American author I had missed in my own work: that plainly we
are driven to conquest, whether by love of God or by some peculiar
DNA code.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: T., the 13-year-old protagonist of your latest novel, ``The
Smithsonian Institution,'' is your bid to rewrite history, showing
us what might have been an alternative future.
 &HT;    A: Yes, Woodrow Wilson provided us with World War I _ after
another invasion of Mexico, just for practice. It should be noted
that, all through this, the American people, ignorant of geography
and history, wanted no part of foreign wars. My guy T. time-travels
so that he can stop World War II, by stopping World War I, by
keeping Wilson from becoming president.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Where would you time-travel?
 &HT;    A: Nowhere without anesthetics.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Do you find the future more interesting than it used to be?
 &HT;    A: Less interesting. The only hopeful sign I see is that our
number two export, after weapons, is entertainment. Can Disney save
us? Tune in to the next millennium.
 &HT;    I haven't even made reservations, since, actually, I'm not going
to spend much _ if any _ time there.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: A good argument for cloning, perhaps?
 &HT;    A: What's the point of a physical duplicate when it is the
mind-experience that is a person? Yet if memory could be saved at
regular intervals, one might have a true immortality _ very
tempting in the sense that the more one knows, the more wonderful
consciousness is.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Do you have any concerns about electronic books, and
specifically, the electronic supertome, whose screen will display
the contents of innumerable books?
 &HT;    A: Yes! How do we _ the creators _ get paid?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What will you write about next?
 &HT;    A: The loss of our Bill of Rights.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What advice would you give to a creative 23-year-old looking
to make a difference in the world?
 &HT;    A: Read.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Did you ever get any good advice at that age, or any other?
 &HT;    A: My father warned me never to date a girl who called her
mother Mummy. So I dated her brother and lived happily ever after.
 &HT;     (c.1998 Conde Nast Publications Inc.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ---------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
