<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRACK-SERIES-ADVISORY     09-30 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRACK-SERIES-ADVISORY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTN: NEWS EDITORS
</P>
<P>
   Crack Series Advisory
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade after crack cocaine gained a foothold in
America's poor, minority neighborhoods, a hidden generation of
motherless children is coming of age. With their parents tethered
more tightly to crack cocaine than to them, these orphans are
rearing themselves without fathers and often without mothers. Now
teenagers, many are having babies of their own. In ``Growing Up
With Crack,'' Atlanta Journal-Constitution writer Jane Hansen
presents their stories and those of the committed individuals
trying to help. Atlanta leads the nation in the continuing crack
crisis, as evidenced by data showing positive cocaine tests among
female arrestees.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a budget for the series. All will be available on
Friday, Oct. 2. Photos and graphics are available from the New York
Times News Service. For more information, please call CoxNet at
404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   (Papers not interested in the whole series may find the most
pertinent information in Part 1 and in the CRACK-CURE story in Part
6.)
</P>
<P>
   PART 1
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-GENERATION _ ATLANTA _ More than a decade after social
worker Donna Carson first detected the effects of crack on
newborns, Atlanta's first generation of crack babies is coming of
age. And they, too, are becoming young mothers, having to fend for
themselves and create their own semblance of family. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-VICTIMS _ ATLANTA _ More than 10 years after crack gained
a foothold in Atlanta's inner-city neighborhoods, children remain
its primary victims. WITH CHART
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-SOCIAL-DAMAGE _ ATLANTA _ Even though babies born with
cocaine in their veins may not be plagued with the developmental
delays experts once predicted, the social deprivation may be just
as devastating and life-long. WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   PART 2
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-CRUISE _ ATLANTA _ Demetria Walls knows the power of crack
cocaine. Now the former addict cruises Atlanta neighborhoods where
the orphans of crack suffer the double blow of neglect at home and
danger in the streets. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   PART 3
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-ABANDON _ ATLANTA _ Medical advances allow Egleston
Children's Hospital and Grady Memorial Hospital to save newborns
who couldn't be helped just a decade ago. But hospital workers
agonize over the choices they face when they send the babies home.
One child's story poses the question: Are we saving babies only to
abandon them? WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-SEND-HOME _ ATLANTA _ A team of physicians, nurses and
social workers move under dim lights from one plastic cocoon to the
next, quietly discussing each of the tiny sick babies that lives
within. Among them are the next generation of crack babies. Despite
the state-of-the-art medical care the newborns receive, their
caregivers wonder what purpose they perform in saving the babies'
lives only to send them home to crack addicts. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   PART 4
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-CHILD-ABUSE _ ATLANTA _ Is crack addiction child abuse? We
shouldn't be surprised, much less shocked, at the consequences of
sending newborns home with crack addicts when the ``family first''
system is at work, experts say. Neglect, and sometimes death, await
them. It's a miracle that some survive. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-COURT _ ATLANTA _ One recent day in Fulton County Juvenile
Court, a 4-year-old boy walked into the austere courtroom of Judge
Sanford ``Sammy'' Jones and headed straight for the judge's lap.
The boy and his twin sister were there that day so the judge could
figure out what to do with them. They'd been living for weeks in an
emergency shelter since authorities discovered that their mother _
a crack addict _ had been neglecting them. Drug addiction _ and the
child maltreatment that often follows _ is so prevalent here that
in the last year, Fulton judges have created a special calendar to
hear nothing but cases involving babies born with positive drug
screens, almost all with cocaine in their systems. WITH PHOTOS AND
CHART
</P>
<P>
   PART 5
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-KINSHIP-CARE _ ATLANTA _ Mary Shannon is a 55-year-old
woman with a new baby. She didn't want another child, and when she
learned of the pregnancy, she wanted nothing to do with it. Shannon
is the child's grandmother, one of thousands of American
grandparents raising their children's children _ a trend becoming
more common because of crack cocaine. Drug-addicted parents have
created a whole new class of children who are flooding the gates of
foster care, experts say. With too few foster homes, child welfare
workers are turning to relatives. WITH PHOTOS AND CHART
</P>
<P>
   PART 6
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-INCENTIVE _ ATLANTA _ Only a handful of residential drug
treatment programs in Georgia allow moms to keep their babies with
them. Gateway Cottage is one. A strict regimen, far from their old
haunts, offers crack moms their best chance at a new life. Their
babies provide the incentive. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-CURE _ Heroin addicts have methadone. Cigarette smokers
have nicotine patches. From opiates to alcohol, there are
substitute drugs that help squelch the urge or discourage the use.
But there is no medication that stems an addict's powerful craving
for cocaine, one of the most addictive drugs known. That could soon
change.
</P>
<P>
   PART 7
</P>
<P>
   CRACK-PREGNANT _ ATLANTA _ Donna Carson used to look at a
pregnant crack addict and see scum of the Earth. Then she got to
know one. She no longer hates crack addicts _ she's devoted to
them. She listens to them, befriends them, threatens them and most
of all coaxes them into drug treatment. WITH PHOTOS AND CHART
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
