<HEADER>
A2746 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTHWEST-ECON-ART-80     09-30 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-ECON-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN CRISIS HITS HOME IN THE PACIFIC NORTHWEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAHLOTUS, Wash. _ The huge piles of golden grain that rise like
sand dunes along the banks of the Columbia and Snake Rivers are a
beautiful sight, but to the wheat farmers of the Pacific Northwest,
they are really a sign of deep trouble. In a normal year, 90
percent of the wheat crop here in the Pacific Northwest is exported
to Asian markets, but this is not a normal year.
</P>
<P>
   Hammered by a sharp fall-off in demand because of Asia's
economic crisis, the region's farmers are faced with one of their
biggest stockpiles ever _ 340 million bushels, enough to fill a
line of hopper rail cars stretching from Seattle to Chicago. The
price of wheat has dropped to a 21-year low, but even then, as
Lonny Lightfoot, manager of the Port Wallula Barge Terminal
explains, ``There's just no selling it.''
</P>
<P>
   In central Washington, the heart of an apple industry that is by
far the largest of any state's, growers are forecasting a record
harvest this autumn. But the growers are so alarmed by the drop in
Asian demand _ Thailand, Malaysia, China and Indonesia all bought
50 percent to 85 percent fewer apples from Washington over the last
year _ that they recently voted to levy a 15-cent-a-box
``promotional assessment'' on themselves for an advertising
campaign. The aim is to get Americans to eat an extra apple a day.
</P>
<P>
   Here in what is by many measures the most trade-dependent region
of the country, Asia's economic problems are clearly hitting home,
starkly illustrating the domestic downside of a crisis that in
other parts of the United States may still seem like an
across-the-world abstraction, or perhaps even a welcome opportunity
in the form of ever-cheaper imports.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the Pacific Northwest's sag in exports to Asia limited to
wheat or apples. Sales to Asia of computers, semiconductors and
software are all down sharply, and ``a lot of that stuff's more
perishable than the food,'' said Jeff Seely, president of Netstock
Direct Corp., an Internet services company in Bellevue, Wash.,
speaking only partly in jest.
</P>
<P>
   And the region's biggest employer, the Boeing Co. in Seattle,
has been hit by the worrisome news from Asia, which typically buys
about a third of its planes and which was long seen as Boeing's big
growth market. In recent weeks alone, China froze all of its
airplane orders and delayed some deliveries, while the flag carrier
of the Philippines went out of business altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Even a cursory survey of industries here indicates the ways that
the strong American dollar can do damage at home. And while the
Northwest's overall economy remains strong, Asia's difficulties
have already led some government officials to project a noticeable
slowdown in growth.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, for instance, the state's top economist, Chang
Mook Sohn, recently cited Asian problems in revising his estimates
for growth. In a presentation to Gov. Gary Locke's council of
economic advisers, he lowered projected job growth in the next two
years to 1.5 percent (it was 4.1 percent in 1997), and he lowered
estimates for the state's tax revenue in that period by almost $200
million.
</P>
<P>
   At the Port of Seattle, imports increased 37 percent in the
first six months of this year, compared with that period last year,
while exports dropped 24 percent, an imbalance that many experts
here find troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade is crucial to the economy in this part of the country,
and anything that happens in Asia affects us very quickly and very
deeply,'' said Patricia Davis, a port commissioner and the
president of the Washington Council on International Trade, a
nonprofit business-backed organization here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are signs of a real downward spiral,'' added Ms. Davis,
ticking off statistics on the decline in current state exports to
10 Asian countries _ 48 percent in crops, 38 percent in apparel, 54
percent in lumber and wood, 22 percent in computers and industrial
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the pain felt more keenly than in the rolling
farmlands here in eastern Washington, where the interconnectedness
of world economies is vividly illustrated by the detailed knowledge
local farmers have of the ups and downs of the Thai baht, the
Japanese yen or the Indonesian rupiah.
</P>
<P>
   These farmers are long accustomed to the vagaries of the
weather, but something about the uncertainty of Asia's economy
seems almost more vexing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating,'' said Gary Galbreath, a 58-year-old
farmer who grew 4,200 acres of wheat under near-perfect conditions
this year. ``Here it seems like you're cutting a pretty nice crop
and Mother Nature is smiling on you, but then you go to market and
you're not making any money at all. Not even close to breaking
even.''
</P>
<P>
   The local price for wheat recently dropped to $2.24 a bushel _
it was as high as $5.20 two years ago _ and most farmers estimate
that they need to make $3.25 to $3.50 a bushel before they can turn
a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough situation all over,'' said Jonathan Schlueter,
executive vice president of the Pacific Northwest Grain and Feed
Association, a trade group based in Portland, Ore. ``Farmers know
they have a good crop, they know they have the quality foreign
buyers want, and yet the buyers are waiting for the markets to go
down. And it gets cheaper the longer they wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Properly covered and aerated, the grain can last for years, but
with all elevators in the area at capacity, wheat is piling up
along the rivers and in unlikely settings, like the broad lawn of a
go-cart track in St. John. But the stockpiles are ominous in
themselves: As the supply grows, prices are likelier to stay low,
so that another bountiful crop next year may only add to the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers here say they can generally ride out one bad year _ they
have all done it before _ but what is worrisome about the Asian
crisis is that no one knows when it will lift.
</P>
<P>
   ``If prices stay like this another year or two, you're going to
see a crisis around here,'' said Vern Regennitter, general manager
of Ritzville Warehouse Co., a grain elevator operator in Ritzville,
a farm community where the welcoming sign at the edge of town
boasts that its Future Farmers of America chapter has won national
championships in parliamentary procedure and land evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are going to be in a world of hurt,'' he
added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In conversations with residents at places like Ritzville's
branch of the Wheatland Bank or the Wheat and Barley, a diner in
nearby Colfax, the worries that Asia's crisis could drag down
American farms are palpable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmers in general have to deal with the weather, and we're
accustomed to taking the bad with the good, but you really get to
wondering if this thing in Asia is the big one,'' said Al Curtis, a
St. John wheat farmer whose summary of his harvest this summer
resembles a grim little haiku:
</P>
<P>
   ``Excellent yield, terrible price, no profit.''
</P>
<P>
   What is also clear is that many farmers are getting increasingly
angry over the trade embargoes that the United States has imposed
on many nations around the world. Many here fervently believe that
they might have faced ruin if Congress had not agreed to
temporarily lift a ban on food sales to India and Pakistan. The ban
was imposed after the two countries tested nuclear weapons in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to turn around and launch a nuclear missile
filled with grain at us,'' said State Rep. Mark Schoesler, a
Republican and a Ritzville wheat farmer. ``If we take their money
and they take our grain, I don't think that's going to hurt
anybody. I can't think of any country we've turned around because
of food sanctions anyway. Castro's still Castro, Saddam's still
Saddam, and we're not making those sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, in a broad reflection of such discontent, the leaders
of groups representing wheat, grain, barley, pea and lentil growers
in the Northwest signed a petition calling for elimination of all
sanctions on American food exports except in cases of ``compelling
national emergency'' or a declaration of war.
</P>
<P>
   Apple growers, coming into their harvest season, are also deeply
worried by Asia's problems. Indonesia, for instance, which bought
4.1 million boxes of Washington apples in the 1996-97 season, the
most of any Asian nation except Taiwan, bought just 670,000 boxes
in the last season. A box weighs about 42 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, American consumption of apples has flattened in
recent years at about 21 pounds annually per person, compared with
35 pounds in Canada and 50 pounds in some European countries, said
Jim Thomas, communications director for the Washington State Apple
Commission in Wenatchee.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the new marketing campaign, which comes amid a projected
record harvest of 103 million boxes in a state that typically grows
nearly two-thirds of all the nation's apples.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to compete for all those stomachs out there,'' Thomas
said. ``We're competing against Frito-Lay and all those people who
are spending millions of dollars to try to come up with what we
already are _ fat-free stuff, sodium-free, etc. But the problem for
us is to get to the consumer with the kind of high-profile imagery
those snack companies already have.''
</P>
<P>
   The $23 million advertising campaign is not exactly huge _
Thomas estimates that is the same amount that gets spent to market
a Snickers candy bar alone _ but it is a start. ``It gets us into
the ball game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the computer industry's problems in selling to
Asia have been generally offset by continued strong sales to
Europe, Canada and Mexico. William Archey, president of the
American Electronics Association, the largest high-technology trade
group in the country, said that he could not break down specific
figures for sales from the Northwest, but he noted that the region
had a heavy and growing concentration of computer companies,
including Microsoft, and that many companies here had been
specifically trying to increase sales in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, he said, sales to Asia of computer equipment and
software in the first six months of this year fell to $28.7 billion
from $32.5 billion in the same period of 1997. That 12 percent
decline is even greater if sales to China are factored out, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue that I think is the most important, and only the
prophets can deal with it, is when this is all going to turn
around,'' Archey said. ``I think the most optimistic expectation at
this point is another two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in the farm region, Northwesterners are trying to
treat the Asian problems with some stoicism. ``There's an old
saying,'' said Pearson Burke, a grain merchandiser and commodities
broker at the Ritzville Warehouse. ``Low prices cure low prices and
high prices cure high prices.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he offered a visitor a tour of his company, including an
elevator stacked full of wheat in a million-bushel pile stretching
more than half the length of a football field and 80 feet high,
Burke said the forces at work in this crisis felt far more remote
than those brought on by nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things a farmer can't control, including
the weather,'' he said. ``But this is something else entirely. The
most skilled farmer here can't control what's going on in the
economy half a world away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
