<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2750 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLET-OVERHAUL-TEX     09-30 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLET-OVERHAUL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DIRECTOR STEERS FORT WORTH DALLAS BALLET INTO MORE ADVENTUROUS
TERRITORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It's been an intense summer for Benjamin
Houk. In June, he left a job as director of the Nashville Ballet to
take over as artistic director at the scandal-rocked Fort Worth
Dallas Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   In the heat of the worst summer in 18 years, he moved with his
wife, Lauri Michelle, and their two preschool-age children to
Rockwall, where they stayed with his wife's parents for two months.
Last week, they bought a house in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   It's been an intense year for the Fort Worth Dallas Ballet, too.
</P>
<P>
   The low point of the company's 37-year history came in January,
when Paul Mejia resigned as artistic director under a cloud of
scandal involving allegations of sexual harassment. The high point
of the company's history came in May, with the long-awaited move to
Bass Performance Hall and the presentation of one of the monuments
of the repertoire in a final, glorious bow for Mejia.
</P>
<P>
   Houk, 36, and the Fort Worth Dallas Ballet are now embarked on a
new path with the first program of the Houk era.
</P>
<P>
   What audiences see this season will be substantially different
from what they've seen for the past 11 years. Most notably, Houk is
rechoreographing that traditional favorite, ``The Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Mejia's leadership, the repertoire included only one work
not by legendary choreographer George Balanchine or Mejia. Houk
will expand the company in three directions:
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine will still be on several programs, but so will such
mid-20th-century contemporaries as Agnes de Mille and Antony Tudor,
whom Mejia avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Works by contemporary choreographers will add a range of
expressions and styles.
</P>
<P>
   And the company will restage 19th-century ballets, including
portions of ``Swan Lake'' and ``Paquita,'' presenting a view of
dance before Balanchine _ the ballet of princes and tutus and fairy
tales, in which refined movement was more important than the
constant emotional energy of the Balanchine style.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia's wife, ballerina Maria Terezia-Balogh, dominated
principal female roles for the past 11 years. She remains
associated with the company as a coach but will not dance this
year.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a different mood at the company.
</P>
<P>
   During the Mejia era, you had to catch the artistic director
before class or between class and rehearsal. He was always there;
if the dancers were working, so was he.
</P>
<P>
   Houk, a former principal dancer with the Pacific Northwest
Ballet, works with the dancers, but not every minute. He is as
likely to be in his office, in a tie, juggling schedules and, in a
switch from the Mejia era, raising funds.
</P>
<P>
   A newly appointed dance mistress, Deborah Hadley, who became one
of the country's most admired ballerinas during her career at
Pacific Northwest Ballet, does much of the rehearsing and teaching.
Hadley, Balogh and Houk rotate teaching the morning class.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Patchell, now in her fourth year with the ballet,
describes the mood around the company as happier. ``I'm receiving
much more encouragement,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Langenstein, beginning her sixth season with the
company, appreciates the variety of approaches in class. ``Ben and
Debbie are from the same company, and are on the same wavelength,''
she says. ``Maria gives class similar to what we're used to, and
it's nice to have that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   What did Houk find when he arrived in Fort Worth?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really good-looking company,'' he says. ``They're all
great instruments for dancing. It was like walking into a music
store and finding a bunch of Strads.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably relaxed compared with Mejia's intensity, Houk has
made it clear that he is broadening the focus away from Balanchine.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's performances will include one Balanchine work,
``Tarantella.'' Lila York, a contemporary choreographer who is
decidedly post-Balanchine, will be represented by her ``Rapture,''
which Houk describes as ``unusual, violent at times, also lyrical
at times.'' The grand Russian classical tradition will be
represented by an excerpt from ``Swan Lake.'' And Houk will present
himself as choreographer in ``Rite of Swing,'' based on the revival
of swing dancing.
</P>
<P>
   The company's most visible and highly attended event _ ``The
Nutcracker'' _ will take on Houk's stamp immediately. Moving to
Bass Performance Hall required that the company replace its
13-year-old sets, which in turn required new choreography. After
some discussion, Houk decided to do the new version himself. The
new ``Nutcracker'' will premiere in November in San Antonio and
arrive in early December in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Houk isn't offering any clues as to who will be the
stars of the company. In the Mejia regime, leading female roles
were dominated by Balogh and Maria Thomas, with Todd Edson as their
male counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to spread the top out,'' Houk says. ``I'm not sure
who the next budding soloists will be. It's not going to be just
one or two people anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The company includes 31 dancers and presents seasons in Fort
Worth and Dallas on a budget of $4.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Houk wants what any young director in a market that is far below
its potential would want: ``A bigger season. A bigger audience.
More performances.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
