<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK NOTES: A BAD BOY'S GOOD AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sometimes nasty, sometimes raunchy man whose lamentation on
radio Wednesday was that ``I'm not having any fun calling Jews on
Yom Kippur'' is about to become the progenitor of the richest
literary prizes in the United States. The very prodigiousness of
that, however embarrassing for book people, should and will bring
howls of joy from writers. Wrap your mind around the Imus American
Book Awards. That's Don Imus, and that's four awards annually.
Three are for $50,000 a pop and one for $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the prestigious but at times unfathomable National
Book Award carries a $10,000 prize, and a Pulitzer Prize is $5,000.
It was his anger at last year's National Book Award that got Imus,
somewhat accidentally, into awarding prizes. He was incensed that
``the elitists,'' as he called awards committees, bypassed Sam
Tanenhaus' biography, ``Whittaker Chambers'' (Random House), which
Imus promoted with gusto on his radio show, for yet another
biography of Thomas Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They send me all the books that are nominated,'' he said, and
it's stuff ``that nobody reads. So I complained on my hideous radio
program. I was just kidding about Imus American Book Awards.
Kidding about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for publishers also to grumble about the
obscurity of some award nominees, and because awards are
subjective, the controversies surrounding them are not surprising.
But out of this Imus rage grew the apotheosis of his literary
awards, which will be presented in December.
</P>
<P>
   Imus luxuriates in everyone's fury, and so it is said that a few
publishers didn't even submit nominations for the Imus Awards,
which, if true, will be an unhappy surprise for their authors. What
is clear is that not only has Imus learned the craft of reading
but, unlike some of his competitors, he apparently actually
practices it as well. His show, between its provocative
vulgarities, is a berth for writers, often with several authors a
week as guests.
</P>
<P>
   The talker wants to be a power in book selling, similar to Oprah
Winfrey (who is considered the best book saleswoman in the
country). Not likely. But is his wish only hubris and largess,
arrogance and ego? No. His show is heard on more than 90 radio
stations and is televised on MSNBC, and his promotion people claim
he has 10 million listeners nationwide. While he's not exactly the
Chips of communications, his listeners attend to him and have a
surprisingly high income and education level for such a wild
program. All of which led one publishing executive to predict that
``Imus can become a huge catalyst for book sales, and suggestions
to his listeners can have a huge impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Imus could not make a best seller out of ``Whittaker Chambers,''
hard as he tried, but he drove up its sales. He did make a best
seller out of Jane Mendelsohn's ``I Was Amelia Earhart'' (Alfred A.
Knopf), a novel bought to his attention by his wife, Deirdre
Coleman-Imus, also an avid reader. When it was published in April
1996, the first printing was 30,000 copies. By August his on-air
``insistence'' _ as the publisher called it _ landed the book on
the New York Times' best-seller list and 200,000 copies were in
print.
</P>
<P>
   The money for the prizes will come from Barnes &AMP; Noble, the
booksellers, and A&AMP;E, the cable television entertainment channel,
through the simple method of buying advertising on the Imus show.
Imus will also do name-dropping for the two companies on his show.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Barnes &AMP; Noble will prominently display books
selected by Imus as must-reads on a special shelf in each of its
500 stores, at the rate of two picks a week, sort of an Imus book
club. After all, Oprah has a book club. The selections will also
get special mention on the bookstore chain's online sales
operation. Ben Boyd, director of communications for Barnes &AMP; Noble,
said, ``Down the road, we're thinking of having him do children's
books selections too.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mohamad, marketing vice president for A&AMP;E, said: ``We
are helping him have fun doing serious things. These aren't
irrelevant books he'll be choosing, and along the way he'll be
mentioning our biography programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Winners will be chosen by Imus and by book buyers, who can vote
in Barnes &AMP; Noble stores from selections made by Imus and an
anonymous panel of five book editors who were chosen by Imus'
literary agent, Esther Newberg. The panel will nominate three
nonfiction books and three fiction books from works submitted by
publishers. Imus will nominate another three from each category,
producing a dozen finalists.
</P>
<P>
   From those the Barnes &AMP; Noble customers will vote on one fiction
and one nonfiction winner, and Imus will pick one of each. Three of
the four winners will receive $50,000 each. Imus will choose one
for the $100,000 prize just because he wants too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people will be surprised who we choose,'' Imus said.
``I'd like the winners to be writers who haven't a lot of money,
haven't yet got big advances or haven't written big sellers.'' He
indicated he was pretty sure that would mostly happen.
</P>
<P>
   There are some problems. For instance, Imus' show is really like
a boy's club. Some women feel they get short shrift, seldom getting
to say anything even when they are guests. One woman who is a
book-publishing executive wondered Wednesday if female writers
would get their share of the loot. On the other hand, it was Mrs.
Coleman-Imus who got her husband rolling on the Earhart book.
</P>
<P>
   And wow, $250,000 for prizes for writers. It's a good thing that
the sometimes viciously sophomoric radio host has concluded that
award juries are about as useful and annoying as the people who put
stickers on fruit. Certainly no literary person thought up this
blockbuster for writers and is making it happen. Anyhow, as Shaw
said in ``Major Barbara,'' you take money from the munition makers
to give to the Salvation Army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
