<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MYSTERY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOUCHING EVIL': THE CRIMINAL MIND AS A MYSTERY'S GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Broadcast notes appear at the end of the review. Time,
channel are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(th) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you justify doing evil to destroy evil? That is one of the
dark questions that slowly emerge from the absorbing, unsettling
five-part series that begins this season of ``Mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Touching Evil'' has a dashing detective hero, Dave Creegan.
But this is no frothy cat-and-mouse game; it is a collection of
twisted contemporary tales in which Creegan, part of a team of
high-powered London detectives, comes face to face with unspeakable
killers.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to guess that ``Touching Evil'' was created and
largely written by Paul Abbott, who invented the great, personally
flawed, crime-solving psychologist of ``Cracker.'' In the mold of
the most intriguing modern crime-solvers, Creegan has psychological
turmoil of his own, and his cases have more to do with confronting
a criminal mind than with hunting down evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Robson Green, who plays Creegan, has piercing blue eyes,
slightly thinning hair and a taciturn quality that causes his
partner, Susan Taylor (Nicola Walker), to ask if he has spent a lot
of time alone lately. He has; he is recently divorced, the father
of two small daughters, and quietly torn apart over it. He also has
a conspicuous scar on his temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touching Evil'' unfolds with such deliberation (too much in
the slow-going early stages) that it takes a while to learn that
the scar is the result of a bullet to his head, taken during a not
so distant investigation. Creegan may be brave and smart, but he's
not infallible (the better to worry when he seems in danger).
</P>
<P>
   The series follows three separate cases (the first complete in
the two-hour opening, with two more stories covered in four
hourlong installments). In the first episode Creegan joins the
fictional OSC, the Organized and Serial Crime Unit, and tackles the
most disturbing case of all.
</P>
<P>
   Three small boys have been kidnapped. The clues _ a buried
sneaker and a plastic daffodil left at the scene _ lead to a cool,
professorial geneticist named Hinks (Ian McDiarmid), who they
suspect has kidnapped and murdered children before. If his pattern
holds, the detectives have six days to find the boys before they
are killed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as the renegade hero, Creegan is willing to break the
rules to save the children. But it is the unfolding of his
character that becomes most fascinating to watch as Green smoothly
allows us to see the tension between Creegan's normal life as a
father and professional, and the flashes of dark intuition that
help him track the killers. (In a more outgoing mood, Green played
the young doctor obsessively in love with the middle-aged Francesca
Annis in the quirky ``Masterpiece Theater'' romance ``Reckless,''
also written by Abbott.)
</P>
<P>
   If Creegan never takes on the complexity of Robbie Coltrane's
Fitz in ``Cracker,'' he has an enigmatic allure that grows through
the series.
</P>
<P>
   The next stories feature similarly monstrous crimes. In the
second, several patients are drugged and killed in a hospital in
what appears to be unsolicited euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   The third has the least interesting crime, involving the
Internet, college students and mutilated corpses. But it offers the
most satisfying glimpses into the lives of the detectives.
</P>
<P>
   All are played with a crispness that suits the series,
especially Ms. Walker. With her cropped hair and brisk manner, she
brings an echo of Jane Tennison from ``Prime Suspect'' to the role
of Creegan's no-nonsense partner. This precision exists in a world
often filmed to look ominously claustrophobic.
</P>
<P>
   Though each case is self-contained, there are threads that go
through subsequent episodes, and the question left dangling in the
first episode leads to the startling conclusion of the final
installment. Another murder is solved but that solution only raises
more questions of ethics and morality.
</P>
<P>
   This psychologically chilling series takes on the big issues
beneath all detective stories: life and death, good and bad, the
extremes to which humans can go. Among its other qualities,
``Touching Evil'' is perfectly named.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY: `TOUCHING EVIL'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Thursday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Written by Paul Abbott and Russell T. Davies; directed by Julian
Jarrold and Marc Munden; Jane Featherstone, producer; David Odd,
director of photography; Claire Kenny, production designer; Adrian
Johnston, composer; Simon Lewis, Susan Hogg and Abbott, executive
producers; Rebecca Eaton, series executive producer; Diana Rigg,
host.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Robson Green (Dave Creegan), Nicola Walker (Susan Taylor),
Ian McDiarmid (Ronald Hinks), Michael Feast (Commander Enwright),
Adam Kotz (Jonathan Kreitman), Shaun Dingwall (Mark Rivers),
Kenneth MacDonald (Cyril), Mary Cunningham (Marion), Saskia Downes
(Kerry Creegan), Holly Earl (Louise Creegan), Molly Maloney (Ruby
Creegan) and Antony Byrne (Barry). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
