</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHROEDER REASSURES FRENCH OF GERMAN COMMITMENT TO ALLIANCE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ He will not become chancellor until after the new German
parliament is sworn in and he can form a coalition government,
maybe at the end of October, Gerhard Schroeder said Wednesday, but
that did not stop the French from hanging on his every word for
signs that he might love them less than he loves the British.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first foray abroad since Sunday's election, Schroeder
reassured President Jacques Chirac, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
and French journalists Wednesday that he wanted to strengthen
Germany's relations with France every bit as much as those with
Britain, for the greater good of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   And he made music to Chirac's ears by agreeing with him on the
need for better regulation of global capital flows to head off
world recession. That is a demand France will press at the coming
meetings in Washington of the International Monetary Fund and
finance ministers of the leading industrial democracies.
</P>
<P>
   Though that and a whole lot else Schroeder said Wednesday does
not yet amount to official policy, as French officials said they
realized, they were happy with what they heard.
</P>
<P>
   Standing side by side with Chirac in the courtyard of Elysee
Palace, where heads of state and government are received, though he
is not yet either, Schroeder said, ``The president and I are of one
opinion on the necessity of regulating capital flows and financial
markets better than in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at the German Embassy later, he added, ``We
need more coordination in international economic policy, especially
for uncontrolled capital flows that can bring whole economies under
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   French officials said Chirac had raised the urgent issue of the
need for a coordinated position of the NATO alliance on how to stop
Yugoslav Army attacks on civilians in Kosovo, a province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   France and Britain sponsored a resolution on Kosovo that the
United Nations Security Council adopted last week, warning
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to stop the attacks, and
French officials said their view now was that this resolution
provided sufficient authority for the alliance to decide to carry
out bombing threats against Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said his party's position was also that a Security
Council resolution was needed before NATO could act.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, a Social Democrat, had lunch at the German Embassy
with the conservative Chirac and then spent the afternoon with the
Jospin, the Socialist prime minister, and key ministers of the
French government.
</P>
<P>
   After the official meetings, French officials said their leaders
had agreed with the chancellor-elect that jobs and the social
consequences of economic policy ought to rank high among European
priorities after years of reducing deficits, at German insistence,
to get the Continent ready for a common currency that will be
introduced in 11 countries in January.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder agreed with Chirac to set up joint working groups to
figure out ways of invigorating French-German relations and of
working out a common position on how to modify the cumbersome
institutions of the 15-nation European Union before it takes in
formerly Communist countries in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Visibly reassured after finishing off his lunch with Schroeder
with Cuban cigars, Chirac told him he should feel at home at Elysee
Palace. Schroeder replied, ``I don't think I'll be moving in.'' The
two could converse directly only in English, since neither speaks
the other's language. Both said they believed that strengthening
relations with Britain was no threat to any third country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
