<HEADER>
A2772 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTHER-NATURE'S-RADIO     09-30 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHER-NATURE'S-RADIO-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENEATH AM-FM, SOUNDS OF SILENCE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before you or your grandparents were alive, before the days of
Thomas Edison or Jesus Christ, even before the first human beings
were around to hear it, there was radio.
</P>
<P>
   And it was beautiful. Sweet descending tones, wispy wavering
pitches and choruses of percussive pops and hisses filled the
airwaves. Only there were no radio receivers in existence to
capture them.
</P>
<P>
   These were the sounds of Mother Nature's own radio station,
produced by electromagnetic energy generated by lightning strokes,
the earth's magnetic field and related phenomena like the northern
and southern lights. But the world is such an electromagnetically
loud place these days _ full of power lines, electric lights,
automobiles and computers, not to mention radio stations programmed
by humans _ that nature's radio has been practically drowned out.
</P>
<P>
   To hear it, one must travel to an area free of electronic
interference (the desert, the jungle, Siberia, Central Park) with a
specially made very-low-frequency radio receiver tuned below the AM
and FM bands.
</P>
<P>
   And that is what a growing number of hobbyists have been doing
over the last few years, attracted not just by the sweet sounds and
the possibility of making discoveries in this bizarre branch of
plasma physics but also by the notion that to hear nature you must
immerse yourself in nature.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, you become attuned to the earth in the same way
that a surfer looking for the perfect wave gets to know the ocean.
Sunspot activity is projected to be at a peak over the next few
years, signaling an increase in magnetic storms and a prime time
for radio explorers in search of sferics, whistlers, tweeks and
chorus, as these sounds have been classified.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most active whistler hunters has been Stephen
McGreevy. He has traveled everywhere from the Nevada desert to the
Arctic Circle, bravely (or stupidly) sticking a metal radio antenna
into the air during lightning storms to hear the ensuing rush of
radio sounds. He recently released the first widely available
compact disk of what is known as natural radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electric Enigma'' (Irdial Discs,
irdial(AT)irdialsys.win-uk.net) is one strange radio show. There
are sections that sound like heavy laser fire or relentless
air-bomb attacks. These are whistler storms, caused by radio energy
from lightning strokes traveling and spreading out across thousands
of miles of the earth's magnetic field.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are recordings that sound like a nest full of birds'
eggs hatching, the babies very hungry and very vocal. These sounds
are dawn chorus, sudden ascending pitches caused when the sun pelts
the earth's magnetic sphere with energy emissions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to making these sounds available on CD, McGreevy has
also made natural radio easy to listen to for anyone who is not on
a first-name basis with his or her local Radio Shack clerk by
selling a hand-held very-low-frequency receiver
(vlfradio(AT)triax.com).
</P>
<P>
   McGreevy's work may be just the beginning of documenting the
radio sounds of the universe. In 1978, two scientists won the Nobel
Prize for discovering radio waves produced by the creation of the
universe. Couldn't those sounds be amplified into audibility?
</P>
<P>
   If I can't see photographs of the big bang, I'd at least like to
hear it. And then there are broadcasts from other planets:
whistlers picked up in radiation belts around Jupiter, Saturn,
Uranus and Neptune. What do those sound like? How about the
ultra-low-frequency signals that some believe are generated before
earthquakes?
</P>
<P>
   If there is a natural radio, then there must be a natural
television too. This may sound ridiculous, but in a much more
recent area of research, scientists and hobbyists are trying to
pinpoint the forces behind nature's own television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Its programs are known as red sprites, blue jets and short-lived
elves _ colorful light flashes, disks and effects that take place
during thunderstorms high above the storm clouds. Like whistlers,
they are a side effect of lightning.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases they are only visible through a television monitor
hooked up to a low-light video camera. But they're cheaper than
pay-per-view.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
