<HEADER>
A2776 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELEBRATION-TOWN-2TAK     09-30 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBRATION-TOWN-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING IN A DISNEY TOWN, WITH BIG BROTHER AT BAY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill.)  (af) 
 Douglas Frantz, a Times national correspondent, is writing a book
about Celebration, with Catherine Collins, for Henry Holt and Co.  
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CELEBRATION, Fla. _ One hot afternoon last month, my wife,
Catherine Collins, was riding her bicycle home from the post office
here when a blue car with Pennsylvania license plates pulled
alongside her. One of the children in the car leaned out the window
and asked, ``Can you tell me where Truman lives?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pardon me?'' Catherine replied, suspecting some kind of
tourist joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truman,'' the child's mother said emphatically. ``Didn't you
see the movie?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that Truman,'' said Catherine, who had in fact seen ``The
Truman Story,'' the media satire starring Jim Carrey. ``He was just
a character. It was all make-believe. And anyway, it wasn't filmed
here. It was filmed over in Seaside, on the Panhandle.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time we had run into the misconception that
the movie had been filmed in Celebration _ or that the new town
where we live is some sort of unticketed gate for Disney World,
which is about eight miles away.
</P>
<P>
   There are similarities between the fictional movie town and this
post-neotraditional town built by those masters of make-believe,
Walt Disney Co. Both are pretty and orderly, populated by smiling,
waving residents and blessed by sunny skies and warm temperatures.
And like the movie town, Celebration has its own unique rules and
designs for social engineering.
</P>
<P>
   But, after living here for 15 months, we can testify that
Celebration is a real place, with its own attributes and its own
problems. Indeed, the town represents an ambitious, real-life
attempt by Disney to employ architecture and urban design to revive
the sense of community and place that Americans tell pollsters are
missing in traditional suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   As journalists, we have lived all over the country, mostly in or
on the edges of major cities. We have been pleasantly surprised to
find a degree of community spirit and neighborliness in Celebration
that we haven't encountered elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   We know everyone on our street, except for one family that never
seems to be at home, and block parties and town-wide festivities
are frequent and popular.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for this community camaraderie is the sense
that we are all pioneers in this new town. But some of it is
attributable to the careful planning that went into Celebration's
design.
</P>
<P>
   The first residents moved in during the summer of 1996, and
today the town has about 2,000 people out of a projected population
of 20,000. The 5,000-acre tract on which the town is being built is
part of the 30,000 acres Walt Disney accumulated in the early 1960s
for his second theme park.
</P>
<P>
   When company planners determined that this swath of swamp and
cow pasture would not be needed for the future expansion of Disney
World, Michael Eisner, the company's chairman and chief executive,
gave a green light to developing the town, though it had nothing to
do with the company's core business of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The architect Robert A.M. Stern, a Disney board member and one
of the designers of Celebration's master plan, described Eisner's
motives in grandiose terms. ``Michael's feeling was that, if the
company were going to do this, it was going to be something that
would set an example,'' he said. ``It would demonstrate that this
was a great company with a great sense of public obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, in a telephone interview from his corporate jet a few
days ago, was more pragmatic. ``The motivation was to do something
with the property,'' he said. ``Once you decide to do something,
you want to do it in an excellent way.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Eisner professed surprise at all the attention
Celebration has received in the press. ``I just thought we were
doing something small and unique,'' he said, though in the past he
has said he hoped the town would be a model for development in the
next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But no one involved in the project ever thought small. Along
with Stern, the roster of architects for Celebration's public
buildings included many of the profession's biggest names.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Graves designed the post office, Robert Venturi and
Denise Scott Brown designed the bank and Cesar Pelli designed the
1930s-era movie house. Philip Johnson created Town Hall, and the
real estate sales center was the last building designed by Charles
W. Moore, who died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Stern and his collaborator, Jacquelin Robertson, another New
York architect, paid close attention to the details of the master
plan for the town.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the streets are straight and narrow to slow traffic and
empower pedestrians and bicyclists. But there are also sweeping
arterial streets that carry the tourist and business traffic to the
town center.
</P>
<P>
   The houses are close together, most with front porches to
promote neighborhood interaction. Garages are tucked away at the
rear and entered from alleys. Most houses are within a five-minute
walk of downtown, though that will change as sections farther from
the town center are developed.
</P>
<P>
   Lots are small, with as little as 10 feet separating houses in
many instances, but the tradeoff is plentiful parks and other
public spaces.
</P>
<P>
   House prices range from about $175,000 to $1 million or more,
but even the mansions must conform to a strict design code that
reflects a Southeastern vernacular architecture from the pre-1940s.
There are deep porches, gables, dormers, loggia and large-columned
porticoes.
</P>
<P>
   To promote consistency and cohesiveness, the exterior color
palette is limited to white and pale shades of beige, blue, yellow,
green and pink.
</P>
<P>
   On the telephone the other day, Eisner asked if the people who
live in Celebration appreciate the architecture. The answer is that
while the architecture contributes to a feeling of genuine quality
to the town center, particularly the Graves post office and Pelli
movie house, the residential side is less satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Within a few months, I found the six basic designs to be
repetitious and the pastel houses to be monotonous. There also is
an ersatz air to the place when you know that most dormers are
fake, with black paint on the windows, and the columns are plastic,
albeit to protect against termites and rot.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner's disclaimer about doing something small aside,
Celebration has been a magnet for attention from the start. Demand
was so high that the first 350 houses and 120 apartments were sold
through a lottery in November 1995. Each month since, 15,000 people
have visited the preview center, and Celebration has remained the
hottest-selling residential development in the Orlando area,
despite prices that are 25 percent or more above the market.
</P>
<P>
   Why the popularity? Part of it is the simple association with
the Disney name. Many of the first wave of residents were drawn
because they believed Disney would build a top-quality town, just
the way it provided top-quality vacations year after year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a dyed-in-the-wool Disney freak,'' said Dan Rudgers, a
retired high school music teacher from Long Island, who visited
Disney World an average of three times a year for 20 years before
he bought a town house in Celebration. ``I had faith in the company
to build the best place.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as control is a hallmark of Disney World, it also is a
central theme of Celebration, where the regulations extend beyond
the shade of pastel on the houses to govern anything visible from
the street, from the varieties of shrubs in the yard to the color
of window curtains _ white and off-white only, please.
</P>
<P>
   Political signs are also restricted, in terms of size, number
and when they can be posted _ only 45 days before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the controls are similar to those found in planned
communities in Florida and elsewhere. Some even echo the restraints
imposed by Frederick Law Olmsted in 1868 when he designed
Riverside, Ill., widely regarded as the first modern planned town
and one of the models for Celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I point to Olmsted in saying that in a freewheeling society,
some interventions have to be made to control the public realm,''
said Stern, the architect. ``There were no bed checks by the owners
in Riverside, and there are none in Celebration. You are alone in
your living room.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is a fine line between harmony and conformity, and
at times the controls seem excessive and even silly. One of our
neighbors got a stern letter from the town manager when it was
discovered that her window curtains were red. She relented and the
curtains came down.
</P>
<P>
   Another couple fought town hall, which is really Disney since
there is no local government, over a demand that they remove two
etched-glass front doors. They refused, and the doors are still
there, an indication that there is flexibility even in this
controlled situation.
</P>
<P>
   We have learned to live with the restrictions, which are not
particularly onerous. What does remain a deeper irritation,
however, is the idea that a corporation exerts so much control over
our lives.
</P>
<P>
   The faith in Disney can be troubling. In the early days, many
residents seemed to expect the company to fix anything that went
wrong. Trouble with the construction of your house? Call Disney,
though the company isn't building the houses. Difficulties with the
progressive public school built here? Call Disney, though the
school is run by the county school district.
</P>
<P>
   But over the last few months, those attitudes seemed to have
undergone a transformation, for the better from our perspective.
The clearest example came last summer, when a large contingent of
parents staged a rebellion against some of the policies at
Celebration School, the K-12 facility that serves the town.
</P>
<P>
   The parents were concerned about the absence of a written
curriculum, textbooks and a clear assessment of students'
performance in the form of grades. In response, grades were
instituted for the upper classes and other changes were made to
restrain what many people regarded as a runaway experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Barnes, a young architect who has been involved with
Celebration almost from the start, said the intention was not to
create a perfect place, but to build a good place for people to
live by providing architecture and planning that promote social
interaction and a sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more residents take over, making it their town, the
better,'' he said. ``The more it becomes Celebration, rather than
Disney's Celebration, the better it gets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
