<HEADER>
A2784 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-BORDER-LAW-600&AMP;A     09-30 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-BORDER-LAW-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BORDER CONTROLS TAKE EFFECT BUT LITTLE EXPECTED TO CHANGE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY DePALMA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ A law that tightens America's borders by tracking the
millions of foreigners who enter each year takes effect on
Thursday. But border operations are apparently unlikely to change,
because U.S. immigration officials say they are not ready to handle
the job and Congress is not sure that it really wants the system
enforced, at least not now.
</P>
<P>
   Border states and the governments of Canada and Mexico strongly
opposed the measure after experts had warned that requiring even
simple checks could cause huge lineups at the borders and 17-hour
delays that would hurt businesses and cost millions of dollars in
delayed or lost trade.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican and Canadian officials had expected Congress to keep the
law from being put into effect on Oct. 1. But a stalemate developed
on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted in July to repeal the law, after the House had
voted to delay it one year. But the two bills could not be
reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   This week members of Congress considered several proposals, but
no quick compromise seemed in sight. Efforts will continue until
Congress breaks for the November elections. Legislators said the
law could be postponed even if it has already officially been put
into effect.
</P>
<P>
   But even when the law takes effect it cannot be enforced,
because the Immigration and Naturalization Service has made it
clear that it does not have the means to collect and process so
much information. At congressional hearings in July experts
estimated that in its first year a border documentation system
would generate as much information as the Library of Congress
holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told Congress early on that the technology and system did
not exist and would not be in place by Oct. 1,'' a spokesman for
the INS, Russell A. Bergeron Jr., said. ``And it's impossible to
project when such a system would be in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian executives and Mexican officials are relieved, but
remain upset about how the law was enacted. They say uncertainty
about what will occur can cause hardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make plans to build cars in Detroit based on parts
made in Canada that might be held up by 10 to 20 hours crossing the
border,'' said Peter Eide, head of labor law policy for the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce and chairman of Americans for Better Borders.
</P>
<P>
   The Better Borders group was started by people who are worried
about the effects of the new law.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are planned months and years in advance,'' Eide
said. ``But you can't make plans based on something Congress may or
may not do.''
</P>
<P>
   The minister of governmental affairs at the Mexican embassy in
Washington, Gustavo Mohar, said Mexico wanted the measure repealed.
``Regardless of the technology available,'' Mohar said, ``it
doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The dispute started with a measure buried in the Illegal
Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996.
Section 110 of the law required the immigration service to develop
an automated system to track the arrivals and departures of all
noncitizens, providing a way to identify immigrants who overstay
their visas.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials told Congress that 40 percent of the
estimated five and a half million illegal immigrants in the United
States might be overstaying their visas, but that pursuing them is
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The new law affects the Canadian and Mexican borders. But
opposition has been strongest in the north, where millions of
Canadians are accustomed to crossing without being checked.
</P>
<P>
   At least some members of Congress who voted for the bill
apparently thought that it would not apply to Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   But in a telephone interview from Washington, Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-Texas, who is chairman of the immigration subcommittee of the
Judiciary Committee, said, ``As far as I'm concerned we in the
House always intended this to apply to all aliens' coming into the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   At a training center in Glynco, Ga., the immigration service is
studying tracking foreigners, including cards with electromagnetic
stripes and electronic tags like those that let cars pay tolls
automatically.
</P>
<P>
   Smith questioned the INS' commitment to making the system work.
``This isn't the first time this administration has ignored or
dragged its feet on immigration law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that he was willing to consider a bill that would
delay the measure for more than a year, but that he opposed repeal
because he believed that a tracking system was necessary to hinder
drug dealers and terrorists who try to slip across the borders.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., who called Section 110 a
``bad law,'' said most legislators knew little about because it had
been ``slipped in'' after the immigration bill had been introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham sponsored the Senate bill to repeal the law at all
points of entry except airports. He said he would not support any
compromise that merely delayed observance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all we do is delay it two years,'' Abraham said, ``we're
going to be stuck with a system that causes massive problems or
we'll incur a lot of expenses developing a system that will be
abandoned after the first day it is implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
