u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QTR-MUTFUNDS-ART-NYT &LR;      09-30 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QTR-MUTFUNDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE MONEY WITHDRAWN LAST MONTH FROM STOCK FUNDS THAN WENT IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: QTR-DEALS, QTR-WINNERS) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on mutual fund flows in the quarter is being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors made net withdrawals of $11.2 billion from
equity mutual funds in August, the biggest outflow on record and
the first month in eight years that more money flowed out of stock
funds than went in, according to industry statistics released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Investment Company Institute, a trade group, confirmed
Wednesday what many fund companies had reported anecdotally since
the tumultuous final days of August, when the stock market fell 19
percent below its July peak. Two independent trackers of mutual
fund flows, AMG Data Services and Trim Tabs Financial Services,
also reported earlier this month that stock funds experienced net
withdrawals in August.
</P>
<P>
   For the mutual fund industry, the withdrawals ended an extended
streak during which the fund industry had expanded enormously. In
September 1990, the last month when investors made net withdrawals
from stock funds, those funds had $227 billion in assets, well
below the $308 billion in bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   Last year alone, stock funds received as much in new investments
as they had total assets in 1990 _ $227 billion. And even with the
August withdrawals, assets of stock funds had grown to nearly $2.4
trillion, more than double the $1.1 trillion invested in bond and
hybrid funds. In the first seven months of this year, stock funds
took in, on average, $20 billion a month in new investments.
</P>
<P>
   In September, however, investors appeared to have returned to
their old ways. With the worst of the volatility of late August and
early September beginning to subside, mutual fund companies have
again begun to see money flowing in, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual Fund Trim Tabs, based in Santa Rosa, Calif., estimates
that in September, stock funds took in net new investments of $19.3
billion. AMG, based in Arcata, Calif., also reported that stock
funds had received positive cash flows last month, although the
amount is uncertain because a significant number of fund companies
report their cash flows to AMG once a month.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some leading mutual fund companies, such as
Fidelity Investments and T. Rowe Price Associates, said investors
put money in stock funds during September after redeeming money in
August.
</P>
<P>
   As investors fled from stock funds in August, they sought out
the relative safety of bond funds and other more conservative
investments. The trade group reported that fixed-income funds added
$5.82 billion in net new investments in August, compared with net
new investments of $6.84 billion in July. Hybrid funds, which
spread their assets among stocks, bonds and cash investments, had
an outflow of $887.5 million in August, after adding $1.07 billion
in July.
</P>
<P>
   Money market funds also proved a sought-after haven for
investors, according to the data released Wednesday. The institute
said that money market funds received a record $50.94 billion in
net new investments in August, compared with $24.93 billion in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Equity fund managers also raised the amount of cash on hand in
their portfolios in August, to 6 percent of assets, on average,
from 5.2 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
   As the major stock market indexes headed lower in August, mutual
fund managers were said by traders at several large Wall Street
firms to be heavy sellers of stocks. That selling might have been
in anticipation of possible waves of redemptions from investors
alarmed by a rapidly declining stock market.
</P>
<P>
   One reason equity fund managers might have been forced to sell
was that they have been steadily slicing away at the amount of
spare cash in their portfolios over the last three years. The July
percentage of assets in cash was down from 7 percent two years ago
and nearly 13 percent in the fall of 1990, before stocks and stock
funds went on their eight-year tear.
</P>
<P>
   The recent streak is not the longest period of consecutive
months of positive cash flow ever recorded, however. For more than
15 years, from October 1954 through May 1970 _ a stretch that
coincided with a strong bull market in stocks _ investors similarly
made monthly deposits into equity mutual funds, according to the
Investment Company Institute.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, that streak was even longer. Before October
1954, the Investment Company Institute tracked fund flows on a
quarterly basis, rather than monthly; stock funds recorded positive
quarterly net flows of cash dating back to the first quarter of
1944.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund shareholders have also gone through extended periods
of disillusionment with equity funds. In the eight years from
November 1971 through October 1979, which includes the bear market
of 1973-74, investors each month took more money out of stock funds
than they put in.
</P>
<P>
   The data for monthly fund flows reported by the Investment
Company Institute measure new sales of funds minus reinvested
dividends and withdrawals, or redemptions, plus the net amount of
money switched between stock funds and other types of mutual funds,
mainly those investing in bonds or money markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
