<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION, FAMILY PLANNING ISSUES BOG DOWN SPENDING BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The continuing controversy over abortion and family
planning threatens to stall four federal spending bills as the
government's new fiscal year begins Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say contentious measures related to abortion and
contraception are the latest shots in a fusillade by a Republican
majority intent on chipping away at the constitutional right to
choose abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have come through the front door and the back door at
every opportunity to restrict or impede a woman's constitutional
right to choose as well as access to family planning and
reproductive health care,'' said Belle Taylor-McGhee, a spokeswoman
for the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor-McGhee said Congress voted nearly 100 times on issues of
reproductive choice since the Republicans took control of both
houses of Congress in 1995. She said abortion-rights advocates lost
all but 14 votes.
</P>
<P>
   A major stumbling block in the spending bill for the Agriculture
Department is a provision that would ban the Food and Drug
Administration from testing or developing drugs that chemically
induce abortion, such as the French abortion drug RU-486, also
known as mifepristone.
</P>
<P>
   A House version of the agriculture spending bill includes the
prohibition, while the Senate version does not. Clinton said he
would veto the bill if the ban is included.
</P>
<P>
   The treasury-postal spending bill is bogged down by the fiery
issue of whether federal employee health plans should be required
to pay for contraceptives if the plans cover other prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Both chambers have included provisions that would require
contraceptive coverage, although the House would give health care
providers the chance to opt out for religious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill, supported by Sens. Olympia J. Snowe, R-Maine,
and Harry Reid, D-Nev., requires the health plans to cover oral
contraceptives, diaphragms, the long-term birth-control implant
Norplant, IUDs and depo-Provera, an injectable contraceptive.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats such as Reps. Nita M. Lowey of New York and Nancy L.
Johnson of Connecticut have led the charge for contraception
coverage, but they face strong opposition from Rep. Christopher H.
Smith, R-N.J., as well as Republican Sens. Don Nickles of Oklahoma,
Sam Brownback of Kansas and Dan Coats of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill for foreign operations is stalled in
House-Senate conference committee because of a perennial roadblock
over abortion. It is the fourth year in a row that disagreements
over abortion restrictions for international family-planning groups
have delayed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Congress has essentially killed such provisions in
the face of threatened vetoes from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would prohibit any international family-planning
organization from receiving federal funding if its employees lobby
or try to educate on the issue of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Another controversy arises in the House spending plan for the
departments of Labor, Health and Human Services, and Education.
That bill includes a provision by Rep. Ernest Istook Jr., R-Okla.,
that would require parents be notified five business days before
minors could receive contraceptives from federally funded
family-planning clinics.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, groups that favor family planning have
succeeded in removing the consent requirement, but this is the
first time the provision has been included.
</P>
<P>
   With Congress scheduled to leave town at the end of next week,
``it's really up to the Republican leadership'' to work out the
conflicts on abortion-related language, said Elizabeth Morra, the
House Appropriations Committee spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Delays in approval of the spending bills are not likely to cause
government shutdowns because Congress two weeks ago passed an
interim budget _ known as a continuing resolution _ to keep the
federal government running.
</P>
<P>
   Until the differences between the House and Senate can be ironed
out, the bills cannot be sent to President Clinton for
consideration. The 1999 federal fiscal year began Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
