<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A STADIUM FOR EVERYONE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Borough president of the Bronx was up early on
Tuesday. A baseball season so sweet it seemed like a child's
fantasy was about to enter the crucial playoff stage. The Yankees,
the sweetest of teams in this sweetest of seasons, would take the
field Tuesday night against the Rangers of Texas. In Yankee
Stadium. In the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have drawn more fans to the stadium this year than
ever before. They won more games in the regular season than any
other team in American League history. They have created a new
generation of Yankee fanatics _ late-20th-century fans who cheer
the likes of Jeter and Williams and Wells and Martinez the way
old-timers once rooted for Ruth and Gehrig and DiMaggio and Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   The Borough president is Fernando Ferrer, and early Tuesday
morning, with the autumn air cool and hinting of many World Series
to come, he was outside the stadium showing reporters a plan that
he hopes will keep the principal owner of the Yankees from spoiling
this moment of glory in the city's cultural history by deciding
that his team should pack its gear and abandon the stadium and the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yankee Stadium is the most historic baseball venue in
America,'' said Ferrer. ``The Yankees belong here.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no rancor in his tone, no hint of anger or
self-righteousness. But there was a clear sense of the devastation,
both physical and emotional, that would befall a large section of
the Bronx if the Yankees were to flee.
</P>
<P>
   So he's got this plan, which incorporates and refines a number
of prior proposals and adds some solid new ones. For starters,
there are plenty of goodies for the fans and the Yankees owner,
George Steinbrenner, who has complained loudly and frequently about
the lack of amenities at the aging stadium, the shortage of parking
facilities, the traffic jams before and after games and the
condition of nearby neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would completely modernize the stadium, turning it into
a more comfortable, more intimate 50,000-seat facility with 120 of
the phenomenally lucrative luxury boxes that Steinbrenner craves.
Parking would be available for more than 10,000 cars. Roads and
ramps leading to and from the stadium would be redesigned to ease
the flow of traffic. And a new Metro-North commuter rail station
would be built practically adjacent to the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   There's more. One of the objections to sinking huge amounts of
public money into stadiums for team owners who are already very
wealthy is that there is little in the way of benefits that are
returned to the community. Under Ferrer's plan, real and
substantial improvements would be made to the area surrounding the
stadium, including a complete transformation of the Bronx Terminal
Market, a depressing 32-acre waterfront slum that is underused in
the daytime and becomes a playground for prostitutes, johns and
drug addicts at night.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer said he would like to build upon the excitement and good
will generated by the Yankees and the rest of Major League Baseball
this year. A rebuilt Yankee Stadium as the sparkling hub of an area
with new retail outlets, themed restaurants, batting cages and
other sports-related facilities would, in his view, be a boon to
the team, the fans and the residents of the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief visit to the Bronx Terminal Market, Ferrer said,
``You want Camden Yards?'' He was referring to the spectacular
success of the stadium complex built in Baltimore for the Orioles.
``Well, you've got it right here.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Ferrer's proposal, known as ``Yankee Village,'' ever see
the light of day? Could it actually happen? Well, parts of it sure
could. Hardly anyone other than Steinbrenner and his good friend
Rudolph Giuliani is in favor of relocating the Yankees into a
stadium that would cost more than $1 billion on the West Side of
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   And despite years of propaganda, there is still no evidence of a
serious plan to lure the Yankees to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   So it's looking more and more as if the Bronx is the answer. And
Ferrer contends that the total cost of his plan is less than half
that of a West Side stadium.
</P>
<P>
   If someone has a better idea, let's hear it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
