<SLUG> BC-GLENN-GOODBYE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR JOHN GLENN, NO LONG GOODBYE TO THE SENATE
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John Glenn has no time for long goodbyes.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Democrat's 24 years in office winked out this morning
amid a flurry of new obligations as he boarded a plane for Houston
to begin the final push in astronaut training before his space
shuttle flight Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   This week has been stacked so heavily with television
interviews, autograph requests, preparations for a long Friday in a
shuttle simulator and what probably was his final vote in the U.S.
Senate Tuesday night, that Glenn never even got a chance to say
farewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had planned to make sort of a farewell speech on the Senate
floor, but I've been so busy with everything else I just didn't
have time to sit down and put it all together,'' Glenn told a group
of Ohio reporters Wednesday. ``And I did want to do that, and
that's one thing I regret.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's not complaining. He's barely even reminiscing right
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'll miss it, sure,'' Glenn said. ``But, you know, you
move on to other things, and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, 77, has moved on to the very thing he left 38 years ago
when he chose to pursue a career in politics: the space program.
His nine days in orbit, just his second space flight despite being
known worldwide as an astronaut, will make him the oldest man ever
in space.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Glenn may not be done with his Senate duties,
because he has promised to return if Democratic leaders require his
presence on an ``important'' or ``tight'' vote. But with the
session scheduled to end for the year on Oct. 9, the docket will be
loaded primarily with essential budget bills that aren't likely to
involve margins thin enough to necessitate Glenn's presence. His
final vote was cast on a procedural matter involving a bill to put
a moratorium on letting states tax Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he missed a retirement dinner honoring him and Sens.
Wendell Ford of Kentucky and Dale Bumpers of Arkansas, two fellow
Democrats who entered the Senate with him in 1974. Glenn couldn't
attend because he was at the Johnson Space Center in Houston, where
NASA doctors were doing extensive tests to establish baseline
physical data that will be used for comparison when he returns from
his nine days in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means I was giving blood two, sometimes three times a
day..'' Glenn said. ``(But, they) had set it up for a satellite
feed from Houston, so I was in the studio there at NASA and I
participated in the dinner and made some remarks.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, Glenn wouldn't contemplate his place in the world as
a national role model, even as he talked about the scheduling
strain of ending a historic career to embark on a historic
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've reflected on what it means to have for the kids, for
young people in particular, to have somebody that they look up to.
But as far as that relates to me personally, no, I have not. ...No,
you just get up every day and try and do what you're going to do
for that day and that's it. However people observe that, that's up
to them.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
