<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2797 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPOSTERS-FILM-ART-2T     09-30 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPOSTERS-FILM-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 FOR STANLEY TUCCI, DOING IT ALL NOW IS ENTIRELY IN CHARACTER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Stanley Tucci is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Karen Durbin is the film critic for Mirabella magazine 
By KAREN DURBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seated in a tiny self-service cafe on Sullivan
Street, Stanley Tucci doesn't look like a man who, at 37, has
achieved the kind of career control most actors only dream about.
He's gazing in consternation at the modest vegetarian sandwich
displayed before him on a piece of white bakery paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe seven dollars for this?'' he asks. ``What's
happened to the Village?''
</P>
<P>
   Uptown prices happened to Greenwich Village a long time ago, but
Tucci's budget-consciousness is a reminder that while he may be one
of the most sought after character actors around these days, he is
also an independent filmmaker, and independent filmmakers know the
value of a sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   He gets his money's worth with ``The Impostors,'' an ebullient
new slapstick comedy that opened Friday. Tucci not only wrote,
directed and produced the moderately priced film; he also stars in
it with Oliver Platt.
</P>
<P>
   They play two down-at-the-heels actors who accidentally stow
away on a luxury liner. This is Tucci's sophomore effort, following
``Big Night,'' the surprise 1996 hit he co-wrote with his cousin
and co-directed with Campbell Scott.
</P>
<P>
   A bittersweet tale of a gourmet Italian restaurant on the Jersey
shore that fails in the spaghetti-and-meatballs 50s, ``Big Night''
was an unlikely candidate for box office success. ``The Impostors''
looks like a surer bet, but who knows? It's neither mean nor
cynical, and for all the physical clowning, there's not a bodily
fluid in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The film is as blissfully out of sync with the times as its
predecessor. Tucci wants it to succeed, but he has organized his
career for maximum disaster insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say I direct one movie and it's a bomb _ it could take years
to do another one,'' he says. ``I'm lucky because I'm able to do a
few different things. I can write something, I can go act in
something.'' He has. ``The Alarmist,'' a dark, funny comedy
starring Tucci and David Arquette, is to open October 16.
</P>
<P>
   And next month HBO will air its highly touted biopic of Walter
Winchell, directed by Paul Mazursky, with an indelible performance
by ucci as the controversial gossip columnist who wielded a bully's
power in the 40s and 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Luck has something to do with the place Tucci is making for
himself, but not that much. A graduate of the acting program at the
State University of New York at Purchase, he first became known for
playing silky villains on television.
</P>
<P>
   Two were especially memorable. In ``Wiseguys'' he was the young,
Harvard-educated mafioso Ricky Pinzolo, who wore black turtlenecks
and squeezed his own vegetable juice when he wasn't taking over the
garment industry and killing anyone who got in his way.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci was 26 at the time, and chillingly good. In 1996, he
played the decadent, baleful socialite-suspect Richard Cross in
``Murder One,'' the Stephen Bochco series that followed a fictional
trial over an entire season. The role won Tucci an Emmy nomination
and many fans, as numerous web sites attest.
</P>
<P>
   That success coincided with the release of ``Big Night,''
creating the synergy needed to kick his career up to a level
commensurate with his talent. But it was Tucci who did the kicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I formed a production company is that I
don't trust anybody to employ me,'' he says. ``Why would I?'' Good
question. In 1995, after a dozen years of steady work in movies,
theater and television, Tucci's career stalled. ``There was this
lull,'' he says, dropping his voice and glancing around the room,
as if the lull might be lurking nearby, waiting to pounce. ``I
couldn't get arrested before ``Big Night,'' if you want to know the
truth. And I had just bought a house. It was awful.''
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of ``Big Night,'' Tucci pounced himself. The
production company he founded with his partner, Beth Alexander,
made deals with Fox Searchlight and October Films. As with ``The
Impostors,'' the terms include creative freedom. ``Otherwise,
what's the point? If you don't trust me, don't give me the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucci more closely resembles Groucho Marx than Karl, but he's
not the first actor to try to seize the means of production. ``I
wanted to be prepared for when I get older,'' he says, ``and people
would say, `Oh well, we're tired of Stanley, we've seen him enough.
He's so bald. He's so ethnic.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He's also so funny. Given his comic gifts, it's easy to imagine
him following a career path similar to Woody Allen's _ or Chaplin's
or Keaton's _ writing and directing films with himself as the star.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion all but gives him the bends. ``Write a movie just
for myself?'' he asks sharply. ``But it's so much more interesting
when you have other people there.'' Warming to his theme, he
exclaims: ``Actors are so wonderful! I want to be able to write for
them all. And work with them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk like that could get a person hooted out of the Directors
Guild, but Tucci seems to mean it. With the casts of his first two
films, he has already made a good start, and ``The Impostors'' is
both a homage to the classic comedies of Laurel and Hardy and the
Marx brothers and a celebration of acting itself.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci belongs to a loose circle of friends that includes some of
the most talented actors in New York, among them Platt, Scott, Hope
Davis and Lili Taylor, all of whom appear to hilarious, sometimes
surprising effect in ``The Impostors.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Scott a closet Nazi? And Hope Davis as the moody young
spinster while Lili Taylor plays the madly efficient stewardess
Scott so sternly craves? ``Normally, you'd cast Hope Davis in that
role,'' says Mr. Tucci, ``and you'd give Lili Hope's part. It's
much more interesting to have it the other way around. Lili is
really very funny, sometimes funnier than she knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davis, who got to know Tucci when he played her elusive
husband in ``Daytrippers,'' says: ``You'd be surprised how many
directors just put you in a scene and leave all the work up to you.
Stanley knows that decent actors want direction. Often when you
finish a scene, he'll yell, `Keep rolling,' and he'll be shouting
all sorts of ideas _ `Try this! Try this!'
</P>
<P>
   All the while he's laughing, and you think, `How can they use
any of this with Stanley making all that noise?' He's a joyous
person. He's no shrinking violet. But he also believes in what he's
doing. I wouldn't trust him otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan Dunsky, who wrote and directed ``The Alarmist,'' dealt with
Tucci from the other side of the camera. In the film, Tucci plays
Heinrich Grigoris, the distinctly shady head of a firm that sells
home security systems (the company logo features snarling Dobermans
neatly labeled ``Safety'' and ``Peace of Mind''); Arquette is his
bright-eyed protege.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heinrich obviously has a dark side,'' says Dunsky. ``He's
conniving and nefarious, but he has this tremendous sweetness and a
weird integrity. Everyone depends on him, and he loves the young
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The part feels more closely tailored for Tucci than any he's
written himself, combining his knack for villainy with the faint
touch of goofiness that inflects his comic persona. Yet he never
dominates the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a wonderful way of bringing other actors into a
scene,'' Dunsky says. As a consequence, ``The Alarmist,'' like
Tucci's own films, is an ensemble piece that showcases everybody's
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci looks terribly L.A. these days _ or at least East Village
_ with his dark, thinning hair bleached palest yellow and smartly
trimmed in a latter-day Caligula cut. He says it's just a leftover
from playing Puck this summer in a film version of ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream'' alongside Michelle Pfeiffer, Kevin Kline, Calista
Flockhart, Rupert Everett and Sophie Marceau.
</P>
<P>
   The film, directed by Michael Hoffman for release next spring,
capped 18 months of nonstop work for Tucci, who returned from
location in Tuscany and promptly fell victim to a short, nasty bout
of Lyme disease.
</P>
<P>
   Although he says he'd like to direct a big Hollywood-scale movie
some day, Tucci really lights up when he talks about a script he's
working on for October Films, based on ``Joe Gould's Secret,'' a
famous two-part 1964 New Yorker profile by Joseph Mitchell, the
legendary chronicler of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The film will focus on the relationship between Mitchell and the
eccentric 1940s bohemian his profile immortalized. While it hardly
sounds like the next ``Titanic,'' there's anticipatory buzz about
the project in New York literary circles, and he is hopeful that
Ian Holm, who did a nice, gritty turn in ``Big Night,'' will play
Joe Gould. Asked if he would play Joseph Mitchell, Tucci says he
thinks he wants to give the role to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Time spent with Tucci lays bare the reason for his lack of
self-absorption: He's too interested in everything else. He has a
passion for modern art, particularly the Abstract Expressionists;
he also paints for pleasure and to clear his head. ``I think very
visually,'' he says, ``and when I come back to my work, suddenly I
see relationships that weren't there before. It opens all these
little windows.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the Katonah, N.Y., area, where he grew up and now
lives with his wife, Kate, and two stepchildren, soon leads Tucci
to discuss New York City's extraordinary gravity-based, fresh-water
reservoir system, a subject on which he waxes ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it sounds silly,'' he says, ``but those reservoirs have
such a huge effect on so much. There's a depth to them, no pun
intended. Well, it's a good metaphor: they're something you draw
from.''
</P>
<P>
   He describes walking through one of the drained reservoirs as a
kid. ``You'd find coins and knives and forks and plates. You'd see
the foundations of the old farms that used to be there, the houses
and barns, and where they cut three or four trees in a row for
somebody's driveway.'' He paints the scene as vividly as any movie.
One can see it now: Stanley Tucci Presents: ``Reservoir!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I like that,'' he says. ``I think it could be a hit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
