<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-DEPUTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREATMENT OF FORMER DEPUTY LEADER UNSETTLES MALAYSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
suggested Wednesday that his jailed former deputy, Anwar Ibrahim,
might have punched himself in the eye in order to accuse police of
beating him.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to some quarters, this is not something that is
impossible as he will gain much mileage if it can be shown that he
is being tortured by police,'' Mahathir said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Anwar's statement in court on Tuesday that he had
been beaten by his jailers would be investigated, but he sounded
skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? Why was he assaulted, if at all he was beaten?'' Mahathir
said. ``This is to his advantage as it is now seen that he has
already experienced what he had forecast at the very outset. His
prediction was, if arrested he'll be tortured.''
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal and subsequent arrest of Anwar, 51, who had been
the deputy prime minister and designated successor of Mahathir, 72,
has stirred unexpectedly widespread anger in what had been seen as
one of Southeast Asia's most politically stable nations.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's remarks Wednesday appeared to inflame the
growing condemnation here and abroad of the treatment of Anwar, who
appeared in court for a second day Wednesday with bruises on his
left eye, his neck and his arms.
</P>
<P>
   The Bar Council of Malaysia together with several opposition
politicians spoke out Wednesday to condemn what they said was the
beating of Anwar.
</P>
<P>
   A local human rights group called Suaram said the prime
minister's remarks went ``against every basic principle of sanity
and logic.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's statement was met with puzzlement by some
people here, who are already confused and distressed by this sudden
government turmoil. Some, obedient by habit, nodded their heads and
murmured that the man they call ``Dr. M'' might well be right.
</P>
<P>
   Others seemed outraged. ``He thinks the people are stupid,
accusing Anwar of this and that,'' said a restaurant worker. ``Our
people are not stupid, I can tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom Wednesday, Anwar wiped his eye with a
handkerchief and pinched his waistband to signal that he had lost
weight since he was arrested 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded not guilty to a fifth and final charge of performing
illegal sex acts. On Tuesday he pleaded not guilty to four charges
of sodomy and five charges of corruption _ all but one of which
also related to the sodomy charges.
</P>
<P>
   After much talk about sedition and the leaking of secret
documents, as well as of capers with prostitutes and transvestites,
all but one of the 10 charges against Anwar boil down to
allegations of four instances of homosexual acts, which are illegal
here.
</P>
<P>
   The one exception is a charge that Anwar tried to use his
influence to deflect corruption charges against an aide.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations of homosexual acts were weakened Tuesday when
two men with whom Anwar was accused of having sex appealed their
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's contention that he had been beaten received support
Wednesday after an independent doctor was allowed to examine him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my expert opinion, Anwar Ibrahim was assaulted over the
left forehead and neck and received blunt trauma that resulted in
residual bruises over the left upper and lower eyelids,'' the
doctor, Ahmad Shukri Mohamed, said in a written report after
examining him on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom Wednesday, Anwar slipped reporters a scribbled
note.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malaysians should be made aware,'' Anwar said, ``of the
deterioration of their fundamental liberties and the dictatorial
acts of Dr. M.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2801 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-30 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: OCTOBER SURPRISE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has invited Benjamin Netanyahu
and Yasser Arafat back to Washington about two weeks before
Election Day. At that time they are expected to reach interim
agreement on another transfer of West Bank land, with Palestinian
reciprocity, and thereby begin final-settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
   I asked the Israeli prime minister if he was familiar with the
American political term ``October surprise'' _ a presidential
announcement designed to influence an election. Bibi seemed
genuinely taken aback: ``I checked my schedule to make sure it
didn't conflict with Succoth,'' he replied, referring to the Jewish
fall festival. ``I wasn't thinking about your elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton was, of course; progress toward peacemaking would
enhance his standing the week before voters choose representatives
who will vote on impeachment. His timing, after a long stalemate,
is hardly coincidental, nor is his possible choice of site: Camp
David, scene of President Carter's only historic legacy.
</P>
<P>
   But the ability to fine-tune the making of world news is an edge
all our campaigning presidents have. More to the point is what lies
behind what Secretary Madeleine Albright calls ``the new urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   For Arafat, urgency comes from his failure to get America to
pressure Israel to cede almost all the West Bank to him on the
installment plan before he makes his final-settlement demand to
partition Jerusalem. His threat to declare a Palestinian state next
May backfired when it became evident that Israel alone would then
decide on borders, annexing what it needed for security.
</P>
<P>
   For Netanyahu, who successfully resisted the salami-slicing of
his bargaining position, urgency to make peace on the local front
is strategic: Iran is building long-range missiles and nuclear
devices, Iraq is shutting down U.N. inspections. He sees
mass-destruction technologists ``gushing'' out of crumbling Russia
to rogue nations, and up to a million more Jewish immigrants to be
absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, the urgency is not only to divert attention from
impeachment, but to make history in a hurry _ or at least to be at
center stage when it is made.
</P>
<P>
   What good end may this confluence of urgencies produce?
</P>
<P>
   The president has learned from his diplomatic blunder. Israel
properly ignored his diktat of an additional 13 percent salami
slice of the West Bank because it was too loosely connected to
reciprocal PLO action against Hamas and Hezbollah terrorism, and
because interim handovers stole the land sweetener needed to close
the final deal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has changed his proposal to 10 percent plus 3 percent
set aside in what is euphemized as a ``nature preserve'' _ in
effect, buffer zones with joint patrols to deny bases to terrorists
within hand-held-missile distance of Tel Aviv, airports and Israeli
(and Palestinian) settlements. Both sides find this acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   That should bring us through Succoth next week to Camp David 1{.
Clinton, though allergic to the Catoctin Mountain air, is primed to
labor mightily there to announce what will be headlined as a
breakthrough: the launch of final-settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
   As the punch line about the Jewish matchmaker goes, ``Now for
the hard part.'' For the Israelis, it will mean giving up more of
the West Bank than many think is wise for the small nation's
territorial security, and risking the conferring of statehood on an
ally of Saddam. For Palestinians, it will mean permanent crackdown
on terror and renunciation of unrealistic and inflammatory claims
on part of Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, a secure final settlement means a new look at
coordinated missile defense. He told Netanyahu he'd been thinking
about it. Israel's Arrow antimissile missile shows promise, but its
U.S.-financed ``bullet to hit a bullet'' is a last line of defense
against weaponry now threatening Israel and American forces near
the Persian Gulf _ and soon to threaten Paris and New York. Only
future U.S. space technology and defense investment will be able to
stop nuclear missiles in their launch phase.
</P>
<P>
   A facile facilitator will do for Camp David 1{. An American
president with a grasp of both the local and strategic security
needs of Israelis and Arabs is required to clamp together a
historic handshake at Camp David II.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
