<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-REFLECT-BOS &LR;      09-30 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-REFLECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS PONDER THE HISTORICAL MEANING OF THE YOM KIPPUR WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ On Yom Kippur, Israel's streets are, on this one
day, forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   As Israelis observed the Day of Atonement Wednesday, the
ultra-Orthodox and even the adamantly secular, all seemed to be
adhering to the custom of not driving.
</P>
<P>
   The usually hellish streets of the Holy City and the busy
boulevards of Tel Aviv were filled with people strolling.
</P>
<P>
   The religious, dressed in white, fasted from sundown Tuesday to
sundown Wednesday, and walked to and from synagogue, praying and
imbibing the purifying spirit of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Secular Israelis, who make up the vast majority of the country,
tended to take to the wide-open streets not to pray, but to saunter
and chat with neighbors or to ride bicycles, skateboards and roller
blades.
</P>
<P>
   All shops and businesses are shuttered. Buses and trains stop
running. There are no international or domestic flights. Seaports
are closed. Border crossings are sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Here in a nation increasingly divided along religious and
secular lines, Yom Kippur is observed as a time of soul searching
by just about everyone, and each in his or her own way. And this
year, the day has taken on a unique form of collective
introspection as it marks the 25th anniversary of the Yom Kippur
War.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 6, 1973, Israel's Arab neighbors attacked on the onset
of the holy day as it fell on the Jewish calendar that year. Almost
2,700 Israeli soldiers died in more than two weeks of fighting,
undermining the belief of Israelis that their country had the most
powerful military in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Yakov Savir, 50, remembered the day in 1973 that he left his
kibbutz near the Jordan border to board an Egged bus that would
take him to the front lines of battle along with thousands of other
reservists who were rushed into fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the signs were around us then and we didn't see them,'' he
said Wednesday as he strolled with his wife along Jerusalem's Ben
Yehuda Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think now all the signs are around us again, and we still
don't see them. The fight now is between the religious and the
secular and the deep divide over the issue of peace,'' said Savir,
who describes himself as ``agnostic on religion, but a believer in
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The price we will pay if we seize on making the peace work now
will be cheap in comparison to the price we will pay if we have
another war,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's newspapers on Tuesday were filled with special
supplements commemorating the 25th anniversary of the war. The
daily tabloid Ma'ariv carried an 80-page section devoted entirely
to introspective and analytical essays surrounded by photographs of
the war, and the leaders, Prime Minister Golda Meir and Defense
Minister Moshe Dayan, who were caught unprepared. The more liberal
broadsheet, Ha'aretz, carried several columns which seemed to make
the case that not only was Israel ill-prepared for war in 1973, it
had also failed to seize earlier opportunities to make peace with
its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Yoel Marcus, in a piece sharply critical of what he feels is
Prime Minister Netanyahu's intransigence in the currently
deadlocked Israeli-Palestinian peace process, wrote, ``As we have
learned from the blindness that led to the Yom Kippur War, history
does not stand still in our region while the leaders of Israel play
chess with themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem's Old City at the Western Wall, Judaism's holiest
site, the prayers of tens of thousands of Jews echoed off the pink
Herodian stone in the fading light of day just before the fast was
broken. In the nearby neighborhood of Mea Shearim, candle light
flickered inside synagogues as Orthodox men rocked back and forth
as they prayed.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Susser, 25, a yeshiva student wearing a white robe over
his black clothing, said, ``Today is a day we are purified of our
sins. And as a people, we look at the 25th anniversary of the war
as God's miracle. Even though we were not ready, we had a victory.
God showed us on that day, He takes care of us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the distance, there was the mournful sound of the ``shofar,''
or ram's horn, an ancient Jewish tradition that symbolically opens
the skies for prayer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
