<HEADLINE>
FOSSIL WORMHOLES SHED LIGHT ON EVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Worms may be among the lowliest of creatures, but the discovery
of a bunch of wormholes being reported this week could lead to a
drastic rewriting of the history of life on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   To the untrained eye, the new evidence just looks like a hole in
the ground or, actually, a whole network of holes in the ground.
But a team of paleontologists says these burrows were left by worms
over a billion years ago, which could make them the key evidence to
demolish a central belief about when complex creatures first
evolved.
</P>
<P>
   By almost doubling the age at which the first multicelled
animals appeared on Earth, the new find could prove that the
appearance of complicated life forms out of what had been a
menagerie of single-celled creatures did not happen suddenly about
540 million years ago, in what biologists call the Cambrian
explosion _ considered the ``Big Bang'' of evolution. Instead, the
complexification of life was really more of a slow sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   The traces of wormholes, in rocks that date to about 1.1 billion
years ago, were found in central India, in beds of sandstone that
formed when that area was covered by a shallow sea. The discovery
by researchers Adolf Seilacher and Friedrich Pfluger of Yale
University and the University of Tubingen, and Pradip Bose of
Jadavpur University in Calcutta, is being reported this week in the
journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's true, it's staggering,'' said paleontologist Charles
Marshall of the University of California, Los Angeles, in a
commentary accompanying the Science paper. But because the evidence
is indirect _ consisting only of burrows apparently left by the
worms, rather than any trace of the animals themselves _ it is
likely to be controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, no fossil traces of multicelled animals, with
muscles, guts or other distinctive anatomical features, had been
found in rocks more than 540 million years old, but in the last few
years a few discoveries _ including some of worm burrows _ have
pushed back the first appearance of complex animals to about 580
million years. The new find, if confirmed, would almost double the
known age of the first appearance of animals with more than one
cell and with differentiated body structures.
</P>
<P>
   The worms responsible for the burrows found in the Chorhat
sandstone, formed from sand washed in by storms in a shallow sea
1.1 billion years ago, must have been fairly complex, the authors
say. The type of burrows they made, which are about the width of a
soda straw, have a structure similar to those made by modern worms
that propel themselves along by peristalsis, rhythmic muscle
contractions similar to those that propel food through a digestive
tract. Such worms are far more complex in body structure than more
primitive flatworms and roundworms, suggesting that worms had
already undergone a significant period of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   The new find lends strong support to evidence gathered by a
completely different kind of analysis: the study of differences in
the genetic structure of different animal groups, which can provide
a kind of ``molecular clock'' to estimate when certain kinds of
animals first evolved. Some molecular biologists have contended for
several years that the first multicellular animals must have
originated 1.2 billion years ago _ but that conclusion faced
widespread skepticism, largely because no one could find any fossil
evidence to support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The molecular work has long established that most of the
(animal) groups we know in the fossil record do go back that far,''
said David Raup, a professor of paleontology emeritus at the
University of Chicago, in an interview Wednesday. The new find
``would be good confirmation for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Indirect fossil evidence, such as the burrows found by this
team, have always been controversial because some natural,
non-biological processes can produce similar structures. The debate
is similar to arguments over the significance of tiny shapes found
two years ago in a meteorite from Mars, which some scientists have
interpreted as evidence of Martian microbial life, but others
contend could have been produced by non-biological chemical
processes.
</P>
<P>
   But the team reporting its research this week went to great
pains to analyze the details of the burrows' structure, and say
they have all but ruled out other possible explanations. the
burrows ``can only be explained as the works of macroscopic
wormlike animals,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Some others are not so sure. Paleontologist Bruce Runnegar of
UCLA, who specializes in early life, said that ``this is not the
smoking gun... I'd say the jury is out.''
</P>
<P>
   Raup agreed that ``It's easy to get fooled,'' but he said he is
familiar with the work of Seilacher and said he would be ``harder
to fool than anybody.... He knows more about worm trails than
anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
