<SLUG> BC-GONZALEZ-RETIRES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SUPREME COURT JUSTICE RAUL A. GONZALEZ TO RETIRE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Justice Raul A. Gonzalez, a former migrant farm worker
who became the first Hispanic to win a statewide election in Texas,
announced Wednesday that he will step down from the Texas Supreme
Court on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The court's senior member, Gonzalez also is the only Hispanic to
ever serve on the court and is one of only two Democrats remaining
on the nine-member panel.
</P>
<P>
   His midterm retirement will give Gov. George W. Bush the
opportunity to appoint another Republican to the court and give the
GOP all the court's seats if Democratic Justice Rose Spector loses
her re-election bid on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Spector faces a strong challenge from Republican Harriet
O'Neill, a justice on the 14th Court of Appeals in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, 58, was appointed to the Supreme Court, the state's
highest civil court, by Gov. Mark White to fill a vacancy in 1984.
He had previously been a state district judge in Brownsville,
Texas, and a member of the 13th Court of Appeals in Corpus Christi,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez won his first election to the Supreme Court in 1986,
making history as the first Hispanic elected to statewide office in
Texas. Two years remain in his current term.
</P>
<P>
   In 20 years as a judge, Gonzalez said, he has ``attempted to
uphold the public trust by making decisions without fear or
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he added, ``It is time for me to move on to other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's partly a case of burnout, partly an opportunity for
financial awards out of government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez and his wife, Dora, plan to remain in Austin, where he
is considering several options for work in mediation and
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Gonzalez worked with his parents, harvesting crops
as far away as California and Washington state before graduating
from high school in Weslaco in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his background and party affiliation, Gonzalez has been
one of the Supreme Court's most conservative justices during an
often-rocky period of major philosophical and partisan changes.
</P>
<P>
   When he joined the court 14 years ago, all its members were
Democrats, and plaintiffs' lawyers, who heavily supported the
campaigns of successful judicial candidates, were influential. The
court majority, with Gonzalez often dissenting, issued major
decisions upholding large damage awards for consumers against
businesses, insurance companies and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the pendulum _ pushed by the retirements of Democratic
justices and large campaign contributions from doctors, business
interests and defense lawyers _ began to swing the other way, and
Gonzalez almost became a wartime casualty.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' lawyers, women's advocates and even some Hispanic
leaders in his own party tried to unseat Gonzalez in 1994 by
backing challenger Rene Haas, a trial lawyer from Corpus Christi,
in the Democratic primary. Gonzalez, heavily supported by political
contributions from doctors and business interests, won, but only
after one of the most bitterly contested elections in Texas
judicial history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought about tucking it in (quitting) then,'' said George
Christian, a consultant for the Texas Civil Justice League, a
business group that strongly supports the high court's
conservatism. ``He found it very distasteful to have to go out and
raise that kind of money. He is a man of great integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt Borges, who monitors the Supreme Court for Texas Watch, a
consumer advocacy group, said he's not sure what Gonzalez's
retirement will mean for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, he was the conservative Democrat,'' Borges
said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, Gonzalez also was independent, often dissenting
after conservatives regained control of the high court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a loose cannon. You could never tell where he would
come in on a case,'' Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, a deeply religious man, was strongly outspoken against
abortion during his tenure on the court, although the panel rarely
addressed that issue.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Gonzalez wrote a concurring and dissenting opinion
in the court's 6-3 decision upholding a $1.2 million damage award
against anti-abortion protesters who staged large demonstrations at
Houston abortion clinics during and after the 1992 Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez approved the monetary damages, but he believed that the
majority's order restricting ``sidewalk counseling'' by
anti-abortion protesters outside abortion clinics was an
unnecessary restriction on free speech.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion, Gonzalez also warned protesters that
anti-abortion violence and vandalism are counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every intimidating gesture or hateful utterance deafens the
public's collective ear to pro-life (anti-abortion) appeals about
the dignity of the unborn,'' he wrote. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
