<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SURPLUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON UNVEILS BUDGET SURPLUS, SETS OFF SQUABBLE WITH REPUBLICANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, marking a new era in government,
unveiled Wednesday the first budget surplus in a generation and set
off a squabble with Republicans over who deserves praise for the
extra $70 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the partisan sniping, the fact remained that after 29
years of budget deficits that sometimes reached $300 billion a
year, the federal government had money left over as the 1998 fiscal
year ended at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The figure quoted by the administration was based on
projections. It will take several weeks for all accounts for the
fiscal year to be tabulated.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the political battle is what to do with the extra cash.
Clinton warned Republicans not to pass an $80 billion tax cut until
Congress overhauls the Social Security system, and Republicans
complained the president was trying to spend the money on items
such as the census count or troop deployment in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest surplus on record and, as a percentage of
our economy, the largest one since the 1950s. Our economy is the
strongest in a generation. That's why we see the deficit clock has
become a surplus clock,'' Clinton said, a small billboard behind
him flashing ``surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton invited several former members of Congress, including
Houston Democrat Mike Andrews, who voted for his 1993 deficit
reduction plan. The vote cost some lawmakers their seats in 1994
because the spending blueprint contained tax increases. Clinton
said without their votes for his measure, which passed despite
opposition from every Republican, the surplus would not be reality.
</P>
<P>
   The president said his 1993 plan reduced the deficit by 90
percent while the 1997 bipartisan budget accord with congressional
leaders finished the job and will lead to surpluses for several
years to come. The Congressional Budget Office predicts $1.6
trillion in surpluses over the next 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a landmark achievement not just for those in the room
who have played a role in it, but indeed for all the American
people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, was one of the first Republicans to
criticize Clinton, saying it was the new Republican majority that
took control in 1995 that pushed for the balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point I'd like to make is if you want to know who led, the
American people led. Those who should be given credit here, and I
think the lion's share of the credit, are basically the people who
came out and voted for a change in 1994. Elections have
consequences,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So who led? The American people led. Who followed? Republicans
followed. And who got out of the way and reluctantly got out of the
way? Bill Clinton,'' Gramm said, adding that the president wants to
spend $14 billion to $20 billion on ``emergency spending'' for such
items as the census count and troop deployment.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, long a conservative voice on budget issues, voted against
all the budget-related measures that both sides claim led to the
surplus. He opposed the 1991 deficit reduction measure crafted by
President Bush, Clinton's 1993 budget request and the 1997
bipartisan budget resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Gramm) has not tried to claim credit for anything. He's
simply tried to do the work necessary to get that job done,'' said
Gramm spokesman Larry Neal. Neal said Gramm opposes spending any of
the surplus, for either tax cuts or appropriations, until Social
Security is overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, issued a statement claiming
credit for Republicans. She said Clinton's 1993 measure was ``the
largest tax increase in the history of America'' and ``only when
Republicans took control of Congress in 1995 did the march toward a
balanced budget begin.'' Hutchison voted for the 1997 accord.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, estimated the 1998 surplus at $63 billion but still
claimed credit for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the Republican Congress, we've balanced the budget,
reformed welfare, cut taxes and cut spending, which is why we have
a budget surplus today. And since American taxpayers are now paying
more in taxes than the government needs, they have a right to a
refund _ it's their money after all,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston legislator also pushed a five-year, $80 billion tax
cut measure he is sponsoring, but Clinton urged Republicans to hold
off until the Social Security system, which will be bankrupt within
another generation, is reformed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I am well aware that it is a popular thing, particularly
right here just four weeks and change before Election Day, to serve
up a tax cut,'' Clinton said. But he also noted the deficit was
made small because the White House and Congress used the Social
Security surplus to offset the red ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us know this problem is looming out there and will need
money to fix. So I think the American people have waited 29 years,
and I think most Americans would like to see the ink change from
red to black and then just dry a little before we put it at risk,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The accumulated national debt from the 29 years of deficits is
more than $4 trillion. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
