<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SAINT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE FAMILY TO VIEW CANONIZATION CEREMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Benedicta McCarthy, whose recovery from an overdose of
painkillers has been attributed to the miraculous intervention of a
Roman Catholic nun murdered by the Nazis, will be in Rome when the
nun is canonized by Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, 14, her parents and 11 brothers and sisters will make
the trip to Rome to witness the pontiff give the official edict
naming Sister Teresia Benedicta a Catholic saint on Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The logistics of getting all the children, who are scattered
all over the United States, to Rome is a lot of work but we'll all
be there,'' said McCarthy's father, the Reverend Emmanuel Charles
McCarthy, a Melkite priest in the Eastern Rite of the Catholic
Church who is permitted to marry.
</P>
<P>
   Benedicta was born Edith Stein, a Jew, but after converting to
Roman Catholicism and entering a Carmelite convent in 1933 she took
the name of Teresia Benedicta after St. Teresa of Avila.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, she was taken by the Nazis from a convent
in Holland after Dutch bishops spoke out against anti-Semitism. The
Nazis were rounding up anyone with Jewish roots. Stein was murdered
in a gas chamber at Auschwitz on Aug. 9, 1942.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1987, when Benedicta McCarthy was two, she swallowed a
massive overdose of Tylenol. Her kidneys and liver ceased
functioning and doctors at Massachusetts General Hospital expected
her to die.
</P>
<P>
   As her family prepared for the worst, Charles McCarthy's
sister-in-law suggested that the family ask friends to pray to
Teresia Benedicta.
</P>
<P>
   The toddler had been named for the murdered nun after McCarthy
discovered that the day of the woman's death in a Nazi gas chamber
was also the same day he was ordained a priest _ Aug. 9, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   As his daughter lay near death at MGH, McCarthy, who had kept a
longstanding commitment to lead a retreat near Fargo, N.D., was
telling retreat participants about his gravely ill daughter. At the
exact time, 1 p.m., that he was discussing her, Dr. Ronald Kleinman
of MGH was recording in Benedicta's medical chart that ``this child
has made a remarkable recovery,'' according to McCarthy, who read
his daughter's medical files.
</P>
<P>
   Kleinman, along with Cardinal Bernard Law, also will be in Rome
to witness Benedicta's sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these years I've just pondered what all these means,''
McCarthy said. ``I ponder it in terms of God working through
history with some kind of power we don't understand and in which
the purpose is to ensure that love conquers evil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
