 &QL; 
TOBACCO PROBE (Undated) - Attorney General Grant Woods has asked
the Justice Department to investigate whether the tobacco companies
and former Gov. Fife Symington violated the Hobbs Act for
corruption and influence-peddling when they sat down to agree how
to pull the state Attorney General's Office off the tobacco case.
Mysterious handwritten notes that refer to a ``PR fund`` that the
tobacco companies apparently were to give Symington led Woods to
turn the case over to the feds for investigation. Because his
office has proceeded civilly against the tobacco companies in a
trial that is to begin in March, Woods declared a conflict and
asked Washington to step in. By ADRIANNE FLYNN et al. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
