<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QTR-DEALS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK AND BOND UNDERWRITING SLOWER IN THIRD QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also QTR-WINNERS, QTR-MUTFUNDS, QTR-GLOBAL) 
(ART ADV: Graphic showing leading underwriters and dealmakers is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street's core business _ the underwriting of
stocks and bonds _ slowed significantly in the third quarter after
relatively smooth growth in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Securities firms and banks issued $392.6 billion of bonds and
stocks in the three months ended Sept. 30 amid much more volatile
markets, greater caution among U.S. investors and issuers of
securities, and the swoon in the stock market that began in
mid-July as global economic problems spread _ particularly in
Japan, other Asian countries and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The volume was up 5 percent from the quarter a year earlier. But
the pace of underwriting has slowed sharply from the first six
months of this year, when banks and securities firms raised almost
$1 trillion as companies issued bonds and shares at record rates in
the most buoyant securities markets in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   The ranking of the firms most active in managing securities
issues for the third quarter was led by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., which
raised $59 billion, followed by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., Salomon Smith
Barney, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street executives, who have had a run of good markets in
recent years were buffeted by this summer's more difficult markets.
``It was tough. The longer the quarter went, the worse it got.
September will show up as one of the worst months in terms of
equity issue business,'' said Steven D. Black, vice chairman and
chief operating officer of Salomon Smith Barney, the brokerage
subsidiary of Travelers Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what you did, you felt you were trying to catch a
falling knife,'' said Black. ``If you were an issuer, why go into
the market with all the uncertainty? You're better off just to sit
and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Some see improvement in the equity markets in recent weeks.
``July, globally, was an unbelievably good market,'' said Mark
Hantho, a managing director in equity capital markets at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. ``In August the brakes were firmly applied;
almost nothing was working in the market. But in September the
market was slowly emerging on a very selective basis,'' with some
big companies gradually coming back to the markets.
</P>
<P>
   But the summer difficulties in securities markets have taken a
toll on even the best companies. ``In a market crack like we have
had, good and bad names suffer,'' said Vincent Pica, group
president of the capital finance group at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The bond markets practically froze over after Russia defaulted
on some obligations in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   The securities industry went ``from printing about $7 billion a
week of investment-grade debt to zero,'' in August, and has only
begun to revive in recent weeks, said Kevin Kelly, the managing
director at Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. in charge of new bond-issue
business.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he said, the industry had continued its recovery,
issuing about $5 billion of investment-grade debt. Recent
debt-issue activity, he noted, involved blue-chip borrowers almost
exclusively. ``We have quite a long way to go before we can get to
covering the gamut of issuers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mergers and acquisitions also slowed markedly in the third
quarter as raising money for acquisitions suddenly became much more
difficult and company managers grew more cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers and acquisitions totaling $327.7 billion were announced
in the third quarter, according to preliminary figures compiled
Wednesday by Securities Data Co. of Newark, N.J. That represents a
decline of more than 50 percent from $701 billion of mergers in the
second quarter of this year, although it still represents a
considerable increase from $192 billion of such transactions in
last year's third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in the volume of new securities issues was
particularly pronounced in more speculative markets, such as those
for initial public offerings and high-yield bonds. The industry,
for example, managed 69 initial public offerings to raise $5.3
billion in the third quarter of this year, down substantially from
the 158 such issues that raised $10.4 billion in last year's third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street issued $20.6 billion of high-yield bonds, in the
third quarter, yet in the first six months of the year the
securities industry issued more than $100 billion of such
securities, which are also known as junk bonds. ``It went from
records to wreckage,'' said Richard Peterson, a spokesman for
Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street professionals are pessimistic about the the
prospects for underwriting. ``I don't think it's going to change
till you get some kind of leveling-off process from these wild
swings,'' Black of Salomon Smith Barney said. ``Individual stocks
and industries moving all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Pica of Prudential said: ``There's still a fair amount of
uncertainty out there. `Traditionally October is a tough month.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
