<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSH TO BONDS PUSHES YIELDS BELOW 5 PERCENT FOR FIRST TIME IN 30
YEARS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Worries about containing the economic crisis abroad
and fears of financial problems at home prompted investors to sell
stocks and buy bonds Wednesday, pushing long-term government yields
below 5 percent for the first time in more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average plunged 237.90 points, or 2.9
percent, to 7,842.62, but prices of Treasury securities rose,
pushing the yield on the benchmark 30-year bond down to 4.97
percent, a rate that most of those working on Wall Street have
never seen in their professional lives.
</P>
<P>
   While the bond market has rallied spectacularly since the stock
market peaked in mid-July, the third quarter was the worst for the
Dow in eight years, down 12.4 percent for the three months.
</P>
<P>
   At the close Wednesday, the Dow was down 16 percent since its
peak and just 303 points from its 1998 low on Aug. 31. The only
good news was that the Dow overcame the odds last month.
Historically, September is the worst month for the Dow. But the Dow
rose 4 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the day after the Federal Reserve cut its
short-term interest rate target one-quarter point in an effort to
prevent the financial crisis abroad from derailing the American
economy, all the news seemed to point to things getting worse, not
better.
</P>
<P>
   More companies offered warnings that their earnings would come
in below forecasts, adding to the gloom that has analysts
predicting that earnings will decline in the third quarter for the
first time since the fourth quarter of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation about the collapse of another hedge fund
on the heels of last week's rescue of Long-Term Capital Management,
which needed an infusion of $3.6 billion from Wall Street's major
brokerage firms and banks to stay afloat. While the fund denied the
rumor, the fact that such rumors spread so easily these days is a
sign of negative investor sentiment. The rumor helped drag down
shares of banks and brokerage firms, which have been among the
hardest hit in the stock market decline since mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   And even the news of declining interest rates was not all that
positive. ``The current rally is based on growing expectations of
negative economic developments,'' said Robert Barbera, chief
economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co. Robert DiClemente, the chief U.S.
economist at Salomon Smith Barney, added, ``This is not the way we
would have liked bonds to go through 5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, while lower interest rates will help home buyers
and consumers, the downward rush in government yields has left the
rates on other debt, like that of corporations, much higher as
investors have chosen the safety of government-backed bonds over
even those of companies with good credit ratings.
</P>
<P>
   DiClemente said that overall credit was already tightening as
the cost of corporate borrowing had risen and banks were becoming
more adverse to risk. As the Fed cuts interest rates, he said,
``there is no assurance that financial conditions will be easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The drop in interest rates was apparently a key contributor to
the losses at Long-Term Capital, meaning that further declines
could mean harder times for it and other hedge funds. It is also
probably contributing to losses for many Wall Street firms.
</P>
<P>
   All these signals lead many analysts to argue that the Fed rate
cut was not enough. ``I think this is a time when you have to take
pre-emptive action,'' said Nicholas Sargen, the global market
strategist for J.P. Morgan's private clients. In his view, it is
clear that the global economic crisis is now impinging enough on
the American economy to offset any inflationary threat from an
interest rate cut that encourages growth.
</P>
<P>
   The price on the 30-year bond, which moves in the opposite
direction from the yield, jumped 1 29/32, to 108 4/32. The yield of
4.97 percent was down from 5.09 percent on Tuesday and is off
three-quarters of a percentage point since the Dow hits its peak on
July 17. The yield on the 10-year note, which is a benchmark for
home mortgages, dropped to 4.41 percent, from 4.56 percent on
Tuesday, its lowest since the end of 1965.
</P>
<P>
   In the stock market, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell
32.01 points, or 3 percent, to 1,017.01, while the Nasdaq index
dropped 40.21 points, or 2.3 percent, to 1,693.84. The Russell 2000
index of smaller-company stocks dropped 2.21 points, or 0.6
percent, to 363.59.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see bond prices go up this much and stock prices go
down this much, the message is clear,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief
investment officer at the First Albany Corporation. ``Investors are
becoming much more worried about the economy and earnings than they
had been.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies issuing third-quarter earnings warnings
Wednesday or after the market closed on Tuesday were RJR Nabisco
Holdings, which cited declining sales in Russia and other republics
of the former Soviet Union; Arch Coal, the second-largest American
coal producer, which said maintenance costs were reducing profits,
and Healthsouth, which runs outpatient surgery clinics and said it
might have to revise its earnings forecast because of price
pressure from managed-care companies. These announcements came a
day after Goodyear Tire and Rubber, Viacom and CBS all fell because
of earnings concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there were signals from Europe that earnings are
under pressure there. Benetton Group, the Italian clothing
retailer, said earnings fell 14 percent in the first half of the
year in part because of reduced sales in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   According to IBES International, which monitors analysts'
earnings forecasts, profits for the companies in the S&AMP;P 500 will
fall by 2.2 percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bank and brokerage stocks fell again Wednesday. Chase Manhattan
fell 1~, to 43[, and Citicorp fell 4}, to 93. Oil company stocks
also dropped along with computer stocks, including Microsoft and
Intel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
