</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MASSACRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON UNRESPONSIVE IN FACE OF KOSOVO ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN   AND DAVID MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ While observers and relief workers assess the grisly
murders of 16 villagers in the troubled Serbian province of Kosovo,
Washington remains too consumed with its own scandal to focus on
the carnage, US legislators and watchers of the Balkans say.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Western diplomats and reporters viewed in the town
of Gornje Oberinje the gruesome remains of 16 ethnic Albanians, 10
of them women, children and elderly, who had been killed by
gunshots at close range or whose throats had been slashed. One man
had a knife lying carefully on his chest. One of the victims was a
pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   In another reported massacre, 14 civilians were killed Saturday
in the Drenica region. A survivor told Western reporters that men
in Serb police and Yugoslav army uniforms carried out the murders
after ambushing the people, who were hiding in a shack.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs deny taking part in the Gornje Oberinje killings.
They also accuse the Western media of implicating the Serbs and in
doing so fueling support for a NATO air strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is true that 16 Albanians were killed in Gornji
Dubrinje, how do Western reporters know that the Serbs are
responsible for the massacres?'' asked the state-run Tanjug news
agency. ``Well, they don't. ...There are no direct witnesses.''
These fresh attacks on Albanians in Kosovo discovered this week
have increased international pressure for NATO air strikes against
Serbia, which has conducted a brutal crackdown on Albanians
separatists in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for the President to be able to act, he needs to have the
support of the Congress,'' Sen. Joseph Biden (D-Del.), the ranking
Democrat on the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, will say today
in a speech before the Center for Strategic and International
Studies. ``If that support is not asked for - and given - because
of the growing chasm created by the impeachment debate, United
States leadership will be forfeited, and the Balkan tragedy will
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are fixated on Clinton...and we're not doing
what the American people need us to do'' on Kosovo, added Rep.
Elliot Engel (D-N.Y.), co-chairman of the House Albanian Issues
Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Non-governmental organizations seeking action on the Kosovo
crisis are also frustrated. ``It seems very much like the debate
over the Clinton issue is clearly taking attention away,'' lamented
Diane Paul of Human Rights Watch. ``There's a self-absorption going
on in Washington. There's a ship afloat without a captain.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting has raged in Kosovo for the last seven months between
ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the population in the
province, and Serb forces. The Albanians demand independence for
Kosovo from Serbia, the core republic of what remains of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic refuses to grant them
independence. Claiming to quash ``terrorist'' activity of the
Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA), the militia of the ethnic Albanians,
Serbian troops have killed Albanians and burned their villages.
Some Serbs living in Kosovo have also died.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict has caused many hundreds of deaths and left
homeless an estimated 300,000 people, mostly Albanians. About
50,000 of them are hiding in the mountains -- a situation that
grows more precarious as the brutal Balkan winter approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations Security Council last week warned Milosevic
to stop the assaults of his troops in Kosovo or face a possible
NATO strike. But fighting has continued. Indeed, the situation in
Kosovo continues to follow a gruesomely familiar pattern. Violence
erupts, the West threatens air strikes, Milosevic promises to pull
back his forces and then breaks his promise.
</P>
<P>
   International observers and diplomats accuse Milosevic of
defying the UN Security Council resolution. Great Britain called
for an emergency meeting of the UN Security Council today to
discuss the situation. And members of the Contact Group on Kosovo,
which includes the United States, France, Germany, Britian, Russia
and Italy, plan to meet Friday in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic had better start moving now,'' warned British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook. Milosevic has insisted that he has
withdrawn his forces, but observers on the ground tell a different
story.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs ``have not pulled back at all. That's all just
political rhetoric,'' said Catholic Relief Services' Mark Davidson,
reached in the Kosovar capital of Pristina. Relief workers were
still sending up to 24 trucks of food and supplies to three
different locations several times a week, he said. ``We're a little
bit nervous, but it's not going to stop us.'' The West remains
sensitive to criticism that it waited too long before it got
involved in the war in Bosnia and as a result added unnecessarily
to the carnage there. But the crisis in Kosovo differs because,
unlike Bosnia, it is occurring within the sovereign borders of one
country.
</P>
<P>
   Since Kosovo is a province of Serbia, Milosevic notes that he
has the right to break an armed insurrection within his own
borders. But the severity of the crackdown - including the reported
killing of civilians - has tested the patience of the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the current UN resolution is that ``there's no
`or else' to it,'' said Kurt Bassuener, associate director of the
Washington, D.C.-based Balkan Action Council. ``I don't think the
West has learned its lesson,'' he said in reference to Bosnia. Air
strikes, he added, ``would make a final political solution more
likely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Until Milosevic understands that we mean what we say, he won't
do anything,'' said Engel, who has gathered nine signatures so far
on a congressional petition calling for use of force by NATO in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is prepared for a possible assault. Outgoing German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl formally offered 14 German Tornado aircraft
for a potential NATO strike. But it remains unclear, say members of
Congress, if NATO must have UN Security Council support before it
acts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Christopher Hill, the United States ambassador to
Macedonia, has been trying to broker a political solution between
the Serbs and the ethnic Albanians. But that process has been
slowed by internal divisions among the Albanians as well as
stand-offs between Serbs and Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Milligan reported from Budapest, Marcus from Washington. Wire
service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
