u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLON-CANCER-BOS &LR;      09-30 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLON-CANCER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VITAMINS DRAMATICALLY CUT COLON CANCER RISK: STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking a multivitamin pill can reduce the long-term risk of
colon cancer by 75 percent, according to a new study of nearly
89,000 nurses.
</P>
<P>
   No one is yet advising Americans to take vitamins to prevent
colon cancer, but the study and other recent evidence suggest it
should be possible to slash the incidence of the disease, the third
most frequently diagnosed cancer among both men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 132,000 Americans will be diagnosed with colon cancer
this year amd 56,500 will die from it, according to the National
Cancer Institute. It strikes men and women equally.
</P>
<P>
   Combining vitamin use with other preventive measures _ exercise,
healthy diet, and possibly regular use of aspirin or other
painkillers drugs _ could prevent 90 percent of colon cancer, said
Dr. Edward Giovannucci of Harvard University, lead author of the
study, which appears today in the Annals of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But it wouldn't happen overnight. While the link between
multivitamin use and colon cancer reduction is the strongest yet
found, the full effect did not appear for 15 years. At the five-
and 10-year marks, multivitamin use was associated with about a 20
percent reduction in risk.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this delayed effect, Giovannucci hypothesized in
an interview, is that colon cancer arises from small growths called
polyps on the lining of the five-foot-long lower intestine, and
``most polyps take 10 or 15 years, or perhaps even longer, to
develop into a colon cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the research was conducted in women, researchers
believe the effect is likely to apply to men as well.
</P>
<P>
   The multivitamin ingredient responsible for curbing colon cancer
is folate, the Harvard group believes, on the basis of animal
research and data from the 21-year-old Nurses Health Study, which
is based at the Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Folate is essential for two important cellular processes _ the
synthesis of DNA during cell division, and the methylation of DNA,
which determines which genes are turned on or off. Animals
deficient in dietary folate are more likely to develop colon polyps
and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   An abnormally low level of methylation marks the earliest stages
of colon cells' transformation from normal to malignant.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies suggested that folate supplements may also
reduce the risk of heart disease by lowering blood levels of the
amino acid homocysteine, which may be involved in the buildup of
sludgy deposits in artery walls.
</P>
<P>
   In the Nurses Study, other vitamins did not appear to reduce
colon cancer risk. Nor did nurses who ate generous amounts of
folate-rich foods _ largely fruits and vegetables _ have less colon
cancer. This suggests that dietary sources cannot provide enough
folate; the folate in multivitamin pills is in the form of folic
acid, which is more likely to be taken up by the body.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1973, multivitamin pills sold in the United States have
contained 400 micrograms of folate, an amount that Giovannucci said
is difficult to obtain from diet alone. A six-ounce glass of orange
juice contains about 80 micrograms of folate.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this year, bread, flour, and grain cereals have been
fortified with folic acid _ a federally mandated step to lower the
risk of birth defects involving the spinal cord. However, this
extra dietary folic acid, which may add about 100 micrograms to the
average American's daily intake, may not provide enough of the
nutrient to protect against colon cancer, according to the Nurses
Study results.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier research, from the Nurses Study and others, suggested
that regular use of aspirin or other analgesics such as ibuprofen
conferred some protection against colon cancer, reducingrisk by 40
to 50 percent. However, such drugs also increase the risk of
gastrointestinal bleeding, and the large Physicians Health Study
found no colon cancer benefit from giving men small doses of
aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   Giovannucci cautioned against relying on pills _ whether
vitamins or pain-killers _ to reduce colon cancer risk. About
one-quarter of Americans are believed to take daily multivitamins
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to suggest that lifestyle isn't important, that
you can just take a multivitamin supplement and aspirin,'' he said.
``Most of the advantages are in overall diet and physical activity.
This finding suggests that an extra boost of folate may be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arthur Schatzkin of the National Cancer Institute agreed.
``I'm a little leery about putting the whole world on folate
supplements on the basis of this kind of evidence,'' he said,
noting that earlier studies involving a different nutrient with
suspected anticancer properties, beta-carotene, surprised
researchers by showing no benefit and perhaps some risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
