<SLUG> BC-HEBRON-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLY DAY MARRED BY WEST BANK VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ As Israel observed the Day of Atonement, the quiet
introspection of the Jewish holy day was shattered by sporadic
outbreaks of violence.
</P>
<P>
   At least 16 Palestinians and 9 Israeli soldiers were wounded in
clashes in the West Bank cities of Hebron and Ramallah Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday afternoon just before the 24-hour period of
prayerful reflection began, a simmering dispute between Israeli
Arabs and Israeli forces once again erupted, resulting in injuries
to some 30 Israeli Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Military security was on high alert. Palestinian lands were
sealed off.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions flared only one day after a round of just-finished
peace talks in the White House in which President Bill Clinton was
unable to push Palestinian and Israeli leaders to break a 19-month
deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes are certain to raise tensions as Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat
prepare for a summit with Clinton toward the middle of this month.
</P>
<P>
   The sides are deadlocked over a US initiative for an Israeli
withdrawal from a further 13 percent of the West Bank in return for
tougher Palestinian Authority action against Islamic militants who
have carried out a wave of terror attacks in Israel aimed at
derailing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   In the deeply divided city of Hebron, 11 Palestinians and nine
Israeli soldiers were wounded in explosions and shooting just
before sundown Wednesday, which marks the end of Yom Kippur.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli army officials said the violence began with a grenade
attack on one of its patrols by a suspected Palestinian assailant.
Palestinian residents of Hebron blamed Jewish settlers for the
violence in the heart of the city close to one of the settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Some 400 Jewish settlers, among the most radical opponents to
the peace process, live alongside more than 100,000 Palestinians in
a city that is holy to Muslims and Jews as the burial place of the
biblical patriarch Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian eye witnesses of the violence told the Reuters news
agency that settlers had opened fire on the Palestinians with
automatic weapons and that one settler threw a bomb which blew up a
Palestinian taxi. Israeli army officials denied that settlers
attacked Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In Ramallah, some 400 Palestinian protesters clashed with
Israeli troops after the funeral of an Islamic militant killed in a
mysterious car explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians marched from Bido village towards a nearby Jewish
settlement following the burial of Zahran Ibrahim Zahran, who
Palestinian security officials have confirmed was a militant member
of the Islamic organization Hamas. The armed wing of Hamas has
carried out a spate of suicide bombings that have killed scores of
Israelis, and it has recently vowed to continue its terror
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Zahran, 35, was killed and brothers Suleiman and Salim Abu Eid
were injured on Tuesday when explosives blew up in their car in an
industrial area near the Palestinian-ruled town of Ramallah.
Palestinian and Israeli security officials initially said that the
three men were believed to have been preparing a bomb for a fresh
terror attack inside Israel. But the dead man's family and Hamas
leadership have claimed that Israel was responsibile for the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In the Israeli Arab community of Umm el Fahm, tension erupted
Monday and continued Tuesday surrounding a dispute over land which
the Israeli military has sought to overtake for a military training
ground. The Israeli Arabs of the village say the military claim is
a ruse to seize the land to build a new Jewish suburb for the
nearby city of Haifa.
</P>
<P>
   During the clashes, Arabs of the village bombarded Israeli
security forces with rocks. Israeli security forces opened fire
with what they call rubber bullets, but which are actually
plastic-coated, steel pellets, injuring some 30 Arab protesters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
