<SLUG> BC-MARKET-FED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED MOVE DOES LITTLE FOR STOCKS; DOW FALLS 237 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ US stocks wrapped up their worst three-month quarter
of the decade Wednesday, with the Dow Jones industrial average
falling 237 points despite a Federal Reserve interest rate cut that
would normally have buoyed investors' spirits.
</P>
<P>
   The stock slide was accompanied by a dramatic runup in the price
of US bonds, a traditional haven in troubled times, that drove
yields on government debt below 5 percent for the first time in
more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The combination was hardly what investors or economic
policymakers had been hoping for, and suggested that further
financial turmoil may be in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing keeping stock is market afloat is interest
rates and, going forward, it's hard to see how they're going to
help that much,'' said Matthew Ruane, an equity trader with Gerard
Klauer Mattison &AMP; Co. in New Yok.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming apparent to people that growth expectations for
equities are too high, and the Fed's rate cut was not enough to
change that,' said Richard O. Lodewick, research director for
Boston Partners Asset Management in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bleak financial news, the US economy continued to
demonstrate substantial strength as it enters its eighth year of
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics released Wednesday showed that although sales of new
single-family houses fell in August for the second month running,
they still continued at a very respectable pace of 838,000 units a
year. Separately, the index of leading economic indicators remained
unchanged in August after rising in July, suggesting that the
economy will continue growing ``through at least early 1999,'
according to the Conference Board, a New York-based business
research organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most statistics are depicting an economy that is still quite
healthy,'' said Richard D. Rippe, chief econoist of Prudential
Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Even on the financial front, there was evidence of trends that
could help stablize the markets. Individual investors appeared to
resume their romance with stock mutual funds in September after
yanking a record $11.2 billion during August.
</P>
<P>
   Stock funds took in an estimated $19.3 billion in September,
close to twice what they lost through withdrawals in August,
according to a Bloomberg report that cites Trimtabs.com, a
fund-flow tracking firm. The August withdrawals were the largest
since the 1987 stock crash.
</P>
<P>
   Individual investors' return to stocks was not enough to lift
the market Wednesday. The Dow slumped 237.9 points, or 2.94
percent, to close at 7842.62, its most significant decline in
almost three weeks. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index declined 32.01,
or 3.05 percent, to close at 1017.01, and the Nasdaq Composite
Index was down 40.21 points to 1693.84.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the market's decline was at least in part
traceable to disappointment with the Fed's decision Tuesday to
shave only one quarter of a percentage point from the federal funds
rate, the rate at which banks make short-term loans to each other.
Investment professionals had hoped for a half-point reduction. The
rate cut was the first by the central bank since early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said that what was really behind Wednesday's market
fall was a broad set of fears that are not likely to be erased
quickly. Among them: worries about Brazil where an exodus of cash
and an uncertain outcome to Sunday's election are roiling markets;
continued concern about the stability of banks and other financial
institutions in the wake of the near-collapse of Long-Term Capital
Management L.P. that was rescued last wek by a Fed-orchestrated
injection of private capital, and continued dismay over corporate
profits.
</P>
<P>
   The investment world is in the midst of pre-announcement season,
a nasty period when companies break the news that their financial
performance may not be quite as wonderful as they had previously
let on. Among those delivering disappointments Wednesday were
Northern Telecome Ltd, North America's second largest phone
equipment maker, and RJR Nabisco, the cigarette and cracker
company.
</P>
<P>
   Both firms blamed overseas sales declins for the problem, both
were punished by invstors, who dumped shares of their stocks and
those of related companies. Shares of Northern Telecom dropped 3
5/8 to 32 1/4. Those of Lucent Technologies Inc., which said it is
seeing no slump in its business, fell an even steeper 5 1/4 to 69
1/4. RJR shares declined 1 9/16 to 25 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   During the three-month quarter that ended Wednesday, the Dow
shed 1,105 points or 12 percent. The S&AMP;P slid 10 percent and the
Nasdaq declined 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Major market measures reached record highs in mid-July before
beginning a steep six-week tumble that at one point erased 19
percent from the Dow's value. By Wednesday, the 30 stocks in the
Dow were essentially flat for the year, while the S&AMP;P and Nasdaq
were up 4.8 percent and 7.86 percent respectively. Those
performances were the stock indexes' worst since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   And analysts said that the indexes' records were not reflective
of the broader market, where the average stock is now 20 percent or
more off it high. ``For the vast majority of stocks, we are in a
bear market,'' said Lodewick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
