<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2845 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      09-30 1679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODEL YEAR '99 IS EVOLUTIONARY  
 (RESENDING TO DELETE BOLDFACE)  
 (EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Model year 1999 is an evolutionary one for the world's
automakers, with a tuck here, a tweak there, and a couple of face
lifts.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few models are brand new for '99, plus the re-entries of
a couple of old names, as the manufacturers gear up for the new
millennium. Corvette adds a model, Oldsmobile adds a compact,
Toyota adds a coupe, Buick loses a coupe, and Infiniti resurrects
its entry-level car.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, trucks are huge, as more and more erstwhile car buyers
switch to the beefy, the brawny and the fully loaded. Jumping on
the four-wheel-drive bandwagon is Cadillac, which introduces its
first-ever truck, the luxurious Escalade.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks are also big news for Chevrolet, GMC, Ford and Toyota,
with the GM siblings trotting out upgraded Silverado and Sierra
pickups.
</P>
<P>
   The GM pickups are playing catch-up with Ford's highly regarded
F-series trucks, updated two years ago and still by far the
bestselling vehicle in the United States. And both companies are
trying to fend off the growing popularity of the macho Dodge Ram
and, soon, a full-size V-8 pickup from Toyota, the Tundra.
</P>
<P>
   On the other, gentler side of the truck fence are the new Suzuki
Vitara/Chevy Tracker models, all new for '99 despite the continued
Tracker name. Suzuki gets the V-6-powered Grand Vitara (sounds like
a lodge leader) with a 140-horsepower V-6. The Tracker has to wait
until next year to be Grand.
</P>
<P>
   And Kia, though beset by financial woes and other heartbreak,
keeps smiling with a soft-top version of its cute-as-a-bug
Sportage.
</P>
<P>
   The Escalade is possibly the world's largest stopgap, hastily
conceived while Caddy prepares its very own sport-utility vehicle.
Caddy makes the end run after watching the Lincoln dealers down the
block eating everybody's lunch with the fast-selling Navigator. Not
even to mention Mercedes-Benz's ML320.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the $45,000 Escalade trundles out as a revised GMC
Yukon Denali with a Cadillac grille, softer suspension and an even
plusher interior. Caddy dealers are rubbing their hands with glee.
At least, they should be. This one is the mother of all
no-brainers.
</P>
<P>
   The summer's General Motors labor strike slowed introduction of
the Chevy Silverado and GMC Sierra pickups at a critical time, but,
word is, they're worth waiting for. Styling is slightly revised,
with the notable changes underneath: new engines, brakes and
suspension systems that have improved driveability and garnered
much critical acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Ford pickups get four doors on their Club Cab models, and the
F-series family is joined by a new set of muscle twins, Hans and
Frans. No, wait, it's really the F-250/F-350 Super Duty pickups,
which are available with 265-horse V-10 engines or monster diesels
packing 400 pound-feet of torque.
</P>
<P>
   Grrrr.
</P>
<P>
   But let's talk about some fun stuff. Let's talk about the New
Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's darling continues as a hot property for Volkswagen,
with widespread price gouging and much unfulfilled desire. For '99,
the Beetle goes uptown with an optional 150-horsepower,
turbocharged four, borrowed from the Passat, and a glass sunroof.
</P>
<P>
   Still no word on a convertible Beetle. Rats!
</P>
<P>
   The Mazda Miata continues to tread its retro path with a
refurbishing that includes a handsome new front end, sleeker body
shape, new interior, more powerful engine and improved suspension.
Still, it keeps the faith as an affordable, enjoyable little sports
car.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Mustang celebrates its 35th year (where (begin ital) has
(end ital) the time gone) with a restyling that recaptures many of
the cues of the original, including deeply scooped flanks, ersatz
hood scoop, and taillight design. Both V-6 and V-8 power is up. In
the hot Cobra version, Mustang gets an independent rear suspension
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of power, the Corvette hardtop joins the hatchback and
convertible with less weight and a lower price. The
performance-oriented hardtop is offered only with a six-speed
manual. As well it should.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Chrysler, there's the new and notable 300M sedan, an
athletic version of cab-forward design, and its longer, plusher
sibling, the LHS. The Plymouth Prowler, a unique hot-rod roadster
and every car lover's dream machine, also gets the powerful 253
horsepower V-6 from the 300M and LHS.
</P>
<P>
   The hyper Dodge Viper gets some wheel and interior options, and
continues being supercool. Chrysler stylists continue to hit as
many home runs as McGwire and Sosa put together.
</P>
<P>
   The Jeep Grand Cherokee receives a complete makeover, with a
body that's slicker and more refined but still recognizable, a new
engine, and enhanced off-highway abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler's new partner, Mercedes-Benz, continues to reinvent
itself with more desirable and technologically advanced machines,
such as the fine and refined CLK320 Cabriolet and the V-8-powered
version of its sport ute, the ML430.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the Mercedes docket is a five-speed manual version of
its supercharged, drop-top sports car, the SLK, which corrects the
error of introducing the little terror with an automatic-only in
the first place. Watch sales soar.
</P>
<P>
   BMW's new 323i and 328 sedans appeared over the summer to
replace the 3-series cars. But the real news at BMW is the ugly
duckling that turns into a beautiful swan as soon as you get behind
the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The Z3 coupe and hotter M-coupe might look ungainly to some
eyes, but they do have the advantages of being stiffer and quieter
than the roadster versions, and a few hundred dollars cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Audi introduced its all-wheel-drive Avant luxury wagon in June,
and the smaller A4 wagon adds a 1.8-liter turbo engine. Soon to
arrive is the exotic TT sports coupe with its bluntly purposeful
styling and aggressive manners, going up against the likes of the
Porsche Boxster, Mercedes SLK, BMW Z3 and the less-pricey Miata.
</P>
<P>
   Acura introduces a new TL, its midlevel car, that's bigger and
more powerful, and the big RL gets restyled with a suspension
upgrade and side-impact air bags. Honda joins the mainstream with
its new Odyssey minivan, restyled in the mode of the Chrysler
minivans.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitsubishi Gallant swims upstream, bigger in all dimensions,
and touting a 195-horse V-6 that puts it on a par with costlier
sedans.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota is coming out with a swoopy coupe version of its faithful
Camry, and its Sienna minivan gets a fourth door. Lexus powers up
its ES300 with a 210-horse, variable-valve-timing V-6, like the one
in the sporty GS300.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota's new Tundra pickup is due in May, posing the first
serious threat to domestic trucks. Toyota planned to call it the
T-150 until Ford fought it off, noting the alarming similarity to
the popular F-150.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan, beleaguered by disappointing sales, sadly is dropping
two of its sporty coupes, the Sentra-based 200SX and the 240SX. On
the other hand, the automaker reportedly is getting ready to bring
back the spiritual successor of the acclaimed 240Z. Let's hope.
</P>
<P>
   The Frontier, Nissan's compact pickup, gets an overdue V-6, at
least in the four-wheel-drive models, and an interesting four-door
model with a full crew-cab treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Infiniti brings back the entry-level G20, a rebadged Primera
sold in Japan and Europe, and powered by a 140-horse four-cylinder
engine.
</P>
<P>
   At Isuzu, watch for the radical VehiCROSS sport-utility vehicle,
introduced two years ago as a concept car. Amigo gets a hardtop
model, as Isuzu soldiers on with Honda's old Odyssey, which it
calls the Oasis, instead of getting the new one.
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac has a redesigned Grand Am, whose aggressive styling
should be a major hit in high-school parking lots, and Buick tunes
its Century for better driveability. Could this be the end of
DynaRide?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Buick is getting ready to cut the Riviera out of the
herd. It's a fate this beautiful coupe doesn't deserve, although it
always was much more amusing to look at than it was to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Another radical-looking coupe makes its entry at Mercury. A hot,
new Cougar replaces the stale old Cougar, introducing New Edge
styling to the up-market Ford division.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln has put off introduction of its midsize LS cars,
designed for a more youthful market, to work out some bugs. Watch
for these cars, designed on a platform shared with Jaguar, sometime
in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Oldsmobile's Alero debuted this summer right in the teeth of the
GM labor strike, and few of them made it to showrooms until
recently. The new model is one of Olds' new breed of sporty,
refined cars. But when you don't feel like being sporty (begin
ital) or (end ital) refined, check out the video system built into
the Silhouette minivan so that back-seat passengers (i.e., kids)
can watch movies or play videos instead of checking out the
scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for this feature as an option on every minivan made within
a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo continues to shed its boxy image with the stylish new S80
sedan replacing the S90 sedan. The V90 wagon goes away. And lest we
forget, Volvo introduced the drop-dead gorgeous and quite sporty
C70 convertible last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Saab also introduced its 9-3 compact, a slick and
nicely engineered replacement for the 900, following the 9-5
replacement of the full-size 9000 last year. At Volkswagen later
this year, watch for the new Jetta with styling similar to the
Passat's. A new generation of the Golf is to arrive after the new
year.
</P>
<P>
   But putting it all in perspective, Rolls-Royce and Bentley have
rolled out a new set of steeply-high-end automobiles, but with a
couple of twists. Rolls' new $229,028 Silver Seraph and Bentley's
$215,546 Arnage sedan both are powered by BMW engines, a V-12 for
the Rolls and twin-turbo V-8 for the Bentley.
</P>
<P>
   And the venerable British automaker now is owned by Volkswagen.
The people's car of Germany. You couldn't make up stuff better than
this. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
