<HEADLINE>
CHOICE OF PITCHING NOW PROBLEMATICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ There was a feeling of inevitability about the
series when all hell broke loose in the top of the first inning. On
the heels of their 11-3 win in the opener, the Red Sox had a 2-0
lead in Game 2 of their best-of-five American League Division
Series and the Indians were unraveling in front of Baseball
America. Boston was flexing its muscle, and you couldn't find
anyone in Cleveland who believed in the hometown team.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribe looked like the Red Sox, circa 1990, when Roger
Clemens thought he was a Ninja Turtle and got tossed from a playoff
game in the second inning. This time we had Cleveland manager Mike
Hargrove and starter Dwight Gooden getting the heave from
rabbit-eared/arrogant/gutless plate umpire Joe Brinkman before the
game was two outs old.
</P>
<P>
   The Jake looked like the Paradise Club on Everclear Night, and
for sure, the Red Sox were going to embarrass Cleveland in three
tidy games en route to a date of destiny with the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But then it all went the other way. The veteran Tribe awoke and
served Tim Wakefield and Red Sox Nation a 9-5 knuckle sandwich. So
now the series is tied, 1-1, and the Sox face the possibility that
their season could end with Pete Schourek on the mound at Fenway
Park Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Saberhagen will start for the Red Sox Friday, and he
certainly deserves the nod. Saberhagen won the most important game
for the Red Sox this season when he stopped the bleeding in New
York in May. He is a big-game pitcher and this season wrote one of
the great comeback stories of all time.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the Sox have trouble hitting Charles Nagy? What if
Boston loses Game 3? The Sox don't want to talk about the
distasteful possibility, and it makes sense to keep quiet until
they have to make a decision. Bu if things go wrong Friday, Boston
has to pitch Pedro Martinez Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation calls for Saberhagen Friday, lefthander Schourek
Saturday, and ace Martinez in Game 5, if necessary. If Boston wins
Friday, it makes sense to stay in turn. That would set up Pedro for
either Game 5 Sunday (with his regular four days of rest) or Game 1
of the AL Championship Series Tuesday with six days of rest.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the Sox lose Friday? Can they take a chance on
losing this series in four games with Pedro pitching only once?
</P>
<P>
   No way. The team has committed $75 million to Martinez, and he
showed Tuesday that he has great command over the Indians. Game 1
was over by 4 p.m., which means Pedro actually would be working
with 3 1/2 days of rest if he pitched Saturday night. The Sox would
have to come back with the ace, then empty the gun Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make any decision,'' manager Jimy Williams
said when asked about changing the rotation if the Sox go down,
2-1. ``I don't think now is the right time to do anything like
that. I think we are going to stay with our rotation as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan scoffed at any suggestion of
changing the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going on what is planned out,'' said Kerrigan.
``It's what we've planned all year and for the last six weeks. We
don't deal with hypotheticals. We can bring Wakefield back in the
bullpen. Right now we're just thinking about Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think that (changing the rotation) is for people who
panic, who don't have a program, who don't have a plan. We can't be
shifting people around when they are used to pitching every fifth
day. It doesn't work that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield is the X factor. Game 2 was his shortest outing of the
year. He threw only 42 pitches and is capable of pitching every
other day under almost any conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can pitch out of the bullpen, I can start Friday, I can
start (Friday) if they want me to,'' he said. ``I let my team down
today. I feel like I didn't even pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   If Pedro starts and wins Game 4, Wakefield probably would get
the nod in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   The most radical plan would be to bring Wakefield back Friday,
pitch Saberhagen with an extra day of rest in Game 4, and have
Pedro ready for Game 5. That would give Boston its top three
starters in the final three games. But it would not be fair to
Saberhagen, who is programmed to pitch Friday. Saberhagen wouldn't
entertain any goofy theories about changing the rotation, and who
can blame him?
</P>
<P>
   If the Red Sox win Game 3, none of the above matters. But if the
Sox lose Friday, they can't start Schourek (1-3, 4.30) in what
would be the biggest game of the year Saturday. It would have to be
Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
