<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-GUV-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AGREES TO DEBATE IN EL PASO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Republican Gov. George W. Bush said Wednesday he
would debate Democratic opponent Garry Mauro, who has been
demanding such a meeting for months.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates will meet for an hour-long evening debate in
El Paso on Oct. 16, less than three weeks before the election. It
will be their only debate, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   With a powerful lead in the polls, Bush had put off the debate
question for much of the campaign, but he said Wednesday he agreed
to it because he believes it's the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro was pleased Bush agreed to the face-off, but he complained
the meeting would take place in far West Texas on a Friday night
when many people would be at high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have suggested that, as a result of the polls, I
shouldn't do it. I disagree,'' said Bush, who is some 50 percentage
points ahead of Mauro in most surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it makes sense for a sitting governor to debate,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro has said almost from the start he wanted to debate Bush _
any time, any place. But he expressed disappointment Wednesday
about the logistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has little to lose because I'll carry El Paso, and it's on
a different time zone in a city a long, long way away and so not
many people will see it,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bush said the sponsors picked the time, and he noted
that his 1994 debate against then-Gov. Ann Richards was held on a
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   For Mauro, the debate is an opportunity for the cash-strapped
candidate to get some exposure on television and take a crack at
upstaging his well-funded and popular opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gets to say he didn't duck a debate and has the chance to
score points with the Hispanic community, which traditionally votes
for Democrats. But Bush denied he accepted the El Paso debate in
search of Hispanic votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way to attract the Hispanic vote is through a good
message. The other way to attract the Hispanic vote is to perform
in office,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate will be broadcast from the studios of the public
television station at the University of Texas at El Paso. It will
be up to individual stations around Texas whether to broadcast it
live, tape it for another time or not air it at all.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso, a city whose residents sometimes feel forgotten by the
rest of Texas, suddenly has found itself the center of considerable
attention this election year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has visited the city often as governor, and he made a stop
there the day he formally announced his re-election campaign. Also,
the candidates for lieutenant governor held their only debate there
last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Paso has become the symbolic city for Bush and his ability
to convert Hispanic voters to the Republican column,'' said Austin
political consultant Bill Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bush is the one that gains on this. Bush gets to say
`I can debate, big deal. Let's go do it, and I'll do it in Spanish
and I'll do it in a city that's historically Democratic,''' said
Miller, who has worked both sides of the political aisle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mauro gets a crack head-on at Bush. There's a lot to be said
for that. That's all you can really ask for in this business is an
opportunity,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
