<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIRD WINS FOR INDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ In sports, weird can be good, and injustice can be
very, very good.
</P>
<P>
   The top of the first inning Wednesday was certifiably weird. A
manager ejected three pitches into the game _ that's weird. The
starting pitcher ejected for saying something about a controversial
safe call at the plate one batter later _ that's weird. Oh, moaned
the Cleveland Indians, the absolute injustice of it all.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what. All this weird injustice actually led directly
to a 9-5 victory over the Red Sox for the Indians, and if you don't
believe it, just ask them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it made the difference in the ballgame,'' declared
shortstop Omar Vizquel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely fired everybody up,'' agreed first baseman Jim
Thome. ``It all worked to our benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the byproduct of it was it turned up our intensity and
it turned our fans' intensity up,'' pointed out manager Mike
Hargrove, who was forced to watch the game on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a playoff situation, you're definitely higher than a kite,
anyway,'' confirmed coach Jeff Newman, who took over the helm after
plate umpire Joe Brinkman gave Hargrove the old heave-ho. ``But
what it did was direct our focus a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we as a team felt, `We've just got to win today,'''
summarized designated hitter David Justice, who had five ferocious
rips at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   And even if you refuse to believe that emotion can play a
significant role in the performance of a baseball team, consider
the unarguable fact that the ejection of Doc Gooden and the arrival
of Dave Burba was a very positive happening for the Indians. We
will never know what kind of afternoon Gooden would have had if he
had gotten past the first four batters, but we do know that Mr.
Burba came in to give the Indians 5 1/3 solid innings before
exiting in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   You've undoubtedly seen it, heard about it, or read about it
elsewhere, but here is one more capsule version of what happened in
that bizarre Red Sox first. Gooden became upset with Brinkman's
version of the strike zone en route to a game-opening base on
balls. After the third pitch, Hargrove came out _ arguing balls and
strikes is a no-no _ and that proved to be the end of his day.
Three batters later, with Lewis on second, John Valentin on first,
and one away, Nomar Garciaparra hit one high off the left-field
wall, missing a three-run homer by a foot or less and winding up
with a double. Lewis scored, of course, but Valentin was thrown out
at the plate on a 7-6-2 relay _ except he wasn't. Though Valentin
was quite clearly out, Brinkman called him safe. Gooden, backing up
the plate and thus in a good viewing position, said something to
Brinkman (an ``expletive,'' according to the arbiter) and was
tossed. Enter Burba, with unlimited warmups.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians felt put upon. The Indians felt abused. The Indians
felt trashed. Suddenly, it was Popeye downing the spinach and
growling, ``That's all I can stands; I can't stands no more!''
</P>
<P>
   Burba got Mike Stanley (who had roughed him up for a two-homer
game earlier this season) on a ground out, and he fanned Troy
O'Leary. That stopped the bleeding. The Tribe got one run back in
the first and five more in the second. Tim Wakefield lasted just 1
1/3 innings, which brings up another possible Cleveland benefit
from all the hoo-ha in the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wakefield had to wait an extra 20 or 30 minutes to pitch after
he was warmed up,'' pointed out Thome. ``That might have helped us,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield was replaced by John Wasdin. He got Vizquel easily
enough, but Justice hit Wasdin's first pitch for a three-run homer.
That pretty much settled things right there.
</P>
<P>
   Justice was a very lethal man in this one. He had a sacrifice
fly in the first, the three-run homer in the second, and a long
double in the sixth. Mike Benjamin robbed him of a hit in the
fourth and Justice lined viciously to Mo Vaughn in the eighth. He
was the living definition of intensity at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to explain,'' Justice said. ``You're already
intense. You know it's an important game. You know you don't want
to go down, 0 and 2. But when something like that happens, it's
like you're backed into a corner. I'm not saying the umpires are
actually against you, but you feel like the only way to win is to
come out fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff sparked us up,'' said Vizquel. ``It's like, `Hey,
we've got to score some runs or else we're gonna be in trouble.' It
got everybody going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that it made us direct our focus,'' explained Newman.
``Everyone started thinking about `what can I do to help us?' It
made us more competitive. But it wasn't as if we carried over a
vendetta against the umpires after the first inning. That part
didn't carry over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little upset about the situation and we went out
there with a different level of concentration,'' said catcher Sandy
Alomar. ``We were very selective. We didn't swing at bad pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Justice, the Indians need this approach if they are
going to win the series. ``We needed this game today,'' he said,
``and it was a tough game. Against Boston, you've got to play the
full nine innings because they keep coming. You've got no choice
against Boston. If you want to win, you've got to score runs. Jimy
Williams keeps that team coming at you.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just baseball. How many times have we seen it in
basketball? The coach or the star player gets tossed, and the team
is aroused. In real life, weird is weird and bad is bad, no
exceptions. But sports aren't real life. The ordinary rules don't
apply, and that is why this best-of-five American League Division
Series is now tied at one game apiece.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
