</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRENADE ATTACK IN HEBRON WOUNDS TWO DOZEN SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Thirteen Israeli soldiers and 11 Palestinian
passers-by were wounded Wednesday when a Palestinian hurled
grenades at an Israeli patrol post in the heart of the divided city
of Hebron, a flash point for violent confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials said the attack took place at 4:30 p.m., close to
a Jewish settler enclave that borders on the casbah, the
Palestinian open-air market, in the Israeli-controlled sector.
Soldiers pursued the suspect, they said, shooting and wounding him
in the leg before he escaped into Palestinian territory, where the
Palestinian police were in charge of apprehending him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We demand widespread searches to find those responsible,''
Yitzhak Eitan, the Israeli commander for the West Bank, said at a
briefing Wednesday night. ``We demand the Palestinians take
responsibility for what happened here, and to prevent attacks on
Israeli targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebron, a city of 120,000, has been a tinderbox since it was
divided in early 1997 by the last peace agreement signed by the
Israelis and the Palestinians. Israel remains in control of 20
percent of the city, where some 450 Jewish settlers live in armed
compounds, protected by a recently beefed up force of about 2,000
Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions run at a constant high, with routine sniper fire and
rock-throwing between the two sides, who live so close together
that the pungent smell of Arab spices wafts through the barbed wire
into the settlers' apartments. But tensions flared with the killing
of a rabbi in late August, after which the settlers raged through
the casbah, overturning produce stands. Just Monday, a Jewish
tourist was shot in the leg.
</P>
<P>
   Hebron was the last city turned over to even partial Palestinian
control as peace talks have been stalled for more than a year and a
half. But in Washington this week, Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasir Arafat agreed to the
essentials of a pact whereby Israel would withdraw from another 13
percent of the West Bank, if the Palestinians act to insure Israeli
security and fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The settlers, who oppose the withdrawal, seized on the attack _
and the suspects' escape into Palestinian territory _ as evidence
that their opposition is warranted. ``That 13 percent is just
another 13 percent of land for them to prepare their attacks and
run back into, as we saw today,'' said David Wilder, a spokesman
for the settlers in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials, too, linked Wednesday's attack to the
peace talks, saying it could give Netanyahu a last-minute excuse to
walk away from the negotiations, which are supposed to culminate in
a three-way summit meeting in Washington in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever was behind this incident was obviously trying to
thwart the peace agreement,'' Jibril Rajoub, chief of preventive
security in the West Bank, said in an interview. ``If the one who
was behind it was a Palestinian, then it is a free service for
Netanyahu.''
</P>
<P>
   Rajoub said he was investigating the attack, which he denounced.
``We were informed by Israelis that the one who was behind it
escaped to our areas,'' he said. ``We are checking. But we have no
evidence regarding this accusation.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the attack, Palestinian security officials announced that
they had raided and dismantled a terrorist explosives laboratory in
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   After the grenade attack, the Israeli Army imposed a curfew on
Palestinian residents. Jewish settlers were briefly held at the
Cave of the Patriarchs _ believed to be the burial place of the
biblical Abraham _ after they finished the prayers of the Yom
Kippur holiday, then were allowed to move freely through the city
center.
</P>
<P>
   Some Palestinian witnesses asserted that the incident happened
differently, and that Jewish settlers played a role in the
violence. After visiting the wounded, a Palestinian Authority
official, Ali Kawasmeh, said some believed that a settler had
thrown something into a Palestinian jitney that exploded during the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli Army officials were skeptical, saying that one of
the two grenades aimed at the patrol post had rolled under the
jitney instead. And Palestinian security officials discounted their
version, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
