<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CIVIL-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES PAID ALMOST $24 MILLION FOR WRONGFUL ARRESTS AT BRIDAL
SHOWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles County has paid nearly $24 million to
36 people who were found to have been wrongly arrested and in some
cases beaten by sheriff's deputies at a bridal shower in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a jury found that the county sheriff's deputies had
used excessive force and violated the civil rights of the party
guests, most of whom were Samoan-Americans. That verdict was upheld
in July by the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday, David Dole received a check from
his lawyer for the largest portion of the award, $5.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bittersweet victory,'' said Dole, who was kicked and
beaten about the head and body. He was hospitalized and said he
suffered brain damage and broken bones. The other awards ranged
down to $57,000.
</P>
<P>
   Vina Camper, coordinator for Police Watch, a Los Angeles group
that tracks police misconduct, said the civil rights judgment was
the largest ever returned by a jury against law enforcement in
California. The City of Los Angeles settled the Rodney King beating
case for $3.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape of the deputies at the party, made by a neighbor and
shown repeatedly on local television, proved to be crucial evidence
in the trial. It showed dozens of deputies swinging batons, kicking
and hitting the partygoers, who appeared to be offering little
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The victims said the officers had yelled racial slurs at them
during the incident, like ``pineapple head'' and ``coconut head.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's department said the deputies had responded to a
call about a street fight in Cerritos, south of Los Angeles, the
night of Feb. 11, 1989. Dozens of deputies, who arrived wearing
riot gear, said that they found a party that was out of hand and
that when they tried to break it up, the guests threw rocks and
bottles.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the incident was over, several of the men and women
arrested were bruised and at least one, in addition to Dole,
suffered a broken bone. The sheriff's department said several
deputies had been injured. The charges against those arrested
included assault with a deadly weapon and rioting.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were eventually dropped or dismissed. Those arrested
then filed a civil suit charging the sheriff's department with
false arrest and using excessive force.
</P>
<P>
   The jury eventually awarded the plaintiffs, primarily members of
the Dole and Paopao families, $15.9 million. That amount grew to
nearly $24 million with interest.
</P>
<P>
   Garo Mardirossian, the victims' lawyer, said he was still
waiting for the sheriff's department to discipline the deputies
involved in the melee. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
