<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2864 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUORUM-COX     09-30 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUORUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quorum probe could impact its hospitals in Georgia
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The fate of Quorum Health Group, whose shares have
plummeted this week on news of a looming federal lawsuit, may
produce some fallout in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The Brentwood, Tenn.-based company manages 17 hospitals in
Georgia, and has two others participating in a joint venture in
Macon with Columbia/HCA Healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   Quorum, which overall owns 18 for-profit hospitals and manages
236 others, almost all of them nonprofits, disclosed this week the
federal government was likely to file suit over company Medicare
billing records.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year probe was prompted by a ``whistle-blower'' _ a
former employee of an unidentified hospital Quorum managed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has informed us they will commence litigation
Oct. 5th,'' said spokeswoman Shea Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is under seal until then, she said. Quorum,
the largest manager of nonprofit hospitals in the United States,
said it's cooperating with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   News of the litigation drove Quorum shares down 27 percent, to
$15.81 1/4 Tuesday. Shares recovered somewhat Wednesday, closing at
$16.25.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jeffrey Villwock of Robinson-Humphrey called the drop
Tuesday an overreaction, part of a general malaise affecting the
whole industry. ``Every health care stock with even a hint of a
problem is down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quorum reported income of $86.7 million on revenues of $1.6
billion in fiscal 1998, ending in June.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state authorities recently have stepped up pursuit
of health care fraud. The biggest target has been Nashville-based
Columbia, engulfed for more than a year in a massive probe into
possible Medicare billing fraud. The impact of the Quorum
investigation on its hospitals in Georgia and elsewhere is hard to
gauge.
</P>
<P>
   But if possible billing problems surface, and are companywide,
some individual hospitals Quorum manages could face potential
liability for questionable practices, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Many Quorum-managed hospitals in Georgia are rural facilities,
already rocked by reduced payments from Medicare, Medicaid and
managed-care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
