<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURPLUS-IMPACT-ART-89     09-30 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURPLUS-IMPACT-ART-890(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET SURPLUS STIRS DEBATE ON SEVERAL FRONTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With SURPLUS-CLINTON, which is moving in ``w'' category)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the better part of two decades, economists and
elected officials promised that all kinds of good things would
happen if the federal government stopped running huge budget
deficits.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the government closed the books on its fiscal year,
and for the first time since 1969 the budget will show a surplus,
which President Clinton said should be about $70 billion when all
the calculations are completed in the next few weeks. That is
slightly higher than the $63 billion projected earlier this month
by the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   So where's the payoff?
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, the answer is straightforward: Interest rates
are lower than they would be otherwise, a development that has
helped push unemployment down and the stock market up throughout
much of this decade. That shift has also helped establish the
United States as an anchor of stability in a world now at risk from
the deepening global financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But even now, some economists and analysts think the benefits
from fiscal prudence have been overstated, and some wonder whether
the projected surpluses will materialize if the economy should slip
into recession. There is still a debate about how much the strong
economy reflects the nation's improved fiscal condition and how
much the improved fiscal condition is a result of the strong
economy.
</P>
<P>
   There is also some lingering doubt, especially among liberal
Democrats, about whether the fiscal belt-tightening will prove a
good deal for low- and moderate-income people in the long run, or
whether it primarily benefited Wall Street and the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is no consensus yet about what to do with coming
surpluses, which the Congressional Budget Office estimated will
total $1.55 trillion over the next decade. The debate over tax
cuts, additional spending, reducing the national debt and
strengthening entitlement programs is only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is a growing battle over whether the government
should consider itself to be in surplus at all, since nearly all of
the excess revenues in coming years come from payroll taxes that
are supposed to be earmarked for the Social Security trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   The dawn of the surplus era passed all but unnoticed Wednesday
in the financial markets, which have long since factored in the
anticipated good news. Meanwhile, in Washington, it was a day for
celebration and contention, with both Democrats and Republicans
claiming credit for the turnaround while laying out their own
priorities for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reiterated his position that the surplus should be kept
in reserve until Congress and the administration settle on a plan
to shore up Social Security for the coming retirement of the
baby-boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans kept up their demands that a chunk of the surplus be
allocated to tax cuts so that it is not used for increased
spending, and said that Clinton had already raided the surplus by
proposing as much as $17 billion in emergency spending next year
for domestic and military programs that fall outside the normal
budget process.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the political posturing, there is agreement among many
economists that fiscal rectitude, when combined with unexpectedly
high tax receipts stemming in part from the rapid run-up in the
stock market, helped to push down interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   That happened because the government's borrowing requirements
declined, and because the absence of fiscal stimulus convinced
investors and the Federal Reserve Board that inflation was less of
a threat.
</P>
<P>
   How much lower rates are than they would have been in the
absence of fiscal improvement is largely a matter of guesswork,
given the myriad of interrelated factors that influence rates.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little question that lower rates have been a key
factor in keeping the economy growing since 1991 and in generating
new jobs at a healthy pace while stimulating business investment in
productivity-enhancing machinery and computers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many analysts say, the United States is facing a
period of deepening global economic crisis with considerable
strength and resilience, a far cry from its position a decade ago
when it was frequently judged to be in economic decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of the economy that we're all enjoying now is in
no small part attributable to the efforts we've made to eliminate
the deficit,'' said Robert Reischauer, a former director of the
Congressional Budget Office who is now a senior fellow at the
Brookings Institution, the research group. ``We can be buffeted by
the winds from Asia and the waves from Latin America, and still our
economy chugs along.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, moreover, moving from deficits to surpluses
provides the United States with greater flexibility in economic and
social policy, from cutting taxes to increasing spending and coping
with the strains that will result from an aging population.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our policy for years was driven by nickel-and-diming
the deficit rather than asking what's the right policy,'' said Van
Doorn Ooms, a former chief economist for the House Budget Committee
who is now with the Committee for Economic Development, a
business-sponsored research group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we maintain our heads and approach this sensibly, it's much
easier now to take on issues like Social Security and Medicare,''
he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, there have been challenges to the prevailing fiscal
orthodoxy from both the left and the right.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, many liberals have long been uncomfortable with
the notion that balancing the budget was more important than
financing social programs. To some Democrats, the emphasis on
eliminating the deficit remains little more than cover for
Republicans who want to shrink the size and influence of the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   But they also acknowledge real benefits from fiscal prudence,
particularly the Federal Reserve's willingness to cut interest
rates early in the Clinton administration and its increased
tolerance for extremely low unemployment rates even as growth has
remained strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those cuts in real interest rates were very important in
propelling the economy forward,'' said Robert Reich, who was labor
secretary during Clinton's first term. ``On the other hand, deficit
reduction meant cuts in domestic discretionary programs, especially
those for the less well off. And the president was unable to do
anything close to the $50 billion a year in education, training and
research and development investments that he had built his 1992
campaign around.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the sacrifices turn out to be worthwhile will depend on
how well the economy holds up the next time the business cycle
turns down and on how the country chooses to use the coming
surpluses, Reich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're turned into tax cuts that are mostly for people in
the top 20 percent of income or wealth, then many of the sacrifices
made by those in the bottom half, in terms of programs lost or
investments not made, will have been for very little,'' Reich said.
``If the surpluses are turned into investments in the productive
capacities of people in the bottom half _ education, job
retraining, an expanded earned-income tax credit, for example _
then the payoff may be quite substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cogan, a senior fellow at the Hoover Institution and a
former Reagan administration budget official, questioned the
premise that eliminating the deficit _ or more precisely,
restraining spending _ had been the key to the economy's strong
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The causality is working in the other direction here,'' Cogan
said. ``The reason we have a budget surplus is not so much because
we have had fiscal restraint _ although we have had more fiscal
restraint in recent years _ but because of a healthy economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogan said the surpluses provided the nation with an opportunity
to change its tax system, strengthen Social Security or reduce the
$5.5 trillion national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having said that, the surpluses can also represent a large
problem,'' Cogan said. ``Along with surpluses come, inevitably, the
pressure to spend more, and we're already seeing the manifestation
of that pressure.'
</P>
<P>
   The assumption that the elimination of the deficit has brought
tangible economic benefits is not universally accepted, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we seem to be moving away from chaos and toward
stability,'' Peter Bernstein, an economic consultant in New York,
wrote recently in Challenge magazine. ``It should be good news. And
yet the payoff we were promised from reducing the budget deficit
remains unfulfilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein argued that the trade deficit, which some economists
had predicted would fall in tandem with the budget deficit,
remained stubbornly high, even before the Asian crisis sent it even
higher. And he made a case that interest rates, adjusted for
inflation, have actually remained stubbornly high despite the
fiscal improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the trade and budget deficits were inextricably
linked may have been questionable from the start, since trade is
subject to political and business influences as well as fiscal
change. And given the tangle of complicated factors that determine
interest rates, it is difficult to say what would have happened to
rates had the nation not balanced its budget.
</P>
<P>
   But Bernstein also made a point that would resonate with many
economists in a world subject to rapid economic change: that it is
hazardous to assume that changing one element in the country's
economic mix could be counted on to have a certain result.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advocates of the mainstream hypothesis fell into error
because they forgot one of the primary lessons of macroeconomics,''
Bernstein wrote. ``Partial equilibrium _ moving one variable while
holding all else constant _ is an interesting but a hazardous basis
for prediction.''
</P>
<P>
   As a case in point, Bernstein cites savings rates. While
deficits declined, reducing what economists call public dissaving,
the savings rate in the private sector was falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The profligate private sector, and a swelling stream of both
domestic and foreign investment in the United States, thwarted the
result that the mainstream had assured us was in the cards,''
Bernstein said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
