<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BLOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPING TO CONTROL SPREAD OF AIDS, CHINA BANS THE SALE OF BLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Reflecting a growing awareness that China's heavy
reliance on paid blood donors is contributing to the rapid spread
of AIDS, a new law banning the buying and selling of blood takes
effect on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Medical centers all over China are bracing for disruptions. To
meet rising medical needs, China's hospitals use a system in which
poor people sell their blood, sometimes to middlemen who falsely
declare that their products have been screened for disease.
</P>
<P>
   Paying for blood, rather than relying on voluntary donations,
has been virtually banned in most countries because it promotes the
spread of AIDS, hepatitis and other infections. People who sell
their blood tend to be at high risk of such diseases and, as has
happened here, unhygienic centers trading in blood for profit may
themselves spread infections.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of a strong cultural aversion to donating blood,
China is unusually reliant on paid sources. According to official
statistics, which some experts consider understated, 40 percent of
all blood used in China has been sold. In some provinces, 90
percent of the blood supply is purchased, according to the official
press, which has carried lurid accounts of the blood trade and its
sometimes disastrous consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Given the high dependence on blood sellers, the new law cannot
be fully enforced for some time, senior blood bank officials admit.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Beijing, for example, collects only half the blood
it requires from local donations, and imports the rest from other
regions of the country, said Zhang Lichuan, an official at the
Fangshan Blood Station in a suburb of the city. Much of that
presumably involved paid donors. With the expected scarcity in
coming months, outside supplies are likely to dry up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if Beijing will be able to solve the shortage,''
Zhang said. ``If not, blood sellers and dealers may come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals will be forced to reduce the number of transfusions,
officials say _ as they have in the West in recent years, without
ill effect. Beijing hospitals plan to encourage surgery patients to
donate blood in advance. Donation quotas for work places may need
to be increased, officials said, and quotas may be imposed on
private companies and migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 15 years, the government tried to encourage
voluntary donations, but to limited effect. Many people fear,
according to traditional belief, that giving up blood will harm
their health. Some simply suspect the hygiene at donation centers
and overall, and there is no ethic of giving blood to strangers.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign has been announced to enlist one million medical
workers for donation. Soldiers will be required to donate once
every five years, and college students once during their four years
of school. But all this does not add up to the national need.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 survey by the Chinese Academy of Preventive Medicine
found that in some poor villages, half of all adults were selling
blood once a month or more. Traders known as ``blood bosses'' pay
the sources anywhere from $2.40 in poor villages to $24 in some
cities for each donation of varying amounts, according to various
accounts, then sell it to hospitals at high markups.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, all blood for medical uses here is screened for AIDS,
hepatitis and other diseases. In practice, the testing is not
always done. Official data show that 17 percent of the hundreds of
thousands of Chinese that have tested positive for the virus that
causes AIDS were infected by transfusions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
