u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-ART-700&AMP;A     09-30 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIPLOMATS VOICE OUTRAGE AT KOSOVO MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain, Canada)  (Eds: See also KOSOVO-MASSACRE) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ As NATO readied its forces for possible air
strikes against Yugoslavia Wednesday, the Security Council
scheduled an emergency meeting for Thursday to condemn the
massacres of ethnic Albanians last weekend by Serbian troops in
Kosovo and to consider future moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be no impunity for such an act of ethnic hatred,''
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook of Britain said at a news conference
in Blackpool, England, where he was attending a conference of his
Labor Party. ``This was not an act of war. This was plain cold
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain, which takes over the rotating presidency of the
Security Council on Thursday, called for the urgent special
session, backed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Council, which last week demanded an immediate end to
attacks on civilians by the Serbian-dominated Yugoslav army, is
expected to condemn President Slobodan Milosevic's forces in even
stronger terms, although the Council, with no troops at its
disposal, remains divided on what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and officials here reacted Wednesday with shock not
only at the horrific killings of civilians _ women, children and
elderly men shot through the head, mutilated or burned to death in
their homes _ but also at the audacity that Milosevic displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats have watched the Yugoslav leader flout world opinion
before through years of fighting in the Balkans, but not as boldly
as he has in recent weeks, as he continues his ruthless suppression
of the ethnic Albanians, a majority in the province where an ethnic
Albanian rebel force, the Kosovo Liberation Army, has been battling
the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   That rebellion, Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Wednesday,
``can never justify the pattern of terror, including the burning of
houses, looting, killing of livestock and wanton killing that have
been reported in these last few days.''
</P>
<P>
   `` Such actions are totally unacceptable to the international
community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Annan was described as ``outraged'' by the descriptions of the
massacres published Wednesday since he had met only Tuesday with
Yugoslavia's foreign minister and delivered a sharp message to him
after hearing reports of atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reports are particularly shocking to the secretary-general
in light of denials received from the foreign minister that such
actions were taking place,'' said Fred Eckhard, the
secretary-general's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International said Wednesday that the massacres in
Kosovo underline the urgent need for human rights monitors in the
area. Last week, the Security Council made that one of its demands.
The European Union and other organizations have volunteered to
monitor Kosovo, but have been rebuffed by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, Cook, the foreign secretary, said that he had been
in touch with the War Crimes Tribunal for the Balkans in The Hague
and had asked its prosecutor, Louise Arbour of Canada, to
investigate the massacres in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Cook also called a meeting in London on Friday of senior
officials from nations that call themselves the contact group on
the former Yugoslavia _ Britain, Germany, France, Italy, Russia and
the United States _ to discuss how to settle the problem
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and France are opposed or very reluctant to condone the
use of force against Yugoslavia at this stage, and would argue that
further Security Council action is needed before it can be seen to
be condoning NATO action. In the Security Council, China could not
even be persuaded last week to join the warning to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the contact group will also meet in New York
on Thursday at the diplomatic level, envoys said here.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright spoke with
her British counterpart by telephone several times Wednesday,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reservations in the Security Council, NATO planning for
air strikes is now complete, Britain's defense secretary, George
Robertson, said Wednesday. He told reporters that the organization
was proposing sharply targeted military strikes on Serb forces, not
random bombing, which would only worsen the situation on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Some NATO officials say that military action could begin as soon
as next week, after Annan is expected to report to the Security
Council on Yugoslav compliance with its demands.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is far from clear, however, that this link is essential,
since the United States has already stated that NATO has the
authority now to strike the Yugoslav forces attacking civilians.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, last week's Security Council resolution was passed
under a provision of the U.N. charter that makes it enforceable by
military means. On the Security Council, the problem is more
political than tactical.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Solana, NATO's secretary-general, also did not rule out
the use of force under the existing Security Council resolution. On
a visit to Azerbaijan, Solana said that NATO's reaction would be
determined by ``what happens on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The behavior of Milosevic should be judged by his deeds, not
by his words,'' he said. ``Too many words have not been complied
with by Milosevic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
