<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2887 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VARITEK-BOS &LR;      09-30 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VARITEK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARITEK DOESN'T REGRET NOT THROWING THE BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Kenny Lofton admitted that he was in a pickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stuck right there,'' said Lofton. ``They had me stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland center fielder said that getting caught off second
base on Omar Vizquel's fly to left in the second inning with one
out Wednesday was no ruse, no ploy to create a rundown so Joey Cora
could score from third. No, it was a Lofton mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stuck right there,'' Lofton said, ``and it was just a
case of playing it out to see what happens. You just can't sit out
there and do nothing and say, `You're out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even on a day when much of Boston's pitching seemed to have been
dug out of baseball's deepest archives of horror flicks, the Red
Sox did not help themselves in the field. ``We made some mental
mistakes out there,'' said third baseman John Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   Primary among them was the play in the second. Vizquel hit a fly
to medium left that was caught by Troy O'Leary. What happened next
caused both Lofton and Red Sox catcher Jason Varitek to be caught
in a freeze frame.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary threw home, but his throw sailed above the head of
Valentin, the cutoff man, which immediately made the situation more
complex. Cora bluffed for home and headed back to third. As he was
doing that, Lofton was some 25 or 30 feet off second, ripe for the
final out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stuck in no man's land there,'' said Lofton. ``It was a
case that if (Varitek) throws to second to get me, then maybe Joey
takes off for home.''
</P>
<P>
   If O'Leary's throw home had been low enough for Valentin to
handle, the third baseman might have been able to pounce on Lofton
more easily and perhaps make the play for the third out. But the
throw flew into Varitek's glove at the plate, and the catcher chose
not to throw to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought was to keep the runner on third from
scoring,'' said Varitek. ``So what I did was I immediately checked
him and I started to run (toward Lofton near shortstop). But I was
off balance and I didn't want to throw the ball when I was off
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   As Varitek recalled the play, Lofton ``already had enough
momentum toward second base, so I didn't make the throw. I mean, we
have two outs, and the most important thing is outs. I just thought
at the time that I was making sure the runner at third was not
going to score. I didn't think two things about it when it
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But then David Justice, the next Cleveland batter, swatted a
three-run homer, the telling blow in the Indians' 9-5 win in Game 2
of the American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek was asked if he had any regrets then about holding the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not really,'' said the catcher, who also had a record two
passed balls on Tim Wakefield knucklers. ``I mean, it was a
mistake. (Justice) hit a mistake pitch. I don't second-guess not
throwing the ball, not in the least bit.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Justice was understandably grateful. ``I was
standing back there behind the plate and I was able to see what was
going on,'' said the DH. ``Kenny is really so fast, so Varitek not
wanting to make a mistake with a throw, he probably just played it
cautious. That's probably why he didn't throw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is probably another reason why the Red Sox lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
