<HEADER>
A2895 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTLER-BIBLE-CHALLENG     09-30 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-BIBLE-CHALLENGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRESTLING WITH BIBLICAL CRITICISM: IT'S NOT SUNDAY SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``What do you mean,'' exclaimed one student, ``that there's no
evidence for a worldwide flood?''
 &HT;    My colleague explained again that no reliable historical or
scientific evidence exists to prove Noah's Ark. The students --
shocked by his scholarly bombshell -- struggled to maintain their
composure.
 &HT;    Every fall, in college and seminary classrooms across the
country, first-year religion students encounter ideas upsetting to
their faith. Most expected Bible courses to be like Sunday school.
They did not expect rigorous critical challenges to the Hebrew and
Christian scriptures.
 &HT;    Biblical criticism is not new. For more than a century, biblical
scholars have employed literary, historical, and other critical
methods to the Bible to better understand its context and message.
 &HT;    Whether they realize it or not, most church people understand
basic biblical criticism. My Sunday school teacher said that Moses
wrote the first five books of the Bible. Yet, when I read the text,
I noticed something odd. Moses wrote his own death scene! How could
that be?
 &HT;    Being curious, I spotted other contradictions. Why did Genesis 1
and 2 seem so different? Why did Peter deny Jesus on six occasions
instead of three? Why were Luke's and Matthew's accounts of Jesus'
birth distinctive?
 &HT;    As if the Bible's internal discrepancies were not enough,
teachers provided additional difficulties to ponder: what about
dinosaurs? a six-day creation? Adam and Eve? a bodily resurrection?
By high school graduation, believing in the Bible is tough.
 &HT;    Then a final blow: some Harvard Ph.D. spouting off about
``myth.'' What's a student to think?
 &HT;    Biblical scholarship explores questions raised by both the text
and by knowledge external to the scriptures. Often their
conclusions -- such as the biblical flood is a myth -- prove
disconcerting to people of faith. Ministers, priests and rabbis
often sidestep these issues with their congregations.
 &HT;    Conservatives insist that Isaiah himself wrote the book of the
Bible that bears his name, while more recent scholarship indicates
that two or three people wrote the book. As we quipped in seminary,
``Three Isaiahs just doesn't preach well.''
 &HT;    Silence regarding these questions helps no one. How do believers
deal with intellectual problems raised by the Bible -- as well as
controversial findings of biblical scholars?
 &HT;    One possibility is, of course, to chuck it. When some people
encounter these problems, they reject the Bible -- ``a bunch of
myths and superstitions'' -- as in any way meaningful to life.
 &HT;    But doubters and atheists aren't alone in chucking it. Believers
often dismiss science, history or biblical scholarship as ``secular
humanism.'' They ridicule science, doubt the findings of history
and archeology, and refuse to engage contemporary intellectual
debate. They sometimes construct elaborate pseudo-scholarship to
prove their beliefs -- and prove that secular scholarship is a
conspiracy undermining Christian truth.
 &HT;    A second possibility is to compartmentalize one's faith and
intellectual life. This option, encouraged by public education, is
an easy way around the tensions. Be devout on the weekend. But in
class or on the job, just do your work. Don't let religion intrude
on your study of biology or anthropology; don't let biology or
anthropology trouble your private prayer. Science is science. Faith
is faith.
 &HT;    Most of us, however, do not live in neat, little boxes. We may
try to bracket, but eventually stuff spills over the edges. Some
professor's lecture sends you reeling. A co-worker commits an
egregious ethical violation. Faith and life collide.
 &HT;    The third -- and most difficult -- option is to allow faith and
intellect to speak with one another. Because of the pressure to
separate religion from other spheres, any attempt to integrate --
rather than segregate -- heart and mind can be daunting. Yet the
pursuit of wholeness -- spiritual and intellectual -- is central to
the quest to know and love God.
 &HT;    To integrate faith and learning, the conversation must consist
of equal partners. One should be fully open to the questions of
both belief and inquiry. Faith and intellect are equally challenged
and challenging. Everything is up for grabs -- with all the
tensions, ambiguities, paradoxes and problems. And therein lies the
adventure.
 &HT;    I commiserate with my students struggling with Noah's story. It
took years for me to accept that the first chapter of Genesis is
poetry, that no wise men showed up at Jesus' birth, and Paul did
not write I Timothy.
 &HT;    Wrestling with contemporary biblical criticism has helped me to
understand that historic literalism and scientific accuracy are not
the Bible's point.
 &HT;    This knowledge, much to my surprise, did not lead to infidelity.
Rather, it has led to a deeper experience of God through the
biblical texts. I've learned to ask different questions of the
Bible -- broader, more relevant, and tougher questions about
meaning, faith and ethics.
 &HT;    Biblical scholarship makes me a better Christian -- not a
secular humanist or atheist.
 &HT;    It may not preach easily, but ultimately, it preaches well.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
