<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGHWAY-GUARD-RAILS-N     09-30 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHWAY-GUARD-RAILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT TO BAN INSTALLATION OF 2 KINDS OF HIGHWAY GUARD RAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Spelling of thrie-beam in 9th and 11th grafs cq.) 
 (sw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Federal Highway Administration is banning, as of
Thursday, all further installation of two popular kinds of guard
rail along government-financed highways after determining that the
guard rails cause full-sized pickup trucks to roll over during
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Pickup trucks are designed to climb up and over obstacles, a
feature that is useful on muddy farms and construction sites but
can be dangerous when they hit guard rails. Most sport utility
vehicles are based on pickup designs and some ride even higher off
the ground, leading many researchers to suspect that sport utility
vehicles may also fare poorly when they strike guard rails. But few
tests have been done with such vehicles, which have only recently
become popular, so nobody knows whether they pose a problem.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials said there were no plans to replace
hundreds of thousands of miles of guard rails because of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   About 15,000 Americans are killed each year when their vehicles
leave the road. About 1,100 of these deaths occur in crashes that
begin when vehicles hit guard rails. Many other deaths occur in
crashes that begin on the road and then send one or more vehicles
into the guard rails, but the government lacks accurate statistics
on these crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph Umbs, the chief of the safety designs and operations
division of the Federal Highway Administration, said changes in the
nation's highways inevitably lagged behind changes in what
Americans drive, including the the fast-growing popularity of sport
utility vehicles and pickup trucks. The best answer is for people
to drive more carefully in vehicles that are harder to handle, Umbs
said, while declining to discuss specific classes of vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drivers should know their vehicles and the capabilities of
their vehicles and drive accordingly,'' Umbs said. The National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration already requires labels on
small and mid-sized sport utility vehicles, warning that they are
more likely than other vehicles to roll over during sharp turns.
</P>
<P>
   When two-wheel-drive pickups were pushed into the two banned
guard rails at a 25-degree angle at 62 miles per hour in tests over
the last several years, the vehicles consistently rolled over,
although they stayed on the road. The reason apparently lies in how
the front ends of pickups are designed, said King Mak, who oversaw
the tests at the Texas Transportation Institute, a state agency in
College Station that does virtually all of the nation's guard rail
research under contracts from the federal government and guard rail
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike cars, pickup trucks and sport utility vehicles have
wheels that are fairly exposed, with little protection for the
wheels from these vehicles' high bumpers and minimal wheel wells.
The positioning of the wheels makes it possible for drivers to
scale muddy mountain trails.
</P>
<P>
   But in tests, the pickup wheels climbed up one of the banned
rails, a thrie-beam rail that looks like a triple ripple when
viewed from the side. The pickup wheels also tended to snag on the
support posts of the other kind of banned rail, a corrugated metal
beam that looks like the letter W from the side and is mounted to
the post with steel blocks that tend to twist on impact.
</P>
<P>
   The wheel problems caused the pickups to roll over in tests with
both types of guard rails, which account for roughly half of the
nation's guard rails.
</P>
<P>
   The thrie-beam rails can be fixed by replacing steel support
posts with wooden posts, while the W-beam rails can be fixed by
replacing the steel blocks with wooden blocks, which are thicker
and twist less, Mak said.
</P>
<P>
   Sport utility vehicles have more weight on the rear tires and so
may be less dangerous than pickups upon impact with guard rails, he
said. A two-wheel-drive Ford Explorer and a two-wheel-drive
Chevrolet Tracker, for example, did not flip over in tests at a
shallower angle than was used for the pickup tests.
</P>
<P>
   But no tests have been done on four-wheel-drive sport utility
vehicles, which tend to ride two or three inches higher, so nobody
really knows what happens when they hit guard rails, Mak said. A
federally financed review of national crash records has found that
sport utility vehicles are a little less likely than cars to hit
guard rails, but are more than twice as likely to roll over when
they do, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some safety experts are starting to advise drivers of pickups
and sport utility vehicles to drive more slowly and cautiously on
bridges and twisting roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going at a lower speed, your propensity for getting
up and over the barrier is lower and your propensity for rolling
over is lower,'' said Dean Sicking, director of the Midwest
Roadside Safety Facility at the University of Nebraska at Lincoln.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
