<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOICES OF WATERGATE HAUNTING CONGRESS IN CLINTON INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-SCHIPPERS, CLINTON-TEENS) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES BENNET and ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leading Democrats and Republicans here are being
haunted by youthful voices of 24 years ago, during Watergate. The
voices are their own.
</P>
<P>
   Gripped by a sense that the hypocrisy is getting thicker than
their sideburns of yore, Republicans and Democrats are turning
history and memory into political weapons as they square off over
possible impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, their proxies, President Clinton and Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, exchanged accusations of conflicting standards
in the Watergate and Lewinsky inquiries. On Capitol Hill, Democrats
and Republicans clashed over how precisely the investigation of
this president should mimic the inquiry about President Richard M.
Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   To Republicans, the Judiciary Committee's impeachment inquiry of
1974 is now a model of congressional restraint and judiciousness.
To Democrats _ who had previously called for the Watergate-style
rules _ that is now too broad an approach.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Democrats noted with delight that minority
Republicans in 1974 were granted subpoena power _ a precedent not
all Republicans are thrilled with.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's Democrats and Republicans reached no agreement
on the scope of the investigation Wednesday. Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., the committee's chairman, dispatched a letter to Rep. John
Conyers Jr. of Michigan, its senior Democrat, gently suggesting he
was being a hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde wrote, ``I want to propose that the model for impeachment''
that the committee should follow ``is the one that you helped to
write in 1974.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott started Democratic aides rummaging through the archives of
his quotations by saying on Tuesday that ``bad conduct'' might be
an impeachable offense. They popped up with a dusty defense of
Nixon by Lott, who was a member of the House Judiciary Committee in
1974. He said that a president should be removable ``only for
serious misconduct dangerous to the system of government'' and not
for ``general misbehavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, White House spokesman Mike McCurry accused Lott of an
apparent ``double standard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His constitutional thinking has undergone quite an
evolution,'' he observed, adding: ``I think he kind of got caught
up in the reverie of memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's spokesman, John Czwartacki, had his own quotation at the
ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is Bill Clinton who seems to have undergone a convenient
memory lapse,'' he said. ``In 1974, Bill Clinton said a president
should be impeached if he admits to lying and interfering with a
government investigation. In 1998, Bill Clinton believes it's his
right not only to lie to the American people and thwart lawful
investigations of his conduct, but to lie under an oath before
God.''
</P>
<P>
   On August 7, 1974, Bill Clinton _ then a shaggy-haired law
professor at the University of Arkansas _ criticized his opponent
in a congressional race for opposing Nixon's resignation. He was
quoted the next day by the Arkansas Gazette as saying there was
``no question that an admission of making false statements to
government officials and interfering with the FBI and the CIA is an
impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the comment in the town of Flippin, where he would
later make an investment in Ozarks property known as Whitewater
that, through many twists and turns, would bring him to the brink
of impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   To Democrats, Watergate and Clinton's predicament over Monica
Lewinsky _ which still lacks a catchy, one-word nickname _ bear no
resemblance. McCurry appeared at his daily briefing Wednesday armed
for a question about comparisons to Watergate. He got it, and
almost ran out of breath as he rattled off a lengthy list of the
accusations against Nixon, including that he ``misused the FBI,
(and) the Secret Service, to conduct unlawful wiretapping of
American citizens'' and that he ``maintained a secret unit in the
White House to violate the constitutional rights of citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   After pausing slightly for air, McCurry added indignantly, ``So
there's no parallel whatsoever.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet there is something of a parallel _ at least through the
looking glass _ in the political commentary. Back in 1974, Conyers
complained about White House ``stonewalling,'' while then-Rep. Lott
_ in remarks that make James Carville sound like a plagiarist _
objected to ``15 months of the most intensive investigation of any
president of the United States, perhaps of any man.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott added, ``Could any man withstand such scrutiny, could any
man go through all of this without some evidence of a questionable
statement under pressure, or while frustrated, or even without
revealing some mistakes?''
</P>
<P>
   Such sweeping comments aside, Lott and Conyers, in their remarks
in the committee, built their attacks or defenses out of the
specific facts of Watergate. Transcripts are packed with period
references to tax evasion, wiretapping and bombs falling on
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   In the battle of musty quotations, Conyers came under criticism
from Republicans Wednesday for having switched his thinking in the
debate over how broad an inquiry the Judiciary Committee should
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In internal negotiations, Conyers had been seeking a time limit
on the inquiry. Republicans pointed out that on the House floor in
February 1974, Rep. Peter Rodino, D-N.J., then the committee's
chairman, derided the notion of a time limit as ``totally
irresponsible and unwise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans said that Conyers, then a member of the
Judiciary Committee, cast his vote against a time limit.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Conyers said that the situations were not comparable,
because, unlike in Watergate, most of the facts are already known
about Clinton's affair with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, a House resolution charged the Judiciary Committee to
``investigate fully and completely'' whether sufficient grounds
existed to impeach Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, such a resolution would give the committee power to
pursue any impeachable offense, meaning it would not have to come
back to the full House for authority to widen its scope if it
wanted to go beyond the accusations related to Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde has consistently refused to rule out looking beyond the
Lewinsky matter, although he has also said that he wants to keep
the investigation focused. The Democrats want any investigation to
be limited to the president's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and
deceptions about it.
</P>
<P>
   But the House Democrats had been pressing for a Watergate model
_ which would also provide them with subpoena power _ so they found
themselves in an awkward position Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased to report that we have been given a
Watergate-type set of rules, which is what we have been asking
for,'' Conyers said, before going on to criticize such rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that this investigation should be open-ended like
Watergate, as the speaker continues to insist, is preposterous,''
he said. ``Watergate involved a wholesale corruption of government
which extended through the FBI the CIA and other federal agencies.
This matter involves the concealing of a private affair for which
the vast majority of facts is already known.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
