<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISER-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI BUSINESSMAN INDICTED FOR MAKING ILLEGAL CAMPAIGN
CONTRIBUTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal grand jury on Wednesday indicted a Miami
businessman on charges of making illegal contributions to
Democratic candidates, including $23,000 in allegedly fraudulent
donations to President Clinton's 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-count indictment, returned in Federal District Court
here, accused Mark Jimenez of defrauding the Federal Election
Commission and conspiring to commit criminal violations of election
laws by using straw donors to make a total of $39,500 in political
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez, who did not return phone calls to his office, is the
chief executive of Future Tech International Inc., a distributor of
computer components and peripherals. The indictment contended that
the contributions were made in the names of employees of Future
Tech and a company owned by a close relative of Jimenez, who later
reimbursed the employees with his own or his company's money.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said Jimenez's actions illegally impeded the
commission in regulating elections and were intended to seek
influence for himself and his company with political leaders and
officials of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The charges involve contributions to the Clinton-Gore primary
election committee in 1996 and to other Democrats, including the
1994 re-election campaign of Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts.
The indictment said that improper contributions were also made to
three Democratic senatorial candidates in 1996, Robert Torricelli
of New Jersey, Thomas Strickland of Colorado and Roger Bedford of
Alabama, and a House candidate, Ann Henry of Arkansas. All except
Torricelli were defeated by their Republican opponents.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication from the indictment that any of the
candidates knew that the contributions were made through what are
known as conduit contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said on Wednesday that the
prosecution was the 12th campaign finance case brought by the
Justice Department, and indicated that the campaign finance unit
``is not letting up.''
</P>
<P>
   But four of the charges accusing Jimenez of false statements
could be in jeopardy. The accusations are similar to counts that
were thrown out on Sept. 10 by a Federal District judge in
Washington, who ruled against the department in the case of Maria
Hsia, another Democratic fund-raiser accused of violating campaign
finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   In that ruling the judge, Paul Friedman, threw out five of six
counts against Ms. Hsia, saying the government made an ``Alice in
Wonderland-like maze of logical leaps and tangled inferences'' to
build a theory that the judge said ``defies logic and stretches
almost beyond recognition the two criminal statutes on which it
relies.''
</P>
<P>
   Department officials said they were considering an appeal of the
ruling in the Hsia case. In addition, Ms. Reno is considering
whether to seek an independent prosecutor to investigate other
potential illegalities stemming from Clinton's re-election
campaign. She has until November to decide whether to seek such an
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 90-day inquiries centers on whether Vice President Al
Gore was truthful in his statements about his telephone fund
raising from the White House. Another focuses on whether Harold
Ickes, a former deputy White House chief of staff, lied about
efforts to assist the Teamsters union in a labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The third inquiry is centered on whether the president violated
federal election laws in an effort to raise millions of dollars
that was diverted to state parties to finance political advertising
campaigns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
