<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QTR-WINNERS-ART-NYT &LR;      09-30 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QTR-WINNERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW STOCKS ESCAPE THIRD-QUARTER CARNAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also QTR-DEALS, QTR-MUTFUNDS)  
(ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even after many lesser stocks had faded, America's
blue chips sailed into the third quarter seemingly headed for yet
another year of improbably outsize gains. On July 17 the Dow Jones
industrial average reached 9,337.97, with commentators still
talking of the just-right ``Goldilocks economy'' and mulling the
existence of a possible ``new era.''
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be the pinnacle. Before long, the blue chips
joined the rest of the stock market in a general slide as an array
of negatives came together at once. Wednesday the Dow dropped
237.90 points, dragging the popular index back into minus territory
for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big consumer stocks are the ones that took the beating,''
said Rao Chalasani, investment strategist at Everen Securities in
Chicago, summing up the worst quarter for the stock market in eight
years. ``Finally things started catching up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Laszlo Birinyi, consultant on trading strategy to Deutsche Bank
Securities, said, ``It was like a New Year's Eve party that ended
at 11 o'clock. People were still dancing when the music stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Asian problems flared again, Russian leadership grew shakier,
the hoped-for gentle deceleration of the U.S. economy suddenly
threatened an acute profit squeeze and President Clinton's grip on
the White House came into serious doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks of tumbling prices preceded a gut-wrenching drop on the
final day of August, a 512.61-point reality check that was the
second-biggest point loss on record. After this, the Dow and the
rest of the market regained some footing before sagging again at
quarter's end.
</P>
<P>
   There was little that escaped the third-quarter carnage. The
30-stock Dow industrials dropped 12.39 percent during the
July-September period, the worst since its 14.86 percent decline in
the third quarter of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 10.30 percent and the
Nasdaq market index _ bolstered by a few technology giants _ eked
out a gain of sixty-onehundreths of 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of this summer's swoon remains. Nervousness and
volatility now mark most trading sessions. The specter of an
overseas meltdown, profit erosion and other worries are beginning
to be reflected in the American economy in the form of lower
capital spending, diminished consumer confidence and more caution
among lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous market leaders have warned recently of profit
shortfalls, further battering their shares. Coca-Cola, for example,
lost 32.6 percent of its share value during the past three months.
American Express lost 31.8 percent; Sears, Roebuck, 27.6 percent,
and Walt Disney and J.P. Morgan 27.7 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find another time in recent stock market history when the
thinking shifted so dramatically,'' said Byron Wien, chief U.S.
strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``This is a major change
in attitude _ and it probably isn't over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the shift was reflected in statements _ and
this week in action _ by the Federal Reserve, where officials kept
reappraising the balance of economic and financial risks and found
that concern about unsustainably rapid growth and revived inflation
had given way to their opposites. On Tuesday the Fed cut the target
rate for short-term interest rates, the first reduction in nearly
three years.
</P>
<P>
   In a single quarter, observed Marshall Acuff, equity strategist
at Salomon Smith Barney, ``you've seen Fed policy go from
potentially restrictive to neutral to ease'' as it became
increasingly worried about exposure to foreign economic and
financial storms.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Dow components, the biggest loss was 38.1 percent by
the Travelers Group, which succumbed to the general implosion of
financial shares and the large foreign exposure of Citicorp, its
merger partner, Citicorp. finished the quarter at 93, barely half
its April peak of 182.
</P>
<P>
   As always, however, there were exceptions _ stocks that powered
through the downdraft, indeed attracting some money pulled from
those that stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer, for example, soared 41.7 percent to close at
$65.75, a performance that topped the company's 37 percent surge
during the spring when its market value surpassed that of General
Motors. IBM, not that long ago mired in the category of fallen
star, climbed 11.5 percent over the summer, the second-best Dow
performer, following a 10.5 percent second-quarter gain.
</P>
<P>
   The top Dow stock among its eight quarterly gainers was Philip
Morris, up 17 percent, as the legal cloud over tobacco issues
lifted a bit and some skittish investors, mindful of the company's
strong food and Miller beer businesses, turned defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of two other major brewers, Anheuser-Busch and Coors, had
strong summers before surrendering some gains in the quarter's
final week.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities, another defensive sector that benefits from falling
interest rates as well, bucked the down trend, too. The Dow Jones
utility average rose 4.4 percent for the quarter, with Peco Energy
up 25.3 percent and Con Edison up 13.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Health-related issues also showed resilience. Johnson &AMP; Johnson
climbed 5.7 percent, and Long's Drug soared 39.2 percent as the
second best gainer among the S&AMP;P 500. Amoco, which British
Petroleum is buying, jumped 29 percent to top a generally stable
energy group as depressed oil prices edged higher.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts took some comfort in scattered strength among
cyclical stocks because their continued slump could have pointed
toward recession. International Paper, for example, was the third
strongest Dow stock during the quarter, rising 8.4 percent, while
Alcoa was right behind with a gain of 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the domestic economy is healthier than we anticipated,''
Birinyi said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
