<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE CRISIS CATCHES ATTENTION OF AMERICA'S YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-CONGRESS and CLINTON-SCHIPPERS) 
(JT) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The crisis in the White House has caught the attention of
America's young people, according to a poll released Wednesday,
with parents reporting that as many as 30 percent of their
teen-agers had watched part of President Clinton's grand jury
testimony and 21 percent had read at least part of the Starr
report.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations against Clinton arising out of his relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky have led to more
family discussions about politics, according to the poll, which was
conducted by the Pew Research Center for the People and The Press.
Almost half the parents of children over 13, a third of those with
children from 11 to 13, and almost a quarter of those with children
8 to 10, said they had discussed politics with their children more
than usual since the Lewinsky case erupted in January.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted on Sept. 19-23, was based on telephone
interviews with a nationally representative sample of 597 parents
with children 8 to 17. The margin of sampling error is plus or
minus five percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Children of different ages reacted differently, the parents
reported. While most children, at every age, were interested in
what would happen to Clinton, teen-agers were more often amused by
the accusations against the president than disturbed by them, while
children 8 to 10 were more confused by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an upside to this, in that it's getting more people to
talk about politics,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of the research
center. ``But clearly with people saying it's making their kids
lose respect for politics, and the kinds of things people are
talking about, it's not good for America's youth. I was struck that
so many parents of the younger children felt it would be harmful to
their long-term views of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Among parents of children 8 to 10 years old, 42 percent said the
Clinton-Lewinsky situation would harm their child's view of
government, while among the parents of teen-agers, only 29 percent
had that view, and 20 percent said the White House crisis would
help their child's view of government.
</P>
<P>
   Republican parents tended to take a more negative view of the
impact on their children than did Democratic ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the polling we've done on this, the responses reflect
politics more than gender or anything else,'' Kohut said, ``and
it's true in parenting, too. These kids are clearly reflecting what
their mommies and daddies say, and the mommies and daddies are
clearly passing their views on to their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Partisan politics influenced both how much a family talked about
the White House crisis and what they said, the poll found.
Republican parents were far more likely than Democratic ones to
report that they had talked with their children about the scandal,
that their children were discussing the matter with their friends,
and that the scandal was making their children lose respect for
politicians. While 74 percent of the parents who disapprove of how
Clinton is handling his job said they had talked to their children
about whether he lied, only 47 percent of those who approve of the
president had done so.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, parents of teen-agers were more likely to have talked
with their children about Clinton's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky
than about the home-run race in baseball, while parents of younger
children were more likely to have discussed the baseball story than
the political one.
</P>
<P>
   When the Clinton-Lewinsky situation came up in conversation
between parents and children, most parents said, the talk was about
morals and values. But those with older children, especially, said
their discussions had also covered sex, their own views on Clinton
and whether he had lied, and whether the president should be
punished or forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, a child's age played a major role in
determining whether the sexual aspects of the situation had been
discussed. Only 17 percent of parents with children 8 to 10 had
talked about whether Clinton had sex with Ms. Lewinsky, and 33
percent had talked about sex in general. Among the parents of
teen-agers, 58 percent talked about Clinton's sexual behavior and
72 percent discussed sex in general.
</P>
<P>
   Across all age groups, fewer than one-third of the parents had
discussed the impeachment process with their children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
