<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUNT ADVICE FOR IMF IN MOSCOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's former tax chief urged the West on Wednesday
not to provide further financial aid unless Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov takes drastic measures to develop a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IMF should learn a lesson from the past five years,'' the
former official, Boris Fyodorov, said, referring to the
International Monetary Fund. ``The IMF was pretending that it was
seeing a lot of reforms in Russia. Russia was pretending to conduct
reforms. The Western taxpayer was paying for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov, an ardent pro-capitalist and veteran of Russia's
rough-and-tumble political wars, has long been known for his
outspokenness. But he is also the rarest of political figures: a
former aide who was in the inner councils of government just days
ago and is willing to talk openly about it.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissed on Monday from his posts as Russia's tax chief and
main economic strategist at the insistence of the Communists,
Fyodorov on Wednesday described a government that was clueless in
the face of growing economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   The government's commitment to economic reform is so shaky that
the West would do more harm than good if it provided fresh help at
this time, he asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, the Group of Seven industrialized nations
should present Russia with a list of 10 steps to build a market
economy and make sure they are carried out before handing over
billions of dollars in new loans and aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demand from Russia drastic economic reforms,'' he told a group
of Western correspondents. ``Giving us drugs in the form of more
money does not help Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov's assessment came as Primakov's team is struggling to
put together an economic plan to rescue the nation from its
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Kommersant Daily reported on Wednesday that Yuri
Maslyukov, the Communist aide who oversees economic policy, was
urging the nationalization of commercial banks, the creation of a
government Reconstruction and Development Bank to funnel credits to
Russian industry and a large increase in the money supply.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting disarray within the government's ranks, Viktor
Gerashchenko, the Communist who is head of the central bank, said
later that he differed with some of these proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Fyodorov said that most of the government's plans appeared to be
very sketchy when he left government a few days ago and that the
nation's top leaders had little sense of what to do.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin had all but detached himself from
economic policy, preferring to spend his limited energy on
diplomatic issues, Fyodorov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not really work for long on any program,'' Fyodorov
said. ``The president is 99 percent'' about military and foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, the former foreign minister and intelligence chief who
became prime minister this month, has the primary responsibility
for the economy. But he has little understanding of the intricacies
of modern economics and tax policy, Fyodorov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very far from the economy all his life,'' Fyodorov
said. ``I think at this stage he practically does not understand
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
