<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BURBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURBA READY FOR THE CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Mike Hargrove made it clear to Dave Burba what he
wanted from his new long reliever before Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians manager's speech was partly a pep talk, but part may
have been premonition. Although Hargrove had penciled in Doc Gooden
as the starter, he wanted Burba, a starter in 31 of his 32
appearances this season, to be ``on call'' all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Dave before the ballgame that I wanted him available
from the first pitch on,'' said Hargrove, ``because even if Doc got
in a little bit of trouble, I wasn't going to mess around. I was
going to go to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Burba found himself on the mound when Gooden was
ejected by plate umpire Joe Brinkman for protesting a play at home
after throwing only 22 pitches in the top of the first.
</P>
<P>
   All Burba did was respond with perhaps a series-saving
performance. He worked 5 1/3 strong innings, allowing four hits and
three runs, as the Indians beat the Red Sox, 9-5, and tied the
best-of-five American League Division Series at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   For Burba, the last week had been a deflating experience. A
starter in Hargrove's rotation all season, the righthander had won
15 games, as many as anyone on the staff. But, facing a short
series, Hargrove had to decide whether Gooden or Burba would join
Jaret Wright, Charles Nagy, and Bartolo Colon in the playoff
rotation. The odd man out would be relegated to long relief.
</P>
<P>
   Burba didn't really like the role, but he was prepared for it
mentally, if not physically. ``I was just stretching in the
bullpen,'' he said. ``When I saw Doc get thrown out, I knew I was
going in.''
</P>
<P>
   Burba's one bonus was that he was allowed as much time as he
needed to prepare, because in the case of ejections and injuries,
relievers are allowed unlimited warmup pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' said Burba, ``was a huge advantage for me. I could go
about getting ready almost like it was a normal start. I could tell
what pitches were working.''
</P>
<P>
   After working his way out of the mess _ and the 2-0 deficit _
that had been created when first Hargrove and then Gooden were
tossed for altercations with Brinkman, Burba settled into a rhythm
that had the Red Sox off balance for the next five innings.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed a run in the third, but by then, the Indians owned a
7-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   By the sixth, Burba was starting to wobble, allowing the Red Sox
to load the bases with none out. But he took the heat out of the
rally by inducing Darren Bragg to hit into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Third base coach Jeff Newman, filling in for Hargrove, felt
Burba had done more than his share and went further into his
bullpen to preserve the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd of 45,229 at Jacobs Field responded with a
standing ovation in appreciation of Burba's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Burba feels his role will remain the same for the rest of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Mike had stated it to me earlier when he told me
that I would be in the bullpen for the playoffs,'' Burba said. ``He
told me I was best suited for that situation because I had the
experience. Especially the way I pitched today, I don't think it's
going to vary one way or another whether I start or relieve. I
think that Mike is pretty happy with the way things went today, and
I probably will remain in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove isn't so sure. ``Right now I look at (Gooden and Burba)
changing roles here for a little bit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's role was just fine with Burba.
</P>
</TEXT>
