<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEAKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young student pushes peers to excel in school
 &HT;    By Derek Ali
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Children all over the world want to be like Mike.
</P>
<P>
   But after his exhilarating, edge-of-the-seat, motivational
presentation Wednesday, students at Van Cleve School for the Arts
want to be like Donte'.
</P>
<P>
   That's Donte' Shackelford, a 12-year-old Fairview student who
has already written a book (School Is My Job), served as a
consultant for a DMHA youth program and shared stages at Ohio
rallies with the Rev. Jesse Jackson and Bishop Desmond Tutu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could be like him and get good grades,'' said Dontay
Oliver, 10, a fifth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   Donte's baby face belies his ability to generate floor-shaking
enthusiasm while leading more than 400 students in chants. The
self-described ``infotainer'' even got the teachers and staff
rocking to his beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``School is your job, there is no excuse for failure. If you
can't read, you can't write. If you can't write, you can't spell.
If you can't spell, you will fail. If you fail, you will sell. If
you sell, you sail, straight to jail'' he shouted, reciting from a
poem from his book.
</P>
<P>
   Students clearly saw the charismatic, 4' 8'', 80-pound
youngster. What they didn't see was his hard work and preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Donte', who has been a motivational speaker since he was 4 years
old, spends at least four hours daily practicing and studying and
researching material he presents publicly. That's after six hours
of school, an hour of homework and 30 to 45 minutes of chores.
</P>
<P>
   Don Blanton, the student assistance provider at Van Cleve, said
he invited Donte' because he can ``help motivate our students in
their school work and show them how important school is and what
school can do for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Donte' said, ``I'm glad kids my age, my peer group, are looking
up to me. I'm also glad knowing they can do it too. All they have
to do is put their minds to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerrelle Franks, a 12-year-old sixth grader said, ``I think it
was a good program because they were communicating to the little
kids to keep them in school and not to do drugs. This program's
original to the kids and they reached out to the kids very
strongly.''
</P>
<P>
   Donte's interest in motivational speaking grew from observing
his role model and uncle, Black Brothers Involved/Black Sisters
Involved founder, Marlon Shackelford. Shackelford, his 4-year-old
son Marlon Jr. and 7-year-old Andre Peterson, also participated in
Wednesday's program.
</P>
<P>
   Donte' described the elder Shackelford as ``my mentor, my
friend, my surrogate father and role model.''
</P>
<P>
   Shackelford and his wife, Pam, are Donte's first audience,
Shackelford said. ``We look at good, excellent and great. The goal
for him right now is to be excellent so he can one day become
great. Our definition for great is when you can take your gift and
help others.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
