<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VALENTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTIN IN THE MIDDLE OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The game began at 1:07 p.m. By 1:09, Jacobs Field
had been transformed into the Land of the Attitudinal. You saw
players cursing umpires, umpires cursing players, and a manager
getting ejected after watching only three pitches. And all that
happened before an umpire named Joe Brinkman got cussed out for
what he saw, or didn't see, on a first-inning play at home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Some people believe that Midwesterners have the gentlest souls
in the nation. If that is true, those peaceful types weren't among
the 45,229 fans here Wednesday for Game 2 of the Red Sox-Indians
American League Division Series. We're not saying it was hostile.
We're not saying people should have chilled out and listened to
some tapes of waves rolling and birds chirping. We'll just direct
you to The Play at the plate, a play that established the rhythm of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I out?'' Sox third baseman John Valentin asked, long after
his team lost, 9-5. He was talking about The Play. He was told he
was definitely out. ``Oh, (expletive),'' he said. He smiled. It was
strange. You would have fainted if you had seen anyone smile two
hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   After Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove had been thrown out of the
game for arguing balls and strikes with Brinkman, Indians starter
Dwight Gooden decided he would go back to work and not worry about
the umpire.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was challenging me,'' Gooden said. ``He was taking off
his mask and saying something. I couldn't even understand what he
was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden stopped listening. He had to deal with Valentin on first
base and Darren Lewis on third. So the man everyone knows as Doc
struck out Mo Vaughn for his only out of the day. But Nomar
Garciaparra got ahold of Gooden's 22d and last pitch, a fastball,
and drove it to left field. Lewis scored easily. Valentin had been
running on contact and was already heading toward third when he saw
left fielder Brian Giles with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that Giles made a clean pick of the ball off the wall,''
Valentin said. ``I knew it would be close.''
</P>
<P>
   Except it wasn't close. The ball came in to catcher Sandy Alomar
long before Valentin got to the plate. Alomar did all the things
they teach you in Little League. He blocked the runner's path. And
he tagged him on the forearm. You looked for the ball to squirt out
of the glove; it didn't. You looked for some quirk, some
complicated slide that would allow Valentin to score; neither was
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see the replay?'' Alomar said. ``I saw it three times.
I tagged him. It wasn't even close.''
</P>
<P>
   Brinkman didn't think so. In fact, he didn't think a lot of
things. He thought Gooden was throwing balls rather than strikes.
He thought Gooden was showing him up and tried to tell him about
it, gesturing toward the mound. ``I couldn't hear him,'' Alomar
said of the umpire. ``It's so much noise out there, sometimes you
can't hear people standing real close to you.''
</P>
<P>
   So Brinkman called Valentin safe at the plate when he obviously
was not safe. The score was 2-0. Gooden went up to Brinkman and
said, ``Get in the (expletive) game.'' Brinkman told Gooden to get
out of the game. The pitcher charged after the umpire. The crowd
cursed and gestured at Brinkman, too. Hours later, a television
reporter would do a live report, saying Brinkman needed an attitude
adjustment. And a radio reporter would tell his listeners that he
had a problem with Brinkman because he sets up ``in a different
area code than the catcher'' to do the very intimate job of calling
balls and strikes.
</P>
<P>
   We're not saying it was a hostile scene, but ...
</P>
<P>
   Gooden's teammates held him back. You could read his lips and
see that he was not saying very nice things. Earlier, Hargrove
could be seen telling Brinkman, ``Don't (expletive) touch me.''
After the game, Gooden said he had no intentions of hurting the
umpire. ``I just wanted to give him my hat and glove and tell him
that he could pitch,'' Gooden explained.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Cleveland clubhouse said the incident inspired the
team, a team that has been playing placidly for the past couple of
months. By the second inning, the Indians had scored six runs and
gotten the best of Tim Wakefield. It was obvious that the series
was going to be tied. And in the ninth inning, when Mike Jackson
and Valentin had words after the reliever threw inside, it was also
obvious that animosity was going to be hanging around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's wearing those elbow pads for a reason,'' Jackson said.
``It looked like he was trying to dive into the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin said he was just playing his game. And Alomar said the
two men just had ``a misunderstanding.'' It certainly wasn't the
first one of the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
