<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHIPPERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID SCHIPPERS: DEMOCRATIC OUTSIDER LEADS GOP INQUIRY ON CLINTON  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (deletes repeated grafs 9 and 10, `Democrats have complained...'
and `It is Schippers' task...')   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ David Schippers, chief investigator on the House
Judiciary Committee, and his boss, Rep. Henry Hyde, bowed their
heads together at a ceremony in Cleveland three years ago and left
church a pair of papal knights.
</P>
<P>
   The honor, given to several hundred Roman Catholics who promote
the church's interests, rekindled the two men's acquaintance,
Schippers said, but it also bestowed on them privileges, like
trotting into a Catholic church on a horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I run into anyone on the way to the gallows,'' Schippers
also said, ``I can pardon them.''
</P>
<P>
   That may seem an unlikely stroke of charity for the lawyer
heading the Republican inquiry into possible impeachment charges
against the president of the United States. But President Clinton
could do much worse than Schippers, a salty Chicagoan whose
Democratic bloodline runs hard through a clan of police captains
and firefighters, and, most recently, a ``radical feminist''
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say I'm a Democrat, that is not a title,'' he said,
clearly relishing his role as outsider on the committee, ``that is
a commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Schippers was the man chosen to face off against
Clinton, a president he voted for twice, was a curious stroke on
the part of Hyde and Republican leaders, who hope, against most
odds, to maintain at least the veneer of bipartisanship during the
inquiry. So far, the proceedings have been chiefly marked by raw
party disputes, and Schippers has had little power to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the day the panel will vote on whether to proceed
with an impeachment inquiry, Schippers will formally address the
Judiciary Committee for the first time, as he and his Democratic
counterpart, Abbe Lowell, discuss the evidence sent to Congress by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr. Democrats have complained that,
so far, committee staff members have spent most of their time
poring over the documents simply to decide what to release, not to
judge their substance.
</P>
<P>
   It is Schippers' task, as well as Lowell's, to analyze the
evidence and determine whether Starr's case is legally sound,
leaving it up to the committee to decide whether to go forward with
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rancor on the panel, Schippers said he would strive
for fairness, regardless of the difficulties, something his current
and former colleagues say has characterized his style since way
back. And he is likely to go about it in an unorthodox manner, at
least for Washington, keeping a respectable distance from the
television lights, the city's power clutch and the carpeted aisles
at Brooks Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Schippers chose to ignore Washington's stable of
lawyers and criminal investigators, bringing with him a team of
specialists from Chicago, including former prosecutors, agents from
the FBI and Internal Revenue Service, and the current tactical
sergeant for the Chicago Police Department. He also brought his son
on board as a lawyer, which left him open to charges of nepotism.
</P>
<P>
   There are ``zero'' Harvard Law School graduates on the team, he
said. ``These lawyers are all guys who squeaked through law school
in South America, for all I know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers agreed to take the Judiciary Committee job in March,
he said, because Hyde asked him. ``The last thing in the world I
wanted is to come out here and do this,'' said the 68-year-old
defense lawyer and former prosecutor who first met Hyde in 1969,
when they both served on an anti-crime panel in Chicago. ``I
figured I had put in my time. I had no political or professional
ambition. I don't want to write books or go on television or be a
big star. My philosophy is come out here, do the job and get out,
go home.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Schippers sees it, he has already peaked professionally,
at 30, back when he slapped handcuffs around the wrists of
legendary Chicago mob boss Sam Giancana.
</P>
<P>
   That was during the 1960s, when Schippers fell in with Robert
Kennedy's gangbusters vision and went to work for the Justice
Department. He eventually became the chief of the organized crime
and racketeering section in Chicago, where he came up with a plan
to immunize Giancana, which got him laughed out of every boss'
office along the food chain until he got to the attorney general
himself, Nicholas deB. Katzenbach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we immunized Giancana, that started the house of cards
falling in the Chicago outfit for two, three years there,''
Schippers said.
</P>
<P>
   His run-ins with ``the outfit'' never worried him too much, he
said. ``I wouldn't screw around with their family and they wouldn't
screw around with mine,'' he said. ``It was an unholy agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But the neighbors could not help but feel a pang of anxiety
about the possibility of a neighborhood blood bath, so, one week,
they took up a collection, knocked on Schippers' door and handed
him a gift. It was a set of oversized numbers for the front of his
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want anybody to make a mistake, am I right?''
Schippers asked his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the Justice Department in 1967, Schippers went
into private practice and made a living defending a ``jillion'' law
enforcement agents and wading though labor cases. More recently, he
dabbled in sexual harassment lawsuits, on both sides of the issue,
and spent time on cases involving race and religious
discrimination. He is also on the public defender's panel, taking
any case offered to him that does not involve the mob or drug
peddlers.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers' rumpled demeanor and streetwise, self-effacing charm
tend to dust over a streak so tough that even one of his daughters
was stunned to see that side of him during a courtroom visit.
Although not as smooth and intellectual as his counterpart, Lowell,
he brings doses of common sense to the job, colleagues and aides
say, and few reasons to blur his focus, mostly because he is near
retirement and does not crave the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings an extraordinary sense of fairness to whatever he
does, practical and in a legal sense,'' said Daniel Martin, a
lawyer with the Federal Defender Program who has worked as
co-counsel with Schippers on several long cases. ``He's a very
pragmatic man who can separate the wheat from the chaff.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he thought that Schippers would bring to the table a
touch of something else that was now sorely lacking in the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's the kind of fellow who gets too involved in
the partisan issues,'' he said, although Republican aides said he
had been tough on Democrats, perhaps to show he can be impartial.
``To the extent that this can be a charade or a Republican witch
hunt, he won't fall prey to that. He won't fall prey to
counter-opinions, either. It's probably one reason why Hyde tapped
into him.''
</P>
<P>
   After a childhood spent at Wrigley Field and in parochial
school, Schippers said he thought about joining the priesthood
during a stint at Quigley South Preparatory Seminary. Then he
decided that ``women were not just soft boys,'' and that he had had
``enough of this nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   He married, and Catholic to the core, he said, began ``producing
children at an obscene rate'' _ ten in all, to be precise, children
who in turn gave him 25 grandchildren. Evenings, he attended Loyola
Law School, a pursuit that crossed his mind at the seminary, when,
after taking a test, a priest told him he had managed to get every
answer wrong, but every reason right.
</P>
<P>
   He had spent a lot of time fishing recently, at least until the
call came in January from Hyde, a casual longtime friend. Hyde told
Schippers' at the time that his task would be to set up a framework
for overseeing the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   But ``between the first call and the actual personal meeting,
guess what happened?'' Schippers asked. ``Here comes the beret.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
