<SLUG> BC-BBA-JUSTICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE HAS A RED SOX-BEATING ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Game 1 produced one hit in four at-bats during a
dismal 11-3 pounding. It also produced something else in David
Justice: a sense of urgency, if not anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cleveland Indians were to make a repeat trip to the World
Series as American League champions, if they even were to get as
far as the AL Championship Series, they could not afford to fall
behind by two games to the Red Sox in the best-of-five AL Division
Series _ at home, no less.
</P>
<P>
   Justice knew what was at stake here. As a playoff veteran, the
Indians designated hitter also knew that the momentum of a series
can sometimes be changed by one person.
</P>
<P>
   This was how he responded Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   First inning; Red Sox leading, 2-0; Indian runner on third, one
out: Boom. Justice lofts a fly to deep center, scoring Kenny
Lofton.
</P>
<P>
   Second inning; Indians leading, 3-2; two out; runners at second
and third: Boom. Justice homers into the right-field stands off
reliever John Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, a close game becomes a laugher and the Indians
are on their way to a 9-5 victory and a 1-1 series tie heading to
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Justice, who has struggled all season after coming back from
knee surgery, made it clear that he understands his role against
the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston never gives up,'' he said. ``I don't think you can
score enough runs to make them lay down.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice's power totals have been down this year _ 21 home runs,
88 RBIs _ but the 32-year-old veteran, once a staple of the Atlanta
Braves' championship outfield, believes his knee has something to
do with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my power stroke goes hand in hand with my consistency
in hitting,'' said Justice. ``When I came off my knee surgery, my
knee bothered me. When it was sore, I wasn't able to drive the ball
like I know I'm capable of. When it's gotten stronger and felt
pretty good, I hit the ball pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice, Lofton, Sandy Alomar, and Manny Ramirez collected eight
of the Indians' nine hits and all eight of their RBIs Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If the Indians are to knock off the Red Sox, Justice knows such
production must continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had Kenny and Sandy up here, we'd tell you we'd love to
play our best every game,'' Justice said. ``But I think our fans
understand the effort we put forward. I'm happy we came out and
swung the bats well _ myself, Sandy and Kenny and a few other guys.
We needed this game. We needed to score runs because I felt the Red
Sox were going to score. We have to score. I do feel satisfied that
we swung the bats well, and we just have to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Hargrove also knows where the Indians must look for
help. ``Those are the three guys that everybody targeted here that
had off years,'' said Hargrove, referring to Justice, Lofton, and
Alomar. ``I think it's ironic that these guys have stepped up big
the way they have. It doesn't surprise me.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're winners, they're good players, and they're good
hitters. They have been good in big situations in the past and they
continue to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
