<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPOSTERS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE IMPOSTERS' RUN OUT OF STEAM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by SLANG partners -- Attn: Rich Irwin) 
OUR RATING: 2 { Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forget sinking an ocean liner or restaging the
Normandy Invasion. The toughest thing to do in movies is make a
successful farce. Stanley Tucci, who wrote and co-directed the
sleeper hit ``Big Night'' two years ago, gives it a game try with
his new film, ``The Impostors,'' and he triumphs over the form for
about an hour. After that, the wheels come off, the manic energy
begins to flag and the film dissolves into the froth. Farce claims
another victim.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean ``The Impostors'' doesn't have its moments. It
has quite a few good bits, in fact. The movie begins with a
brilliant piece of silent filmmaking that calls to mind the best
work of Buster Keaton. Mixed in with the opening credits, two men,
Arthur (Tucci) and Maurice (Oliver Platt) are shown quarreling at
an outdoor cafe. Tensions escalate, a knife is pulled and Platt
dramatically keels over dead. It looks like Laurel and Hardy have
gone gangster.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice isn't really dead, of course. It turns out that he and
Arthur are perpetually out-of-work actors who go around New York
staging these kinds of scenes to practice their craft. In this
case, Arthur is very upset because it was his turn to die. ``You
stole my death,'' he complains bitterly. Arthur lives to die, you
see.
</P>
<P>
   After an attempt to extort a few cream puffs from a baker goes
hilariously awry, Arthur and Maurice find themselves with tickets
to the theater as a consolation prize. They go, even though the
show stars a hambone actor, Jeremy Burtom (Alfred Molina), whom
they despise. One thing leads to another, and soon the two are on
the run from police over a misunderstood altercation with Burtom in
a bar. Maurice and Arthur hide in a crate, which, naturally, gets
loaded on a departing ocean liner which, naturally, counts Burtom
as one of its passengers. So the chase continues, this time on
water.
</P>
<P>
   The ship contains a wide assortment of oddballs and Tucci has
cast some of the independent film world's finest actors wonderfully
against type to play them. Lili Taylor, usually the social outcast,
plays Lily, the ship's ingenue head stewardess, while the beautiful
Hope Taylor portrays a comically morose passenger. (``All is
death,'' she says with utter conviction.)
</P>
<P>
   Steve Buscemi is a suicidal lounge singer, Campbell Scott the
German head steward with eyes for Lily, and Billy Connolly a tennis
pro with improbable eyes for Maurice. (His pickup line: ``I once
wrestled a man on the steps of the Acropolis when the sun was at
its peak, wearing only what God Almighty sent me into the world
with. Can you picture that?'') Woody Allen also has an unbilled
cameo as a Broadway director.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone looks like they're having a ball, and the cast's
enthusiasm for the material proves contagious. There are many
laugh-out-loud moments. Unfortunately, Tucci isn't able to sustain
the momentum throughout the entire film. The turning point comes
when the plot abruptly reverses course, with Arthur and Maurice
doing the chasing instead of being chased. From there, ``The
Impostors'' takes on a forced, stilted tone. Too many characters
and too many subplots sink this movie faster than the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough business,'' Tucci's Arthur says at one point
about acting.
</P>
<P>
   He could well have been talking about making a farce, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
