<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DOLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE URGES GOP FAIRNESS IN IMPEACHMENT PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bob Dole, the former Senate majority leader and
presidential candidate, warned Wednesday that to avoid a backlash,
congressional Republicans must be scrupulously fair as they move
toward an impeachment inquiry into President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Republicans have to be very careful,'' Dole said at a
Boston campaign stop. ``When you are the majority party, I don't
care what the issue is, you've got to be very, very careful that
you are not only fair, but that you are perceived as being fair,
and it really is not only perception, it is reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Senate Republican leader also said that if both sides
wanted, he might be willing to play an elder statesman's role in
the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were asked by people on each side to try to be helpful, I
think obviously you have an obligation to do things like that,''
said Dole, who was in Massachusetts to endorse the former
congressman, Peter G. Torkildsen, in his rematch battle against US
Representative John F. Tierney in the 6th Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Dole said he thinks that the inquiry into President Clinton's
conduct must move forward, and that all the facts must be fully
examined before any resolution is possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Republican said the key vote on an impeachment
inquiry would take place not in the highly polarized House
Judiciary Committee, but on the House floor. He also recommended
that Republicans model their process on the Watergate congressional
inquiry, which was managed by the majority Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would guess at least half the Democrats are going to vote
for it, maybe more,'' Dole said. ``I mean, if they take some of the
Democratic concerns and use the old Watergate resolutions drafted
by Democrats, how are Democrats going to vote against it?''
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell Democrat and member
of the House Judiciary Committee, disputed that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``During Watergate, the evidence was released only after the
committee had reviewed it thoroughly and established its relevance
to the case against President Nixon,'' Meehan said in a separate
interview. ``It would be impossible, even retroactively, to follow
the precedent set under Watergate.''
</P>
<P>
   In another development, mayors from 41 cities signed a letter to
Congress urging them to decide Clinton's fate quickly and to focus
on solving the problems facing American cities.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, delivered Tuesday to congressional leaders, was
signed mainly by Democrats, but included Republicans as well.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino said his colleagues are frustrated
that the legislative process has been ``paralyzed'' over the Monica
S. Lewinsky scandal. Menino thinks that the public humiliation
Clinton has suffered should be punishment enough, and he is opposed
to impeachment or censure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark D. Preston of States News Service contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
