<HEADLINE>
CLINTON EXULTS IN FIRST US BUDGET SURPLUS IN 29 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Wednesday celebrated the first US
budget surplus in 29 years, calling it a ``gift-giving achievement
for generations'' and an example of America ``at the top of its
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the last day of the 1998 fiscal year to announce
the estimated $70 billion surplus, wretching up a debate with
Republicans over who should claim credit for the surplus and how it
should be used.
</P>
<P>
   At an elaborate ceremony in the Old Executive Office Building
near the White House, Democrats lavished Clinton with praise for
his stewardship of the improved economy. The president, in turn,
gave some of the credit to Democrats who voted for his 1993
economic plan, which raised taxes on the wealthiest taxpayers and
cut government spending.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned Republicans to resist the election-year urge to
cut taxes and not ``start spending a little here, a little there, a
little yonder on the tax cuts just because we're a few weeks before
an election,'' and to reserve the surplus for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders countered that it was Clinton who was trying
to spend the surplus, not on a tax cut but on government programs.
They criticized him for failing to give them credit for the
surplus, and argued that they were the original deficit hawks who
held Clinton's feet to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the president seems to want to take credit for balancing
the budget and building the surplus...the credit belongs to the
American taxpayer, the Federal Reserve Board and yes, the combined
efforts of Congress and Congresses, the president, this one, past
presidents,'' said Senator Pete V. Domenici, the chairman of the
Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Though Clinton said the $70 billion surplus, which is an based
on an estimate and will not be official until the end of the month,
``launches a new era of budgets and surpluses,'' his former labor
secretary, Robert B. Reich said such an assessment was
``unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Reich, who teaches economics at Brandeis University, said the
surplus was largely a result of tax revenues from affluent
taxpayers who have benefited from the booming economy, and that the
economy probably wouldn't continue to grow at its current pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will enter into a recession, at some point, probably within
the next few years, and then tax receipts, even from the
higher-income individuals, will likely fall,'' Reich said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, looming liabilites connected to Social Security and
Medicare, which are not expected to have enough money to pay their
bills as the nation's population ages, will affect the budget,
which showed a record $290 billion deficit for 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the nation's $5 trillion-plus debt that resulted from
years of deficit spending, the surplus was greeted with fanfare by
the White House, which invited seven former Democratic members of
Congress who lost their bids for re-election after supporting
Clinton's 1993 economic plan to the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Also invited was Kay McClure, who owns a family business in West
Virginia that makes precision tools for heavy construction
projects. She credited the company's expansion to an improved
economy and low interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   A billboard with flashing orange lights heralded the surplus,
which the White House sought to put in context, saying that the
last time there was a surplus was when Neil Armstrong walked on the
Moon, a can of Coca-Cola was 15 cents and the Boston Celtics were
the NBA champs. The past year's surplus is the largest ever in
dollar terms.
</P>
<P>
   Besides celebrating the surplus, Clinton promoted his proposed
budget, which includes tax credits in such areas as education and
child care, offering it up as an alternative to using the surplus
for a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not against tax cuts,'' Clinton said. ``But we don't
take any money out of the surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a tax cut ``is a popular thing, particularly right here,
just four weeks and change before an election day, to serve up a
tax cut,'' Clinton said, would be wrong before Social Security had
been shored up.
</P>
<P>
   The American people, he said, ``have waited 29 years, and I
think most Americans would like to see the ink change from red to
black and then dry a little before we put it at risk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
