<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-BOSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS WHIP BOSOX, 9-5, RESPONDING TO EARLY LOSS OF GOODEN AND
HARGROVE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The tale of two pitchers nearly turned into the tale
of the tape Wednesday when the anxious Cleveland Indians met the
Boston Red Sox in Game 2 of this American League division series at
Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   What was supposed to be a showdown between Dwight Gooden, the
once- celebrated veteran in search of his first post-season
victory, and Tim Wakefield, Boston's soft-throwing knuckleball
pitcher, became something akin to a pre-fight press conference gone
awry, with Gooden, Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove and home plate
umpire Joe Brinkman exchanging everything but punches only minutes
after the game's first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The trio's yelling, cursing and posturing resulted in the
ejections of Hargrove and Gooden before the day's second out had
been recorded and had the crowd of 45,229 spectators screaming for
Brinkman's neck. The fans' hostility must have been accompanied by
panic as everything pointed to their Indians, who had dropped six
of their last seven games, losing their second contest in as many
days and being on the brink of elimination from this
three-of-five-games series.
</P>
<P>
   But the Indians, all but written off by many onlookers after
Tuesday's Game 1 debacle, responded to the adversity by fighting to
a 9-5 victory that restored their hopes of winning a second
straight pennant and evened the series at one game apiece heading
into Friday's Game 3 at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   With four hits, including doubles by Sandy Alomar and Kenny
Lofton and a homer by David Justice, the Indians scored five runs
in the second inning to take the lead for good and knock Wakefield
out of the game after 1 1/3 innings. The Cleveland right hander
Dave Burba, a starter during the season, earned the victory,
allowing three runs on four hits in 5 1/3 innings in relief of
Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   Justice, who doubled in the sixth and scored Cleveland's eighth
run when Manny Ramirez doubled in the next at bat, said the
ejections inspired the Indians, who led by 6-2 after two innings
and 7-3 after three.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already knew how important this game was but I think what
happened in the first inning really upped our intensity,'' Justice
said. ``I don't want to say the umpires are against us, but then
you look across the field and see the Red Sox want to beat you and
then something happens early and you feel like, `Man, everyone is
against us.' I think that makes the players dig down inside, come
together, and up our intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   The confrontations began almost immediately as Gooden began
complaining about Brinkman's calls after running the count to 3
balls, no strikes against the leadoff hitter, Darren Lewis. Without
uttering a word, the 33-year-old right hander threw his hands into
the air in exasperated fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting to quell a possible blowup, Hargrove went to the mound
to calm down Gooden and then headed toward Brinkman. Chest to chest
and nose to nose, the two began arguing and moments later Hargrove
was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what I felt I had to, and Joe did too,'' said Hargrove,
who after being ejected and going into the dugout returned to the
field to extend his argument with Brinkman. ``For me, it's one of
those things that happens in the heat of battle. Not once would I
ever question an umpire's integrity or his competitiveness. It was
just a difference of opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   His next pitch a ball, Gooden walked Lewis and then the next
batter, John Valentin, before striking out Mo Vaughn, the hero in
Boston's 11-3 Game 1 victory. Just when it seemed that Gooden's
tensions had eased, he gave up a double high off the left-field
wall to clean-up hitter Nomar Garciaparra. After Lewis scored
easily on the hit, Valentin sprinted toward the plate, hoping to
avoid shortstop Omar Vizquel's throw to Alomar at home.
</P>
<P>
   Replays showed that Vizquel's throw reached Alomar in time and
that the catcher tagged out the sliding Valentin a couple of inches
in front of the plate. But Brinkman called him safe, giving the Red
Sox a 2-0 advantage and prompting Gooden, who was backing up Alomar
on the play, to curse at him on his way back to the mound. Without
hesitation, Brinkman ejected him, sending Gooden to the dugout with
the shortest outing of his 14-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a situation where he was in bad position,'' said
Gooden, who had to be restrained from going after Brinkman by three
Indians coaches. ``He was right there where I was standing to see
the play. I can't even say he missed it. For whatever reason, he
wanted to say safe. I was shocked. It wasn't a bang-bang play. He
was out by a few feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Brinkman issued this written statement after the game: ``The
ejection on Hargrove was questioning balls and strikes. The
ejection on Gooden was that he screamed an expletive right in my
ear. That's all there is to it.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   With DWIGHT GOODEN and TIM WAKEFIELD combining for less than two
innings of work, both MIKE HARGROVE and Boston manager JIMY
WILLIAMS said Wednesday's starters might be used in relief later in
the series. Wakefield, who lost his second straight postseason game
to the Indians, said he hopes to get another start. ``I told DENNIS
ECKERSLEY that I feel like I didn't even pitch,'' Wakefield said
... The starting pitchers in Game 3 will be right hander CHARLES
NAGY (15-10, 5.22 ERA) for Cleveland and right hander BRET
SABERHAGEN (15-8, 3.96 ERA) for Boston. Saberhagen was 2-0 with a
0.75 ERA against the Indians during the regular season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0370 </DOCNO>
