u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DREAMS-MOVIE-LADN &LR;      09-30 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAMS-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODERN-DAY TALE OF HEAVEN AND HELL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by SLANG partners -- Attn: Rich Irwin) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Computer graphics technology has been put to all
kinds of silly cinematic uses in recent years. Think last summer's
dueling space rock movies. Think ``Godzilla.''
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, creating multiple visions of heaven and hell
seems _ make that is _ a much more uplifting purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``What originally drew me in was the idea of using the
technology for making something other than an explosion, an alien
or a dinosaur,'' says Robin Williams, who plays a recently deceased
doctor wandering vivid afterlife environments in the
soul-searching, new feature film ``What Dreams May Come.'' ``That,
combined with the emotional journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was a challenge trying to keep emotionally alive in the
face of all these special effects,'' adds Williams, who had to play
heart-wrenching scenes against backdrops of floating cities and
battleship graveyards _ that were created months after his
performance by complicated, work-intensive computer programs.
``When you're standing in a field full of orange balls, it's hard
to be in a state of catharsis. It's some sort of Method hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as hard, though, as creating a hell, and its opposite, that
could credibly translate the ideas of Richard Matheson's source
novel to the screen. Since making a cult hit out of Matheson's
``Somewhere in Time'' two decades ago, producer Stephen Simon has
been trying to turn his friend's novel into a movie.
</P>
<P>
   But Simon and his producing partner Barnet Bain not only had to
wait for CG technology to advance to a point where it could realize
the story's celestial dreamscapes. They had to find a director who
had a persuasive inkling of what the afterlife should look like.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conceit of the movie is that you create your own
post-death reality,'' Simon says. ``And the script (by Ron Bass,
the superhot scripter of ``Waiting to Exhale'' and ``My Best
Friend's Wedding''), as wonderful as it was, did not distinguish
your picture from my picture, or anybody else's.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it was a question of whose paradise would define
a $75 million production that would obviously have to appeal to a
wide range of people. People who, inevitably, would have varying
views on life after death.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand director Vincent Ward didn't have a clue at first.
Trained as a painter and known for such visually striking,
metaphysically themed romances as ``Navigator'' and ``Map of the
Human Heart,'' he was initially flummoxed by the story _
essentially, a kind of contemporary ``Orpheus'' in which Williams'
spirit tries to retrieve that of his suicide wife's (Annabella
Sciorra) from a psychic purgatory of her own making.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in telling personal stories about individual
experiences, and I try to present them in an individual way,'' says
Ward. ``So I like to craft worlds for my central characters that
don't just relate to objective reality, but are also very much
emotional and psychological landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was faced, here, with a screenplay that I loved. But I
didn't know how you create heaven and hell in the 20th century. I
wanted to make it a visceral experience for people, and after about
a month of thinking about it, I came up with the idea of making
(Sciorra's character) a painter and art restorer.''
</P>
<P>
   That led fairly naturally _ as Williams' character passes
through various stages of death, then through other beings'
afterworlds _ to a digital display of art motifs.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor awakens from his coma, for example, in an
impressionist-inspired field of brightly colored flowers that
squish into oily swirls. When disorientation and panic grip him, he
finds himself atop awesome mountains that, according to Ward, evoke
``romantic German painting of the 19th century, a particular look
that was tempestuous, lonely, when man was smaller than nature. All
of that seemed to serve a story about a man who's in paradise, but
his paradise is hell without the woman he loves.''
</P>
<P>
   A younger spirit's heaven resembles the warmly colorful fantasy
paintings of magazine artist Maxfield Parrish. A stairway to heaven
was influenced by a John Martin engraving, while medieval woodcuts
and Gustave Dore's infernal etchings informed some of the film's
darker dimensions. The ship's graveyard, Ward admits, ``was just an
image I had in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of these fantastic realms required a year and a half's
worth of programming and virtual artistry _ Ward reckons it took
between nine and 20 man hours of post-production to create every
four seconds of CG footage. For many of the eye-popping sequences,
a process called Lidar was employed. Designed for military mapping
purposes, the laser range-finding technology supplied data that
could be used to reconstruct, in a computer, acres of footage (the
orange balls Williams mentioned were used as plotting points).
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted the camerawork to be like a documentary in paradise
but look like a painting, so I could just move anywhere, be
hand-held, be shot from water, whatever,'' Ward explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer was to shoot (the live action) during the day, then
have the Lidar crew come in at night and map the area
three-dimensionally. The two shots would be married together
digitally later on, and then you could change all the elements you
liked. If you were adding computer-generated flowers or anything
like that, it gave you a terrain in three dimensions that you could
move through and change perspectives in.''
</P>
<P>
   All very high tech. But the digital wizardry also inspired some
very human, humorous moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every morning I'd come and take all my clothes off and these
two guys would put dots, like Band-Aids, all over my body,''
explains Cuba Gooding Jr., who plays a kind of celestial
orientation guide who initially appears as a kind of humanoid blur.
``Then I'd put a mesh around my waist and that's how I'd do the
scene. We did this scene where I had to walk into this Baptist
church full of people at 4 in the morning. They were going, `This
boy ain't got no clothes on!' That was pretty funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Less humorous for Gooding, who is a born-again Christian, were
the film's decidedly nontraditional concepts. But after insisting
on a dialogue change or two, he was able to reconcile the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the positive message that was coming from the movie, no
matter what your religious background,'' the Oscar-winning ``Jerry
Maguire'' actor says. ``I do believe there is a heaven, I do
believe there is a hell, they're both very real. But the Bible says
that `in my house there are many mansions,' and in essence I think
that means that heaven and hell are what we imagine them to be. A
movie making that statement is something that I supported.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon and Bain, whose company, Metafilmics, is dedicated to
producing films with spiritual themes, say they hope ``Dreams''
will spark debate among viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a test screening, we walked out to the parking lot and
five people who had seen the film were having a really heated
argument about aspects of the film, how it conflicted or conformed
to their belief systems,'' Simon recalls. ``They were really,
really going after each other. Barnet and I looked at each other
and said, `We did our job.' This film provides no answers. It asks
a lot of questions, which the audience can then determine for
themselves when they go home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Metafilmics was set up with a view to bringing to an audience
stories that inspire, that empower, that model relationships that
give folks greater insight into the choices they make and how they
behave,'' adds producer Bain, whose screenwriting credits range
from a British ``Carry On'' comedy to a film about Jesus.
``Metafilmics makes films about utopian futures. We have a history,
for a lot of years now, of making big, epic spectacles about
dystopias, about post-apocalyptic futures. Our company is really
about putting an end to this kind of existential, romantic,
tortured artist vision of life.''
</P>
<P>
   But will it sell?
</P>
<P>
   ``This genre has the best track record of commerciality that
there is,'' Simon says of positive fantasy films. ``They just don't
make enough of 'em. If you make `Ghost,' it's an extraordinary
success, but there's no follow-up to it. You make `Die Hard,'
you're gonna make 30 imitators. But the industry is starting to
recognize that there is a hunger in the audience for movies that
really look upon our humanity as being not debauched, but something
really beautiful and extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen to that. Of course, statements like these leave the
Metafilmics guys open to charges of excessive New Aginess. But
they're as serene as producers can get about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what? Maybe it's good, maybe it's not good, but we
are the New Age filmmakers,'' Barnet reckons. ``To have your work
reflect the biggest, most passionate questions of your life and
your relationships is terrific. To hide from it because somebody's
going to take a potshot? Look, they're going to take potshots
anyway. We might as well be out there and doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd add one word,'' Simon, always in touch with his inner
producer, says. ``If they're going to call us New Age filmmakers, I
hope they add the word `successful'.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
