<HEADLINE>
A WORD WITH THE HORSES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Self magazine's self-proclaimed special issue on improving one's
self _ as though other issues are about anything else _ describes
Miraval, a luxury desert resort that includes an ``equine
experience'' program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a life lesson in confidence,'' said ``equine
facilitator''  &UR; Wyatt Webb &LR; . ``You practice communicating what you
need on horses.'' Whoa, Flicka, I want eternal love, universal
brotherhood, run-proof pantyhose and equal numbers of chocolate
chips in every chocolate chip cookie. ``If you don't learn to ask
for what you want,'' says Webb, ``the odds of getting your needs
met are slim to none.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL HOUSE OF WORSHIP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Charles  &LR; and  &UR; Maurice Saatchi &LR; , British advertising moguls,
have founded a new synagogue in London and given it their own name.
The brothers told British newspapers that the Saatchi Synagogue is
named in honor of their parents, to make it up to them for the
sons' marrying outside the religion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, an advertising agency hired to promote the
synagogue with a full-scale ad campaign, &LR;  is emphasizing the
name-recognition factor. ``Young people know the Saatchi art
gallery,'' said  &UR; Lionel Salama &LR;  of the Hype agency. ``In the same
way, they hopefully will feel an association with the synagogue.''
</P>
<P>
   The first ad emphasizes that the new synagogue won't be boring
and that it will offer a four-course dinner after Friday night
services.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Jimmy Carter &LR; , who turns 74 Thursday, told the Atlanta Journal
and Constitution that he spent the summer watching  &UR; Mark &LR; 
 &UR; McGwire  &LR; and  &UR; Sammy Sosa &LR; , ``trying to pick up a few pointers.'' In
Plains, Ga., over the weekend, he played for the Secret Service
Giants in an annual game against the Plains High School Alumni;
Carter's team won.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roll Call reports that &UR; Hillary Rodham Clinton &LR;  told celebrants
at a recent dinner of the National Hispanic Arts Foundation that
 &UR; Jimmy Smits  &LR; was the first person to call her with birthday wishes
when she turned 50 last October.
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers at Vanderbilt University have come to the defense
of political attack ads, saying they actually contribute to the
political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans like a good fight,'' said political scientist
 &UR; John Geer &LR; , ``and attacks stimulate voter interest. In addition,
our research showed that attack ads contain more information than
the positive ads, and people remember the negative ones better.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Norman Durieu  &LR; says that his Bloomingdale's Christmas catalog
features a ``Monica'' card in a place-card holder shaped like a
nutcracker. On the other hand a reader, who says she feels shy
about using her name because she lives in a retirement community,
writes that she's ``sick and tired of the people's princess and the
president's penis.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawyers for the  &UR; Princess Diana &LR;  Memorial Fund, upon losing a
court battle over rights to Diana's likeness, have called the
Franklin Mint ``vultures feeding on the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If you are gored by a rhinoceros, don't blame us: A
manufacturer's disclaimer about possible side effects of the flu
vaccine, issued by Connaught Laboratories, specifies: ``Medical
events completely unrelated to the vaccine may occur coincidentally
following vaccination.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Gene Marine &LR;  is delighted by Andronico's express lanes in
Berkeley that read: ``12 Items or Fewer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW BEING CHEAP IS A VIRTUE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A profile of  &UR; Rudolf Nureyev &LR;  in W, a magazine favorably
disposed to people who own lots of dry goods, notes that the famous
dancer ``rarely picked up a check and forever grumbled about the
high cost of help,'' but was happy to spend lots of money on such
things as silks, furniture, tapestries and rare maps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another facet of his sensuality,'' said former Royal
Ballet star  &UR; Lynn Seymour &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``No one reading Rolling Stone knows who Tina Brown is, and no
one gives a f(ig).''
</P>
<P>
   _ Letter to the editor of Rolling Stone from an irate rock 'n'
roll fan in Fresno. Elsewhere, the New York Observer reports that
S.I. Newhouse has said yes to New Yorker editor David Remnick's
request and will give him about 10 more pages per issue for
criticism. This is said to come at a cost of $1.5 million to $2
million a year.
</P>
