A2952 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-EJECT-BOS &LR;      09-30 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-EJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARGROVE, GOODEN CROSSED BRINKMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ This was the first statement of the defendant, one
Dwight Gooden, in the case of Richie Phillips's Sometimes
Confrontational Men in Blue vs. Cleveland's Men in White.
</P>
<P>
   Legal beagles call a defendant's first utterances ``spontaneous
outbursts'' and often assign more credibility to them than later
versions of the same incident. Gooden would tell his story
repeatedly after Wednesday's bizarr-o baseball game between the Red
Sox and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, here are defendant Gooden's first utterances
regarding his first three pitches in a first inning that could have
come only from the mind of Monty Python:
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go and ask Joe Brinkman (one of Richie Phiillips's
Confrontational Men in Blue, the plate umpire) Wednesdaywhat
happened,'' Gooden began. ``Myself? The first pitch (to Boston
leadoff hitter Darren Lewis) was obviously a ball, and the next two
I thought were strikes. I never said a word (to Brinkman).
</P>
<P>
   ``I just looked in (toward Brinkman). And then he took off his
mask and then he was going off. I don't know what he was saying.
Then I just put my hands up and I was saying to myself, `Let's get
back to work and let's play the game.' I wasn't saying anything to
him. Obviously, I thought those balls to Lewis were strikes, and
when it went to ball three, I didn't say a word. (Brinkman) took
off the mask and he wanted to provoke me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Darren Lewis, a disinterested witness, gave his version.
Lewis saw the first three pitches and heard the discourse between
plaintiff Brinkman and defendant Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't looking at Doc (Gooden), so I don't know if he felt
they were good pitches or not,'' said Lewis. ``Basically, Joe just
told him, `They were low.' That's what the umpire said. Joe said
they were low, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove came to the
mound. ``Mike asked me what I thought of the pitches,'' said
Gooden. ``I told Mike that I thought they were strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Defendant Hargrove agreed with the version of defendant Gooden.
``I felt that Doc was a little upset and I wanted to calm him
down,'' Hargrove said in his statement to the court of public
opinion. ``I also wanted to stop anything that was going on between
him and Joe Brinkman if I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas for fans of decorum, Hargrove had a word or three for
Brinkman as he headed back to the Cleveland dugout. A brouhaha
ensued. ``I'm not really getting into the specifics of it,'' said
Hargrove. ``It was just a difference of opinion. I did what I had
to do and Joe did what he had to do. And Joe is very good at what
he does.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Brinkman was very good (and very quick) at
ejecting Hargrove. After only three pitches of a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ejection of Hargrove,'' Brinkman said in a prepared
statement that was read to baseball's court, ``was (for)
questioning balls and strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   The first inning progressed as well as it could amid the boos
and catcalls from the home folk of Jacobs Field. Lewis walked. John
Valentin walked. Mo Vaughn struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra then hit a drive a foot short of a home run in
left, a drive that easily scored Lewis from second. Valentin
chugged toward home as cutoff man Omar Vizquel fired to catcher
Sandy Alomar, with Brinkman off to the side of the plate and Gooden
not far from the umpire. Valentin slid arm first, a fadeaway slide.
Alomar applied the tag.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin appeared out.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkman called Valentin safe.
</P>
<P>
   Eruptions occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden, meanwhile, was irate at the call and said several words
to Brinkman as the pitcher headed back to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked by him and I just said to him, `Hey, let's just get
into the (expletive) game,'' Gooden said. ``Oh, (Valentin) was out.
He was definitely out. I mean, it wasn't a case where (Brinkman)
was in a bad position to make the call. I was standing right by him
and I couldn't even say he missed the call. For whatever reason, he
wanted to say (Valentin) was safe.''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Brinkman said, ``The ejection of Gooden was
that he screamed an expletive right in my ear and I ejected him.
That's all there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly, as 45,229 fans of the team in white uniforms
volunteered to testify. Gooden had walked past Brinkman when the
umpire ejected him and never saw that he had been tossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was back toward the mound and the other umpires told me I
was tossed,'' said Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   Another eruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I just gave the umpires the glove and hat and told them,''
Gooden testified, ``and I said, `OK, you guys go out and pitch.'''
</P>
<P>
   Manager and starting pitcher gone after only one out in the
first inning. A long delay for Dave Burba, Gooden's replacement, to
warm up, a delay that cost Boston starter Tim Wakefield any chance
to retain the rhythm he had achieved in his pregame warmups.
Cleveland pummeled Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   Bizarr-o baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
