r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX     09-30 1954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINSTON CUP A LITTLE TOO PREDICTABLE FOR BRUTON SMITH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know that NASCAR Winston Cup championship chase that has you
riveted in front of the TV for three-plus hours each weekend?
</P>
<P>
   You know those heated battles for track position and every
valuable Winston Cup point?
</P>
<P>
   You know all the strategy that goes into deciding between two
tires vs. four tires, a pound of air here and a round of wedge
there?
</P>
<P>
   Sure you do, because these are some of the ingredients that have
made big-league stock-car racing the fastest growing spectator
sport in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Then why is racetrack developer Bruton Smith so concerned?
</P>
<P>
   Because Smith, as chief executive officer of Speedway
Motorsports Inc., has taken a hard look at NASCAR ticket sales from
across the country. And he senses that the fans who loyally have
filled the grandstands, including at his five racetracks, are
becoming bored with the show NASCAR is cranking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week, every week it's the same thing,'' Smith said
during a conference call this week. ``It's either car 24 (Jeff
Gordon) or car 6 (Mark Martin) racing with each other. You can bet
that last 100 miles, there they are. Are the fans tired of that? I
think they are. Thank God that Ricky Rudd won on Sunday (at
Martinsville (Va.) Speedway). I hate to say this _ and I know you
won't print it _ but it's getting rather monotonous.''
</P>
<P>
   Right, like Smith really doesn't want or expect his comments to
get back to NASCAR president Bill France Jr., vice president for
competition Mike Helton and Gary Nelson, Winston Cup Series
director.
</P>
<P>
   Next to France, Smith is viewed by many as the second-most
powerful man in the sport. He also is a practical businessman. As
the series settles into Smith's Charlotte Motor Speedway for the
UAW-GM Quality 500 this weekend, the race for the championship of
NASCAR's 50th season is shaping up into a one-on-one matching
Gordon and Martin. And yet all of the seats at CMS _ the crown
jewel of Smith's motorsports empire _ were not sold as of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The outcome of Cup races has become a little too
predictable. Gordon, who is bidding for his third championship in
four years and second in a row, has a 199-point lead over Martin
after 27 events.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has his now obligatory 10 victories in the bag, and
Martin has a career-high six. They are 1-2 in victories and have
finished first and second in six races. Gordon and Martin also
stand 1-2 in money won, laps led and miles led. Sunday's NAPA
AutoCare 500 at Martinsville marked the first race this season that
neither Gordon nor Martin led a lap.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Smith is not criticizing either Gordon and the crew at
Hendrick Motorsports or Martin and his team at Roush Racing for
doing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what I'm thinking about is these guys don't race side by
side. These fans like that. They like some rubbing,'' said Smith,
who spent approximately $3 million to revamp his Texas Motor
Speedway in Fort Worth earlier this summer to address that problem,
as well as water leaks in turns 1 and 4. ``Right now the cars
aren't handling the way they could handle. Maybe if we make some
changes on these race cars, where these guys can drive them easier
... if they could do that, the racing could be better.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a veiled reference to the 5-and-5/inch rear spoiler and
front air dam rule instituted by NASCAR this season to take away
aerodynamic downforce and slow the cars down through the corners by
making them a little less stable.
</P>
<P>
   H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler, the president of CMS and Smith's trusted
comrade, joined a chorus of drivers critical of the lack of
downforce on the 3,400-pound Cup cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the best racing out there is in the (NASCAR) Busch
Series because the cars have more downforce, less horsepower and
are easier to drive,'' Wheeler said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to suggest that even with some sort of aero tweaking,
Gordon and Martin would not end up dominating a given race day.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it'd be great to have more than two cars competing for the
win,'' Smith said. ``I hope NASCAR will take a hard look, so we can
get these guys racing the way they used to race.'' &QL; 
THE BUZZ &QL; 
NASCAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ford Taurus owner/driver Ricky Rudd's victory at a boiling
Martinsville Speedway on Sunday was not only one of the most
courageous performances of the Winston Cup season. It also struck a
blow for that vanishing breed known as the single-car team. Through
27 races, only Rudd (1), Bobby Hamilton (1) and Bobby Labonte (2)
have scored victories for the sport's so-called ``little guys.'' In
fact, Hamilton and Morgan-McClure Racing remain the only single-car
Chevrolet team to have won a Cup race since the start of the 1995
season. ...
</P>
<P>
   Cup regular Ken Schrader will become a multi-teamer when Kenny
Wallace joins Andy Petree Racing next year. The addition of Wallace
to Petree's Chevy lineup has received Schrader's endorsement. ``I'm
all for it, the key factor being Kenny Wallace,'' said Schrader,
who is 11th in points, 23 behind John Andretti with six events to
go. ``We just feel we can help ourselves with a better budget, more
equipment, more personnel and more knowledge. I believe that two is
better than one _ two that are close are definitely better than
one. But I don't believe three is better than two or four is better
than three.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's annual Winston Cup prerace extravaganza at Charlotte
Motor Speedway has been billed as ``Showdown at Charlotte,'' and is
scheduled to feature Batman and Robin pitted against the Joker in a
battle royale for Gotham City _ or at least as it exists on the CMS
infield. Here is the plot, as explained by H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler,
CMS president and general manager and promoter par excellnce: ``The
Joker captures the Speedway, and Batman rescues the whole (Winston
Cup) field. We've got car chases and something might get up in the
air.'' Gee, you hardly ever see that during one of these shows at
CMS _ fireworks and assorted explosions. ``We need some humor in
this sport,'' Wheeler said. ``You go into the (Cup) garage area and
nobody's having any fun. They're up too tight. Maybe this will
loosen them up a bit.'' Keeping with the program, Dale Jarrett will
drive a Batman-themed No. 88 Ford and teammate Kenny Irwin Jr. will
compete in a Joker-themed No. 28 Taurus on Sunday. &QL; 
CART &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Championship Auto Racing Teams released a series record
20-race schedule for 1999 on Monday, and the lone Texas stop is
booked for the streets of downtown Houston on Sept. 26. That is the
date for the second annual Texaco Grand Prix of Houston. And they
haven't even run the inaugural Houston race yet. It's scheduled for
Sunday at 3 p.m. on a 1.68-mile temporary course surrounding the
George R. Brown Convention Center. The course length appears mighty
short, until you consider that the ultra successful Toyota Grand
Prix of Long Beach is contested over a 1.586-mile street layout.
``The length is not the difference. It's the layout,'' said Michael
Andretti, the Newman/Haas Racing star who has scored 15 of his
career 37 CART victories in street races. ``You look on paper at
what it's going to be and you can't tell. I know it's going to be
very wide for a street circuit. That's one positive. Maybe there'll
be a spot for passing at the end of the straightaway. That's always
the biggest complaint on a street circuit, there's no place to
pass. Hopefully, they'll have a place.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Andretti's comments fit nicely into A.J. Foyt's view
of CART's first foray into his hometown. Foyt, first four-time
winner of the Indianapolis 500, is aligned with the all-oval Pep
Boys Indy Racing League in its rivalry with CART. But Foyt, whose
67 Indy-car victories top the all-time list, could care less about
this weekend's FedEx Championship activities. ``It's not really
Indy-car racing,'' Foyt said. ``That's actually Formula One racing.
And to me, (CART is) just a secondary Formula One racing they're
running. We're (IRL) a different league of racing. We're actually
oval racing. And I don't mind a good road course _ a ``good'' road
course. But this stuff of running downtown ... that ain't racing.''
...
</P>
<P>
   Andretti also held out little hope of CART ever racing at the
1.5-mile Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth, where the 24-degree
banked turns could be expected to whip the cars around well in
excess of 230 mph. That's even with the addition of the Handford
Device rear-wing flap employed by CART for the first time at the
2-mile, 18-degree banked Michigan Speedway in July. ``Politically,
we were ready to race there,'' said Andretti, referring to TMS.
``It was a safety issue, and I believe it still is an issue for us.
Even with the Handford Device, with that amount of banking and that
layout, we'd be going way too fast. We feel it would be way too
dangerous. The Gs )gravity forces) we'd pull through the corners
would be the biggest of anywhere else we've raced. I think it's a
safety issue more than anything.'' &QL; 
FAST LAPS &QL; 
TMS ANNOUNCEMENT SET &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A ``major announcement'' regarding the 1999 racing season at
Texas Motor Speedway is scheduled for this afternoon. Pep Boys Indy
Racing League driver Greg Ray of Plano is to join Eddie Gossage,
executive vice president and general manager of TMS, which
sponsored Ray at the Indianapolis 500 in May.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, league officials continue to firm up next year's
schedule. An 11-race tour, same as this year despite the loss of
New Hampshire International Speedway, is expected to be announced
between now and the season finale at Las Vegas Motor Speedway on
Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 schedule will likely see the race at Charlotte Motor
Speedway moved from its late July date to a spot in May, before the
running of the 83rd Indianapolis 500. That will give the teams a
major speedway shakedown heading into the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway. &QL; 
NUTS AND BOLTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   National Hot Rod Association Pro Stock driver Bruce Allen of
Arlington has qualified for only eight of 17 events heading into
the Parts America Nationals at Heartland Park Topeka (Kan.) this
weekend. Allen has 10 elimination-round victories in the Outlaw
Pontiac Firebird.
</P>
<P>
   Newly crowned NTB Trans-Am Series champion Paul Gentilozzi heads
to the season finale in downtown Houston this weekend with seven
victories and nine poles (in 12 starts) in his Corvette. Included
were four flag-to-flag victories.
</P>
<P>
   Open-wheel veteran Jack Hewitt became the first driver in the
18-year history of the 4-Crown Nationals to sweep all four features
at Eldora Speedway in Rossburg, Ohio. Hewitt, 47, won the 50-lap
U.S. Auto Club Silver Crown race, 30-lap Sprint feature, 25-lap
Midget race and 20-lap UMP Modified race last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips 66 Racing has agreed to sponsor Team 34 and driver Todd
Bodine for the 1999 NASCAR Busch GN season.
</P>
<P>
   Rising Busch GN star Matt Kenseth will be sponsored by DeWalt
Tools next season. Kenseth will return with crew chief Robbie
Reiser in Chevrolet Monte Carlos.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Musgrave has been signed to drive the No. 13 FirstPlus
Financial Ford Taurus in the next three Winston Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grissom is scheduled to drive the No. 96 Caterpillar
Chevrolet in the Winston Cup UAW-GM Quality 500 at CMS on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace's Winston Cup winless streak is at 56 races
heading into CMS on Sunday. &QL; 
LAST WORDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They say NASCAR is the fastest-growing sport in America. That
makes sense because we're racing almost every weekend. I barely
have enough time to get home and wash my clothes before I have to
leave again.'' _ Jerry Nadeau, Winston Cup rookie, on the nomadic
NASCAR lifestyle
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
