<HEADLINE>
USS INDEPENDENCE PASSES INTO HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUGET SOUND NAVAL SHIPYARD, Wash. _ It was a moment of crisp
ceremony and spontaneous tears as they lowered the flag for the
last time on the USS Independence.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old aircraft carrier, until Wednesday the oldest
warship on active duty in the Navy, passed into history in a
decommissioning ceremony here that drew senior Navy officials and
scores of carrier veterans from all over the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioned in 1959 at the height of the Cold War, the
80,000-ton carrier saw duty in practically every crisis and war in
the subsequent four decades, said Navy Secretary John Dalton, who
served a brief training tour on the carrier in 1961 as an Annapolis
midshipman and who returned Wednesday to speak at its retirement.
Over its lifetime, the Independence had 386,000 ``traps'' _
controlled aircraft landings using the flight deck arresting gear _
and steamed more than 3 million miles, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Gesturing to a long row of sailors along the rail on the
Independence's four-acre flight deck, Dalton said, ``Anyone who
believes that Navy ships are simply steel and cable, oil and iron,
has not walked the deckplates of USS Independence and felt the
powerful presence of naval history _ American history _ in every
frame and compartment.''
</P>
<P>
   The ship, which has been based on both coasts and in Japan,
served in the 1962 Cuban missile crisis, took part in combat
operations in Vietnam, Grenada and Lebanon, and was the first
carrier rushed to the Persian Gulf after the 1990 Iraqi invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Adm. Mike Bowman, commander of Pacific Fleet naval air
forces, choked back tears as he read the official message ordering
the carrier's decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
   Although the carrier's retirement has been long planned _ the
Navy is continuing to commission new nuclear-powered Nimitz-class
flattops _ Dalton yesterday took note of the Pentagon budget
strains that have caused shortages in key personnel and a falloff
in recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton said the Navy has sufficient operating funds for now, but
warned of ``clouds on the horizon'' if Congress fails to provide a
proposed short-term infusion of money. Dalton, who has already
announced his resignation as the Navy's civilian chief, added it is
imperative that Congress approve two more rounds of base closings
to save unneeded expenses of operating obsolete facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The fleet has shrunk by 45 percent from about 600 ships to 350
today, but support bases have been cut by only 17 percent, Dalton
said. ``Clearly we have too much infrastructure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton said personnel support _ including pay, quality-of-life
programs and retirement compensation _ should have the Navy's top
budget priority. ``It doesn't matter about the other (budget
programs) if we can't keep the people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's ceremony, Dalton presented the carrier and its
crew with the Navy Unit Commendation award for their role in
several military emergencies during 1996-98.
</P>
<P>
   The Independence took part in a surge of Navy warships to the
Taiwan Strait in 1996 to signal U.S. resolve in the rise of
tensions between China and Taiwan. And earlier this year the
carrier was rushed to the Persian Gulf for five months as the
Pentagon beefed up naval power in a standoff with Iraq over United
Nations weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of about 1,500 Navy officers, family members and
veterans rose to applaud as the ship's last skipper, Capt. Mark
Milliken, marched aboard his command for his final order: ``Debark
the crew.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Navy band played, the crew of 1,100 sailors marched from
the flight deck down to the pier gangways in a long line of white
uniforms. The final act of the ceremony was to lower a
one-of-a-kind flag _ the original Navy jack with the ``Don't Tread
on Me'' motto _ that is flown only aboard the oldest warship on
active service.
</P>
<P>
   The flag has been transferred to the USS Kitty Hawk, now the
Navy's senior ship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
