<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BO     09-30 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRACTIOUS GAME LEAVES RED SOX IN 1-1 PLAYOFF TIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Cleveland Indians spotted the Red Sox a manager,
a starting pitcher, and a two-run lead four batters into Game 2 of
their American League Division Series Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Add some eyeblack and Ninja Turtle shoelaces, and the ejections
of Indians manager Mike Hargrove and pitcher Dwight Gooden by plate
umpire Joe Brinkman would have been Roger Clemens-Terry Cooney all
over again.
</P>
<P>
   But a loss of composure doesn't always translate into defeat,
despite the pathetic playoff example set by Clemens and the Sox
eight years ago in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of surrender, the Indians opted for inspiration. With
Red Sox starter Tim Wakefield barely sticking around longer than
Gooden, and with a Jacobs Field crowd of 45,229 energized by the
first-inning fireworks between Brinkman and the home side, the
Indians rallied for a 9-5 win behind Gooden's emergency stand-in,
Dave Burba, to even the best-of-five series at a game apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proved they played better without me,'' said Indians
manager Mike Hargrove, who apparently succeeded in igniting his
team as much as irking Brinkman when he was tossed for complaining
that the umpire not only ruled Gooden's first three pitches were
balls but engaged the Indians righthander in discussing his calls,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously _ I mean, I think it's seriously,'' Hargrove said
with a laugh, ``if it turned up our intensity and our fans'
intensity, then it did some good.''
</P>
<P>
   David Justice hit a three-run home run off reliever John Wasdin
in a five-run second inning, which might have ended sooner if
rookie catcher Jason Varitek had been less cautious when he had
Kenny Lofton trapped between second and third after the runner in
front of him, Joey Cora, elected to stay put on Omar Vizquel's
one-out fly ball to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stuck out there,'' said Lofton, but it was Varitek who
became momentarily unglued, electing to check Vizquel at third and
hold on to the ball while Lofton retreated safely to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a mental mistake,'' said third baseman John Valentin.
``He should have thrown the ball. Maybe he didn't want to throw the
ball away. That was his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not to say he was afraid to throw the ball, but you've
got to play aggressively. Unfortunately, he didn't throw the ball
and the next guy hits a home run. Stuff like that happens all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians then had an answer each time the Red Sox tried to
climb back into the game, knocking out seven extra-base hits,
including six doubles, and putting runners on base in every inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give them credit,'' Red Sox pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan said. ``Their backup starter was better than our backup
starter. That's what the game boiled down to.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden walked the first two batters, Darren Lewis and John
Valentin, whiffed Mo Vaughn, then was gone when he barked in
Brinkman's face after Nomar Garciaparra doubled _ missing a home
run by 6 inches _ and the umpire called Valentin safe when replays
showed he was clearly out despite his best headfirst slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ejection of Hargrove was (for) questioning balls and
strikes,'' Brinkman said in a statement released by the league.
``The ejection of Gooden was that he screamed an expletive right in
my ear and I ejected him. That's all there is to it.''
</P>
<P>
   All there was? That was only the beginning of it. Gooden, who
had been backing up home plate when he crossed paths with Brinkman,
had to be restrained from charging the umpire when he returned to
the mound and discovered belatedly that he'd been ejected. Then he
had to be physically wrestled back to the Indians dugout by coach
Jeff Newman, who'd become manager-for-a-day when Hargrove was
tossed. Then Gooden toosed his cap and glove onto the field in
Brinkman's direction, hollering, ``Here, you pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitching was left to Burba, who was supposed to be
Cincinnati's Opening Day starter but was traded here the day before
the season. He seized this opening, limiting the Red Sox to a run
through 4 2/3 innings before tiring in the sixth, when the Sox
scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   But despite three RBIs from Garciaparra, giving him seven in two
games, the Sox could not overcome the early exit by Wakefield, who
couldn't blame Brinkman for his unscheduled departure.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, who was forced to warm up twice because the top of
the first lasted so long, was charged with more runs (5) than he
got outs (4) in his shortest outing of the season. A 17-game winner
in the regular season, Wakefield gave up a run in the first when
Lofton walked, stole second, and eventually scored on Justice's
sacrifice fly, then failed to survive the second, when he gave up a
single to Travis Fryman, doubles to Sandy Alomar and Lofton, and a
walk to Cora.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' Wakefield said. ``I told Eck (Dennis
Eckersley) when I came into the dugout, `I feel like I didn't even
pitch.'''
</P>
<P>
   Justice hit the first pitch he saw from Wasdin, a split-fingered
fastball, into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Wasdin's splitter breaks away from lefthanded hitters.
Not this time. ``It cut down and in and right into his sweet
spot,'' Kerrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   There was one last sour note before this one was over, when a
fastball by Indians closer Mike Jackson came thisclose to creasing
Valentin's nose. Valentin made a move toward Jackson, the pitcher
started flapping back, benches and bullpens emptied, but there was
no rumble, only grumble.
</P>
<P>
   And when the noise ended, there were flights to Boston to be
made. Game 3 is Friday at Fenway Park, Bret Saberhagen vs. Charles
Nagy, barring ejections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy we've got going Friday is a big-game pitcher,'' Mo
Vaughn said. ``The big win to get was Game 1. It would have been
beautiful to win Game 2, but it's tough. For them, the season was
on the line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
