<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-REDSKINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON FILM, CAMPO CAN'T SEE 0-4 'SKINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ When Cowboys defensive coordinator Dave Campo watches
film of the Washington Redskins offense, he sees a unit that belies
its winless record. And it has not taken much preaching by Campo
for his players to see the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety Darren Woodson contends the 0-4 Redskins have
offensive firepower similar to the Denver Broncos, a team that went
through the Cowboys for 515 yards in Week 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``They move the ball probably better than anyone we will play
this year,'' said Woodson, whose club has not won in Washington
since 1994. ``They are not as consistent as the Broncos. But just
look at their talent. They match up with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins have been matched against some of the league's best
teams in the Broncos, San Francisco 49ers, Seattle Seahawks and New
York Giants. Yet coach Norv Turner's club is ranked fourth in total
offense (376.3 yards per game), and tied for third in total first
downs (83). Wide receiver Michael Westbrook leads the league with
418 receiving yards, and has five receptions of 26 yards or longer.
Running back Terry Allen is 10th with 339 rushing yards and a 4.7
yards-per-carry average.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins' efforts, however, have been undone by turnovers
and penalties. They have an NFL-worst minus-11 turnover ratio,
resulting in 59 points for their opponents. They have committed
penalties at the worst times, with three negating two touchdowns
and a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake parade has been led by quarterback Trent Green. With
play that has been at times terrific, and at other times
terrifying, Green has been intercepted five times and lost four
fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turnovers and penalties have been really frustrating
because that's been a strength of our team the last few years,''
said Turner, whose club's plus-13 turnover ratio the two seasons
before 1998 was fourth-best in the NFL. ``Most of the turnovers
have been related to the passing game. We've got to do a better job
there, a better job protecting the football.''
</P>
<P>
   Green has been productive when protected. In three starts in
place of Gus Frerotte, Green has six touchdowns and 1,044 yards
passing, third most in the league. But the Redskins' line has
allowed 18 quarterback sacks, fourth worse in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Campo intends to apply heavy pressure on Green to add to the
total. Yet the task figures to be challenging. The Cowboys average
a mere two sacks per game. This weak pressure has been underscored
by the slow development of defensive ends Kavika Pittman (one sack)
and Greg Ellis (one sack). And so Cowboys coaches are prepared to
bring an all-out assault at Green, while hoping the coverage
abilities of cornerbacks Deion Sanders and Kevin Smith can bail
them out against the likes of receivers Westbrook and Leslie
Shepherd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to blitz, no doubt,'' said linebacker
Randall Godfrey, whose new role as a pass rusher this season has
netted him one sack. ``If you look at the successful teams in the
league, they all do some kind of stunting, something to get to the
quarterback. You just can't let a guy sit back there and pick his
targets out.''
</P>
<P>
   Outscored 80-30 in the second half, the Redskins have been
forced to play catch up, rendering their running game useless. Yet
Allen has been solid while the games have been competitive. Of his
339 yards rushing, 266 have come in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   When their opponents have rushed for more than 100 yards, the
Cowboys have lost both games. The Broncos beat the Cowboys with big
plays from Terrell Davis. The Raiders, meanwhile, were not
necessarily dominating on the ground. But they ran enough (37
times) to take the pressure off quarterback Jeff George, who
attempted 20 passes and was not intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins hope to employ this same strategy.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cowboys, with tackles Leon Lett and Chad Hennings
nearing full strength, appear to be ready for the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has consistently hammered the ball down our throats,''
Campo said. ``The thing we've got to do is eliminate the big plays.
And the Redskins have the ability to make big plays. They spread
the ball around and get up field. They've just shot themselves in
the foot this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys hope they pull the trigger again Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
