<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER, PITCHING, DEFENSE _ BRAVES SHOW ALL IN 7-1 WIN OVER CUBS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From start to finish, Game 1 was an impressive display
by the Atlanta Braves. They showed power. They got superb pitching
and fielding. And when it was over, the Chicago Cubs had been
pummeled.
</P>
<P>
   With Michael Tucker's two-run home run providing an early lead,
and Ryan Klesko's seventh-inning grand slam turning the game into a
rout, the Braves opened the playoffs with an easy 7-1 victory over
the Cubs Wednesday before 45,598 at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz became the all-time leader in postseason victories
(11), holding the Cubs to one run and five hits through 7 2/3
innings of dominant work. In 21 postseason starts, Smoltz has an
11-3 record, and Wednesday's win moved him past Whitey Ford and
Dave Stewart, both of whom had 10 postseason victories.
</P>
<P>
   It may not get any easier for the Cubs, who will face another
quality starter in Tom Glavine on Thursday night, followed by Greg
Maddux, who will pitch for the Braves in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the playoffs was difficult for the Cubs. But to get
past the Braves, the Cubs will have to find a way to get past
Atlanta's starting pitching. ``Smoltz was the story of the game,
and made us look like we weren't out there fighting,'' said Jim
Riggleman, Chicago's manager. `He wouldn't let us get on base
hardly. And if we put a base runner on, it seemed like he just
turned it up a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   After qualifying for the playoffs by winning a one-game playoff
Monday against the San Francisco Giants, the Cubs hoped to ride
that emotion into Wednesday's game. Instead, the Braves rode the
arm of Smoltz, who struck out six, did not walk a batter, and
prevented the Cubs from reaching second base until the seventh
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the best stuff, but I got away with some
pitches, and the defense was outstanding,'' said Smoltz, who had a
superb 17-3 record during the regular season. ``I'm just going to
continue doing what I've been doing all season, and hopefully it
will be a magical year and we can celebrate a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves never looked back after Tucker's two-run home run in
the second inning against Mark Clark, Chicago's starting and losing
pitcher. Tucker's blast was set up by a Chicago mistake. With two
outs in the bottom of the second, Cubs shortstop Jose Hernandez
failed to end the inning, when he juggled a slow ground ball by
Andruw Jones, allowing him to reach base on an error. Tucker
followed with a drive into the right field seats on a 3-2 pitch,
giving the Braves and Smoltz an early lead on two unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta added another run in the sixth inning to go ahead, 3-0.
After back-to-back singles by Andres Galarraga and Klesko, Jones
hit a sacrifice fly to right field that scored Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the crowning blow, Klesko's grand slam to right field
in the seventh inning against Chicago reliever, Matt Karchner.
Clark started the inning by walking Smoltz, so Riggleman called on
Felix Heredia in relief. But affer Walt Weiss grounded into a
fielder's choice, Heredia walked Keith Lockhart and Chipper Jones
to load the bases. Riggleman replaced Heredia with Karchner, who
got Galarraga to pop out. But after reaching a 3-2 count to Klesko,
Karchner threw a fastball that Klesko powered over the right field
wall, giving the Braves a 7-0 cushion.
</P>
<P>
   With Smoltz pitching, that was far more offense than Atlanta
needed. Tyler Houston hit a solo home run in the eighth inning
against Smoltz to account for Chicago's only run. Sammy Sosa, who
led the Cubs to the playoffs with his remarkable 66 home run
season, went 2 for 4 with a single and a double, and he received a
standing ovation as he stepped into the batter's box in the first
inning. But the Braves kept Sosa in the park, and he was one of the
few Cubs who looked comfortable at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   A key point in the game occurred in the top of the seventh, with
the Cubs still trailing just 3-0. Sosa led off the inning with a
scorching line drive double down the left field line, but he was
stranded at second base, as Smoltz reached back for something
extra. Mark Grace, 0 for 4, flew out weakly to centerfield. The
next better, Henry Rodriquez, was a strikeout victim, then Smoltz
got Gary Gaetti on a ground out to second base.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs will start Kevin Tapani in Game 2, and, as expected,
Kerry Wood was added to Chicago's playoff roster Wednesday, and he
may start Game 3. Wood, a 21-year-old rookie phenom who has been
sidelined with a sore elbow, was 13-6 this year, with 233
strikeouts in 166 2/3 innings. While getting Wood back would give
the Cubs a lift, they need a win in Game 2 to avoid falling behind,
2-0, in the three-of-five game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came down here to win two games, and now we're down here to
win one,'' said Grace. ``We're still a confident bunch. We've
bounced back all year, so we have to try and bounce back
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
