<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI TARGETS ANOTHER NEW YORK NUISANCE: THE POTHOLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Having all but declared victory in his war on crime
and tackled such urban nemeses as squeegee men, jaywalkers and
reckless cab drivers, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced Wednesday
that he was on the verge of eliminating one of New York City's most
irritating ills: the pothole.
</P>
<P>
   The city has made steady progress toward eradicating potholes in
recent years, mostly because the winters have been mild, Giuliani
said. The city filled 64,309 potholes in the 1997 fiscal year and
71,633 in the 1998 fiscal year, and transportation officials said
yesterday that they hoped to fill 85,000 by the end of this
calendar year.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish that goal, 35 construction workers will fan out in
teams to fill what Giuliani claimed were the last 25,000 potholes
scarring city streets.
</P>
<P>
   Some motorists, whose shocks and struts have long battled the
city's legendary potholes, were enthusiastic, although a bit
skeptical, that the mayor could win this latest battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's put himself on the line with this one,'' said Roberto
Williams, a cabbie driving in lower Manhattan Wednesday. ``But I'd
be in favor of it. I need those potholes fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was characteristically resolute, saying his plan was
``very, very well designed'' and vowing that the streets would be
``in the best possible shape'' by early December, when Operation
Pothole Blitz is scheduled to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potholes, of course, are a perennial issue, problem, complaint
in the city of New York,'' Giuliani said, standing near a gaping
hole that city workers had cordoned off in Queens. ``Even Los
Angeles, which has a lot of traffic, doesn't really have the kind
of repetitious traffic that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came two weeks after Giuliani released his
annual management report, which contained mostly good news, but
revealed that only 44 percent of potholes were being repaired
within 30 days of being reported.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation officials said they did not find Giuliani's plan
especially daunting, because the city has an unusually small number
of potholes this year.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly 25,000 potholes that city officials say exist these
days are nothing compared to the 200,000 that scarred city streets
in 1994, after one of the most bruising winters on record. That
winter, a round-the-clock pothole SWAT team filled 85,000 potholes
in 10 days _ more than one for each of the roughly 79,000 blocks in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had two mild winters, so we're pretty much ahead of the
curve,'' said Maria Smith, a spokeswoman for the city Department of
Transportation. ``It's a good time to get every single last one of
them out of here, before we have a bad winter again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said that while the repair teams would hunt for
potholes daily, the transportation department would also post
fliers in dozens of libraries, community centers and schools with
numbers for residents to call to report potholes.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation groups were enthusiastic about the plan
Wednesday, saying it would affect more people than any of
Giuliani's previous quality-of-life campaigns. New York is
notorious for having some of the country's most perilous potholes,
said Douglas Love, a spokesman for the Automobile Club of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted with the mayor's action and look forward to
the day when we can cruise down silky smooth roads,'' Love said.
</P>
<P>
   But the pothole campaign did not escape criticism Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ludovic Blain, legislative advocate for the New York Public
Interest Research Group, said the city should focus on other
problems that were mentioned in the mayor's management report, like
slow police response time to emergencies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, who has challenged several of Giuliani's
quality-of-life crackdowns, said the mayor was focusing on potholes
in an attempt to raise his national image but that he was ignoring
more complex issues facing the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can argue with eliminating potholes,'' Siegel said.
``The only question is whether this should be a high priority in a
city where there are serious systemic problems with regard to race
relations, poor people and many social justice issues that he
hasn't addressed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
