<SLUG> BC-TV-MYSTERY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS' `EVIL' WELL-CRAFTED BUT COLD TO THE TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The newest ``Mystery!'' sleuth isn't portly, whiskered or
pleasantly eccentric. He doesn't even have the weary humanity of
Jane Tennison.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Inspector Dave Creegan (Robson Green) is steel,
stainless and humorless.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shock, in the last hour of ``Touching Evil,'' to hear him
tell a joke. Even then, it's more calculated than mirthful. He's
got a nervous police decoy to calm. It's more telling to watch
Creegan at a raucous children's party with his two kids.
</P>
<P>
   The independent British production premieres Thursday on PBS
with a two-hour story line. Two more ``Touching Evil'' cases unwind
in four one-hour installments beginning October 8.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Abbott (``Cracker''), the screenwriter who created Creegan,
also concocted the elite Organized and Serial Crimes unit, or OSC,
where Creegan and his mates tilt with some of Britain's most
demented criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's case, which resonates through all six hours of
the ``Touching Evil'' series, involves a pharmaceutical engineer
(Ian McDiarmid) who is suspected of abducting three English
schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the OSC is on the case when several patients die of
drug overdoses at a London hospital; someone is practicing murder
under the banner of euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   On October 29 and November 5, the OSC tracks a cyberspace Web
master who uses a computer fantasy game to manipulate youths into
crimes that begin with the mutilation of horses and escalate to
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Gruesome murder. Animal mutilation. Euthanasia. Child abduction.
Obviously, Abbott means to punch emotional buttons and not write an
armchair ``Mystery!'' He scrambles the brain and flutters the
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Creegan nor the production style is any comfort.
``Touching Evil'' is an icy, off-putting and downbeat piece of
business. Even England itself looks coldly impersonal. And then
there's Creegan.
</P>
<P>
   Robson never invites you to cozy up to Creegan. With his sharp
features and brilliant blue eyes, he looks like a cross between a
young Paul Newman and Brian Benben. He bears a scar above his left
eye, from a bullet wound; that experience figures in the euthanasia
story.
</P>
<P>
   His divorce appears to have left him bitter. He's brusque,
intense, impulsive and occasionally flashes an eruptive temper. If
he isn't a manic-depressive, he could probably fool the OSC
assessment team.
</P>
<P>
   You get the impression that Creegan takes personally every
brutal crime committed in Great Britain. Probably in the former
colonies, too.
</P>
<P>
   The only softening element for Creegan and for ``Touching Evil''
is Creegan's partner, Susan Taylor (Nicola Walker). She's not
exactly Oprah Winfrey herself, but she seems capable of spending a
couple of hours a day away from her job.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and Creegan become casual lovers midway through the
series. It's not even officially underscored as a plot development;
it just seems to happen.
</P>
<P>
   So ``Touching Evil'' isn't for everyone. It's for the viewer who
prefers a boa constrictor over a puppy as a pet.
</P>
<P>
   This is cold-blooded, reptilian television. But it's good
cold-blooded, reptilian television.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
