<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Springs to shut down mill, modernize its other plant
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRIFFIN, Ga. _ Springs Industries Inc. said Wednesday it will
close Griffin's oldest textile mill and spend $26 million to
modernize its other Griffin plant as it cuts costs and brings its
towel manufacturing up to date.
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred jobs will be lost, or about 16 percent of Springs'
1,900-person work force in Griffin, when the project is completed
in mid-1999. Besides adding 55,000 square feet to the second plant,
Springs is spending $40 million to build a weaving plant in
Hartwell, Ga. Springs is based in Fort Mill, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Springs' Dundee Mills Plant 1 _ Dundee Mills was purchased by
Springs in 1995 _ opened in 1888. It takes in raw cotton and
manufactures towels under the brand names of Dundee, Centennial and
Spring Maid.
</P>
<P>
   But the rambling facility, which has been added onto and
revamped many times, just isn't suited for another overhaul,
Springs spokesperson Betty Turner said. Springs, a maker of home
furnishings and specialty fabrics, announced in March it would cut
costs and modernize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Textile manufacturers always have to be on the lookout to
reduce costs,'' said analyst Kay C. Norwood at Interstate/Johnson
Lane. Discount retailers Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and Kmart Corp.
``fall over themselves to see who can cut costs first, so there's
constant pricing pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood said Springs' third-quarter earnings will come in below
last year's $1.19 per share because of problems keeping inventories
under control. The company is expected to earn 77 cents, the
average estimate of seven analysts surveyed by First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Springs, with 1997 revenue of $2.23 billion, operates plants in
10 states.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the company said it would close a 69-year-old
textile mill in Rock Hill, S.C., and fire 480 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Springs shares have fallen more than 42 percent since mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the loss of jobs comes just days after
Thomaston Mills said it was closing a plant in Griffin, sending 150
employees to its plants in Pike and Upson counties.
</P>
<P>
   Spalding County Commission Chairman Martha McDaniel noted
Spalding County, which once was dominated by textile mills, has
several new companies, including Caterpillar, Hoshizaki and Nacom,
looking for workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years ago this would have been devastating,'' McDaniel
said. ``It still is sad for the people who have worked at the mill
for years to have to leave, but the ones who want to work should be
able to find jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said affected workers will get the first shot at
vacancies at other Springs plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the people of Spalding County, it's a landmark,'' McDaniel
said. ``If Springs is not going to use it, I'd like to see it
converted to loft apartments or turn the property into a park.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
