<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-PENSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADER MAY HAVE CAUSED $150 MILLION LOSS AT AT&AMP;T PENSION FUND  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A trader in Boston cost a pension fund for employees
of AT&AMP;T Corp. $150 million in 1996 as he made huge unauthorized
bets on the direction of technology stocks, the Securities and
Exchange Commission contended in a lawsuit Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said the trader, Bing Sung, also lost $12 million
belonging to a pension fund for Massachusetts teachers and state
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Sung managed hundreds of millions of dollars for the two funds
for at least three years while he was chief investment officer of
Rhumbline Advisers, a firm that mostly manages funds meant to
mirror the performance of stock indexes.
</P>
<P>
   The commission sued Sung, 51, in federal district court in
Boston, accusing him of securities fraud and seeking unspecified
monetary damages. The commission also announced Wednesday that
Rhumbline and its chief executive, John Nelson, had agreed to fines
and other penalties to settle an SEC proceeding against them for
failing to adequately supervise Sung.
</P>
<P>
   Rhumbline agreed to a censure, to improve its monitoring of
employees' compliance with securities laws, and to pay a $50,000
fine. Nelson agreed to pay a $10,000 fine. He also agreed to stop
serving as an investment adviser for three months and to relinquish
his supervisory role for an additional nine months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're at the helm, you're at the helm,'' Nelson said in a
telephone interview Wednesday. ``We hired a lot of expertise and I
put confidence in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson founded Rhumbline in 1990 after serving as a division
head for State Street Bank. He said his company no longer traded
options and would concentrate on index funds.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at home in Andover, Mass., Wednesday night, Sung would
say only that, ``I deny categorically all of the charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Sung joined Rhumbline in 1991 after serving as chief trader for
Harvard Management Co., which invests Harvard University's
multibillion dollar endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Sung's losses, as described by the commission, fall well short
of recent unauthorized losses at Daiwa Bank, Barings PLC and Showa
Shell Sekiyu, each of which came to more than $1 billion, as well
as the $350 million in false profits that Joseph Jett, the bond
trader, was accused of creating while at Kidder, Peabody &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   But the losses would overshadow the $128 million lost by the
Common Fund, which invests for colleges, in 1995 because of
unauthorized trading at First Capital Strategists Inc. That episode
prompted many institutional investors to tighten their controls on
outside money managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of unauthorized trading and failure to disclose, this
ranks up there,'' Grant Ward, an assistant district administrator
for the SEC's Boston office, said. ``You have to have systems in
place to monitor what's going on. Rhumbline didn't have the people
or the systems in place to monitor what was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the AT&AMP;T and Massachusetts funds were able to absorb a
multimillion dollar loss. When the alleged fraud was first
discovered, in September 1996, the AT&AMP;T fund held about $47
billion. The Massachusetts fund holds about $22 billion. The $150
million loss is roughly equivalent to only one day's revenue for
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's lawsuit followed a two-year investigation by the
commission. According to the SEC's complaint, all of Sung's $150
million in losses for the AT&AMP;T fund were realized in the third
quarter of 1996 but came after almost two years of unauthorized
trading.
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, Rhumbline had agreed to manage
AT&AMP;T's options programs in a conservative fashion, with no
potential losses on index options of more than $6 million, and
limiting the writing of options for technology stocks to $25
million in underlying value. But beginning in early 1995, according
to the complaint, Sung began to exceed those limits while at times
misleading AT&AMP;T. In late 1995, Sung secured waivers from normal
limits on options trading at the Chicago Board Options Exchange and
the Philadelphia Stock Exchange by fraudulently saying he was
hedging $9 billion in stock holdings by AT&AMP;T, according to the
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Sung's positions grew so large that by September 1996, the
options on the Nasdaq 100 index in AT&AMP;T's Rhumbline account made up
two-thirds of the entire market for those options, according to the
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``They engaged in hedge activity that was far riskier than we
had authorized and for amounts that were far in excess of that we
authorized,'' Eileen Connolly, an AT&AMP;T spokeswoman, said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tanya Styblo Beder, principal for Capital Market Risk
Advisors Inc., which consults investors on risk controls for their
investments, said AT&AMP;T potentially could have done more to protect
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unfortunate thing here is that this is not a new fraud and
there are many well-established techniques in the marketplace for
avoiding this sort of risk fiasco,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, AT&AMP;T has put in place daily electronic monitoring of
trades made on its behalf, Ms. Connolly said. She said those
measures would help insure that the company could not be taken
advantage of by unauthorized trading in the future.
</P>
<P>
   R. Scott Henderson, executive director and general counsel for
the Massachusetts Pension Reserves Investment Management Board,
which oversees the Massachusetts fund, said Rhumbline had
reimbursed the fund for less than half of the $12 million in
losses. Ms. Connolly said AT&AMP;T had received a small amount, but
that it was a mere fraction of $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
