<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FBCCOL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 TEAMS CAN'T EVEN SPELL RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether you were in Lincoln, Neb., Tallahassee, Fla., or simply
watching The Weather Channel last Saturday, there wasn't much
reason to cheer for the Pac-10. The conference that seems
perpetually incapable of producing a national champion put its
prestige on the line with three marquee games before the entire
country.
</P>
<P>
   Make that two games, but more on that later.
</P>
<P>
   First to Nebraska, where the Cornhuskers throttled Washington
55-7. It was only the Cornhuskers' largest victory ever against a
top-10 opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to crawl into a hole,'' Washington quarterback
Brock Huard said. ``It was just a bad, bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Huard, considered one of the top quarterbacks in the country,
was waving the white flag by the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Stop hitting me.' He was starting to whine a
little,'' said Nebraska defensive end Chad Kelsay. ``But his
offensive line wasn't giving him much protection and it had to get
old time after time having guys in his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Down in Florida, things were only slightly better. USC produced
23 yards passing and was pushed around like a 98-pound weakling in
a 30-10 loss to Florida State. Perhaps indicative of where the
Pac-10 stands today, Florida State coach Bobby Bowden couldn't
resist taking a minor dig after the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nearly like a child in that game,'' Bowden said. ``It
was all because of having USC in our stadium. I nearly couldn't
believe it. Twenty years ago, USC was playing for national
championships and we were little ol' Florida State.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   The one contest in which it looked like the Pac-10 would save
some face is becoming the most lingering embarrassment. UCLA's game
with Miami was canceled, uh, postponed, by Hurricane Georges, the
hurricane that went everywhere but Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Bruins are clearly the superior team, their manhood
is being challenged in Miami. Hurricanes officials are portraying
the Bruins as losing their nerve by backing off attempts to
reschedule the game. Miami athletic director Paul Dee said Tuesday
the Hurricanes want to reschedule, but UCLA has scheduling
``impediments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of the University of Miami, we really don't have any
impediments,'' Dee said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about UCLA's ``impediments,'' Dee responded, ``You'd have
to ask them.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrows are coming from all directions and with good reason.
The Pac-10 is offering little resistance from critics who believe
the conference remains too pass-happy and finesse-oriented to ever
seriously compete against the nation's elite.
</P>
<P>
   As far restoring its national reputation, the Pac-10 won't have
many more chances as the teams settle into conference games. That
means teams will beat up on each other and there's little hope of
watching a Pac-10 team in the Fiesta Bowl on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   __ Mourning a friend: The day after he rushed for 318 yards
against Rice _ the second-highest single game total in school
history _ Texas running back Ricky Williams learned he had lost a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Williams won the Doak Walker Award, which is given
to the nation's top running back. Sunday, Walker, the former SMU
star and the 1948 Heisman Trophy winner, died from complications of
being paralyzed in a skiing accident in January.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Walker became friends, particularly after Walker
suffered his injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to dedicate the season to him and try to win the
award that carries his name,'' said Williams, who is third
nationally in rushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I look at his photo in my locker, I'll think of
everything he stood for,'' Williams said. ``Things like humility
and being well-liked and respected by everybody. I'll try to
emulate him as much as I can. He had accomplished so much in his
life, but he was very humble.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Team cheerleader: Where else but Vanderbilt could a
cheerleader end up playing on the football team?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some girls talked me into trying out for cheerleading,'' said
Thomas Gallant. ``A friend of mine was already on the squad and
said, `Just come out and meet the girls,' and I said, `OK.' I threw
a couple of them in the air and it was kind of fun so I decided to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always talked to my cheerleading partner about what it would
be like to be out there playing.''
</P>
<P>
   So he tried out for Vandy's team last spring and has earned some
playing time on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kelly Adams, Gallant's former cheerleading partner: ``I was
a little concerned about him playing in the SEC. There are some big
guys out there and I didn't want him to get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Bet the over: The Minnesota-Purdue game Saturday will make
bookies earn their money when it comes to the over-under line. The
two teams have combined for 437 points and 5,104 yards of total
offense in their last five meetings. That's an average of 87.4
points and 1,021 yards a game.
</P>
<P>
   The scores: 59-43 in 1997, 30-27 in 1996, 39-38 in 1995, 49-37
in 1994, 59-56 in 1993. (The Gophers won in 1993 and 1995, Purdue
in 1994, 1996 and 1997.)
</P>
<P>
   __ On the hot seat: Speculation increases daily that South
Carolina coach Brad Scott is in serious trouble even though his
contract was extended last year and runs through 2001. ``I'm not
worried about that a bit,'' Scott insisted last week, which means
he is probably in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The 70,052 fans who watched the 38-0 loss to Mississippi State
was the smallest turnout since the stadium was expanded prior to
the 1996 season. Doesn't that still make the stadium the
second-largest city in the state? &QL; 
TOP 10 &QL; 
1. Nebraska (4-0): Too bad Huskers can't expose K-State as fraud
now instead of later. &QL; 
2. Ohio State (3-0): Buckeyes get first test with Penn State. Will
they choke? &QL; 
3. Kansas State (4-0): Enough with the victories over all those
directional schools. &QL; 
4. Florida State (3-1): Seminoles defense makes up for
inconsistency of QB Chris Weinke. &QL; 
5. LSU (3-0): Best team in country that remains question mark but
keeps winning. &QL; 
6. Tennessee (3-0): Big surprise here. Houston coach Kim Helton
likes Vols over Bruins. &QL; 
7. UCLA (2-0): Miami Hurricanes not nearly as big a headache as
Hurricane Georges. &QL; 
8. Florida (3-1): Gee, now Steve Spurrier says he'll finally start
recruiting a kicker. &QL; 
9. Syracuse (2-1): Orangemen have regrouped nicely from early loss
to Tennessee. &QL; 
10. Penn State (3-0): Even with bye, somehow a two-touchdown
underdog to Ohio State. &QL; 
__ Five more to watch: Virginia (4-0), Colorado (4-0), Texas A&AMP;M
(3-1), Georgia (3-0), Oregon (4-0).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
