<HEADER>
A3001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOCKS-QUARTER-COX     09-30 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-QUARTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stocks' quarter worst since '90
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The stock market ended its worst quarter in eight
years Wednesday with the bears seemingly in control.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, fearing banks will be hurt by trouble at some hedge
funds and disappointed by the size of the Federal Reserve's
interest rate cut, accelerated the selling they began Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also blamed the market's bearish mood on investor worry
about third-quarter profits, problems in Asia and Japan, and
closer-to-home currency problems in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street was hoping the Fed would lower rates, but when a cut
finally came Tuesday, the quarter-percentage-point decline in
federal funds _ to 5.25 percent _ failed to satisfy U.S. investors.
Europeans regarded the rate cut as too conservative.
</P>
<P>
   But as small as it was, some analysts viewed it as a significant
recognition by the Fed that foreign currency problems have replaced
inflation as the main threat to the U.S. economy _ a threat the
rate cut was designed to thwart.
</P>
<P>
   Fed defenders say the rate cut was most likely the first of
several cuts by a central bank that chooses to be cautious, but has
demonstrated a willingness to go as far as necessary to get its job
done.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction by many banks was to cut their prime rate from 8.5
percent to 8.25 percent. The prime is a benchmark for many business
and consumer loans, including home equity lines and credit card
rates. That came as the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell
below 5 percent for the first time. What happened was that the
flight from stocks to bonds pushed Treasury prices higher. That
lowered yields, which move opposite to price.
</P>
<P>
   The selling of stocks pushed the Dow Jones industrial down 2.9
percent and the Nasdaq composite down 2.3 percent. The Dow's
decline _ nearly 238 points _ was its seventh-biggest one-day point
drop.
</P>
<P>
   While all the major stock averages posted their worst
July-September losses since the third quarter of 1990, a number of
factors help put the sell-off in perspective:
</P>
<P>
   --The losses were smaller than in 1990. The Dow's loss was 12.39
percent vs. 14.86 percent eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   --Unlike 1990, when the losses occurred throughout the quarter,
most of this year's damage was done in July and August. September,
historically a down month for stocks, saw the Dow post a 4 percent
gain in volatile trading.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with interest rates low, inflation under control and the
Fed moving to protect the economy, the stock market's biggest
challenge is the prospect of some dismal corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   And the omens have not been good. Company after company came
forth in September with disappointing advance announcements,
including Coca-Cola, Gillette, RJR Nabisco Holdings, Nike, Deere
and Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   First Call, a Boston-based research group that tracks analysts
earnings estimates, said third-quarter profits are expected to
decline for the first time since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Estimates for the third quarter are showing the steepest
downward revisions than for any quarter since the 1990-'91
recession,'' said First Call research director Charles L. Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But an earnings decline is not the same as a loss, and some
analysts argue that earnings growth of any size against a strong
U.S. economic backdrop will set the stage for a bullish rally. Some
analysts believe the worst of the sell-off is already over, as
reflected in the September upturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of encouraging technical market indicators
that support our view that the lows for the year have been seen,''
said Alfred E. Goldman, chief market strategist for A.G. Edwards &AMP;
Sons.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he noted that bearish sentiment among Wall Street
professionals is at the highest level since 1994 _ a positive
signal for contrarians.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
