<SLUG> BC-IMF-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF ISSUES PESSIMISTIC ASSESSMENT OF RUSSIAN, JAPANESE ECONOMIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-IMF) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an unusually pessimistic report, the
International Monetary Fund said on Wednesday that it now expects
the Russian economy to contract by 6 percent this year and next,
and Japan to sink into its deepest recession since the end of World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued a day before finance ministers from around
the world arrive here for annual meetings of the World Bank and the
IMF, also drastically scales back estimates of how fast other
economies will grow. It urges 90 percent of the world's central
banks to cut interest rates in an effort to spur growth and calls
for greater cuts in the United States. The Federal Reserve on
Tuesday announced its first cut in three years _ a modest
quarter-percent off one of its key short-term rates.
</P>
<P>
   Usually the IMF puts the very best spin on bad news. Repeatedly
it has said the Asian crisis _ and its destabilizing effects around
the world _ was abating. On Wednesday, instead, it warned that
``Chances of any significant improvement in 1999 have also
diminished and the risks of a deeper, wider and more prolonged
downturn have escalated.''
</P>
<P>
   Another notable change in this report was the call for interest
rate cuts. Just months ago, the IMF was prescribing high interest
rates in Thailand, Korea, Indonesia and then Russia, confident that
once their currencies were stabilized there would be a chance to
cut rates again and resume growth. But now the IMF _ and the U.S.
Treasury, which deeply influences the fund _ regard the choking off
of growth as the greatest risk.
</P>
<P>
   The news about Russia came as the World Bank, in another blow to
the government of President Boris Yeltsin, suggested that it might
have to cancel $6 billion in planned aid for the country. The money
was promised in July, before Russia let its ruble devalue and
forced out virtually all of its economic reformers. Since then the
IMF has suspended its aid &UR; to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; p
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not a total of $6 billion for the 18-month period
makes sense is, I think, debatable at this point,'' Johannes Linn,
World Bank vice president for Europe and Central Asia, told a news
conference on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In its report on Wednesday, the IMF predicted that world growth
would be limited to 2 percent this year. That is a huge step
backward: A year ago, before its last annual meeting in Hong Kong,
the fund forecast that the global economy would expand by 4.3
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's slowdown is perhaps the most worrisome news. The fund
predicted that the world's second largest economy would shrink by
2.5 percent this year. Until recently, most economists have guessed
that Japan's growth would be zero to minus 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's growth is critical because it serves as the engine for
other Asian economies. But the downturn in Japan is so severe that
the country's banks have stopped lending _ causing a credit crunch
that is freezing economies in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF's revised figures also show that five of Asia's most
critical economies will be deep in recession this year: Malaysia,
Indonesia, Thailand, the Philippines and South Korea. Indonesia's
downturn will be the worst, and rice shortages there are
increasingly severe. China's economy, the IMF said, will grow at
5.5 percent, making it the healthiest major economy in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
