<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED-SOX-INDIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY EJECTIONS SERVE AS INDIANS' WAKEUP CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Down 1-0 in the series, behind 2-0 early in the
game, with even the umpires ]apparently against them, the Cleveland
Indians responded yesterday like defending American League
champions.
</P>
<P>
   They came out fighting. Or, at the very least, yelling and
cursing. Their response led to the early ejection of their manager
and their starting pitcher, but the ultimate result was worth it: a
9-5 Game 2 victory against the Red Sox that sends the series to
Boston tied at a game apiece.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that showed as much emotion as a sleepwalker for most
of the regular season, the game was a revelation. The Indians could
play a fiery brand of baseball, as Cleveland players acknowledged.
It just took a brouhaha with an umpire to ignite them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were intense coming in knowing that we can't go to Boston
down two games,'' said Indians' hitting star of the day, David
Justice, who drove in four runs with a home run and a double. But
it was the two swift ejections, he added, that took his team's
intensity to another level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say the umpires are against us,'' Justice
said, ``but when you look across the field and see the Red Sox want
to beat you, and then something happens early and you feel like,
man, everyone is against us. I think that makes the players dig
down inside, come together, up our intensity and just go take it.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened early to motivate the Indians was that Cleveland
manager Mike Hargrove and starting pitcher Dwight Gooden were
thrown out of the game in the first inning by home-plate umpire Joe
Brinkman.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove was tossed, Brinkman said in a prepared statement, for
``questioning balls and strikes'' to leadoff hitter Darren Lewis.
``The ejection of Gooden, which came three batters later, occurred
after Gooden, ``screamed an expletive right in my ear,'' Brinkman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden's dismissal followed what appeared to be a blown call at
the plate that cost the Indians a run and an out. Brinkman ruled
Boston base runner John Valentin safe at home even though videotape
replays indicated Cleveland catcher Sandy Alomar appeared to have
tagged Valentin out well before he touched the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The run, coming on a double by red-hot Nomar Garciaparra, gave
the Red Sox a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden's surprise dismissal turned out well for the Indians,
however, and not just because of the spark it provided. It also
caused Cleveland to go to the bullpen for Dave Burba, a starter all
season long who Hargrove had moved to a long relief role for the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Burba came on with a runner in scoring position, down two runs
and stopped the Red Sox's momentum, quickly ending the first inning
without further damage and pitching well into the sixth. He left
with the Indians leading 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a fantastic job for that club, bottom line,'' Red Sox
manager Jimy Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave stepped up huge for us today,'' Hargrove said. ``He came
in in a tough situation. He threw strikes and he got us out of the
\Rfirst\S inning with only two runs being scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Burba's performance bought the Indians time to mount a comeback.
They got one run back in the first on a Justice sacrifice fly.
Cleveland took a 6-2 lead in the second inning when nine men went
to the plate. Justice's three-run home run off Boston reliever John
Wasdin, who replaced knuckleballer Tim Wakefield in the inning, was
his ninth career postseason homer.
</P>
<P>
   Justice has been plagued by knee problems all season that he
said have affected his hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it felt pretty good,'' he said, ``I hit the ball pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   With the series tied heading to Fenway Park, Hargrove also was
feeling better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go in there,'' he said, ``feeling good about winning
today when we had to. Now it's down to a best of three.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
