<HEADLINE>
BANK ROBBERS BRANCH OUT INTO LANDSCAPING
</HEADLINE>
 THE BUSH-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL WEISSENSTEIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ Their landscaping was excellent. Their bank robbing
needed a little work.
</P>
<P>
   In a move evoking cartoon coyotes sneaking up on the Roadrunner,
two men who robbed a Bank of America branch Wednesday apparently
camouflaged their hiding spot near the entrance with a half-dozen
waist-high shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   Two bank employees who arrived to open the South Hulen Street
branch about 8 a.m. paid no attention to the additional bushes
until the masked men burst out and ordered them into the bank at
gunpoint, bank officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They noticed the additional shrubbery there, but really
attributed it to landscapers who had not necessarily cleaned up
after they trimmed,'' said Darryl Ewing, a Bank of America
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The robbery plan swiftly unraveled from there.
</P>
<P>
   A bank employee included a dye pack in the bag of money from the
safe. The remotely activated device was triggered when the robbers
tried to get out the locked back door, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The robbers found the keys and unlocked the back door, but not
before the dye pack exploded, staining the money red. The robbers
dropped the bag of cash on the bank floor and fled, leaving the
money _ and the bushes _ behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is assuming that the bad guys brought it,'' police Lt.
Alice Adams said about the shrubbery. ``We won't know that until we
catch them and they tell us.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams didn't know whether the bushes were collected as evidence,
and she speculated that they may have been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that people who rob banks buy their own
shrubs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
