<HEADLINE>
OFF CITY ON GULF COAST, CASINOS RIDE OUT STORM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Nev., N.J.)   (See also DOMINICAN-GEORGES, moved in `i' category) 
(nk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILOXI, Miss. _ The locals call it the Mississippi Miracle. But
proud as they are of the glittering gambling casinos that over the
past six years have turned this once-seedy Gulf Coast town into
something akin to Atlantic City South, the people of Biloxi have
always had in the back of their minds that, well, if the time ever
comes when the chips are really down during hurricane season,
Biloxi might need a more heavenly kind of miracle.
</P>
<P>
   For unlike Atlantic City, N.J., and for sure unlike the desert
city of Las Vegas, Biloxi is one gambling town that requires, by
law, that casinos float.
</P>
<P>
   This is not some kind of enticement concept, anything but.
Rather, it is a legal conceit whose intent is to isolate gambling,
confine it, so that the sensibilities of those who see wagering as
sin or socially destructive are salved. That concession is no small
consideration down here in the Bible Belt or in parts of the
straight-laced Midwest, where casinos are often required to float
on rivers.
</P>
<P>
   If Las Vegas had a floating casino requirement, they'd put the
paddle wheeler Delta Queen in the middle of a big pond out among
the plastic magnolias and cactus and have some Rhett Butler
character _ cheroot, riverboat gambler's white hat and all _
greeting patrons at the gangplank. They may yet do that. But here
in Biloxi, with a couple of exceptions, casino operators have met
the boat requirement by building businesslike, windowless gaming
rooms on huge barges, then permanently snugging up the barges so
close to waterside hotels that they look like extensions of the
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 6,000 gamblers who visit almost-tropical Biloxi each
day never know they are afloat as they work the tables and slots of
what is now the third busiest gambling town in the country, behind
Las Vegas and Atlantic City. But they are afloat, hence the concern
about the eventual Big Blow.
</P>
<P>
   It came shortly before dawn on Monday when Hurricane Georges
pounded ashore, fixing its eye on Biloxi and then battering its
already deserted casino row with 100-mph-plus winds.
</P>
<P>
   Trees and billboards went down. Shingles, siding, even entire
houses went flying. A 10-foot tidal surge, combined with more than
a foot of rain, left water, sand, sailboats, fish and not a few
alligators and snakes in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   But the barges _ the anchor, as it were, of a $2 billion
investment in Biloxi by gambling operators _ rode it out with only
minor damage. So, too, did the adjacent hotels, though several
hundred of the 14,000 rooms suffered water damage when their
windows were smashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always said we could build casinos that would ride one out
and we did,'' Harry Joachim, the executive director of the Biloxi
Chamber of Commerce, said Wednesday, relief in his voice, as repair
crews and cleanup teams labored to put everything back in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say we weren't lucky,'' he added, ``because
the whole Gulf Coast was pretty lucky this time around. But we came
through as advertised.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, most casinos will probably be shut down for the better
part of a week for repairs and refurbishing, which will cost them,
together, better than $3 million a day in gambling revenue, and
perhaps that much more again in lodging, restaurant and other
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to come out of this OK but it's going to set
them back a bit for a while in revenue and the number of patrons
playing,'' said Jason Ader, a gambling analyst for Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   At least one casino, Treasure Bay, could be shut down for almost
two weeks. Its barge, which actually looks like a pirate ship
instead of part of a hotel, suffered some hull damage _ above the
waterline _ when surging seas slammed it against some pilings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was designed to pull itself away from the shore and ride
out storms while moored fore and aft between two sets of big
posts,'' Barbara Shattles, Treasure Bay's executive vice president,
said. ``But it cut loose a little bit too much and took some hard
banging. Still, we consider the system a big success.''
</P>
<P>
   Most other Biloxi barges not only do not look like pirate ships
or any other kind of vessel but also do not sit as exposed to open
water as the Treasure Bay barge, which is docked on the beach
front. Some are nestled in coves, while others lie behind
breakwaters, protective measures that stood up well against
Georges.
</P>
<P>
   Just west of Biloxi, at Gulfport, the Copa, another casino that
more resembles a boat than a barge, rode out Georges by taking on
water as ballast. It, too, suffered only minimal damage, according
to gaming officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel pretty good about the way things turned out,'' Chuck
Patton, executive director of the Mississippi Gaming Commission,
said. ``The fact is, for all the dire warnings, the casinos are
designed to take a lot more than Georges offered. But let's hope
that test never comes.''
</P>
<P>
   How much more?
</P>
<P>
   ``Upwards of 200 miles an hour,'' Ms. Shattles of Treasure Bay
said. ``But that's something you don't even want to think about,
especially if you lived through Camille back in 1969. I did. When
she came ashore here, she was blowing a 150 miles an hour and more
and it was terrifying, just absolutely terrifying. We got
flattened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
