<HEADER>
A3010 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICHS-COX     09-30 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICHS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rich's doing far more than moving furniture at `flagship'
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Depending on which floor you're on, the Rich's at
Gwinnett Place mall either looks like the classiest store in the
chain or a disaster area.
</P>
<P>
   Practically everything is new upstairs, where hardwood fixtures
and racks gleam in brightly lit departments. But it's a virtual war
zone on the level below as shoppers dodge construction workers
scrambling to finish a major overhaul by Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   This is no run-of-the-mill renovation, though. The changes under
way at Gwinnett Place signify a new direction for the Atlanta-based
Rich's/Lazarus/Goldsmith's division of Federated Department Stores,
which is revamping the store at a cost of $20 million _ double what
the entire mall is spending on its current renovation project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gwinnett Place store represents a strategy we either have
or will replicate in other cities,'' said Russell Stravitz,
chairman and chief executive of the $2.17 billion division. ``This
is our new flagship department store, which is designed to be the
dominant department store in its trading area.''
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy is being rolled out in the Gwinnett Place
store, which generates the highest volume in metro Atlanta,
Stravitz said. ``Atlanta is very important to our strategy,'' he
said. ``We will probably have three to four of these flagships
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich's, along with the nearly identical Lazarus and Goldsmith's
chains, is Federated's third-largest division behind Macy's East
and Macy's West. Rich's currently has 13 stores in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Since Federated merged with Macy's in 1994, industry observers
and shoppers have wondered how the precarious competition with
Rich's would pan out in metro Atlanta, where you'll find both
anchors in seven of the area's 13 major malls. But in a rare media
interview, Stravitz outlined a strategy that would indicate Rich's
has dug in its heels on its home turf _ at least for the immediate
future.
</P>
<P>
   The guts of the new flagship strategy, Stravitz says, is pulling
the furniture out of the main store and showcasing it in a
50,000-square-foot free-standing showroom, as it did outside
Gwinnett Place earlier this year. ``This allows us to expand the
department store fully so that we have very large apparel and soft
lines,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Removing the furniture from the 270,000-square-foot Gwinnett
Place store allowed Rich's to expand all departments 30 percent to
40 percent. The new flagship stores are larger than most Rich's,
which range from 150,000 to 225,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   The departments also are better organized, Stravitz said.
``We've put all the women's apparel on one floor so that it's
easier to shop,'' he said. Everything associated with men's
merchandise has been grouped together, too.
</P>
<P>
   Like many department stores, Rich's is courting designer-hungry
shoppers who have embraced certain brands so much that designer
labels are popping up all over the store. From shirts to sheets,
Tommy Hilfiger is hot. So is Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to designer brands, department stores are increasing
private labeling because it tends to deter price comparisons, and
it's more profitable because no middlemen are involved. Plus, it
allows retailers to distinguish themselves with something other
than price.
</P>
<P>
   But the concept of differentiation is fuzzy within Federated,
which carries the same private labels under different department
store names. Federated's private labels, which include Charter
Club, Alfani and Inc., generate about 15 percent of sales.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Rich's/Lazarus/Goldsmith's division, the main
distinguishing feature among the nameplates is the sign on the
outside of the building. Everything inside is the same, except for
differences in regional merchandise, where Federated has made great
strides in tailoring its inventory on a store-by-store basis,
Stravitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Through high-tech scanners, individual cash registers track and
reorder individual items as they are sold. ``In many cases, the
customer is (restocking) the merchandise herself,'' Stravitz said.
``Because everything is electronically tracked, we can be back in
stock as quickly as one week.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich's, along with other Federated stores, is also tackling its
customer service image, which began sliding in the late 1980s and
early 1990s as management became preoccupied with cost cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Employees have said they didn't have time to help customers
because the cutbacks forced them to take on other jobs like
stocking or cleaning. ``We are trying to create more time for sales
managers and associates to spend more time helping customers,''
Stravitz said.
</P>
<P>
   At Rich's, for example, the staff has been split into teams. The
merchandise crew starts at 3:30 a.m. to stock and clean so the
sales staff is free to sell.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious customer service effort is the company has
ditched individual registers for large, clearly marked checkout
stations at the juncture of departments. ``It's very clear where
you can get service now,'' Stravitz said.
</P>
<P>
   As one of 93 department stores in the Federated family to
undergo a major remodeling project, the timing of the new Rich's at
Gwinnett Place is particularly crucial, analysts and observers
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to get this done before the Mall of Georgia came
in,'' said Brenda Gilpatrick, an Atlanta-based retail marketing
consultant. Rich's pulled out of the Mall of Georgia, which has
signed Dillard's, Nordstrom and Lord &AMP; Taylor as anchors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're rushing on this one because when Nordstrom opened at
Perimeter Mall, Rich's got caught with its pants down,'' Gilpatrick
said. Rich's was still in the midst of a major renovation at
Perimeter when Nordstrom opened in February.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say it's a matter of time until Federated pares down
the overlap between the Rich's and Macy's chains, which go after
the same middle-to-upper-scale customer. Tight-lipped Federated
executives say they're holding on to the brand names to preserve
the local identities of various chains, but analysts say customers
could care less.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things start opening like Mall of Georgia or Nordstrom,
all that history goes out the door. There's no loyalty among
customers today _ all they see is Tommy Hilfiger or Donna Karan,''
said Prudential Securities analyst Wayne Hood.
</P>
<P>
   Federated would not likely give up anchor spots to competitors
when it decides to consolidate, but it may split up its merchandise
to have women's apparel in one store spot and menswear in another,
said Hood, who noted such a plan would fit in with its merchandise
expansion strategy at Gwinnett. ``Just because they're building the
bricks and mortar doesn't mean they won't eventually change the
identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
