<HEADER>
A3011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEDGEFUND-REGULATE-80     09-30 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-REGULATE-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS TO DEBATE GREATER OVERSIGHT OF HEDGE FUNDS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE WAYNE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the financiers who rescued Long-Term Capital
Management try to salvage what is left of the hedge fund, Congress
will debate whether these secretive, risky investment funds that
cater to the very rich should be subject to greater scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The House Banking Committee will take up the issue Thursday at a
hearing where Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve,
William McDonough, the president of the New York Federal Reserve
Bank, securities officials and top financial regulators will
testify.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital nearly collapsed last week from an enormous
amount of bad bets with borrowed money in turbulent global markets.
A group of big banks and brokerage houses, fearful that a collapse
would further destabilize the markets, rescued the fund with a $3.6
billion package of loans.
</P>
<P>
   For as long as hedge funds have been around, since the late
1960s, Congress and regulators have struggled over how to properly
supervise investment funds that can cause financial damage but are
organized in ways that escape securities laws and minimize the
information they must disclose.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, future attempts to bring about greater
governmental oversight of hedge funds might become mired in the
same tangled issues, politics and complicated details that have
kept regulators away.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, lawmakers are long on concern but short on specific
ideas. Following other hedge fund calamities, whether the 1992
Salomon Brothers ``squeeze'' on the government securities market
using hedge funds or the 1994 collapse of the $600 million Askin
Capital Management hedge fund, hearings, reports, studies and
recommendations have flowed from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been mild tweaks in existing regulations even
as the industry has expanded to about 4,500 domestic and offshore
funds with nearly $300 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the types of financial transactions done by
hedge funds have become more complicated and could present greater
global risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hedge funds have been allowed to exist in a regulatory black
hole,'' said Edward Markey, D-Mass., and member of the House
Banking Committee. ``Hedge funds are defined by what they are not.
They are not mutual funds. They are not banks. They are not
brokers. They are constructed in ways in which the wealthiest
people in America can invest and do it without any regulation. And
this creates huge problems since hedge funds have acted so
irresponsible as to threaten a global financial collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Greenspan has dismissed the need for more oversight,
saying that hedge funds are ``strongly regulated by those who lend
the money,'' mainly banks and Wall Street firms. But even Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin, who is not scheduled to testify, has
admitted the free market may have faltered. In response to
Greenspan's comment, Rubin said: ``That assumes the creditors are
careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the difficulty of regulating hedge funds is the
slipperiness about what a hedge fund is. No precise legal
definition exists. The term ``hedge fund'' is not even used in
federal securities law. Generally, though, hedge funds in the
United States are private partnerships of wealthy, sophisticated
investors that buy and sell stocks, bonds, commodities and more
exotic derivative securities, using sophisticated strategies to
make bets on their direction.
</P>
<P>
   Offshore hedge funds are usually mutual funds headquartered in a
tax haven country, with some structured so that they can accept
American customers.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1992, a joint report on hedge funds by the Treasury,
the Securities and Exchange Commission and the Fed concluded that
``regulators have little access to information about these entities
and their day-to-day activities'' and warned of the ``potential of
these funds, due to their size, active market presence and use of
leverage, to cause market disruptions.'' Hedge funds are generally
not subject to SEC oversight because they are private. They do not
have to register with the SEC as broker-dealers and provide
disclosure because they fall under a ``trader'' exemption because
hedge funds trade for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge funds escape oversight, too, from the Investment Company
Act of 1940, which regulates mutual funds, because, again, hedge
funds do not make public offerings. As a result, hedge funds are
exempt from regulations on disclosure, fees and borrowing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Conversely, hedge funds face indirect regulation since they do
business with regulated entities, banks and brokers. Moreover,
since 1992, when efforts at hedge fund regulation began, leading
hedge fund managers have learned to play the Washington game and
have effectively avoided closer government scrutiny through adroit
lobbying and heavy campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge fund managers were especially active in 1994, when a
Democrat-controlled House Banking Committee considered federal
hedge fund oversight, and three leading managers, including Julian
Robertson of Tiger Management, contributed $550,000 in soft money
to Republicans. When Republicans took over Congress in 1994, a
``Large Trader Reporting System'' for hedge funds seriously
considered by the Democrats died quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The main regulatory question raised by the Long-Term Capital
episode was why banking regulators never saw early warning flags
that would have indicated banks had extended too much credit to an
already overly indebted fund. Banks lending to Long-Term Capital
are regulated primarily by the Federal Reserve and by the State of
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone was asleep at the switch,'' said Paul Roth, vice
chairman of the American Bar Association's task force on hedge
funds. ``It's not like the banks making these loans don't have
sufficient regulatory oversight. There is sufficient regulation in
place, but it's a question of whether the people were paying
attention to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Ely, head of an Alexandria, Va.-based bank consulting firm,
said the focus of regulatory concern in Long-Term Capital should
have been over threats to the safety and soundness of the banking
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-Term Capital would have never been able to grow and have
the leverage it had, if it had not been lent the money,'' said Ely.
</P>
<P>
   One question securities regulators will be examining is whether
brokerage firms' loans to Long-Term Capital were made through their
broker-dealer operations, which are regulated by the SEC, or by
their corporate holding companies, which are not.
</P>
<P>
   Despite concern about what happened at Long-Term Capital, even
advocates of more scrutiny profess some cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like going back to the savings and loan crisis, which
caused us so much grief,'' said Thomas Petri, R-Wisc., who
advocates higher bank premiums for higher risk activities.
``Anything the government comes up with, you will find some really
smart people to manipulate it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
