<SLUG> BC-SAUDI-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUDI PRINCE MEETS CHIEFS OF BIG OIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A quarter-century after Saudi Arabia nationalized its oil
industry, putting narrow limits on investment by Western oil
companies, the heir to the Saudi throne, Crown Prince Abdullah, has
asked top executives of seven major U.S. oil companies how his
financially pressed country should be developing its vast oil and
natural-gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Saudis are now prepared to shift policy and open
their vast oil reserves and refining industry to investment by U.S.
companies remains unclear, according to several participants in a
private meeting held on Saturday in McLean, Va., at the residence
of the Saudi ambassador to the United States, Prince Bandar bin
Sultan.
</P>
<P>
   But a person who attended the meeting, Nat Kern, president of
Foreign Report, a Washington consulting company to the oil industry
that also publishes a newsletter, said in an interview that there
was an openness by the crown prince and by Saudi Arabia's foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
   He related that they were saying, ``Tell us what things would be
beneficial for us.'' And when the oil executives held a general
discussion of ideas for exploration and production, the Saudis
nodded in agreement. ``There were no taboos,'' he said. ``They were
open-minded. Before, they were closed-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said that both sides realized
they needed each other, more than in the past, and that this would
lead to more cooperation. Richardson added that he would visit
Saudi Arabia in December, the first time a U.S. energy secretary
has been there in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Attending the meeting were top executives of Mobil, Exxon,
Texaco, Chevron, Atlantic Richfield, Conoco and Phillips Petroleum.
The Washington Post reported the meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since nationalization, Saudi Aramco, the state oil company, has
produced and refined most of the oil. Production now amounts to 8
million barrels a day, making Saudi Arabia the world's largest oil
exporter.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil, the biggest U.S. investor in Saudi Arabia, and some other
companies have been allowed to develop petrochemical and lubricant
plants, but Saudi Arabia has kept foreign companies from moving the
vast fields into production and out of basic refining.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Lucio Noto, chairman and chief executive of Mobil,
said in a statement that the meeting was ``about the sharing of
ideas.'' He added that the discussions were not specific on whether
the exploration and production of oil fields or the refining
industry would be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Lower oil prices have severely cut into the revenue of Saudi
Arabia, which has been running huge budget deficits, even though
its proved reserves of 260 billion barrels are the world's largest.
</P>
<P>
   Some neighbors, like Kuwait, have been courting Western oil
companies and attracting big investments. Iran, which is off limits
to U.S. companies, has been seeking to open its industry to
European companies.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Yergin, chairman of Cambridge Energy Associates, a
consulting group based in Boston, said that with lower oil prices
the Saudis could be seeking partners so they would not have to
absorb all the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are benefits in sharing the risk with other companies,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
