<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARGROVE, GOODEN HAVE DIFFERENT TAKES ON EJECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Indians manager Mike Hargrove and starting pitcher
Dwight Gooden had somewhat different takes on the first-inning
debate with plate umpire Joe Brinkman that led to their ejection.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden said he didn't think he deserved his dismissal, nor did
he expect it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think so, especially with the playoffs. They are very
intense,'' Gooden said. ``By no means did I think I was going to
get thrown out, and I didn't even know I had been thrown out until
I got back to the mound and the rest of the umpires told me I had
to leave the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gooden-Brinkman conflict, which led to Hargrove's ejection,
began after Brinkman called three consecutive balls to Boston
leadoff hitter Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I thought the first pitch was a ball and the next
two pitches were strikes,'' he said. ``When it went 3-0, I didn't
say a word. He took off his mask and said something.''
</P>
<P>
   What did he say to get ejected after Brinkman called Boston's
John Valentin safe at home four batters later?
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't really nothing to get kicked out,'' Gooden said.
``Now, if I did say something to offend him at that time, I think
it should have been a warning or something. There have been times
when I had disagreements with umpires and said something a whole
lot worse than that and they just say, `Hey, Doc, knock it off,' or
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hargrove: ``The main reason I came out (to the mound) was
that I felt Doc was a little upset and I wanted to calm him down. I
had other reasons for going out there, but that was the main one.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what Hargrove did to warrant ejection, he said, ``It was
just a difference of opinion. For me, it's one of those things that
happens in the heat of battle where everyone's competitive.'' &QL; 
GAME OF STRATEGY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both teams went to their stoppers in somewhat unusual
circumstances. Boston manager Jimy Williams brought in ace Tom
Gordon with his team trailing by three runs in the eighth inning.
Gordon was wild, and allowed a run that increased the Indians' lead
to 9-5 entering the ninth. Gordon last pitched Sunday, and with an
off day today, needed work.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians called on Mike Jackson in the eighth inning, one
inning earlier than usual. He got the final six outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we not been able to rest Mike Jackson in the last 10 days
of the season, I think (pitching him two innings) would be a major
concern,'' Hargrove said. ``Given the fact that he has been a setup
man who has gone two innings at a time until this year, and given
the fact that we have a day off (today), it's not a major concern
right now.'' &QL; 
WAKEFIELD STRUGGLES &QL; 
Anticipating his start against Cleveland yesterday, Red Sox
knuckleballer Tim Wakefield said the key to his success would be to
``throw strikes, get as much movement as possible and see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield got movement but didn't throw strikes and what
happened was that he was out of the game by the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield allowed five runs on three hits with two walks. He
threw 42 pitches, half of them balls. &QL; 
BRIEFLY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indians hitters laced six doubles in the game, setting a
Division Series single-game record.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox catcher Jason Varitek set a dubious record. His two
passed balls equaled a Division Series mark for a single game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
