<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURPLUS-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT ENDING FISCAL YEAR WITH RECORD SURPLUS, CLINTON
ANNOUNCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for new 14-17th grafs) (See also SURPLUS-IMPACT, moved in `f' category) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton announced on Wednesday that the
government was ending the fiscal year with a budget surplus of $70
billion, the first since 1969 and the largest on record. ``It is a
landmark achievement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight at midnight,'' the president declared in a ceremony
here as the clock ticked toward the close of the 1998 fiscal year,
``America puts an end to three decades of deficits and launches a
new era of balanced budgets and surpluses.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president's celebration of the surplus did little to
mask an untidy budget process that is unfolding on Capitol Hill and
must be resolved in the next nine days, before Congress adjourns
for the fall election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus is contributing to the untidiness: both the
administration and congressional Republicans have found the
emergence of an extra pot of $70 billion or so _ the exact size
will not be known until after a couple of weeks, when the
government makes a final accounting _ too tempting to ignore,
especially in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want to use part of the surplus to finance a tax
cut, while the administration wants it to bolster Social Security
and pay for other measures.
</P>
<P>
   Although a new fiscal year begins on Thursday, Congress has
finished work on only 2 of the 13 spending bills needed to keep the
government running beyond Monday night. As a result, Congress and
the president have agreed to a stopgap measure to finance most of
the government through Oct. 9, a device used in 8 of the last 10
years to buy the two sides more time to resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasm over the surplus has been tempered by the
international markets' growing turmoil, which has made it unclear
how long the United States can expect to sustain its own economic
growth. Indeed, whether the annual surpluses projected for the next
decade will materialize if the nation slips into recession is just
one of the questions being debated by wary economists.
</P>
<P>
   The availability of a surplus, anticipated for months, once
seemed to offer the nation the opportunity for a philosophical
debate over its direction in a new era of plenty. But that debate
has been cut short in the last several weeks by the drive on
Capitol Hill to impeach the president over the Lewinsky scandal,
and the budget process, surplus and all, has been all but lost in
the shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Congress, reflecting a rift within the Republican
Party between deficit hawks and supply side tax-cutters has not
even passed a budget resolution this year. Instead it is using last
year's agreement, which does not project a surplus until 2002, as
its spending guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are starting a new fiscal year, and the road map is
still in dispute,'' Rep. David Minge, D-Minn., who is a member of
the House Budget Committee, said incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   In place of a broader debate in the era of surplus is the
horse-trading and the philosophical standoffs over abortion, issues
that have characterized the endgame of every recent budget season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alliance at the end of the session is there is no
alliance, except to spend money and get out of town,'' said Rep.
Tom Coburn, a conservative Republican from Oklahoma who wants
Congress and the president to stay within the spending limits to
which both agreed in the budget-balancing agreement last year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said for months and reiterated on Wednesday that he
wants to save the surplus to bolster the Social Security system for
retiring baby boomers. At the same time, the administration is
seeking to spend an extra $17 billion for ``emergencies'' that it
did not calculate in its budget. These emergencies include the
peacekeeping troops in Bosnia, fixing the Year 2000 computer bug,
improving security at U.S. embassies around the world and providing
disaster relief to American farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say the administration is dipping into the surplus
to pay for these efforts. But Linda Ricci, a spokeswoman for the
White House Office of Management and Budget, said that under budget
rules, a lifting of spending limits to pay for emergencies was
permitted and that the surplus was not being tapped. Republicans
say this is a distinction without a real difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you spend the money, you reduce the surplus,'' said Sen.
Pete Domenici, R-N.M., who heads the Senate Budget Committee and
has strongly opposed the effort by House Republicans to spend part
of the surplus on a tax cut. The House passed an $80 billion tax
cut last week, but the Senate appears ready to kill it; if not, the
president has promised a veto.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the projected surplus has deepened the rift within
the Republican Party, separating further the deficit hawks devoted
to staying within spending limits from the supply-side tax-cutters
who say lower taxes would spur growth.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Republicans appear prepared to go along with most
of the president's requests and spend at least $13 billion on the
emergency programs. This despite some grousing over the apparently
elastic definition of ``emergency,'' which provides for events like
the year 2000 computer glitch and the Bosnia mission, both of them
issues for some time.
</P>
<P>
   The president on Wednesday soft-pedaled his recent criticisms of
Congress, but did urge Republicans not to ``squander'' the surplus
before Social Security is secured.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we squander this surplus and start spending a little here,
a little there, a little yonder on the tax cuts, just because we
are a few weeks before an election, before we take care of this,
what are we going to do when times get tough?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   With his ceremony on Wednesday, the president was able to appear
as if he were responsible for the surplus, and he extended credit
to Democratic members of Congress who voted for his tax increase in
1993. This annoyed Republicans, who resent Clinton's ability to
take credit for events for which they feel responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton's trying to make everybody assume that just
because he raised taxes in 1993, he balanced the budget,'' said
Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla. Reflecting a long-standing gripe that
Republicans have with Clinton, he added: ``The president today even
took credit for welfare reform, which he vetoed twice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
