<HEADER>
A3023 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAMU-KILLINGER-SPI &LR;      09-30 1766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAMU-KILLINGER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WASHINGTON MUTUAL'S KILLINGER, NOW COMES THE HARD PART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In his eight years as chief executive of Washington
Mutual, Kerry Killinger has transformed the company from a small
Seattle-area savings bank and home lender to a multi-billion,
coast-to-coast financial giant.
</P>
<P>
   He did it while maintaining the sort of understated approach
that leads one area banker to describe him as ``a really nice
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Accomplishing all that may have been the easy part.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Washington Mutual Inc. officially takes control of its
latest acquisition, H.F. Ahmanson &AMP; Co., a deal that boosts its
assets to $150 billion, gives it more than 1,000 branches from the
Pacific Northwest to California and Florida, and makes it the
eighth-largest bank in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Killinger's abilities as an administrator and leader will be
tested as never before. Washington Mutual is no longer a company
whose most distant branches could be driven to in a day.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the size of Washington Mutual that's
different. So is the level of attention Killinger, 49, now a
national figure in the banking industry, and Washington Mutual
receive. There are more customers, more shareholders, more
community groups, more media, all clamoring for a piece of
Killinger's time and scrutinizing ever more intently what the
company does.
</P>
<P>
   Will Kerry Killinger be able to continue Washington Mutual's
success and maintain the executive and personal style that achieved
that?
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder if he'll have to adjust his style,'' says R. Jay
Tejera, a banking industry analyst with Dain Rauscher Wessels in
Minneapolis who has followed Washigton Mutual and Killinger for
years. ``One of the things he does is deliver a high-touch style of
management ... The demands are a lot tougher ... Expectations are
very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Killinger are betting he won't change. Says John
Ellis, president of the Seattle Mariners, former chief executive of
Puget Power and a Washington Mutual board member for more than 20
years, ``So far he has demonstrated this remarkable ability to be
used more and more and still keep the bank on course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all get forced to make adjustments, but I don't think you
fundamentally change who you are,'' says Craig Tall, Washington
Mutual executive vice president. ``I don't think Kerry's going to
change who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Killinger acknowledges that times have changed since he made it
a point to visit every branch every six months. But his management
style is not materially different, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to have an approach that is hands-on, to be a company
of doers,'' he says. ``Naturally it's a challenge to adapt to the
size and requirements'' of a larger company and that may mean
substituing regional meetings with groups of employees for those
individual visits.
</P>
<P>
   But the intent is still the same, he adds. ``We still try to
reach the people.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a lot to suggest, when Killinger was named chief
executive in 1990 and chairman in 1991, that Washington Mutual
would approach the end of the decade as the nation's biggest
thrift. There was some question whether it would make it very far
into the 1990s as an independent company.
</P>
<P>
   When Killinger took over, Washington Mutual had limited
territory; competitors, meanwhile, were bulking up by merger.
Earnings were lackluster. ``We were not a very efficient company,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   There were also, as Ellis recalls, some questions about whether
someone with a background in investment research like Killinger was
the right person to get Washington Mutual out of its fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into the bank when he did was fortuitous both ways,''
Ellis says. ``We did not need an old-time conventional banker ....
Small banks would not be able to survive in the new environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Killinger started out by asking the board ``to endorse a
commitment to being an independent company, subject to earning that
right to remain an independent.'' Earning that right meant
improving Washington Mutual's financial performance.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, Killinger laid out this plan: emphasize Washington
Mutual as a consumer bank; shed underperforming businesses that
weren't related to that core consumer banking business; improve
operating efficiency; and diversify geographically.
</P>
<P>
   Then Killinger and his management team went out and did it.
Eventually Washington Mutual expanded as far as Utah. Then came
California: Washington Mutual bought American Savings, wrested
Great Western away from a hostile takeover bid by Ahmanson, at one
time the nation's biggest thrift, then eventually got Ahmanson
itself.
</P>
<P>
   To build its consumer banking business, Washington Mutual
launched a free-checking campaign. That was an effective move for
several reasons; checking accounts are a low-cost source of funds
with which to make loans, and they're considered the core account
with which to attract and retain customers.
</P>
<P>
   The plan worked both because of its execution and some
fortuitous developments over which Washington Mutual had no
control. The emphasis on consumer banking came as many customers
were feeling whiplashed by mergers among commercial banks. The
stock market's strong performance in the 1990s allowed Washington
Mutual to use its increasingly valuable shares to do deals.
Favorable interest rates and economic climate also helped.
</P>
<P>
   But companies can't expect strokes of good fortune to do all the
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do is take whatever external environment is given to
us and work with that,'' Killinger says. When California's economy
was in the tank, Washington Mutual deliberately stayed out of that
market and concentrated on the more vibrant Pacific Northwest. When
California improved, Washington Mutual made its move.
</P>
<P>
   Says James Grabicki, a Port Townsend banking consultant who once
ran a thrift that Washington Mutual bought, ``His timing has been
impeccable.''
</P>
<P>
   Killinger has long been a man on the move. He finished his
bachelor's and master's degrees at the University of Iowa in a
combined four and a half years. ``I had one ambition, to get
through as quick as possible and get out in the real world,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Killinger's time at Spokane-based investment firm Murphey Favre
proved valuable for two reasons: it gave him insights into Wall
Street he used later when he was trying to convince the investment
community that his planned acquisitions would work. It also got him
into Washington Mutual, when it bought Murphey Favre in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Killinger remark on his direct, unaffected manner
_ ``What you see is what you get,'' says his wife of nearly 30
years, Debbie. He exudes energy. Says one Washington Mutual
officer, it's a ``real positive energy, not the kind that wears you
down.''
</P>
<P>
   He lacks the self-aggrandizing bombast of some chief executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the years I've known Kerry, I've never known him to raise
his voice,'' says Tom Cleveland, formerly head of Enterprise Bank
(now part of Washington Mutual) and now head of Access Capital in
Bellevue. ``He's very aggressive, make no mistake about it.'' But
what he has accomplished has been done ``without a lot of
chest-pounding.''
</P>
<P>
   That, along with the allure of working for a growing and
successful company, helps account for the low level of turnover in
Washington Mutual's executive team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's created an unusually high level of teamwork for a company
that size,'' says Tejera, the banking industry analyst. ``He has
pulled a lot of these people along with him. It's a very young
group. He's given these people a lot of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Killinger's success isn't due just to those at Washington
Mutual. At every annual meeting Killinger concludes the
introduction of directors and officers by presenting his wife,
whose music teacher from the fourth to the 12th grade was
Killinger's father. ``She has always been a good balanced
adviser,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the job, Killinger channels his energy into a manic
style of landscaping (``If you have him prune, you will not have to
do it for a long time,'' Debbie says) and a seemingly endless
series of remodeling projects at his Bellevue home. As a young
couple in Spokane the Killingers bought a series of run-down
houses, fixed them up and sold them. Their two sons were paid 25
and 10 cents an hour for pitching in, and got ``profit sharing''
when properties sold.
</P>
<P>
   The days of remodeling houses as a side business are over,
although Debbie Killinger says Washington Mutual managers at one
point asked her to suggest another home improvement project to her
husband ``because we need a break.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to build things and tinker with things,'' she adds.
``He likes to build things in business.''
</P>
<P>
   What Killinger and his fellow executives have built, with the
latest deal, is a huge opportunity. California is already the
biggest market for Washington Mutual, and Ahmanson merely bolsters
its presence there. Adding Ahmanson also adds heft in Florida, and
introduces Washington Mutual to a new state _ Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual is moving into California at an opportune
time, says Alan Fisher, executive director of the California
Reinvestment Committee, when two of its biggest competitors there,
BankAmerica and Wells Fargo, are going through mergers.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the opportunities made possible by expansion are
greater, so are the potential pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   As others have proven to Washington Mutual's benefit, mergers
are minefields of hazards that, negotiated badly, can blow up with
fouled customer accounts and defections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very comfortable, in the sense we've done this over and
over again,'' says chief financial officer William Longbrake. In
fact, Washington Mutual has executed nearly two dozen mergers and
acquisitions in its growth spurt, including two huge ones (American
and Great Western) in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market will be watching closely for problems. After
hitting a 52-week high of $51.67 a share in May, the company's
stock tumbled to $30 in August (it closed Wednesday at $33.75).
Some of that is due to the market swoon; some is the work of a
squeezing of interest rate spreads. But it's also due to concern
over whether Killinger can deliver on the cost savings he has
promised that will result from the Ahmanson deal.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever lies ahead, Killinger is likely to study the landscape
and move accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put yourself in position,'' he says, ``and good things can
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
