<HEADER>
A3024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-COX     09-30 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parties argue about scope of impeachment inquiry
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Republicans push for a wide-ranging impeachment
inquiry of President Clinton, the senior Democrat on the House
Judiciary Committee said Wednesday he would support the same rules
as governed the Watergate probe, but not its open-ended scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased to report that we have been given a Watergatelike
set of rules,'' said Michigan Democrat John Conyers, the ranking
member and the only lawmaker remaining on the panel from the 1974
impeachment inquiry of former President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   But Conyers told reporters that the inquiry into whether Clinton
committed perjury, obstructed justice and abused his presidential
powers to conceal an adulterous relationship with Monica Lewinsky,
a former White House intern, did not warrant the broad mandate
given to investigators on the Watergate panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that this review should be open-ended like
Watergate, as the speaker continues to insist, is preposterous,''
said Conyers, referring to House Speaker Newt Gingrich, (R-Ga.).
``Watergate involved a wholesale corruption of government which
extended through the FBI, the CIA and other federal agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   But pushing aside the Democratic demands to limit the
investigation's scope, the Republican-led committee unveiled a
draft resolution calling for Watergate-style proceedings. The
committee is planning to debate the resolution Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed outline would give committee investigators broad
authority to subpoena witnesses and evidence without a committee
vote if Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) and Conyers agreed. It also
would let the president and his lawyers attend all executive
sessions and hearings, cross-examine witnesses, object to evidence,
suggest consideration of additional evidence, and respond to all
evidence presented.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent closed-door meeting with Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt (D-Mo.) about the status of the impeachment process,
Gingrich was reported to have said that the impeachment inquiry
should include allegations that may stem from other ongoing
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich also has said the investigation's scope is in the hands
of one person: Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde told reporters the Judiciary panel would not be limited to
the material sent to Congress from independent counsel Kenneth
Starr. ``No, we're not restricted,'' Hyde said. ``I think it is our
duty to look at all of the evidence, including exculpatory.''
Gephardt and Conyers recently have asserted that any impeachment
inquiry should have a time limit, a restriction on the focus of the
inquiry and a definition of what is impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Conyers supported an unlimited timetable and an
open-ended inquiry for the Watergate investigation.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry noted Wednesday that another
member of Congress during the Watergate era, Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott (R-Miss.), seems to see things differently this time
around.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, a congressman in 1974, voted against the Nixon articles of
impeachment, but now says that even ``bad conduct'' could warrant
removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1974, Trent Lott signed a minority report for the committee
that was quite clear,'' McCurry said. ``It was the kinds of crimes
that subvert the Constitution and damage the country. And the
question before the House is: Does the president's conduct in this
instance rise to that level? And we argue it does not.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry went on to attack the way Republicans have handled the
investigation and committee proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lack of focus, a lack of discipline,'' he said.
``They're kind of running around _ they want to bring back Rep. Dan
Burton and Sen. Al D'Amato _ for a reprise of their greatest
hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton (R-Ind.) ran the House campaign fund-raising probe and
D'Amato (R-N.Y.) ran the Senate inquiry into Clinton's Whitewater
land dealings.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations against Clinton stem from a more than four-year
investigation that has cost more than $40 million, according to
General Accounting Office audits released Wednesday. First assigned
to investigate the president's involvement in Whitewater, Starr has
spent nearly $33.5 million since taking over the probe in 1994.
Starr's predecessor, Robert Fiske, spent $6 million, making the
cost of investigating the Clinton administration almost $40 million
_ a number that will climb significantly when updated with the past
six months' activity.
</P>
<P>
   The most costly independent counsel probe was Lawrence Walsh's
$48.5 million, six-year investigation of the Reagan
administration's Iran-Contra dealings.
</P>
<P>
   As both parties prepare for Monday's deliberations on the call
for a formal impeachment inquiry, committee staffers are combing
through the documents from Starr's office to back up their
presentation of facts. About 5,000 of the remaining 50,000 pages
are expected to be released to the public in a two-volume set as
early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The final document dump is expected to include transcripts of
secret grand jury testimony from high-level Clinton aides and taped
conversations between the former intern and Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, White House adviser Sidney Blumenthal says he
raised a question about Lewinsky with Hillary Rodham Clinton and
was told not to worry, that the president was ``ministering to a
troubled young person.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Clinton adviser Dick Morris' testimony says the White
House has a ``secret police'' unit of aides who would try to
intimidate women who say they were involved with Clinton. But
Morris said Tuesday he relied on published accounts and affidavits
and had no firsthand knowledge of such an operation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
