<SLUG> BC-IRAN-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ STIFFENS DEFIANCE OF U.N. DEMANDS FOR ARMS CHECKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Iraq on Wednesday hardened its defiance of
Security Council demands that it allow spot arms inspections to
resume. At the same time it publicly staked its hopes of ending
sanctions by calling on Secretary-General Kofi Annan to take over a
major review of Baghdad's stalemated relations with the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes Iraqi officials are working diplomatic circles
to try to reopen Security Council splits as Baghdad moves into a
critical period in its relations with the organization, which is
now united in demanding Iraqi cooperation before any concessions
are made.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the effects of the embargo on Iraq ``tantamount to
internationally proscribed acts of genocide,'' Foreign Minister
Mohammed Said al-Sahaf of Iraq told the General Assembly in a
speech that an across-the-board look at more than eight years of
sanctions could break the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   But he appeared to assume that Iraq could expect the broad
review _ different from periodic reviews of sanctions, which have
now been suspended _ before making concessions.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 5, Iraq stopped on-site inspections by arms monitors,
prompting the Security Council resolution that freezes the regular
60-day reviews but leaving open the chance to look at the bigger
picture if _ and after _ Iraq falls back into line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason for Iraq to believe that it can renegotiate
the resolution and thereby change the sequence of events,'' said
Peter Burleigh, the acting U.S. representative. In an interview
Wednesday, Burleigh said he knew of no one who was prepared to make
that case for Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is the only permanent Security Council member
to refuse to meet this week with Tariq Aziz, Iraq's deputy prime
minister and a liaison aide with the United Nations on sanctions.
Aziz has met envoys from Britain, China, France and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The British, who have been the strongest supporters of the
United States on Iraq, take over the rotating presidency of the
Council on Thursday for the month of October.
</P>
<P>
   Next week the U.N. Special Commission, or UNSCOM, and the
International Atomic Energy Agency are due to present major reports
to the Council amid reports that Iraq has continued to try to
assemble parts for a range of prohibited weapons through purchases
abroad or in cooperative efforts with friendly nations like Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   At the independent Nuclear Control Institute in Washington, the
research director, Steven Dolley, said Wednesday that in nuclear
weapons Iraq might be ``just a Russian smuggler away'' from being
able to build a bomb with illegally obtained material. Large
stockpiles of natural uranium also remain in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Large questions also surround chemical and biological weapons
programs, UNSCOM arms inspectors say.
</P>
<P>
   Some Security Council members say that all questions about
possible weapons can never be answered and that the Council should
begin closing files wherever possible as an incentive to Iraq. The
diplomats say it was a mistake not to have closed the nuclear file
in July, when it came up for review.
</P>
<P>
   Restitution is being paid to victims of the Iraqi campaign
against Kuwait through the U.N. Compensation Commission in Geneva,
which has been given one-third of all money earned on limited Iraqi
oil sales through the program that is intended to counter the
problems that Iraqis face because of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday in Geneva, where the Compensation Commission once
languished for lack of money before the ``oil for food'' program,
the panel announced Wednesday that it had paid $1.9 billion in
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq and some U.N. officials have been critical of the Security
Council decision to take the first 30 percent off oil sales for
compensation rather than allowing it all to go to food, medicine
and other urgent civilian needs.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday in Baghdad, Denis Halliday, who resigned as head of
the program in Iraq and is leaving the United Nations, called the
results of the oil sales ``a shot of oxygen for Iraq and the people
of Iraq.'' He said that the country had received more than 7
million tons of food since March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Halliday, who is to meet 40 members of Congress next week to
assess the effects of the sanctions, said he was uncomfortable with
what he called the incompatibility of tough sanctions' inflicting
suffering on one hand and relief aid on the other, both coming from
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think nobody anticipated the duration of these sanctions,''
he said, ``and therefore the human cost that they represent in
terms of child mortality, infant mortality, chronic and acute
malnutrition, and the collapse of many of the most positive aspects
of Iraq's society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
