<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFITABLE DAY FOR MABEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ John and Betty Mabee's Advancing Star lost a
photo finish to Dance Parade in the Autumn Days Handicap on opening
day of the Oak Tree season at Santa Anita, costing the Mabees
$40,000 in purse money.
</P>
<P>
   Do not feel sorry for them.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, the San Diego couple sold Worldly Manner, the
nation's top-ranked 2-year-old, for a price confirmed to be in the
neighborhood of $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``A `Godfather' offer,'' said Rick Taylor, racing manager for
the Mabees' Golden Eagle Farm. In other words, an offer they
couldn't refuse, even though Worldly Manner is a leading prospect
for next May's Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, despite the gaudy price, probably didn't set any kind
of thoroughbred record. But it's distinctive in another way: The
Mabees and Taylor don't expect to know until today who the buyer
is, because he or she wanted to remain anonymous for some reason.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said Bob Baffert, who trained Worldly Manner to win three
of four races, most recently the Sept. 9 Del Mar Futurity, thinks
the son of Riverman is going to Kiaran McLaughlin's barn in
Kentucky. McLaughlin trains for Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid al
Maktoum and other Dubai-based owners, so it's a good bet there's an
Arab connection here.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Worldly Manner won't run here in the Oct. 11
Norfolk Stakes, the local prep for the Nov. 7 Breeders' Cup
Juvenile at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the offer came through a Kentucky bloodstock agent
in September, and the Mabees waited until after the Del Mar
Futurity to set a price, which, to their surprise, was accepted.
The money was wired to the Mabees Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said at Santa Anita that one reason the Mabees were
willing to part with Worldly Manner is that they have ``a very deep
bench this year.'' He said they're excited about colts by Seeking
the Gold, General Meeting and Avenue of Flags, all scheduled to
make their debuts in November and December, as well as Del Mar
Futurity runner-up Daring General.
</P>
<P>
   Also, even if Worldly Manner races for another owner, the Mabees
would share in his success because of the increased value of his
dam, Lady Pastor, whom they own, and her future offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the $5 million can't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   John Mabee, 77, made a fortune with the Big Bear grocery chain
and founded Golden Eagle Insurance in 1984. But last year, he was
forced to sell the insurance company following a battle with
California regulators over business practices.
</P>
<P>
   The Mabees' best-known racehorse was Best Pal, the 1991 Kentucky
Derby runner-up whose $5.6 million in earnings set a record for a
California-bred.
</P>
<P>
   All of which puts the $100,000 Autumn Days in perspective,
doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Advancing Star and jockey Chris McCarron led in midstretch but
lost by a head to Dance Parade ($7) and Kent Desormeaux in the
6{-furlong turf race. Dance Parade earned $60,000 for Prince Fahd
Salman.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 14,641 attended the first of 32 days of racing at the
30th Oak Tree meet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
