<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3034 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROGUE-TRADER-BOS &LR;      09-30 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROGUE-TRADER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGUE TRADER COSTS RHUMBLINE, AT&AMP;T PENSION FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bing Sung is a numbers man, a Harvard Ph.D in
statistics, one among an arcane breed of securities traders whose
investment theories have been compared to the complicated
mathematics of nuclear physics.
</P>
<P>
   For almost four years, few could have been more pleased with his
methods than RhumbLine Advisors, the Boston money management firm
that hired him, and AT&AMP;T Corp.'s pension fund, one of his largest
clients.
</P>
<P>
   But in a complaint, the Securities and Exchange Commission
alleged Wednesday that the 51-year-old Sung's claims about the
fund's performance were a fiction and that he had actually lost
$150 million through unauthorized trading. After suffering setbacks
during 1995's rollercoaster market, Sung tried to regain ground for
more than a year, making improper trades and misrepresenting them
to AT&AMP;T, the SEC alleged. The same improper trading cost the
Massachusetts state employees pension fund, another RumbLine
client, $12 million, according to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``His theory crumbled and then he got over his head,'' said
Grant Ward, assistant district administrator in the SEC's Boston
office.
</P>
<P>
   Sung, who faces a possible ban from the securities industry, did
not return calls to his home in Andover.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said its pension funds, which are managed by more than 50
outside firms and held a total of $47 billion at the time of of
Sung's trades, were able to absorb the loss. In fact, the company's
pension trust had a $1.6 billion net gain in the period that the
losses occurred.
</P>
<P>
   But officials warned that Sung's case illustrates an alarming
problem in the securities industry: Rogue traders can often operate
undetected for years and, left unsupervised, can cause serious
financial harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This went on for almost two years,'' said the SEC's Ward.
``And nobody was there looking over his shoulder. AT&AMP;T could handle
the losses, but maybe in another situation the outcome is worse.
What we're saying is that this stuff goes on despite the best
intentions of the firm and the clients, and the exposure is very
large.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides filing the complaint against Sung, the SEC has settled
charges against firm and its chief executive, John D. Nelson, for
failing to adequately supervise Sung. Under the settlement, the
firm has agreed to pay the SEC $50,000, and Nelson $10,000, the SEC
said. Nelson neither admitted nor denied responsibility for Sung's
trades in agreeing to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to hide anything,'' Nelson told Bloomberg
News. When the losses were discovered, he said, ``I went to the
clients and I went to the SEC.''
</P>
<P>
   Sung, a native of China, approached RhumbLine in 1991, according
to the SEC's complaint, filed in US District Court in Boston. He
came with an impressive background. He was a former partner of
Harvard Management Co., which manages Harvard University's
endowment, and developed a quantitative trading strategy that
involved writing options on stock indexes, such as Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed that RhumbLine, one of only 50 minority- or
wommen-owned money mangement firms in the country, start an
investment program using the strategy. Nelson hired Sung as his
chief invesment oficer. In return for future equity in the firm and
salary, Sung agreed to work for a year without pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sung brought the brains, and Nelson brought the clients,''
including the AT&AMP;T pension fund, the SEC's Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, all seemed to go well. Sung's strategy involved
writing options _ essentially bets that certain market indexes
would rise or fall. To limit the risk of each bet, AT&AMP;T required
Sung to buy an offsetting option, which hedged against big losses
but also lowered overall returns.
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy, backed by complicated mathematical formulas,
worked only as long as US markets remained stable. In 1995, the
markets swung wildly, and the AT&AMP;T account began to lose money.
What happened next, according to the SEC complaint, is a tale of
what can go wrong when a trader is given free rein.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than telling AT&AMP;T what was happening, Sung secretly
changed the nature and size of his bets beginning in January 1995,
the SEC alleged. He stopped buying the offsetting options AT&AMP;T
required. By February, his losses totaled more than $6 million,
exceeding AT&AMP;T's cap on losses by $38,600.
</P>
<P>
   When AT&AMP;T learned of the loss, Sung's client rebuked him and
said they'd take away the account if he didn't ``trade in a more
disciplined manner,'' the SEC complaint alleged.
</P>
<P>
   But in May 1995, Sung again secretly embarked on trades that
violated AT&AMP;T's restrictions, writing huge options on technology
indexes, including the Nasdaq 100 and the Philidelphia
Semiconductor Index, the complaint alleged.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to get around regulations limiting such trades,
Sung allegedly falsified an application to the Chicago Board
Options Exchange, saying he managed $9 billion in AT&AMP;T assets. Sung
was then able to fill the AT&AMP;T account with securities that at one
point represented two-thirds of the entire market for options on
the Nasdaq 100, the SEC said.
</P>
<P>
   Sung's scheme seemed to work, depsite his ``excessively risky
trading,'' the complaint said. ``By the June 1996 quarterly
closing, the AT&AMP;T account had made up its earlier losses and had
cumulative realized profits for the year of nearly $3 million.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the third quarter of 1996, Sung increased the ``magnitude
and and riskiness of his unauthorized trading,'' the SEC said. He
wrote ``enormous unhedged'' options against hundreds of millions of
dollars in underlying assets. They would have been profitable if
the market had continued to decline. But it didn't. Sung lost
another $37 million.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of disclosing the improper trades, Sung ``repeatedly
doubled his bets that the market would decline,'' the SEC said.
AT&AMP;T's entire $150 million loss came in that quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 19, 1996, Nelson discovered the extent of the losses
and informed AT&AMP;T, which closed the account the next day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
