<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON MAY START AGAIN SATURDAY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Randy Johnson has a four-game losing streak in the
playoffs after being outpitched by Kevin Brown on Tuesday in
Houston's 2-1 loss to San Diego. But Johnson may get a chance to
break that streak _ and possibly face Brown again _ sooner than
anybody thought.
</P>
<P>
   With his team in an early hole, losing at home and trailing by
1-0 in the three-of-five-game division series, Houston Manager
Larry Dierker Wednesday raised the possibility of starting Johnson
in Game 3 in San Diego on Saturday. Dierker said he had heard the
Padres might start Brown on Saturday on three days' rest, something
San Diego Manager Bruce Bochy and the Padres' pitching coach, Dave
Stewart, confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Brown, who struck out 16 Astros in Game 1, does not
pitch on Saturday, Johnson might.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might do it if it gets down two games to none,'' Dierker
said. ``It could get to the point that even if it isn't the best
idea, you're going to get killed in the media if you don't do it.''
Shane Reynolds of the Astros will face Andy Ashby of the Padres in
Game 2 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to think about it very much until after
tomorrow's game,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, Johnson allowed two runs and nine hits, with a walk
and nine strikeouts, in eight innings. He did not pitch on three
days' rest this season, but Dierker said, ``When he first came
over, he told me he could do it.'' In 1995, Johnson won the
deciding fifth game of the Seattle Mariners' dramatic division
series victory over the Yankees, pitching three innings of relief
on one day's rest after he had pitched seven strong innings to win
Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Houston's Mike Hampton (11-7, 3.36 earned run
average) and San Diego's Sterling Hitchcock (9-7, 3.93 ERA), both
left-handers, are scheduled to start on Saturday. But the Astros,
who have never reached the World Series, acquired Johnson at the
trading deadline to get them there. ``We're not going to get to the
World Series without him winning a few games,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Brown can pitch on short rest. He
started Game 1 on three days' rest and turned in one of the most
dominating performances in playoff history, striking out more
batters (16) in a post-season game than anyone but Bob Gibson of
the St. Louis Cardinals, who had 17 strikeouts in Game 1 of the
1968 World Series against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   And on Aug. 20, in his first start on three days' rest since
1994, Brown pitched six and a third scoreless innings in a victory
over Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, that's an option,'' Bochy said. ``It's a possibility.
We'll see how he's feeling on Friday. It's something we talked
about earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said, ``I'll do whatever they want me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Much hinges on what happens here Thursday, when the right-hander
Ashby (17-9, 3.34 ERA) faces the right-hander Reynolds (19-8, 3.51
ERA). ``It's not a must-win situation for us,'' Dierker said. ``But
it's close.''
</P>
<P>
   A Houston victory, on the other hand, may increase the chances
of Brown's starting Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not even looking that far ahead,'' Stewart said. ``But
if we leave here with a split, I don't know what they're going to
do with Randy, but with Kevin on the mound, we have a chance to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who was 10-4 as a starter in post-season and World
Series games, often pitched on three days' rest himself during the
post-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's uncommon for today's pitchers to go on three days' rest,
but it was not uncommon in the 1980s and early '90s,'' he said. ``I
preferred pitching every fourth day, and Kevin is really similar to
that. He'd pitch every third day if I allowed him to. He's blessed.
He's got a rubber arm.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
