<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW PLUNGES 237.90; LONG BOND YIELDS 4.97 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Investors turned from stocks and into bonds, pushing long-term
Government yields below 5 percent for the first time in more than
30 years, reflecting worries about the economic crisis abroad and
financial problems at home. The Dow Jones industrial average
plunged 237.90 points, or 2.9 percent, to 7,842.62, but prices of
Treasury securities rose, pushing the yield on the benchmark
30-year bond down to 4.97 percent.
</P>
<P>
   OUTFLOWS AT EQUITY MUTUAL FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Investors made net withdrawals of $11.2 billion from equity
mutual funds in August, the biggest outflow on record and the first
month in eight years that more money flowed out of stock funds than
went in. Bond and money market funds posted net gains.
</P>
<P>
   IMF SEES CONTRACTION IN RUSSIA
</P>
<P>
   The Russian economy will contract by 6 percent this year and
next, and Japan will sink into its deepest recession since the end
of World War II, the I.M.F. predicted in an unusually pessimistic
report.
</P>
<P>
   BANKERS TRUST IN HEDGE FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust disclosed that it had about $1 billion in exposure
to hedge funds, but added that about 99 percent of that exposure
was collateralized with cash or Treasury bills. Nevertheless, its
stock, closing at $59, was down about 3 percent for the day and was
well below its 52-week high of $136.4375, which was reached in
April.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge funds' total assets under management have increased
roughly sixfold since 1990 to some $300 billion at the end of 1997,
Cerulli Associates of Boston estimates.
</P>
<P>
   BIG BANKS CUT PRIME RATE
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan, Citicorp, Nationsbank and some other big banks
lowered their prime rates by a quarter-point, to 8.25 percent, a
day after the Federal Reserve cut its target rate for overnight
loans between banks.
</P>
<P>
   LIMITS FAVORED ON OPTION PLANS
</P>
<P>
   A New York Stock Exchange task force will recommend tightening
loopholes in a recent controversial ruling on plans to issue stock
options without shareholder approval.
</P>
<P>
   HOME SALES FELL 4.4 PERCENT IN AUGUST
</P>
<P>
   Sales of new single-family homes fell 4.4 percent in August.
Separately, the Conference Board said the index of leading economic
indicators was unchanged in August.
</P>
<P>
   SAUDI PRINCE CONSULTS U.S. OILMEN
</P>
<P>
   A quarter century after Saudi Arabia nationalized its oil
industry, limiting Western investment, Crown Prince Abdullah ibn
Abdulaziz, left, has opened discussions about development of his
country's vast oil and gas reserves with top executives of seven
major American oil companies. With oil prices falling, the Saudi
budget is in deficit.
</P>
<P>
   SONY AND TOYOTA PLAN DATA SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Sony and Toyota are teaming up with a relative unknown, Internet
Initiatives Japan, to develop a data transmission service for
Japanese business in direct competition with Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone.
</P>
<P>
   COMPLAINTS OVER FOREIGN STEEL
</P>
<P>
   Seeking Federal relief, a coalition of 12 American steel
companies and two unions accused Japan, Russia and Brazil of
selling steel in the United States at unfairly low prices and
imperiling the domestic industry.
</P>
<P>
   A CRISIS FOR NORTHWESTERN FARMERS
</P>
<P>
   Huge piles of golden grain rise like sand dunes along the banks
of the Columbia and Snake Rivers. Normally 90 percent of the crop
from the Pacific Northwest goes to Asia. Now, because of the
economic crisis, Northwestern farmers are unable to sell their
grain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
