A3045 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      09-30 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL SEEN SET TO DROP STARR COUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee is poised to reject
several of the independent counsel's 11 allegations that President
Clinton committed acts warranting impeachment, according to
committee members in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Although the committee plans vigorously to pursue several
perjury and obstruction-of-justice charges lodged by independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr, the lawmakers said recently that Starr
has failed to produce evidence to support a number of his other
allegations, including the charge that Clinton abused the power of
his office.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is expected to vote early next week to
recommend a full-scale impeachment inquiry, and the House is
expected to approve the recommendation quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation, the Judiciary Committee chairman,
Representative Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, Wednesday proposed broad,
Watergate-style plans for the inquiry, rebuffing requests by
Democratic members to limit the scope of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the focus of the inquiry could quickly narrow, according to
Judiciary Committee members, because Starr appears to have
overreached in claiming he had ``substantial and credible''
evidence to support at least two of his five allegations that
Clinton attempted to obstruct justice and his single charge that
the president abused the power of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many committee members said they expect the impeachment
inquiry to be pared to the core question of whether Clinton
committed perjury by lying to a federal grand jury. ``That's what I
want to focus on,'' said Representative Lindsey O. Graham, a South
Carolina Republican.
</P>
<P>
   A small number of lawmakers on the 37-member committee, such as
Representative Bob Barr, a Georgia Republican, want to dissect
every element of each allegation Starr has leveled against Clinton.
Barr is among more than 50 House members who have called for
Clinton to resign, and he was one of the first lawmakers to urge
Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, a few of the 16 Democrats on the Judiciary
Committee have said they believe none of Starr's charges against
Clinton warrant impeachment, generally because the allegations stem
from Clinton's consensual sex with Monica S. Lewinsky and what they
describe as his effort to conceal an adulterous affair from his
family.
</P>
<P>
   But even some committee Democrats who oppose impeaching Clinton
see a chance to reach agreement with Republicans over dropping a
number of Starr's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the facts, as outlined by the independent
counsel, rise to the level of high crimes and misdemeanors,'' said
Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell Democrat. ``We could
limit the scope of this inquiry, which would result in a
less-contentious process that would not go on and on for over a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many Republicans on the committee balked at publicly
rejecting several of Starr's allegations before a formal inquiry
begins, several of them voiced opposition to particular charges,
most notably the abuse-of-power count.
</P>
<P>
   To support the charge, Starr said Clinton violated his
``constitutional duty to faithfully execute the laws'' by, among
other things, invoking executive privilege in an attempt to block
his lawyers from testifying before a grand jury about their private
conversations with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe invoking executive privilege is an abuse of
power,'' said Representative George W. Gekas, a Pennsylvania
Republican, echoing several other GOP committee members.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also asserted that Clinton abused the power of his office
by misleading his family, his staff and the Cabinet about his
illicit affair. As a result, Starr alleged, many of the president's
allies, including Hillary Rodham Clinton, ``relied on and publicly
emphasized the president's denial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we want to impeach the president because his
wife defended him on television,'' said Representative Bobby Scott,
a Virginia Democrat who serves on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's charge that Clinton tried to obstruct justice by
delaying his grand-jury appearance for seven months and lying to
potential grand-jury witnesses, his aides, about the Lewinsky
matter also appeared to lack merit as an impeachable offense,
according to committee members in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also questioned the wisdom of pursuing Starr's
allegation that Clinton should be impeached for attempting to
obstruct justice by lying about his relationship with Lewinsky to
his secretary, Betty Currie. ``Lying to one's staff is not an
impeachable offense,'' said Representative Barney Frank, a
Massachusetts Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``refusing an invitation to appear before the grand
jury,'' Frank said, ``even Miss Manners wouldn't go after someone
over that.''
</P>
<P>
   A few committee members have steadfastly refused to comment on
any of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   However, many members have expressed confusion about what
constitutes an impeachable offense. Under pressure from Democrats,
Hyde has called for a hearing on the issue, although no date has
been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   As for the formal impeachment inquiry, Hyde released a proposed
resolution that would grant committee investigators broad authority
to call witnesses and subpoena evidence. The full committee would
not be required to vote on each legal maneuver so long as Hyde and
the panel's top Democrat, Representative John Conyers Jr. of
Michigan, agreed on them.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee ``is authorized and directed to
investigate fully and completely whether sufficient grounds exist
for the House of Representatives to exercise its constitutional
power to impeach William Jefferson Clinton, president of the United
States of America,'' according to Hyde's proposed resolution. The
wording of the resolution is identical to that used for the
impeachment inquiry of Richard Nixon in 1974, except for the the
name of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, Clinton's lawyers could participate in all the
inquiry proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers criticized the resolution because it proposes no
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders were busy last night trying to draft an
alternative to Hyde's resolution.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility being considered by Democrats is to have the
Judiciary Committee or the entire House vote on censuring Clinton
instead of starting impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the final batch of Starr's investigative material
that the Judiciary Committee approved making public is scheduled to
be released Friday, although the release could be delayed until
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
