<HEADLINE>
GARRETT KEEPS EMOTIONS IN CHECK DESPITE OUTCOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Cowboys quarterback Jason Garrett doesn't expect to
have any lingering effects from Sunday's 13-12 loss to the Oakland
Raiders _ despite his two costly interceptions _ for the same the
reason he didn't get too excited about his play in the Cowboys'
31-7 victory against the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I try to do is keep it normal,'' said Garrett, who
has completed 30 of 61 passes for 444 yards, including one
touchdown pass and two interceptions in two starts in place of
injured starter Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was excited about the outcome of the Giants game.
But it was just one game. I think you have to treat it that way
when you win and treat it that way when you lose. It's hard to do.
But you try to keep it as normal as possible and get back to
work.''
Aikman throws
Aikman threw pass routes to receivers yesterday for the first time
since suffering a fractured collarbone against the Denver Broncos.
Aikman threw crisply and didn't seem to experience any problems
with his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who is scheduled to have his shoulder X-rayed again on
Monday, is expected to return for the Oct. 11 matchup against the
Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said the final decision on
whether Aikman plays against Carolina could be affected by the
outcome of Sunday's game against the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   How Aikman feels and the assessment of the coaches and trainers
will carry the most weight, Jones said, but he admitted a victory
in the crucial NFC East matchup could influence the team to rest
Aikman another week.
Linebacker, tackle visit
Linebacker Purcell Gaskins and defensive tackle Nathan Davis were
given tryouts by the Cowboys yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Gaskins, a second-year player out of Kansas State, received more
of an informational visit, since the Cowboys are stocked at
linebacker with Tuesday's signing of Myron Smith.
</P>
<P>
   However, the 6-foot-5, 312-pound Davis, a former track
All-American at Indiana in the shot put and a second-round pick of
the Atlanta Falcons in 1997, is intriguing to the Cowboys because
of his size and athletic ability.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who has been out of work since quitting the Falcons two
days into this season's training camp, has visited eight teams in
the past seven days, including the Cowboys. Two of the teams
already have offered practice-squad contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the Cowboys were going to take a couple of days
before making a decision on Davis. To make room, the Cowboys would
have to put linebacker Nate Hemsley, who is out until at least
December after undergoing ankle surgery, on injured reserve.
Briefly
That Cowboys tight end David LaFleur has only caught two passes,
and none since the season opener, is no surprise. Although he
expects LaFleur to get the ball more, coach Chan Gailey favors
throwing to wide receivers, as his offensive philosophy puts an
emphasis of getting more speed on the field in passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith (strained hamstring), Daryl Johnston (swelling left
knee) and Leon Lett (sprained left knee) did not practice yesterday
for precautionary reasons. However, all are listed as probable for
Sunday's game against the Redskins.
</P>
</TEXT>
