<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-BRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES OVERWHELM CUBS, 7-1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three months ago during a rehabilitation stint at
Single A Macon, Atlanta Braves righthander John Smoltz recalled,
his confidence had reached its lowest ebb. After offseason surgery
on his right elbow and a spring spent mostly on the sidelines,
Smoltz had serious doubts about his future when an inflamed elbow
sent him to the disabled list on May 24, one day after he lasted
just two innings against the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really struggled to win in the minors,'' Smoltz said. ``I
really wondered if I wanted to continue and how many years I had
left.''
</P>
<P>
   WednesdayNow it's obvious that Smoltz has plenty of good years _
and good times _ left in his right arm. Enough, perhaps, to carry
the Braves to another World Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a 17-3 regular season, Smoltz became the winningest
pitcher in postseason history Wednesday when he stifled the Cubs,
7-1, before 45,598 fans at Turner Field in the opener of their
best-of-five National League Division Series. Smoltz's 11th
postseason victory, which broke a tie with Whitey Ford and Dave
Stewart, was a vintage performance.
</P>
<P>
   He answered Atlanta's call to arms with a smoldering 116-pitch
effort, which included 81 strikes. He threw seven shutout innings,
striking out six, before he made his only mistake, surrendering a
leadoff homer to Tyler Houston in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a day where I didn't have the best stuff, but I got
away with a lot of pitches and the defense was outstanding,'' said
Smoltz. ``This game meant a lot to me for a lot of reasons, and it
meant a lot to Dr. (Joe) Chandler (Atlanta's team orthopedic
surgeon) and all the things we've been through. The good Lord's
blessed me to be able to keep doing this. I would've never believed
that I'd be here today, in the playoffs, with the ability to throw
the way I did today.''
</P>
<P>
   But here was Smoltz, shining in the postseason _ again.
</P>
<P>
   He got plenty of defensive and offensive support, in particular
from outfielders Michael Tucker and Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, who had entered the postseason in a 29-for-156 (.186)
slump, provided an unlikely source of power with a two-run homer in
the second off Cubs starter Mark Clark that gave the Braves a 2-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Andruw Jones made it 3-0 in the sixth with a sacrifice
fly, Klesko, who like Tucker made a couple of splendid catches,
delivered the crushing blow, a grand slam in the eighth for a 7-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said he had no concerns about his
team's physical and mental state after it clinched the NL wild card
with an emotional 5-3 victory over the San Francisco Giants in a
one-game playoff Monday night at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' said Riggleman. ``Our guys were preparing hard
before the game. During the game, they did everything they could to
get something going. Smoltz was just the story of the game. He made
us look like we weren't out there fighting. He wouldn't let us get
on base hardly. We just couldn't get it going against him.''
</P>
<P>
   After allowing Sammy Sosa, the 66-home run man who is considered
a shoo-in as MVP, to reach in the first inning on a broken-bat
single to left, Smoltz retired the next five batters, two via
strikeouts, before he gave up a sharply hit single to left to
Clark. Then he tightened the screws on the Cubs, retiring the next
eight batters before Lance Johnson blooped a two-out single to left
in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lockhart ended that threat with a leaping stab of Mickey
Morandini's sharply hit line drive.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's fly brought in Andres Galarraga, who had led off with a
single to left and advanced to third on Klesko's single up the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa led off the seventh with a double that rattled around the
corner in left. But the Cubs stranded him when Smoltz got Mark
Grace to pop to center, struck out Henry Rodriguez, and ended the
inning by inducing Gary Gaetti to ground out to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark was the guy, for me, who I didn't want to beat me because
he's hit me so well,'' Smoltz said. ``He was a big out. It seems
like I've pitched against him for 15 years, so I've got a lot of
respect for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs imploded in the seventh. Smoltz drew a leadoff walk
that prompted Riggleman to give Clark the hook. After Felix Heredia
came in and got Walt Weiss to force Smoltz, he proceeded to load
the bases on back-to-back walks to Lockhart and Chipper Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Galarrraga popped out to Grace, giving Heredia some wriggle
room. But Klesko jumped on a 3-2 pitch and put the game out of
reach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
