<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-DATA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DATA VENTURE BY TOYOTA AND SONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Two of Japan's mightiest companies are teaming up with a
relative unknown to develop a business service that provides data
transmission, perhaps challenging the domain of another Japanese
corporate titan.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Corp., maker of some of the most popular consumer
electronics and movies, and Toyota Motor Corp., Japan's largest
automaker, have reached an agreement with Internet Initiatives
Japan, to create a company that will offer Japanese businesses a
cheaper way of sending data over telephone lines than is currently
available.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will compete directly with Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone, which controls more than 90 percent of the burgeoning
market in data communications in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   No formal announcement has been made, because final details of
the agreement remain incomplete, but Sony and Internet Initiatives
confirmed that they and Toyota had a deal to create such a
business. The deal was first reported in Nihon Keizai Shimbun,
Japan's leading business daily.
</P>
<P>
   The new venture is a step by Sony toward bridging the gap
between the audiovisual and technology sides of its business, and
at a relatively low cost.
</P>
<P>
   The initial investment will be around 100 million yen, or
$741,000 at current exchange rates. Toyota and Sony will each own
30 percent of the new company, and the rest will be held by
Internet Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to build a network across Japan that uses leased
fiber-optic cables designed to carry large quantities of data
efficiently and to start offering the service nationally next
spring and internationally by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Toyota has a significant stake in Teleway Japan
Corp., which has such a fiber-optic network, the new company may
lease its pipelines from Teleway.
</P>
<P>
   Teleway is in the process of merging with KDD, the nation's
largest long-distance telephone-service provider, and Toyota will
end up with somewhat less than 10 percent of the merged company.
</P>
<P>
   But Teleway is just one of several companies from which the new
venture is considering leasing cables, a spokeswoman for Internet
Initiatives said.
</P>
<P>
   Toshiaki Iba, a telecommunications analyst at ING Barings, said
he doubted that the new venture would cut into NTT's dominance.
``Maybe it will be a kind of scratch on the side of the elephant,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Iba contended that without ownership of the cables that transmit
the data, the new venture would be unable to gain a competitive
advantage. ``As long as they run it as a resale business, it's not
sustainable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman for Internet Initiatives said the lines for the
new venture would be leased virtually in perpetuity. And NTT's
president, Junichiro Miyazu, did not dismiss the new venture's
potential, saying that not only did he expect it to present a
challenge, but that other companies would also enter the fray. ``It
may become a threat for us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sony-Toyota-Internet Initiatives alliance contends that it
will have a significant cost advantage over NTT that it can pass on
to customers. The advantage derives from its plans to lease lines
designed specifically for data traffic, which are proliferating
worldwide. NTT relies on lines designed to carry voice traffic, and
while it doubles as a data carrier, it does so more expensively,
Internet Initiatives' spokeswoman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2156EDT &QL; 
