<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Crisis in Minority Home Ownership   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Citing government figures that show African Americans and Latinos
in California falling further behind whites and Asian Americans in
getting home loans, a San Francisco consumer group yesterday called
on the Federal Reserve to hold an emergency meeting ``to save
minority homeownership.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a letter to Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco President
Bob Parry, the Greenlining Institute and more than two dozen
minority business and civil rights groups said that just-released
1997 lending statistics show that ``the minority inner-city home
ownership crisis is even greater than the (Long Term Capital
Management) investment fund crisis that caused Chairman Greenspan
and your New York Federal Reserve counterpart to take unprecedented
action to resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Although conventional home loans to Hispanics and blacks were
up 3.6 percent and 9.7 percent respectively last year over 1996,
they paled in comparison to mortgage loan increases overall.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the number of Asians and whites who received new
conventional home loans last year was up 37 percent and 38 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   More alarming is the three-year trend, said Greenlining
Institute Policy Director Robert Gnaizda. The number of
conventional home loans to Latinos and African Americans declined
15 percent from 39,692 to 33,576 from 1994 through 1997. Over the
same period, home loans to whites increased by more than 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity in lending rates occurred despite growing
prosperity in the past few years, large increases in minority
populations in the home-buying age bracket, and the fact that 72
percent of whites already own homes. By contrast, just 42 percent
of Latinos and African Americans own homes.
</P>
<P>
   Greenlining called on Parry to copy the Fed's bailout strategy
for the Long Term Capital Management, which helped save the wealthy
investors. ``Here's a crisis within the Fed's jurisdiction,'' said
Gnaizda. ``Hedge funds are not,''
</P>
<P>
   Greenlining would like the San Francisco Fed to host an
emergency meeting attended by the CEOs of California's largest
lenders. The aim would be to create a five-year plan to help
eliminate the present racial divide in home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco did not immediately
say it will hold a special meeting, but indicated it is concerned
by the lending trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Home Mortgage Disclosure Act data surprise us,'' said Fed
spokeswoman Sallie Weissinger. ``They raise concerns on our part
about mortgage credit for minorities and low-income individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   However, before agreeing to hold a special meeting, she said the
Fed wants to examine the data to see if there are any ``unusual''
reasons that might explain the statistics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
