<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENCER ON TRACK FOR STARDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So who is Shane Spencer? And why hasn't somebody
begun a campaign to put him in the Yankee Hall of Fame? All right,
all right, so maybe it's a tad early _ like 10 or 12 years _ to be
anointing him for the pinstripe pantheon. But that doesn't obscure
the fact that the 26-year-old rookie outfielder has taken New York
by storm with a September out of Joe Hardy's dreams.
</P>
<P>
   It continued Wednesday night when Spencer, making his postseason
debut, launched a second-inning homer that gave the Yankees a 1-0
lead over the Texas Rangers in Game 2 of their American League
Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   If first impressions are a gauge, the Yankees are correct in
projecting Spencer as a star of the future. The Rangers didn't need
any convincing _ and that was before Spencer victimized them
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good player who has had an unbelievable September,''
said Texas manager Johnny Oates. ``He's having a lot of fun, and
the fans love him. He has hit three grand slams and definitely has
power. Do not take him for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can, at least not anymore. During the final month of the
regular season, Spencer batted a team-high .421 with 8 home runs
and 21 runs batted in. Three of the homers were grand slams _ one
against Baltimore and two against Tampa Bay. And seven of the
homers came in the last nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a fluke, but Spencer's minor league credentials argue
against that notion. At Triple A Columbus this season, he batted
.322 with 18 homers and 67 RBIs in 67 games. A year ago, he hit 30
homers at Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many felt his addition to the playoff roster was window
dressing. It would mean using him in left or center instead of
Darryl Strawberry or Tim Raines. But Strawberry was scratched
Wednesday night for medical reasons. And playing Raines on a
rain-soaked field is a risk. So why not give the kid a break?
</P>
<P>
   ``We did,'' said Yankees manager Joe Torre, who freely
acknowledges that Spencer has greatly exceeded expectations. ``I
hit three grand slams in 17 years. He's hit three in nine days. He
did it against righthanded and lefthanded pitchers. He's been in
the organization a few years and was with us early and didn't get a
chance to do much of anything. It was like he shouldn't be here
yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that really wasn't fair to evaluate because he didn't play
much. We brought him back and he's more comfortable. He's done
everything that you'd like to see from a young player. He's shown
us power. He's pretty much been in a groove, and I hope there is
something left.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer well knows it's not easy to crack the Yankee lineup, but
he wasn't overwhelmed after getting the nod Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay prepared all the time,'' he said. ``So I wasn't
surprised. In fact, I think I like it that way. I don't know if my
home runs should be called sudden or not. I was hitting them in the
minors. I've worked on hitting them for seven or eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's doing it on the big stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty exciting,'' he said. ``You get to go places.
People recognize you while you're eating dinner. I'm not used to
that. The guys are enjoying it because the media goes to my locker
instead of theirs. Meanwhile, I'm having fun. I'm glad I made it
with the Yankees. This way, I can say I made it with the best
organization ever instead of a team that finished at .500.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3052 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELAHIAN-SFCHRON &LR;      09-30 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELAHIAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 The Magic of Failure   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The license plate on Kamran Elahian's Ferrari F355 reads
``Momenta.'' Which says a lot about the man who drives it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Momenta is not a wildly successful company. In fact, it was one
of the biggest flops in Silicon Valley history, a maker of
pen-based computers which burned up $40 million in financing in
less than three years before going belly up.
</P>
<P>
   Elahian co-founded Momenta International in 1989 and was its
chief executive. He was fired six months before the company filed
for bankruptcy in the summer of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   For Elahian, that was the low point in what otherwise has been
an exceptional career as an entrepreneur. Prior to Momenta, he
co-founded two successful companies, and since then, he has
co-founded a fast-growing chipmaker, NeoMagic of Santa Clara, and
two other promising companies _ PlanetWeb, whose software connects
the Internet to consumer electronics products, and Centillium,
which has developed a chip set for high-speed Internet access. He
is the chairman of all three.
</P>
<P>
   So why put Momenta on his license plate?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to remind me not to be too proud,'' he says. ``Unlike
other entrepreneurs who put the names of successful companies on
license plates, I decided to put my biggest failure. That way, I
have to be reminded of it every time I get in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Elahian, who now is 43, not only speaks openly about Momenta's
failure _ he considers it the crucible that has given him humility
to go with his face-sweeping smile.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a year after Momenta went under, Elahian traveled the
world. Part of the odyssey involved doing things, like learning
French, for which he had never had time. And part of it was just
soul-searching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was quite confused about what I had done wrong,'' he
recalls. ``And I had started to lose confidence. When you get the
rug pulled out from beneath you, you start to question whether you
can create a successful company, get products out and make the
right calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that part of my failing was that I had thought I
couldn't do anything wrong. I had started to believe my own PR.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem also was that the market just wasn't ready
for computers that used pens to input information. Another
pen-based computer company, Go, used up $75 million before its
investors pulled the plug. And of course there was the Apple
Newton, the most famous flop of all.
</P>
<P>
   If Elahian was down on himself, venture capitalists apparently
didn't share his pessimism. When he put together a team of former
Cirrus Logic engineers to start NeoMagic in 1993, financing proved
no problem at all. Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, Sequoia
Capital and U.S. Venture Partners all invested in the new company.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of other people who went through an experience like
Momenta wouldn't have bounced back as quickly as Kamran did,'' said
Jim Lally, a partner at Kleiner Perkins and a friend of Elahian.
``That's a real tribute to his positive attitude. It lets him
accomplish things that others couldn't accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1993, NeoMagic makes graphics chips that are widely
used in notebook computers. Last year, it had earnings of $20.8
million _ its first annual profit _ and sales of nearly $125
million, up from $41 million the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   NeoMagic has made a rich man of Elahian, the son of an Iranian
entrepreneur who owned a string of stores selling eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Tehran, Elahian immigrated to the United States after
high school and went to the University of Utah. (His grades weren't
great, so he couldn't get into a lot of schools.) He took college
seriously, however, graduating with a double major in computer
science and mathematics at age 20. Two years later, he got his
master's in computer graphics, also from Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Elahian started his career in 1978 designing automation software
for Hewlett-Packard. But in 1981, he got the entrepreneurial bug
and co-founded his first startup, CAE Systems, which made
computer-aided engineering software. Within three years, it was
bought by Tektronix for $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Elahian co-founded Cirrus Logic, a graphics chipmaker,
and stayed with it until 1989, when it went public. Cirrus sales
grew to more than $1 billion in 1996 before the company began to
founder, unable to come up with new products for the emerging 3-D
market.
</P>
<P>
   Elahian happily concedes that he likes the risk that comes with
startup companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love risks,'' he says. ``My basic view of life is that you
have to dream to be happy and you have to try to make your dreams
come true. And to make dreams come true, you have to take risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin Federman, a partner at U.S. Venture Partners, says
Elahian's secret is ``an incredible thirst for new things. He has
incredible leg drive, and he's interested in everything.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that occupies a lot of Elahian's time these
days is Projectneat, the nonprofit organization he started to
connect poor schools worldwide to the Internet. In its first two
years, more than 2,600 schools have been wired using equipment
donated by Projectneat.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the money for the organization comes out of
Elahian's own pocket. This year, he has donated $2.7 million, and
he hopes to raise a total of $3.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a donation to make something happen that he believes in,
and it's an incredibly impressive thing,'' said Kleiner's Lally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
