A3054 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANCOCK-SFCHRON &LR;      09-30 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Ellen Hancock Hasn't Slowed After Apple   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Ellen Hancock only has an hour.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As soon as a last-minute interview wraps up, she's traversing
the United States for several weeks on an exhaustive tour of which
Jack Kerouac &UR;  &LR; would have approved.
</P>
<P>
   There's a computer conference in Cape Cod, Mass. A board meeting
in Hartford, Conn. Analyst meetings in New York, Boston, Houston
and Denver. And a customer meeting in New York. If all goes well,
she might even squeeze in a stop at the Greenwich, Conn., home she
shares with her husband, Jason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's tiring,'' the personable CEO of Internet company
Exodus Communications in Santa Clara says, wearily nodding her
head. ``After a while, you ignore it.''
</P>
<P>
   She admits that the fast-track schedule sometimes can be as
hair-raising as a Keystone Cops caper. Hancock laughingly recalls a
$390 taxi cab fare she rang up a few weeks ago after missing a
flight from Lake Tahoe to San Francisco. She made her speaking
engagement with 10 minutes to spare.
</P>
<P>
   The breakneck pace perfectly suits Hancock's self-described
``type-A personality.'' Her hard-driving work ethic and technical
expertise propelled her to the position of highest-ranking female
executive at IBM Corp., Apple Computer and National Semiconductor,
and established her as a female pioneer in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ellen came up through the corporate ladder and broke the glass
ceiling in the technology arena for women,'' said Anna Lloyd,
president of The Committee of 200, a Chicago organization
representing nearly 400 prominent female leaders and executives in
the United States. Hancock also is a member. ``She demanded to be
included in that all-male-bastion world, and they obliged because
of her hard work and intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   George Scalise, the former chief administrative officer at Apple
and National Semiconductor who worked with Hancock, calls her a
``very bright, dedicated woman with a deep understanding of
computer software.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock is putting her expertise to use these days at Exodus, a
350-person company that went public in March. Exodus is a provider
of Internet network-management tools for the likes of USA Today,
Hewlett-Packard, GeoCities and J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a jam-packed calendar, Hancock relishes her role,
logging 12-hour workdays and burning the oil replying to e-mail in
her South Bay condo at night and on weekends. (Hancock typically
commutes to Connecticut every two weeks to catch up with Jason, her
husband of 27 years who retired from IBM after 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe you have to work harder,'' Hancock said. ``I don't
mean to be sexist, but guys are reading novels on flights and I'm
plugging away on e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Plugging away is nothing new for Hancock, 54, the eldest of four
overachievers who grew up in Connecticut. She said her father, who
was president of a New York advertising company, had a particularly
profound influence on her. ``I got a lot of encouragement from
home,'' she said. ``My parents were blind to gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock also is a devout Catholic. She went to all-girl schools,
regularly attends church and carries rosary beads in her purse.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock excitedly points out a photo on her office wall, showing
her handing the Pope an IBM ThinkPad laptop. ``Most nervous moment
in my life,'' she recalls. ``I was afraid I would call him your
highness instead of your holiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Possessing so much faith, Hancock appeared to be a natural fit
for the highly charged environment of the Macintosh faithful.
Instead, her one-year tenure at Apple as chief technology officer
was anything but positive. The Apple faithful charged that she was
a corporate suit who lacked imagination and technical acumen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Along with her mentor, former Apple CEO Gil Amelio, and
fellow Apple executives, Hancock was ousted in a high-tech power
struggle shortly after Steve Jobs rejoined &UR;  &LR; the company in late
1996 as part of Apple's $400 million acquisition of Next Software
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve was gracious in face-to-face meetings, but behind the
scenes, he called everyone in upper management a bozo,'' Hancock
said. ``It felt like a reverse merger. Gil, myself and the rest of
the executive team are gone. Steve is now interim CEO, and his Next
team is running things.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you bounce back, and I have,'' Hancock continued. ``I'm
onto the Exodus chapter of my career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
