<HEADER>
A3061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVESCUBS-COX     09-30 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVESCUBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz' performance puts him in lead line-up
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They knew John Smoltz would show up. He does so by
habit, the primary reason he has now won more postseason baseball
games than any man in history.
</P>
<P>
   The question remained, who among the Atlanta Braves would join
him? Michael Tucker and Ryan Klesko stood up first Wednesday
afternoon. For the long-deprived Cubs Nation, this news was not
good.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's two-run homer in the second inning started what
Klesko's grand slam in the seventh finished. The Braves and Smoltz
rolled over Chicago in the first game of the National League
Division Series, 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz' performance _ one run on five hits in 7 2/3 innings _
was good for his 11th victory in the postseason, erasing a record
co-held by Whitey Ford and Dave Stewart, who each made 22 career
postseason starts. This was Smoltz's 21st.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to me. but it means more that the team I play
for allowed me to do this,'' said Smoltz, whose only mistake was a
lead-off homer by ex-Brave Tyler Houston in the seventh. ``I've
piched 21 games now, and they all have been incredible. But it's
the product behind me that has allowed it to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine faces Kevin Tapani tonight in Game 2, and the odds
are not with Chicago. The Braves, 4-0 in Game 1 play of the
division series, are 10-1 in all LDS games, and Glavine is unbeaten
in three career division series starts.
</P>
<P>
   Even after holding Chipper Jones and Andres Galarraga to one
single on Wednesday, the Cubs were victimized by two of the least
successful Braves, a dark harbinger. Both homers came with two out,
both with 3-2 counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's big because Michael and Ryan were big factors,''
manager Bobby Cox said. ``Mike's cooled off the last 1 1/2 months
or so, but he's got a good swing. The playoffs are different.
Anybody can be a hero in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   After Andruw Jones reached first in the second on shortstop Jose
Hernandez's error, Tucker, who had struck out once every 3.7
at-bats this season, worked a 2-2 count against Cubs starter Mark
Clark. After holding up on a low forkball that filled the count,
Tucker was surprised by a ball over the heart of the plate and
blasted it five rows deep into the right-field stands. With Smoltz
in the on-deck circle, Clark threw the second forkball the one
place that he couldn't. The lead was tonic for Smoltz, who opened
awkwardly and needed a pair of outstanding catches by Klesko and
Tucker to get out of the early stages. But he proceeded to retire
10 of 11 men in faced from the third on, until Sammy Sosa led off
the seventh with a double. Then came his best work. Mark Grace
(.333 career average) was induced to pop-out to center, Henry
Rodriguez went down swinging and Gary Gaetti ended the inning on a
check-swing ground-out.
</P>
<P>
   That, aside of Houston's homer, was the extent of Chicago's
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoltz was the story,'' said Cubs manager Jim Riggleman. ``He
made us look like we weren't fighting because he wouldn't let us
get on base.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his time of year,'' Jones said. ``When he takes the
mound, he goes out there expecting 100 percent to win. If we give
him a little bit of a cushion, it's Katy-bar-the-door. Tuck got the
homer, you could see him settle in.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko, who has driven just 16 runs the last two months, matched
25 percent of that on one swing in the seventh off reliever Matt
Karchner, who inherited a bases-loaded mess from Felix Heredia. The
grand slam was just the third in LDS history, but represented
Klesko's ninth postseason homer, another unforeseen development
after he slumped to 16 home runs this season.
</P>
<P>
   That it came in Game 1 against the same Cubs that vexed them
this summer made for an interesting message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they're all important,'' said Klesko, ``but in the same
sense, yeah, it was. It is a five-game series and they did play
good ball against this year.''
</P>
<P>
   That was then. October starts today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
