u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVESCUBS-NOTES-     09-30 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVESCUBS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chicago question: Cubs fired up or tired out?
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   That Monday night euphoria in Chicago has momentarily subsided.
Cubs in! Cubs in! In the postseason, where the question now is,
who'll weather this NL Division Series?
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa and a Cubbies club high on adrenaline, low on sleep
and likely arm-weary? Or the team of the '90s, this deepest and
most versatile Braves assemblage, losers of five straight to the
Cubs?
</P>
<P>
   ``They won (Monday) night,'' Tom Glavine said of the Cubs, who
got an 11th-hour reprieve Sunday, then a 5-3 wild-card playoff win
over San Francisco Monday that sends Chicago to Game 1 today at
Turner Field. ``I'm sure they're all fired up. I'm sure they're
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Both fire and fatigue are factors come the postseason. ``For us
in '93,'' said Glavine, ``after we caught the Giants (on the last
day of the season to end an epic pennant race), we were all worn
out.'' As evidenced in the NLCS, which Philadelphia won in six
games.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Chipper Jones knows, ``I think emotion can take you a long
way, and they have emotion on their side now. They're so sky-high
right now and happy to be in the playoffs, they're looking to take
advantage of any mistakes we make.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Chicago did during the season. After the Braves took three
of four here in mid-May, the Cubs swept a three-game series four
days later in Wrigley Field. The Cubs took two games here July
20-21, Kerry Wood beating Greg Maddux 3-0 in that finale. ``Chicago
caught us a couple of games when we were not playing our best
baseball,'' said Jones. ``We faced Kerry Wood three times; he got
the best of us all three outings (one win, two no-decisions in
three Cub victories). Other than him, the season series was pretty
close.''
</P>
<P>
   Try 3-all. But Wood hasn't started since Aug. 31 due to arm
problems, although he threw 2 2/3 scoreless innings Monday in an
Arizona Fall League game, allowing three hits and averaging 95 mph
on his fastball. Rumors persist that Wood could start Game 3
Saturday at Wrigley.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, ``We need to play the way we've been playing,'' said
Bobby Cox, whose Braves won their last seven games, 14 of 16. ``I
tried to explain that (in a Tuesday team meeting). There's no, `Hit
'em high, hit 'em low.' You go out and play your best game.''
</P>
<P>
   The cat's meow
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga's choice for NL MVP? His good friend Sammy
Sosa. ``I think he has to be the MVP,'' said Galarraga. ``There's a
lot of pressure. He helps the team. There's the (home run) race
with (Mark) McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Good for them
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, who'll start Game 3, was glad for his good friend and
ex-Cubs teammate Mark Grace, as well as his good friend and
ex-Braves teammate Jeff Blauser, that Chicago beat San Francisco.
``It was good to see Gracie (the lone relic from the Cubs' last
playoff team in 1989),'' said Maddux, who also played on that team.
``And Blaus. He knows what it's like to win, but he got a different
taste of winning, like here in '91.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, the Game 2 starter and one of two Braves left from that
1991 turnaround team, was also happy for Blauser. To a point. ``The
postseason's a different story,'' he said. ``I don't want Jeff
Blauser to do well anymore. I'm sure he feels the same way as us.
It doesn't change the way I feel about him. He's a friend of mine.
But I want to win.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
