<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MYSTERIES FOR GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ There are no surprises awaiting the Galaxy as
it begins its quest for the Major League Soccer title. Galaxy
players and coaches know what they're going to see from the Dallas
Burn, and they know the Burn know they know.
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds a tad convoluted, it isn't. Simply put, the Burn
have come to Pasadena to play defense _ tight, space-clogging,
opportunity-killing defense _ and see if it might steal a victory
in tonight's Western Conference semifinal series opener at the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It worked last year, when Dallas wrestled the Galaxy to a
scoreless draw in the Rose Bowl opener, winning a shootout behind
master 'keeper Mark Dodd, then finished a first-round sweep with a
3-0 romp at the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect them to come out here and do the same thing they did
last year,'' midfielder Danny Pea says. ``They're going to wait for
us to come at them and wait for whatever opportunity we may give
them on a counterattack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you that Dallas will sit back and look for a
couple counters and hope we make a mistake,'' says Dan Calichman,
who's eligible to play _ but won't _ after being activated off
injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The teams that have succeeded against L.A. this season have
employed similar tactics, plugging the spaces the Galaxy needs to
operate the dynamics of its attack and taking advantage of L.A.'s
tendency to push forward in search of goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Galaxy does well when teams want to play with us,''
Calichman says. ``It's the teams that sit back whose defense is
very sound we have trouble with. We've got to get an early goal
because if we get an early goal, teams have to come at us, and if
they come at us, that's exactly what we want because it opens up
space. When we don't get the early goal, then we've got to be
patient and wait for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has enough men capable of putting the ball in the net
_ Cobi Jones scored 19 goals in the regular season, Welton had 17,
Mauricio Cienfuegos 13, Martin Machon and Carlos Hermosillo six
apiece _ but it has only done so once in its last three games and
was shut out six times this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn has been erratic, in large part because of injuries,
but has played its best soccer the past month, with Dodd,
post-World Cup addition Chad Deering and Salvadoran Jorge Rodriguez
firming up the defense. There's no mystery how it is approaching
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest,'' said Dallas coach Dave Dir, ``I think
everybody knows the way to play L.A. I don't think there are any
secrets there....
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever L.A. loses a game, they talk about the style of the
other team, but there's no team that sits back deeper and plays to
counter more than L.A. Teams that have beaten them have played the
same way they do. You can't let Cobi and those players behind you.
You have to be patient with the ball, keep possession, and make
them work harder defensively than they're used to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
