A3066 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-STRAWBERR     09-30 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-STRAWBERRY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING STRAWBERRY TO UNDERGO TESTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yankees outfielder Darryl Strawberry left the team
yesterday to prepare for tests to diagnose an illness some fear
might be cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time you take tests, obviously cancer is the one
thing you fear,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``You've got to
hope it's something they can handle real quick. You keep your
fingers crossed and pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry has been bothered by abdominal pain. He underwent a
CAT scan yesterday to attempt to find the cause, but the results
were inconclusive so further tests are scheduled for today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything goes well, he could join us in Texas in time for
Game 3,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, tied for third on the team with 24 home runs despite
being a part-time player, started experiencing pain and cramps in
his lower abdomen about two months ago. The pain was at its worst
when he woke up and lessened as the day went on, so he ignored it.
It didn't prevent him from playing, and he didn't want to go on the
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has been bothering him for a while, but he really
never let anybody in on it,'' Torre said. ``The only indication I
had was his performance on the field, and he didn't seem to be
moving around as well as he had before. But all of a sudden he'd
hit a home run and you'd put that stuff in the back of your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But after a recent conversation with good friend Eric Davis, the
Baltimore Orioles' outfielder who battled colon cancer last summer,
Strawberry decided to undergo blood tests on Monday and the CAT
scan yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to miss him, and we're going to be concerned about
him until we find out everything's OK,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry arrived at Yankee Stadium about 4 1/2 hours before
game time yesterday to tell Torre about the tests and to talk to
his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to stay and have a talk with the players, because he
understands what can happen when something physical happens to a
player,'' Torre said. ``We have a job to do, and I'm sure that's
what Darryl went around saying to everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
