A3070 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-FINE-SPI &LR;      09-30 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-FINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING TO PAY $10 MILLION FINE IN SEA LAUNCH CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Though it remains the subject of a criminal
investigation, the Boeing Co. agreed Wednesday to pay a $10 million
civil penalty so it can resume work with Russian and Ukranian
rocket companies on a commercial space venture, Sea Launch.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 million payment is worth one-fifth the price of an
orbital launch once Sea Launch gets going. It will include a $7.5
million civil penalty, reported to be the largest ever under the
Arms Export Control Act. The remaining $2.5 million is to set up a
computer system in Long Beach, Calif., to allow Defense and State
department officials to monitor the work of Boeing managers and
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department stopped Boeing's work on Sea Launch on July
27, three years into its collaboration with the Russians and
Ukranians.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional source earlier said Boeing had broken the terms
of its export license by discussing technical information without a
State Department representative present. A State Department
official on Wednesday declined to describe the violations, but said
Boeing had violated the license 207 times. The official added that
none of the violations damaged national security or harmed U.S.
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the federal government is continuing a criminal
investigation, which Crain's ``Washington Outlook'' newsletter says
includes a grand jury in Seattle. Boeing has agreed not to
challenge criminal prosecution on the constitutional grounds of
double jeopardy as part of its civil penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Launch affair pits U.S. export-control laws against a
novel business plan to combine the rocket technology of Russians
and Ukranians with the project-management skills of Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The first two stages of the rocket are the Zenit, supplied by
Yuzhnoye/Yuzhmash, the Ukranian group that built the big Soviet
SS-18 nuclear-tipped missile. The third stage is built by Moscow's
RSC-Energia, which launched the first Sputnik in 1957 and lately
has been building hardware for the international space station.
</P>
<P>
   The whole point of Sea Launch is to create a cheap way to launch
satellites by using the spin of the Earth at the equator. Boeing
has 40 percent of the venture, with smaller shares for the two
Russian partners and for Kvaerner Maritime A.S. of Oslo, Norway.
</P>
<P>
   As of July, Boeing had 18 orders for launches, 13 from Hughes
Space &AMP; Communications International Inc. and five from Loral Space
&AMP; Communications Ltd. Analysts estimate each launch will bring in
about $50 million, currently about one-tenth of one percent of
Boeing Co. annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something that is likely to make them a lot of
money,'' Paul Nisbet, a defense analyst with JSA Research Inc.,
told Bloomberg News. ``When everything is going well they maybe
have 15 launches a year.'' But it is the sort of venture that could
set the company on the road to bigger things in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Dolan, spokesman for Boeing Space communications at Seal
Beach, Calif., said work will quickly get back up to speed. Russian
and Ukranian engineers that had been sent home will return to
California. The oil platform will arrive at Long Beach soon, and
testing will begin at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan said the first launch is scheduled for the first three
months of 1999, and that Boeing is discussing the possibility of
orbiting a dummy satellite on the first launch. Reuters recently
reported from Moscow that Energiya had postponed the launch from
January to March and that the satellite would be a dummy because
Hughes Electronics Corp. needed more time to get its satellite
ready.
</P>
<P>
   Crain's ``Washington Outlook'' reported that insurance companies
had lost $226 million on Boeing's failed Delta launch Aug. 26, and
want Sea Launch tested with a dummy satellite before they
underwrite any risky ventures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
