<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HITTING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS CONTINUE POSTSEASON SLUMP 
WITH CHART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If the Killer B's continue to produce like Killer
Fleas, the Houston Astros are dead.
</P>
<P>
   Extending a disturbing postseason trend, the Astros' big-boppin'
trio of Derek Bell, Craig Biggio and Jeff Bagwell again shot blanks
Tuesday in Houston's 2-1 loss to the San Diego Padres in Game 1 of
their National League Division Series. In four playoff games over
two seasons, the Killer B's are an atrocious 2-of-47 with 15
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got here with those guys producing hits, power and runs,''
Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``They've got to come through
for us or we won't win this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite carrying the Astros to consecutive NL Central
championships and a franchise-record 102 victories this season, the
team's stars have been miserable in the postseason. Performing like
the worst Texas trio since the Mavericks' failed Three J's,
Houston's threesome suffered an offensive Brown-out against the
Padres, going 0-of-10 with seven strikeouts against masterful Kevin
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with their nightmarish performance in last year's 3-0
loss to the Atlanta Braves, Bell is 0-for-17, Bagwell 1-for-16 and
Biggio 1-for-14 in the playoffs. The Astros, in turn, are 0-4 by a
combined score of 21-6 without ever holding a lead against Greg
Maddux, Tom Glavine, John Smoltz and Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we were in over our heads against Atlanta,'' said
Bagwell, who had 34 homers and 111 runs batted in in the regular
season. ``And Kevin was awesome, too good for us in Game 1. But
that doesn't mean it's a psychological thing with us. We're better
than we were last year and we know it. One game against a hot
pitcher doesn't make it time to panic.''
</P>
<P>
   But it does make Game 2 at 3 p.m. today in The Astrodome
crucial. The best-of-five series shifts to San Diego's Qualcomm
Stadium over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we hoped we could win; this year we know we can,''
said Biggio, who became only the second player this century along
with Hall of Famer Tris Speaker in 1912 to record 50 doubles and 50
steals. ``It's different. We're not all of the sudden going to
forget how to hit. It's not going to happen. We've been too good
for too long to just give up because of one game.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite setting franchise offensive records and being deemed the
NL team to beat by many, the Astros were totally handcuffed by
Brown's dipping sinker and four-seam rising fastball. Every Astros
player in the game struck out at least once, and they got only two
runners to third base and only four balls out of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who hit .314 with 22 homers and 108 RBI in the regular
season, struck out swinging with two outs and two on in Houston's
best scoring chance against Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know those guys' character and right now they're pulling
their hair out,'' said former Astro-turned-Padre Ken Caminiti.
``They're blaming themselves because they have to carry that team.
We all know what great players they are. I just hope we don't wake
them up.''
</P>
<P>
   The alarm needs to go off for the Killer B's, or the city that
helped launch men to the moon still won't be able to send a team to
the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything less than getting to the \RWorld\S Series will be a
disappointment for us,'' Bagwell said. ``We need to come through,
and we have confidence that we will.''
Killer Fleas? The Astros Killer B's _ Derek Bell, Craig Biggio and
Jeff Bagwell _ have been dreadful in four playoff games the past
two years. A look at each player's hitting horrors: Year H-AB SO
Derek Bell '97 0-13 3 '98 0-4 3 Tot. 0-17 6 Jeff Bagwell '97 1-12 5
'98 0-4 2 Tot. 1-16 7 Craig Biggio '97 1-12 0 '98 0-2 2 Tot. 1-14 2
Combined 2-47 15
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
