<P>
   (NYT24) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- SURPLUS-CLINTON, 9-30 --
At a ceremony Wednesday, the president announces that the
government is ending the fiscal year with a surplus of about $70
billion. Clinton also gives credit to lawmakers who voted for his
tax increase in 1993. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- BBA-YANKS-RANGERS, 9-30 --
Andy Pettitte of the Yankees pitching Wednesday night against the
Texas Rangers during Game 2 of the American League division series.
This has been a trying and perplexing season for Pettitte, who went
16-11 with a 4.24 earned run average and was considered
disappointing. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- GRANDCENTRAL-RENOVATION,
9-30 -- The formal rededication of Grand Central Terminal will take
place Thursday morning, after a $200 million renovation of the
landmark. The ceremony will highlight features like the restored
ceiling, balconies full of restaurants, opened-up vistas, new
underground passages and walkways, and a monumental new east
staircase. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) VRANIC, Yugoslavia -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- KOSOVO-MASSACRE,
9-30 -- Ethnic Albanians stand Wednesday among the hundreds of
vehicles that were vandalized by the Serbian police near the
village of Vranic in Kosovo on Monday after villagers were forced
to temporarily evacuate the region. (Wade Goddard/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) LAS MINAS, Domican Republic -- Sept. 30, 1998 --
DOMINICAN-GEORGES-4, 9-30 -- Blasmaria Diaz recovers some tin
Tuesday from the muddy field that was the site of his home, and
many others, before Hurricane Georges came and the San Juan River
overflowed. Diaz is determined to rebuild his home in Las Minas,
though not a piece of it was left standing after the hurricane
barreled along the southern coast of the island before shifting
violently inland. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LAS MINAS, Domican Republic -- Sept. 30, 1998 --
DOMINICAN-GEORGES-3, 9-30 -- Volunteers bury a drowning victim in
Las Minas. The village, nestled in between mountains, is a poor
community of farm workers that had the terrible luck of being in
the way of Hurricane Georges as it barreled along the southern
coast of the island before shifting violently inland. (Angel
Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LAS MINAS, Domican Republic -- Sept. 30, 1998 --
DOMINICAN-GEORGES-2, 9-30 -- Horses and pickup trucks have been
enlisted as ferries in lieu of a bridge in Las Minas - destroyed
when Hurricane Georges caused the San Juan River to overflow. The
hurricane dealt one of its most devastating blows to the 15,000
people living here and in the surrounding villages on the western
edge of this nation. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LAS MINAS, Domican Republic -- Sept. 30, 1998 --
DOMINICAN-GEORGES-1, 9-30 -- Jose Amado Zabala shovels mud from the
kitchen of his home in Las Minas, which was engulfed when Hurricane
Georges caused the San Juan River to overflow. While most people in
this Caribbean nation begin the arduous task of repairing their
homes, schools and businesses, few in this forsaken village have
been left with anything to repair. Their homes have nearly all
disappeared. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) KAHLOTUS, Wash. -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- NORTHWEST-ECON,
9-30 -- One million bushels of surplus wheat form a monument near
Kahlotus. Hammered by a sharp fall-off in demand because of Asia's
economic crisis, the region's farmers are faced with one of their
biggest stockpiles ever - 340 million bushels, enough to fill a
line of hopper rail cars stretching from Seattle to Chicago. (Jeff
Green/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BRADENTON, Fla. -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- WHOOPI-STORE-2-COX,
9-12 -- The Johnson Smith Co.'s version of Disappearing Ink. ``It
looks like any blue mess,'' says 62-year-old Paul Hoenle, president
of the novelties and gadgets company established in 1914 by Alfred
Johnson Smith. ``Gone in 5 minutes, yet causes 5 minutes of howls.
Great gag - sure fire.'' (Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BRADENTON, Fla. -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- WHOOPI-STORE-1-COX,
9-12 -- The Johnson Smith Co.'s infamous Whoopee Cushion. To
survive in an ocean of mail-order competition and yet remain true
to the founder's insistence that the catalog be a fun read, Johnson
Smith now offers catalogs in two flavors: Things You Never Knew
Existed, aimed at men, and The Lighter Side, unusual gifts pitched
to women. (Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NORTHAMPTON, Mass -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- HARR-HOUSE-3,
9-30 -- The study where Jonathan Harr wrote his million-selling ``A
Civil Action'' is now filled with light. The story of an ambitious
lawyer with a passion for social justice, Harr's book follows a
lawsuit against two companies accused of dumping toxic wastes and
causing leukemia in children in Woburn, Mass. (Lionel
Delevingne/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NORTHAMPTON, Mass -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- HARR-HOUSE-2,
9-30 -- When Jonathan and Diane Harr renovated their dignified
Victorian in Northampton, they splurged on the kitchen, now its
riveting center. Wine racks run under a 10-foot island. Anchored by
a 48-inch professional Viking stove and a Sub-Zero refrigerator, it
is designed to accommodate two cooks working side by side. (Lionel
Delevingne/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NORTHAMPTON, Mass -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- HARR-HOUSE-1,
9-30 -- Thanks to the success of ``A Civil Action,'' a nonfiction
blockbuster that has sold a million copies since its publication in
1995, Jonathan and Diane Harr were able to renovate their dignified
Victorian home, first purchased for $86,000 in 1981. ``When you go
from $2,500 in the bank to $1.25 million, a strange delirium sets
in,'' says Mr. Harr, 49, the book's author. (Lionel Delevingne/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- NY-RED-HOOK-2, 9-30 --
Story Mann keeps his dog, Peanut, cool in the garden he and his
wife, Melina, planted in a vacant lot on Coffey Street. The area is
one of three in Brooklyn and one in the South Bronx that are
reportedly being considered for a garbage transfer station after
the Fresh Kills Landfill on Staten Island closes in three years. A
decision is expected in about a month. (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- NY-RED-HOOK-1, 9-30 -- From
her window in Red Hook, Bettina Magi, a painter, can see the boats
on Buttermilk Channel. This section of Brooklyn has a spring in its
step. But will it falter under 10,000 tons of the city's waste a
day? The old 48-acre Todd Shipyard here is one of sites three in
Brooklyn and one in the South Bronx that are reportedly being
considered for a garbage transfer station. (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 9-30
-- Most household cutting jobs consist of slicing through paper,
cloth or wood. Do-it-yourselfers can easily handle these cutting
chores although sometimes cutting lumber to size can present
problems. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UPPER WIND RIVER VALLEY, N.M. -- Sept. 30, 1998 --
CIR-SAVING-ROCK-ART, 9-30 -- Larry Lowendorf, a New Mexico State
University archeologist, examines endangered 1,500-year-old rock
drawings in the upper Wind River Valley of New Mexico. What must
have seemed permanent centuries ago is now vanishing because of
erosion and vandalism. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- CIR-WRITING-RECOGNITION-B&AMP;W,
9-30 -- The Crosspad, left, takes notes on paper and captures them
as electronic computer files, center. Then handwriting-recognition
software translates the notes into a text file for word processing,
right. (Naum Kahzdan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- CIR-JIGSAW-GAME, 9-30 --
Daffy and company entertain players who solve the Looney Tunes
Cosmic Capers Animated Jigsaws. As with any toy transported from
the physical world to the computer screen, there is the question of
whether a digital interface adds anything to the experience. In
this case, it does. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- CIR-TRADING-ONLINE-2, 9-30
-- At firms like Broadway Trading, small investors use online
systems for day trading. Unlike traditional on-line investing,
where investors hang on to stocks for months or even years, day
trading is a fast and furious game of speculation that can mean
jaw-dropping returns but is also notoriously risky. (Chester
Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- CIR-TRADING-ONLINE-1, 9-30
-- Landon Ray, an independent investor, makes thousands of dollars
in seconds in day trading but loses thousands just as quickly. A
high volume makes tiny profits and losses add up by the end of the
day. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW BEDFORD, Mass. -- Sept. 30, 1998 --
FOOD-SWORDFISH-BOS, 9-30 -- Fish cutter Anibal Duarte slices open a
140 lb. swordfish at Foley Fish Co. in New Bedford. A boycott of
North Atlantic swordfish began last January, when the fish hadn't
migrated this far north yet. Now some chefs who honored the boycott
are wondering if they did the right thing, responsible retailers
are handing out position sheets, and consumers are left in a
muddle. (Joanne Rathe/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PRINCETON, Mass. -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- WOM-TRIATHLON-BOS,
9-30 -- Catherine Jones and her 7-month-old son, Killian, often log
training miles together on her shorter runs. On Saturday, Jones,
35, will compete in the 20th edition of the Ironman race in Hawaii.
The event includes a 2.4-mile ocean swim, a 112-mile bike ride, and
a 26.2-mile run. The biggest thing about the marathon is, it's
hot,'' she says. ``The pavement is black tar - it's hot.'' (Tom
Landers/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
