<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-QUARTERBACK-TEX </SLUG>
 
McCOWN BACK IN STARTING GATE AT A&AMP;M 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randy McCown has been there and done that, and he doesn't want
to go there and do it again the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Tagged by Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum to make the second start
of his collegiate career this week in the Aggies' Big 12 opener at
Kansas, McCown has only to recall the sight of Lubbock in his
rear-view mirror to bring Saturday's task into calm, clear focus.
</P>
<P>
   It was on the South Plains last October that McCown was given
his first chance to replace Branndon Stewart as the Aggies'
starting quarterback. The net result in two quarters as a starter
was, to be kind, less than everyone had hoped _ 2-of-8 passing for
7 yards, three sacks that resulted in minus-24 yards, and a fumble
that led to Texas Tech's lone touchdown. Stewart relieved him at
the half. Tech won, 16-13.
</P>
<P>
   Memories are not made of this. Resolution, however, may be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into it this year, I'm a lot more relaxed. The
difference is like night and day,'' said McCown, a third-season
backup who won his second chance with another clutch relief
performance in a 28-9 victory against North Texas last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put too much pressure on myself in the Tech game last year,
and by doing that I didn't have any fun. Since then, I've decided
that given another shot I would be just as focused, but more
relaxed _ just as if I was playing football in my backyard in
Jacksonville with my brothers and my buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're having fun, you play your best.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks coach Ray Dorr says he believes McCown has given
every indication he's ready for this step and will respond to this
challenge better than he did an autumn ago. But Dorr cautions
against forming iron-clad projections about the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy has had a year to grow,'' Dorr said. ``\RAgainst Tech\S,
he tried to play outside of Randy. Right now, he's playing within
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But let's be realistic, up-front, and not try to paint a rosy
picture that everything is wonderful. Life isn't always wonderful,
it's tough. And Randy still has to go in and play well as a
starter. He's come off the bench and been extremely effective in
every one of the games he's played at A&AMP;M. But he still has to jump
over that hurdle of being a starter.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown harbors no particular NFL aspirations. His current plans
are to take an agricultural economics degree, go back to East Texas
and open a commercial plant farm. He regards College Station as a
city. He has taken up golf to compensate for a lack of opportunity
to pursue his favorite pastimes _ hunting, fishing and exploring
woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   But McCown loves to play football, and his enthusiasm is
infectious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy is really fired up in the huddle,'' noted receiver Chris
Cole, who caught two of his three touchdown passes against UNT from
McCown. ``He's a great quarterback, a motivator. Branndon is a good
leader, but Randy is more vocal.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown is also more the scrambler, more the athlete. He finished
eighth overall among team members in off-season strength and
conditioning competition.
</P>
<P>
   Dorr says he has no trepidation about making a change just as
the Aggies open conference play, a week before entertaining
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won three games, but our productivity wasn't as good as
it's been,'' Dorr said. ``The quarterback's job in football is to
move the team down the field and get into the end zone _ we did not
feel that was being done. You \Rmake a change\S the day one
\Rquarterback\S isn't performing right.''
</P>
<P>
   An evolving offensive line has contributed to A&AMP;M's
less-than-impressive offensive production. But Stewart has taken
the switch in stride, as he did last season when he responded to a
similar situation by playing the best football of his college
career in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I was the starter for the first \Rfour\S games,
the competition between the two of us is always there,'' Stewart
said. ``We always know that one of us has as good a chance to play
as the other. It's no different now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
