<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS FLY AT SOLHEIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to the antics of Dottie Pepper and Annika Sorenstam and
the mouth of Laura Davies, future versions of the Solheim Cup could
well have a Ryder Cup edge to them. That is to say the combatants
in these biennial matches will go at each other with a little more
fervor that is usually displayed when they compete during the
regular LPGA season.
</P>
<P>
   And this could end up being good for women's professional golf.
This year's motto of the LPGA Tour is, ``Hey, we can play this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes they can. Trouble is, for most of the year they do so in the
relative obscurity of cable television and the briefs or summaries
of newspaper sports sections. Consider the recently completed
Solheim Cup, which the U.S. won 16-12 after three days of sparkling
play at the Muirfield Village Golf Club in Dublin, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The matches got network exposure but no major newspaper
coverage. So lots of golf fans missed out on some fascinating
gamesmanship and, in the end, sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   It all started on Saturday with Pepper, an intense competitor
with a fiery disposition. Think Raymond Floyd staring down a
twisting 45-footer and then Tiger Woods fist-pumping after the putt
drops. That's Pepper.
</P>
<P>
   On the 18th green during a Saturday match, Pepper's partner,
Julie Inkster, rolled a long putt to gimme range. The Europeans
conceded the putt and before they could attempt their own chip shot
to halve the hole and get a much-needed half point, Pepper went
into her cheerleader routine, egging on the crowd to a rousing
round of applause.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the European squad took exception, most notably
Sorenstam and Davies. Sorenstam had brought a pop-up punching bag
with her to Murifield. So after the Saturday competition she and
her teammates took turns clobbering the bag, which they nicknamed
Dottie.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam would later say it was just a good way to unwind.
Davies would say Pepper should learn some manners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw what happened on the 18th green and I've been excited in
Solheim Cups,'' she said. ``But when you pick your ball up when
it's been conceded and you excite the crowd when your opponent
still has to play a very, very difficult chip shot, and we're
desperately trying to get a half point out of the match, that's
when I took exception to it. That's when Annika and I started
beating up that dummy thing in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just unprofessional, unnecessary and it spurred us
on. So it was a big mistake on top of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies also said that her team was full of good losers, meaning
that they lost with class. And they did.
</P>
<P>
   If Pepper, who finished the competition with a 4-0 record and
was the only undefeated player, was miffed, she did not let on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear about that until after it was finished,'' she
said of the punching-bag incident. ``I'll tell you what I told
them. I take it as a compliment, period; if that's what it takes,
then I'll be glad to be their punching bag.''
</P>
<P>
   And she maintained that not once did she cross the line between
gamesmanship and sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain, though. If the competition is expanded to
include an international team rather than a European team, as some
have suggested, Davies will find something else to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fed up with answering that one,'' she said of questions
about an expanded team. ``I won't play on an international team
ever. I don't think anyone would be interested in playing the rest
of the world against America. It's an insult to every single one of
us on the team and every time they question us, it's another
insult.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is no doubt that while the Europeans lost with class,
American Meg Mallon also won with class. The U.S. had already
clinched the cup and Mallon came to the 18th hole with a one-stroke
lead on her opponent, Sweden's Sophie Gustafson.
</P>
<P>
   After their tee shots, as they walked to the green, Mallon
conceded the hole to Gustafson, meaning that they would halve the
match and at the end of the day there would be no losers or
winners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
