<SLUG> BC-BOEING-DISCRIMINATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY FINDS FOR BOEING IN DISCRIMINATION CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A black security investigator whose accusations of
race bias against The Boeing Co. helped focus national attention on
the aerospace giant, failed to prove his claims, a federal court
jury said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Investigator Jesse Jones said the company discriminated against
him when it denied him several deserved promotions, and then
retaliated after he complained. A jury of eight men and four women
disagreed Wednesday, finding that he hadn't proved any of the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokesman Peter Conte said the company was ``gratified''
by the jury's decision and reiterated its central position in the
case, that Jones has been ``treated fairly and compensated well''
throughout his career.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' attorney, John Sheridan, said he was surprised by the
jury's verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt we proved our case,'' Sheridan said. ``We showed
the insensitivity of Boeing higher-level executives'' to issues of
equal employment opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is still enmeshed in questions about racism. It is facing
dozens of complaints, a lawsuit by its employees, and drew a visit
from civil-rights champion Jesse Jackson in early September to
discuss the issue with chairman Phil Condit.
</P>
<P>
   Conte stressed Boeing's commitment to being an ``inclusive''
company with a diverse and representative workforce, as well as its
no-tolerance policy toward discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Jones claimed he was passed over four times for promotions in
Boeing's security department, and each time the job he sought went
instead to one of several former FBI agents who worked in the
department.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally filed a complaint, he said, his co-workers'
attitudes toward him grew negative, his job evaluations suffered,
his boss tried to get him fired and higher-ups ignored his pleas
for help.
</P>
<P>
   The company acknowledged that ``distinct cliques'' in the
security department pitted former FBI agents against non-agents.
All of Jones' experience prior to joining Boeing had been in the
military.
</P>
<P>
   But it concluded that the department's problems weren't
race-related, and addressed them by moving people out _ including
Jones, who was made director of disaster preparedness, a job he
didn't want.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it has been fixed, and without regard to race,''
Boeing said.
</P>
<P>
   Several of incidents Jones felt were discriminatory were not
discussed at the trial because the statute of limitations had
expired. Asked why he hadn't filed his case earlier, in time for
them to be considered, Jones said, ``I'm not a lawyer ... I didn't
know about the statute of limitations. The company just kept
saying, `Have patience, we're working on it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the jury allowed to consider certain other information
potentially damaging to Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   One item was a report prepared by Wichita attorney Gloria
Flentje, whom Boeing had asked to evaluate Jones' allegations and
whether he had a strong legal case. The report was to be
confidential, but a surreptitious copy was sent to Jones, who gave
it to his attorney, Sheridan.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing asked the judge in the case to remove Sheridan for using
a ``purloined document'' as a ``road map'' to sue Boeing; the judge
let Sheridan remain but ordered all copies returned to Boeing and
required all who had read it not to reveal its contents.
</P>
<P>
   Also ruled off-limits was courtroom testimony by Viola Keith,
Boeing's former director of equal opportunity, who said company
lawyers had tried to slant her testimony in Jones' case.
</P>
<P>
   As they prepared her to testify, she said she felt ``they would
prefer that I not be forthcoming with the truth'' and told her such
things as, ``You don't have to say this,'' and ``You could say
this,'' and ``Maybe you could take a trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's attorneys vehemently denied her allegations, calling
them ``nonsense,'' a ``flat-out lie'' and ``outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge was visibly angry about the developments, but said
they would essentially require a new trial and ruled that Keith's
testimony was not admissible.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan said there are ``several issues worthy of appeal'' but
he and Jones had made no decision on what course to pursue. Jones
was not in court when the jury returned with the verdict at about
3:30 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
