<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BURN-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESILIENT BURN BEGINS PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First came the injuries. Then the losing. Then the bickering.
Then the trading.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Dallas Burn players questioned their coach's
tactics and general manager's judgment. The Burn brain trust
questioned the team's intensity and fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   Everything that could happen to derail the Burn's Major League
Soccer playoff hopes did in 1998. Somehow, Dallas avoided implosion
and now hopes for a run to the MLS Cup as a bottom-seeded team.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Galaxy (24-8) will play host to Dallas (15-17)
at 9 tonight in Game 1 of the best-of-three Western Conference
semifinals at the Rose Bowl. Game 2 is scheduled for 2 p.m. Sunday
at the Cotton Bowl. Game 3, if necessary, is scheduled for 9:30
p.m. Wednesday at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, No. 4 seed Colorado raised the bar for lower-rung
playoff teams. The Rapids, seeded third in the West this season,
advanced to the MLS Cup but fell, 2-1, to two-time champion D.C.
United.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas swept a hot Galaxy club in two semifinal games last year,
a trick Dallas players know won't be easy to turn this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we all hoped and expected early in the season to
be in this position,'' Burn goalkeeper Mark Dodd said. ``We didn't
know how difficult we'd make it on ourselves to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd shut out Kansas City, 1-0, with 12 saves in the
next-to-last game of the regular season to clinch the last MLS West
playoff spot. It was a fitting performance, given how Dodd's season
began.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn's '97 All-Star goalkeeper missed the first six games of
the season with a broken hand and took nearly a full season to
rediscover his game.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd's absence was the tip of the iceberg. Eventually, 10 Burn
starters missed a combined 82 games due to injuries. Three players
_ forward Gerell Elliott and midfielders Mark Santel and Alain
Sutter _ are done for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty amazing, the stuff we've battled through,'' Burn
coach Dave Dir said. ``I feel good to have been through a lot more
adversity than other playoff teams. Really, we may be better
prepared for this postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas also battled through a stretch of nine losses in 12 games
that looked to end any playoff hopes. Some Burn veterans then
questioned whether Dir should remain as coach or if general manager
Billy Hicks could pull the trigger if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hicks went to work acquiring more talent. U.S. national
team defender Chad Deering moved in at sweeper with 15 games left,
and struggling forward Damian was traded to New England for center
midfielder Oscar Pareja.
</P>
<P>
   The latter addition has given star midfielder Jason Kreis
(team-high 26 points) the freedom to roam from his defensive
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were searching for answers when Alain got hurt,'' Kreis
said. ``Oscar has fit into those shoes and meant higher production
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to injuries and finger-pointing, the heat did its
part in slowing down the Burn. Dallas trained and played through
the hottest Metroplex summer since 1980. From May 31 to Sept. 2,
gametime temperatures averaged 95 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice to use the heat to our advantage, like
the altitude or cold in Denver,'' Dodd said. ``I'm not sure it was
ever an advantage for us. When it gets this hot, it just wears you
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dir called the harsh summer an ``equalizing factor'' in games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's 106, it just takes away both teams' energy,'' he said.
``Looking back, I'm not sure we could have dealt with it any
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with success was another matter. What few big victories
the Burn had were followed by momentum-killing losses. The trend is
evident in the Burn's three-year record of 48-48, which Dodd calls
deceptive with shootouts figured in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's obvious room for improvement,'' Dodd said. ``We're not
where we're supposed to be. You'd be hard-pressed to say anybody's
had their best year. But now we find ourselves in the playoffs, and
this is the same group of guys who know we have potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe facing a big winner like LA will give us the motivation
to finally shine and play to our maximum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
