<HEADER>
A3098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAND-TRUSTS-500&AMP;ADD-N     09-30 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAND-TRUSTS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAND TRUSTS GROWING FASTEST IN ROCKIES AND SOUTHWEST, STUDY SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)  (nk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERGREEN, Colo. _ Land trusts, once restricted to genteel
corners of New England, are now growing the fastest in the Rockies
and the Southwest, according to a national survey of this land
conservation movement.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, as ranchers and urbanites grafted the land
trust movement onto the rural West, the number of local land trusts
jumped by 160 percent in the five-state Rockies division, 147
percent in the four-state Southwest division, and 108 percent in
the six-state West division. While New England still has the
largest number, 417, growth there was only 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``People drive past shopping malls and subdivisions, they fight
the traffic jams, and they are joining together as never before to
protect land for the future,'' said Jean Hocker, president of the
Land Trust Alliance, a nonprofit group that represents about
two-thirds of the nation's 1,200 local land trusts. The Alliance
conducted the national survey, which is to be released in
Washington on Thursday. Local land trusts, one of the nation's most
popular conservation movements, claim to have 1 million members.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide in the last decade, these private conservation groups
permanently protected from development 2.7 million new acres, or an
area nearly the size of Connecticut. This represented a 135 percent
growth over the 1988 level.
</P>
<P>
   Land owned by land trusts nearly tripled, hitting 828,000 acres.
But the fastest growing segment was land protected by conservation
easements, which increased nearly fivefold, to 1,385,000 acres.
Here, landowners donate or sell to a land trust development rights
in perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, the overwhelming majority of new acres coming under
land trust protection is not owned by trusts, but protected by
easements. Montana, with 258,416 acres, now has the largest acreage
under conservation easement of any state.
</P>
<P>
   These private measures are part of a trend in which counties and
states have supplanted the federal government as leaders in
open-space conservation. Florida, for example, announced last week
that it has bought 1 million acres since 1990 as part of its
Preservation 2000 program. Florida is spending about $300 million a
year to buy land for conservation. In contrast, the National Park
Service is spending about $50 million a year nationwide for new
property, down from $300 million a year in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   For land trusts, the boom can be seen most clearly in Colorado,
home to 29 of the 52 local land trusts in the Rockies. In five
years, the acreage protected by Colorado's trusts has nearly
tripled, to 130,000, said Katharine Roser, executive director of
the Colorado Coalition of Land Trusts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colorado is one of the nation's fastest-growing states, and
there is a direct correlation between growth and growth of land
trusts,'' Ms. Roser said Wednesday. ``The pressure is on. People
are seeing our farmlands being gobbled up, our scenic views being
gobbled up. People see that land trusts are a way to do something
about it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The pressure can be seen in Evergreen, a mountain suburb west of
Denver where fast-food restaurants and chain stores line a new
highway into an area renowned for its meadows and pine forests.
Since 1980, the population of Evergreen has doubled, to 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The development pressures are incredible,'' Kathlene Sutton,
executive director of the Mountain Area Land Trust, said Wednesday
from the group's new office here. Moving from battle to battle, the
trust first organized a $3.4 million campaign to save 408 acres of
elk-grazing land from a planned subdivision. Now it is negotiating
conservation easements with five landowners, totaling 2,600 acres,
and is negotiating to buy 6,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Evergreen voters are expected to back a ``Save Open
Space'' initiative that would allow Jefferson County to issue up to
$160 million in bonds to accelerate the buying of land for open
space.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, the state also fosters local land trusts. Over the
last five years, Great Outdoors Colorado, a state entity financed
by casino taxes, has given $1.3 million to 14 local land trusts for
organization and planning.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that Colorado's neighbors are far slower to
develop land trusts. In contrast to Colorado's 29 local land
trusts, there are two in Wyoming, two in Kansas, four in Utah and
seven in New Mexico.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
