<HEADER>
A3099 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-SPENCER-T     09-30 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-SPENCER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES NEWCOMER STRIKES EARLY BLOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Back when he was clubbing home runs in the minor
leagues but seemingly no one in the New York Yankees' front office
was paying attention, Shane Spencer dreamed of playing for another
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the minor leagues, I thought if I was with another team I
might have a shot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he got his shot with the Yankees this year and became a
late-blooming phenom. Spencer, a 26-year-old outfielder, batted
.421 with a team-leading eight homers and 21 runs batted in in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it worked out it seems like this year I was ready, and
I'm glad I stayed with the Yankees so I can say I made it with the
best organization ever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The afterthought for most of his career earned his first
postseason start yesterday, playing left field in Game 2 of the
American League Division Series against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm just enjoying myself and having the time of my
life,'' he said. ``I couldn't have imagined making the postseason
roster, but I got a chance to play and opened some eyes, and here I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   The good times continued as Spencer hit a homer run off Rangers
starter Rick Helling in the second inning, staking the Yankees to a
1-0 lead and earning a curtain call from adoring New York fans.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer was on the bench for Game 1 because Yankees manager Joe
Torre opted for the better defense of Chad Curtis. With Joe Girardi
replacing Jorge Posada behind the plate for Game 2, Torre needed
something else out of his left fielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not having Posada in the lineup, you lose a little bit of a
bat there,'' Torre said. ``I was thinking more offensively in
putting Shane out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer certainly provided offense down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   He bounced up and down between New York and Triple-A Columbus
for most of the season before coming up for good Aug. 31. The
right-handed hitter played mostly against left-handers until a
doubleheader at Cleveland on Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   He went 3-for-4 with two solo homers in the first game, and
Torre decided to leave him in for the second game to see what he
could do against a right-hander. He went 2-for-3, earning more
playing time down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer hit three grand slams in the final 10 days of the
season, and had six homers and 15 RBI in the final week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a strong kid,'' Torre said. ``He's hit fastballs, he's
hit pitches other than fastballs, he's hit them to right field,
left field. He was in a pretty good groove there, and hopefully
there's still something left from that.''
</P>
<P>
   His first at-bat against Helling indicated that there was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
