</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEDGE FUND'S CREDITORS NAME INVESTMENT SUPERVISORY GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story, previously eliminated from NYT News Service
budget, is now restored.) 
(th) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Six leading members of the bank consortium that
rescued the speculative hedge fund Long-Term Capital Management
from collapse last week have named a full-time committee to
supervise the fund's huge investment portfolio _ and promised to
keep trading information secret from themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The six bankers, representing the consortium that has taken a 90
percent equity stake in Long-Term Capital, will have ultimate
control over the fund's investment strategy, capital structure,
credit and risk management and personnel, the consortium said late
Wednesday. They will work together with Long-Term Capital's
founding partner, John Meriwether, who remains as day-to-day
manager and part-owner.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Bank of New York brokered the rescue of
Long-Term Capital, in which consortium members injected $3.6
billion in fresh capital into the troubled fund. The firms have
pledged to keep their investments in Long-Term Capital for up to
three years, seeking to trim its riskiest positions and,
eventually, to realize a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street banks and brokerage houses involved in the
bailout agreed to erect a so-called Chinese wall between the
operations of Long-Term Capital and their own trading desks. That
is because inside knowledge of the hedge fund's trading strategy _
in many markets Meriwether used bank loans to take dominant
positions _ could be used by consortium members to make
``front-run'' trades in advance of Long-Term Capital's moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has instructed members of the oversight committee
not to discuss the activities of Long-Term Capital with anyone at
their member firms,'' the consortium said in the statement. ``They
have also been instructed to base decisions on the best interests
of Long-Term Capital taken as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the banks have taken any other measures to
safeguard the independence of Long-Term Capital. But the six banks
on the oversight committee have each assigned one expert to work
full-time at Long-Term Capital's offices in Greenwich, Conn. The
banks relieved those six of ``substantially all'' their duties at
their parent firm.
</P>
<P>
   The six people chosen to supervise Long-Term Capital are: David
Rogers of Goldman, Sachs, Conrad Voldstad of Merrill Lynch, John
Fullerton of J.P. Morgan, Brian Leach of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, Richard Stuckey of Travelers Group and Michael Allen of
UBS.
</P>
<P>
   News of the oversight structure came as Long-Term Capital got
some relief from creditors. Some 20 banks that own a piece of a
$483 million credit line to the fund, led by Chase Manhattan Corp.,
agreed not to force Long-Term Capital into default over its failure
to pay margin calls on the loan, said bankers connected with the
bailout. The group also extended the terms of the loan by six
months, to May 1999. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
