A3105 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-BAG-LADN     09-30 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BAG-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOASTY SLEEPING BAG IS MUST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A word about sleeping bags: warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Without it, catching 40 winks is all but impossible in the High
Sierra, where evening temperatures in the fall dip into the teens.
</P>
<P>
   You can be wearing every stitch of clothing you packed and still
wake up shivering hourly if your bag isn't rated to keep out the
cold. Imagine trekking out of the backcountry more tired than when
you went in.
</P>
<P>
   Ensure that won't happen by doing your homework beforehand.
Research the overnight lows and shoulder in a bag with enough fill
to ward off the chill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to bring the right bag for the conditions, just like
you need the right tool for the job,'' said Rob Henderson, store
manager of Northridge's REI, an outdoor equipment retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Being caught without the right bag can have dire consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most people who get into trouble in the high country, if
they are going to die of anything it's usually going to be of
exposure,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to stay warm and dry. Depending on the weather, the
top piece of equipment is a toss-up between a sleeping bag and a
tent. You can certainly stay warm by having the right bag and dry
by finding shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   But selecting the proper sleeping bag can be a confounding
process. Most are rated, or gauged for warmth, at three
temperatures in Fahrenheit _ +20, 0 and -20. Theoretically, a bag
rated +20 will keeps its occupant comfortable when the thermometer
reads 20 degrees. All bets are off if the mercury drops any farther
below freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Henderson said the comfort level of that same +20 bag isn't
so cut and dried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell people the +20 is more like a laboratory rating; it
was assessed in a controlled environment,'' he said. ``There are a
lot of variables in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people it will keep them warm at 20 degrees provided
a) you're dry, b) you're on an insulating sleeping pad and c)
you're not exposed to wind and frost.''
</P>
<P>
   At this time of year, it may be best to hedge your bets by using
a 0-rated bag at higher altitudes. Then again, this isn't typically
the period when Californians do most of their outdoors recreating,
and buying a 0 bag may be a mistake for someone on a limited budget
since it likely will be too hot for summer backpacking. Sweat can
be worse than shivers. Having a 0 and a +20 bag to choose from is
ideal for just such a situation, but how fat is your wallet?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough time of year to recommend a bag because we are
in (a seasonal) transition,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   To help with decisions, here are the choices of backpacking
bags:
</P>
<P>
   __ +20: Most popular choice for the region, considered a
three-season bag (or more precisely 2{ seasons) for California _
spring, summer and early fall; $110-$200.
</P>
<P>
   __ 0: A four-season bag ... but not really, because it's not
designed for winter mountaineering and is too warm to use here in
summer and a lot of spring and fall; $160-$275.
</P>
<P>
   __ -20: Winter-mountaineering or expedition bag geared for
extended snow camping and extreme conditions at altitude; $200 to
more than $400.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
