<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKERS-TRUST-NYT &LR;      09-30 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKERS-TRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKERS TRUST HAS EXPOSURE TO FUNDS BUT SEES NO LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amid continuing concerns about the troubled world of
high-octane investment vehicles known as hedge funds, Bankers Trust
Corp. disclosed Wednesday that it had about $1 billion in exposure
to such funds.
</P>
<P>
   To allay fears that the bank may face serious losses from its
hedge fund plays, Bankers Trust said that about 99 percent of such
exposure was collateralized with cash or Treasury bills _ in other
words, that the bank was almost fully protected from any financial
problems at hedge funds with which it has an investment or trading
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust's announcement was prompted by unfounded
speculation that the bank was facing big losses from positions
taken with Everest Capital, a Hamilton, Bermuda, hedge fund.
Bankers Trust has no relationship with the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust is the second big bank in as many days to disclose
its hedge fund exposure, a move prompted by the forced bailout last
week of Long-Term Capital Management.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Chase Manhattan Corp. said it had $3.2 billion in
hedge fund exposure, with about 72 percent of that amount backed by
cash and Treasury bills. Citicorp, J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. and other
large commercial and investment banks have yet to detail their
hedge fund exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said concern about banks' exposure to hedge funds,
largely unregulated investment pools for the wealthy that often
borrow large amounts of money to place complex financial bets, has
been overblown.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, analysts said, is that the potential damage
banks face from withering businesses like syndicated lending,
initial public offerings and securities underwriting may be far
more severe than downturns linked to hedge funds. The huge,
potentially destabilizing losses incurred at Long-Term Capital,
these analysts said, were an anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think looking at hedge fund exposure is the wrong place to
look,'' said David Berry, an analyst with Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   All bank stocks have been battered lately, but Bankers Trust has
fallen more sharply than most over the last year. It closed
Wednesday at $59, down about 3 percent for the day, and well below
its 52-week high of $136.4375, reached in April.
</P>
<P>
   While all investment and commercial banks are facing bleak
prospects because of weak markets and global economic turmoil,
Bankers Trust is more vulnerable than most because of its smaller
size.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, Bankers Trust has been caught in a very
volatile market and they're not in a great position to deal with
it,'' said Gerard Cassidy, an analyst with Tucker Anthony. ``They
may have to scale back some of their capital markets activities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
