<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SCHEDULES NEW TALKS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the reality of canceling regular-season games a
month away, National Basketball Association players and owners have
decided to go back to the bargaining table for the first time in
nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides agreed earlier this week to meet here next
Thursday. But league officials have said that the date was not soon
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bowled over to hear that we can't meet for almost nine
days while Rome is burning,'' Deputy Commissioner Russ Granik was
quoted as saying in The Philadelphia Daily News on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Granik was referring to a Monday meeting he attended with
Commissioner David Stern, Patrick Ewing, the players association
president, and Billy Hunter, the players association's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask him who lit the match,'' Hunter said
Wednesday. ``It was the first mutually agreeable date for both
sides.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of no progress except for an arbitration hearing,
the gamesmanship and propaganda on both sides appear ready to flow
freely. Before Granik's comments, Ewing earlier this week
criticized a proposal by the owners that was sent to the players
last week, calling it nothing more than the same offer delivered in
late May that did not address the players' main concern, the
ability to make as much money as possible during free agency.
</P>
<P>
   The league is weighing canceling more preseason games next week
after indefinitely postponing training camp and canceling the first
week of exhibition games. Both parties have admitted that the
chance of the season's starting by the scheduled opening date of
Nov. 3 is slim.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the stalled negotiations is the impending
outcome of the hearing. Sometime before Oct. 18, the arbitrator
John Feerick, the Fordham Law School dean, will rule whether $800
million in guaranteed contracts will be paid to players during the
leaguewide lockout, which is now 3 months old.
</P>
<P>
   League officials have accused the players of delaying bargaining
to wait for Feerick's ruling, which would give more leverage to the
players if they won.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
