<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS PREPARE FOR REVITALIZED DOLPHINS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The statistics and films tell a story of a
Miami Dolphins team that has renounced its dependence on the pass,
thriving as it has opted to run the ball instead of relying on the
arm of Dan Marino. Aaron Glenn has seen those statistics and
studied the films, and he is not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team knows, when you think of the Miami Dolphins, you
think of Dan Marino,'' Glenn said. ``His arm is the security
blanket you fall back on. If worse comes to worse, they're going to
go back to `Marino, you do what you do,' because he's had some
success against us. Hopefully, we can try to slow him down.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise that the Jets would view the Dolphins'
performance in their 3-0 start with skepticism. Marino has beaten
them seven straight times, throwing at least three touchdown passes
in four of the last six meetings. He has thrown for more yardage
and touchdown passes against the Jets than any other team, the 67
touchdown passes representing the highest total by any quarterback
against one opponent in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   But in their perfect start, the Dolphins have utilized a reborn
rushing attack led by Karim Abdul-Jabbar, who has already topped
100 yards twice behind an improved offensive line, and a stingy
defense which has surrendered only 22 points in 3 games. After
relying on Marino for almost every down of his 15-year career, the
Dolphins rank last in the AFC in offense and second to last in
passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't thrown because he hasn't been behind,'' Jets coach
Bill Parcells said. ``We know what he's capable of. His arm is
good. When he's 50, he'll be able to throw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of style. Jimmy Johnson has brought in his own
style and I think it's a good judgment on his part. But I think
it's to Dan's advantage to play this way. It's easier for a
quarterback to be efficient when he has balance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The offensive ranking doesn't mean that much,'' Marino said.
``If you look at our games, we were ahead in all three in the
second half. We didn't have to throw it. So we didn't. We're not
concerned. We'll be effective whenever we want to be. When we have
thrown it, we've been able to move the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson agreed with that assessment, stressing that it has been
an easy sell to the 37-year-old Marino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan's got all the records,'' Johnson said. ``He doesn't need
records. Paramount in his mind is to win. I think it's only natural
that every player, if he throws the ball, wants to throw it. But
Dan wants to win the game, wants to get back to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three games, Marino has thrown the ball 24, 26 and
22 times, throwing three touchdown passes without an interception.
And the Jets' defensive line does not have a sack yet this year.
Those are numbers that Marino has savored before facing the Jets
before, but he insists that if he leaves the Meadowlands with
similar numbers but another victory, he'll be happy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
