<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOTTI-BAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SLOW DANCE OF BAIL REVIEW FOR A GOTTI 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DEBRA WEST   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ Each day a half-dozen men, some in nylon
track suits, others in pressed jeans, all in glaring white
sneakers, lounge on the shadeless steps of the U.S. District Court
here. They don't play cards. They don't read newspapers. They wait.
</P>
<P>
   Their role, it seems, is to welcome the dozens of people who are
offering their homes as collateral for the $10 million bail set for
John A. Gotti, also known as Junior.
</P>
<P>
   When the pledges arrive, in rented limousines or beat-up cars,
these self-styled courthouse ambassadors, whom defense lawyers
identify only as ``friends of young John,'' snap to attention. They
grab for car doors, offer vigorous handshakes and usher people up
the steps, extending the kind of hushed greetings that are heard
more often at hospital bedsides or funeral homes than in federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   The friendly scene outside the courthouse, however, is a far cry
from what has been going on inside for nearly two weeks. There,
both sides are locked in an excruciatingly slow bail review that
the prosecution maintains is necessary but that some legal experts
think is intended to keep Gotti exactly where the government wants
him: behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   After all, defense lawyers have said, while prosecutors may have
described Gotti as the acting boss of the Gambino crime family, he
is not charged with anything as serious as murder, and murder
suspects are released on bail every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecutors are doing everything they can to avoid having
to give him bail,'' said Murray Richman, a criminal lawyer who
represented Leonard Minuto Jr., who was indicted with Gotti in
January and pleaded guilty to gambling in March in exchange for an
18- to 24-month sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to intimidate those people who come forward to
help him,'' said Richman, who added that he had been involved in
similar bail negotiations. ``They say we're going to make you open
all your books. If we find any hint of wrongdoing, we will explore
the possibility of your involvement with the Gambino family, and if
we find any, we will prosecute you.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution, of course, sees the proceedings much
differently. A spokesman for the U.S attorney's office said the
government was not trying to scuttle the bail process by
interviewing the property owners in detail about their finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all acting diligently and in good faith in accordance
with Judge Parker's order,'' said the spokesman, Herbert Hadad,
referring to the federal judge in charge of the trial, Barrington
Parker. Gerald Shargel and Bruce Cutler, Gotti's lead lawyers, both
declined to comment directly on the bail process.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution and the defense will meet again on Thursday over
Gotti's bail, as they have regularly since January, when he was
indicted on a variety of extortion, loan sharking, gambling and
racketeering charges. The government contends that Gotti has taken
over the family business from his imprisoned father, John J. Gotti,
who recently underwent surgery for throat cancer.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in Thursday's hearing are some properties the defense
has offered as collateral that the government, people knowledgeable
about the discussion say, wants to see rejected. They include the
biggest parcel, the $4 million mansion owned by Gotti's sister,
Victoria, and her husband, Carmine Agnello.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen Gillers, a professor at the New York University
School of Law and an expert on legal ethics, said the government
was acting properly. He said prosecutors must investigate to ensure
that the property was being offered freely and that the money to
buy it was obtained legitimately.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government's valid position is that the proceeds of crime
should not be used for bail,'' Gillers said, adding that asking
homeowners to provide financial records was not a burden.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti had initially been denied bail for months, with the court
accepting the prosecution's arguments that, as the reputed acting
head of the Gambino crime family, he was a threat to the community.
Two weeks ago, his lawyers proposed a set of restrictions on his
release that convinced the judge that Gotti could be given bail.
</P>
<P>
   If he is released, he would be placed under house arrest and
electronic monitoring and his telephone conversations would be
recorded by the government. He would not be allowed to visit his
lawyers' offices, a guard would be posted outside his door 24 hours
a day, and visiting friends would have to meet in only one room of
the house, where conversations would be monitored by the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The bail proceedings are just another chapter in a case that
could have taken a page out of ``The Godfather'': hushed meetings
in social clubs, a son said to be taking over the family business.
And now an ailing father.
</P>
<P>
   But the scene outside the courthouse, conspicuous in this
Westchester suburb, has been more like the comedy ``Married to the
Mob.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his arrest, as if foreseeing his fate, the younger Gotti
alluded to his ``friends'' and their future predicament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surrounded by 12 guys, and one is more incompetent than
the other,'' he said in a telephone conversation taped by the
government and transcribed in legal papers. ``What are you guys
going to do when I go to jail? Who's going to feed you? Who's going
to feed your families?''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, they have apparently answered his
question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2246EDT &QL; 
