<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3124 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTZ-MOVIE-LADN &LR;      09-30 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTZ-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ANGST OF `ANTZ'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by SLANG partners -- Attn: Rich Irwin) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One way to distinguish DreamWorks' new
computer-animated insect movie, ``Antz,'' from Disney's upcoming
``A Bug's Life'' comes during an early scene where a worker ant
reclines on his psychiatrist's couch and complains about being the
middle child in a family of 5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get much attention, you know,'' the ant, aptly named
Z, grumbles. Later he adds, ``All I really want to do is get in
touch with my inner maggot.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that it's Woody Allen, in all his neurotic glory, who
is providing the voice of Z tells you all you need to know about
the spirit of this subversive animated offering. Kids will dig the
eye-popping visuals, but ``Antz'' has a decidedly adult sensibility
with its themes of class struggle, modern romance and
post-traumatic stress syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at its heart, the movie pits Z's socialist leanings
against the fascist leadership of the ant colony. As a comedy,
``Antz'' leans closer to Karl Marx than Groucho.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no surprise then, that when we meet ``Antz''
co-directors Eric Darnell and Tim Johnson, Darnell introduces
himself by saying, ``I'm the communist. Tim's the one bent on world
oppression.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was just the opening line. These guys are brimming with
off-the-wall jokes, probably because they've finally finished their
movie and have a chance to relax. ``Antz'' is the culmination of
years of hard work by Johnson, Darnell and hundreds of other people
at Pacific Data Images (PDI), the Palo Alto-based production
company that has partnered with DreamWorks to create
computer-animated fare. Whereas Pixar (makers of the 1995 smash
``Toy Story'') took four years to make ``A Bug's Life,'' PDI
delivered ``Antz'' in two years and change.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was definitely a little push at the end to have it ready
by October,'' says PDI president and founder Carl Rosendahl.
``There were a lot of unknowns when we started because this was our
first movie. But we were able to deliver it ahead of schedule, and
I think they were pretty happy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an understatement. The early finish allowed DreamWorks to
release ``Antz'' nearly eight weeks ahead of ``A Bug's Life,''
giving the studio a potentially potent one-two punch with its other
anticipated animated film, the biblical epic ``Prince of Egypt,''
due out Dec. 18. The advanced release also helps ``Antz'' avoid
bumping heads with potential mammoth hits like the ``Babe'' sequel,
``Babe: Pig in the City,'' and the ``Rugrats'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (DreamWorks) had no choice,'' says a studio distribution
executive. ``If they came out after `Bug's,' they would have been
dead in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Maybe not. But beating Disney out of the gate has bigger
ramifications for the studio than just the bottom line. DreamWorks
executive Jeffrey Katzenberg left Disney four years ago when
chairman Michael Eisner wouldn't make him president. Katzenberg was
one of the primary forces behind Disney's resurgence in animation,
and some at the Mouse House privately say that Katzenberg took the
idea for ``Antz'' with him to DreamWorks.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the issue is a pitch meeting on Aug. 25, 1994, with
Pixar's director John Lasseter. Katzenberg was still on the Disney
lot but wasn't at the meeting. However, Disney sources say he was
told of the pitch. Katzenberg denies this. A year later, DreamWorks
executive Nina Jacobson came to Katzenberg and proposed the insect
movie. It was green-lighted quickly and rushed into development.
</P>
<P>
   Such synchronicity isn't a new development in Hollywood. In the
past couple of years, rival studios have given us two volcano
movies, two end-of-the-world asteroid films, two Steve Prefontaine
movies. Before that, competing Wyatt Earp and Robin Hood projects
dueled to the wire. In a pipeline full of remakes and movies based
on TV series, originality often proves to be the exception, rather
than the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Darnell, it turns out, had been toying with their
own animated bugs movie, titled ``Lights Out,'' when they learned
of Jacobson's idea. It was a natural marriage then for PDI (known
mostly for its effects work and for turning Homer Simpson into a
3-D character in the 1995 Halloween episode of ``The Simpsons) and
DreamWorks to join forces and meet the beetles, as it were.
</P>
<P>
   As for allegations that Katzenberg and PDI made off with Pixar's
concept, Darnell laughs and says, ``It would have been ridiculous
for us to have attacked an idea just because somebody else was
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Johnson: ``Look at it this way. You had our concept,
`Lights Out,' which we were pitching to studios back in 1991. Since
then, we've had `Joe's Apartment,' `James and the Giant Peach' and
`Starship Troopers.' There's just something about insects that
lends itself to computer animation. It's a medium that likes
hairless, naked creatures because they're easier to realistically
depict.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at that, ``Antz'' pushes the level of such animation to an
even higher level with jaw-dropping crowd scenes that humorously
depict life inside an ant colony. There are more than 500 of these
kinds of shots, ranging in size from a handful of ants to more than
60,000. What makes the work remarkable is that every ant in the
crowd is doing something interesting, moving at a different angle
or in a unique fashion _ marching, fighting, dancing _ so that
anywhere you look on the screen, you can enjoy the view.
</P>
<P>
   PDI ratcheted up the computers' ability to provide characters'
facial expressions, too, going beyond the typical happy-sad-angry
palette to give animators some 300 different options for their
invertebrates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of like a blessing and a curse mixed together,''
Johnson says. ``We had 300 controls. There was no emotion or hint
of thought or feeling that we couldn't pull off. If you gave
someone with a marionette that many options, they'd probably go
insane. But in the end, I think it provides some of the best
moments of our movie, where the audience can really get into the
head and soul of the characters and imagine that they're human
beings instead of animated ants.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with being an animated ant.
Woody Allen, Gene Hackman, Sharon Stone, Sylvester Stallone, Danny
Glover didn't think so; neither did Jennifer Lopez, John Mahoney,
Anne Bancroft, Jane Curtin and Christopher Walken. Katzenberg was
the primary force in attracting the all-star cast and has worked
similar magic for ``Prince of Egypt.'' (Michelle Pfeiffer, Val
Kilmer and Ralph Fiennes are among the participants in that movie.)
</P>
<P>
   `` `Antz' was written with Woody in mind,'' Darnell says.
``Jeffrey kind of buttered him up and got him interested. Once he
signed on, the movie was very attractive to other talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Johnson: ``Z is the kind of ant who looks around and says,
`This is not for me.' He's uncomfortable with everything in the
overly regimented world of the colony and, of course, Woody Allen
does uncomfortable really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, Allen will be plenty comfortable with the finished
product. ``Antz'' is his funniest movie in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recorded him in a studio off Broadway,'' says Darnell,
``and I remember thinking of all the other people paying 80 bucks a
pop for a theater ticket and here we were with the best show in
town.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when the workers control the means of
production. Beautiful, isn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
