<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSSES IN A BOX  
 BUDDING BIKER  
 CRAWFORD SPURNS `OUTLAW'  
 BIT PART 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Has George Steinbrenner III mellowed? A look at the
guests in the Boss' box at Yankee Stadium for the first game of the
American League playoffs on Tuesday suggested that he has learned
to forgive and maybe even forget.
</P>
<P>
   There with Steinbrenner was John McMullen, owner of the New
Jersey Devils. He is also a former owner of the Houston Astros and
a former limited partner in the Yankees who was not afraid to let
his frustration show. In 1979, he declared, ``There's nothing more
limited than a limited partner in the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's current limited partners remembered that line on
Tuesday, for the Boss had them moved to another box to make room
for McMullen and Rupert Murdoch, chairman of News Corp.; Allen
Neuharth, former chairman of Gannett Co.; the actor Kevin Costner;
Wellington Mara, owner of the New York Giants, and Phil Rizzuto, a
star shortstop for the Yankees in the 1940s and 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   As if Yankee officials did not have enough on their minds
already, the Yankees' general manager, Brian Cashman, was quoted as
saying that President Clinton should step down because of the
Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should resign,'' Cashman told Bloomberg News. ``I don't
think it's right for people to sit around lying to people. I don't
like people who go around messing around with interns. It's just
not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman did not return a call seeking additional comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Sanitation Chief Reviews Options
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No, John Doherty is not va-va-vooming off to
California on a motorcycle, as some workers in the Sanitation
Department had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty, who spent his last day as commissioner Wednesday
officiating at a ceremony for 142 new sanitation workers and 73
uniformed managers, ``probably will'' buy a motorcycle, he said. He
recently took a three-day course and got his license, he said. It
was a refresher course, for Doherty had a motorcycle when he was
younger.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty, who spent 38 years in the Sanitation Department, said
he had not started job hunting and did not know whether he wanted
something in waste management.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what a lot of people think,'' he said, ``but there are
lots of other things out there.'' His successor has not been named.
</P>
<P>
   No Pose
</P>
<P>
   More on motorcycles: Cindy Crawford will not be posing for
Outlaw Biker magazine any time soon. Its editor, Casey Exton,
bought a freelance photographer's shot of her, fully clothed, on a
motorcycle. Then Exton wondered whether Miss Crawford, who is
pictured without clothes in the September issue of Playboy, would
pose for Outlaw Biker without clothes but with motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not. ``A spokesperson for Cindy Crawford told me that
she doesn't want to do a layout for Outlaw Biker,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to Please
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Geraldine Ferraro has been given a part in Cole
Porter's ``Jubilee'' at Carnegie Hall on Oct. 10. Four lines, no
singing.
</P>
<P>
   But what she wants to do is play the piano. Why? Her mother
always wanted to be able to say she had a daughter who played at
Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro took piano lessons from age 7 until she graduated from
high school. ``I was pretty good,'' she said. ``I played
Beethoven's `Pathetique' and Gershwin. Then I went to college and
did not play. Now I sit with my grandson on my lap and play `Old
MacDonald Had a Farm' and the songs he sings.''
</P>
<P>
   She is not seeking to play in the show, a benefit for the Gay
Men's Health Crisis. A quick moment at the keyboard before or after
a rehearsal would be fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tap one of the keys,'' she said. ``That's sufficient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
