<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
 
A McBRIDESMAID NO LONGER 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shocked and amazed, UCLA safety Tod McBride
couldn't respond. It was two days after the Bruins' lackluster
performance against Houston, and defensive coordinator Nick Aliotti
needed a playmaker for his beleaguered secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tod, how'd you like to be my starting strong safety against
Miami?'' Aliotti said.
</P>
<P>
   McBride was stunned silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't say anything, but I knew my prayers had been
answered,'' he said. ``This has all been about persevering. I just
told myself one day it would pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   A fifth-year senior from Walnut, McBride spent his first two
seasons as a reserve receiver. In spring '97, he underwent surgery
to repair tears in both patella tendons. He returned six months
later and switched to defensive back, having lost the speed
necessary to play receiver.
</P>
<P>
   He began training camp '98 as one of three players competing for
Shaun Williams' vacant spot at free safety. A few weeks later he
became the backup strong safety _ a position ideal suited for his
hard-hitting style.
</P>
<P>
   In UCLA's post-Houston reorganization, All-American Larry Atkins
slid from strong safety to free safety, and McBride got the call.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great view. But the window won't stay open forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a nice talk with McBride and (reserve cornerback) Eric
Whitfield,'' coach Bob Toledo said. ``I told them they've been
given an opportunity and they need to take advantage of that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ How they stand: No unit save the defensive line has undergone
more change than the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Against Washington State, McBride and Atkins will start at the
safety spots, with Jason Stephens (free) and DuVal Hicks (strong)
playing in relief. Ryan Roques and Jason Bell will start at
cornerback, with Marqes Anderson and Whitfield in reserve.
Whitfield will play the nickel (fifth) defensive back in passing
situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not satisfied, but we're getting better,'' Aliotti said.
``These changes won't be forever.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Review of the week: All-American offensive tackle Kris Farris
is a film buff who wants to direct when his playing career ends. He
has agreed to review movies for the Daily News. This week: ``Urban
Legend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The new horror film `Urban Legend' provided me with an
experience unlike anything I've had before: It marked the first
time I was actually embarrassed to be in a movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technically, this film makes Ed Wood's `Plan Nine From Outer
Space' look like `Citizen Kane.' Most of the problems derive from
Silvio Horta's ridiculous screenplay, and the performances are so
one-dimensional you find yourself relieved each time a character is
killed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're itching to see a scary movie, rent Alfred
Hitchcock's `Psycho,' turn out the lights, and watch it alone.
It'll do something `Urban Legend' couldn't. It'll scare you.'' Half
a pancake (out of four).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
