<SLUG> BC-NY-JAILS-CARE-(860)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD TO ASSESS CARE IN JAILS, OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER DREW and DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As investigations expand into possible problems with
medical care in city jails, including several deaths, top New York
City health officials have acknowledged that they have had trouble
monitoring the jail system's shift to managed care.
</P>
<P>
   The health officials said that they were scrambling to set up a
better system for supervising medical treatment on Rikers Island,
and that they were demanding more medical services from the
contractor, St. Barnabas Hospital in the Bronx, to keep it from
earning excessive profits on the three-year, $342 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials insist that the overall quality of care for
inmates remains high. But both the Manhattan district attorney's
office and the New York City Board of Correction are investigating
whether a deterioration in medical care contributed to the deaths
of several inmates this year. And some critics, including current
and former jail doctors, have contended that pressures to cut costs
have seriously eroded the level of service provided.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints began after the city shifted in January to the
managed care approach, which is now sweeping through the nation's
jail and prison systems much as it is in the world of private
health insurance. But city health officials acknowledge that the
transition to this money-saving system has been difficult, and that
regulators have not yet taken all the steps that were promised to
insure that cuts in costs did not compromise care.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the contract calls for the city's Health and
Hospitals Corp. to evaluate St. Barnabas quarterly on more than 30
quality measures. But regulators have not completed any of the
evaluations _ or assessed any penalties _ because of problems in
collecting and analyzing the data, Joseph R. Erazo, the
corporation's executive director for correctional health services,
said in interviews this week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Erazo said his office was improving those monitoring
systems and expanding independent reviews of patient complaints and
other standards of care. And in response to concerns that St.
Barnabas stands to reap large earnings, Erazo said the city was
requiring the hospital to reinvest some of that money by adding
more services and installing expensive medical equipment at Rikers.
He said the city expected to limit St. Barnabas' earnings to a rate
of 10 to 14 percent, or about $11 million to $16 million a year, on
the annual contract payments of $114 million.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the difficulties so far, Erazo said: ``You've got
to be a little bit reasonable. The transition phase is going to
cause great problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``We're now in a phase where we're going to be
doing harder and harder reviews and harder and harder monitoring.''
He added, ``We're not going to be enriching any organization on
this contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry officials said that annual profit rates of 6
percent to 10 percent were the norm for companies providing managed
care in jails. And critics say the city should have been tougher in
monitoring St. Barnabas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to take the problems seriously and do the kind
of oversight we probably should have done in the beginning,'' said
David R. Jones, a former board member of the Health and Hospitals
Corp. who raised questions about the jail contract when the board
approved it late last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very strongly that while prisoners are considered by
some the least among us, society has an obligation to provide
decent medical care,'' he added. ``We can't go back to the Middle
Ages, where people are allowed to literally rot in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Barnabas submitted the lowest bid of five institutions
considered for the jail contract. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
administration has cited the contract as a model for saving money
in public health operations, and it has hired St. Barnabas to
manage city-owned Lincoln Hospital in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new contract, instead of paying each time an inmate is
taken to the hospital, the city provides an annual lump sum for
each inmate's care.
</P>
<P>
   The city's aim was to lower the number of times that inmates
were taken to city hospitals and encourage St. Barnabas to offer
more emergency and specialist care on Rikers Island itself.
</P>
<P>
   But since St. Barnabas took over, the number of trips by inmates
to city hospitals has dropped by 57 percent. Some city officials
and doctors contend that delays in going to hospitals could
endanger inmates and may have played a role in several deaths. St.
Barnabas, like other managed care operators that receive lump-sum
payments, can increase earnings by limiting service and keeping
costs as low as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In urging his board to approve the contract last year, Dr. Luis
R. Marcos, president of the Health and Hospitals Corp., brushed
aside some of Jones' concerns about enforcement, saying, ``We will
be paying close attention.''
</P>
<P>
   But Erazo and other officials said this week that though the
creation of more than 30 measures for checking quality was an
important step, regulators occasionally ran into delays in getting
basic data from St. Barnabas and were still setting up systems to
verify the data.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most of the gauges are simple statistical checks, like whether
inmates with HIV received drug therapies. But some also involve
medical staffing levels and inmates' access to dentists and medical
specialists _ all issues on which St. Barnabas has been criticized.
The regulators can fine St. Barnabas up to $5,000 for each quarter
that it fails to meet one of the standards.
</P>
<P>
   But Erazo said that regulators did not have enough information
to do a formal evaluation in this year's first quarter, and that
his office was just getting close to completing one for the second
quarter, which ended June 30. As a result, he said, no penalties
have been assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials said that as managed care had spread into
jails and prisons in more than two dozen states, questions about
the quality of care and monitoring had been common. Profit levels
have also been controversial, especially in the first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally when you switch from a fee-for-service
environment to a managed-care environment you would get a savings
of 25 to 30 percent after the first year,'' said Leon M. Clements,
chief administrative officer of Correctional Managed Care, a
division of the University of Texas Medical Branch at Galveston,
which also bid on the New York jail contracts.
</P>
<P>
   He and other executives said a frequent source of tension was
what share of that would go to the contractor as profit.
</P>
<P>
   Erazo confirmed that in the first six months of this year, St.
Barnabas spent about $7 million less on care in the jails than it
received from the hospitals corporation, a figure reported
Wednesday in The New York Observer. The Observer said that was
equivalent to a 14 percent profit.
</P>
<P>
   But Erazo also said that St. Barnabas had already paid for extra
services that were not in the contract, including a $500,000 CAT
scan diagnostic device at Rikers and a $650,000 therapeutic drug
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be doing much more of that,'' he said. He added that
for all of 1998, St. Barnabas' income was likely to ``come in at a
level that's more conservative'' than earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said that some of the scrutiny was prompted by
the recent death of one inmate from liver failure shortly after he
was given a drug that can strain the liver. Officials said earlier
this week that the Manhattan district attorney was examining that
death and three others as well as allegations that the medical
records of a handful of inmates were improperly altered.
</P>
<P>
   A hospital spokesman did not respond to a request for comment
Wednesday. But St. Barnabas officials have defended the quality of
their care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
