u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT &LR;      09-30 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO MAKES ANOTHER SWING FOR VOTES AS `POTHOLE SENATOR' 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JAMES DAO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACEDON, N.Y. _ Sen. Alfonse D'Amato continued his campaign to
win the hearts and votes of upstate New Yorkers on Wednesday,
visiting a string of storm-ravaged farms from Syracuse to Lake Erie
and pledging to play the role of the ``pothole senator'' by winning
federal disaster aid for the region.
</P>
<P>
   In his second swing across northern New York state in two weeks,
D'Amato, a Republican seeking his fourth term, munched apples,
inspected wind-shorn trees and hail-pitted apples, wore an oversize
``Apple Country'' cap and touted his Senate votes to help farmers
on issues like maintaining dairy price supports.
</P>
<P>
   At fruit farms near Syracuse, Rochester and Niagara Falls,
D'Amato said he would try to add money to an agriculture
appropriations bill, which is expected to reach the Senate next
week, to help farmers hurt by a series of freak hail and wind
storms that swept through western and central New York this summer.
Farm groups have estimated that the storms caused $40 million in
damage, mainly to fruit growers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a battle for our people, for the little guy,'' D'Amato
said at a stop at G and S Orchards in rural Macedon, 17 miles
southeast of Rochester. ``You know, they call me the pothole
senator. They do. They make fun. But let me tell you, the potholes
are real people.''
</P>
<P>
   But as much as he sought to use the one-day trip to burnish his
record on agriculture in a solidly Republican region, D'Amato also
tried to take some swipes at his Democratic challenger, Rep.
Charles Schumer of Brooklyn, by complaining about people who think
that ``upstate New York is Westchester.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never pitted the interest of one region against the other
or denied support from one to help the other or looked at one with
indifference or disdain,'' D'Amato told reporters following the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Though D'Amato, who comes from Long Island, claimed that he was
not referring to Schumer in making those remarks, his recent stump
speeches and commercials have hammered at Schumer as a ``New York
City liberal'' who is oblivious to the needs of upstate residents
and believes that ``the West begins across the Hudson River.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who was observing the Jewish holy day of Yom Kippur,
was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In focusing again on northern New York on Wednesday, D'Amato and
his advisers provided further evidence that they believe his
fortunes in a tight race will hinge on driving up voter turnout in
Republican-rich communities like Macedon, as well as on denting the
reputation of Schumer, who despite his own free-spending campaign
still seems to be an enigma to most voters here.
</P>
<P>
   Some local politicians said Wednesday that there may be good
reason for D'Amato to be concerned about upstate turnout in
November because voter discontent is running relatively low and
because the race for governor, typically a voter draw, is not
attracting much attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he knows he's going to have a real tough time
downstate and feels in a close election that upstate can win it for
him,'' said Frank Guelli, a Democratic supervisor in Walworth, who
is supporting D'Amato. ``Unfortunately, there's not much of a
governor's race and that could affect turnout.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were also hints Wednesday that D'Amato's attacks on
Schumer may be wearing thin among some upstate residents. During
D'Amato's Macedon appearance, local reporters peppered the senator
with sharp questions about the negative tone of the campaign and
the potentially divisive nature of his upstate strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Placed on the defensive at one point by a series of questions,
D'Amato testily challenged one television reporter to take a
critical look at Schumer, who has accused D'Amato of lying and of
being ``sleazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not engaged in any personal attacks,'' D'Amato said.
``But you won't run any of this. You'll slice it and dice it the
way you want it.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of the farmers who came out to meet D'Amato at G and S
Orchards said they thought his strategy was just right. ``There's a
mentality around here, and I have it as well, that New York City
ought to form its own country,'' said Brandon Furber, 36, a
third-generation farmer in Huron.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
