<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOW START DOESN'T WORRY HEBERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Even though the Anaheim Mighty Ducks are 1-5
in the exhibition season and have allowed 26 goals in their past
four games, goalie Guy Hebert insists it's not time to panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time to continue to be positive,'' he said. ``Everybody
is still excited. We didn't expect to come in and win every game.
I've played for a long time and I've never seen a team go 9-0 or
10-0 (in the exhibition season) and go on to win the Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert says it's going to take time for the team to learn new
coach Craig Hartsburg's defensive system, which features at least
one defenseman remaining in front of the net at all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are used to playing man-to-man, and in this system you
have to be very patient,'' he said. ``I think it will be effective,
but you're not going to learn it and perfect it in two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert says the system is something completely new to him but
that he likes the idea that Hartsburg is very committed to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited Craig is going to work with one system and keep
working on it,'' he said. ``(That he's) not going to change from
night to night and get guys more confused.''
</P>
<P>
   __ New view: Hartsburg wasn't thrilled after the Ducks gave up
four third-period goals in Monday's 5-3 loss to the Kings, but he
seemed to soften his stance on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of good things happened,'' he said. ``I'm not happy we
lost, but we are trying to build.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no lack of effort. Eventually, we will be a
good team. It could be days or a couple of weeks, but we will get
there. Maybe to some people it doesn't look like (we are
improving), but we see things.''
</P>
<P>
   __ On the bubble: Pavel Trnka, a 22-year-old defenseman who
played well toward the end of last season, is not guaranteed a spot
on the team for this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fighting for a position.... he needs to show us more,''
said Hartsburg, who added that Trnka missing a portion of camp
because of a contract dispute ``didn't help.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Another chance: Goalie Patrick Lalime, who has struggled in
his past two outings (12 goals allowed), will play one of the games
against Nashville _ either in Cincinnati on Friday or Milwaukee on
Saturday. Hebert will play the other game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
