<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-AIDS-VACCINE (Kampala, Uganda) _ In Uganda _ a country
struggling valiantly to cope with an AIDS epidemic that has
infected 20 percent of its population, desperate Ugandans clamor to
participate in an AIDS vaccine trial. In the past, ethical
guidelines have made it clear that vaccines should be tested where
health care is excellent before they are ever used in places
without a safety net, like Uganda. Now the international medical
community has set aside that requirement. By Michael Specter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients. Locator
map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DOMINICAN-GEORGES (Las Minas, Dominican Republic) _ In a town
destroyed, Dominicans salvage little but the will to go on.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT17,18,19,20) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
