<P>
   SURPLUS-IMPACT (Washington) _ For the better part of two
decades, economists and elected officials have promised that all
kinds of good things would happen if the federal government stopped
running huge budget deficits. On Wednesday the government closed
the books on its fiscal year, and for the first time since 1969 the
budget will show a surplus. So where's the payoff? By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-REGULATE (Washington) _ As financiers poke through the
shards of the failed Long Term Capital Management hedge fund,
Congress is debating whether such highly secretive, highly risky
funds should be subject to greater scrutiny. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   MOCKUMENTARY-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Once a particular style of
television commercial becomes popular, it is soon overused and then
discarded. The latest kind of commercial to catch fire, the
``mockumentary'' _ a spoof done in the style of a documentary film
_ may be on its way out, too, according to some creative directors.
By Greg Farrell.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Judging from the volume of
criticism from left and right, President William McDonough of the
Federal Reserve Bank of New York must have made a dreadful mistake
when he orchestrated a ``bailout'' of Long-Term Capital Management
LP, a multibillion-dollar investment fund that bought almost all of
its assets with borrowed money. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
