<HEADER>
A3276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOCKUMENTARY-AD-COL-7     09-30 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOCKUMENTARY-AD-COL-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV COMMERCIALS OFFER TOO MUCH OF A GOOD THING ALL OVER AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GREG FARRELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Advertising may be at its best when it breaks conventional
rules, but at least one rule is sacred: Once a particular style of
television commercial becomes popular, it will quickly be overused
and then discarded. Good examples are the disappearance of the
shaky, hand-held camera technique of the late 1980s and the reduced
emphasis on computer-generated special effects, most popular in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The latest commercial form to catch fire, the ``mockumentary,''
may be on its way out, too, according to some creative directors.
</P>
<P>
   The mockumentary commercial is a spoof done in the style of a
documentary film. The best-known mockumentary campaign of recent
years is Wieden &AMP; Kennedy's work for ``Sports Center'' on ESPN, the
cable sports network owned by the Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in late 1995, each commercial in the campaign has
taken viewers behind the scenes, as it were, of the nightly
``Sports Center'' report. The spots range from the bizarre (Keith
Olbermann, a former anchor, ripping the guitar from the hands of a
meek folk singer and smashing it) to the sublime (the heavyweight
boxing champion Evander Holyfield running ESPN's day-care center,
feeding his charges a diet of raw eggs and telling them, ``Don't
forget your gloves'' as he hands each departing youngster a pair of
boxing gloves).
</P>
<P>
   The ESPN commercials use either people from the show or sports
stars and throw them into absurd situations. The campaign has
become such a cultural hit that star athletes ask to appear in the
commercials _ and ESPN does not pay them for doing the spots.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's popularity has naturally spawned imitators. Last
year, the agency behind one of the longest-running campaigns of the
decade turned to the mockumentary format to keep its work fresh.
</P>
<P>
   For the Energizer brand of batteries sold by the Ralston Purina
Co., TBWA Chiat/Day, a unit of Omnicom Group, introduced a
commercial that followed a group of ``bunny spotters'' as they
tried to find EB, the elusive pink bunny. The campaign also
detailed the fortunes of a high school track team that had adopted
the bunny as its mascot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole purpose of the mockumentary is to say, `This isn't a
commercial, this is real,''' said Chuck Bennett, creative director
at TBWA Chiat/Day in Playa del Rey, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, it was a highly appropriate technique and
style,'' he added. ``It had a fresh, disarming quality. Now that
there's so many of them, it's a known execution and you go, `It's a
commercial.'''
</P>
<P>
   The mockumentary style has blossomed at Nike Inc. over the last
two years. The athletic-footwear giant sponsored one commercial
that showed a ``speed recovery'' meeting for athletes who run too
fast and another promoting golf etiquette on Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   Another Nike campaign, for skateboarding, showed what would
happen if participants in other sports were treated the way
skateboarders often are. The deadpan scenes depicted runners and
tennis players being heckled, harassed or even arrested. Finally,
there's a campaign starring the ``fun police,'' National Basketball
Association players who arrest young players for never passing the
ball and chase referees who don't make the right calls.
</P>
<P>
   The skateboarding campaign, from Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners
in San Francisco, part of Omnicom, won the Grand Prix in June at
the International Advertising Festival in Cannes, France. But not
all judges of award shows applaud the popularity of the
mockumentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the lookout for something fresh,'' says Mike Shine, a
partner and creative director at Butler, Shine &AMP; Stern in
Sausalito, Calif., who was a judge of the One Show awards
competition in April, sponsored by the One Club for Art and Copy.
``I wanted to be inspired. And then I saw three mockumentaries in a
row from three different clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Shine blamed the success of the ESPN campaign for the flood of
mockumentaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens when something wins big and defines a new type of
execution,'' he said. ``Everybody has figured the formula out so
perfectly that you can't figure out whose brand it is until the
logo appears. If we're that sick of it, it won't be long before
consumers are sick of it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another judge at the One Show, Bill Heater, chairman of Heater
Advertising in Boston, estimated that six of 10 commercials he saw
there were mockumentaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lacks originality,'' he said, pointing to ``This Is Spinal
Tap,'' a 1984 mock documentary about a rock band on tour that has
become a cult favorite, and ``Waiting for Guffman,'' a 1997 film in
the same style, as sources of the imitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creative people see those films and they're funny and
quirky,'' Heater said, ``and it becomes an advertising idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Multiple awards for commercials in the same style, said Arthur
Bijur, president at Cliff Freeman &AMP; Partners, a unit of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi PLC in New York, usually prefigures ``the beginning of the
demise of that style.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Wieden &AMP; Kennedy work for ESPN made the mockumentary
format popular, Goodby, Silverstein has been an advocate of the
genre for years. Just as ``Spinal Tap'' was being released in 1984,
the agency, then known as Goodby, Berlin &AMP; Silverstein, produced a
small but memorable commercial for an annual film festival in Mill
Valley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was intentionally stupid,'' says Jeff Goodby, co-creative
director. ``We wanted to know what would happen if a French film
crew came to cover it and everyone was incredibly knowledgeable
about the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   In the commercial, local residents talk like film experts. The
butcher, for example, discussed the art of editing while cutting
meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're within 15 minutes of the demise of this,'' said
Alan Marcus, executive vice president and creative director at
Arnold Communications, a unit of Snyder Communications in Boston.
He recently completed three spots for Ocean Spray in mockumentary
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the permanent nature of advertising,'' he added. ``If you
do something or see something that's interesting, we love it so
much that we eventually kill it. We are so quick to jump on things,
and we're quick to move on to other things.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Judy Fearing, senior vice president for marketing at
ESPN in New York, said she was in no hurry to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN is ``ecstatic'' about its campaign, Ms. Fearing said,
adding: ``What is important to ESPN is that we think of advertising
ideas that show that we appreciate and understand the sports scene.
As long as our executions deliver on that promise, and are unique
and fresh, we'll continue.''
</P>
<P>
   But the mockumentary is history for at least one agency. After
returning from judging the One Show, Shine of Butler, Shine forbade
any of the creative staff at his agency to use the format anymore.
</P>
<P>
   (Photo of XXXXXX has been sent to photo clients via INS at
212-643-2005. The photo also is available now to mail clients who
use Wieck Photo Database at 214-416-3686. For a fee non-subscribers
can get it by wirephoto. Call NYT News Service Photos, 212-556-1243
weekdays 9-5 EDT.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
