<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEFEAT RANGERS, 3-1, TO TAKE 2 GAME LEAD IN DIVISIONAL
PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Joe Torre announced that Andy Pettitte would
start the second game of the American League Division Series, he
spoke confidently of Pettitte's pedigree as a big-game pitcher, of
how he was sure Pettitte would respond to the challenge, in spite
of a late-season slump.
</P>
<P>
   Torre's handling of Pettitte on Wednesday night revealed his
true fears. Whenever Texas hitters reached base in Game 2, the
phone rang in the Yankee bullpen and relievers scrambled to warm
up, preparing for the urgent call for help.
</P>
<P>
   But that call never came. Pettitte allowed just one run in seven
innings, striking out eight and walking none, and the Yankees beat
Texas, 3-1, before 57,360 at Yankee Stadium. Thus, the Yankees have
taken a 2-0 lead in the best-of-five series that will resume Friday
night in Texas, where David Cone will try to finish the sweep,
against the Rangers' Aaron Sele.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie Shane Spencer, a late insertion into Wednesday
night's lineup, hammered a home run and Scott Brosius hit a two-run
shot for the Yankee offense. The bottom third of the Yankees'
lineup has accounted for all five runs in the first two games and
the Rangers, who led the league in hitting, have just 10 hits in
those game.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte often talks to himself on the mound, his catcher Joe
Girardi has said, issuing self-criticisms understood only by
Pettitte himself. On Wednesday night, however, Pettitte seemed only
to be communicating with Girardi's glove; see the glove, hit the
glove.
</P>
<P>
   Before each pitch, Pettitte stood at the top of the mound,
staring at the ground, a moment of mental preparation before
staring in for Girardi's sign. Girardi would signal, and like a
robot, Pettitte would draw his hands in front of him, completely
focused on Girardi's glove.
</P>
<P>
   Then he would throw: sinkers, cutters, curveballs. Pettitte had
a superb curveball, which he threw with great effort, his hand
cocking and then, as he released the pitch with an explosive turn
of his wrist, his whole body seemed to twist.
</P>
<P>
   The first three Texas batters grounded out, Pettitte needing
only eight pitches in the first inning, his confidence growing. The
Rangers went down in order in the second inning, the third, and on.
He retired the first 12 batters before allowing Texas' first hit.
</P>
<P>
   During 32 starts in the regular season, Pettitte never retired
more than 11 batters consecutively. He threw only 44 pitches in the
first four innings on Wednesday night, in direct contrast to the
efficiency of the Rangers' starter, Rick Helling.
</P>
<P>
   Muhummad Ali invented the boxing style known as the Rope-A-Dope.
Lay back, take your opponent's best shots, let him tire himself out
_ and then pounce. The Yankee hitters have been playing rope-a-dope
against opposing starters all season, patiently taking pitches,
waiting out walks, reaching to foul off two-strike fastballs and
breaking balls. Then they pounce.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees performed rope-a-dope to perfection on Wednesday
night against Helling as they quickly wore down the Texas
right-hander. Helling averaged 16.2 pitches an inning during the
regular season, and yet in the first three innings on Wednesday
night, Helling needed 72 pitches; after four innings, he had thrown
91, an average of nearly 23 per inning.
</P>
<P>
   Helling kept trying to pump fastballs over the outside corner
and then spin curveballs low in the strike zone, and the Yankees
kept fouling them off _ 24 foul balls in the first three innings.
Derek Jeter struck out leading off the third inning, but only after
forcing Helling to throw 12 pitches in the at-bat and, incredibly,
after fouling off eight pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The pace was dangerous for the Rangers. Before the series, Texas
Manager Johnny Oates suggested that his starting pitchers had to
last deep into games for the Rangers to win. What he didn't say
directly was that the Rangers possess poor middle relief, and a
seven- or eight-inning outing by the Texas starter was tantamount.
But because Helling threw so many pitches early, the Rangers'
bullpen began working in the fourth inning; twice pitching the
Texas pitching coach Dick Bosman visited the mound seemingly to buy
time for Helling to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, threatening to outlast his alloted 15 minutes of fame,
put the Yankees on the scoreboard in the second inning, smashing a
thigh-high fastball over the left-center field wall, beyond the
399-foot sign. It was Spencer's eighth home run in 28 at-bats,
dating to the last days of the regular season. Spencer returned to
the dugout grinning broadly, but the fans would not let him sit
until he acknowledged their cheers once more. Spencer emerged with
a practiced and exulted wave.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the fourth inning, Spencer skipped a hard
grounder through the middle. Brosius then launched Helling's 79th
pitch of the game beyond the fence in right field, a two-run shot.
</P>
<P>
   After Brosius' home run, Girardi followed with a single,
continuing the rampage of the lower third of the Yankees' order.
That part was responsible for both runs in Game 1, and the Yankees'
first three runs in Game 2, going 6-for-6 in the first four innings
on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, shutout in Game 1, scored their first run of the
series in the fifth inning. Juan Gonzalez pulled a grounder down
the third base line for a double, tagged up and moved to third on a
fly ball and scored on Ivan Rodriguez's line single.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza quickly began warming up in the Yankees' bullpen,
a strong indication that in spite of Torre's confident public
backing of Pettitte, he was prepared to pull Pettitte immediately,
rather than permit the left-hander margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte finished off the fifth by retiring Todd Zeile and
Mike Simms, and struck out three in the sixth inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
