<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAND-CENTRAL-RENOVATION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENOVATED GRAND CENTRAL TO BE REDEDICATED 
</HEADLINE>
  ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The shiny, cavernous spaces of Grand Central Terminal
on Wednesday resembled nothing so much as one of those dazzlingly
choreographed numbers in a '40s musical with a cast of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of hard-hatted workers hammered and painted and
measured and cleaned. An electric flatbed truck rolled by, its horn
honking rhythmically. Tour guides shouted to make themselves heard
over the whine of drills and saws. And all around, commuters,
playing the dual roles of audience and extras, wandered through,
gawking up at the twinkling stars in the jade green sky of the main
concourse ceiling, taking in the intoxicating smell of railing
polish and eventually tearing themselves away to board a train.
</P>
<P>
   The terminal's formal rededication ceremony _ featuring a speech
by the governor, a laser-light show and the premiere of a new work
for wind orchestra and train whistle _ would not take place until
Thursday morning. The ceremony will highlight features like the
restored ceiling, balconies full of restaurants, opened-up vistas,
new underground passages and walkways, and a monumental new east
staircase.
</P>
<P>
   But as the workers scrambled to complete the main phase of a
two-year, $200 million renovation of one of the world's grandest
public spaces, Wednesday was the real show, an impression
reinforced by the photographer in the hard-hat watching Jerry
Barbier lay down his disk grinder after slicing up a big piece of
the wall on the south side of the main hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry, you going to use that tool again?'' the photographer,
documenting the job for one of the construction contractors, asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, you want another shot?'' Barbier said before he duly
sliced into the stone again.
</P>
<P>
   Over in the opposite corner of the main concourse, tourists
posed for photos in front of the enormous brown cast-iron eagle
that had temporarily touched down in front of the entrance to Track
30.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just wonderful,'' said Betty Herrin, who was up from
South Carolina visiting relatives in Westchester. ``I've been
coming up here three or four times a year since 1991 and I never
thought it would look anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rella, a track worker for Metro-North railroad, stood
transfixed before the eagle, which will eventually adorn the Grand
Central Market on the Lexington Avenue side. ``I think it's
awesome,'' he said. ``It's beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Boylan, a deputy executive director of the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority, Metro-North's parent agency
and the owner of the terminal, swept by with several other
busy-looking men in suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be wild tomorrow,'' he said. ``Don't quote me on
that. I mean, it's going to be wildly wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   For some workers, the mammoth renovation has been life-changing.
Barbara Stork, a commercial sculptor and self-described
``finishing-toucher,'' reckons she has become the world's leading
expert on the repair of Caenstone, a corrugated limestone
look-alike made of plaster, marble dust and fiberglass. Caenstone
comes in a thousand delicate shades of beige, tan and eggshell, is
as fragile as it is beautiful, and Grand Central is rife with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've probably done 7 or 8,000 patches,'' she said from atop a
scaffold. ``It's wonderful to have an opportunity to work this long
on something and really master it.''
</P>
<P>
   For other habitues of the station, though, the remodeling has
simply been one long disruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just looking forward to when they open this all back up so
we can buy food,'' Matt Treasure, an engineer on Metro-North's
Harlem River Line, said as he gestured around the lower level,
where the Eclair Bakery, the Fannie Farmer chocolate shop and a
Dunkin' Donuts used to be and where a new food court is still
several months away. ``Two years now we haven't been able to buy a
sandwich in this place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
