<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-EDITOR-PROFILE-NYT     09-30 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-EDITOR-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBITIOUS VOICE OF A PUGNACIOUS WEEKLY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At first glance, Russ Smith does not look as if he
belongs in the Chelsea offices of The New York Press, the
pugnacious, profane weekly newspaper that turned 10 years old this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   The beige offices are ``very Lou Grant,'' Smith says, but they
have unmistakable Lou Reed overtones: the sound of a pounding
guitar drifts from somewhere, piles of books and papers litter the
floors, and young editors meet in well-worn concert T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 43, the newspaper's majority owner and its editor in
chief, wears a pinstriped Paul Stuart suit and shiny gold cuff
links. He could easily be a father who has come up from Wall Street
to take his bohemian daughter to lunch at a place she can't afford.
</P>
<P>
   But then Smith puts his feet up, lights a Merit and launches
into a lazy, obscenity-laced diatribe against the evils of the
establishment. He rails against excessive taxes, government
regulations and powerful media companies that are obsessed with
celebrity culture.
</P>
<P>
   He reminisces about when he was a ``20-year-old drug-taking
hippie,'' says he still supports the legalization of marijuana, and
describes proudly how the police showed up at the newspaper's last
raucous party. Then he talks glowingly about former President
George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   If Smith is an improbable set of walking contradictions, he is
the perfect embodiment of his free newspaper. Founded with the sole
objective of knocking The Village Voice off its alternative
pedestal, The New York Press has long sought to attract readers
mainly by infuriating them with its eclecticism.
</P>
<P>
   Its columnists include Alexander Cockburn, a former Village
Voice writer with a pronounced Marxist viewpoint, and Christopher
Caldwell of The Weekly Standard, the conservative Washington
magazine. Its sex columnist recounts her bedroom encounters in
vivid, sometimes excruciating detail on one page while the next
page features a column on obscure historical facts.
</P>
<P>
   Besides having plowed $3.7 million of his own money into the
paper, Smith also contributes a dyspeptic column called Mugger, in
which he has excoriated everyone from President Clinton to Tina
Brown to waiters at expensive restaurants near the Tribeca loft he
shares with his wife and two young sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want our readers to turn to one column and say, `I just hate
this guy, and I'm never going to read him again,' and then turn to
another one and say, `Man, I love this!''' Smith says. ``I want
that kind of passion.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a kind of passion he believes The Voice no longer
inspires. Growing up in Huntington, N.Y., the youngest of five sons
of a carwash owner, Smith fell in love with journalism reading The
Voice in the late 1960s, and he says he modeled his first weekly
newspapers, in Baltimore and Washington, after it. (He sold those
papers in 1987.)
</P>
<P>
   But now, he says, The Voice has become ossified, full of
``stuck-in-the-70s, left-wing stuff'' and pompous writing. ``What
about the 20-year-old who just wants to hear about the Smashing
Pumpkins' new album,'' he asked, ``and doesn't want a
four-paragraph discourse on Baudelaire or Thomas Carlyle?''
</P>
<P>
   (Donald H. Forst, the editor of The Voice, declined Wednesday to
debate Smith point by point, saying only: ``The man does foam at
the mouth.'')
</P>
<P>
   Smith deftly dodged every question about revenues, profits and
salaries, but he said his paper became profitable two years ago and
was slowly gaining ground on The Voice, which switched to free
distribution in Manhattan only in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, The Press expanded from tabloid size to include a
full-size front section that is wrapped around the tabloid. When it
started in 1988, Smith said, it had five full-time employees and
published 24 pages a week. It now employs 55 people, 10 of them on
the editorial side and the rest in sales and management, and its
most recent issue was 120 pages. Every Tuesday, it distributes
110,000 copies, a little less than half of The Voice's circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Its rivalry with The Voice provides a glimpse into what remains
of the great city newspaper wars of yesteryear. Far from trying to
scoop The Voice on news, The Press has avoided conventional
reporting, Smith said. Its boldest competitive move so far came
about six weeks ago, when Smith dispatched an editor and a cartoon
artist to sneak into a picnic for The Voice's staff and write about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath The Press' masthead, the paper bills itself modestly as
``New York's Free Weekly Newspaper,'' facts that are all true but
that make no grand promises about what is inside. And despite
Smith's criticisms of The Voice as moribund, he does not enumerate
any high journalistic goals for The Press, except that it remain
interesting and its opinions honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being free is very liberating,'' he said. ``We know why people
pick up our paper. It's for the listings. It's for the classifieds.
It's for the adult ads. It's for the astrology column. And for some
people, it's for the actual stories. Because of that, as
journalists, we can print anything we want.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not presumptuous enough to think that I can force The
Voice out of business,'' he said. ``I just want to be the No. 1
paper, and in many ways right now, I guess, we are still the No. 2
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused and then added defiantly, ``Of course, in many ways I
think we're the No. 1 paper.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
