<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: BOOKER PRIZE SHORT LIST; OLD THEATER, NEW LIFE;
AWARD FOR ROBERT WILSON; TAKEMITSU RETROSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Great Britain)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The countdown to the Booker Prize, Britain's top literary award,
is on. A short list of six has been winnowed from 125 novels
entered in the competition, which brings the winner some $34,000.
The finalists are ``Master Georgie'' by Beryl Bainbridge, ``The
Restraint of Beasts'' by Magnus Mills, ``The Industry of Souls'' by
Martin Booth, ``England, England'' by Julian Barnes, ``Amsterdam''
by Ian McEwan and ``Breakfast on Pluto'' by Patrick McCabe. A
five-judge panel will choose a winner on Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Rescued
</P>
<P>
   With civic ceremonies and a new musical, yet another old movie
palace spared from dusty death by wrecker's ball begins a new life
Friday in Cleveland. There, the 77-year-old Allen Theater, restored
at a cost of $15 million, will become the last of four contiguous
vaudeville and movie theaters to be renewed in the historic
Playhouse Square Center. The completion of the 2,500-seat Allen
makes the 9,500-seat complex the largest performing arts center in
the United States except for Lincoln Center, and the world's
largest finished theater restoration project, Playhouse Square
Center says.
</P>
<P>
   The Allen, intended primarily for touring Broadway musicals, is
expected to draw 300,000 patrons and inject $30 million a year into
the local economy. A weekend-long celebration begins with a
ribbon-cutting and marquee-unveiling by Mayor Michael White and
other dignitaries. On Tuesday the curtain goes up on the national
premiere of the touring biographical musical ``Jolson.''
</P>
<P>
   Acclaim
</P>
<P>
   The avant-garde theater artist and designer Robert Wilson, whose
works include ``Einstein on the Beach'' and ``The Civil Wars,'' is
to receive the 1998 Harvard Excellence in Design Award from the
Harvard Design School next Thursday in Cambridge, Mass. From Monday
through Oct. 29, the school will present ``Theater of Drawing,'' an
exhibition exploring the role of drawing in Wilson's work from 1969
to 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Homage
</P>
<P>
   ``Spirit Garden,'' the first British retrospective of the music
of the prolific Japanese composer Toru Takemitsu since his death at
65 in 1996, will begin at the Royal Festival Hall in London Friday
when Andrew Davis leads the BBC Symphony Orchestra and Chorus in
works by Takemitsu and Ravel.
</P>
<P>
   With performances by the Philharmonia Orchestra, the London
Sinfonietta and the visiting Reigakusha Gagaku Ensemble, including
three British premieres, the festival, running through Oct. 28,
brings together artists associated with the composer and his music
in his lifetime. They include the guitarist Julian Bream, the
pianists Paul Crossley and Peter Serkin, the violist Nobuko Imai
and the event's artistic director, Oliver Knussen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
