<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-PETTITTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: PETTITTE'S FATHER TURNS DEAF EAR TO THE CRITICS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tom Pettitte punched the clock at 6 p.m. to work a
12-hour shift at Lubrizol Chemical Plant in Deer Park, Texas,
Wednesday night, about two hours before his son, Andy, threw his
first pitch to Mark McLemore. The elder Pettitte did not request
the night off to travel to the Bronx, he did not have access to a
radio, and there is no television at the plant. That is the way the
father wanted it. No baseball. No problems.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, this sounded bizarre. How could a father not want to
see his son pitch the second game of the American League division
series? How could he miss being inside Yankee Stadium with the son
who first flipped a baseball to him 18 years ago? How could he
concentrate on mixing additives for motor oil when his son was on
baseball's grandest stage?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Pettitte insisted that it was easy to ignore. Any father
would understand, he contended. The thrill of watching his
26-year-old son pitch for the Yankees is bathed in bitterness. He
bristles over every negative word about Andy, so he stopped placing
himself where he could see the criticism. Tom went to the plant and
his wife, Joann, went to church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun listening to people beat up on your kid,'' Tom
Pettitte said. ``I have always been more critical of Andy than any
New York fan or New York media, but he's my kid. I can do that. To
hear other people ripping your kid hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a trying and perplexing season for Pettitte, who
went 16-11 with a 4.24 ERA and was considered disappointing. That
bothers his father. Still, Pettitte made $3.75 million this season,
and part of the responsibility of a major leaguer is to handle the
criticism. But listening to a father lament how painful it is to
watch a game that should be enjoyable made me think about
Pettitte's situation again. Was too much expected of him because he
won more games than any other American Leaguer in 1996 and 1997?
Maybe. But Pettitte set a lofty standard. Now he is judged by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if he's making $100 million a year, it still
hurts,'' his father said. ``When you go to the playground and
someone knocks your kid over, you don't like it. It's always going
to hurt. Ask any parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Tom Pettitte being too dramatic and too sensitive? Probably.
Andy Pettitte has been criticized this season, but some of it has
been deserved and he is not a pariah. But a father hears things
differently, and a father knows more than any fan or reporter. The
folks who litter the radio talk shows with anger look at ERA. Tom
Pettitte remembers ICU and Andy's son, Jared, who struggled after
he was born last May 28. Try pitching through that, is what Tom
Pettitte wanted to scream.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a nurse is running to the ICU with your grandson because
he can't breathe and he's blue from his neck up and your son is
crying and running behind them and you're running behind him, well,
a lot of things happened with Andy,'' Tom Pettitte said. ``I'm not
making excuses. It's been frustrating because we haven't been able
to figure this out.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tom Pettitte does not watch the games live, he tapes
them and studies them. He has spoken to his son and to Mel
Stottlemyre, the Yankee pitching coach, about what might have gone
awry as Andy, a left-hander, went 3-5 with a 6.14 ERA in August and
September. They dismissed the notion of tipping off pitches,
although Tom said he knows when Andy uncorks one specific pitch.
They acknowledged that Andy, who has been plunked with three batted
balls, sometimes flinches on the mound and that can hurt his
pitches. They discounted the theory that his pitches had lost
velocity. But they admitted that Andy longs to be perfect. It
seemed as if he did not know how to react when he was imperfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's satisfied unless he pitches a perfect
game,'' Yankee Manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Pettitte has witnessed that intensity since Andy was 5 years
old and wept for hours after losing a peewee football game. Tom
indicated that Andy put extra pressure on himself this season
because he had received his first major contract and because there
was uncertainty about David Cone's surgically repaired right
shoulder. Perhaps Pettitte, thinking he had to be an ace, tried to
be better than perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's one of my flaws, but it's the way I've pitched my
whole career,'' Andy Pettitte said. ``It's something I deal with
and try not to get down on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   While Tom's co-workers badgered him for not being at the stadium
Wednesday night, he occasionally called family members for an
update. That was as close as he planned to get to his son's game
and, actually, as close as he expected to get to the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we make it to the World Series, I don't think I'm
going,'' Tom Pettitte said. ``I just don't want to be around it. I
don't want to go through it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The father should purchase earplugs and change his mind. Any
father will tell him how precious these moments are.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2340EDT &QL; 
