<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-TOURGUIDE-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOMELESS TOUR GUIDE'S OFFBEAT CITY VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Drawing notice in Greenwich Village's Washington
Square Park is no easy feat, but as Timothy Levitch ambled through
it Monday afternoon, eyes turned, brows furrowed and one or two
jaws summarily dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was his outfit, distinguished by burgundy velvet
pants that billowed like a skirt, and a gargantuan,
rhinestone-spangled hat that looked like a souvenir from Alice's
sojourn in Wonderland. More likely it was his oration, the
effervescent likes of which are seldom heard on either side of the
looking glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pigeons!'' Levitch exulted, as if the winged scavengers on the
path before him were uncommon finds. ``Pigeons are what many New
Yorkers become in the next incarnation. They are trying to teach us
something. I don't know what.''
</P>
<P>
   Passing a dog run, he fondly pronounced it a ``community of
saliva'' inhabited by ``emissaries of drool.'' Levitch was treating
a reporter to his personal take on the wondrous island of
Manhattan, cradle to so many eccentrics like him. But his
exuberantly articulated vision was more than just another oddball
perspective; it was the warped window through which thousands of
visitors over the last seven years have first glimpsed New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Levitch, 28, may well be the most unorthodox, unusual tour guide
the city has ever spawned, a distinction confirmed by the upcoming
release of a feature-length documentary that focuses exclusively on
him and principally on his long stint as an employee atop
double-decker buses.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, ``The Cruise,'' is scheduled to open on Oct. 23 at
the Angelika Film Center in the Village. For a documentary to get a
commercial theatrical release is atypical _ an immediate badge of
success _ but ``The Cruise'' has also attracted sizable audiences
and garnered extremely positive reviews at the screenings and film
festivals where it has been shown in the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   And it has already begun to turn Levitch into something of a
demi-celebrity and cult figure _ for the next 15 minutes, at least
_ with friends in the movie industry, a literary agent and a
budding business in privately arranged walking tours. He quit the
double-decker scene a year ago but still takes small groups around
Manhattan on foot.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if they can find him. He has not had a permanent
residence since 1992, relying instead on the hospitality of friends
to support a mode of living he refers to as ``couch surfing.'' It
prompts him to evaluate new acquaintances in idiosyncratic ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got a great couch,'' he said approvingly of the actress
Natasha Lyonne, the 19-year-old star of the recently released movie
``Slums of Beverly Hills.'' She saw ``The Cruise'' at an advance
screening and befriended Levitch.
</P>
<P>
   For one busload of tittering tourists in the movie, he warbles
an unsteady version of the pop standard ``But Not for Me'' as a
build-up to pointing out where the song's composer, George
Gershwin, once lived.
</P>
<P>
   And he frequently grows philosophical, as when he surveys the
pricey boutiques lining Madison Avenue and tells another group of
tourists, ``This is ludicrousness and this cannot last.'' Then,
without missing a beat, he adds, ``The new Ann Taylor store is on
the right.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is done in a nasal voice somewhat like that of the
exercise guru Richard Simmons and with an eclectic, tattered
wardrobe that's more thrift-store accident than grunge chic. As for
grooming, well, it's hard to keep up when, every once in a while,
you bed down on a bench in front of Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   The one time that Levitch's supervisor at Gray Line tours
reprimanded him, it was for his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his hairbrush had made contact with his hair, it had to be
by metaphysics,'' the supervisor, Lee Gelber, recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But Gelber said that Levitch drew many more raves than
complaints from customers, who often heard about Levitch from other
tourists and made a point of getting on a bus with him. Gelber said
that drivers would also ask for Levitch, because it usually meant
bigger tips.
</P>
<P>
   But not from everyone. Levitch recalled a man from Oklahoma who
insisted that Levitch had spoken a gibberish unrelated to English
and demanded his money back. ``There was an infinity of
reactions,'' Levitch said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Levitch grew up in a middle-class Jewish family of five in
Riverdale, the Bronx, and attended Horace Mann, a respected private
school. He said his fanciful, flamboyant musings emerged in
adolescence as a response to his status as ``a wallflower in the
darkened corners of the cafeteria, acne-infested.'' His
subsequently manic demeanor earned him a nickname, Speed, which he
still goes by.
</P>
<P>
   While his older brother headed to Yale University and a State
Department job, Levitch sought a more bohemian milieu as a
dramatic-writing major at New York University, from which he
graduated in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   That summer, he perused the Michelin guide to New York, aced the
exam to get a license as a tour guide and went to work for Big
Apple tours.
</P>
<P>
   Levitch moved in 1994 to Gray Line for a pay raise to $9 an hour
from $7. Around the same time, Bennett Miller, an aspiring
filmmaker whose younger brother had gone to Horace Mann with
Levitch, caught up with Levitch at a party. The idea for a
documentary was born.
</P>
<P>
   And Levitch found yet another occasional sleepover host. ``If
you invite him to stay at your place,'' Miller cautioned, ``you'll
probably notice a missing shirt or belt the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitch seems to have perfected the rare art of voluntary
homelessness, his attempt to remain unencumbered by rent or other
domestic responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves some items of clothing at a variety of friends'
apartments and carries others, along with toiletries and
spiral-ring journals, in a small suitcase with wheels that he often
stows for the day with bellhops at any of a variety of hotels that
simply assume he is staying there.
</P>
<P>
   But Levitch is not without troubles. As ``The Cruise'' vaguely
signals, he was arrested in 1996 and spent several days in jail.
Levitch would not discuss the incident, saying he was abiding by
the wishes of the movie's makers, but criminal records show that he
was charged with assault for violently shoving a female friend who
did not share his interest in a romantic relationship. Levitch
pleaded guilty to a reduced charge of second-degree harassment and
was sentenced to 10 days of community service.
</P>
<P>
   Gelber said the incident had nothing to do with Levitch's
departure from Gray Line, which, he said, was Levitch's own
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Levitch said the repetition inherent in the job was driving him
crazy. In the movie, he also makes clear that he didn't like being
asked to adhere to a dress code.
</P>
<P>
   But his career as a guide survived. Over the last year, as ``The
Cruise'' was screened for private audiences, Levitch began to build
a business of walking tours for small groups that sought his
services.
</P>
<P>
   He is also working with an agent on a proposal for a special
guidebook about New York, and he has been promised 5 percent of any
net profits from ``The Cruise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My entertainment lawyer said that 5 percent of the net of a
documentary is like having 5 percent of an illusion,'' Levitch
said. ``Then he reminded me that he has 10 percent of my
illusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980930.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3299 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORGAN-DRAWINGS-2TAKE     09-30 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-DRAWINGS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHERINE, ALSO GREAT AS A COLLECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN RUSSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Master Drawings From the Hermitage and Pushkin
Museums,'' at the Pierpont Morgan Library, could not fail to be a
remarkable exhibition. The collections now in the Hermitage in St.
Petersburg, Russia, were initiated by Catherine the Great in ways,
and on a scale, that could not be paralleled today. They were
powered by greed and impatience on the one hand and by dexterous
networking on the other.
</P>
<P>
   It was not in Catherine's nature to buy drawings in ones and
twos. She wanted a great museum, the way Peter the Great had wanted
a great capital city. The deadline, in both cases, was tomorrow,
and both of them succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine began buying for her museum in 1764. By 1769 she had
bought two of the greatest collections of drawings in Western
Europe. One of them belonged to Count Cobenzl, then living in
Brussels, who was minister plenipotentiary to Empress Maria Theresa
of Austria and a leading figure in the administration of what was
then the Austrian Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   With this single stroke, Catherine the Great acquired more than
4,000 master drawings by Western European artists. Sheets from the
Cobenzl collection in the present show include examples of Poussin,
Rubens, van Dyck, Primaticcio, Hans Holbein the Elder, Jacob
Jordaens, Hendrick Goltzius, Guercino and Greuze. Every one of them
is a touchstone of quality. In the Poussin ``Baptism'' _ a sketch
for the painting of that name that is a part of Poussin's ``Seven
Sacraments'' _ rigor and awe work as equal partners.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine went on to buy 1,020 drawings from the collection of
Count Heinrich Bruehl, who was at the time a minister at the court
of Saxony in Dresden. Virtually on her own doorstep she also
acquired the drawings _ almost 2,000 _ that had been collected by
Count Butskoy, the president of the Imperial Academy of Fine Arts
in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   That Butskoy bought with teaching in mind is made clear by the
presence in the Morgan Library of the ``Allegory of the 12 Years'
Truce,'' by Hendrick de Clerck. The truce in question ended a
grueling civil war between Flanders and the Netherlands and ushered
in a period in which the great port of Antwerp reopened, normal
trading resumed and the economy flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Students in the Imperial Academy could learn a whole alphabet of
celebration from this drawing. The rulers of Flanders come floating
down from heaven with olive branches in hand. To the left, 10 young
women, each armed with sword and shield, personify the Catholic
provinces of Flanders.
</P>
<P>
   To the right, seven other young women, each in full combat rig,
personify the Protestant provinces of the Netherlands. In the
distance, a flotilla of warships reminds us that, not long before
the picture was drawn, the Dutch navy had blockaded Antwerp.
Jubilation reigns, and in the foreground Belgium itself is
personified as a seated figure who raises her eyes as if to say,
``Thank Heaven that's over!'' Is all this warfare in fancy dress?
Yes, but history lessons do not come prettier than this one.
</P>
<P>
   The show also includes three drawings by Greuze that came from
the Butskoy collection. One of them _ of a young woman sitting at
ease in a chair _ is the very image of well-being touched in with
throwaway panache.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful beginning, therefore. We can imagine Catherine the
Great's meaty arms as she reached for her favorite drawings while
leaving hundreds of others unopened in their crates.
</P>
<P>
   In the matter of a major museum, Moscow for a long time lagged
behind St. Petersburg. It never had either the virtually unlimited
money or the single-minded, centralized focus that powered the
Hermitage. The first museum of art in Moscow did not possess any
drawings until 1873. The Pushkin Museum did not get its present
name until 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Examples That Hold Their Own
</P>
<P>
   But there had been true collectors in Moscow _ noblemen,
merchants, lawyers, professional soldiers, perfumers and a
discerning printer _ who bought very good drawings that finally
ended up in the Pushkin Museum. It is represented at the Morgan
Library by examples of the work of Carpaccio, Rubens, Guido Reni,
Parmigianino and Caspar David Friedrich that amply hold their own
with the loans from the Hermitage.
</P>
<P>
   It was thanks to the Russian poet Vasily Zhukovsky that the
future Emperor Nicholas I of Russia and his German-born wife had
visited Friedrich in his studio in Dresden in 1820. The magical
unflinching strangeness of Friedrich's vision is wonderfully borne
out in his ``Coffin on a Grave,'' from the Pushkin.
</P>
<P>
   After the October Revolution in 1917, it took quite some time
for the priorities of the Moscow museum world to sort themselves
out. This was a sensitive matter, in that it had been in Moscow,
and not in St. Petersburg, that the finest Western European art of
the late 19th and early 20th centuries was collected.
</P>
<P>
   Much credit for that went, then as now, to the Moscow collectors
Sergei Shchukin and Mikhail Morozov. In his dealings with Henri
Matisse between 1908 and 1913, Shchukin had shown a daring and a
prescience unrivaled by other collectors. Morozov, though less
audacious, had a sensitivity all his own. (He cut a wide swath,
moreover. It was he who bought the monumental Daumier drawing
``Camille Desmoulins in the Palais Royal.'' This brings a glorious
physicality to the moment on July 12, 1789, when Desmoulins caled
the citizens of Paris to arms _ a call that would result in the
storming of the Bastille.)
</P>
<P>
   As to what would be done about the works of Cezanne, van Gogh,
Gauguin, the Douanier Rousseau, Matisse, Picasso and Bonnard and
others in Moscow after the Revolution of 1917, opinion was divided.
To the Soviet hard-liners, and to some of the soft-liners as well,
they presented a dangerous encumbrance. Which side were they on,
after all?
</P>
<P>
   As to where they should go, hesitation was yearlong. To put them
in major metropolitan museums would give them a standing that might
sap the visitors' moral fiber and undermine the official cult of
socialist realism. Stalin was said at one time to favor the widest
possible dispersal, the better to limit their possible effect.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   From One Museum to Two Others
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they were gathered together in Moscow in the State
Museum of Modern Western Art, in which they enjoyed a conditional
liberty. But in 1948 that museum was done away with, and its
contents were divided between the Hermitage and the Pushkin Museum.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, the present show, which runs through Jan. 10,
is not a parade of old-master drawings that quietly peters out. On
the contrary, it ends by turning an important corner in the history
of art. There is, for instance, the watercolor sketch of four
bathers by a river that Matisse sent to Shchukin in March 1909.
</P>
<P>
   Matisse had hoped that the sketch would persuade Shchukin to
commission a third large panel to go with the two _ ``Dance'' and
``Music'' _ that he had already acquired for the staircase in his
house in Moscow. Shchukin said ``no'' to that, but Matisse
nonetheless went ahead with the full-scale ``Bathers by a River.''
Worked and reworked, the huge canvas was finally completed in the
fall of 1916 and is now in the Art Institute of Chicago. Lent by
the Pushkin, and never before seen in the United States, the tender
and lyrical initial sketch is an important document in the career
of Matisse.
</P>
<P>
   The show ends with another Pushkin loan _ the celebrated
``Trans-Siberian Express,'' in which a Swiss-born French poet,
Blaise Cendrars, collaborated with a Russian-born painter, Sonia
Delaunay, in 1913.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by a journey by train from Moscow to Harbin, the poem
comes in free-form fragments of varying length. Delaunay decided to
merge the text with images devised by herself. ``Simultaneous
contrast'' was her name for the result, which was folded lengthwise
and crosswise and published in book form.
</P>
<P>
   As the book, when opened, is 6{ feet long, it is never easy to
display. But it takes the Morgan's visitors out of the world of the
formally framed drawing and drags them, feet first, into the 20th
century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
