<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PENTAGON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE INSATIABLE PENTAGON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Oct. 1:
</P>
<P>
   The nation's top military commanders and Senate Republicans
engaged in a surreal argument this week over whether the Pentagon
has enough money to keep American forces and weapons ready for
combat. The senators complained that the generals had soft-pedaled
an erosion in readiness, while the commanders maintained that
Congress had diverted money to marginal military programs that
benefited the home districts of Republican leaders. Lost in the
noise was any recognition that an annual Pentagon budget of $271
billion should be more than sufficient to keep American forces in
fighting trim, provided it is spent in rational ways.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years after the collapse of the Soviet Union it is
dispiriting to find the Pentagon asserting that it needs ever
larger budgets to insure that American forces can quickly and
effectively deal with potential threats like Iraq and peacekeeping
assignments like the one in Bosnia. The reason is that despite
substantial reductions in forces and all manner of strategic
reviews, the Pentagon has never figured out how to allocate money
where it is really needed or to reduce waste and duplication,
especially in the development and production of expensive new
weapons systems. The hyperbolic expectation that the United States
should be able to fight two regional wars simultaneously is used to
justify an Army of nearly half a million active-duty troops and a
Navy with 12 aircraft carriers, only one less than the Cold War
fleet had in service.
</P>
<P>
   With each of the services shielding pet projects, the cost of
advanced weapons rising and Congress unwilling to close obsolete
bases, it is little wonder that there may not be enough money left
to keep military salaries competitive or to retain an adequate
number of combat pilots. Instead of asking for more money, a
request that a politically weakened White House is afraid to
reject, the Pentagon should make some hard decisions about how to
use the billions it already has. The Army can do with fewer new
tanks, the Air Force can live without dozens of additional
warplanes and the Navy faces no threat that requires production of
new submarines. The notion of adding an extra $20 billion a year to
the budget to recruit and retain troops and to replace equipment,
among other things, is insulting to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders compound the problem when they insist that
scarce dollars go to defense contractors in their districts. Newt
Gingrich, for example, has championed the production of C-130
transport planes that are manufactured by Lockheed in his Georgia
district. In the past three years the Pentagon spent $1 billion for
20 of the planes, even though the Air Force did not ask for them.
No citizen wishes to deny the Pentagon the money it needs to defend
the country, but Americans have not issued the military a blank
check.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
