</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-SPENCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTING SPENCER WAS A RISK WORTH TAKING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The slightly risky decision for Joe Torre before the
division series was whether to start Shane Spencer in left field.
Placing a 26-year-old rookie in the lineup could have put both
Spencer and Torre in jeopardy if a ball was mishandled in left
field. Still, despite what Chad Curtis accomplished in helping the
Yankees win Game 1 against the Texas Rangers on Tuesday night, it
would have been the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Torre got it right and started Spencer in left in
Game 2. The fans were pleased because their newest folk hero
managed to get three at-bats, three chances to continue his
imitation of Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said that one reason he chose Spencer over Tim Raines in
left field Tuesday night was that he did not want the 39-year-old
Raines to aggravate an already sore left knee. Sure. It was a
polite gesture toward Raines, but Torre obviously wanted Spencer in
the pivotal game for his power. There was no need to camouflage it,
no need to disguise the reason for making a smart decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in a pretty good groove,'' Torre said. ``Hopefully,
there's something left.''
</P>
<P>
   There was. The wisdom of starting Spencer became evident when he
pounded Rick Helling's 2-2 fastball into the Yankee bullpen in the
second inning.
</P>
<P>
   If a fan had his eyes closed when Spencer swung, he would have
been thinking homer. The ball clashing with the bat had that
crushing, explosive sound. It was loud and long and it was,
amazingly, typical of Spencer's September to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's ninth homer of the month put the Yankees ahead, 1-0,
and was the first time in the game that their patience and
persistence against Helling paid off on the scoreboard. The Yanks
made the 20-game winner toil by taking pitches and fouling off
pitches until they saw ones they liked. The fastball Spencer saw
was chest-high and sliced through the middle of the plate, akin to
putting the ball on a batting tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm just enjoying myself and having the time of my
life,'' Spencer said before the game. ``I got a chance to play and
opened some eyes and here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The risk, however slight it was, no longer exists. It is time
for Torre to stop being diplomatic and to start Spencer in left for
the remainder of the series and even for the rest of the
post-season. It is impossible to leave a player who has 8 home runs
in his last 30 at-bats in the dugout. If Spencer's hitting were an
aberration, opposing pitchers would have figured him out by now.
They have not, so Torre should jump on Spencer's broad back and
ride him. Spencer is very patient at the plate and is not lunging
at the breaking pitches that pitches dangle down and away. This is
not a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way he carries himself,'' Torre has said. ``He has
a presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer started another rally in the fourth inning, when he
slapped an 0-1 pitch to center for a one-out single. Scott Brosius
followed the home run kid by slapping a two-run shot to right field
to give Andy Pettitte a 3-0 lead. With Spencer hitting seventh and
Brosius hitting eighth, the Yankees are even more formidable than
usual. In fact, the bottom third of New York's order, which
included Joe Girardi batting ninth, was 6 for 6 off Helling in the
first four innings.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason for not starting Spencer would be defense, and
he showed that he is not a statue in the outfield. When Juan
Gonzalez ripped a ball off the left-field stands, Spencer scooted
over to play the carom and fired a one-bounce bullet to second. If
Chuck Knoblauch had caught the ball cleanly, Gonzalez would have
been out. Instead, Knoblauch bobbled it in his glove and Gonzalez's
right foot jarred it loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has pretty much done everything you like to see from a
young player,'' Torre said. ``He's not a graceful outfielder, but
he's aggressive and he does the job very well both in left and in
right.''
</P>
<P>
   When Spencer was recalled from Class AAA Columbus around 11 p.m.
on Aug. 31, he became eligible to be on the post-season roster with
an hour to spare. Spencer, who did not even understand the
implications of the roster move until reporters explained it to
him, figured then that he should call home to let his family know
he might be on the Yankees in October. There was no need to phone
anyone Tuesday night. Spencer should be here and in the starting
lineup to stay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
