<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-JEWS-HOLIDAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THREE BUSY WEEKS OF SHOPPING AND PRAYING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONSEY, N.Y. _ For many Jews, the High Holy Days mean two trips
to temple, one each for Rosh Hashana and Yom Kippur, and then the
welcome suspension of alternate-side parking rules for other holy
days they do not celebrate and can hardly pronounce.
</P>
<P>
   But in this enclave of Orthodox and Hasidic Jews in Rockland
County, this is a time of great vitality, both spiritually and
commercially, that continues through Sukkot and Simhat Torah. For
more than three weeks, from the first to the 23rd day of Tishri on
the Hebrew calendar, or Oct. 13, stores and synagogues are full to
bursting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running on adrenaline,'' said Tuvia Rotberg, shirt hanging
from his trousers and yarmulke askew as he helped customers at
Tuvia's, which bills itself as the One Stop Shop for All Your
Judaica Needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone needs something new for the New Year,'' said Esther
Blau, owner of Esti's World of Fashion, who scours hundreds of
collections looking for the few ensembles suited for the religious
woman, who is forbidden to show legs, arms or cleavage. ``This time
of year, it's a fashion show.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowds line up at Mrs. Frank's bakery for round loaves of hallah
warm from the oven. Then it's on to the silversmith for a new honey
dish, or perhaps an esrog box to hold the gnarly citron that is
part of the Sukkot ritual. All these stores are dimly lighted and
stacked to the ceiling with merchandise, like a memory of the Lower
East Side in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Buses make regular passage between Monsey and the Orthodox and
Hasidic sections of the Bronx and Brooklyn in New York City. In
those urban centers, the sights and sounds of ancient religion are
part of the weave of life. But here, in the land of raised ranch
houses and sport utility vehicles, these unassimilated habits are
exotic, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   The Sukkot citrons, or esrogen, are imported from Israel and
cradled in skeins of raw flax. At Tuvia's, men in long black coats,
high hats and side curls line up to inspect the fruit, which sell
for about $45. The most prized are unblemished, with a slight
indentation around the middle. Still, the price brought a gasp from
a Central American laborer. ``For a lemon?'' he blurted.
</P>
<P>
   Other supplies for the harvest festival, like panels for
building the sukkot or outdoor eating huts, are sold at seasonal
stands that spring up like pumpkin patches. A billboard points
customers to the ``Esrogen Center, Next to Bubba's Bagels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Christmas season,'' said Rotberg, who sells tinsel
to decorate the sukkot, which are roofed with branches and open to
the stars. ``There is great warmth and everybody gets into it.''
</P>
<P>
   As Esti's World of Fashion, some wealthy women buy entire new
wardrobes for a holiday trip to Israel. The selections are all
demure. Sometimes that forces Mrs. Blau, the owner, to find extra
fabric and make a dickey to fill a neckline that only the Orthodox
would consider plunging.
</P>
<P>
   Even among these ultra-observant Jews, there are distinct
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Hasidim turn out in the days before Yom Kippur to buy a
live chicken and swing it around their heads like a lariat. The
ritual, known as shlogn kapores, is a vicarious atonement,
accompanied by a prayer that says, ``This chicken shall meet death,
but I shall find a long life of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monsey this week, Hasidim gathered in a parking lot to buy a
chicken for $10 off a truck, swing the shrieking bird by its wings
and then watch as it was slaughtered for donation to the poor. The
stench was suffocating and the air a blizzard of chicken feathers.
</P>
<P>
   On every corner, so it seems, a large house is being torn down
to build one even larger, roomy enough for a family with 12 or more
children. The little ones ride in double or triple strollers that
clog intersections and doorways. There are dozens of new Hasidic
shuls and yeshivas, some of which bar children who live in homes
with television sets.
</P>
<P>
   At the edge of one Hasidic neighborhood, gates are lowered at
sunset on Friday to keep the uninitiated from driving through on
the Sabbath. Yiddish is the primary language. Even in the heat of
summer, men and women dress in dark colors and fabrics heavy as
drapery.
</P>
<P>
   But secular life intrudes. There is a technology store called
Kosher Komputer. Delicatessens stock Mayim Chaim beverages, in the
same rainbow of flavors as Snapple. Tuvia's sells Orthodox rap
music.
</P>
<P>
   Even a tiny minority gets into the act. The sign at the Monsey
Christian Reformed Church offers the traditional blessing
``L'Shannah Tovah Tikatevu,'' or ``May You Be Inscribed for a Good
Year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
