<HEADLINE>
BROSIUS PRODUCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Yankees acquired third baseman Scott Brosius
from the Oakland Athletics for Kenny Rogers before the season, they
didn't know what kind of player they were getting.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius hit a career-high .304 for the Athletics in 1996, then
slumped to .203 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``You
look at '96 and '97, and those were two different years.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius rebounded in a big way, batting .300 this year as the
Yankees' primary No. 9 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to find out he's a good bat-control guy,'' Torre said.
``When you get that kind of production out of the bottom of your
lineup, it's pretty incredible. It keeps from having a soft spot in
the lineup.'' Yankees impress Melvin Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin said it's no fluke the Yankees won an American League-record
114 games in the regular season and beat his team in the first game
of the playoffs Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that impresses me the most is they have a lineup
that very seldom swings at bad pitches,'' he said. ``They make you
work to get them out. There are no easy outs. You can't go out
there and get two guys out and think you can relax for a third of
an inning. You have to stay focused for the entire 27 outs. Any
pitcher that faces the Yankees lineup, you're not only physically
tired at the end, if you're going to be beat them, you're going to
be mentally tired, too.'' Going to the Wells Yankees starter David
Wells threw 135 pitches, a high figure, in pitching eight shutout
innings in Game 1. However, Torre said Wells should have no
problems coming back Sunday if the series goes to five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we have done over the last 21/2 weeks or so is
we have cut back on pitch counts for everybody,'' Torre said. ``We
hope that we saved something. We sort of planned for this. I think
he'll be fine.'' Catching platoon Joe Girardi replaced Jorge Posada
as the Yankees' catcher for Andy Pettitte's start last night.
Girardi catches Pettitte and David Cone, the scheduled Game 3
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Posada will catch the rest of the series if it goes beyond three
games. He's the catcher for Game 4 starter Orlando Hernandez and
Wells. Briefly How confident are the Yankees in advancing a couple
of rounds in the playoffs? Their pitchers are taking batting
practice, a skill that won't be needed until the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees trotted out a couple of old favorites for the
pregame festivities. Robert Merrill sang the national anthem, and
Hall of Fame shortstop Phil Rizzuto threw out the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Game 1 crowd of 57,362 was the second largest at Yankee
Stadium since it was remodeled 23 years ago. The biggest was 57,398
for Game 1 of the 1997 Division Series against the Cleveland
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The shutout in Game 1 was the first for the Yankees in the
postseason since Game 5 of the 1996 World Series in Atlanta by
Pettitte and the first at Yankee Stadium since the Los Angeles
Dodgers' Tommy John did it in Game 2 of the 1981 World Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
