<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKS USE THEIR HOME ADVANTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 114 victories don't count anymore, but they did
one thing for the New York Yankees _ they guaranteed that the extra
game in the league playoffs, if needed, would take place in front
of the most demonstrative fans in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   In typical New York self-involvement, the fans like to believe
how important they are. They like to think they cause outfielders
to stumble and umpires' arms to jerk into a called-strike
punch-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those fans in right field are crazy,'' said Shane Spencer, the
instant idol, who whacked yet another home run in the Yankees' 3-1
victory over the Texas Rangers in Game 2 on Wednesday night.
``Thank God I'm doing good.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer was starting against a right-hander, Rick Helling, a
task that Darryl Strawberry might have had except that Strawberry
is undergoing tests for worrisome intestinal problems. The Yanks
are concerned about Straw. (``Sure, cancer always comes to mind,''
admitted Joe Torre, the manager.)
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime there are the fans, and there is Spencer. He
also singled and scored a run, after taking a curtain call against
his own modest instincts, to please the crowd, which has been
treating him like a reincarnation of Mickey Mantle. If they demand
a curtain call, you'd better pop out of the dugout, arms waving.
You want to keep these people happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get two strikes, you hear them cheering, you want to
please them,'' said David Wells, who won the first game Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Ballplayers perform in front of huge crowds, at home and on the
road, and tend to be blase about it during the season, but they
seemed legitimately affected by the rumbling visceral power in the
stands Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius, the third baseman, who hit a two-run homer on
Wednesday night, played for the world champion Minnesota Twins in
1991, in the Metrodome, a dismal fabric bubble that holds the noise
quite well. He said, ``The dome is loud, but you just don't see
fans in other places standing up with two strikes on every
batter.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius called the Yankee Stadium fans ``the best in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the most knowledgeable,'' he said. ``They understand
things like moving the runners over. They're not just looking for
the home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius said that before he sent his home run soaring toward
what is left of the hard-core Bleacher Creatures in right field.
The fanatics have been scattered by ticket-sale policies, but in
this town it is hard to tell the zealots from the enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee fans seem to have cleaned up their act a bit after
the ugliness of throwing batteries and other lethal objects from
the right-field stands in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   This year the Yankees played all season for the right to play in
front of these fans in the extra game in the first two rounds of
the league playoffs. The three other major sports in North America
_ football, hockey and basketball _ all give a home-field advantage
in every round to the teams with the best records, an incentive to
play hard all season.
</P>
<P>
   However, in baseball, the extra home game used to rotate among
divisions. When baseball expanded its playoffs to include a
wild-card team in 1995, it became apparent that a team could have
the best record in its league, play two home games and then go on
the road for three games and never be heard of again. There was no
reward for a year of good work.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the team with the best record has the extra home game
in the division and league championship series. And by the luck of
the draw, the American League has the extra home game in the World
Series this year.
</P>
<P>
   But first, a team will have to survive this short series, which
frightens Torre, who said: ``You play 162 games, and now you're
faced with 5. I'd rather have seven. Seven gives you a better shot.
But I don't know how you can do it without cutting down on the
regular season. But if you do, nobody will catch McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing they faced three games in Yankee Stadium, the Rangers
tried to think positively. Helling had said: ``It's fun for me.
This is the most storied franchise in sports. This is the same
field that Babe Ruth and Lou Gehrig and Joe DiMaggio played on.
During the regular season it's one thing. You hear them when you
warm up; you can't help it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it will be the loudest crowd I'll ever hear. You know
the crowd will be into it even when the score is 0-0. I know the
crowd is going to be going crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Going crazy is a normal condition for the fans in the Stadium.
The Yankees earned the extra home game in this short series, and
now they are guaranteed another game in this manic den where their
strength is replenished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
