<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PRIMARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A PRIMARY POLITICAL PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Oct. 1:
</P>
<P>
   Now that Gov. Pete Wilson of California has signed a bill moving
his state's presidential primary to March 7, the process of
electing a president in the year 2000 will probably include a
primary season that is too hasty and a general election campaign
that is too long.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the nation's political leaders move to intervene, the
next presidential nominees will almost certainly be decided in the
late winter, in a flurry of West and East Coast primaries that
follow close on the heels of New Hampshire. That will be followed
by an eight-month campaign for president, while the voters wallow
in boredom and buyer's remorse.
</P>
<P>
   The March 7 primary schedule also includes New England, New York
and possibly other West Coast states, since California wants to
create a Western regional primary to compete with the new Yankee
Day primaries in the East. A big bicoastal primary tilts the odds
strongly in favor of familiar names with lots of money for
television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, that means Vice President Al Gore. Many
of Gore's fellow party members believe that the Democratic National
Committee's hands-off attitude toward the primary schedule is
intended to help the vice president pre-empt the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme compression of the nominating process is a bad idea at
any time and especially so for the Democrats in 2000. The party
must decide if it wants a nominee with strong ties to President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic voters and party leaders need a process that will
allow time for alternative candidates to emerge. If Gore wins the
nomination, he will benefit from a process that does not make
Democratic voters feel they were stuck with the only package on the
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans learned the importance of a choice among viable
candidates in 1996. Many Republicans who regarded Bob Dole as a
weak candidate for the general election also knew he was virtually
unbeatable in a rapid-fire set of geographically dispersed
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing primary voters to make a choice from a restricted field
and then subjecting the country to a final campaign that runs
almost as long as the school year is ridiculous. But states are
scrambling to get in the front of the line because everyone wants
his vote to be important to the final outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The front-loading will not stop unless some national body
imposes order. The National Association of Secretaries of State,
whose members supervise state elections, will meet this weekend in
Washington to discuss plans to head off what could be a disastrous
year 2000 election schedule. The secretaries of state have been
talking up a series of regional primaries, spread out over several
months, with regions going first on a rotating schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But the association will not have the power to get the states in
line without considerable support from the national parties. So far
that help has not been forthcoming. The Republicans did attempt to
lure states into holding later primaries by awarding extra delegate
strength to those who waited. That reward was not enough, and it is
obvious that only a guarantee that all states will get a decent
chance to influence the nominating process is going to end the
present destructive trend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
