<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-30 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3325 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  By &LR; BrianDohn &UR;      09-30 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 By  Brian Dohn  
!by2!Daily News Staff Writer!dlim!
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !text! &LR; The gap between each of Southern Utah's offensive
linemen is a few feet. The five of them are spread across the line
of scrimmage about 10 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in a pair of slot backs, a fullback and a quarterback, and
it's one of the funkiest offenses in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw them on film and I was like, `Boy, I'm going to get
sacks. I'll be blasting gaps. I'm going to go all the way,''' Cal
State Northridge nose guard Sean Beard said. ``Coach is like, `No,
that's what we don't want to do.' Then you look at film and see
other teams run on them. It's weird because it's like you're
playing against a kickoff team. Everybody's spread out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tricky. Plays can be executed like that, though I didn't
think it could.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, there's been a lot more teaching going on
during practice this week as the Matadors (2-1) try to slow the
nation's fourth-rated running game (317.4 yards per game). The
teams meet Saturday (3:05 p.m.) at North Campus Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their running game is good, but their passing game is
garbage,'' Beard said. ``The quarterback (Matt Cannon) has a lot of
guts. Our main focus is to try and blast him and try to take him
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Conventional football wisdom gets thrown out this week as
aggressiveness on defense takes a step back in favor of assignments
to each gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to stop the fullback, no question about it,'' CSUN
coach Ron Ponciano said. ``You have to secure the line of
scrimmage. They have the ability to break a lot of tackles; spin,
run through arm tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Redshirts and eligibility: &UR; !off! &LR;  Ponciano and injured
linebacker Cos Abercrombie, who broke his jaw against Northern
Arizona, met before practice and the two decided the sophomore will
redshirt this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to lose a lot of muscle mass, and I don't want to
aggravate the shoulder he worked so hard to rehabilitate,''
Ponciano said. ``Plus, just the idea of reinjuring that jaw, I
don't want to even put him in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Abercrombie is going to redshirt, it opened another spot
on its 85-man roster for practices, which was immediately filled by
defensive end Carlos Medrigal. Ponciano said Medrigal probably
won't play against Southern Utah but could dress for next week's
Big Sky showdown with Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ponciano said offensive lineman Taffe Aina, who is
academically ineligible, was granted a redshirt season this year
and will return next year.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Hall of Fame night: &UR; !off! &LR;  Former CSUN quarterback
Sherdrick Bonner will be one of three people inducted into the
school's Athletic Hall of Fame on Friday at The Odyssey Restaurant
in Granada Hills. Bonner, who began his career with CSUN in 1987,
is fifth on the school's passing-yardage list (3,533) and third in
completions (319). He'll be inducted along with former athletic
director Robert J. Hiegert and former cross country All-American
Darcy Arreola. Information: (818) 677-3215. &UR; !dlim! &LR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-98 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
